<SLUG> BC-LETTER-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANDMOTHER CAPTURED NAZISM IN HER LENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A distinct genre has grown up along with the children and
grandchildren of the Holocaust's Jewish survivors and victims.
Grappling with a past that is both painfully immediate yet forever
beyond their reach, they have created family memoirs that range
from extraordinary to sincere but ineffectual. What makes Lisa
Lewenz's film ``A Letter Without Words, '' to be seen Monday night
on PBS stations, so exceptional and gripping is the rare cache of
films her German-Jewish grandmother left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Ella Lewenz was a well-off wife, mother and amateur filmmaker
who for most of her adult life documented everything from family
gatherings in the backyard to traffic on the streets of Berlin.
Relying heavily on these priceless first-hand visions of life in
Germany before and during Hitler's rise, Ms. Lewenz has created an
eloquent hourlong film, illustrating how one person has
reconstructed and absorbed her ancestral past.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Ella's films are sharply focused, well-composed,
black-and-white images, though one scratchy bit of film shows
Albert Einstein, a family friend, walking in a park. Later, in a
burst of color, she captures bright red banners with swastikas
hanging from windows everywhere. And in one chilling scene she
turns off the camera abruptly when an SS officer looks her way; by
then such amateur filmmaking had been banned. After the Lewenz
family fled Germany in the late 1930s, Ella chronicled her life in
New York, including the bright balloons in the Thanksgiving Day
parade.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ella's films are the heart of this documentary, its frame
is Lisa's search for her family heritage. Her father, Ella's son,
converted to Christianity when he began a new life in the United
States, and Lisa did not know of his Jewish roots until she was 13.
Her own narrative voice adds a distinctly nonprofessional tone, and
at first her words are cliched. ``In 1981 I found a Pandora's
Box,'' she says of her grandmother's films, which had been stored
away for decades. But like Ella's films, her granddaughter's work
is a home movie in the best sense; they share an immediacy that is
the essence of their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   After Ella's films resurfaced, diaries and letters also began to
appear, allowing Lisa to fill in her grandmother's story. An
off-camera voice reads from her diary the day before Germany's
defeat in World War I: ``Nov. 10th, Sunday. Packed jewelry for
possible flight.'' Lisa interviews two of her aunts, Ella's
surviving daughters, and she travels to Berlin, where she films
some of the same scenes her grandmother did, layering them to
create a pentimento effect. All these elements flow together
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   In a startling turn Ms. Lewenz plays an audiotape her father
left, and which she heard only after his death. He says he regrets
turning his back on his Jewish identity; his daughter's passionate
but nonjudgmental film restores it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as much as she has learned about Ella, she admits at the
end, ``She seems elusive even today.'' Such honesty is at the core
of ``A Letter Without Words,'' which becomes more compelling as it
goes along, more powerfully concerned with the enigmas of
personality and history.  &QL; 
A LETTER WITHOUT WORDS
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Lewenz, producer, director and screenwriter; Lisa Lewenz
and Ella Lewenz, cinematographers; Penelope Falk, Anand Kamalakar,
Ruth Schell and Lisa Lewenz, editors; Paul Bartholomew, Lisa
Lewenz, Lewis Spratlan and Bob Telson, music. Presented by the
Independent Television Service (ITVS).
</P>
</TEXT>
