<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSTNER GETS CHEERS, ANGELS GET WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Edison Field became a field of dreams Sunday,
as the Anaheim Angels hosted Cal State Fullerton and Titans alumnus
Kevin Costner.
</P>
<P>
   With the serious business of roster decisions _ including one to
put Jim Edmonds on the disabled list _ completed late Saturday
night, the Angels and fifth-ranked Titans enjoyed a spring day in
the park.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels defeated Fullerton 2-1, but the outcome mattered
little to the crowd of 17,745 who were admitted free and cheered
Costner's every move.
</P>
<P>
   Costner played 72/3 innings at shortstop before striking out Jeb
Daugherty looking in the bottom of the eighth. In the spirit of the
day, the Angels were allowed an extra hitter and Costner got
Anaheim manager Terry Collins to ground out.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a serious side to Sunday's game as well. Chuck
Finley and Omar Olivares got in some much needed work. Finley
pitched 51/3 innings for the Angels, striking out seven and
allowing only one unearned run. Olivares pitched four shutout
innings for Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck threw great and the big thing was that he got to the
90-pitch mark,'' said Collins of Finley, whose last start ended in
the first inning, when he was hit on the left arm by a line drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of spring training is to get pitchers ready. We
needed the game, and I appreciate (Fullerton coach) George (Horton)
taking the time to play us. They didn't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing it safe: Edmonds has been sidelined with a right groin
injury and an irritated right shoulder, and the Angels decided they
would take no chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy felt with a couple of more days of rest he could play,
but it just doesn't work that way,'' said Collins of Edmonds
jumping back into the lineup after a lengthy absence. ``I don't
want to lose him for a month. Before this guy takes the field he
has to be able to play Jim Edmonds baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Season starters: The Angels will keep only four outfielders, six
infielders and 12 pitchers to begin the season.
</P>
<P>
   With Edmonds starting on the DL and Collins concerned about
Finley's early-season endurance, the Angels optioned first-baseman
Chris Pritchett to Vancouver and kept Tim Unroe, who can play the
infield and outfield as can Jeff Huson.
</P>
<P>
   Called up to be the team's 12th pitcher was young left-hander
Scott Schoeneweis.
</P>
<P>
   More on game's ``star'': Costner made two nice plays Sunday at
shortstop, including a backhanded stop and long throw to get
Charlie O'Brien. But the ``Field of Dreams'' star did drop a pop up
that led to the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   At the plate, Costner was 0 for 3. Finley blew him down on
strikes in the third inning and he grounded out twice.
</P>
<P>
   Greene pastures: Todd Greene, who will open the season as the
Angels' DH, greeted Fullerton's Barry Hawkins with a booming
first-pitch home run in the fifth inning to tie it 1-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
