<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-DIET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, WHAT'S FOR LUNCH AT L.A. SCHOOLS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Staring at a half-eaten heap of chicken nuggets,
Byrd Middle School student Deisy Murillo is on the front line of
the L.A. school district's battle for the minds and stomachs of
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always give us the same food,'' 14-year-old Deisy sighed.
``I just get bored with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under federal order to cut fat and boost nutrition, the Los
Angeles Unified School District and other school systems are
engaged in a daily struggle to balance food that is good for
students with what students think is good food.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of California, Los Angeles,
recently found that more than 50 percent of kids in 14 Los Angeles
public schools are obese. Charlotte Neumann, a professor who
conducted the study, said the culprit seems to be bad eating habits
at home _ and fast food.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the high fat and calories and salt come from,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   So why does the school district allow high schools to serve
Subway sandwiches and Pizza Hut pizzas? School officials say it is
their best chance of keeping kids on campus, where there is at
least a chance to control what they eat.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some wonder whether selling fast food undercuts school
efforts to teach kids how to eat right.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're caught in a tough bind here,'' said Phil Shanholtzer,
spokesman for the U.S. Department of Agriculture. ``They want to
serve nutritious meals, and they want to give students something
they like, because they need to maintain their customer base.''
</P>
<P>
   Many schools nationwide serve fast food, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the district's own menu for 700,000 meals a day adheres to
federal nutrition guidelines, brand-name sandwiches and pizzas need
not meet the same standards. And to complicate matters, many
schools sell chips and candy in their student stores.
</P>
<P>
   By offering fast food and candy, schools may be inviting in the
same culprits that are already harming the health of many children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're to teach the kids proper dietary habits, and if we
say you can't smoke on campus because it's bad for you, shouldn't
we have healthier food?'' said Byrd Principal Gerry Horowitz.
</P>
<P>
   School officials argue that if they can keep students in the
habit of staying on campus for lunch, they have a greater chance of
giving them a healthy meal. And even a serving from Pizza Hut won't
necessarily throw the whole week's nutritional balance out of
whack, said Laura M. Chinnock, senior nutrition specialist at the
district's Newman Nutrition Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they combine it with the other items served, it would
probably be OK,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Entrees are balanced with pieces of fruit and vegetables, more
than the federal government requires.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, once kids grab their meals in the lunch line,
they can toss anything they don't like. Fruit and vegetables often
end up in the trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``On many days, we'll pick up buckets of fruit,'' said Carlu
Hermann of Chatsworth, who volunteers as a monitor at Germain
Street elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Hermann estimates 75 percent of the school's kids won't even
open packets of fruit or vegetables, although they seem fascinated
with furry Kiwi fruit. ``It's a hassle to peel something,'' she
said. ``It's easier to grab that chalupa and eat it. It's easier to
pick up a McNugget.''
</P>
<P>
   Her youngest son, Mark, a fifth-grader at Germain, has a simple
explanation for why he and his peers ditch the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't like how it tastes,'' said Mark, 11.
</P>
<P>
   He would prefer a sack lunch. ``That way I get to pick what I
want,'' he said, adding that he would like to fill a sack with food
from Taco Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiments lie behind the district's decision to include
some fast food in high school cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fight students' preferences, district nutritionists
tinker with popular foods to make them healthier.
</P>
<P>
   Pizza is made with low-fat crust and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The raw meat that becomes school hamburgers has to meet
guidelines on the proportion of fat, Chinnock said.
</P>
<P>
   While not knowing exactly how school nutritionists watch fat
content, Deisy and her friends were not surprised that they do. She
reluctantly said she'd probably take a school lunch over a burger
from a fast-food chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, we'd get fat,'' she said. ``And we want to be
skinny.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Los Angeles schools are ahead of the curve in the
battle for student stomachs. While the latest federal nutrition
guidelines became mandatory at the start of this school year, the
school district actually adopted them several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   No more than 30 percent of calories in a week's meals can come
from fat, and no more than 10 percent from saturated fat. Violating
those rules could jeopardize the $161 million the district receives
in state and federal funding for food each year.
</P>
<P>
   Testing recipes at the district's central kitchen in East Los
Angeles, nutritionists constantly search for ways to trick kids
into eating healthy meals. Chocolate chip cookies are made largely
from prune paste. Lean turkey masquerades as beef.
</P>
<P>
   But in balancing the 700,000 meals served each day, the
district's food service specialists run smack into the same problem
parents constantly face _ the whims of children's taste.
</P>
<P>
   Some kids hate fish, Chinnock said. If something looks weird to
them, such as creamed spinach, they won't touch it. Finger food,
especially for small children, seems to work.
</P>
<P>
   Field testing offers some clues. ``We'll put it on the menu,''
she said, ``go to the school, stand by the trash and see what they
throw away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
