<SLUG> BC-NJ-FLORIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME DEMOCRATIC LEADERS, BURNED ONCE, ARE WARY OF FLORIO'S SENATE
BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLMAWR, N.J. _ ``Here he is,'' bellowed the local party
chairman above the raucous crowd of nearly 400 Democratic Party
regulars packed into the fire hall. ``Here is New Jersey's pride _
New Jersey's next United States senator.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Jim Florio and his wife, Lucinda, barreled through
white frosted-glass doors, as the crowd erupted. The former
governor made his way to the stage, grabbing outstretched hands,
blowing kisses to old friends and embracing supporters from 16 past
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Six years after voters threw him out of the New Jersey State
House and elected Christie Whitman, a Republican, Jim Florio is
trying to make a political comeback. He is running for the
Democratic nomination for the U.S. Senate seat to be vacated next
year by Sen. Frank Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   But as popular as he is here in his base, the southern part of
the state, Florio is having difficulty building support elsewhere
for his candidacy. And the biggest threat comes not from Whitman,
who is also considering making a bid for the Senate seat, but from
leaders within his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Many party leaders from northern and central New Jersey shudder
at the prospect of seeing his name on a ballot next year and a
possible rematch with Whitman. Some are even courting other
potential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that he has a certain amount of baggage,'' said
Joseph C. Spicuzzo, Middlesex County's sheriff and Democratic Party
chairman. ``He is very popular down south, but the majority of
Democratic leaders in the state have not come out and endorsed
anyone yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Florio is that party leaders are worried that
voters may have lingering memories of his tax increase. Almost a
decade ago, Florio inspired a statewide tax revolt after ramming a
$2.8 billion tax increase through the Legislature to meet a court
order demanding more state money for urban schools.
</P>
<P>
   Within two years, Democrats lost control of the Legislature, and
in 1993 Florio became the first governor in modern history to lose
a second term in a general election. As a result, many Democrats
worry that a Florio campaign could reignite voter anger over the
tax increase and damage the chances of other Democrats, including
the candidate for president on the ticket next year.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Raymond J. Lesniak, an Elizabeth Democrat, said that
while he did not belong to the ``stop-Jim-Florio-at-any-cost
school,'' the party needed to consider other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have better candidates, and I am not ready to hand
over the nomination to Jim Florio,'' said Lesniak, the Democratic
leader in Union County. ``The tax issue is a real concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio, who has been practicing law since he left office,
insists that he is in the race to stay, whether or not he wins the
backing of the party leaders elsewhere around the state. He has
moved quickly to demonstrate his strength in recent weeks, lining
up two major Democratic fund-raisers and endorsements from nine
county chairmen, mostly from southern New Jersey, where he
represented Camden County in the State Legislature and Congress for
16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although he says that the last few years have softened him a bit
and made him more empathetic to voter concerns, Florio remains very
much the former Navy boxer. Even his opponents acknowledge that he
would be tough to beat in a primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm not troubled entering the contest, why should they
be?'' he asked as he sipped tea over breakfast. ``Anybody who wants
to run in the Democratic primary should be out there. Tell us what
you think. Tell us what you stand for. And then let the people in
the state _ north, south, central, by area codes, whatever _
decide. I don't have any problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio, 61, has spent all but the last five years of his working
life in politics. He has run for governor four times, winning once,
losing one primary battle and losing two of the closest general
elections in the state's history, including his 1993 re-election
campaign. Whitman's last-minute pledge to cut taxes helped her come
from behind and beat Florio by 26,000 votes out of 2.5 million
cast.
</P>
<P>
   Florio dismisses talk that his 1990 tax increase would hurt his
prospects or the chances of any other Democratic candidates on the
ballot. He defends the tax increase but acknowledges that he did
not properly reach out to voters and explain why it was necessary
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he did not view a possible matchup with
Whitman as a replay of the 1993 gubernatorial campaign, because
Whitman did not have a record then. Now, he said, she does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any difficulties with the idea that we had to
fund our schools,'' he said. ``You have to balance the budget. I
think it is interesting that people are bragging now about a $700
million surplus. I came into office with a $600 million deficit,
went through the worst recession since the Great Depression, and
finished my administration with a $400 million surplus. And now,
after these six or seven years of unprecedented prosperity, you're
only talking about a $700 million surplus?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it comes to pass,'' he said, ``it will almost become an
ideal opportunity for people in this state to contrast dramatically
different individuals, styles, philosophies, backgrounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is seeking vindication or redemption, as some of his
critics have suggested, he replied: ``Redemption is going to
heaven. I'm talking about the Senate. I am very confident. Maybe
too confident. I have a sufficient amount of self-esteem so that I
don't have to prove anything to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   When he learned in February that Lautenberg would not seek
re-election, he said he jumped at the chance to get back into the
arena because he believes he can address the public's concerns over
health care, Social Security and education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
