<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-NETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO NETS TAKEDOWN FOR CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ We were told to wait until the home games. Then, things
would turn around. Someone obviously forgot to mention that the
home games would be next year. This year, they are proving to be an
ongoing disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Nets have won twice on the road all season. Both
wins have come in the FleetCenter. Sunday, with a roster only a CBA
coach could love, Jersey dominated Next Year's Playoff Team, a.k.a.
the 1999 Celtics, with an easy 91-79 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the sixth straight at home for Rick Pitino's
beleaguered boys, who were booed again for their overall,
underwater performance. The franchise record of seven straight home
losses, set in the halcyon days of M.L. Carr and Chris Ford not too
long ago, is on the line Wednesday. Meanwhile, the Celtics play in
Orlando Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   How bad was this one? Well, the Nets were 7-24 entering the game
and, at one point, had three guys on 10-day contracts on the floor.
They still won with ridiculous ease. Lucious Harris played 15
minutes and had as many baskets (five) as Ron Mercer and Paul
Pierce, who combined for 72 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Boston shot 37.5 percent, its third-lowest percentage of the
season, and turned it over 23 times, second worst of the season. It
had only 12 assists, a season low. For the second straight Sunday,
the Celtics never led. But this wasn't the Pacers. It was the Nets
of William Cunningham, Jamie Fieck, Mark Hendrickson, and four
pretty good players named Keith Van Horn, Stephon Marbury, Kerry
Kittles, and Kendall Gill. They were all the Celtics could handle.
</P>
<P>
   In their six straight home losses, the Celtics have held no
leads in two games, have led by only 2 points in two others, and by
7 in the other two. Put another way, in the last 24 quarters of
basketball in the FleetCenter, and one overtime period, a span of
293 minutes, the Celtics have not led by as many as 8 points. The
average margin of defeat in those games is 9.5 points.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino actually said he liked his team's effort until things got
out of hand in the fourth quarter. That's a bit like saying you
thought ``Saving Private Ryan'' was easy on the eyes and stomach if
you missed the Omaha Beach stretch. But that does not translate
into him liking the result. He says he will be Mr. Mellow the rest
of the way, all the while salivating at the prospect of next
season, his goal for the last six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me a lot,'' the coach said. ``But yelling and
screaming is not going to do anything to turn it around. It's tough
for the fans, it's tough for you all, it's tough for me, it's tough
for the players. But, I'm committed to winning next year. We're
going to try as hard as we can this year. We're not going to make
the playoffs this year, but we'll give our effort.''
</P>
<P>
   There, does that make you feel better now? The Celtics are going
to try real hard for the rest of the season, including the final 12
at home. Presumably, that means the fans won't be shouting, ``We
want our money back,'' as they did Sunday. The Nets aren't going to
make the playoffs either and have lost key guys for the season,
including all their big men. They merely won for the third straight
time, elevating bon vivant interim coach Don Casey to 5-7 since he
took over for the jettisoned John Calipari.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how we're looking at things,'' Casey said. ``We're
5-7.''
</P>
<P>
   They're also only two wins astern of the Celtics. Boston had
plenty of chances in this one, but hit every wall/land mine there
was. Antoine Walker had 32 points, matching his season high. But
Pierce bricked his first seven shots and was 1 for 10. Mercer was 4
for 12. The Celtics' bench, once again, was almost nonexistent,
scoring four baskets and 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   But it was still a game, theoretically, starting the fourth. The
Nets led by 7 (Boston had been within 4 in the final minute of the
third) and the Celtics opened the quarter with the ball. But Mercer
missed and Harris nailed a 16-footer to start a quarter-opening,
game-closing, stands-emptying, boo-inducing 10-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics shot 3 for 20 in the fourth, looking like the Swiss
marathoner who stumbled home in the 1984 Olympics. They missed 15
of their first 16 shots, including an uncontested dunk by Walter
McCarty. The 10-0 Jersey run blew the lead to 17 and the Celtics
needed a 6-0 run in the final 1:43 to finish only a dozen points in
arrears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
