<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUBACH WIDE-EYED FOR OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It will not yet be dawn when the caravan
leaves the apple blossoms and peach trees of home, crosses the
Mississippi River near the great arch of nearby St. Louis, then
drives more than 200 miles across the breadth of Missouri for a day
so long in coming, no amount of tears will obscure the view.
</P>
<P>
   Someone else will have to deliver the mail Monday in Belleville,
Ill. Dale Daubach of the United States Postal Service has a date in
Kansas City, where he and his wife, Angie, family members, assorted
friends, and well-wishers will see for themselves that after nine
years of long hours and short paychecks in the minor leagues,
Opening Day finally has arrived for Brian Daubach.
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Sox are introduced Monday afternoon at Kauffman
Stadium before their season-opening game against the Kansas City
Royals, Dale Daubach and company will be in the stands when his son
Brian, No. 53 on the scorecard, will assemble on the same
third-base line as Nomar Garciaparra, Mike Stanley, and Jose
Offerman. If Daubach's face is not familiar, just look for the
uniform jersey fluttering from the heart beating so hard
underneath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's going to be a little emotional,'' Daubach said
Sunday. ``I've been through enough. I think I've put in my time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of my grandparents are still living, and they told me
they wanted to see me in the big leagues before they pass away.''
</P>
<P>
   Step aside, Jimmy Connors, the tennis star anointed by Bud
Collins as the Brash Basher from Belleville. For at least a day,
there's a new favorite son in the town of 40,000 tucked away in the
southwestern corner of Illinois, and he bashes baseballs for a
living.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time ever in spring, Brian Daubach,
27-year-old rookie reserve for the Red Sox, has found a team that
believes he does it well enough to be in the big leagues. Even he
wasn't sure what to think when Jimy Williams summoned him last week
to tell him he was on the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy called me into his office,'' Daubach said. ``When a
manager calls you into his office, you never know what's going to
happen. I think that was the first time I've ever been called into
the office where it wasn't bad news.''
</P>
<P>
   It may last only as long as it takes Reggie Jefferson's back to
heal. But for now, Daubach has won a job as the team's lefthanded
pinch hitter, on the strength of a spring training performance in
which he batted .313 and had four home runs, two doubles, and a
triple among his 15 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully I'll stay here,'' Daubach said. ``They say the
hardest part is getting here. But as long as I'm here, I'm going to
have fun every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach, a former 19th-round draft pick of the Mets who tore up
his knee in a pickup basketball game back home when he was barely
19, never made it to big-league camp with the Mets. He signed as a
minor league free agent with the Marlins in 1997, the year they
went to the World Series, and was among the team's first cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Even last year, when the Marlins were in the midst of
deconstructing their team, Daubach was dismissed with barely a
glance.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach went back to the minors last season, just as he has done
every year since 1990, in places like Kingsport and Pittsfield,
Binghamton and Norfolk. He'd thought about quitting just once, he
said, the year he was trying to come back from knee surgery and
also broke up with a longtime girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   He chose to continue riding the buses and stretching his thin
meal money summer after summer. Winters, he sold sporting goods and
took classes and, for a couple of weeks one year, worked
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, it all fell into place for Daubach on the field. In
Charlotte, playing for the Marlins' Triple A team, he batted .316
and led the International League in almost every slugging category,
including home runs (35) and RBIs (124). A line-drive hitter who
hit to all fields, Daubach said that he finally figured out how to
pull the ball.
</P>
<P>
   In September, he was called up for a cameo appearance by the
Marlins. He hit a double off Curt Schilling of the Phillies. His
parents came to Atlanta to see him play, but he got in just one
game.
</P>
<P>
   When the Marlins let him go after the season, Daubach returned
to the Dominican Republic, where he played for the second straight
winter on a team managed by Sox coach Dave Jauss. He was on the
verge of taking a job playing in Japan, even if it meant going to
the minors over there, when Jauss pleaded with him to reconsider.
Daubach relented, he said, when Sox general manager Dan Duquette
called him in his hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `We're going to give you at least a good look in
spring training,' '' Daubach said. ``That's all I've ever asked
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams gave him that look, and the Red Sox uniform he'll be
wearing Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
