<HEADER>
A5814 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK     04-05 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYER MAKING CONTRACT PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariners and left-hander Jamie Moyer have made
significant progress toward a contract extension, and though
neither side wants to negotiate too far into the season, an
agreement could be reached soon.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer, the M's No. 2 starter, said negotiations are going too
well to call them off just because the season is starting. He is
optimistic about reaching a deal within a week if progress
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we've done our part and they've done their part,
and it's just a matter of finding out the finality of getting
something done to appease everybody,'' Moyer said. ``If we get to a
stalemate, then we won't worry about it. But I don't foresee that
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old Moyer, who is in the last season of a
three-year, $6 million deal, had been hoping for a three-year
extension. The sides now are working on deals of two years or two
with an option, believed to be worth between $4 million and $7
million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to go in the three-year direction, but I
kind of understand their situation and where they're coming from,''
Moyer said. ``Any contract negotiation, whether it's one year, two
or five, I think both sides have to give. And I think both sides
here are moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Woodward, the M's vice president for baseball operations,
said he also won't let the opening of the season stifle positive
contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to negotiate into the year; we need to
concentrate on getting the season started,'' he said. ``(But) if
there's good progress being made, we'll take a look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The club is not close to extensions with the other players it
was hoping to sign by opening day, left-hander Jeff Fassero and
first baseman David Segui.
</P>
<P>
   Segui, who will not negotiate during the season, was seeking a
four-year contract and said he was willing to go well below market
value for it. The Mariners have stuck to a three-year offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad that (because of) one year, they didn't want to
get it done,'' said the 32-year-old Segui, who is in the last year
of a two-year, $4.75 million deal. ``They know where we stand. If
they want to get it done, we'll get it done. If they don't, there's
no hard feelings, I'll go somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``My No. 1 choice is to stay here, but I would never be
unreasonable. I'm tired of signing bad deals. I just want what I'm
worth in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero and the Mariners have not had contract talks in two
weeks. In fact, ``There hasn't been any hard negotiating,'' Fassero
said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Moyer, Fassero is 36 and could be seeking a three-year
deal. He doesn't want to think about his contract during the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'd rule out negotiating (during the
season),'' Fassero said. ``I just don't want to be on the phone
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, who is in the final year of a deal that will pay him
$4.75 million this year, never has been a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Might be fun,'' he said. ``But it definitely is fair to say
I'd like to finish my career here.''
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: Segui landed with the rest of the Mariners at
4:30 a.m. Sunday. But unlike the remainder of the team, which slept
off a weekend in Las Vegas, Segui headed to the Kingdome for an
hourlong workout on his back, chest and triceps. ``Those other guys
are lazy,'' he joked. Segui isn't much on gambling, but he did use
the Vegas excursion to change his hair color from silver to blond.
... Right-hander Ken Cloude threw five innings against the M's
Class AA team in Peoria, Ariz., Sunday and will start again for
Class AAA Tacoma on Friday. He will be on pace to start next
Wednesday against Texas if needed. ``He threw the ball very well
today,'' said farm director Benny Looper. ``He worked on his
changeup a lot, and that's a good pitch he needs to develop.'' ...
Looper said 19-year-old phenom Ryan Anderson will start at Class AA
New Haven _ a level higher than first thought _ but another top
pitching prospect, right-hander Cha Sueng Baek, remains in Korea
with visa problems. ... Here's Woodward's scouting report on
right-hander Jimmy Turman, the 23-year-old Class A right-hander
acquired from Montreal Saturday for reliever Bobby Ayala: ``He's
got to develop a lot, and that's what we're taking a shot at. If he
does, then he's going to be real special. He's got the size and the
potential.'' Turman, 11-7 with two Class A teams last year, might
begin an extended spring training, but eventually will go to Class
A Lancaster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
