<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5815 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-US-BRITAIN-     04-05 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-US-BRITAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURIER CARRIES US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, England _ The rowboat named Courier would not sink.
</P>
<P>
   Battered by resounding surf on all sides, assaulted by a tidal
wave called Greg Rusedski, the deceptive rowboat was really a
battleship whose big guns hammered the gallant Brits to the
narrowest of defeats, and carried the US Davis Cup team to Boston
and the wished-for July quarterfinal against Australia at Longwood
Cricket Club.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom, if ever, in the 100 years of the sterling crock's
existence has an American guy come through as brawny James Spencer
Courier did Sunday &UR;  &LR; night in helping the US seize the 3-2 triumph
at the extreme limits of the game _ tail-end of the fifth set of
the fifth match of the best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   This was heart-stopping stuff at the seething National Indoor
Arena, which resembled a bygone English madhouse called Bedlam. But
through deafening tumult and shouting, horn-blowing, and chanting
of 9,400 voices (``Go, Greg, Go!'' as well as a minuscule band with
``USA! USA!''), Courier's lionheart didn't miss a beat. He hung on
grimly, coolly in the turbulent rising and falling tides for nearly
four hours, and busted the biggest serve in tennis as a valedictory
to win, 6-4, 6-7 (3-7), 6-3, 1-6, 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   For the US, a sunnyside-up Friday start, a 2-0 lead, had gloomed
to 2-2 when Todd Martin couldn't hold off a rampaging shotmaker,
Tim Henman. Despite a bright start, a set and a service break to
4-3 in the second, Martin lost his composure over a disputed line
call. He fought back to hold a set point in the fourth. However,
Henman canceled that with a stunning serve-and-volley volley,
proceeding to win, 4-6, 7-5, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4).
</P>
<P>
   Courier was brazen and bodacious, making everybody forget the
disdainful Pete Sampras. At one point Courier lifted his shirt to
tap his chest and roar: ``Nobody's got a bigger heart than me!''
</P>
<P>
   But inwardly he was another man. ``Calm, serene, peaceful,'' he
said. ``It was eerie. I felt like I was in a rowboat in the middle
of the ocean. The noise, the fans were waves breaking all around
me. I was enjoying it all. And I kept sniffing at Rusedski's serve
until at last I could break it'' _ for only the third time in 26
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the locker room waiting for Todd (Martin) to finish I was
reading a book called `The Perfect Storm.' It put me in this nice,
ocean mood.'' Even though the Gloucester, Mass., fishing boats in
question tragically went to the bottom, Courier had read only the
first 20 pages. Still, to his captain, Tom Gullikson, and
teammates, Courier fit the title _ the perfect storm.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was in the fire, and Courier, who, of course, ``as
a little boy wanted to be a fireman,'' came on to put out the
blaze. As the US' all-time Cup fireman, he is 3-0 in ultimate fifth
matches. His presence means more than a hook-and-ladder truck,
since the team is now 13-0 with him in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Seven times over the century, a US series has gone down to the
fifth set of the fifth match. Four Americans have won: Don Budge
over German Gottfried von Cramm, 1937; John McEnroe over Swede Mats
Wilander, 1982; Michael Chang over Austrian Horst Skoff, 1990; and
Courier twice, stopping Russian Marat Safin last year. He also beat
Netherlander Jacco Eltingh in a fifth match (four sets) in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man for the crunch, like no player I've been associated
with,'' lauded Capt. Gullikson. ``I don't care where Jim's ranked''
_ currently No. 54 _ ``but when he's got his Davis Cup game face
on, he's the No. 1 he used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Lefty Rusedski launched many torpedoes into that face, serves
that traveled up to 133 miles per hour, 31 of them for aces while
he was miserly with break-point openings, only six. Courier leaped
on the last one, driving a backhand return toward the charging
Rusedski's right hip that he couldn't volley. It was over.
Finished, leaving everyone drained, slowly realizing that the US,
7-4 short-enders with British bookmakers, had won by a margin no
greater than one of Courier's scarlet whiskers. After eight hours
in the asylum, the crowd had to go home at 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we lost, but it was a great occasion,'' said a
spectator, framing it well. It had been appropriate in this
celebrational 100th year of the Cup that the original foes should
clash.
</P>
<P>
   Although Courier, who had beaten Henman also in a squeeze (7-5
in the fifth) to open the series, didn't serve as large as
Rusedski, he served tougher (66 percent to 54), and warded off
seven of nine break points. The match could have slipped away from
him a game before he tucked it away. Rusedski goaded him to deuce
with a rifling forehand, whereupon Courier lashed a serve that set
up a forehand winner and got to 7-6 with a service winner.
</P>
<P>
   Courier had missed the lone previous break point of the set as
Rusedski took it away with a snaking second serve, and reached 4-4.
``But in the last game I was reading his serve,'' Courier said.
Rusedski started with his 16th double-fault and was beaten by a
ripping forehand passer, and two concluding backhand returns.
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski, who had lost to Martin, felt, ``I let the team down.''
Not with his part of the incredibly high-quality performance
Sunday. It was brinksmanship all the way, 3:47 of memorable fury
and firing from both. Rusedski kept coming at Courier, volleying,
half-volleying, and hitting a gang of passers himself. Courier was
a volleying master, too, though storming the net half as much.
</P>
<P>
   Together they made a masterpiece that had Longwood president
Steve Roiter in a deep sweat. ``We wanted the US and Australia, and
we got it. We should give Courier a key to the city,'' he enthused.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least a rowboat to drift and dream victorious thoughts on
the Charles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
