<HEADER>
A5817 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKC-MAINE-BOS &LR;      04-05 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-MAINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSEVERANCE IS THE RULE FOR MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It did not appear to be the ideal way to end
the regular season and pick up steam heading into playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Maine went to a rocking Whittemore Center at
the University of New Hampshire and got rocked. Absolutely rocked.
UNH won the games, 6-1 and 4-1, and won the Hockey East
regular-season championship.
</P>
<P>
   And Maine coach Shawn Walsh was calm as could be afterward. Said
he loved the atmosphere. Couldn't wait for the playoffs to begin.
Loved the way his team played.
</P>
<P>
   But 10-2 in two games, coach?
</P>
<P>
   Not a problem. There were bigger _ much bigger _ to come.
</P>
<P>
   Losing a couple of games in March sure beats losing a game in
April, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Black Bears, who didn't exactly roar into the playoffs,
roared through them and were April perfect. Two wins, no losses. An
NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night they outlasted UNH, 3-2, in overtime at Arrowhead
Pond to finish off their second title of the decade. This team, led
by captain Steve Kariya, matched the 1993 title of the team led by
his older brother, Paul, then a freshman at Maine and now a
superstar for the Anaheim Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul said to me all year long just to go out and relax and
have fun,'' Steve said. ``To enjoy the moment. I can't say enough
about my four years here. It's gratifying for me and the fellow
seniors. We knew we'd be a winning team. And there's no better
feeling than this.''
</P>
<P>
   The game and the season _ and the last four years, for that
matter _ were a credit to perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   Maine players stuck with the program through the NCAA penalties
for rules violations that kept the school ineligible for the NCAA
tournament in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Maine led, 2-0, on goals by Ben Guite in the
first period and Niko Dimitrakos early in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three minutes after Dimitrakos made it 2-0, it was
nearly 3-0. Dan Kerluke put the puck in the net, but the goal was
disallowed after video review because a player's skate was in the
crease.
</P>
<P>
   Still, UNH, getting tons of chances but being denied by an
outstanding effort by Maine goalie Alfie Michaud, was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the Wildcats. They hung in and killed off a minute and 23
seconds of a five-on-three Maine power play. They got a shorthanded
goal from Darren Haydar, breaking out of the penalty box, and it
was 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the third period, junior Mike Souza tied it, finishing a
Haydar-Krog-Souza relay.
</P>
<P>
   Remember last year's championship game at the FleetCenter when
Boston College lost to Michigan, 3-2, in overtime? This was that
all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's BC-Michigan game was a great game, and this game
was right there with it,'' said Maine coach Shawn Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   Spectacular saves from both goalies. Great defensive plays to
break up great scoring chances. Help from the posts. Good bounces.
Bad bounces.
</P>
<P>
   Michaud, who had 46 saves when it was all over, got Maine to
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   UNH sophomore Ty Conklin, who had 36, did his share, too.
Conklin, on the ice, held off a couple of Maine chances 6:47 into
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Michaud stopped a Krog tip-in try at 8:53 and then barely got
his stick on an in-close shot by John Sadowski.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Maine senior forward Marcus Gustafsson took a
pass from Cory Larose. He shot and then followed his rebound and
popped it over Conklin.
</P>
<P>
   It was over. At 10:50 of overtime, Maine, which lost in the 1995
title game to Boston University, clinched another title.
</P>
<P>
   And how about Gustafsson for perseverance? He was on the roster
but dressed for only one game in the 1995 season. He went home to
Sweden to fulfill a military obligation. He believed he had
something to prove as a player, and came back to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in myself and I wanted to come back and show
everyone I was a better player than I was in my freshman year,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He did that. He finished his career on the Black Bears' top line
with Larose and Kariya, and scored a huge goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Maine had one power-play goal _ Guite's _ in seven
tries. New Hampshire was 0 for 7 on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   In Durham last month, Maine was 0 for 12 over the two nights.
New Hampshire was 5 for 9.
</P>
<P>
   The teams split their first four games, and at the end it should
have come as no surprise to anyone that the rubber match went to
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Maine finished 31-6-4, New Hampshire 31-7-3.
</P>
<P>
   UNH took a couple of major steps this season. First outright
Hockey East championship. First NCAA championship game appearance.
Most wins. First Hobey Baker Award winner in Krog.
</P>
<P>
   And the Wildcats came up just short of a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The puck bounced for Maine and they made a great play to end
the game,'' said UNH coach Dick Umile, who will try to take his
Wildcats one win further next year.
</P>
<P>
   Maine beat league rivals Boston College and then UNH, both in
overtime, to win its title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, either of these games could have gone the other
way,'' Walsh said. ``Hey, you get lucky. They didn't score on one
and we scored on one. That's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   And what happened was a national championship. No team has won
back-to-back titles since BU in 1971 and 1972. There have been
rumblings that Walsh may move on, but with him or without him, that
will be a target.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes right down to it, one out of three ain't bad.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears lost the series at New Hampshire and missed out
on the regular-season league title. They lost to BC, 3-2, in the
Hockey East semifinals, and thus missed out on the tournament
title.
</P>
<P>
   Then they bagged the big one.
</P>
<P>
   They'll take that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
