</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-GANGKID-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING NOWHERE: `I WON'T MAKE IT TO 30,' GANG KID SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The black (italics) R.I.P. (end italics) tattoo
crudely inked into the neck of 11-year-old Robert Lomas is the
first sign the youngest member of the notorious Langdon Street Gang
has grown up around killing, death and pain.
</P>
<P>
   The second sign is the street name of Robert's gunned down
mentor Sal ``Sneeky'' Saladona, also needled into the
sixth-grader's flesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't make it to 30,'' Robert said one recent morning,
staring at the pavement until the last word slipped out his mouth,
and then shrugging his shoulders and turning away.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way or the other, someone will get me before I turn 30.
They will. I know I'm going to die. But I like this life and
kicking it with my homeboys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't make me join. I wanted to be with them. They look
out for me, and I stay out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoic and coarse, but still holding on to his little boy grin,
Robert has literally become the poster child for Los Angeles City
Attorney James Hahn's war against gangs in North Hills, northwest
of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   When Hahn announced a lawsuit against the Langdon Street Gang
last week, he used a photograph of Robert's tattoos to underscore
the rise of what he says is a new generation of street thugs, in
place ``to terrorize'' residents for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Robert was not among 31 of his older Langdon Street Gang cohorts
specifically named in the proposed gang-abatement injunction which,
if approved by a judge, would prohibit the defendants from
associating with one another in public.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why police photos of Robert and his tattoos were chosen
by the City Attorney's Office was not clear. A spokesman for Hahn
and gang investigators declined to comment on Robert or any other
juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that Robert is of prime age for recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At their age, they see the older ones flashing money from a
dope deal, and there is an allure of the gang subculture and
mystique,'' said Marty Vranicar, supervisor of the City Attorney's
Gang Unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always a constant effort to recruit these kids,''
Vranicar said. ``There is safety in numbers, and you need people to
fill the ranks after arrests and casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not news to Robert or his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to talk to Robert all the time about the gang. But the
more I ask him to leave, the more he's going to get into it,'' said
Melinda Lomas. ``What he does, he does behind my back.''
</P>
<P>
   Lomas says she's upset that the gang controls her neighborhood
and her son's life.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she is not willing to speak out against the
gang, even though they are responsible for at least three fatal
shootings near Monroe High School since November 1997 and lord over
drug sales in an area known as Los Angeles' drug supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got nothing to say about his homeboys. The guys from
Langdon bring me bags of groceries when we need food. Whatever else
they do, they do for their own personal reasons, and that's their
business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lomas family wound up in Langdon Street Gang turf eight
years ago, when Robert was about 4. They were looking for a better
life and fleeing their past.
</P>
<P>
   After breaking up with Robert's father, Lomas said she threw him
and three of his siblings into a car and sped toward California.
She abandoned a three-bedroom home with a ``big, gigantic back
yard'' on the outskirts of San Antonio for a cramped apartment on
the fringe of the 405 Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drove here quickly to get away,'' Lomas said. ``We've been
trying to make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lomas' 12-year-old son Joey and toddler Frankie are her
only two children not running with Valley gangs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids don't have anything to do around here. There are no
parks, no place to go,'' Lomas explained. ``I'm always worried
about them. Some people are doing good things for them and got Joey
not to get involved in gangs.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 10, Robert was beaten into the Langdon Street Gang behind
an apartment complex by two older street thugs. He says he asked
for the brutal initiation and doesn't regret it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They socked me a whole bunch of times. It was all right,'' he
said, quickly adding, ``I got some shots in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down on the ground for a few seconds. When I got back
up,'' he said, ``it ended.''
</P>
<P>
   But the beating was so severe, Robert's older brother Joey, who
had planned to join the gang before witnessing the attack, decided
thug life wasn't for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to join when Robert did,'' he said. ``But I saw him
get his ... kicked _ and I changed my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey's resolve was strengthened last month when Robert was
accidentally shot.
</P>
<P>
   According to Robert, several of his homeboys were passing around
a semiautomatic pistol when the gun fired. The bullet ricocheted
off the pavement and superficially wounded him in the knee. The
middle schooler has nine stitches; police have no record of the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Fiddling with the zipper on his Adidas basketball jacket, Joey
downplayed his brother's shooting and predicted early death. ``I'm
not worried about that. When he's 29 I'll start to worry because
I'll know he has a year left to live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother can do what he wants to do. It's his life,'' Joey
said. ``I'm not into the gang.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Robert's mother credits the Rev. Jim Hamilton, the graying,
passionate pastor of the United Methodist Church of Sepulveda, with
saving Joey and handfuls of other children from the Langdon Street
Gang and their rivals.
</P>
<P>
   For the last four years, Hamilton has opened the church's gated
courtyard on Rayen Street to local children. He gives them a place
to play basketball, take art classes, do homework, or just hang out
away from both the street violence and the swarms of police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have much money, but we give some of them jobs and
give others a safe place to go,'' Hamilton said. ``They're all good
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the kids Robert and Joey hang out with at the church and
local pizza place say they don't have ambitions to be gangbangers.
</P>
<P>
   And despite reports from police and the City Attorney, the
children, ranging from 11 to 16, insist they're not being recruited
or pressured into the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Langdon says they don't want me, but they've never asked me or
anyone to join. You make your own choice. I don't want them,'' said
Tommy Slayton, 15, who recently moved into the neighborhood from
the south side of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen too many people die,'' Tommy said. ``But you need to
know the police thing is real bad also.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They already look at you like you're doing something wrong,''
he said. ``Now they'll be bothering us even more. We don't have to
be on that list for them to hassle us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrinkling the right side of his mouth in a display of anger and
sudden worry, Robert glared at two uniformed cops outside the
church courtyard's iron gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get panicked when I see them. They can't come in here and
hassle me, can they?'' he asked, before shaking off his own
question.
</P>
<P>
   Robert should be scared. If the injunction is approved, police
would have unprecedented powers in the North Hills neighborhood to
roust suspected gang members.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, the suspected street thugs would not be allowed to
own cellular phones and pagers or congregate in public. They would
have to abide by a 9 p.m.-to-sunrise curfew in two sections of
North Hills near the 405 Freeway, including around Langdon Street
Elementary School and James Monroe High School. And they would be
forbidden to go on private property without written permission from
the owner.
</P>
<P>
   While 12 of the named members are incarcerated and police
recently reported a 20 percent decline in crime in the area, Hahn
and gang investigators insist the injunction is needed because
traditional law enforcement has failed &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In court documents, Los Angeles police Officer Adrian Torres,
perhaps the most recognized and feared cop in the neighborhood,
declares: ``There are definite signs that Langdon is raising up yet
another generation of gangsters to terrorize the target area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The youths that I have discussed in my declaration are not
alone. There are others more than willing to take their place on
the streets ... to peddle their drugs,'' Torres continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can only be an increase in the violence and havoc
visited upon the people of the target area as this next generation
works to make names for themselves,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law-abiding people of the target area are forced to live
with Langdon and all its stealing, shooting, robbery, graffiti,
threats, and of course drug dealing,'' Torres writes. ``Just
because they suffer in silence does not mean they don't suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Langdon Street Gang has moved beyond criminal to become a
habitual and commonplace fact of life,'' he concludes. ``In short,
it has become a nuisance and must be dealt with accordingly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
