<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5825 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     04-05 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This one smelled &QL; 
from the beginning
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If the loss in Utah was a speed bump on an open
highway, this was like talking on a cell phone while driving into
the back of a bus.
</P>
<P>
   If blowing that fourth-quarter lead to the Jazz was supposed to
be a lesson and make them better students, this was trying to tell
the teacher the dog ate your homework.
</P>
<P>
   Shotless in Seattle. Careless in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Hopeless in Seattle. Gutless in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Meg Ryan and Tom Hanks would have put up more of a fight. Maybe
just Meg.
</P>
<P>
   On the odor-meter, this one would rank up there with the
leftovers from last year's Easter egg hunt. Except in this case,
the Rockets were soft-_ not hard- _ boiled. But still rotten.
</P>
<P>
   You can spin Sonics 101, Rockets 84 like a top until the new
millennium, and there is only one thing positive to say: It's over.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it was essentially over in the first quarter when it
was evident only one team came to play.
</P>
<P>
   It was unsightly, even unprofessional.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton nailed a 3-pointer to open the game. Then Hersey
Hawkins hit one and then another. Detlef Schrempf dropped in a
finger roll. Payton tore in for a spinning banker. Aaron Williams
slammed home a dunk. When Hawkins finally missed a layup, Payton
came right in behind to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it was the start of daylight-saving time. But with all of
the personal trainers and bodyguards and assistant coaches in the
Rockets' traveling party, certainly it was somebody's job to set
all of their alarm clocks and watches ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting your butt beat in this league, there's no shame in
that,'' said coach Rudy Tomjanovich. ``But to go out there and act
surprised that the other team came ready to play, well
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was an energy deal. You could see from a lot of the
loose balls on the floor that they got to before we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Crotty-chopped
</P>
<P>
   You also could see it from the way the Rockets played on
offense, lazily and stubbornly relying all game long on the 3-point
shot, a weapon that misfired (5-for-27), if it was ever loaded at
all. And you could see it from the way the Rockets defended the
basket from start to finish, looking more like polite doormen in
search of a good tip rather than tough, hard-nosed bouncers.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Rudy T, there's no real shame in letting Payton
run rampant and pick you apart off the dribble and with his jumper
for 30 points, eight rebounds and seven assists because he's the
most potent all-around threat at point guard in the NBA today.
</P>
<P>
   But there isn't enough shame in a season's worth of Melrose
Place to cover up for the fact somebody named John Crotty exploded
for a career-high 19 points, including 14 in the second half after
the Rockets had gotten up off the floor after trailing by 17 and
taken an oh-so-short-lived 59-58 lead with 4:16 left in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crotty was definitely the difference in the game,'' Scottie
Pippen said. ``By the second half, we got Payton under control. But
Crotty came in and gave them a lift.''
</P>
<P>
   A lift? He gave the Sonics an express elevator ride to the top
of the Space Needle.
</P>
<P>
   Crotty, playing for his fifth team in the past five NBA seasons,
is supposed to be the kid who valet-parks your car at the
restaurant or bags your groceries. But the Rockets' listlessness
turned him into as uncontrollable and unrelenting a foe as Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Live by the 3
</P>
<P>
   Which was just the tip of the iceberg. The Rockets were beaten
by the hustle of union-card-carrying bricklayer Olden Polynice, who
shot just 3-for-13 but never stopped working. They were beaten by
Payton going just 12-for-27 and Schrempf 6-for-15 and Dale Ellis
1-for-3. The struggling, .500 Sonics were a cool 45.8 percent from
the field. But the Rockets could not match it because the gyroscope
on their outside shooting was broken.
</P>
<P>
   They tried Michael Dickerson (0-for-5) from long range and
Pippen (0-for-4) and Sam Mack (1-for-7) and Cuttino Mobley
(2-for-7). With the Sonics using their usual assortment of traps
and double teams down low to stop the first option to Hakeem
Olajuwon, what the Rockets never did try was kicking the ball back
outside and then attacking the basket. Or making a return pass back
inside to Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we relied too much on the '3,''' Pippen said.
``I mean, we are a 3-point-shooting team.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, like Linda Tripp was Queen of the May.
</P>
<P>
   So the nine-game winning streak is a thing of the past, and the
good feeling built up on the first part of the five-game road trip
becomes lost luggage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I think things are better than a couple of weeks ago,
even with two losses,'' Pippen said. ``I think we can all look at
ourselves in the mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is how badly they would flinch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
