<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5827 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-B     04-05 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACE MARTINEZ KNOWS WHAT'S IN THE CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It was only after he went home to the
Dominican Republic last fall, Pedro Martinez said, that he
recognized the toll his first summer in Boston had taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized there had been a lot of stress and strain, a lot of
pressure,'' Martinez said. ``The expectations were so high that
everybody had. They all expected a perfect game, the same thing
every day. It's impossible. I'm only human.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the huge contract, of course. And the specter of Roger
Clemens. And the way Martinez raised the bar of those expectations
himself when in his first Opening Day in a Red Sox uniform, he spun
seven shutout innings and struck out 11 against the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Martinez was able to more than balance that burden on
his slender shoulders, despite a month-long bout with a virus that
left him weak for much of the summer. He won 19 games, plus a 20th
against the Cleveland Indians for Boston's lone win in the
playoffs. His 2.89 earned run average ranked second in the American
League. So did his 251 strikeouts. Eight times he struck out 10 or
more batters, who collectively hit just .217 against him.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Rocket went home with his record fifth Cy Young Award,
with Martinez finishing second. But for as demanding as they have
been, Red Sox fans may have merely gotten a preview of coming
attractions from the 27-year-old ace who will open the 1999 season
Monday afternoon against the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A better year?'' Martinez said. ``It's possible. Why not? I
can't predict that I'm going to have a better year, but it's
reachable.''
</P>
<P>
   For one, he said, he feels stronger, having packed on a few
pounds. He has become acquainted with the American League, not only
the hitters but the umpires, who occasionally frustrated him by
their seeming reluctance to call third strikes.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps most important, he said, he has come to terms with
what others want from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it's going to be,'' he said, ``but I
guarantee you I will be more relaxed than last year. I'm getting
paid to do the job I have. I'll take the same responsibility as
always. I'm still well-paid. I'm still the player people expect to
do good.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I plan to keep my level as a player, and grow higher if I
can. It's not going to be easy. But if I do the same things I've
done the last six years, work hard and stay healthy, good things
will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   As close as he is to his older brother, Ramon, who will join the
team for the home opener next Tuesday and may be in the rotation by
mid-July if his shoulder regains its strength, Martinez bristles at
the notion that having big brother around is going to have a
profound effect on his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramon doesn't mean anything to my relaxation,'' he said.
``I've been alone the last six years, and I've managed to do well.
The way I am, I will feel more comfortable having Ramon, yes,
that's a fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not like everything is going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Red Sox, status quo will be just fine, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine he has his own expectations,'' manager Jimy Williams
said. ``He can't worry about other people's expectations. We have
other pitchers who are going to pitch. This is a team concept.''
</P>
<P>
   But everyone understands that this team, beginning Monday
afternoon in Kauffman Stadium, when Martinez takes the mound
against Kevin Appier, has something in common with its fans. Great
expectations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
