<HEADER>
A5834 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-05 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMMER MANAGING TO STAY SANE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If this were a 1940s movie, it would be called
``The Reluctant Manager'' and the part of Don Zimmer would be
played by William Frawley. (That's ``Bub'' to you thirty-somethings
and ``Fred Mertz'' to the Social Security set.)
</P>
<P>
   In the climactic scene, Joe Torre, played by Dana Andrews, would
enter the Yankees dugout just as the game is about to begin. Waving
a piece of paper, he would have a big smile on his face, and he'd
say, ``Move over, Zim, the Doc says I'm all clear. Got the medical
clearance right here.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is not a movie, '40s or otherwise. It is real life, and
Zimmer, who wants to be managing the Yankees as much as he wants to
adopt Bill Lee, is the skipper of the defending world champions,
and will be until the cancer-ridden Torre feels fit enough to
reclaim his job. Or until he runs afoul of owner George
Steinbrenner, and don't laugh. These are the Yankees, remember,
and, as Gilda Radner used to remind us, ``It's always something.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmy has landed in the middle of what the Japanese might call a
Grade A dekigoto, or incident, involving Japanese righthander
Hideki Irabu, who drew the wrath of the principal owner by failing
to cover first base on a grounder to the right side last Thursday.
It was his second such spring training infraction, and it set off
the volatile Steinbrenner, who reached a 10 on the Boss-O-Meter,
labeling his expensive Asian import a ``fat . . . toad,'' among
other things.
</P>
<P>
   Much silliness ensued. Irabu did not immediately accompany the
team to the West Coast, where, following exhibition tilts Saturday
and Sunday at Dodger Stadium, it will begin defense of its world
championship Monday night in Oakland with Roger (``I'm not talking
the day I pitch, the day before I pitch, or the day before the day
before I pitch'') Clemens on the mound. Was it Irabu's idea to stay
in Florida, or was it Steinbrenner's? We heard it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   The fun really started when acting manager Zimmer announced
that, in light of the Irabu developments, Ramiro Mendoza would be
starting on Wednesday in Oakland. Suddenly, The Boss, who has
invested more than $12 million in this particular project, was
again pro-Irabu. Fat Toad or no Fat Toad, he was to remain in the
rotation. Uh-uh, said Zim. I'm the manager, and I say Mendoza is
starting.
</P>
<P>
   Shown newspaper clippings in which The Boss had identified
himself as the only one ``in Irabu's corner,'' Zim fired back in a
very public way, basically telling Steinbrenner that such an idea
is nonsense and that if he didn't like what Zimmer was doing, well,
you can fill in the blanks.
</P>
<P>
   So here's where we are now. Zimmer hasn't spoken to Steinbrenner
directly. Mendoza will start Wednesday. Irabu will work out of the
bullpen, but only at the start of an inning. And Zimmer, starting
his 51st season in organized baseball, is doing things his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't read George's mind,'' he explains. ``I said what I had
to say, and I don't regret what I said. As far as I'm concerned,
it's over with until I hear differently.''
</P>
<P>
   The P.S. is that Irabu, communicating through his interpreter,
spoke with both Zimmer and the team before Sunday's game. Referring
to the ``winds blowing around me,'' he apologized to his teammates
for ``making trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of credential-toting folk were surprised with just how
sanguine Zimmer has been through this whole affair, but that just
goes to show they don't quite understand this very straightforward
and uncomplicated man. What they must be made aware of is that
Zimmy is bullet-proof. He never has managed out of fear, and he
certainly isn't going to start now, at age 68, especially when he
is doing the job only because both Torre and Steinbrenner asked him
to take it.
</P>
<P>
   Some poor soul actually asked him if he were nervous.
``Nervous?'' he replied. ``I wasn't yesterday. I'm not now. I
wasn't two weeks ago. I'm too damn old to be nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   I keep thinking back to a day in the summer of 1977. It was
about 3 1/2 hours before the start of a night game, and we were
sunning ourselves in the Fenway Park box seats behind the
third-base dugout. We were talking about this and that, and at one
point Zimmer said, ``I know I'll get fired here some day because
all managers get fired. And when that happens, it will be OK,
because I'll go right back over there (pointing to the third-base
coaching box) and I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 21 years ago. Zimmer would manage in both Texas and
Chicago. He would coach in New York, San Francisco, Boston, and
Colorado before landing in New York in 1996. He has been supremely
happy acting as the consiglieri to Torre, who truly appreciates his
advice and counsel. He has no desire whatsoever to manage _
especially this team.
</P>
<P>
   He is in a lose-lose situation. His team is coming off a
record-breaking season, and the man he's replacing is generally
regarded as merely the perfect man for this particular job. The
best Zimmy can do is not screw things up.
</P>
<P>
   Again, he's not afraid. He's just wary. He knows that if the
Yankees win only 124 this year, someone will have something to say.
That's No. 1. He doesn't think he's as good a manager for this team
as Torre. That's No. 2. The circumstances of his getting the job
are bad. ``Who wants to become a manager because someone has
cancer?'' he inquires. So that's No. 3. He is in daily pain because
he has had no chance to recuperate properly from knee surgery.
That's No. 4. And there's another human element to consider: ``I
know there are other guys who would have liked to have been named
manager,'' he explains. That's No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the stunning announcement that Torre had prostate
cancer, it was far from an idyllic Yankee spring. ``Someone said it
looks like we gave up victories for Lent,'' Zimmer joked. Sunday's
loss gave them a 13-20 March record, and while, yes, spring
training is spring training, there were days when it was just ugly
enough to allow the prime contenders to believe the Yankees are at
least a little vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   When you've been around the game for 51 years, you tend to be
cautious. ``I keep reading here and hearing here that we're a
cinch,'' says Zimmer. ``But no one's ever a cinch. We had a very
good team last year, and everything possible that could have gone
right did go right. If I'm Baltimore, or I'm Cleveland, or I'm
Boston, I'm laughing when I hear New York is a cinch. I know I'd be
laughing if I were them.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer/William Frawley will manage the Yankees as long as
he's needed. But he will be waking up every day hoping that Joe
Torre/Dana Andrews will be making him move over on that bench.
``I'll hug him and give him a kiss,'' he promises.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope a photographer is ready when that moment comes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
