<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5835 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ROYALS-BOS &LR;      04-05 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ROYALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYALS, FANS MAY PAY PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Kansas City Royals posted the best record
in the major leagues this spring (22-9). But based on their
troubles over the last few seasons, they know 1999 could be another
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Kansas City, which hosts the Red Sox in the season
opener Monday, finished third in the American League Central, 16
1/2 games behind the Cleveland Indians. That actually was closer
than the wild-card Red Sox came to the Yankees in the AL East (22
GB). So what did the Royals do? They elected to strip payroll,
letting five free agents walk _ pitchers Pat Rapp and Tim Belcher
and infielders Jose Offerman, Dean Palmer, and Hal Morris. (Rapp
and Offerman signed with the Red Sox.) Terry Pendleton retired.
</P>
<P>
   To take their place, Kansas City picked up catcher Chad Kreuter,
shortstop Rey Sanchez, and third baseman Joe Randa, and has added
rookies in outfielder Carlos Beltran and second baseman Carlos
Febles, neither of whom has played above Double A. The strong
spring showing means things could work out. But, then again, maybe
they won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably kidded ourselves in the previous winter,'' said
Royals GM Herk Robinson. ``We'd finished last for two years (1996
and '97), and by signing some of the people we did, we offered some
hope to all. It did allow us to get out of last place and finish
third. But at no time did we compete with the Cleveland club. It
came down to the fact that you just can't compete with a $35
million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no point in losing $10-12 million. There were days
when our late owner, Ewing Kauffman, would write checks for $1
million, $2 million, or $3 million that would allow us to be
competitive with the payrolls of Toronto or New York. But the same
kind of money just doesn't do anything today.''
</P>
<P>
   After a 72-89 record only got it third place, the club needed a
roster overhaul, as well as an injection of cash and new ownership.
The Royals are trying. But in today's large market-vs.-small market
setup, the outcome is rather predictable.
</P>
<P>
   If the goal is to bring the franchise back to where it was from
1976-1985, the task is monumental. After moving into Royals Stadium
in 1973, it took Kansas City three years to win a division title.
In the late '70s, the Royals dominated the West, and in 1980 they
overhauled the Yankees. They won a World Series over St. Louis in
1985. Along the way, George Brett became a Hall of Famer. Frank
White, Amos Otis, Paul Splittorff, Willie Wilson, Darrell Porter,
Cookie Rojas, Steve Busby, Dennis Leonard, and Hal McRae became
Kansas City legends. But that's history. The Royals have placed
second three times but have not won a division title since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, much of the talent from the farm system that
used to fuel the big club was allowed to drift away, or to be
traded away, especially after the death of Kauffman in 1993. The
notion was that Kansas City could remain competitive by spending
millions on salaries of players acquired in trade or via free
agency. That will stop, says Robinson. Now if a minor leaguer has
talent, he will play in the big leagues _ with the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're making an attempt to get younger,'' he said.
``And with that comes a lower payroll. We've lived beyond our means
for several years. It doesn't make a lot of sense to have a $35
million-$36 million payroll, lose a lot of money, and not be able
to compete. We're going to concentrate on signing draft picks and
amateur free agents. We hope to break even.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking even means holding on until the club is sold or there
is an infusion of cash. The current budget is around $26 million.
The eventual goal for this year is $20 million. If the Royals are
in the hunt, that could change. But it's the plan for now.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said the team will include some veterans, even pitcher
Kevin Appier, although when he gets healthy he will be traded to
the highest bidder. But Robinson wants to give young players a
chance to see what they can do. After all, Brett, who will enter
the Hall of Fame this year, was an unknown when he started.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably rushing some guys to the major leagues,'' said
Robinson. ``We know that. We're bringing up two players in Carlos
Beltran and Carlos Febles who have never played Triple A baseball.
In a perfect world you'd allow them to play a year at that level.
We're not going to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope by the end of the year for our payroll to be $20
million. To be competitive with the Yankees, you'd have to spend
$80 million. That's a $60 million difference, and our franchise is
hardly going to sell for more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   And what if one of his young prospects develops into another
Brett and then decides to leave? After winning the Series in 1985,
the Royals drew 2 million or more for the next six years. But
attendance began to drop after Brett retired in 1993. Last year,
the club had a horrible 29-51 record at home and drew only
1,494,875.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our fans understand,'' said Robinson. ``They know that
as things stand, there isn't a thing we can do about it. I'm sure
they don't like it. But they also know we don't have the up side of
other small-market teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the saddest things I heard about George being elected
into the Hall of Fame is (someone said) that the Royals will never
have another one because they couldn't keep a player like that
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the ongoing need for revenue, requirements have
changed. New stadiums in such places as Milwaukee, San Francisco,
and Detroit all have or will have at least 100 luxury suites that
sell from $75,000 to $100,000. In Chicago, one can take in a show.
In Arizona, one can swim in a pool or take a sauna.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a destination like Disney World,'' said Robinson.
``You come to the stadium and park in the lot. You get out of the
car and you go into the park. There's nothing else to do. And when
you get inside, there is little more to do than to go to your
seat.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes the play of the Royals has fans getting off those seats
and cheering this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
