<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE'S BEEN A NET GAIN FOR BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He has been written about and much discussed in and out
of the Bruins dressing room. If you took an informal poll of
players, chances are excellent that goalie Byron Dafoe would be
voted the most valuable player on the team.
</P>
<P>
   If last year was Dafoe's breakout season, this year has been
even more impressive for a variety of reasons. Last year, Dafoe was
a key part of an efficient defensive machine. He did his job well
but didn't often have to make up for his teammates' lapses since
there weren't very many. This season has been different. Because of
holdouts early in the year and injuries throughout much of it,
Dafoe has had to be better than he was last year. He's been called
on to carry a bigger load and he's seen far more defensive
breakdowns than last season.
</P>
<P>
   His goals-against average and save percentage consistently have
been among the best in the league. The one statistic that was
deceiving was his record, which is only recently beginning to
approach his lofty other numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's 3-0 victory over Philadelphia, Dafoe earned his
ninth shutout of the year, tying Terry Sawchuk (1955-56) for the
most by a Bruin in a season since Hal Winkler's team-record 15 in
1927-28. Dafoe, who came to the Bruins with one career shutout, now
has 16.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe is scheduled to become a restricted free agent July 1, and
his stock keeps rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was pretty much learning for him to be in that role
where he was the main guy,'' said right wing Rob DiMaio. ``This
year, I think he just built on that and developed more, and has
more confidence. Maturity does a lot for a goaltender, especially
somebody like Byron. He wants to play every night. He relishes the
role that he's in, being the main guy, and he's a quality
goaltender.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe has started 19 straight games and with the Bruins in
decent playoff shape, an obvious day off might be Thursday's game
in Tampa Bay, a team backup Rob Tallas never has lost to and Dafoe
never has beaten. It also would be the second game in two nights
during a week in which the Bruins are scheduled to play four games
in six days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him (Saturday night) and he'd like to play them
all if he could,'' said DiMaio. ``It's good to have a goaltender
back there who really wants to be the guy and who wants to be in
there every night. You know he's going to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe was quite a revelation last year but because of the
stringent defensive system put into place by coach Pat Burns, it
was difficult to tell how Dafoe would be if his team were in
trouble. This year, it was Dafoe who bailed his teammates out of
jam after jam.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio, like most everyone, didn't know a lot about Dafoe before
he came to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew of him but I knew of pretty much everybody in the
league,'' said DiMaio. ``I never really played too much against
him. I don't think he got as much ice time or as many games as he
would've liked being in other places. Fortunately he came here and
won the job early and he never gave it up. He developed into a
great goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know he'll make that first save and second save a lot of
the time and just having somebody back there gives you a boost.
Obviously, you don't want to abuse that fact and just play a
different game and let teams have their way with you and just think
Byron is going to stop everything, but you know he's going to make
that first save. When he does, it just builds our confidence and we
know he can compete in low-scoring games.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio said Dafoe has his own style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Character-wise he's . . . I don't think I've ever met a goalie
who's the same as anybody else, but Byron's a pretty charismatic
guy,'' he said. ``He's a fan favorite, he's good with the media,
and he does a lot of good things for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio, who missed Saturday's game because of an injury he
suffered to his forearm during warmups, said he will play Monday
night against Montreal at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all right,'' said DiMaio, who took therapy Sunday. ``It's
feeling a little better, so I'm playing. I really don't know
exactly how I did it. I took a slap shot, and as soon as I took the
shot in warmup my forearm . . . I thought I ripped something. I
couldn't hold onto my stick and it was pretty painful to straighten
my arm. I thought I did something worse than I did. Fortunately,
it's stiff but not that bad. It just happened. It was strange.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio is the second Bruin to be injured in warmups in the last
two games. In Montreal Thursday night, Tallas was struck in the
head by a puck that ricocheted off the crossbar. It cut him for
five stitches but he was the backup. ``Life for me has been
Murphy's Law lately,'' said Tallas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
