<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION BELIEVE IN ZENGA'S SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Finally, the Revolution seem to have an
effective blend of fantasy and pragmatism, at least in goal. Walter
Zenga, their 39-year-old player-coach who returned from retirement
in an attempt to save a floundering team, is capturing attention
with both spectacular saves and sheer charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Zenga is hoping his personality and style filter into a
team that has exhibited little of either in its first three
seasons. Zenga was again in top form as the Revolution took a 1-0
victory over the Kansas City Wizards Saturday, increasing their
all-time point total to 102 in 100 Major League Soccer
regular-season and playoff contests.
</P>
<P>
   The timing coincided with the buildup to the Revolution home
opener and not only restored some of the team's confidence, but
also might have recaptured the faith of fans. Season-ticket sales
are just over 5,000, a drop of about 1,000 from last year, as the
Revolution prepare to meet D.C. United at 7:30 p.m. Saturday at
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga seems to have discovered a formula for success. At least
he is indicating a viable path for the Revolution, who had the
lowest points per game average in the 12-team MLS entering this
season. Zenga's tactics are conservative, defense-first, but he is
showing that such a philosophy can generate drama and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Revolution had few choices but to follow Zenga's
lead. In three-plus seasons, they have won only 30 games in
regulation time, half of those with Zenga involved. And Zenga only
has been involved in 31 Revolution matches, 23 as player, six as
coach, and two as player-coach.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Revolution set an MLS record with nine consecutive
regular-season defeats after Zenga departed with a knee injury.
Zenga retired, and they matched that losing record last season.
Apparently, Zenga was propping up a porous defense and a team
lacking imagination and resourcefulness. Now, he is providing
guidance as a coach, and restoring confidence as a goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   In the Revolution's first two games, both Miami and Kansas City
have had ample scoring opportunities. But Zenga has discouraged
those chances, usually in a masterful way, allowing the defense to
regain its composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows their role this year,'' defender Richard
Goulooze said. ``And we are appreciative of each other. Everyone is
battling and the guys up front are doing a lot of running. Everyone
is more relaxed. We are not taking a lot of risks, but we have been
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is panicking. If we lose a couple of players with
injuries, we are convinced we can still get a good result.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution played without midfielders Imad Baba (groin),
Edwin Gorter (suspension), John Harkes (right knee), and Kris
Kelderman (right knee), and striker Giovanni Savarese (right
ankle). Gorter is due back this week, Kelderman and Savarese are
probable, Harkes is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter talks a lot back there and he takes his time,''
Goulooze said. ``He has a lot of experience. He helps the defense
and he tells us what he wants. Kansas City had shots but he covered
them. We always know he is there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are anticipating some difficult challenges. Zenga
still is adjusting to the exigencies of the MLS schedule. In every
major soccer league in the world, opponents are spread out,
allowing more time for buildup and preparation. Though the
Revolution have gained some stability, they have yet to prove they
can compete with the top contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very difficult for us to play against the best team in
the league two times in two weeks,'' Zenga said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 0115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
