r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TESTS-AZR &LR;      04-05 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS, TEACHERS AGREE TEST LOAD CAN BE OVERWHELMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a good thing Arizona students get a spring break, because
many of them return to school this month to face a full plate of
tests.
</P>
<P>
   To the alphabet soup mix of Stan9, SAT, ACT, AP and NAEP, plus
district finals and regular classroom exams, students can add AIMS
_ Arizona's Instrument to Measure Standards _ which debuts later
this month throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   All of which has some teachers and district testing directors
questioning whether students are spending too much time filling in
the bubbles instead of learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are overly testing these kids,'' said Kathy Williams, an
instructional specialist at Dobson High School in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Williams cites the latest example to make her claim. Several
weeks ago, 85 Dobson High students were randomly selected to take
the National Assessment of Educational Progress, called the
nation's report card. It's a mandatory test the students had no say
in. And to add to their angst, the students won't be told how they
scored.
</P>
<P>
   So test-conditioned are students, Williams said, that when she
gives her history class the Alabama Literacy Test as part of its
course study of the Reconstruction, the students ask if the score
will register on their permanent school record.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agrees that testing is important to find out what
students have learned and how they stack up against their peers.
The problem is everyone _ the nation, the state, the university and
college, the district, the teacher _ has a different way of
measuring students' academic progress, leading to a glut of tests.
</P>
<P>
   All of that probing leaves students dreading the sight of No. 2
pencils and circles as they conjure up story problems and
multiple-choice questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all kids are talking about this week,'' said Sal Leyvas,
a 17-year-old student at Chandler's Hamilton High School.
</P>
<P>
   Students care most about the tests that impact them the most,
including classroom tests that determine their grades and advanced
placement exams that can exempt them from introductory college
courses. Soon, AIMS will join that list.
</P>
<P>
   But while conscientious students such as Leyvas _ he even
rehearses basic math concepts before taking the Stanford 9 _ know
testing is important to hold the education they receive
accountable, they sometimes feel overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can get a little boring,'' the junior said. ``If it goes on
too long, you start losing your concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparing students for multiple exams affects classroom
instruction as well, educators say.
</P>
<P>
   In the Marana school district in southern Arizona,
Superintendent Wade McLean recently formed a curriculum team
composed of teachers and administrators to make sure educators felt
part of the process, everything from revising what is taught in the
classroom to devising successful test-taking techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work real hard to get people to celebrate by showing what
they've learned,'' McLean said of the tests. ``If you're not
excited about it, you won't do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers feel the pinch for time. Williams finds herself
weighing which lessons to cut and doling out more out-of-classroom
assignments, including homework during school breaks. Students come
in before and after school as well as lunch to stay on top of what
they need to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids keep rising to the occasion,'' said Williams, who
teaches in an already test-heavy district. ``But there will be a
breaking point.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the state's approximately 800,000 pupils in about 225
school districts and 270 charter schools will take the Stanford 9
achievement test this week. Many of them will follow it up with one
or more of a half-dozen other tests, including college entrance
exams and semester finals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, in late April and early May, AIMS will be given to
high school sophomores, and a pilot version of the state exam will
be administered to some elementary school pupils.
</P>
<P>
   Even testing advocates say the level of testing may have reached
critical mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one test with the hors d'oeuvre. There's another with
the main course. There's another with dessert,'' said Chester Finn,
president of the Fordham Foundation, a national conservative
education research group. ``It would be nice if the meal had one
test.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be a long way off. The reason: Some of the tests
measure different things and follow different formats, state
education officials say. The Stanford 9 achievement test, given to
second-graders through high school juniors, is a timed test to
compare students across the nation. AIMS is a power test that will
measure whether students are learning prescribed standards.
Beginning in 2002, pupils must pass it to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's valuable time in that you're going to get
feedback,'' said Billie Orr, the Arizona Department of Education's
associate superintendent. Testing prepares students who ``will have
to show what they know for the rest of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   One possible solution to overtesting is to rearrange testing
blocks. In the Tempe Union High School District, one board member
recently suggested giving some annual district tests and the
Stanford 9 during the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't teach kids anymore in April. We only test kids in
April,'' Dick Foreman said.
</P>
<P>
   Others recommend that the school year be lengthened. But that
may be a pipe dream. For decades, lawmakers have bellyached about
the cost of increasing the instructional days beyond 175.
</P>
<P>
   Some students see little good, educational or otherwise, in the
type and the amount of testing. Carrie Ellingson, now a freshman
elementary education major at Mesa Community College, said
standardized testing only demoralized her when she saw that her
scores weren't as high as other students'.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't make her a better student, said the 19-year-old Dobson
High graduate. ``I never saw a use for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the biggest waste of time,'' she insisted. &QL; 
Kelly Pearce can be reached at 602-444-7981 or at
kelly.pearce(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
