<HEADER>
A5841 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLECAM-AZR &LR;      04-05 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLECAM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE MINING GOP DONOR LISTS FOR 2000 CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle is running for president, but
don't expect to see him working rope lines in Iowa or attending
living room coffees in New Hampshire until later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Republican primary voters who hope to meet with Quayle _ and
virtually every other GOP candidate for president _ will have to
pay an admission cost, usually $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   As the first deadline for filing the first set of campaign
finance reports in the 2000 presidential race approached Wednesday,
Quayle was crisscrossing the country in search of contributions
from big donors. At the same time, his aides were hard at work
beefing up a grass-roots donor list to help him mine smaller
donations.
</P>
<P>
   Now, well into April, Quayle is in a different city nearly every
night, attending a swank fund-raiser in Manhattan one evening,
making a sweep of smaller fund-raisers in the coastal towns of
Florida on another, raking in as many of the $1,000 donations _ the
maximum allowable contribution by a single donor _ as he can.
</P>
<P>
   In the past several weeks, Quayle's schedule has included
fund-raisers in Illinois, Kentucky, Nebraska, Louisiana and Oregon.
Quayle's first real campaign event _ his official campaign kickoff
in Indianapolis _ won't happen until April 14.
</P>
<P>
   The donor list, which is being supervised by Oliver North's
former direct-mail guru, Richard Norman, may be the key to Quayle's
future.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview in New York, Quayle acknowledged the
strategic importance of the list, which he purchased for $45,000
from his leadership political action committee, Campaign America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raised a lot of money. We supported a lot of candidates.
Campaigned for a lot of candidates,'' Quayle said. ``Those lists
are very important, believe me. Those who supported me for Campaign
America, by and large, will support me for president. Not all, but
a good majority.''
</P>
<P>
   As he had hoped, Quayle was able to raise $2 million by the end
of March, when candidates for president were required to file their
first finance reports with the Federal Election Commission. The
forms will be released by the commission April 15.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to raise large sums has been made even more critical
by the virtual money machines of Vice President Al Gore and Texas
Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of Bush have indicated he may forgo federal matching
funds in order to be able to spend at will. Bush fund-raisers have
indicated they will try to raise $45 million, and Gore's supporters
have bragged that they are capable of hauling in $55 million.
</P>
<P>
   By forgoing federal matching funds in the primaries, Bush would
be better positioned to vie with GOP presidential candidate Steve
Forbes, whose self-financed campaign last year allowed him to
bypass state primary spending limits on the way to spending $32
million.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle insisted that he wasn't worried about besting Bush or
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about whether I have the most,'' Quayle said.
``I'm just going to have adequate financing to get my message out,
and once my message is out there, I am convinced that the people
will gravitate toward it, they will support me, and I'll be the
nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance consultant Stan Huckaby, who is advising Quayle
and six other Republican candidates on raising money, has estimated
that candidates must have $15 million to $20 million to compete in
the primary.
</P>
<P>
   That means each candidate must raise $6,000 a day, a task that
is made even more difficult by the limited number of donors who can
shell out $1,000. Huckaby estimates that there are 45,000 such
donors in the GOP fund-raising pool.
</P>
<P>
   By Huckaby's count, to hit the $20 million target, each of the
GOP aspirants must grab 18,000 to 19,000 of these $1,000
contributions, in addition to 5,000 donors who can give $500 to
$999 _ a numerical impossibility, given the limited circle of
donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun. Anyone who thinks it's fun, you shouldn't vote
for,'' Quayle admitted of the treadmill atmosphere of fund-raising
this year. ``If you want to have fun, go play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance experts view the current fund-raising realities
as evidence of a system that has spiraled out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The madness has gotten madder,'' said Fred Wertheimer,
president of Democracy 21, a Washington, D.C., public policy
organization. ``We know that if you've got to raise $20 million in
1999 to be credible, that means you've got to to raise $6,000 a
day, and that just doesn't make sense at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a system that is very out of whack.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a system that rewards candidates who cultivate huge
donor lists far in advance of the campaign. A few candidates _
including Quayle, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, publishing
magnate Forbes and Family Research Council President Gary Bauer _
have done this using PACs and, in the case of Forbes, an
issue-advocacy organization. Bauer, a foe of abortion rights, has
proved by far the most effective at turning a PAC into a campaign,
cobbling together 90,000 donor names during his time as director of
the Campaign for Working Families.
</P>
<P>
   The PACs allow candidates to legally ``prospect'' for donors up
to four years before the election without declaring an official
candidacy. Even as they are campaigning for state and federal
candidates, the presidential candidates are gradually building up a
list of Republicans with a record of making donations. Then, just
before or after declaring for the presidency, the candidates
purchase the donor lists from their PACs for use in their own
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   FEC records indicate that Quayle's Campaign for America amassed
a donor list of at least 3,100 names from 1995 to 1999, when the
PAC closed its doors. The PAC raised $6 million during a time in
which Quayle and his wife, Marilyn, campaigned for more than 200
state and federal candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle advisers believe the list gives them the opportunity to
cultivate grass-roots supporters at the same time the candidate is
attempting to woo big-money donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Dan Quayle has the ability to excite grass-roots
activists out there,'' said Quayle 2000 Campaign Chairman Kyle
McSlarrow. ``What I like about it is, it gives us a balance. I like
the idea that we are not just stuck on raising major donor money.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle plans to continue building the donor list, according to
McSlarrow, despite the high costs associated with prospecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, when you have a list (from a leadership PAC), it
does transfer over, but you also have to kind of build a new
list,'' McSlarrow said. ``People sometimes decide, `Well, maybe for
the presidential race I'm not going to be with you.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
