<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA DIAMONDBACKS HOPES HIGH ENTERING 2ND SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Year 2 of the Arizona Diamondbacks is upon us with
fresh faces in the lineup and a new focus in the community.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your radical departure from the frenzied buildup to
Opening Day 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks open their season today in Los Angeles against
the Dodgers in the marquee pitching matchup of the day: Arizona's
Randy Johnson, who signed a $52.4 million, four-year deal in
November, against Los Angeles' Kevin Brown, who became baseball's
richest player 12 days later when he signed a $105 million,
seven-year deal. The same two teams come to Phoenix next Monday for
the home opener at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   It's been an off-season of transformation for the Diamondbacks,
both on the roster _ thanks to a $119 million free-agent spending
spree _ and in the community. The buzz at BOB this year focuses
more on the team's chances of contending than on the facility, the
controversial quarter-cent sales tax that financed it, or the
novelty factor of major-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Baier, director of sports development for the Arizona
Department of Commerce, said that building a baseball tradition and
speeding up economic development downtown have replaced the
controversial stadium funding as key issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's definitely starting to be a change,'' he said.
``From the political side those feelings (of resentment) may linger
a little, but from the people especially the feelings are
soothed.''
</P>
<P>
   The off-season has seen the team spend heavily on veteran
talent, with an eye toward contending for a playoff berth right
away. Johnson is foremost among the additions, but the team also
added outfielders Steve Finley, Luis Gonzalez and Tony Womack,
pitchers Todd Stottlemyre, Armando Reynoso and Greg Swindell and
utility man Greg Colbrunn. The heavy investment in payroll came
after a highly criticized decision to raise ticket prices by about
12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Season ticket sales are down from 36,000 last year to about
27,000 this year, but the Diamondbacks still expect to be one of
the leading draws in Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   General Managing Partner Jerry Colangelo attributes much of the
drop-off to fans combining their tickets with friends because they
found attending 82 games in a season too much.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks drew 3.7 million fans last year, fifth in the
major leagues. They also were fifth in worldwide merchandise sales
in Major League Baseball, trailing only the New York Yankees,
Cleveland Indians, Atlanta Braves and Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   They have sold 2.3 million tickets this year before the first
game.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dozer, president of the Diamondbacks, said that there
are about 2,000 tickets left for opening day April 12, and that
season ticket sales will continue for a short while after the
season begins. Dozer also said about 1,000 20-packs have been sold.
</P>
<P>
   For Colangelo, Dozer and others, the trick now is to build
tradition and allegiance, cultivating a baseball culture in the
Phoenix area similar to those in Chicago, New York and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building an allegiance takes time,'' Colangelo said. ``We
believe that it takes time to build that baseball tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   KTAR-AM (620) talk show host Brad Cesmat wonders if the Valley's
(Phoenix area) typical ``until they win, who cares'' attitude will
prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get the sense that there's a real buzz about opening
day yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that as a city we have the capability of being on the
same par as a Chicago,'' Cesmat said. ``I think the expectations on
the fans should be higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Expectations also are high that the Diamondbacks and BOB will
continue to spur redevelopment and the downtown economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think that the Diamondbacks have made a huge
improvement for downtown,'' Dozer said. ``The ballpark is almost
the icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   The total economic impact of the downtown stadium's operations
last year was projected at $319 million in a study paid for by the
Downtown Phoenix Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Partnership officials have said the challenge this year is to
spread out the benefits beyond BOB, its concession stands and
associated restaurants, including TGI Friday's and the
Leinenkugel's brew pub.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that 94 percent of the increase in downtown
sales came from those entities.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's on Third was the major new bar/restaurant venue in the
area for last season, and it is joined this year by Alice
Cooperstown and the Tee Pee Tap room.
</P>
<P>
   Another brew pub has been proposed for Third Street next to the
railroad tracks, a permit has been filed for loft condominiums at
Second and Buchanan streets, and a hotel development has been
proposed for the parking lot between BOB and Jackson's on Third.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot going on. A lot of this impact is related to the
stadium,'' said Brian Kearney, executive director of the downtown
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're starting to see bit by bit these things happen,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kearney said those projects and other housing developments
downtown demonstrate the synergy of a developing area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased with what is happening so far and don't see the
momentum slowing down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that brings 3 to 4 million people a year downtown has
to be seen as a large impact.''
</P>
<P>
   But some find the development lagging and wonder when the pace
will pick up, whether downtown will ever be a place to be or just a
place to go for an event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think downtown is a New Orleans or a Broadway,'' said
Art Kaufman, a vocal stadium critic who maintains that the
Diamondbacks ``pulled a fast one'' on the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman believes baseball would have come to the Phoenix area
regardless of whether it was financed by the taxpayers, but now
that it's here, he thinks its impact is a positive one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is all right, it's a good sport,'' he said. ``It's
good having a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell whether it's the team that matters to fans, or
whether it's just BOB and its amenities that draw crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously they fit in real nicely, they're a great addition to
downtown,'' said Baier of the Department of Commerce. ``It's
especially great that in the summer Bank One Ballpark is someplace
to go in air-conditioning and see great entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it will definitely take a while to build a baseball
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Tradition and winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to start being competitive,'' Dozer said. ``We need to
keep people coming out in July and August.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
