<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 M's CALL TO ARMS BEGINS IN KINGDOME  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Joe Carter was going over his Mariners game notes
Sunday, and the former All-Star-turned-ESPN-broadcaster had to
shake his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been impressed with this team,'' Carter said.
``How many times can a guy hit 56 home runs and get overlooked,
like (Ken) Griffey last year? They've got Alex Rodriguez, Edgar
(Martinez). And the spring they've had? They've got a few young
guys, but when you have a veteran ballclub playing like that in
spring training, it's a positive note. Usually veteran ballclubs
don't play well in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing you have to look at is the bullpen. Until they
right that, that'll always be the talk.''
</P>
<P>
   That talk, of course, is a little less shrill these days. The
Mariners finally unloaded Bobby Ayala on Saturday, dealing the
beleaguered reliever to the Montreal Expos, who it's safe to say
won't be paying much of the right-hander's $1.8 million contract.
The move secured the roster spot of right-hander Eric Weaver, the
sixth Mariner pitcher with less than a year of big-league
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the M's introduce a familiar lineup for Monday
night's Kingdome opener against the Chicago White Sox, a lot of
their other players are largely unknown. Ten Mariners _ plus
reliever Mark Leiter, who is on the disabled list _ never have
played for Seattle before. Some of them have hardly played anywhere
before.
</P>
<P>
   If there was one thing the Mariners most wanted from spring
training, it was the development of their young arms. In the course
of winning 20 of 32 games, that happened. Two pitchers, No. 3
starter Freddy Garcia and potential fifth starter Brett Hinchliffe,
made the team despite no major league experience. Relievers Weaver
and Mac Suzuki have seven career appearances, left-hander John
Halama six. Set-up man Jose Paniagua has worked in 40 games over
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know they've got talent, but you never know how they'll
perform here,'' said Woody Woodward, M's vice president for
baseball operations. ``It's a very positive thing, the impression a
lot of these pitchers made, but you never know until you run them
out there in the season. It takes a lot of patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience won't be a buzzword in the stands, where fans are
expecting the Mariners to recover quickly from last year's 76-85
debacle. Players have the same expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a lot stronger,'' said David Segui, who is back at first
base as Jay Buhner, less than seven months off serious elbow
surgery, returns to right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't judge spring off wins and losses, but what we saw on
the mound was impressive. We know what we'll get from Jeff
(Fassero) and Jamie (Moyer) and the rest of the veteran guys, but
the eye-openers were the Hinchliffes, Garcias and Halamas. A lot of
guys stepped up in roles that we really needed. Our defense is
going to be much better, and when you take into consideration the
amount of runs this offense can score, if you put that together
with good pitching, it's going to allow us to win a lot of
ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Although at least one national publication _ Athlon's _ picked
the M's to win the wild-card, few are picking Seattle for first
place in the AL West. The reason most often cited is pitching,
which new catcher Tom Lampkin said is predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin, a former Blanchet High of Seattle star who signed with
the M's this winter after four years in the National League, said
he'd rather judge for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get a chance to see them first-hand, but after it's
beaten into your head on ``SportsCenter'' and all the other media
outlets, you're going to hear about it,'' he said. ``But it's a new
year, and you can throw all the numbers away and put them on the
back of your baseball card. I haven't seen any indication that this
staff is as bad as everyone says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pitching is better than a lot of people think, and we're
going to surprise some people.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero starts Monday night, hoping to erase a spring training
in which he had a 13.20 ERA. He will be followed by Moyer, who had
a solid spring, and Garcia, who was at times overpowering. Butch
Henry is the fourth starter, making his M's debut Friday against
the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
