<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-ROCKETS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS REBOUND TO .500 AFTER SNUFFING ROCKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They say this is it.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sonics' 101-84 win over the Houston Rockets on Sunday is
any indication, then that is the public service announcement for
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   This is when the Sonics get on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to have to be,'' center Olden Polynice said. ``We
need to definitely switch gears. We can't keep saying it's going to
get better. We did that the first 30 games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics (16-16) labored through the first 31 games in which
they talked a good game and played too many bad ones. But after
falling below .500 for the first time in nine seasons, the team
climbed back by demolishing one of the hottest teams in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Houston (22-11) had won 9 of its past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Sonics were the aggressive, irreverent bunch in
snapping a three-game losing streak. The Sonics picked apart the
Rockets with a frantic defense and offensive contributions
throughout the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star point guard Gary Payton's 30 points led the Sonics.
Backup point guard John Crotty scored 14 of his 19 points in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Crotty, who had just 25 points in seven games as a Sonic, summed
up the team's day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything went right,'' Crotty said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   The only smear was when the Sonics blew a 17-point lead in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They went into the final frame with a just a 65-61 advantage.
But the Sonics then distanced themselves from the Rockets by
scoring their most points in a quarter this season, and outscored
Houston 36-23 down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to come back home and lose. We want to start a
new streak _ going up,'' Polynice said. ``Our defense was the key.
We were very aggressive. We looked like last year's Sonics.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have not been as consistent as last year's team that
won 61 regular-season games. The team was coming off a brutal
five-games-in-six-nights stretch in which it finished with a 1-4
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying we've been playing hard on the road trip even
though we were only 1-4,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said. ``I
like a lot of what I've seen from how aggressively we've been
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   With swingman Billy Owens sitting out with a sore left knee,
Westphal used his ninth different starting lineup. Hersey Hawkins
was reinserted at shooting guard, Detlef Schrempf moved to small
forward and Aaron Williams got his first start this season at power
forward.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics got off to a fast start, pouncing on the Rockets with
a trapping defense that clogged the middle. They effectively
harassed Houston center Hakeem Olajuwon in the middle. Olajuwon
finished with 18 points and nine rebounds, but he was 2 of 6 in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   That, combined with Payton's early dominance, ignited the
Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Payton amassed 22 points in the first half and scored at will in
the paint and on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics led by nine after the first quarter. The team shot 50
percent in the first half and held the Rockets to 35-percent
shooting. What the defense gave up was 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Rockets misfired from long range. Houston missed 21
of 27 3-pointers. Forward Scottie Pippen was 0-for-4 from 3-point
range, and a non-factor the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense set the tone for the way the game went,''
Houston coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``The Sonics looked like they
were rested and we looked like we were playing back-to-backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, which hadn't played since Thursday's loss at Utah,
turned the ball over 14 times. The Sonics parlayed those miscues
into 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make them hurry the threes,'' said Westphal, whose
troops countered by making 10 of 19 3-pointers. Payton and Hawkins
each had three.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins' bomb with 4:02 left in the game was a dagger. The
basket put the Sonics ahead 86-76, and into a not-too-common cruise
control mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed this win desperately,'' Hawkins said. ``It was one
of those games where it's gut-check time, where you see what kind
of heart you have, you see what you're made of as a team.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Forward Vin Baker will practice again Monday, and
possibly attempt an early return after sitting out the past nine
games with a partially torn ligament in his right thumb. Baker
hopes to play Tuesday against Sacramento. ... Federal Way High
(Wash.) product Michael Dickerson finished with just two points on
1-for-9 shooting for Houston. ... With his 12 field goals, Payton
(4,499) passed Jack Sikma (4,493) for second place on the team's
list for career field goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
