<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S PAYING FOR AYALA TO PITCH ELSEWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With opening day upon them and the club desperate to
eliminate any lingering stink from last season, the Mariners got it
right _ for the most part.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Ayala was not only banished from Seattle, the Mariners
sent him across the continent (ITAL) and (END ITAL) north of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the right-hander is an Expo, Ayala's only hope is that
any boos that come his way will be in the unfamiliar patois of the
native Quebecois in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Canada is about as far as Ayala needed to be from the
Mariners, which proves that some moves a ballclub makes are as much
for symbolism as for the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   How much of Ayala's $1.8 million salary the Mariners are paying
the Expos to do them this huge favor is not a matter of public
record, but anything less than $1.5 million would fly in the face
of Expo tradition of maintaining baseball's lowest payroll.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Mariners are paying Ayala to pitch in
another city, another league, another country.
</P>
<P>
   Which means the Mariners have money to spend on absolute
necessities, like getting rid of a pitcher who is hurting them,
which makes you wonder why they could not have paid to get a
pitcher who could actually help them.
</P>
<P>
   As themes go for the start of a new season, this certainly is
not one the Mariners want. Not when there is so much goodwill to
restore among their suspicious fans. Not when the club is boasting
better defense and better clutch hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played better this spring, we have a clubhouse that is a
lot more energetic and we're not reading in the newspaper every day
about what's happening with Randy Johnson,'' Jeff Fassero, Monday
night's opening day pitcher, said Sunday about the difference
between last year and now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not one distraction here. Not one person with any
contract problems. Everyone is happy with the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the optimism of the season's start, but there was
serious talk about how the M's needed to bolster their rotation.
This winter, Woody Woodwardy, Mariners vice president of baseball
operations, wanted to go after Todd Stottlemyre or Tim Belcher, but
when Arizona and Anaheim offers were too high, the M's would not
play the free agent game.
</P>
<P>
   That fiscal restraint seemed penny-wise, pound foolish then. It
seems even more questionable now _ with Ayala gone, at a big price
_ why wasn't there money to throw at a pitcher who could bolster a
still-wonderful team populated with the likes of All-Stars Ken
Griffey, Alex Rodriguez, Edgar Martinez, Jay Buhner and Dan Wilson?
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have arrived on the threshold of 1999 with a
pitching staff that outside of Fassero, Jamie Moyer and Jose Mesa
could double for bubble-gum rockers Backstreet Boys. The combined
experience of six-tenths of the staff is fewer than 50 major league
baseball games.
</P>
<P>
   But at least they don't have Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, Bobby epitomized our past failures,'' Lou
Piniella said Sunday from his manager's office in the Kingdome
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some success here, but last year was just terrible. I
don't know what the response would have been here when he was
introduced (opening night), but it was clear that he was growing
more and more apprehensive as spring training came to a end.''
</P>
<P>
   This was most certainly a humanitarian act on the part of the
Mariners, who still like Ayala's arm and his forkball even though
he blew nine saves in '98 and became a lightning rod for Kingdome
rancor.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good deed on behalf of Ayala, who deserved a fresh
start.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be viewed as a good deed to the citizens of
Marinerville, whose late-innings' patience was worn so thin last
season that booing Ayala escalated to a sort of vicious art form.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, on the sick flip side of sports, sometimes the
crowd actually starts rooting for disaster. Another walk, another
blown save, another bullpen implosion.
</P>
<P>
   Sad to say, on everyone's part, but that's what happened last
season. And it started on Day One, when Ayala and his pen-mates
gave up four walks in the eighth inning and let a 9-6 lead over
Cleveland slip to a 10-9 loss, setting an awful tone for a
disappointing season that made the Kingdome a testy place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fans have a right to voice their opinion, but by
the same token, I don't think they should boo the guy just for
walking to the bullpen or standing up,'' Fassero said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They boo him coming out to the mound, he throws three strikes
and then they cheer him. Where's the sense in that?''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners could not afford to have last year's scenario
repeated. Not when the Kingdome is getting its last baseball opener
and a new stadium looms to the south, waiting for a smiley-happy
bunch of fans to push through the turnstiles.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala is gone, at a price. The pitching staff is still a big
question, at what price we'll soon find out.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
