<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZING OUTCOME TYPICAL OF ATYPICAL NBA SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A team of basketball scientists, working 24/7 for a
month, could not explain Sunday's outcome at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an NBA schedule made by Bart Simpson, the Houston
Rockets had been living in town long enough to meet state voting
requirements. The Sonics, meanwhile, were playing their sixth game
in eight days, and the first one at home in that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had been a good team getting better, evidenced by
nine wins in their past 10 games. The Sonics had been a decent team
going bad, evidenced by seven losses in their past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have a style, a direction and a purpose. The Sonics
make kindergarten recess look like a parade march at West Point.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? A 101-84 Sonic win that made sense in only in
that it made no sense.
</P>
<P>
   That means it was a fine metaphor for an NBA regular season so
haywire that almost nothing resonates from one day to the next. The
compressed schedule, the slapdash rosters and the Butterbean
lookalikes passing for pro basketball players have rendered this
exercise as disingenuous as a Bill Clinton affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of presidents ... read my typewritten lips: This
regular season will forecast almost nothing about playoff outcomes.
More weird creatures will emerge from this silliness than next
month's new ``Star Wars'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Rockets, who have three of the NBA's 50 greatest
players, were beaten mainly by the 19 points of Sonic backup point
guard John Crotty.
</P>
<P>
   No offense to Mr. and Mrs. Crotty, who raised a fine child, but
winning behind the young man is like winning a Pier Six brawl
because Bluto gets a paper cut.
</P>
<P>
   A waiver-wire pickup from the overstuffed Portland Trail
Blazers, Crotty, in seven previous games as a Sonic, scored 25
points. Then in one game, he nearly doubled his season total. Sonic
coach Paul Westphal could coach 10,000 more NBA games and never get
this same result.
</P>
<P>
   How Hakeem Olajuwon, Charles Barkley and Scottie Pippen let this
happen is a sports mystery that ranks with the continual granting
of a boxing promoter's license to Don King.
</P>
<P>
   As Barkley put it dryly: ``Giving him 19 in half (actually 14)
was not in our game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Heads were being scratched so much in the Rocket quarters that
scalp divots were visible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't believe we didn't have that edge against these
guys,'' said Rudy Tomjanovich, the bewildered Rockets coach. ``I
wish I had an answer for why we came out soft and non-aggressive
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich wasn't intending to put down the Sonics, but he,
too, had to figure the Sonics for pulp after a 1-4 road trip
smashed into six semi-horrifying days. Instead the Sonics played
with the kind of energy and poise that were utterly absent in their
last NBC national TV appearance _ a 104-87 embarrassment exactly a
week ago in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of that game, the Sonics were as pulseless
as the Rockets were in the opening period. Both teams were equally
without reasons for the rigor mortis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't do anything in the first half,'' Tomjanovich said.
``Give (the Sonics) credit, yeah, but it seemed like when there was
a loose ball, our guys bumped heads.''
</P>
<P>
   A more fitting word picture for this season has yet to be drawn.
But it isn't just the Rockets. The Sonics have been even more
buffoonish, and they're better than at least half the teams in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   The chaos extends into coaching. Sunday, Westphal went to his
ninth different starting lineup in 32 games, inserting backup
center Aaron Williams into the power forward spot, while Hersey
Hawkins returned again to start in place of Billy Owens, who sat
out again with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this particular lineup had no more influence on the outcome
than stock prices have on the tides. Williams had nine points and
seven rebounds in 16 minutes, and Hawkins made four field goals,
production that each could have had from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   A look around the league suggests that many teams are similarly
vexed. The Indiana Pacers can't win close games, the Miami Heat
suddenly can't win anything, the Utah Jazz have been in a downward
spiral and the Los Angeles Lakers are one thrown chair from a full
Jerry Springer show (``Freakazoid forward: Can't live with him,
can't live without him!'').
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the trendy NBA darlings, the Trail Blazers,
haven't gotten beyond the playoffs' first round practically since
Bill Walton wore a ponytail. Until they do, and until Isaiah Rider
doesn't need a bail bondsman on 24-hour call, don't speak of them
loudly.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, for all the talk of their rise and their stars, are
using an all-rookie starting backcourt of Michael Dickerson and
Cuttino Mobley _ a charade that was exposed embarrassingly. They
well may be good NBA players, but not now, and not next month when
the playoffs begin.
</P>
<P>
   There is no explaining this NBA season. And there is precious
little enjoyment of it, unless you're a fan of bonking heads and
24-percent free throw shooters.
</P>
<P>
   Given the flatness of the competition, the rise in popularity of
pro rasslin is beginning to make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
