<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER05-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHOLD THE COLD: WINTRY WEATHER MAKES LATE SHOWING IN ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Another spring storm hit Arizona on Easter morning,
forcing worshipers to move Phoenix-area sunrise services inside and
hiding the red rocks of Sedona under 8 inches of snow. Forecasters
say the unseasonably cold weather will continue at least until the
end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Some Valley families changed tradition, moving their annual egg
hunts inside from wet, muddy and _ in some places like Cave Creek
and Carefree _ snow-dusted yards.
</P>
<P>
   Low temperatures and snow canceled the final round of the 1999
Tradition golf tournament in north Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, drivers found slow going as police required
chains in some areas and closed roads in others.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's storm, the third in the past four days, dropped
Phoenix-area temperatures to a record afternoon low of 45, 36
degrees below normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way, this kind of weather is cold for here
even in the winter. But for April, it's really cold,'' said Craig
Ellis, a meteorologist for the National Weather Service's Phoenix
office.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix-area temperatures are expected to warm to the upper 60s
today then rise to the low 70s on Tuesday. Wednesday will bring
more rain and temperatures in the mid-60s. By Thursday and Friday,
temperatures will rise again to the mid- to upper 70s.
</P>
<P>
   But even by week's end, the temperatures are expected to be 10
to 15 degrees below normal, Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Another storm is expected to hit northern Arizona on Wednesday,
possibly dumping another 8 inches in Flagstaff and record snowfalls
in other cities, forecasters say.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One Ballpark kept its roof closed for the Diamondbacks
exhibition game against the Cleveland Indians. Once again, visitors
from the Midwest found balmier temperatures at home. Cleveland had
a high of 78 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix hit its Sunday high of 58 at 12:01 a.m. That's a record
low, Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Another cold, low-pressure system will move across the state
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's exactly sure why it's coming this cold this time of
year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no patio seating at popular brunch spots.
</P>
<P>
   The popular sunrise services atop Squaw Peak were moved to one
of the ramadas near the parking area.
</P>
<P>
   And the Easter storm left empty picnic tables at Phoenix's
Encanto Park on its busiest picnic day of the year. Some families
huddled under tarps but a few just ignored the cold and hid eggs in
the wet grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so bad,'' said Brenda Mendez, 8, as she peeled the
colorful shell off a boiled egg. ``It's better than having to hide
them in the house, this is harder,'' said the second-grader from
Washington Elementary School, who came to the park with her family.
</P>
<P>
   While Phoenix-area residents were challenged to find indoor
activities for out-of-town guests, those in northern Arizona faced
even bigger problems.
</P>
<P>
   Chains were required for drivers on Interstates 17 and 40 near
Flagstaff where 9 inches of snow set down Sunday. That brings the
month's total to 29 inches, the same amount at the city got all
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona University canceled today's classes to keep
students who traveled home for Easter weekend off the roads.
University officials will decide Tuesday at 6 a.m. when to re-open.
</P>
<P>
   Sedona got a record 8 inches, said Darren McCollum, a
meteorologist with the weather service's Flagstaff office.
</P>
<P>
   East of Phoenix, two adults and six children found themselves
stranded in the wilderness off Arizona 87 near Four Peaks when
their van got stuck in the snow, the Maricopa County Sheriff's
Office reported. The group was camping, had food and heat, and
wasn't in danger, deputies said. A snow plow will clear the road,
and the eight were expected back in town late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The three spring storms that hit are surprising, forecasters
say, though not unheard of. The high snow totals occur about five
times every 100 years, McCollum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first storm was amazing, the second was too, but to get
three, that's another thing,'' he said. ``But to think we might get
another _ wow.'' &QL; 
Laura Trujillo can be reached at (602) 444-8891 or at
laura.trujillo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
