<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5853 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUGDEATHS-AZR &LR;      04-05 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGDEATHS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUGS LINKED TO KILLING OF 3: FAKE BOOBY TRAPS DIDN'T DETER KILLER
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The wires hung from windows, walls and ceiling were
supposed to look like booby traps set to snare any would-be
thieves. But the decoys didn't stop someone from shooting three
people to death Sunday inside the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Parks, 37, and his sister, Shelly Parks, 33, died in the
living room of the apartment, police said. A third man, whom police
did not identify, was found shot to death in a back bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Wires were strung menacingly throughout the apartment, and the
bomb squad spent an hour looking for tripwires or any explosives
before detectives entered to gather evidence, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the family were afraid to go into there for fear of booby
traps,'' said Lt. Mike DeBenedetto, head of the bomb squad.
</P>
<P>
   All the wire ended up being stereo wire _ some actually hooked
up to speakers but most hooked up to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, police said they found drugs they believe were sold
at the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   DeBenedetto said drug dealers will sometimes put the word on the
street that their places are booby-trapped to prevent thefts.
</P>
<P>
   There was a surveillance camera trained on the front room where
the Parks siblings were found, DeBenedetto said. The monitor for
the camera was in the bedroom where the unidentified man died, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The camera was also hooked to a VCR, but there was no tape
inside it, DeBenedetto said.
</P>
<P>
   A yellow flier posted on the front window warned in red letters,
``Continuous Video Taping.'' There was a faded ``Beware of Dog''
sign on the door frame, but there was no dog inside. Black tape
held wire to one window. The other front window was covered in
aluminium foil.
</P>
<P>
   The patio held furniture, tools and bicycles. A tag on one of
the bikes read, ``$160 obo.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend found the bodies just before 7 a.m. Sunday, police
said. Neighbors said they heard shots and screams around 3 a.m.,
but didn't call 911, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they have no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Stone, 45, who lives across a courtyard from the
apartment, described the apartment's occupants as ``long-hair
types, but they were pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone said he asked one of the men, whom he described as a
``Harley-Davidson type'' what all the stuff was on the patio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he bought and sold things and that's how he made
money,'' Stone said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said he didn't notice an unusual amount of traffic in and
out of the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any noise,'' he said. ``If they partied, they
did it quietly.'' &QL; 
Richard Ruelas can be reached at (602) 444-8473 or at
richard.ruelas(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
