<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-ART-1     04-05 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO BROADENS ITS TARGETS, YUGOSLAV TV REPORTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting)  (ART ADV: Map, of sites attacked, is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MOBILIZE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-MILITARY, KOSOVO-U.S.-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MEDIA,
KOSOVO-GENEVA, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERMONS, KOSOVO-FAMILIES,
KOSOVO-INTERNET, KOSOVO-POPE) 
(sw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ NATO cruise missiles and bombers struck
Serbia hard again early on Monday morning, the 13th day of the
bombing campaign, with targets ranging from the air force
headquarters in Zemun, in greater Belgrade, to a factory in Nis,
the Serbian state television reported.
</P>
<P>
   State television urged viewers to remain in air raid shelters in
case of further strikes on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   According to the television, there were also new attacks at
Belgrade's Surcin airport, 10 miles from the city, and Pristina's
Slatina airport, which have both civilian and military landing
strips.
</P>
<P>
   A civil defense headquarters at Raska, 100 miles southwest of
Belgrade, was also hit. The most spectacular television footage was
from Nis, where huge flames were seen rising high above trees at an
unspecified industrial facility.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:30 a.m. anti-aircraft fire was visible in the skies over
central Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks were the latest in a widening series of strikes all
over Serbia on civilian as well as military infrastructure. The
official Yugoslav news media reported Sunday that at least 4
civilians had been killed and 17 wounded in the strikes overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Some citizens of Belgrade interviewed Sunday expressed new
concern about how long the bombing would last, how many civilian
targets NATO would hit and how the war would end.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns were more widespread among older people who
remember World War II. One of them, a skittish retiree of 68 named
Bojan, returning from church with a sprig of willow on the Orthodox
Palm Sunday, asked that his surname not be used. ``There is more
fear today, that NATO will hit anywhere,'' he said. He also
suggested that his friends ``are more afraid to talk about politics
and to make political jokes on the telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, central Belgrade filled again on Sunday
afternoon with thousands of people attending the daily anti-NATO
rock concert and wearing the target symbol that has swept the city.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, there was no official word about military or civilian
casualties in Kosovo, where NATO is trying to stop Serbian forces
from destroying the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army and forcing more
ethnic Albanian citizens to flee.
</P>
<P>
   There was also no official response to charges made Sunday by
the NATO spokesman, Jamie P. Shea, that television footage of a
meeting said to have taken place on Thursday in Belgrade between
President Slobodan Milosevic and the pacifist ethnic Albanian
leader Ibrahim Rugova had been faked from footage taken two years
ago. Shea said Rugova remained under house arrest in Pristina, the
Kosovo capital.
</P>
<P>
   Given that there was no sound track for the footage, there were
immediate doubts about what Rugova had said, and even whether the
meeting had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Ministry officials, asked on Friday whether there was
any doubt that the two men had met, scoffed at the idea, but a
request to interview Rugova went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, an official government statement referred to the
meeting, saying, ``After the Milosevic-Rugova meeting, there is a
strengthening conviction of the people of Kosovo that this crisis
can be solved through political means.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday, NATO planes struck bridges, fuel depots, a heating
plant, an oil refinery and a Interior Ministry academy in Belgrade
said to be used for the instruction of high-ranking intelligence
officials. A military hospital near the academy suffered broken
windows, but apparently there were no further casualties among the
patients.
</P>
<P>
   NATO missiles also smashed the Pancevo oil refinery, some 10
miles northeast of Belgrade, killing two refinery workers and
wounding four others, the official Tanjug news agency reported
Sunday. Three more people were reported wounded when a fuel depot
near the town of Kraljevo, 75 miles south of Belgrade, was also
hit.
</P>
<P>
   A 73-year-old woman was killed and seven people were wounded in
another NATO attack _ the third so far _ on the Sloboda factory in
the industrial town of Cacak, 50 miles south of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday, NATO also destroyed a heating plant in the New
Belgrade district, across the Sava River from the old city center,
filling the sky with flame from a burning fuel storage depot. Three
people were wounded at the plant, according to official media, and
supplies of hot water to thousands of people were cut. A police
academy in the Banjica suburb was also destroyed, but there were no
reported casualties.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday about 8 p.m., NATO destroyed a second bridge over
the Danube River at Novi Sad, leaving only one railway bridge. The
Beta news agency said that cars were using the bridge when a
central span was destroyed, and that seven people on the bridge at
the time were badly wounded. On Sunday, boats ferried people across
the river.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also damaged another Danube River bridge at Backa Palanka,
near the Croatian border.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav media also sharply criticized NATO-led forces in
Bosnia for destroying a railroad link between Serbia and
Montenegro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
