</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BRINGING OUT THE DEAD &LR;  By Joe Connelly. Vintage Contemporaries,
$12. Frank Pierce, a paramedic working the night shift in the
Hell's Kitchen neighborhood of New York, is driven to emotional
exhaustion by the brutal world he witnesses. Last year in The New
York Times Book Review, Charley Rosen called this ``a stunning
first novel'' and praised ``the vigorous rhythms of Connelly's
writing _ the poetry of broken bodies and broken lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILD THOUGHTS FROM WILD PLACES &LR;  By David Quammen.
Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $13. This collection of magazine
articles covers a lot of territory _ from the Missouri River to
Tasmania to Chile _ but is grounded in the author's reverence for
the natural world. ``Quammen easily passes the acid test of any
essayist: He is a good companion,'' James Gorman wrote in 1998.
``He has a wide range of knowledge, an agile pen and a generous
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RED HOURGLASS: LIVES OF THE PREDATORS &LR;  By Gordon Grice.
Delta, $11.95. This is an arrestingly macabre ode to rattlesnakes,
black widow spiders, tarantulas, jackals and other creepy critters.
Grice ``combines the observations of a naturalist with a dry,
homespun philosopher's wit,'' Richard Bernstein wrote last year in
The New York Times. ``This is first-rate, unsentimental writing
about nature and about the ways that human beings try to cope with
the most terrible cruelties that nature offers up.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PACK OF CARDS: AND OTHER STORIES &LR;  By Penelope Lively. Grove,
$13. A young intellectual and his materialistic girlfriend, a
sharp-eyed grandmother visiting her daughter in London and an
agoraphobic housewife are among the characters featured in these
realistic, small-bore tales of British life in the Thatcher years.
``Lively writes beautifully, with meticulous detachment,'' Jay
Parini wrote in 1989. ``The stories ... are uniformly entertaining
and, often, inspired.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued the author's first novel,  &UR; THE
ROAD TO LICHFIELD &LR;  ($12), in which a 40-year-old suburban mother
traveling back and forth to an English village to tend to her dying
father falls in love with one of his neighbors. In 1991 Ellen Pall
called this ``a homey, companionable book'' that is ``concerned
with time and memory.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CHILDREN &LR;  By David Halberstam. Fawcett/Ballantine, $17.95.
The author, who was a young reporter in Nashville, Tenn., in the
1950s, tells the story of the black college students there whose
protests were instrumental in igniting the civil rights movement.
The result is a ``powerful, densely packed'' narrative, David M.
Oshinsky wrote last year. ``There is much to admire in Halberstam's
book.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; KILLING THE DREAM: JAMES EARL RAY AND THE ASSASSINATION OF
MARTIN LUTHER KING, JR. &LR; , by Gerald Posner (Harvest/Harcourt Brace,
$15), the writer who attacked Kennedy conspiracy theories in ``Case
Closed'' takes on Ray's claim of innocence in the 1968 murder of
King. This skeptical account is ``a model of investigation,
meticulous in its discovery and presentation of evidence,'' Anthony
Lewis wrote in 1998. ``And it is a wonderfully readable book, as
gripping as a first-class detective story.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KALIMANTAAN &LR;  By C.S. Godshalk. Owl/Holt, $14. In the 19th
century, a young Englishman is driven by his idealized love for his
dead mother to create his own private raj in Borneo and help the
British government expand its trading empire. This is ``a first
novel of formidable imaginative power,'' Annette Kobak wrote in
1998. ```Kalimantaan' is the work of a born storyteller.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GEORGIA O'KEEFFE: A LIFE &LR;  By Roxana Robinson. University Press
of New England, $19.95. This authorized biography chronicles the
artist's long life and career and ``does much to give body to the
O'Keeffe myth,'' Hayden Herrera wrote in 1989. ``The author
presents a person who was both vulnerable and fierce, passionate
and coolly withholding, sensuous yet oddly unsexual.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DARKNESS VISIBLE &LR;  By William Golding. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$13. This disturbing novel explores the intertwined fates of a boy
hideously scarred during the London blitz and a set of beautiful
twins scarred by their father's icy neglect. ``Golding's magical
fable ... draws us with seductive words into a vision of elemental
reality so vivid we seem to hallucinate the scenes,'' John Thompson
wrote in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAFE EUROPA: LIFE AFTER COMMUNISM &LR;  By Slavenka Drakulic.
Penguin, $12.95. In these essays, a Croatian journalist finds a
metaphor for the daunting problems of Eastern Europe in the bad
teeth of her friends and relatives. ```Cafe Europa' ... is studded
with such everyday observations that open out, like windows, to
reveal wide-angled historical vistas,'' Michiko Kakutani wrote in
The New York Times in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNEXPECTED SALAMI &LR;  By Laurie Gwen Shapiro. Algonquin,
$10.95. At the center of this 1990s screwball comedy are a spoiled
New Yorker, her Aussie bass-player boyfriend and his ex-bandmate, a
recovering heroin addict who is taken in by a Jewish-Italian family
in New York. It all makes for an ``endearingly quirky first
novel,'' Anthony Bourdain wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
