<P>
   The $3.9 billion program began in the early 1990's and has had a
nearly unending series of setbacks. Lockheed has two more chances
to pass the test or face another $20 million in penalties.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ELIZABETH BECKER
</P>
<P>
   Sony Gives Up on 007
</P>
<P>
   In a James Bond caper with a decidedly 1990s twist, the prize
was not a nuclear bomb, or killer satellite, but _ what else? _ a
movie deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Pictures Entertainment announced 18 months ago that it had
signed a deal to make new Bond films, essentially trying to grab a
piece of one of Hollywood's most lucrative and durable franchises
from its current home, Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Inc. The fighting was
furious, but now Sony Pictures has dropped its plans to pursue
Agent 007.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Pictures received a net payment of $5 million to give up on
the franchise, and the elusive Bond escaped yet another diabolical
plot.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES STERNGOLD
</P>
<P>
   Government Is Ready for Y2K
</P>
<P>
   Through a combination of subtle pressure and public exhortation,
a White House official named John Koskinen has galvanized a small
army of federal computer managers to get their machines in shape
for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen reports that 92 percent of the government's critical
computer systems are free of year 2000 problems. And he predicts
that the laggards will fix their computers so Medicare and Medicaid
claims can be paid on time and air traffic controllers can guide
planes safely into the new year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT PEAR
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
