<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 08:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5930 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BBO-MCGWIRE-REVIEW-     04-05 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BBO-MCGWIRE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 CHANGE-UP FOR McGWIRE: A SLUGGER PITCHES QUESTIONS  
 (The Week in Review)  
 (duplication warning: also sent with `s' code)  
 (editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN SCHWARZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Mark McGwire's eyes lit up as if he'd just seen
a down-the-pipe fastball. Expecting yet another, ``Can you hit 70
home runs again?'' question-and-answer fest, the St. Louis
Cardinals slugger was asked if he'd like to reverse roles and pose
questions to other people for a change. ``That's great,'' he said,
clearly relieved. ``I love it!''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire came up with one question for a dozen people from
baseball and beyond. Some declined to answer _ President Clinton
passed on, ``Are you glad Sammy Sosa and I took some pressure off
you last summer?'' _ but most everyone enjoyed giving the most
interviewed man in sports a break. With today being Opening Day, it
might be his last. McGwire's questions and his subjects' answers
follow.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALAN SCHWARZ
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Rich DeLucia of the California Angels has
only a 38-50 career major league pitching record, but he owns
McGwire, yielding him just a single and double in 19 at-bats. This
begged McGwire's question, ``Why don't you ever throw me anything
over the plate?''(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   DeLucia: Last year there were 70 balls over the plate, I know
that. I'm not stupid. I just try to get ahead of him and then move
the ball off the plate. If you miss early and you have to come over
the plate, you're in trouble. I throw him down and away hard stuff
and belt-high up and in. But believe me, out of all those at-bats,
I'm sure I got lucky sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Garth Brooks lived his dream this spring
training by trying out for the San Diego Padres. His Mitty-esque
pursuit prompted McGwire to ask him, ``Do you know anyplace where I
can sing country music?''(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Brooks: Tell Mark he'd better buy his own record label. That's
the best way to do it. But tell him not to quit his day job. He's
too good at what he does.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Tim Forneris, a 22-year-old computer analyst
from Collinsville, Ill., and part-timer on the Cardinals grounds
crew, retrieved McGwire's record-breaking 62d home run ball last
Sept. 8 _ and baffled some by giving it to McGwire rather than
auctioning it off for $1 million or more. But Forneris didn't go
away empty-handed: A Chrysler dealer gave him a fully loaded red
minivan with ``No. 62'' license plates. McGwire wanted to know,
``Hey, how's the van running?''(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Forneris: It's running awesome! The only problem is it's much
bigger than my old car. I've had a tough time parking and I hope I
don't cut people off and cause an accident.
</P>
<P>
   I met Mark at a dinner a few days after they gave me the van.
You might remember he got a '62 Corvette the night he hit 62, and
he was telling me that he was having a hard time fitting into it _
he's so big. I told him, ``Next year in St. Louis, we can
car-pool.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Steve Trachsel of the Chicago Cubs threw the
down-and-in fastball that McGwire slammed for No. 62. McGwire
asked, ``Was that as good a pitch as I thought it was?''(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel: It was actually a little lower than I'd planned. We'd
had success and other teams had had success pitching him up and in,
and I was trying to do that that night, too. I pretty much missed
my spot and he got it.
</P>
<P>
   The attention hasn't been bad at all. Hey, he couldn't have done
it without me.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Joe McIlvaine, now a Minnesota Twins
executive, used the Mets' No. 1 overall pick in the 1984 draft on a
future washout, Shawn Abner, instead of McGwire, who slid to the
Oakland A's nine picks later. McGwire asked McIlvaine a question
Mets fans surely want answered as well: ``Why didn't you take me
No. 1?''(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine: We called the night before the draft and talked for
45 minutes with his father. We never once mentioned money. Our
question was, ``If we draft your son, would you have any interest
in signing with the New York Mets?'' They kept saying: ``We need
more time. We're not sure. We like the West Coast. . . . '' They
just wouldn't say they'd be interested in signing with us. Do I
regret not taking him? Of course. He was my pick. I loved him.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Gene Hackman is McGwire's favorite actor.
Recalling Hackman's role as a basketball coach, McGwire asked,
``Could you manage a baseball team as well as you coached the team
in `Hoosiers'?''(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Hackman, clearly baffled: I wouldn't want people to think I
actually know how to coach a basketball team. I'm just an actor who
plays a part.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)When McGwire hit No. 62, the Cubs' first
baseman, Mark Grace, patted the slugger's behind as he jogged by.
The two occasionally golf together in the offseason _ prompting
McGwire to ask, ``Hey, how many strokes you gonna give me the next
time we play?''(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Grace: Hmmm. Because of his celebrity status, I'll have to give
him a celebrity stroke. But only one celebrity mulligan per round.
</P>
<P>
   He's pretty much a gorilla off the tee. And he chips and putts
like his driving. You can print that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 0849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
