<SLUG> BC-R-SOCSEC-MEDICARE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON SOCIAL SECURITY, THE GOOD NEWS IS BAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(EDITORS: This text is a precede for the graphic cited above. It is
recommended for use only with the graphic.)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At first blush, last week's news from the Medicare
and Social Security trustees was good. The economy over the last
year has been so strong, actuaries found, that even with no changes
in the law, the Medicare system should be solvent until 2015, seven
years longer than previously expected, and Social Security reserves
should be sufficient to pay full retirement benefits until 2034,
two years more than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, President Clinton and Republican leaders were quick to
say that the wise course would still be to resolve their
differences and act this year to put Medicare and Social Security
on sound footing. But the truth is that for Congress, now on recess
for Passover and Easter, the news was political manna. It made the
problem of the insolvency of the two largest and most popular
federal programs seem less urgent. And it provided an excuse for
postponing tough decisions until after the next election.
</P>
<P>
   But data buried in the trustees' report illustrated why the
matter cannot be put off indefinitely. The figures showed how the
ratio of people of retirement age (who receive Medicare and Social
Security benefits) to those of working age (who pay the taxes that
finance the benefits) will rise after the baby boomers begin to
retire. This almost certainly means that sooner or later taxes will
have to be increased or retirement benefits reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, for example, there will be 210 people age 65 and over
for every 1,000 people ages 20 through 64. By 2030, the number of
Americans of retirement age will rise by 69 percent to 354 for
every 1,000 people of working age. And by 2075, it is projected
that the figure will nearly double.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 0849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0076 </DOCNO>
