<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 09:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5941 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-CARPHONE-KAN &LR;      04-05 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-CARPHONE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, COMEUPPANCE FOR MOTORISTS WHO WON'T HANG UP AND DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brooklyn (no, not that Brooklyn; the one in Ohio near Cleveland)
has done a marvelous thing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It would behoove all communities everywhere to follow suit.
Brooklyn has banned the use of cellular phones by people driving
cars. Well, almost. The newly passed ordinance says it's a minor
misdemeanor for a driver to use a cell phone unless both hands are
on the wheel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The law makes an exception for ``emergencies,'' which I take to
be something more serious than needing to order pizza for your
Dow10K party. And the Solons of Brooklyn will let you use a car
phone if the transmission is in ``park'' or if you use a
speakerphone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I do not know how many accidents car phones cause, but surely
more than they get blamed for. I do know that most drivers can't
even drive and breathe at the same time without losing
concentration. Driving and telecommunicating is altogether beyond
the capacity of most humans to sustain safely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So I applaud the eminent good sense of the leaders of Brooklyn
and I suggest this is a battle all people of good will should
join. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It would be progress, in fact, if, as a start, we could simply
get all the other Brooklyns in this country to adopt similar
ordinances. Besides the Brooklyn in Ohio _ and the one in New York
I alluded to in the opening paragraph of this remarkably sensible
column _ you will find Brooklyns in Connecticut, Illinois, Indiana,
Iowa, Maryland, Michigan and Mississippi, to say nothing of
Brooklyn Center and Brooklyn Park, both in Minnesota. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can find them if, that is, you know where to look for
them. Some of them _ like my essay on ``How Al Gore Invented the
Internet'' _ don't take up much space. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But while we're trying to spread the no-car-phones movement, I
think we should not neglect several other modern automobile
hazards, annoyances and idiocies that need reform. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, is there no municipal statesperson anywhere in the
country with the chutzpah and foresight to lead the drive for an
ordinance that would ban the playing of any car radio, tape deck or
CD player that can be heard anywhere outside that very car? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the city council of my own community would adopt that
ordinance, I would speak kindly of its members for years. And the
best part is that my honorific words might actually be heard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and while we're banning various appliances and distracting
car devices, let's make it illegal for drivers to shave, apply
makeup or consume a six-course dinner while cruising the highways.
Please, people, the person you kill while edging your sideburns,
lipsticking your mouth or devouring a leg of ram might be me. And I
would take a very dim view of such an outcome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also, can we please get rid of stupid bumper stickers and
``Knucklehead on Board'' signs that demand our attention as we come
up behind or alongside other cars? We already have way too much
information flowing our way from way too many sources. There is no
public demand at all for you to tell us via a bumper sticker what
your position is on Kosovo or nuclear waste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm happy you've developed a position on Kosovo. So have I. But
if it can be contained on a bumper sticker, it's so amazingly
moronic and meaningless that you should not want to advertise and
reveal its nincompoopness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if I see such an annoying bumper sticker on your car, I
will pull off the road, find a pay phone, ring your car phone and
tell you how dumb it is. If you're stupid enough to answer while
driving, I win the point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
