<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5969 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FED-FINANCIAL06-COX     04-05 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-FINANCIAL06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEDERAL FINANCIAL RECORDS STILL A MESS, AUDIT FINDS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Suppose a major corporation sent out an annual
report confessing to problems with fundamental record-keeping that
kept the company from accurately reporting a significant portion of
its assets, liabilities, and costs.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose that same company admitted that last year, it wrote
checks for billions of dollars in improper payments, had only a
rough estimate of its loans, and lacked adequate records for a
majority of its buildings, facilities and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Few people would seek to invest in such a company.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is the financial condition of the U.S. government and
its 24 major departments and agencies, according to the 1998
financial audit released last week.
</P>
<P>
   So faulty is the bookkeeping, in fact, that government auditors
disclaimed any opinion about the reliability of the financial
statements from most of the agencies.
</P>
<P>
   These deficiencies significantly impair the federal government's
ability to adequately safeguard assets, properly record
transactions, and comply with selected
</P>
<P>
   provisions of laws and regulations related to financial
reporting, U.S. Comptroller
</P>
<P>
   David M. Walker said in his overview of the audit.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin pointed out that it was only
the second year that the government has attempted such an
accounting and said it represented an important step in providing
the American public with useful information about their government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The progress we have made to date is extraordinary,'' said
Edward DeSeve, deputy director for management in the White House
Office of Management and Budget. ``We are working hard to resolve
the problems, but much work remains to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Progress is coming, but we've sure got a lot to do,'' agreed
Rep. Steve Horn, R-Calif., chairman of the House Government Reform
subcommittee on government management, information and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the public can learn from the 90-page report issued
by the U.S. General Accounting Office:
</P>
<P>
   _ The government can't balance its checkbook. A private citizen
may struggle over a few dollars that throw a bank account off
balance at the end of the month. The government last year had an
unexplained $24 billion, which bookkeepers simply plugged into the
federal financial statement as unreconciled transactions. The
Treasury Department has attributed the problem to a failure to
track transactions among federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Agencies do not keep good records of how money is spent. They
were unable to
</P>
<P>
   support significant portions of the more than $1.8 trillion
reported as the total net cost of government operations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medicare, which has been listed as in grave financial danger
already, doles out a huge amount of improper payments. The program
made $12.7 billion in improper
</P>
<P>
   fee-for-service medical payments. Although that was down from
$20 billion the
</P>
<P>
   year before, the error rate for 1998 was still huge, 7 percent
of the fee-for-service program.
</P>
<P>
   _ Computers, vital to government operations, have been poorly
safeguarded and
</P>
<P>
   vulnerable to fraud and illegal snooping, even at the Defense
Department. Attackers have accessed systems and stolen, modified,
and destroyed both data and
</P>
<P>
   software at the Defense Department and shut down entire systems,
said the audit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Internal Revenue Service computers are so inadequate that the
tax agency regularly pursues collection efforts against taxpayers
who already have paid in full.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the end of 1998, the government had no accurate accounting
for its loan and credit programs. It reported that it was owed $167
billion and that it had liabilities of $38 billion for loans that
it had guaranteed against default. Auditors said those
</P>
<P>
   amounts could not be reasonably estimated because of a lack of
adequate historical data or other evidence.
</P>
<P>
   _ The government reported that it had $225 billion in
liabilities for cleaning up
</P>
<P>
   hazardous waste caused chiefly by weapons systems and other
military operations. The auditors said that amount was understated
by at least tens of billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
