<HEADER>
A6001 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN06-C     04-05 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fears of Y2K bug mean all work, no play
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For years, many Americans have been planning to party
madly at midnight on New Year's Eve 1999. As the 12 o'clock
countdown begins, they want to hear horns, fireworks, cheers and
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   But what they may hear is a chorus of beepers. ... assuming the
beepers work. Millions of would-be celebrants are just now
realizing that because of the Y2K computer bug, they will be
sitting at their desks on 12-31-99, not dancing in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers, computer programmers, factory supervisors, government
regulators and many others who haven't worked a holiday since they
waited on tables in college are being warned not to make party
plans for New Year's Eve. They will be needed to help ward off
snafus related to the Year 2000 Bug, or Y2K, the software flaw that
could cause equipment to malfunction when the year changes.
</P>
<P>
   Many computers and computer chips embedded in equipment were
programmed to read only the last two digits of the year, so 1999 is
read as 99. When the date changes from 99 to 00, the computers and
chips may interpret the date as 1900 and become confused enough to
shut down. Computer programmers are working furiously to stamp out
such bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Though most businesses and governmental agencies insist they
will be fully prepared for Dec. 31, many bosses are taking no
chances. They will want staff on duty to fix any glitches or simply
to reassure customers and journalists that everything is going
well. So throughout the land, word is going out: Don't even think
about taking vacationbetween Christmas and New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   As a journalist for CNN, Clay Owen ``was used to working on the
4th of July, Thanksgiving, Christmas and New Year's.'' By moving to
the corporate world, ``I thought I had finally gotten out of
working every holiday,'' said the BellSouth spokesman, who will be
handling press inquiries about potential Y2K problems on New Year's
Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Owen will be among the hordes of phone company supervisors,
programmers and others stationed in places ``where we can keep an
eye on the system.'' Even those who aren't expected to work will be
``on call,'' he said. Many bankers who usually work, well, bankers'
hours will be burning the midnight oil rather than lighting
firecrackers. At the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta, the lights
will be shining in the offices of supervisors and others who ``will
be working to ensure that things are progressing well,'' bank
spokesman Pierce Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Even U.S. workers stationed in other countries will be downing
only dry data at midnight and even days beyond. For example,
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the financial services company with 64,000
employees worldwide, has ordered managers and other key personnel
to remain tethered to their desks from Dec. 1 through Feb. 15,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   And for some government regulators, monitoring the millennium
midnight will be more than a job, it'll be an adventure. Take
Federal Aviation Administration chief Jane Garvey. Like aviation
officials in countries from China to England, Garvey has promised
to be flying in a airplane on New Year's Eve to show confidence in
the air-traffic control system.
</P>
<P>
   The most exciting thing expected to happen on her flight is that
a few passengers may toss their peanuts in the air and exchange
kisses. It may not be the most lavish New Year's Eve party, but
it's all the excitement Garvey and other FAA officials will want.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Y2K, visit these Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   www.bytewise.com/atlyear2000/
</P>
<P>
   www.igc.org/millennium/
</P>
<P>
   millennium(at)whitehouse.gov
</P>
<P>
   www.everything2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
