<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Hey, just kidding!
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ There's a fine line between humor and insult.
Comedian Don Rickles, the master of insult, built a career on
knowing where that line was. Our sons haven't figured it out yet,
but they're about to.
</P>
<P>
   They've entered an annoying phase (is there one that isn't?) in
which they say something that draws an unfavorable response, then
they try to make it all right by smiling and saying ``Just
kidding!''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't working.
</P>
<P>
   As is normal with teens, they're testing their _ and my _
limits. The latest is this ``just kidding'' phase. Here's how they
try to make it work:
</P>
<P>
   ``How come we never go skiing over spring break?''
</P>
<P>
   (Parents quickly snarl something about money growing on trees.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Just kidding!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, that shirt's kinda straining the buttons, old man.''
</P>
<P>
   (Weighty reply from Dad in angry tone.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Just kidding!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you always have to know where I'm going and who will be
there?''
</P>
<P>
   (Parents leap from chairs, backing child into a corner.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Just kidding!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you ever cook anything worth eating?''
</P>
<P>
   (Mom replies with well-chosen words, each syllable emphasized by
a jabbing motion with wooden spoon.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Just kidding!''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if we don't ``chill'' and ``lighten up'' and ``get
over it,'' then we're just uptight fuddy-duddies who can't take a
joke.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how a joke works, boys. If just one of us is smiling, and
it isn't a parent, then it isn't a joke.
</P>
<P>
   There's another angle to this whole ``just kidding'' thing. They
use it as a trial balloon _ you know, run a wild idea up the
flagpole and see who goes ballistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go pick up a bunch of the guys and then go over
to some girls' houses and then go to a late movie and I'll probably
spend the night at somebody's house. Good-bye!''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing my eyeballs bulge, my face redden in anger and the steam
begin to come from my ears, my son backs off quickly with ``Just
kidding!''
</P>
<P>
   You know what, kids, I'm tired of the kidding.
</P>
<P>
   I don't recall having a handy, quick-draw phrase like that when
I was growing up. If I had dared open my mouth to, say, criticize
my mother's cooking, I would have found myself in my bedroom until
7 the next morning, starving for whatever incredibly delicious food
she would deign to put on the table.
</P>
<P>
   If I had had the nerve to tell my dad it was none of his
business where I was going and who I would be with, I would have
been going nowhere and seeing no one other than my immediate family
for a whole week.
</P>
<P>
   A feeble ``Just kidding'' wouldn't have changed my fate, either.
</P>
<P>
   But, you know, I'm willing to play the game a bit. Let's see if
I can get the hang of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son, I'm not happy with your study habits, so you can't drive
again until you bring home straight As.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys, if I see your clothes scattered all over your floor like
this again, you're grounded from the computer and TV for a week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since you don't like what I cook for dinner, you're making
dinner for the next two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you've complained about how I iron your cargo pants,
with these stupid luggage-sized pockets on each outer leg, you can
do your own ironing from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   But here's the punchline, guys. ``I'm not kidding!''
</P>
<P>
   Geez fellas, chill. Where's your sense of humor?
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
