<HEADER>
A6005 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN06-COX     04-05 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Read this! Important column below
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ ``Important message.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone rush to open an e-mail that says ``important
message''? Like people, e-mails that announce their importance
usually aren't important. Yet the header worked. It helped deliver
the Melissa computer virus to systems around the world.
</P>
<P>
   If you use Microsoft Word and open the computer file that comes
with the Melissa bug e-mail, the program will find your e-mail
address book and mail itself to the addresses it finds. Then it
will let your cat out, stain the carpet with fruit juice and burn
popcorn in the microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Those last dangers are hypothetical. They involve the virus
working with suggestible 13-year-olds. It seems possible.
</P>
<P>
   I am becoming ever more grateful for the boring reliability of
the mailbox at the end of my driveway. The worst thing it has done
to me lately has been to accept junk mail in envelopes printed to
look like tax refunds. Fools me every time.
</P>
<P>
   In my electronic mailbox, by contrast, I've received the Melissa
and Happy99 viruses within a month of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Happy99 shows a hokey little fireworks display and then attaches
itself to your outgoing e-mails. If the recipients, in turn, click
on the attachment, they also will see the hokey little fireworks
display and it will go out on their e-mails. And so on and so on
around the world forever.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, I did not open the Melissa or Happy99 files. I
deleted Melissa unopened because I saw the heading ``important
message'' and assumed it was junk mail. By the time Happy99 got to
me I had already heard about the way it made people unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   Close calls.
</P>
<P>
   Next time I may not be so lucky. If somebody is bright enough to
use the header ``Do Not Open Under Any Circumstances'' that would
be it. My number would be up, my virtual goose metaphorically
cooked, my posterior fit to be mowed.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how I'd respond if a more savvy virus-maker came up
with a header that directly challenged my perverse nature. I don't
think I want to know.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail headers are a powerful new literary form. As we get more
mail, it's harder to tell it apart. This forces us to be our own
headline writers and come up with cooler or louder headers. Few of
us are any good at it.
</P>
<P>
   I send out e-mail with headers like: Stuff, Hectic Friday,
Misc., Hey ... . To think I was once paid American money to write
hard-copy headlines.
</P>
<P>
   When we write old-fashioned lick-the-envelope-shut mail, we
don't have to write a header that shouts ``pick me! pick me!'' from
the swarm of incoming data. A handwritten envelope can accomplish
the same thing in a fistful of hard-copy junk mail.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-mailers also have the advantage of not being expected to
say what's on our mind until the third paragraph. You are supposed
to say hello, offer profuse apologies for not writing earlier and
then say a word about the weather, changing seasons or the
children's state of health. Only after these customary matters are
exhausted, do you need to say anything. By then you're warmed up
and ready.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail, however, is supposed to announce itself in the heading
and run from there. Cyberspace doesn't have time for pleasantries.
The only time I write about weather in e-mail is to razz Canadians
and New Englanders. E-mail also brings out latent aggressiveness in
people.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps over time, people will develop mindless niceties
tailored for e-mail. Instead of straining for importance in the
header, we will work out new little rituals to warm up to the
message.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we will start by assuring our correspondents that we, the
writers, are not e-mail-generating programs but real humans and
that the message is certified clean of viruses, worms and prank
macros.
</P>
<P>
   That would feel comforting even if untrue _ the sure sign of a
good beginning.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, don't worry that this column will disrupt the
rest of the paper or harm the other contents of your recycling bin.
There are no viruses yet developed for newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   All we can ruin is your morning.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
