A6006 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN06-COX     04-05 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bad manners no indicator of independence, kids
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Each Monday morning, my eighth-graders and I
respond to a voice crackling over the intercom asking us to please
stand for the Pledge of Allegiance. Setting aside whatever we
happen to be doing, we pause to pay our respects to the country we
live in. Always, one or two kids in an effort to demonstrate their
``cool'' lag behind, pretending either they didn't hear, or that
they're inextricably entwined with their desks and unable to make
it to their feet. Thanks to a little peer pressure (``Oh, get over
it, stupid'') they're usually upright and mumbling along by the
time we reach the part about ``...and to the Republic for which it
stands.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no federal law commanding the pledge be recited in
American classrooms. As citizens, we cannot be forced to swear
allegiance to our country, nor can we be compelled to speak or
think in any particular way. We
</P>
<P>
   are free to decide for ourselves, and should we choose not to
``pledge allegiance to the flag of the United States of America,''
the same flag that we are free to burn in protest, no soldiers will
come to arrest us.
</P>
<P>
   As far as I'm concerned, freedoms like these are a good enough
reason to pledge allegiance to the country that guarantees them.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there are things happening that we don't like, but
isn't it terrific that we can complain out loud? I'm not
particularly happy about living in the shadow of a morally bankrupt
president, but I am glad there are no
</P>
<P>
   laws demanding ``death for stupidity.'' And as objectionable as
I find an oddity with purple and gold hair who makes ungodly
amounts of money pushing a ball through a hoop, I'm proud to be
part of a system where folks can't be locked up for bad taste and
looking funny.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I have a major problem with kids who are too young to
have walked a mile in anybody's shoes, complaining that the
recitation of the ``Pledge of Allegiance'' in their classrooms is
the establishment's attempt to ``robotocize'' them and brainwash
them into conformity. If it's a loss of individuality that's
worrying them, then they're raising hell in all of the wrong
places. Adolescents instinctively travel with the herd and fear
difference more than a dateless Saturday night. So why carry on
about the pledge? Because it wasn't their idea?
</P>
<P>
   Young folks, like the ones I recently read about in a Washington
state high school, who are responding to a recital of the ``Pledge
of Allegiance'' with a Nazi salute, or a refusal to face the flag,
seem to be confusing singularity with rude behavior; they have not
yet learned that bad manners aren't an indicator of independence.
They don't understand that complaint without contribution rings
hollow.
</P>
<P>
   So may I suggest that until they've gotten over zits and into
taxes, until they've registered for the draft and seen more of the
world than Disneyland, or until they've had a chance to talk with a
WW2 Gold Star mother, they just stick to what they know. When
they've paid their dues, then maybe somebody will listen.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio, 43431 or e-mail:
eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
