</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: When lawn care turns vicious
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been an urban dweller for going on two decades, but I grew
up before World War II in a community that was a virtual prototype
for the standard-issue suburbs that would be spread out like
mayonnaise around our cities after the war. So don't get me wrong.
I know suburbanites are capable of at least a base-line humanity.
</P>
<P>
   How shocking it is then to learn that all these years
suburbanites have been literally torturing nature, Saturday sadists
absolutely devoted in the practice of their peculiar cruelties.
</P>
<P>
   This intelligence comes from the journal ``Geophysical Research
Letters.'' On the off chance you missed the recent issue _ hard to
believe, but I suppose a few of you may have been, let me be blunt,
lazy _ I'll recap: Homeowners and hireling lawn-care companies have
been routinely, and here I quote, ``wounding'' their grass by
cutting it.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have found that when grass and crops are cut and
begin to dry, they release methanol, hexanal, acetaldehyde, acetone
and butatone. These the researchers characterize as ``wound-induced
compounds.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't understand the full implications of all those chemicals,
but none sounds friendly and there is no way to stay upwind of
them. Researchers say they add to smog and other pollution. Cutting
and cropping produce 1.6 million tons of acetone alone every year.
That's a whopping lot of acetone. Or, at any rate, I suppose it is,
although I have to admit that my idea of just what constitutes ``a
little acetone'' is not yet fully formed.
</P>
<P>
   One Carlton J. Howard of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration Aeronomy Laboratory in Boulder, Colo., has been
quoted as saying this discovery ``is something that needs to be
looked at carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, but we are counseled by the researchers not to panic.
Ray Fall of the University of Colorado says the smell of newly mown
grass probably isn't toxic _ the cautious will note that
``probably'' _ and mowing the lawn is no more hazardous than eating
fresh vegetables, inasmuch as chewing vegetables releases the same
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   (This would seem to raise a problem for vegetarians, because if
chewing and harvesting vegetables is, scientifically speaking,
wounding them, then where is the ethical advantage over eating
animals, which we at least have the decency to put entirely out of
their misery before consuming? But this is another matter entirely
and we will just have to come back to it another day.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Wounding'' may seem strong language but, really, what are all
those emissions if not a cry for help?
</P>
<P>
   So, while we're awaiting that further, close look that Mr.
Howard suggests, it would seem prudent, as an interim strategy,
that lawn movers be put away until further notice. The new suburban
status symbol will be, not the manicured, but the profligate yard.
And the makers of lawn fertilizers might be wise to get their
research shops hopping on new grass-stunting products.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, homeowners, be a prince to nature. Not a Marquis
de Sod.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
