<HEADER>
A6020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-CO     04-05 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Draga vs Tito: a precursor?
 &HT;    (For release April 7, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was an impressional youngster during World War II, I
became infatuated with Yugoslavia because, I believed, this was the
one country overrun by the Nazis that was giving its occupiers a
truly nasty time.
</P>
<P>
   This was enhanced by the 1943 motion picture ``Chetniks!,''
starring Philip Dorn and a ton of people nobody ever heard of.
``Chetniks!'' was what they called a B-movie. It was so much a
B-movie that it isn't even available on videotape for me to have a
refreshed remembrance.
</P>
<P>
   As the ethnic cleansing takes its toll and as the missiles fly
into Yugoslavia, I recall the film _ but vaguely. I know it was
about a man named Mihailovich, and he was the heroic leader of a
Nazi-fighting group called the Chetniks. It was patriotic stuff;
it's called wartime propaganda now.
</P>
<P>
   A long time has passed since Mihailovich. Students of
Yugoslavian history know that his first name was Dragomir, and that
his last name was sometimes spelled as Mihajlovic and that he also
was known as Draga or Draza, and that he was mysterious except that
he was fighting Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   There was at the time another group fighting the Nazis in
Yugoslavia. They were called the Partisans but they hated the
Chetniks as much as they did the Nazis. Their paramount commander
was Josip Broz, a.k.a. Tito. I don't recall any of that being in
the film so I looked it up.
</P>
<P>
   Know this: Draga was a Serb, Tito was a Croat. They were an
extension of the hostilities that have obsessed Yugoslavia since
its forced formation at the end of World War I. These were peoples
with diverse languages, cultures and governments who were jammed
together for postwar political accommodation. But it wasn't
felicitous.
</P>
<P>
   When Draga and Tito weren't killing Nazis, they were killing
each other.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, the Nazis dissected the patched-together
Yugoslavia and doled out portions of it to other members of their
Axis alliance. At its conclusion, Tito emerged the more powerful _
largely because the Western powers discarded Draga (why, I don't
know) while the Soviets embraced Tito. A communist, Tito was
strongly anti-West and wanted a return to the unification of the
states comprising Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   To benefit his assumption of power, Tito captured Mihailovich
and had him executed. That out of the way _ i.e., a Serbian
nationalist disposed of _ Tito proceeded to reunify Yugoslavia with
an iron hand.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike today's Slobodan Milosevic, Tito demanded all parties get
along, even though they despised each other. Milosevic goes in a
different direction. Keeping the land together is fine with him but
some of the people have to go. Thus, the ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the communist leaders, Tito was perhaps the most
independent, and flexible. When Cominform, the association of
communist states, excommunicated Tito because of independent
thought, the old Nazi fighter just rolled a little to his right and
took up with the U.S. and other Western nations, which, by 1951,
were already providing him military equipment in case the Soviets
thought they could shove him around.
</P>
<P>
   There's no telling what would have happened if Mihailovich had
won over Tito. As a Serbian nationalist, might he have done earlier
what Milosevic is now doing?
</P>
<P>
   But it was Tito who prevailed and, despite his dictatorship,
Yugoslavia enjoyed a lengthy period of relative peace. It was Tito
who created what we now call the Third World, that in-between
buffer that separated the U.S. and the West from the hard-line
communist bloc.
</P>
<P>
   If communism can have a good side, Yugoslavia was there.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mihailovich, I'll always remember him fondly. Not because
of who he was or wasn't _ I was too young to comprehend _ but for
the motion picture in which he killed lots of Nazis. In retrospect,
I thought it was better than a B-movie.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
