<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6029 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE06-COX     04-05 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net sites take aim at computer viruses
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you use the Internet at all, it doesn't take a
psychic to know viruses, especially the ``Melissa'' e-mail virus,
have been on your mind lately.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the viruses you read about these days are spread over
the Internet. So it's only right we use the Net to find ways to
fight them.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start at what may be the best anti-virus site on the Web,
the federal Energy Department's Computer Incident Advisory
Capability, most commonly known by the initials CIAC. You'll find
this site at ciac.llnl.gov/.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, you'll immediately recognize it as a government
site. It isn't fancy, and most of the information consists of text
files with information about the latest viruses. Last week, for
instance, the latest bulletin on the site discussed Melissa.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a couple of features of the site that make it so
valuable. For one thing, you'll be able to understand most of the
information without having a degree in computer science. For
another, most of the text bulletins contain Web links that take you
to other sites with valuable data and information. For example, the
Melissa bulletin has a link that takes you to a Microsoft site
which offers a patch (a tiny program that updates or fixes a
problem in another program) for Word 97 that makes changes so the
word processing program is less vulnerable to Melissa.
</P>
<P>
   The same document provides step-by-step information for making
changes in the options for Word to make it safer when it comes to
viruses such as Melissa that tamper with macros (tiny programs that
automate many tasks).
</P>
<P>
   The Web is actually crammed with anti-virus pages. Some of them
are owned by the publishers of commercial anti-virus software.
Don't look down your nose at these sites just because they're
commercial. You'll find plenty of useful information and _
sometimes _ free demo programs. Since there are so many sites, the
next page is a good one to bookmark.
</P>
<P>
   It's called Anti-Virus Web sites and is basically a collection
of links to some of the best places on the Web for virus
information. You'll find this page of links at www
</P>
<P>
   .virusbtn.com/AVLinks
</P>
<P>
   /sites.html. You'll find everything from the expected (the CIAC
site we've already mentioned) to the bizarre, a link to sites you'd
never stumble across such as the Slovak Anti-Virus Centre (CQ) at
ftp.elf.stuba.sk/packages
</P>
<P>
   /pub/pc/.
</P>
<P>
   As you learn more about viruses from visiting some of these
pages, you'll discover that rumors and myths spring up on a regular
basis. The real viruses are bad enough but, if all the
misconceptions about viruses and all the phony virus warnings were
true, the Internet would be virtually useless.
</P>
<P>
   At the Computer Virus Myths Homepage at kumite
</P>
<P>
   .com/myths/home.htm, you'll learn some of the legends that
abound in the virus world, including an especially harmful rumor
that circulated on the Web concerning an electronic greeting card
site. The rumor was that a site spread viruses along with the
electronic cards it delivered. That just isn't so, but the buzz
became so pervasive that the site was forced to run a large
disclaimer promising its products were virus-free.
</P>
<P>
   Beware of sites that offer do-it-yourself virus kits and hacking
software. While the information on these sites can be fascinating,
the prudent will avoid visiting these sites and should resist the
temptation to download anything.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
