<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6031 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCHER06-COX     04-05 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCHER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net brings depth to Kosovo issues
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For a generation used to wars and international
conflicts that start on Friday and are over by Sunday and broadcast
live or at least in part by CNN or ``Nightline,'' NATO's air
strikes in the Balkan province of Kosovo are bewildering.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Iraq, Iran or even the former Soviet Union, the names and
nationalities of the players in the Balkan drama are unfamiliar to
many Americans. Just as TV can bring graphic depictions of war and
its aftermath to people around the world, the Internet can provide
breadth and depth of content impossible to find anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of talk about community on the Net, but the
international community that has formed around this issue is
something Web surfers should take advantage of.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of personal feelings about NATO, Kosovo or the
Serbian government, the Web provides the opportunity for an
exchange of views and information that can't be found anywhere
else. There are many sites that can help you understand the
geography and the nature of the conflict, and they are worth
checking out. But after that, why not go a bit deeper and listen to
the voices, American, British, Serbian and Albanian, sharing their
thoughts, feelings and strongly held opinions?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think the Internet is so appropriate now because there is
a general lack of knowledge. The geography is certainly an issue as
well, as well as the nationalities involved,'' says Katherine
Dillon, ABCNews.com's vice president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ABCNews.com features a special section on its Web site called
``Balkans for Beginners,'' which provides maps, time lines and
other background to help readers understand where the fighting is
and who the participants are.
</P>
<P>
   It's an excellent geography and history lesson and a good
jumping-off point for anyone attempting to understand the conflict.
The Web site is one of the best there is for breaking complicated
news stories down to basics without talking down to or over the
heads of its readers.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, CNN and MSNBC report large numbers of postings to message
boards from national and international users. CNN has also set up a
special message board for Balkans residents only, but doesn't vouch
for the validity of the posts. ABCNews.com says it has received
more than 13,000 posts on the subject in just over a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very emotional story,'' says Dillon. ``People are
opinionated, and they are angry. Nobody seems to be wishy-washy on
this. We've never seen the flood of reaction. We are amazed how
focused and informed and intelligent these boards are.''
</P>
<P>
   British Broadcasting Co. (news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english
</P>
<P>
   /specialreport/1998/kosovo/), considered by some to be the
finest news organization in the world, offers an international
perspective on the crisis. A RealAudio clip of the BBC World
Service featuring the BBC's John Humphreys in a heated argument
with Milodrag Popovic, deputy information minister in Belgrade,
winds up in a near shouting match that's nothing like the staid
impartiality of the BBC's World Service radio broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in tears for the millions of people who have lost
their lives and their homes in Kosovo,'' Humphreys nearly screams,
as Popovic maintains the genocide _ if there is any genocide _
didn't begin until NATO began bombing. ``Why did you call me if you
don't want to listen to me?'' Popovic shouts.
</P>
<P>
   The BBC also offers an interactive guide to the Kosovo crisis at
news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/natointeract/nsinteract.html,
which includes an area called talking points, where users can post
opinions and responses.
</P>
<P>
   The BBC has highlighted two comments that illustrate the
complexity of the situation. A Kosovo Albanian writes: ``NATO, we
were waiting for this day to bomb Serbian terrorists. We love you
Nato.'' From the other side, a Belgrade resident writes: ``NATO
please stop your bombs it is not our fault. We are not Slobodan
Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on CNN, one reader wrote to another: ``Again, what
evidence there is seems to dispute your version of events, or at
least your sources' version. What is NOT in dispute are the tens of
thousands of refugees being created in Kosovo by Milosevic and his
henchmen. This forced exodus is a human disaster of epic
proportions not seen since WWII.''
</P>
<P>
   While the BCC and others continue to cover the war and engage
its participants, there is no longer any news from Belgrade radio
station B92 (www.b92.net). The posting on the Web site says the
station was shut down on Good Friday by inspectors, policemen fired
the station's director and a court appointed a new director who
will take over on Monday. The signoff reads: ``The struggle
continues. We shall never surrender. Radio B92, Belgrade, Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   The B92 site uses RealAudio to replay the chilling sound of an
air-raid siren that lasts for what seems like hours but is in
reality a few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Even from the comfort of your den, in front of your computer
with perhaps the TV or a favorite CD playing in the background, the
Balkan war seems to come right into your living room. And when it
does, it gets harder not to become just a little bit smarter and
just a little bit more interested in events taking place half a
world away.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
