<HEADER>
A6032 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFK-CHECKITOUT06-COX     04-05 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-CHECKITOUT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Watch out, Mulder and Scully
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``The X-Files'' has a little competition on the Web.
It's called the Why Files _ and unlike TV's FBI agents Fox Mulder
and Dana Scully, it has the answers. The Why Files, at
whyfiles.news.wisc.edu/welcome/index.html, provides in-depth
articles about science and how it affects our everyday lives.
Recently the site explored how science can help solve art crimes
and looked at chickens with three legs. Plus, the site offers a
Cool Science Image feature with pictures from the front lines of
science.
</P>
<P>
   Kids choose what rules
</P>
<P>
   Pizza rules for dinner, and chocolate ice cream is tops for
dessert, according to a recent survey by the Quaker Oats Co. Kids
ages 3 to 12 voted online to ``Choose Who Rules.'' Here's how the
votes shook out: 70 percent would like to have pizza for dinner
over mac and cheese (19 percent) and PB&AMP;J (11 percent); 42 percent
would rather listen to oldies as compared to 34 percent for rap and
24 percent for swing; while 50 percent want chocolate ice cream
over vanilla (32 percent) and strawberry (18 percent). At school,
52 percent of girls preferred art while 42 percent of boys were
crazy for science. You can find more results at
www.quakerkids.com/ChooseWhoRules/WhoElseRulesWinners.html.
</P>
