</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. increases attacks on Serbian troops
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The United States and its allies in the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) increased their bombing of Serbian
troops in Yugoslavia last week. NATO warplanes destroyed a bridge
over the Danube River and struck at military units in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials say the Serbs, who rule Yugoslavia and are
Christians, are trying to kill or run out the Albanians who live in
the country's Kosovo province. The Kosovar Albanians are Muslims
and would like their province to be independent.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150,000 refugees have overwhelmed neighboring
countries in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Three U.S. soldiers were captured by the Serbs last week.
President Clinton told Serbs the United States would protect its
own.
</P>
<P>
   Florida kids smoking less
</P>
<P>
   Middle school students in Florida are lighting up a lot less,
according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. From
1998 to 1999 smoking has declined among those students 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some are crediting an anti-smoking ad campaign for the decrease.
The Florida Legislature provided $70 million to enforce smoking age
limits and for a series of TV and radio ads produced by teenagers
that poke fun at the tobacco industry. The program started last
April.
</P>
<P>
   The decline is the largest among kids since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Braves open season
</P>
<P>
   Break out your peanuts and Cracker Jack. The Braves' season
officially starts today. The team will take on the Philadelphia
Phillies at 4:10 p.m. at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The team is a little less confident than last year with several
key members not playing. Andres Galarraga is fighting back cancer,
Kerry Ligtenberg tore a ligament in his pitching elbow and Bruce
Chen flopped as the newest member of the pitching rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Cloned sheep gives birth
</P>
<P>
   Dolly, the first mammal created by cloning, gave birth to
triplets last week. The three lambs were not created by cloning,
but by Dolly mating with a ram.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say the lambs indicate Dolly can make healthy babies.
Her creators say it is important to breed from cloned animals to
check for any unexpected changes in their offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Dolly had another baby last year from the same ram. Scientists
say that lamb, Bonnie, appears to be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Dolly was born in July 1996 after scientists cloned her from a
cell from another sheep's udder. She was named after the singer
Dolly Parton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
