<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PC World dissects Pentium III performance
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   In print
</P>
<P>
   The first Pentium III microprocessors, which can hit speeds up
to 500 megahertz, are featured in the cover story of the April
issue of PC World. The magazine review said the Pentium III at that
speed can run some business applications 10 times faster than
current state-of-the-art chips. Web applications and games also run
faster with the Pentium III, says the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue of PC World, you can also get a sneak peek at
Office 2000, the ubiquitous business suite from Microsoft. The
magazine says Microsoft has not made any dramatic improvements in
the latest version of Office, due out later this year. It has,
however, tweaked many of the components. Those components include
Word, Excel, PowerPoint and Outlook. PC World also says Office
continues to grow in size, now commanding at least 189 megabytes of
hard disk space.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   You can build a city, fly a fighter and now you can build and
manage an amusement park on your computer. It's part of a new game
called ``Rollercoaster Tycoon.'' In this computer CD game, you
design, build and manage a roller coaster theme park. It's designed
for kids 9 and older. Published by Hasbro Interactive,
``Rollercoaster Tycoon'' is available only for PCs running Windows
95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Another new simulation is the latest addition to the ``Fighter
Squadron'' series from Activision. This one is called ``The
Screamin' Demons over Europe'' and features aerial dogfights from
World War II. The game offers 10 authentic aircraft to choose from.
The ``Fighter Squadron'' series is only for PCs using Windows 95 or
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   As a description on Yahoo! put it, ``You'll want to wash you
hands after visiting this Web site.'' That's because it features
the world of infectious diseases. The site is the online version of
an exhibit at the American Museum of Natural History in New York.
It's a history of epidemics. You'll find the site at www.amnh.org
</P>
<P>
   /exhibitions/epidemic/epidemicindex.html.
</P>
