<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6041 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHTOOLS06-COX     04-05 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHTOOLS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delicate operation succeeds, but accomplishes nothing
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When last we saw Oklahoma Warner, he was indulging in
a refreshing nap before trying to snatch the Bus of Doom off the
pedestal so swiftly the cave didn't collapse on him.
</P>
<P>
   It was close, folks. Real close.
</P>
<P>
   Those who tuned in last week may remember I was trying to review
a $100 gadget called a Philips USB PC Camera, which uses the new
Universal Serial Bus connection. After a lengthy and tedious
installation project, the camera wouldn't work, presumably because
my computer's BIOS needed updating.
</P>
<P>
   Updating a BIOS is the computer equivalent of brain surgery. One
slip and the old Pentium II is a cabbage. It was not something I
wished to rush into.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions with the new Intel BIOS I downloaded from the
Gateway Web site said to begin by making a startup floppy disk
through the Create Startup tab in the Add/Remove Programs section
of the Control Panel. OK, no sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Then it said to copy onto this same disk all the files contained
in the new BIOS. Sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps these instructions were purely theoretical. In the
practical world, the files wouldn't all fit on the disk. Using my
trusty 12-foot bullwhip _ being a Lash LaRue fan, I actually owned
one of these as a kid _ I shaved a few seemingly unnecessary
programs like FDISK and DRIVESPACE out of the startup disk section
so all of the BIOS files would fit.
</P>
<P>
   Shut down, insert the disk, start up. A program guided me
through the installation of the flash BIOS, with lots of red text
and exclamation marks to keep my blood pressure from falling too
low.
</P>
<P>
   The next step was to open the computer, locate jumper J7B1, and
change it from pins 1-2 to pins 2-3, which puts the computer into a
maintenance mode so one can be sure the proper processor speed is
set.
</P>
<P>
   Those of you who have never had the pleasure of fiddling with
these devices will no doubt be clamoring for elucidation here.
Jumpers are, in this case, on the motherboard of the computer. The
motherboard is a very busy place, full of all kinds of little
shapes and thingies. J7B1 is a three-pin setup. Each pin is copper,
about half the thickness of an ordinary paper-clip wire, and
perhaps a quarter of an inch long. Of course, since you are looking
pretty much straight down on them, it doesn't matter how long they
are. The jumper is a plastic affair that slips over two of the pins
to connect them.
</P>
<P>
   It took a while to find J7B1, it being dark and me being
semi-blind, but it was at least out in the open. Changing the
jumper is a simple matter if you have a hand the size and
suppleness of my 10-year-old granddaughter. But I have done enough
of these now to know what's going to happen, and to be reasonably
patient with the whole process.
</P>
<P>
   Once the jumper was changed, the computer was rebooted and the
BIOS setup checked. All was fine. The jumper was returned to pins
1-2, the computer booted again, and after a few grumbles and
whimpers it came to life in a reasonably normal fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The camera still won't work. I never really thought it would.
</P>
<P>
   I can well imagine the frustration of the average computer owner
who goes out and lays down $100 for something like this, hoping to
extend the capabilities of his equipment and have some fun. After
$200 worth of aggravation, he's right back where he started _ at
the computer store, getting a refund.
</P>
<P>
   People who don't enjoy tinkering with the insides of a computer
shouldn't feel bad about it. Most things will have a better outcome
than this, but don't go beyond a point where you feel really
uncomfortable. Do what you feel up to doing, and if that doesn't
work, then let it go.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, if I didn't get paid to do this sort of thing, I would
have tossed in the towel without trying to replace the BIOS.
Snatching the Bus of Doom safely off the pedestal was a rush, but
discovering it didn't work as advertised was a bummer. Oh, and in
case you're wondering what happened to those outraged natives I
heard screaming at the mouth of the cave, they turned out to be the
guinea pigs demanding dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
