<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please tell me how to get June tickets for a tour of
Buckingham Palace. _Virginia Beddow
</P>
<P>
   A: Unfortunately, Buckingham Palace is open to the public only
from Aug. 6 to Oct. 3. Maybe next trip? Buckingham House was
purchased by King George III in 1761 for his wife, Queen Charlotte,
to use as a comfortable home close to St. James' Palace. In fact,
14 of George's 15 children were born there.
</P>
<P>
   Q: About two years ago in Iowa, people broke into an animal
shelter and killed a bunch of animals. I want to know the status of
that case. Were the people put in jail? What is the address of the
animal shelter so I can make a donation? _H. Dalton
</P>
<P>
   A: The incident involved Iowa teens who bludgeoned cats with
baseball bats after breaking into the Noah's Ark Foundation
facility. Sgt. Joe Smutz of the Jefferson County sheriff's
department said the four teens were sentenced to one day in jail
for each cat killed and three years' probation in the juvenile
offender program. Smutz says the Iowa Legislature is considering
legislation to change the penalty for such crimes. Contact the
facility by writing Noah's Ark Foundation, P.O. Box 748, Fairfield,
Iowa 52556.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I received a disturbing telephone call in which I heard,
``This is a collect call from the IRS to confirm your address.'' I
was so shocked I did nothing, and the call was disconnected. Was
this actually the Internal Revenue Service IRS or an outfit using
the initials to sell something? _Frieda R.
</P>
<P>
   A: Although the IRS does many things taxpayers find annoying,
calling collect is not one of them. IRS spokesman Kenneth Vargas
says IRS agents are required to give a name and badge number as
identification.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I used my sister-in-law's gas dryer, and there was a pen left
in some clothes. Now there are streaks all over the inside of the
dryer drum. I have used every cleaner I can think of with no luck.
_Donna G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Try Maytag consumer information at (800) 688-1120.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent hail storm left our new car with slight damage.
While we have full insurance, I have heard that using dry ice on
dents will cause them to pop out. Does this work? _ Wade W.
</P>
<P>
   A: You can try it and it may work _ more importantly it won't
hurt. Let the sun heat the metal and pick up some dry ice at a
local store (handle carefully). The warm metal may pop back into
shape when the ice contacts it.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com
or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
