<HEADER>
A6047 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN06-CO     04-05 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Backups simplify desktop brain surgery
 &HT;    By Gerry Yandel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yea, though I walk through the valley of Win95, I fear
no evil ... for I have backed up system.dat and user.dat.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like the threat of totally annihilating your
operating system to add a little edge to customizing your computer
and the way it works.
</P>
<P>
   So when you go rooting around in the Windows registry, you're
walking about as close to that edge as you can (without having to
reinstall). I was lucky the first time I went stumbling through the
confusing directory tree of HKEYs. I blithely clicked hither and
yon, not a care in the world, not a backup in sight.
</P>
<P>
   I actually messed up the registry enough that I couldn't boot
into Windows and had to use a special feature of Win95, detailed
below, to restore my system.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, well, we're all newbies once.
</P>
<P>
   I've since been fiddling in the registry with a little more
awareness, and it's quite a powerful little database. It stores all
the configuration information and settings for the operating
system, whether it's Win 95, 98 or NT.
</P>
<P>
   You can use it to remove those ugly little arrows at the bottom
of shortcut icons, clean out the add/delete programs list in your
control panel or bury dead file types from old programs. You can
also use it to fine-tune Windows to make your hardware run more
smoothly. It came to the rescue when I moved Office 97 onto a new
hard drive and the program suddenly couldn't find its own
templates.
</P>
<P>
   Windows takes some of the thrill out of doing desktop brain
surgery by automatically creating backups of system.dat and
user.dat in files called system.da0 and user.da0 every time your
operating system successfully boots. (That's helpful because
Microsoft doesn't support hacking the registry, and any attempts to
get their tech support to help fix one you've messed up will
probably not yield decent _ if any _ results.)
</P>
<P>
   System.dat and user.dat are hidden files, so open Windows
Explorer and go to file types under ``view'' and change it to
``show all'' if you can't find them.
</P>
<P>
   You can make your own copies in addition to the auto backups (a
good idea). There's also a Microsoft backup program called
cfgback.exe available on some Win95 CDs in the
(backslash)Other(backslash)Misc(backslash)Cfgback directory _ and
the sites listed below _ that makes multiple backups. Now you're
ready to open regedit.exe, which is in the Windows directory.
Regedit is simply a utility that allows you to see the registry
database as a directory tree, similar to the Windows Explorer. It
also allows you to search the registry with relative ease and avoid
printing the registry out _ which can easily run to more than 1,000
pages. Instead, we'll open regedit, and we find the infamous HKEYS:
</P>
<P>
   HKEYUSERS
</P>
<P>
   HKEYLOCALMACHINE
</P>
<P>
   HKEYCLASSESROOT
</P>
<P>
   HKEYCURRENTUSER
</P>
<P>
   HKEYCURRENTCONFIG
</P>
<P>
   HKEYDYNDATA
</P>
<P>
   The first two are the primary branches, with USERS storing the
preferences for the different users, and LOCALMACHINE keeping track
of the hardware configuration and the software file types. The next
three HKEYs are actually places to store information while the
system is in use, with CLASSESROOT being a mirror of the software
settings under HKEYLOCAL
</P>
<P>
   MACHINE/SOFTWARE/Classes. The last one, HKEYDYNDATA, keeps track
of plug-and-play devices and changes as they are added or removed.
</P>
<P>
   The actual keys are stored inside the HKEYs as subdirectories,
sometimes several layers into the directory tree, and appear as
folders holding one or several icons. Each icon represents a data
type and has a value written as either a string of text, binary
data (as a hexadecimal) or dword data (also as hexadecimal).
</P>
<P>
   So what does all this mean? These values are where you can do
your most stunning _ or devastating _ work on your system. For
instance, when Office 97 somehow lost track of its templates (never
mind that they were sitting right in the Office subdirectory), the
fix was simple and quick. I opened regedit and, after doing a few
searches, I was able to find several values that pointed to the old
hard drive path. Simply changing the drive letter in the
appropriate values made everything run smoothly again.
</P>
<P>
   When my video capture card and NetMeeting weren't getting along,
the fix was even easier. On the card manufacturer's tech support
Web page, I found the answer to my specific situation, which merely
involved finding one key in the registry and changing three values
slightly. Voila! These fixes were mere parlor tricks, though,
compared with what a little reverse engineering on the registry can
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   But it wouldn't hurt to familiarize yourself with the procedures
for restoring a backup registry, just in case you get a little too
zealous with your experiments and end up facing the Windows blue
screen of death.
</P>
<P>
   More information on topics covered in Power User can be found at
the following sites:
</P>
<P>
   _ www.winmag.com/library/1997/0201 /featu159.htm
</P>
<P>
   _ www.regedit.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.halcyon.com/cerelli/registrytips.htm
</P>
<P>
   _ www.winreg.com/members.aol.com/evanetten/registry.htm
</P>
<P>
   Usenet: comp.os.ms-windows.win95.misc
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
