<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Splurge at buythebest.com
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Are you in the market for a $2.5 million,
single-engine turboprop but just don't have the time to shop?
</P>
<P>
   A Web site, www.buythebest.com, might be worth checking out. The
site is devoted to the real expensive and mildly practical. Think
of it as Robin Leach meets Sharper Image. It's the type of site
where Bill Gates could find something nice and little for fellow
Microsoft founder and billionaire Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
   You can't actually buy a plane from the site. If you are
interested in the Pilatus PC-12, you can fill out a form and a
Pilatus dealer will contact you.
</P>
<P>
   There are more-affordable items, relatively speaking, as well.
An ergonomic chair sells for $1,070. A titanium-frame bike is
peddled for $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site targets the consumer searching for state-of-the-art
stuff. Products include a $580 briefcase, an $85,000 Hummer and a
$12,000 jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   The site features more than 20 products. Included are product
pictures, information, descriptions and reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Buythebest.com, the catalog for connoisseurs, is based in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   An online Easter
</P>
<P>
   A new Web site lets you make a virtual pilgrimage to the Holy
Land, just in time for Easter Sunday. The site,
virtualholyland.com, seeks to be a portal for all things Middle
East. The start page offers weather reports for Jerusalem and
Galilee and 24-hour news updates from the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   It has a host of Middle East-themed features, including the
Holycam, a camera focused on Jerusalem's Western Wall; a free
e-mail account, zionmail.com; a scrolling breaking-news ticker; and
Holy Land-themed chat rooms and forums.
</P>
<P>
   The site lets visitors observe a traditional Passover seder, the
meal Jesus ate the night before he died. The site also features a
video tour of Calvary, including the skull-faced hill that some
believe to overlook the site of Jesus' death and the Garden Tomb, a
hand-carved grave said to be where his body lay for three days
between Good Friday and Easter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, the site will transmit the radio broadcast of two
Easter services from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The site, launched in December, includes travel tips, a Kid's
Club and an online Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Online arts connection
</P>
<P>
   In its race to be a mass medium like television, the Web already
has the commercial and low-brow departments covered. But it also
will need more culture.
</P>
<P>
   A site at www.culturefinder.com/ hopes to add some. The site
claims arts listings for more than 1,000 cities. Detailed
information is given for larger cities. Atlanta, Dallas, Houston,
Miami and Minneapolis are on that list, which also includes Boston,
Chicago, Los Angeles, New York, Philadelphia, San Francisco and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers information about plays, classical music
concerts, opera, visual arts, dance and film.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the site can search by state or by arts
organization, date or venue. They can also check museum listings
for certain museums. The only museum listing for Georgia is the
High Museum of Art, in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   You can also add your e-mail address to the free weekly e-mail
newsletter. In its January issue, Yahoo! Internet Life magazine
rated CultureFinder.com the Internet's best cultural directory.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
