<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Updated anti-virus program has become a necessity
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I remember years ago writing a column that said
computer virus fears were overblown. I said the chances of getting
hit by a virus were about the same as a meteor hitting you while
driving along Interstate 285.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that advice was true at the time. But nowadays, the
Internet and the computer world are being bombarded regularly by
meteor showers when it comes to viruses and other malicious
programs designed to invade your privacy or destroy information on
your hard disk. The most recent example is ``Melissa,'' a tiny
stealth program that sneaks into your computer as an e-mail
attachment.
</P>
<P>
   You probably have read all you want to read about Melissa. She's
been one popular girl. And police in New Jersey arrested David L.
Smith, 30, Thursday night and charged him with being Melissa's
daddy. So I won't spend much time with her other than to tell you
if you still need to know how to defend yourself against that
particular virus, you can find all the information you need online.
One great site is located at www.zdnet.com.
</P>
<P>
   While Melissa is a danger, the really frightening news is the
me-too viruses all that publicity spawned. The creators of viruses
do it partially for the twisted joy of watching all the turmoil
they create. And we've already seen Melissa imitators such as Papa
that invade your computer using a spreadsheet attachment instead of
_ as in the case of Melissa _ a Microsoft Word document. Most
anti-virus software companies have created patches (tiny programs
that update an existing application) that allow their programs to
catch Melissa and Papa. Just check the Web site for your anti-virus
program.
</P>
<P>
   The new viruses are being created so fast that even the best
anti-virus software can't keep up. That's not to say you shouldn't
use anti-virus protection. Nowadays, you're just plain foolish if
you don't. But think of all the people _ including employees of
companies that have excellent security and anti-virus protection _
that suffered from Melissa before it was discovered. In a twisted
way, these folks were the pioneers who suffered the embarrassment
and inconvenience of learning sensitive Word documents of theirs
were being sent around the world by Melissa.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no longer good enough to simply rely on anti-virus
software. I'm not being hysterical when I say you are vulnerable to
a virus attack, no matter what you do. But there are some
precautions you can take _ especially in view of the latest fad of
invading the documents and data on your hard disk _ to lessen the
risk.
</P>
<P>
   First, get a good anti-virus program and make sure you update it
regularly. Once a week isn't too frequent.
</P>
<P>
   Next, simply refuse to open e-mail attachments, even if they
come from someone you know. As you'll recall, that's the trick
Melissa introduced, making it seem the e-mail came from someone you
know. If you receive an attachment, don't open it. Up to now _ and
things are changing so fast you can't count on this in the future _
all of these viruses and malevolent programs arrive in an
attachment. Plain old-fashioned e-mail is safe.
</P>
<P>
   If you have documents or e-mail that would be embarrassing or
could be used to invade your bank account or reveal other financial
information, you may want to consider keeping them on a ZIP drive
disk or a floppy disk. This is painful, since the whole idea of a
computer is convenience and storing sensitive documents elsewhere
takes time and is inefficient. But there's no other way I know to
protect this information.
</P>
<P>
   This is all depressing to a fellow like me. I've spent years and
years extolling the virtues of computers and the Internet. And now
I worry that, unless someone comes up with a way to increase
security, it's becoming a risky and even seamy place. I wish I
could offer reassurance. Instead, I offer my sympathy along with a
Web site that offers a free computer check for viruses:
www.mcaffee.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
