<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, April 5, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-TOURISTS (San Francisco) _ By taking the investigation
into the Yosemite killings of a woman and two teenage girls before
a federal grand jury, the FBI has grasped one of the most powerful
tools in the prosecutorial arsenal. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-PHYSICIAN (San Francisco) _ Three days after the
disappearance of three women visiting Yosemite National Park, a
Santa Clara doctor vanished in ski country. Few people have heard
about Dr. Katherine Wong, who disappeared while skiing Feb. 19
about 167 miles north of where the sightseers disappeared. By JIM
HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER (Aptos, Calif.) _Under other circumstances I
wouldn't be the least bit uncomfortable gazing on the image of the
totally naked breast on the cover of the book. But this was my book
about breast cancer. I liked how my name looked on the cover.
Spelled correctly. Just above the woman's underarm. I liked how the
title, ``Now Breathe,'' was laid out in two different fonts. But
the naked breast. The sunlit nipple. Oh my. By CLAUDIA STERNBACH.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ENERGY (San Francisco) _ Nowadays, it seems like you
can buy everything from clothing to credit checks on the Internet.
So why not energy? That's the idea behind Albany, Calif.- based
utility.com, a new e-commerce site that began selling electricity
over the Web last month to consumers and businesses in California.
By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ When it comes to building
trails, Jane Gomery has learned the First Commandment of the public
in the San Francisco Bay area: ``Don't tell me about the labor
pains, just show me the baby.'' Well, a baby is being born, the Bay
Trail, 5 miles of trail along the Burlingame shore that is a
testimonial to what could be possible elsewhere in the trail's
planned route around the San Francisco Bay. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GARDENS (Undated) _ In celebration of spring, a roundup
of some of the best gardens from around the world. From Keukenhof,
an 80-acre garden with more than six million flowering bulbs, more
than half of them tulips, in the Netherlands, to Bellingrath
Gardens in Theodore, Ala. By SYD KEARNEY and HARRY SHATTUCK (Photos
available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TEXAS (Undated) _ A roundup of some of Texas' premier
gardens. By SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AUSTRIA (Galtur, Austria) _ An Austrian ski resort almost
totally dependent on tourism struggles back after deadly
avalanches. By SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ April's arrival not only signals a
need for spring cleaning; it's a reminder to formulate our travel
plans and make early reservations for the peak season. By HARRY
SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Can you believe those Serbs over
in Kosovo? Killing and torturing people who look just like them
because of something that happened in 1389? What's the matter with
those people? Do they thrive on bloodshed and violence? It makes
you wonder sometimes if they're actually human. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   DREYFUS-AFFAIR (Danville, Calif.) _ Friday is the birthday of
Emile Zola: novelist, journalist, playwright, critic, and the
unlikely hero of the Dreyfus Affair _ the 19th century mother of
all government coverups. While these days the Dreyfus Affair is
little remembered, its distinguishing motifs _ lies in high places
for high-minded reasons, media circus trials, hate-filled
demagoguery _ are all too familiar. By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
</TEXT>
