it FREE by subscribing to Ian Spelling's INSIDE SCI-FI column,
which is distributed by The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   Ian's first interview _ with Samuel L. Jackson, who plays Mace
Windu _ is below. For more information about the package, call
toll-free 888-269-8796 to connect to a New York Times Syndicate
sales executive near you.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE SCI-FI &QL; 
 &UR; THE FORCE IS WITH SAMUEL L. JACKSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) &QL; 
 &UR; Includes color slide and B&AMP;W photo of Samuel L. Jackson. &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN SPELLING &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   For years, Samuel L. Jackson has been a star. Now, at last, he's
a star warrior.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong sci-fi fan and an admirer of director/producer George
Lucas, Jackson makes a cameo appearance in ``Star Wars: Episode I _
The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   The much-anticipated ``Star Wars'' prequel opens nationwide on
May 19, and it stars Ewan McGregor as Obi-Wan Kenobi; Liam Neeson
as Kenobi's mentor, Qui-Gon Jinn; and Natalie Portman as the young
Queen Amidala. Jackson, whose sci-fi credits include ``Jurassic
Park'' (1993) and ``Sphere'' (1998), is cast as Mace Windu, a Jedi
Master.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the genre,'' says Jackson over lunch at the Four
Seasons Hotel in New York City. ``I wanted to be in a `Star Wars'
movie. So the next time I was asked (which director he wished to
work with) I said, `I would love to work with George Lucas.'''
</P>
<P>
   Word of Jackson's interest got back to Lucas, who invited the
actor to meet with him at his Skywalker Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``George said, `I've seen some of your work, and you're very
good, but you could wind up yelling, `Look out! Go this way! Run
that way!' I said, `I don't care.' Sure enough, he found something
for me.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas handed Jackson the Windu character _ and a mere five pages
of script.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to act with Yoda (Frank Oz), and I shot my scenes out in
England (at Leavesden Studios),'' Jackson says. ``I have no idea
what happens before my character shows up, and I have no idea what
happens after my character is gone. I had my pages and that was it.
Nobody gave me a whole script.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was so low-key,'' he adds. ``To know the incredible
pressure that's around the film, to know that it's his baby and
that he hadn't directed in 20 years, and to see him so calm was
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Always a busy actor, Jackson counts ``The Phantom Menace'' as
but one of many projects on his dance card. The Oscar-nominated
star of ``Pulp Fiction'' (1994) will soon be seen in the drama
``The Red Violin'' and the sci-fi/action thriller ``Deep Blue
Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Slated for summer release, ``Deep Blue Sea'' reunites Jackson
with Renny Harlin, who directed him in ``The Long Kiss Goodnight''
(1996). The story centers on a group of scientists who breed
smarter, speedier and nastier sharks, then must deal with the
consequences when the genetically enhanced creatures threaten to
escape their high-tech confines.
</P>
<P>
   Co-starring with Jackson are Saffron Burrows, Michael Rapaport,
Deborah Unger, Wayne Knight (another ``Jurassic Park'' veteran),
rapper-actor LL Cool J and Stellan Skarsgard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be an intriguing film,'' Jackson says. ``People are
already starting to call it `Jurassic Shark,' and that sounds about
right.''
</P>
<P>
   When not acting, Jackson spends time pursuing his other
endeavors of choice, which include relaxing with his wife, actress
LaTanya Richardson, and daughter, Zoe, at their home in Los
Angeles; golfing until he can swing no more; and voraciously
reading scripts and novels that he can potentially option and
produce as films.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, though, Jackson can't help but get caught up in the
``Star Wars'' fever sweeping the globe. He felt it on the ``Phantom
Menace'' set, and he feels it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``(On the set) some guy would come over to me and he'd open a
case,'' says Jackson, who recalls seeing the original ``Star Wars''
on its opening day in 1977. ``Inside were, like, nine lightsabers,
and he'd say, `Choose yours.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be there, hyperventilating. I'd say, `Oh, I'll take THAT
one.' That was very, very cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only did my one little bit, so it's going to be new and
exciting for me to see the movie,'' he says. ``I can't wait to see
it all put together.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Ian Spelling &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
