<HEADER>
A6087 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-JOHNSON-Q&AMP;     04-05 2419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-JOHNSON-Q&AMP;A-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS ACE JOHNSON SHARES APPROACH TO GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since signing a four-year, $52.4 million contract with the
Diamondbacks on Dec. 1, left-hander Randy Johnson has been in the
Arizona spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who starts against the Los Angeles Dodgers in today's
season opener, recently met with Don Ketchum, The Republic's
Diamondbacks beat reporter, to discuss his thoughts about the
upcoming season, people's perceptions of him and how he sees
himself. &QL; 
: Now that the season opener is almost here, what are your thoughts
about that game? You've pitched in a lot of big games _ how does
this compare, given the significance of the new team and the
high-profile nature of your path to get here? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: Obviously, I'll be extremely excited about opening day. I'm
sure there will be a lot of focus on that game between Kevin
(Brown) and myself. I'll probably be even more excited when I get
to pitch for the first time at Bank One Ballpark for my home fans.
I've never gotten to pitch at BOB yet. I was there with Houston and
Seattle but never got the opportunity to pitch there. But I am
looking forward to the season, helping the team get off to a good
start. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Any more impetus placed on the first game because you're going
to be relied upon perhaps more than anyone? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: Sure. Yeah. But I don't think the situation is like in Seattle
and Houston, where I was relied upon more than I would be here. I
mean, I still have my job to do and will look at it in the same
way, going about my business as I did in Seattle. But I don't think
there's going to be as much emphasis on, ``When is Randy
pitching?'' or, ``We need Randy to pitch today.'' There won't be
that kind of situation because our pitching here is so deep. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: That, in turn, helps you to pitch more relaxed? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: A great deal. When I was in Seattle, there was a reason why I
pitched every big game. I was the No. 1 guy, but there weren't a
whole lot of other people over there who had been in the same
situation as me with the experience of being able to go out and
pitch a big game like that. That won't be the same case here, with
Andy (Benes) here and Todd (Stottlemyre) here, and I think the
sleeper in my book would be Omar Daal. I feel he is going to have a
terrific year. There will be a lot of pressure taken off him by
myself and Andy and Todd. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: What is game day like for you? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: The day before, if it's the same team we've played the night
before, I've been watching the game, watching the hitters. Assuming
what players I'm going to face. Watching videotapes of my
mechanics, making sure that everything is all ready. I've prepared
myself mentally and physically. I've been in the training room,
doing anything I need to do. I've been in the weight room doing all
my exercises. Getting scouting reports. Now it's a matter of going
out there. I'm pretty high-strung on the day that I pitch. Very
focused. I have tunnel vision, and I don't like to be . . . I like
to be pretty much in my own little world. But I'm not the only one
like that on the day that I perform. You're extremely focused. I
get to play baseball only once every five days, and so it's, ah . .
. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Almost like five days of energy crammed into one? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: Exactly. Well, I pitched yesterday. Now I'm starting to get
ready for five days from now. There's a lot of stuff that builds up
in between those starts. A lot of excitement and a lot of
anticipation. When I go out there and pitch, I have a chance to
release a lot of that. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Gregg Olson, the Diamondbacks' closer, keeps a computer log and
charts. Do you go to that extent? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: No. I get a scouting report about the day that I pitched before
against that team, so when I face that team again later in the
year, I can go back and get a scouting report on what they did,
what they hit, and that's my only record. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Can you sometimes clutter yourself too much with that type of
thing? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: Yeah. When you're gifted with a good fastball. It's not like
I'm going to try to go out there and fool anybody. If I go out
there against a guy who's a good fastball hitter, well, I'm not
going to throw him a handful of change-ups now. He hits my
fastball, he hits my fastball. There's lots of people who have.
It's just a matter of what I do after that. A guy who's got a base
hit _ can I get a double-play ball now and eliminate a big inning? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: How would you describe yourself as a pitcher? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: First and foremost, I like to think I'm just as competitive as
the next person. I don't like to lose. Very high-strung, very
intense and very focused on the day that I pitch. I go out there
with every intention of winning. I have no desire to get a
no-decision or a loss. My job is to keep the other team at bay
until we can score some runs. And then, when we have scored runs
and I'm still out there pitching, it's kind of a take-no-prisoners
mentality _ as the game gets deeper and deeper, continuing to turn
it up a notch. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: You get more intense as you go along? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: Sure. Especially if it's a close game. I kind of like to think
I have a killer instinct late in the game, where I don't want the
other team to feel like they have a chance to come back. I turn it
up a notch, trying to eliminate any possibility of a big inning.
The only way to do that is showing the other team that you're not
going to crack. I've been able to do that a lot, but sometimes the
other team has gotten the best of me. They've got a job to do, too,
but that's my makeup on the day that I pitch. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Do you consider yourself the best pitcher in baseball, or is
that for others to decide? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: That's for others to judge, yeah. The other question I can't
answer is if I'm intimidating. How can I answer how the other
person feels? Those are two questions I get asked a lot, but two
questions I can't answer. I feel I've worked hard to get where I'm
at. I had a lot of roadblocks early on with my mechanics, my
height. It took me a long time to get where I'm at. I've had to
work extremely hard like anyone else, maybe even more so, because
of my height, dealing with my mechanics. And it's paid off. But now
I work just as hard, if not harder, than I did early on, because
now it's a matter of maintaining and always trying to stay a step
above everybody else. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Do you think a lot of people don't realize how much work goes
into it? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: I know any athlete has had to work at what he has done. A good
hitter who has perfected hitting, like a Tony Gwynn or a Rod Carew,
you'd probably find them after practice hitting off a tee, or
soft-toss or whatever. He's perfecting his trade. Myself, early on,
coming up, I was out in the instructional league for four years,
fielding ground balls, whatever. When everybody was gone, I was out
there for another hour working with my pitching coach. Those were
the things that, as time went on, I benefited from because I was
learning coordination, learning how to field my position, and I was
learning how to pitch. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: People obviously know a lot about Randy Johnson, the pitcher.
What about Randy Johnson, the person? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: I have three beautiful kids, a beautiful wife, and when I'm at
home, I enjoy being at home. I enjoy my family being with me on the
road. I enjoy going out and playing golf with the guys (teammates),
being competitive. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: If you could tell the fans something about yourself that they
don't know, what would it be? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: I don't think too many people really care that I play the
drums. I'm not really musically inclined, but I enjoy music and
playing the drums. It's one thing . . . that when I try to learn
something, I try to be good at it, much like pitching or basketball
or anything I've ever done. Like hitting right now. Hitting is
something I haven't done in 10 years. But I'm doing it so I can try
to be good at it. I have to be good at it because it's my job. I
enjoy being a photographer and taking pictures. I got good enough
to where I had an art exhibit, and I sold some of my work. When I
do something, I try to be good at it. I want to put 110 percent
into it. That's the way I was raised. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: You seem to be a guy who enjoys your time away from the
spotlight. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: Exactly. That's why I got a little bent out of shape when a
reporter came to my house. Just because for six months out of the
year, I realize that when I come to the ballpark, sign autographs,
do interviews, giving my time to people is my job. The first person
who says that I should be able to do the same things at my house is
wrong. Because that's my solitude. That's where I go to get away
from baseball. I enjoy my privacy with my family away from the
ballpark. It's my time to give them 110 percent like I give 110
percent to my teammates and baseball when I'm at the field.
Baseball is very time-consuming. I'm at the ballpark more than I'm
at home. So the last thing I want to do is interview at my house.
There've been lots of people who have wanted to do interviews at my
house. ``Sports'' ``Illustrated.''`` USA Today.'' People have
wanted to walk around my house. Roy Firestone wanted to do one of
those sit-down things. I don't do stuff like that at my house. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Do you feel you've fit into this clubhouse so far, getting
comfortable with your teammates? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: I'm not a real outgoing person. People have said that, and
that's fine. People have said I'm pretty moody. Some people have
said I'm a loner. Well, there's nothing wrong with that. But I
don't feel like I'm like that. I feel that my moodiness comes from
my competitiveness. People who have judged me have never walked in
my feet, to know what it's like to be expected to win every fifth
day. It's one thing to go and show up on the day that you pitch,
but it's another to be actually expected to win. I expect to win
when I go out there. Lou (Piniella, Seattle Mariners manager)
called me last year a little moody. I didn't think it was an insult
or anything, but there's a reason for that. That's my way of
preparing for my next start. I'm not going to go up and initiate a
conversation, as opposed to maybe someone coming up to me. I can
talk to you now, now that you've started something. I can talk for
the rest of the day. But I'm not going to go up to you. I'm not the
big, mean guy that I portray on the day that I pitch, on the other
four days. I may have a lot of things on my mind during the season
_ my kids, my wife or my next start _ but so does everybody.
Everybody goes about it a little differently. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Have you ever thought about what you might do once you leave the
game? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: Well, when I'm done with this contract (four years with an
option for a fifth), I'll be 40 years old. My 4-year-old daughter
will be 8 years old, my soon-to-be-3-year-old son will be 7, and my
10-month-old girl will be almost 5 years old. I will have had my
career. If I feel the four years is done, and I can't be
competitive anymore and I've seen signs of that, then I will be at
home every day with my family. I will be interacting with them and
being a part of what they want to do. And I'll try to do that these
next four years. But the amount of quality time you can give your
children, say one of your kids' plays or graduation or birthday
party . . . some of those things actually happen during the season.
So I miss a lot. A lot of us miss a lot. We sacrifice, and our
families sacrifice. And so when I'm done with my career, I will try
to be there for everything that I possibly can. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: So you'll be done with the game altogether? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: You never know. Maybe I'll have the desire to coach my son's or
daughter's Little League team. It all depends on what avenues, what
doors, open up for me. If I have some success here like I did in
Seattle, then maybe the door would open to possibly be a coach, if
that was what they (Diamondbacks) were willing to allow me to do.
Or if that's what I even want to do. Because I'm not a very
outgoing person. I'm not a real teacher. I've been taught more than
I've been able to teach. I've been taught by Nolan Ryan and Tom
House, and I've tutored myself by reading and analyzing _ most of
us do. I feel I've been able to teach a little bit, but I don't
feel like . . . if someone wants to come up to me today, right now,
and say, ``Well, how did you turn the corner on your success?'' I
would teach them, and I would tell them if they were willing to
learn. I feel funny going up to someone who's at the major league
level and hasn't asked for my advice to try to give them my advice,
unless they want it. Any time I've ever wanted help, I've gone out
to get it by initiating it. If one of these guys wants my help, I'm
willing to help him. Like Brian Anderson is a left-handed pitcher .
. . I could probably be of benefit to him. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: A lot of pitchers who began their careers as starters _ Dennis
Eckersley comes to mind _ ended their careers as closers. How would
you feel about that? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: The scenario has come up, right before I signed this contract.
``To prolong your career, would you want to be a closer?'' Well, I
can't answer that question because I have four years ahead of me of
_ hopefully _ successful starting. Once again, I would have to see
how I'd feel at the time. Between now and the next four years, I
will have a lot more innings pitched in me. I've relieved a couple
of times. It was fun, but at the time I knew it was a temporary
thing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Who is the toughest hitter you've ever faced? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: There's been a lot of them. There's been probably a lot of
hitters who have had success against me that I don't realize. Maybe
I've only faced them a few times, and the few times that I have
faced them, they're batting a thousand off me, you know, maybe two
triples and a home run . . . I can't rattle off their names . . .
But I can't tell you I've had a lot of success against, either. So
it works both ways. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Now that you've seen and been around this team, what do you
think its chances are for success? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A:: This team looks even better now . . . inside, I know I made the
right decision coming to a team I feel is going to be competitive.
It's just me talking, but now we have to go out and do it. A lot of
people are saying that I'm going to be sitting home in October. A
lot of people said that I sacrificed by coming here. Well, I feel I
have a little bit of knowledge in the game, and I feel we have a
complete lineup from top to bottom. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
