<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6097 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-E-COMMERCE-$ADV11-COX     04-05 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESS GETS ONLINE TO GET ON TOP
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories for
release Sunday, April 11, or thereafter
 &HT;    with COX-E-COMMERCE-GRAPHIC-$ADV11
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- When Michael Dell addressed the International
World Congress on Information Technology last June, he wowed the
crowd with this statistic: Dell Computer Corp. was doing $5 million
a day in Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a year, the figure has shot up to $14 million daily
-- and it's still growing. Today, the company Michael Dell founded
generates 25 percent of its revenue from online sales. By the end
of 2000, Dell wants that figure to hit 50 percent. ``The Internet
is turbocharging the way we do business,'' he crowed.
</P>
<P>
   But Dell isn't simply putting up a Web site and hoping surfers
will click on it. Instead, the company is integrating the Internet
into every aspect of its business. For example, the company has
launched a pilot project to build Web pages for its 30 top
suppliers. These links eventually will allow suppliers to
``virtually'' view Dell's manufacturing lines-- so they will know
when supplies are needed. Already the company has used technology
to reduce its inventory from 30 days worth to six days.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, this isn't sexiest stuff on the Web. Online
retailers such as Amazon.com and eBay are making a bigger splash
and grabbing more headlines. But the Internet has touched off an
online earthquake across nearly every industry. The result is that
electronic commerce is reshaping American business: Supply chains
are shifting. Businesses are shuffling resources to keep pace with
the online revolution. New players are emerging overnight to
threaten traditional ones such as distributors and middlemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is clear: You're going to need to conduct business
and reach your customers electronically,'' says Daniel L. Manack,
senior vice president and general manager at the Atlanta-based
Harbinger Corp., an e-commerce software and service company with
$135 million in revenue last year.
</P>
<P>
   Today, e-commerce between businesses accounts for 84 percent of
all Internet transactions. And that figure is expected to climb to
92 percent of Internet commerce by 2003. Forrester Research Inc. of
Cambridge, Mass., projects business-to-business online commerce
will hit $1.3 trillion in 2003-- or 9 percent of U.S. business
trade. That dwarfs the estimated $108 billion in goods and services
businesses will sell to consumers in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until now, businesses needed to provide a good quality
product at a good price and deliver it on time,'' says Steven R.
Bell, an analyst with Forrester Research who wrote the report.
``Now executives need to look at every step in the business cycle
before the retailer sells the product to the consumer. This is what
is moving to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the computer and electronics industry is
leading the way. This year, the industry is expected to conduct
$50.4 billion worth of domestic business on the Web, or about 46
percent of all business-to-business trade.
</P>
<P>
   That's followed by utilities, which will exchange $15.4 billion
of goods and services over the Internet, or about 14 percent of all
business trade. Electric utilities are trading electricity online
as well as automating billing and service for commercial clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deregulation of the utility industry has been the catalyst
behind this,'' says Ronald Lynde, senior information analyst for
the Washington-based Edison Electric Institute. That's because
utilities now must trade information and electricity amongst
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A key way businesses are using e-commerce is by revamping and
automating communications within traditional supply chains. For
example, the Automotive Industry Action Group, a non-profit trade
group in Southfield, Mich., for 1,500 auto manufacturers and
suppliers, recently launched its AutoChain Online Web site. The
site tracks which North American suppliers are able to conduct
business electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's auto giants want to save money by reducing
inefficiencies caused by a complex web of communications between
manufacturers and suppliers. Today, it takes as long as four weeks
for information to trickle from manufacturers to suppliers. A 1996
study found North American auto industry could save $1 billion
annually, or $71 per car, if it moved communications online.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet also is forcing companies to shift resources to
online endeavors. A company that has embraced this challenge:
United Parcel Service, the $24.8-billion-a-year global package
delivery company headquartered in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, the company has pumped an estimated $1
billion annually into information technology. Today, UPS relies on
a handful of key e-commerce functions. For example, customers
connect directly to UPS's mainframe computer to manage orders,
payables and receivables. An online tracking systems enables each
customer to ship and track 100 packages a day. And a high-tech
delivery service lets companies send electronic documents that are
validated, digitally signed, verified and tracked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The implications of electronic commerce are forcing all of us
out of our comfort zones, `` UPS Chairman and Chief Executive
Officer James P. Kelly told business leaders in a January speech.
``It requires radical changes in our thinking and a retooling of
our business models.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the Internet is creating new types of companies
called ``infomediaries'' that use technology to bring buyers and
sellers together online.
</P>
<P>
   Two paper executives, Clay Maloney and Hilton Plein, founded the
PaperExchange.com in June. The Boston-based company maintains a web
site that enables paper suppliers and buyers from 40 countries to
negotiate for products ranging from container board to writing
paper.
</P>
<P>
   The company makes money by taking a 3 percent commission on any
deal struck on its site.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the startup has about 30 employees. Its online
membership has quadrupled in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Such new competitors are making traditional distributors and
middlemen nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of people out there that are trying to
figure out what their role in this new economy is going to be,''
says Manack, of Harbinger.
</P>
<P>
   Richard W. Oliver, a professor at Vanderbilt University's Owen
Graduate School of Management, says the companies that will thrive
in the Internet age will be those that embrace change.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question anymore that you need to be on the
Internet,'' says Oliver. ``The companies that win will be the ones
that get there first and do the most... Some others may find
themselves out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
