<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6170 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-APPOINTMENT-HN     04-05 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-APPOINTMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEPARD NAMED PRESIDENT OF HEARST'S KING FEATURES SYNDICATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ T.R. ``Rocky'' Shepard III has been named president
of King Features Syndicate, the world's largest distributor of
comics and editorial features to newspapers worldwide and a leader
in merchandise licensing.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment, effective April 1, was announced Monday by
Raymond E. Joslin, group head of Hearst Entertainment &AMP; Syndication
and vice president of The Hearst Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocky is ideally suited for this very important role at King
Features,'' said Joslin. ``He is a seasoned executive in
management, marketing and sales, including directing national sales
forces and selling creative properties across media platforms. He
is exceptionally skilled and will be an asset to the Hearst
Entertainment &AMP; Syndication Group.''
</P>
<P>
   Shepard has been with The Hearst Corporation since 1978. He most
recently was senior vice president, advertising sales of Hearst New
Media &AMP; Technology's HomeArts.com (now a part of the Women.com
Networks), where he was responsible for sales and marketing for the
largest women's content site on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard previously held vice president/publisher positions in
Hearst Magazines at both Country Living and Redbook. Prior to those
posts, he served as advertising director at Good Housekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard is succeeding Lawrence T. Olsen. During Olsen's 16 years
at King Features, the company attracted new talent, like ``Baby
Blues'' and ``Zits''; refocused product licensing to turn Betty
Boop into a merchandising star; rapidly developed Reed Brennan
Media Associates' electronic pagination business; and was
reorganized to put it on solid financial footing for the future.
Having accomplished his personal goals, Olsen has decided to pursue
new challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Features is fortunate to have been able to benefit from
Larry Olsen's many contributions,'' said Joslin. ``During his eight
years as general manager and the past two as president, King has
reinforced its position as the world's leading syndication company.
We wish Larry the best in his new career choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Joslin also announced that Keith A. McCloat has been appointed
vice president, business manager of King Features Syndicate.
McCloat previously was the company's vice president, resident
controller. He has held several posts in finance and accounting
since joining King Features in 1979, including assistant resident
controller, manager of accounting, accounts receivable section
supervisor, and general ledger bookkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   King Features Syndicate, which includes its North America
Syndicate and Cowles Syndicate affiliates, distributes some 180
features to nearly 5,000 newspapers around the globe. The company's
many popular comic properties include ``Blondie,'' ``Beetle
Bailey,'' ``The Family Circus,'' ``Hagar the Horrible,''
``Popeye,'' ``Zits,'' ``Hi and Lois,'' ``Dennis the Menace,''
``Mutts,'' ``Baby Blues,'' and ``Sally Forth.''
</P>
<P>
   King Features distributes newspaper columns by such well-known
figures as Heloise, Dan Rather, Dr. Joyce Brothers, Dr. Ruth
Westheimer, Marianne Means, and Arthur Frommer. The company
licenses its comic-character trademarks to more than 1,000 quality
manufacturers, advertisers and promotional partners worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   King Features Syndicate is part of Hearst Entertainment &AMP;
Syndication, the operating group of The Hearst Corporation that
also oversees the Company's television programming production and
distribution activities, and cable network partnerships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
