<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREYFUS-AFFAIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREYFUS: THE MOTHER OF ALL GOVERNMENT COVER-UPS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA BASS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ Emile Zola was a novelist, journalist,
playwright, critic, and the unlikely hero of the Dreyfus Affair _
the 19th century mother of all government cover-ups.
</P>
<P>
   While these days the Dreyfus Affair is little remembered, its
distinguishing motifs _ lies in high places for high-minded
reasons, media circus trials, hate-filled demagoguery _ are all too
familiar. And the affair's two great lessons _ that people of
conscience must always stand up to defend what is right, and that
official lying is always a dicey business _ are as relevant now as
they were a century ago, when scandal gutted a nation.
</P>
<P>
   The affair itself began in 1895, when Alfred Dreyfus, the only
Jew on the French general staff, was found guilty of espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus' conviction was based on one piece of evidence: a list
of military secrets, found in a wastepaper basket at the German
Embassy in Paris. Although some experts _ and Dreyfus himself _
insisted the handwriting wasn't his, the argument ``What can you
expect of a traitor and a Jew?'' made a guilty verdict inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus was sent off to perish on Devil's Island.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen months later, something most disturbing surfaced: a new
list of stolen military secrets, found in the same trash can, and
in the same handwriting. A secret inquiry easily _ and conclusively
_ matched the handwriting to Maj. Ferdinand Walsin-Esterhazy.
Dreyfus clearly had been framed.
</P>
<P>
   But then ... nothing happened. The army, taking the position
that protecting its honor was more important than rendering
justice, refused to admit its mistake. Instead, it forged
documents, threatened witnesses, gathered perjured depositions, and
told Esterhazy _ the real traitor _ that the Army and the War
Ministry would protect him if he kept his mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   Like all conspiracies, this one both stank and leaked. Soon
rumors of something official and evil spread; France split into
camps, Dreyfusard and anti-Dreyfusard. Frightened that so much
attention might blow its conspiracy sky-high, the government made a
bold public announcement: to prove it had nothing to hide, it would
court-martial Esterhazy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the court-marital was fixed. After two days of
meaningless testimony, Esterhazy's judges deliberated for three
whole minutes, then declared him innocent. The Dreyfusards were
stunned. It was then _ Jan. 13, 1898 _ that Zola spoke out.
</P>
<P>
   That he did so is quite remarkable, for Zola, until the affair,
had not been especially civic-minded; he'd been too busy becoming _
and then remaining _ an extremely successful writer. He produced
his first best-seller when he was 37; he was awarded the Legion of
Honor at 53. (A testimony to his popularity was the fact that _ in
those pre-cinema days _ his novels routinely were made into highly
commercial plays.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1898, Zola was at the zenith of his career. He had a lot to
lose, and he knew it.
</P>
<P>
   But he went ahead. On the front page of a Paris newspaper, under
the headline ``J'Accuse'' (``I accuse'') Zola lashed out at every
government and military official involved in the cover-up. He
charged them by name with outrage after outrage: falsifying
evidence, lying to the press, Jew-baiting and _ worst of all _
condemning an innocent man and acquitting a guilty one, all in the
name of honor and national defense. He ended by daring the
government to sue him for libel.
</P>
<P>
   The government, cornered, did sue, and won, driving Zola into
exile. A year later, he returned to France, where the
administration _ forced to react to the growing pressure exerted by
``J'Accuse!'' _ retried Dreyfus, again found him guilty, then
issued a general amnesty forgiving everyone: Zola, the generals,
Dreyfus himself. Zola returned to his novel writing. He died two
years later of carbon monoxide poisoning _ possibly murdered, which
some feared, and quite a few others hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Had Zola not put his career on the line, Dreyfus, however
innocent, would have died on Devil's Island _ an impressive
reminder (acknowledged by Dreyfus himself) of just how important it
is that people stand up, no matter the cost, and demand justice, no
matter for whom.
</P>
<P>
   And the affair is itself an impressive reminder that government
lies and official cover-ups, however high-minded the reason _
French national honor, U.S. strategic interests, the dubious
reputation of sitting presidents _ ultimately harm precisely those
institutions which the lies and the cover-ups hope to save.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cynthia Bass is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
