<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFANT BAY TRAIL COULD GROW UP NICELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When it comes to building trails, Jane Gomery
has learned the First Commandment of the public over and over
again: ``Don't tell me about the labor pains, just show me the
baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, a baby is being born, the Bay Trail, but the extended
labor is making this project along the San Francisco Bay both
prolonged and painful. Gomery, associate engineer for Burlingame's
Department of Public Works, has been one of the insiders trying to
ease the delivery.
</P>
<P>
   While the Bay Trail consists of a patchwork quilt of small
completed sections, the five miles of trail along the Burlingame
shore is a testimonial to what could be possible elsewhere in the
trail's planned route around San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   It runs roughly from the city limits of Millbrae on south
through Burlingame, and then hooks up with Coyote Point Regional
Park in San Mateo. It is an ideal trail for walking, jogging and
family-style easy biking, as well as for sightseeing across the
South Bay, watching the jets land at the nearby airport, bird
watching and shore fishing.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Bay Trail so difficult to complete is that there
is no single entity charged with building and maintaining it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every respective city government ringing the Bay is
responsible for its own section,'' Gomery said. The Bay
Conservation and Development Commission (BCDC) has the overall
authority for the right of way, but there is no time line, work
schedule or master budget to get the trail completed.
</P>
<P>
   With so many different governments involved, it has made for a
management nightmare. For instance, the Bay Trail on the Peninsula
dies at the south end of the San Francisco Airport.
</P>
<P>
   However, BCDC has arranged for an access route as part of the
airport renovation. This presents a ton of problems, both
engineering and political, with several agencies involved, to reach
completion.
</P>
<P>
   But in Burlingame, the emerging trail has had far fewer
problems, best represented on the section from ``Hotel Row'' in
Burlingame on south to Coyote Point.
</P>
<P>
   (To reach it, take the Broadway exit from U.S. 101 and park at
one of the small parking areas along Airport Boulevard, or at the
lots for a hotel, such as Embassy Suites or Marriott _ by contract,
recreation parking must be provided at the hotel lots.)
</P>
<P>
   Because these hotels are popular for those at conferences and
business trips, heading out on the nearby Bay Trail has become an
attractive adventure for visitors and their No. 1 orientation to
Bay Area outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   From here, it is a great stroll, hike or bike ride, heading
south toward Coyote Point. The first thing you will notice is the
dramatic expanse of the South Bay; up close, it is much bigger that
most envision, particularly at high tide. But even at low tide,
when miles of mud flats are exposed, there is a sense of great
magnitude, yet a place which nearly everybody takes for granted.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing that comes to mind is the procession of jets
landing at the airport. When the wind is blowing out of the north,
the jets will make their approach from the south, and from the Bay
Trail here, you can watch the jets make their descents and
touchdowns over a precision guidance landing system that extends
out over the water. At twilight, the blinking lights create
reflected radiance across the water.
</P>
<P>
   As you head south, you leave the jets behind, and in turn, start
seeing a variety of marine birds. Egrets, coots, sandpipers are
residents of wetland habitat here, and other migrants, such as
avocets in the past week, also make regular appearances.
</P>
<P>
   This trips makes a great family bike ride because the route is
flat and it extends far enough south to provide a decent round
trip, 10 miles. The destination, Coyote Point, is also a fun place
to explore, especially for youngsters, watching boats come and go
from the marina and launch ramps, and also with good fishing for
jacksmelt and perch.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Trail in Burlingame also is one of the best shoreline
access points for fishing in the South Bay. In the past two weeks,
for instance, huge bat rays have migrated to the South Bay, and on
high tides at night, often emerge from the main channel of the
South Bay to bottom forage within casting range of Hotel Row. Using
squid for bait at high tides at night, I have caught many bat rays,
known for their huge wings, sharp stinger, and long, thin tail, but
never the big one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For information on the Bay Trail, call the Burlingame
Department of Public Works at 650-696-7230.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
