<HEADER>
A6220 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      04-05 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARIABLE-ANNUITY MUTUAL FUNDS ATTRACTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 47, single and am concerned about ways to invest for my
retirement. I have contributed the maximum $2,000 a year to my IRA
account for the last 17 years, all of it invested in stock mutual
funds, and of course I am very happy with the results. I've also
managed in the past few years to put aside another $4,000 per year,
with the account now at $30,000 and all of it in money market
accounts. What is the best vehicle for this kind of retirement
savings? Would mutual funds be the answer? I won't be needing this
money for at least 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   R.W., Cathedral City, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds to me as if you're a good candidate for a variable
annuity invested in mutual funds. These accounts are very similar
to mutual fund investments, with one huge advantage and several
small disadvantages. The big advantage is that you can take
after-tax money such as your $30,000 and put it in a variable
annuity account where the taxes will be deferred until it is
withdrawn in your retirement years. When it is withdrawn in
retirement, only the portion of the balance that represents the
internal growth is taxed. The amount representing your initial
contribution of after-tax dollars is treated as a non-taxable
return of your capital. That's the advantage, and in view of the
fact that the account would grow to $125,317 if your investment
earned an average 10 percent annual returns over 15 years, it's
indeed a big one -- you'd have deferred taxes on $95,317 of income.
</P>
<P>
   The major disadvantages of variable annuities are twofold. The
first is that the expenses for variable annuity accounts are higher
than for traditional mutual funds. This is because these accounts
all carry some form of (FL)insurance,(FR) typically a guarantee
that after a set number of years, the account value will at least
equal the amount of your initial contribution, or the insurer will
make up the difference. Such (FL)insurance(FR) is critical, because
that's the element that allows you to claim the tax deferral.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the cost of the insurance tends to reduce the
investment returns by about one half of one percent when compared
to investments in traditional mutual funds with similar objectives.
</P>
<P>
   The second disadvantage is that when you put money in variable
annuity accounts, you will probably face penalties if you withdraw
it prematurely; these penalties can be levied either by the
government as tax penalties or by the company which offers the
product. It's important to read the prospectus for a variable
annuity carefully, because this instrument is much more complex
than a mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   If none of this has frightened you away, you'll find that most
major mutual fund companies offer variable annuity accounts, with
investment pools that very closely mirror most of their major
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you do make that move, you'll find that most of your
retirement savings will be in tax-deferred accounts. To get a
better mix, why not switch ongoing IRA contributions to Roth IRA
accounts, with the goal of having some of your retirement money in
accounts on which the taxes have already been paid, thus balancing
the heavier amount of money which has been tax deferred.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am contemplating selling my house, which is valued at
roughly $180,000. If I decide to do so, I will rent for a period of
six months to a year, after which I'll likely purchase or build a
new home. What would be a good investment vehicle for my money?
While I am renting, my housing costs will be reduced by about $600
a month. Thus I'll be able to save an additional $3,600 to $7,200
during the period while I'm renting. Where would you suggest I put
that money?
</P>
<P>
   S.S., Stoughton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, most people don't tend to think of it as much of an
(FL)investment,(FR) but to my thinking the best vehicle for you
here is a money market mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   Your investment time frame will be so short that you'd face
heavy risk even if you went with a conservative investment such as
bond funds. With such an investment, a rise in interest rates could
drive the value of your principal down sufficiently that you'd end
up with very little return -- and possibly even a loss. Stock
funds, of course, present still bigger risks. So I suggest you do
what a banker would do in such a situation -- balance the duration
of your asset (the savings) with that of the liability (the
requirement to have cash on hand in six to 12 months). If you were
more certain about when you'd need the cash, you might do a little
better with a sequence of CDs -- but that move would give you less
flexibility in timing the purchase of your new home.
</P>
<P>
   As for the $600 a month that you'll save during the period when
you're between houses, the appropriate investment depends on the
eventual purpose of the money. If you think of it as money which
will eventually go toward the new home, I'd invest it the same way
-- in that money market fund. But if you view this simply as a
short-term windfall and you want to treat it as long-term savings,
if you qualify for one why not use some of it to establish a Roth
IRA, adding an additional element to your retirement savings (which
I have edited out of your letter)? Since you have a number of
retirement savings accounts, I'd suggest that you use this to add
some real zip to the retirement portfolio -- buying shares in
Fidelity Select Health Care fund. If these savings amount to more
than what you can put into a Roth IRA I'd just add the extra money
to your existing taxable Fidelity mutual fund accounts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We will be selling our home and relocating to another state.
We are 48 and 50 years old and have a 10-year-old child. We have no
debt, and are currently in the 28 percent tax bracket. We are
adequately funded for retirement. We will have about $440,000 cash
proceeds from the sale of our home. We plan to buy another house,
but one costing less than that $440,000. We expect to live in that
home about 10 years. How do you suggest we pay for our new home
purchase? Should we finance it to the maximum? Should it be a
15-year or 30-year mortgage? How would you advise us to invest the
balance of the money to maximize our return?
</P>
<P>
   R. H., San Diego,
</P>
<P>
   A. Boy, what an opportunity -- if there's one thing that's nicer
than burning that old mortgage document in your own fireplace, it's
not having a mortgage to burn. Despite low mortgage rates and
despite the loss of the tax advantages that come with a mortgage on
your principal residence, I don't hesitate to suggest you use
whatever cash it takes to buy your new home, investing only
whatever money remains from your $440,000.
</P>
<P>
   As for a target investment for whatever remains, that would
depend on when you think you might need it. For example, if you're
likely to need all or some of it in about seven years when that
10-year-old begins college, I'd suggest a conservative bond
portfolio -- perhaps a combination of a short-term corporate bond
fund and a solid GNMA fund.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking that you'll only be in the new house for a
decade because you'll be retiring at that point and will then need
the money, I'd suggest a proven balanced fund, such as Fidelity
Puritan which divides its investments between the stock and bond
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Only if you have no specific purpose for this money and expect
that it will remain invested for many years, would I suggest that
it go into the stock market. And even then I'd invest it
cautiously, at least for the near term. In a case like this, you
might consider Vanguard Windsor II, Fidelity Value, or any other
proven value-oriented large-cap stock fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
