<HEADER>
A6222 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SMOKE-BOS &LR;      04-05 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SMOKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLOCAUST MEMORIES LINGER IN `SECOND HAND SMOKE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
SECOND HAND SMOKE 
By Thane Rosenbaum 
St. Martin's Press, 320 pp., $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so much that as a family they were strange, or that
from the beginning they had been estranged _ although both of these
things were true. It was that they were damaged. Irreversibly
ruined. The Katz family of Miami Beach came assembled that way,
without manuals or operating instructions or reassuring warranties.
Everything was already broken. Nothing worked right. Nothing ever
would.''
</P>
<P>
   With these attention-must-be-paid opening lines, Thane
Rosenbaum's ``Second Hand Smoke'' immediately reveals itself as an
expansive, challenging novel unconcerned about overreaching
self-importance. And for the most part, Rosenbaum's muscle-flexing
ambitions aren't necessarily a bad thing. A first-time novelist, he
writes with energy and urgency, as if everything on his mind must
be said, and said at once.
</P>
<P>
   Even its title is a clever slight-of-hand. In common parlance,
second-hand smoke refers to cigarette fumes, which can exact
devastating consequences on those who inhale them. The smoke
Rosenbaum often mentions comes from the more distant fires of the
Holocaust. The thick, death-filled haze of crematoriums wafts and
lingers through the decades, continuing to invade and choke the
life from its survivors, and especially their children.
</P>
<P>
   It is this heirloom of infinite horror that weighs on Duncan
Katz. He is the son of Mila and Herschel ``Yankee'' Katz, who
survived Auschwitz and Bergen-Belsen. He was born many years and
miles away from his parents' tribulations, but they remain for him
as present and indelible as a birthmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``What his parents gave him he couldn't pass off on someone
else,'' Rosenbaum writes. ``He couldn't even explain or understand
what it was that he had. Splintered, disembodied memories that once
belonged to them were now his alone, as though their two lives
couldn't exhaust the outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   That outrage percolates in his tough-as-nails mother, Mila. Once
she could find happiness banging out Gershwin tunes by ear on a
piano. By the time of Duncan's birth, though, she was so hardened
by her imprisonment that she declared music lessons were ``for
sissies.'' She wouldn't even allow her son a toy piano.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she enrolled him in martial arts and kickboxing
classes, goading him to finish off his opponents. By age 9, he was
a black belt, and in Mila's eyes, ready to defend against the
bullies, the persecutors, the ``pogromists in training.'' Mila
would often tell Duncan, who grows to become a Nazi-hunting lawyer,
``You must avenge our deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum, a child of Holocaust survivors, understands well the
paranoia of people like Mila, whose trust in humanity eroded during
the dark years when friends and neighbors turned against her.
Duncan is ever-suspicious, raised to trust no one. His mother even
had a code word _ ``Keller'' _ to shut down any conversation where
she felt her son had divulged too much, even if he was just telling
a friend where his father was.
</P>
<P>
   These early passages are especially vivid, deftly portraying a
Jewish community less than a decade removed from the Shoah trying
to re-create itself in 1950s Miami Beach. It's a colorful, singular
world where the local deli is a hang-out for Jewish goodfellas;
where the mohel, who performs circumcisions, is also a bookie named
Morty; and where Duncan's godfather, Larry Breitbart, really is a
Godfather, and a one-time compatriot of gangster Meyer Lansky.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum is equally confident in detailing how a parent's best
intentions can ruin a child. While Mila instills in Duncan
preparation for any atrocity, she's incapable of loving him for
fear that she will lose him. Having experienced so much loss, she
shuns attachments, even to her own son. Duncan grows to be a
wounded man, left incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum's footing is less certain as Duncan loses his job
because of his overzealous pursuit of a suspected Nazi, and his
wife, fed up with his Holocaust obsessions, skips out with their
young daughter. Then there's a twist involving a long-held secret
Duncan discovers after his mother's death. Neither the revelation _
which leads to Poland and a journey into Birkenau camp _ nor the
sticky emotional conclusion is as poignant as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what most distinguishes ``Second Hand Smoke'' are
Rosenbaum's own observations about the lasting stain of the
Holocaust. Through the book, he hovers above the story like an
all-knowing narrator from a Thornton Wilder play. Yet frustration
and tension are ever-present in his comments, as if he is trying to
unravel a particularly vexing equation, but knows there is no
soloution. What he finds is the unsettling reality that the more he
_ and we _ discover about the Holocaust, the less we can comprehend
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When would the world learn,'' Rosenbaum writes, ``that the
mystery of madness and atrocity would never be learned in books _
or even museums _ because the questions themselves are unknowable,
and the answers, even more so?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
