<HEADER>
A6223 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-HEMINGWAY-LIST     04-05 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HEMINGWAY-LIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW HEMINGWAY HAS FARED IN THE MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood's love for Ernest Hemingway may have been unrequited,
but love him it did. Only two of his novels haven't been filmed. A
screen version of one of them, ``The Garden of Eden,'' is in
production. As for the other, ``Across the River and Into the
Trees,'' John Huston wrote a screenplay he long dreamed of
directing.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has loved Hemingway so much it's not only made movies
from his works but also remade them. There have been three versions
of ``To Have and Have Not'' (Howard Hawks's 1944 classic; six years
later, ``The Breaking Point,'' starring John Garfield; and, in
1958, ``The Gun Runners,'' starring Audie Murphy), two of ``A
Farewell to Arms'' (1932 and 1957), two of the short story ``My Old
Man'' (1950 and 1979), and two of the short story ``The Killers''
(1946 and 1964).
</P>
<P>
   The first ``Killers'' was Hemingway's favorite among films made
from his works. He owned a print and would run it for guests at his
home in Cuba. Only the first 10 minutes come from the Hemingway
story; the remaining 93 spin out a noir tale of betrayal and
misogyny cleverly plotted by Anthony Veiller and superbly directed
by Robert Siodmak. It's also notable for being Burt Lancaster's
screen debut. The only things notable about the 1964 version are
Lee Marvin, in one of the title roles, at his most matter-of-factly
malevolent and Ronald Reagan, in his last film appearance, playing
a villain (slapping around Angie Dickinson, no less) for the only
time.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway's financial favorite was ``For Whom the Bell Tolls''
(1943): Paramount paid $150,000 for it, a then-record price for the
rights to a literary property. The studio spared no expense on the
production, and even on video the Technicolor looks ravishing.
Unfortunately, the locations look more like Lake Tahoe (much of the
picture was shot in the Sierra Nevada mountains) than anywhere
Iberian. Nor do director Sam Wood and screenwriter Dudley Nichols
spare any effort removing all ideological references from the
script. Someone not knowing any better could get the idea the
Spanish Civil War was being fought over a dress code. Loyalists
Ingrid Bergman and Gary Cooper look fabulous (even by movie-star
standards) in, respectively, jeans and leather jacket, while the
Fascists stand out with the comic-operetta ugliness of their
helmets and hats.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman, as Maria, gives one of her most luminous performances.
Cooper, as Robert Jordan, is at his most sturdily Gary Cooperish.
Katina Paxinou won a best supporting actress Oscar for her
scenery-chewing as Pilar, but the great supporting turn is Akim
Tamiroff's Pablo. His bellowing voice and wolfish beard cannot
conceal how the ravages of war have left him emotionally dying _
and morally dead. Bergman's Maria, Cooper's Jordan, or especially
Paxinou's Pilar might have wandered in from any number of other
movies (none of Pilar's would have been any good). Only Hemingway
could have created the wreckage of a man that Tamiroff plays.
</P>
<P>
   The one adaptation Hemingway had any hopes for was ``The Old Man
and the Sea'' (1958). After plumping for Vittorio De Sica as
director (a startlingly acute choice coming from someone who
professed to have no regard for the movies), he agreed to assist
Fred Zinnemann, the director of ``High Noon'' and ``From Here to
Eternity,'' with preproduction. After Zinnemann was replaced by
John Sturges, Hemingway disowned the final product (though Mary
Hemingway, his wife, makes a cameo appearance in a crowd shot).
``No picture with a . . . rubber fish ever made a dime!'' he
declared. One can only speculate as to how Hemingway would have
responded to ``Jaws.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that ``Jaws'' helped get ``Islands in the Stream''
(1977) made. The former's record-breaking grosses led to a
mini-vogue for nautical pictures (``The Deep,'' ``Voyage of the
Damned''). The one thing to recommend it is George C. Scott, who
looks quite Hemingway-esque, with his puffed-up chest and snowy
beard, as Thomas Hudson. This is the sort of intuitively right
casting all too rare in Hemingway screen adaptations. For example,
Gregory Peck is not the first name that comes to mind as a
Hemingway type, yet he starred in both ``The Macomber Affair''
(1947), a version of ``The Short Happy Life of Francis Macomber,''
and ``The Snows of Kilimanjaro'' (1952). Apparently, Hemingway
didn't think much of the casting either: He fell asleep while
watching ``Macomber.'' Presumably, he would have made a point not
to do that watching Ava Gardner as Lady Brett Ashley in ``The Sun
Also Rises'' (1957): He and she were friends. Gardner had acquitted
herself respectably as a femme very fatale in the first
``Killers.'' But even if she'd been a better actress, it's hard to
imagine her bringing much plausibility to playing an aristocratic
Englishwoman.
</P>
<P>
   Even more questionable than Peck and Gardner are Richard Beymer,
best known for his Tony in the movie version of ``West Side
Story,'' playing Nick Adams in ``Hemingway's Adventures of a Young
Man'' (1962), which cobbles together a number of early short
stories; and Rock Hudson as Frederic Henry in the 1957 version of
``A Farewell to Arms.'' Thirty-five minutes into a specially
arranged screening of the latter, Hemingway walked out.
</P>
<P>
   The 1932 ``Farewell'' is a different proposition. True, Helen
Hayes's winsomeness as Catherine Barkley verges on the toxic. And
the filmmakers' disregard for the novel is indicated by the fact
they filmed an ending in which Catherine lives (they finally
decided to stick with the original). Even so, it's a surprisingly
good film. Adolphe Menjou's trademark brilliantine sleaze is ideal
for Major Rinaldi, and there's a stunning montage depicting the
retreat from Caporetto that's pre-Code Hollywood filmmaking at its
most exciting. Of course, the sequence really doesn't have much to
do with the book, but that raises an important point: The Hemingway
movies that have succeeded best generally don't have all that much
to do with what Hemingway wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing demonstrates this better than Hawks's ``To Have and Have
Not.'' Lauren Bacall makes one of the most famous debuts in
Hollywood history. She and Humphrey Bogart create one of the
screen's great love matches. Throw in a supporting cast with the
likes of Walter Brennan, Marcel Dalio, and Hoagy Carmichael, and
you have one of the most entertaining films of the Studio Age. ``I
can make a movie out of the worst thing you ever wrote,'' Hawks
told Hemingway. So he did, but only by throwing out everything from
the novel except its title, the hero's name (Harry Morgan), and his
occupation (charter-boat captain).
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's love of Hemingway extends to his person as well as
his works. Alas, he's fared no better as character than
inspiration. In ``The Moderns'' (1988), it's Hemingway during his
Paris years. Kevin J. O'Connor plays him as a sententious macho
blowhard, a comic foil given to muttering possible titles for ``A
Moveable Feast'' (``A traveling picnic?'' ``A portable banquet?'').
Bad as O'Connor's Hemingway is, it's preferable to Chris
O'Donnell's in ``In Love and War'' (1996), which tells the story of
Hemingway's love affair with nurse Agnes von Kurowsky while
recuperating from war wounds in Italy in 1918. For winsomeness,
O'Donnell rivals Hayes in ``A Farewell to Arms,'' and Sandra
Bullock, as von Kurowsky, makes two.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest movie portrayal of Hemingway takes place in Robert
Altman's ``The Long Goodbye'' (1973), adapted from Raymond
Chandler's novel. The author in question is named Roger Wade, but
there's no doubt who inspires the characterization. Magnificently
played by Sterling Hayden (who once auditioned for the part of
Robert Jordan in ``For Whom the Bell Tolls''), Wade has a
patriarchal beard, drinks too much, and alternates between violent
rage and crushing depression. Instead of putting a shotgun to his
head, he walks into the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Wade's death is all the more memorable and moving for being
played so undramatically: He simply leaves the frame. The single
most impressive thing about Hemingway's style is the impression it
gives of absolute control. What that control masks, though, is an
equally absolute terror of the loss of control. Watching Wade
surrender himself to the surf, we get some small, awful sense of
the price that style exacted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
