<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6225 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-DEBT-BOS &LR;      04-05 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-DEBT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBT-LADEN CARDHOLDERS GO FROM PARIAHS TO PRIZED PROSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as Scott M. dodged ``customer service representatives'' who
telephoned more often than his mother in pursuit of $40,000 in
credit-card debt, congratulatory offers for easy money continued to
roll in.
</P>
<P>
   With one hand, card issuers prodded the unemployed 30-year-old
musician to pay up. With the other, they continued to push
additional cards with hefty interest rates and catchy names like
``Aspire Visa'' and ``Future Card.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they don't really make the offers until you get
late'' with payments, said Scott, a South Boston resident.
</P>
<P>
   Prolific debt hasn't kept Scott and others like him from
becoming the latest darlings of a credit industry that now reaps
some of its biggest profits from those already in over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The new willingness to lend to those who a decade ago wouldn't
have survived an initial credit check comes as more customers have
begun paying their credit-card balances off each month _ thereby
denying lenders the interest rate charges that have traditionally
been their bread and butter. While $3,500 in credit-card purchases
earns a creditor between $30 and $35 in transaction fees, it can
generate between $300 and $350 in revenue from interest payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers have changed, that's the thing that has become most
unsettling,'' said Robert B. McKinley, president of CardWeb.Com, a
Maryland firm that tracks the credit-card industry. ``Your best
credit risks are paying their balances off in full.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinley estimated that between 29 percent and 43 percent of all
card holders, many of them baby boomers and professionals, no
longer carry a monthly balance. Credit-card firms have perversely
dubbed them ``deadbeats,'' and in some cases have slapped annual
fees on those who refuse to revolve their debt.
</P>
<P>
   Enter those who are willing to pay, and pay dearly, for the
privilege of putting it on plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Have a history of shirking your bills? You may not qualify for a
card that carries a competitive interest rate, but Aspire Visa will
issue you one for 27 percent a year and stiff late charges.
Recipients are automatically enrolled in a fee-based ``credit
protection plan,'' tacked onto their monthly balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that the prevailing philosophy was get your
credit cards in the hands of the most credit-worthy individuals,''
said Norm Magnuson, vice president of marketing for Associated
Credit Bureaus, which provides financial data to the nation's
credit-reporting agencies. Now, he said, ``the question put to
lenders is, `How do I find my niche so I can make money off of it?'
''
</P>
<P>
   High-debt homeowners, whose names home equity lenders regularly
purchase from credit bureaus, are another coveted market. More than
half of the $268 billion in home equity loans originated in 1997
were ``subprime,'' meaning they were obtained by consumers with
less-than-perfect credit, according to the National Home Equity
Mortgage Association. That can be anything from a few late payments
on a credit card to a bankruptcy filing.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors ``don't necessarily look at your ability to repay,
they just look at the equity in your house as the primary
determinant for eligibility,'' said John Roddy, a Boston bankruptcy
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   And while a Federal Reserve study found that almost half of the
home-equity loans taken out last year were used to reduce debt,
economists say many consumers appear to be loading up their credit
cards within months of wiping away previous obligations.
</P>
<P>
   The motivation to lend to people like Scott runs all the way
from Waltham to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years of growth _ the longest peacetime expansion in
US history _ Americans are spending more, owing more, and saving
virtually nothing. Last month, consumers spent 0.2 percent more
than they took in, while credit-card debt, which accounts for over
40 percent of all nonmortgage debt, climbed to $574 billion in
January.
</P>
<P>
   One result of the buying binge: Bankruptcies last year hit 1.4
million, a record, even as interest rates, inflation, and
unemployment grazed record lows.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in bankruptcy filings prompted the credit-card
industry, which sent out more than 3 billion offers last year, to
lobby Congress for new laws that would make it harder to declare
insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   Credit-card debt _ bundled and securitized _ has become one of
the hottest investments on Wall Street, a staple of pension funds
and mutual fund portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the highest-performing credit-card company stocks are
those of subprime lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the fastest growing credit-card issuers in this market
are Capital One Financial Corp. of Virginia, whose 1998 earnings
rose to $275.2 million from $189.4 million in 1997; and the $6.05
billion Providian Financial Corp. of California, the nation's
biggest issuer of credit cards backed by deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Providian charges its extra fees _ such as a $49 one-time
processing charge for its unsecured 23.9 percent Visa Classic _ in
an effort to insulate itself from losses if consumers default,
according to Ellen Richey, Providian's executive vice president.
Many, she said, are willing to pay more if it means a chance to
rebuild their credit. ``Try to rent a car without a card,'' Richey
said. ``If you are not getting a credit card, you really have
trouble going through life.''
</P>
<P>
   For consumers with troublesome credit there is also the Visa
Future Card, touted by another firm to those who make at least
$10,000 a year and have, among other things, not been bankrupt or
unemployed in the past six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``These customers are already at the end of their rope to begin
with,'' McKinley said. ``You are just handing them more rope.''
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts it is those in the middle and bottom of the
economic spectrum who flock to Consumer Credit Counseling Service
of Mass. for relief. The average amount of nonmortgage debt
reported by the 12,529 people who received counseling last year
from CCCS was $23,755. Their average income: $32,480.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that years ago, one of the biggest complaints I
heard when credit was tight from young people and people with
credit problems was that they weren't given an opportunity to
either establish credit or reestablish credit,'' said Mel Stiller,
executive director of CCC, which is underwritten by credit-card
companies. ``Now it's come full circle.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Law School professor Elizabeth Warren, an expert on
bankruptcy, worries that low- and middle-income debtors are using
credit cards to make up for reductions in real wages. She fears
that when the economy turns, so too will the fortunes of many
families now coasting on credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Americans have taken on more and more credit-card debt,
their capacity to weather the things that go wrong has declined,''
Warren said. ``Smaller and smaller bumps in the road cause them to
trip and they can't get up.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say it's too early to sound the alarm, because
credit-card delinquencies remain relatively stable, and an
increasing number of lenders have fine-tuned their ability to
determine who will ultimately pay their bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like you have some devil here handing you the keys to
hell, because if you don't pay, he loses too,'' said Richard
Kopcke, an economist with the Federal Reserve Bank in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens to folks like Scott when the nation's economic
engine _ stoked by large gains on Wall Street that have spurred
consumer confidence and spending _ starts to drag?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are looking for the economy's Achilles' heel, you've
hit upon it,'' said Mark Zandi, chief economist at Regional
Financial Associates, a Philadelphia-area firm that analyzes data
for banks and investors. ``This is the economy's most significant
weak spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's Warren was more bleak in her prediction: ``We are
dancing,'' she warned, ``even further out on a cliff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
