<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMC-MISSION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEERS KEEP AMC STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Jennifer Huntington, president of the Appalachian
Mountain Club, recalls that before she could join the club she had
to get signatures from two members willing to sponsor her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a lot more democratic now,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The operative word for the venerable outdoor organization that
Huntington joined in the early 1970s was ``clubby.'' It wasn't all
that far removed from the gentlemen's clubs that many of its
original members also belonged to when they founded the AMC in
1876. The earliest members were hiking enthusiasts affiliated with
Harvard and the precursor of MIT.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Boston-based AMC actively seeks new members and
aggressively markets both itself and the land it seeks to protect:
the mountains, forests, and hiking trails of the northeastern
United States. Joining the club now can be done with just a click
on its Web site: http://www.outdoors.org.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 10 years the AMC has nearly tripled its
membership'' to 82,000, says Huntington, who became president two
years ago. ``And it's the member volunteers who are the backbone of
the club. They run the chapters, maintain the trails, and make
things happen.'' The presidency is an unpaid position. Huntington
is, in effect, the head volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Born in India, Huntington, 57, grew up in England and came to
this country in 1963. A Newton resident, she is a former principal
of Watertown High School. ``I came onto the board of trustees when
the club was reenergizing itself and trying to attract new and
younger members and to become more diverse,'' she says. ``Now we're
searching for ways to conserve land for future recreation.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its outreach efforts, however, the AMC _ based in an
elegant bow-front brick mansion on Beacon Hill's Joy Street _ still
has an elitist image in some quarters. There is confusion in the
minds of many as to just what it is the club does.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most common misperception about the Appalachian Mountain
Club is that we run the Appalachian Trail, and we don't,'' says
Andrew J. Falender, executive director. The club is responsible for
only 350 miles of the 2,200 mile-long trail, though its members do
maintain 1,400 miles of other hiking trails in Massachusetts,
Maine, New Hampshire, Vermont, New York, and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   A self-described ``flatlander from Indiana'' but an ardent hiker
and mountain climber, Falender has been the club's salaried
director since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking isn't complicated, but making life easier and trails
smoother for hikers can be. The AMC operates more than 50 huts,
lodges, and other shelters in the Northeast and has an annual
operating budget of $13 million. ``We annually provide over 100,000
overnight stays,'' Falender says, ``serve more than 200,000 meals
and run around 500 workshops.'' The club also publishes its own
maps and guidebooks, and puts out AMC Outdoors, a monthly magazine,
as well as Appalachia, a biannual journal.
</P>
<P>
   America's oldest mountaineering club, the AMC was founded the
same year the telephone was invented, and was itself an innovation,
at least for Americans. At the time, recreational hiking was
popular in Europe but not in the United States, where most people
still regarded the wilderness as something to be conquered and
exploited rather than savored and saved.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the club focused its energies on developing a trail
system in the White Mountains and building huts along it to shelter
hikers. The eight ``high huts,'' spaced a day's hike apart and
operated under special-use permits from the US Forest Service,
gradually became synonymous with the AMC, as well as icons of
back-country New England.
</P>
<P>
   Most huts date from around the turn of the century, but each has
its own character, traditions, food specialties (hardy meals are a
high-hut tradition) and lore. The hut at Carter Notch, for
instance, is reputed to be haunted by the spirit of a man who
managed the entire hut system in the 1920s _ and liked Carter best
of all.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the high huts _ and the AMC _ declined in the
decades immediately after World War II as young postwar parents
concentrated on raising their children. Then in 1961, US Supreme
Court justice William O. Douglas, an outdoorsman, hiked the
high-hut system and wrote a lyrical account for National
Geographic.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, many baby boom kids were old enough to scale
mountains, and parents who read the article said: ``Why didn't
somebody tell us about this before?'' It soon became difficult to
get a bunk in the high huts in midsummer without a reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's the baby boomers's turn to hike with their children and
grandchildren, and the AMC is experiencing another surge of
interest. According to Falender, club membership has soared from
the 32,000 of 1990 to the 82,000 of today. (Annual membership fees
are $40 for individuals, $65 for families.) The club has 12
chapters. The Greater Boston chapter has nearly a quarter of the
total club membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lodging reservations for this summer are up 10 percent over
last year, and we got a record number of new members last month,''
says Falender, 54, who can readily relate to the new generation of
hikers: One office wall is covered with photos of his 12-year-old
son and 10-year-old daughter hiking along AMC trails.
</P>
<P>
   The high huts have probably never been more in demand than they
are now. So it came as a shock to the AMC leadership several years
ago when a normally routine application to renew the hut permits
for another 30 years met with fierce and well-organized opposition
from White Mountains residents. ``They called us a bunch of tree
huggers from Boston'' says Huntington. ``It was a wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the anger directed at the club was in reaction to the
AMC's intervention in the permit-renewal process of several paper
company dams on the Androscoggin River. Restricting dam use, it was
claimed, would result in a serious loss of jobs in an area already
suffering high unemployment. The AMC was also accused of noise
pollution from frequent helicopter flights to bring supplies to the
huts, of overcharging to stay in them, and of using its educational
programs to influence young people on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the club withdrew from the Androscoggin dam permit
dispute. It also agreed to reduce the number of helicopter flights
into the mountains and to have its educational materials reviewed.
``We have to be more sensitive to the economic concerns of northern
communities,'' admits Falender. ``That's something we haven't been
very good about in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Full-service fees for the huts, up to $62 a night (including two
full meals) for non-member adults and $39 for their children, were
not reduced. However, the age limit for a child was raised from 12
to 15, and the club has made one high hut, Carter Notch, a
self-service facility where guests cook their own food and pay a
maximum of $16 a night.
</P>
<P>
   The huts generate a good deal of money, Falender acknowledges,
but he says it's still not enough to cover the cost of operating
them. ``We estimate that for every dollar taken in the club spends
close to $1.50,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service recently recommended renewing the hut
permits. The recommendation is subject to review but is expected to
be granted.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dam-permit issue, Falender says, the AMC will
continue to push for worthy conservation causes _ such as
protection of the Northeast's 26 million acres of forest. ``Our
membership has made it clear,'' he says, ``that's what they want
their club to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
