<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR MOTHERS, OURSELVES, GOOD AND BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend had her nose surgically reshaped because it reminded
her of her mother. Every time she looked in the mirror, there was
her mother's nose.
</P>
<P>
   My friend had a particularly difficult relationship with her
late mother, so her decision to remake her nose is understandable.
She's spent years trying to undo the damage her mother did, trying
to forgive her. The nose change is a symbol of how far she's come,
and how far she's prepared to go not to become her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you get along with your mother you can fear turning into
her. Sometimes I catch myself behaving like my mother, doing
something that drives me crazy when she does it, and drives me even
crazier when I do it. I find myself saying: Oh no, I'm turning into
my mother.
</P>
<P>
   Part of this fear is a dread of aging, an unwilligness to accept
the inevitable. My mother is old, I'm getting older, and as I age
I'm becoming more like her. As the man says in that clever ad about
negative body image: I have my mother's thighs, I have to learn to
accept it. But I can't accept it. I have to fight it, even though I
know it's a losing battle.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with my thighs is easy compared to trying to change some
of the habits and quirks I seem to have inherited from her. It
occurs to me that one reason I fear turning into my mother is that
I dwell too much on the things I don't like about her. Maybe if I
try to think more about her positive qualities I'll want to become
more like her.
</P>
<P>
   My mother has a lively mind and a good sense of humor. She's
generous. She's resilient. She has a passion for certain things
that I envy. Now that she's in her 80s much of that passion
revolves around playing the lottery, but if that's what she wants
to do, who am I to say she shouldn't?
</P>
<P>
   I have been reading Anne Lamott's new book, ``Traveling Mercies:
Some Thoughts on Faith.'' She has a wonderfully frank chapter about
her relationship with her mother. She's torn between loving her
mother and being frustrated and annoyed that she's become old and
needy.
</P>
<P>
   LaMott's mother is a strong woman. She was a lawyer at a time
when few women were admitted to law school. She was divorced. She
raised two children. Now she's old. LaMott admits she's having a
difficult time accepting the change in her mother, the new
docility, ``the need of an elderly woman for people to see that she
is a very good girl.''
</P>
<P>
   LaMott writes, ``She used to wear a mask of makeup, so she
didn't always seem as vulnererable as she does now. The makeup
seemed to hold her together somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Now her mother always seems to have lipstick on her teeth. This
irritates LaMott because, she writes, ``It tells the whole world, I
tried, I missed, I have no idea it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   I can undertand how this might drive LaMott crazy, but viewed in
another way, that lipstick, however misapplied, is a sign that her
mother is still strong, that she hasn't given up on life.
</P>
<P>
   For years I tried to change things about my mother. I finally
came to realize that no one can change anyone else. My mother is a
separate person with her own ways, her own dreams. I can't make her
happy by trying to change her. I never could. I have to honor her
individuality. I'm the one who has to change.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about all this makes me happy I don't have an
ungrateful daughter like me telling me how to run my life,
browbeating me to exercise more, dress differently, clean the
house, eat this, don't eat that, save my money, spend my money. I
have to try harder not to be that kind of a daughter, for my
mother's sake, and for my own.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
