<HEADLINE>
FREE VOICE-MAIL SERVICE AIMED AT YOUNG ADULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN AND BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For teenagers and young adults who want to be liberated from
their parents' phone lines, a California company is offering a free
voice-mail service this month that they think is one step toward
that goal.
</P>
<P>
   The service is called EchoBuzz, and it requires users to listen
to three to 10 seconds of advertising before using the voice-mail
program. The service is being aggressively marketed in the Los
Angeles area for now, but anyone in the country of any age can sign
up and receive an activated password for use this month.
</P>
<P>
   Blaine Ung, chief executive officer of Blue Diamond Software,
which provides the EchoBuzz service, said the user dials a
toll-free 800 phone number, then enters a membership number and
password. After hearing the ads, the user can send and retrieve
messages. Anyone can deliver a message to a member, as long as the
user has the 800 number and the receiver's membership number.
</P>
<P>
   To sign up, users fill out a brief questionnaire at the
company's Web site (http://www.echobuzz.com). The company promises
confidentiality with the information it obtains, which includes the
member's name, address, gender, age, and e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   Although anyone can sign up, company officials acknowledge their
marketing and advertising is geared to the 15- to 19-year-old crowd
with a growing need for independence from their parents. The Web
page is tailored to teens, and after signing up they get a thank
you e-mail with a note emphasizing their ability to have a more
independent life with this service.
</P>
<P>
   ``EchoBuzz is ideal for teens that want to stay connected and
maintain their privacy without having their own phone lines,'' Ung
said. ``The service also benefits parents who get tired of taking
telephone messages for their busy, hard-to-reach teenagers.''
</P>
<P>
   A touch-tone phone is not needed for this service. EchoBuzz has
speech-recognition technology that allows the service to be used
hands-free.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said different regions of the country will be
activated at different times. If a particular region does not have
enough subscribers, there might be a delay in the start-up date.
All parts of the country are expected to be activated by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   EchoBuzz members will be able to send, retrieve, forward, save,
and reply to messages, as well as set up a group distribution list.
For example, if soccer practice is rescheduled, one message can be
broadcast to the entire soccer team distribution list as long as
everyone on the team is a member.
</P>
<P>
   The voice-mail service has some similarities to a program
unveiled three months ago by a Maryland company, BroadPoint
Communications. It offers free long-distance phone calls for anyone
willing to listen to advertisements first. BroadPoint's Freeway
service can be used after signing up through its Web site at
http://www.broadpoint.com.
</P>
<P>
   BroadPoint, which is unrelated to the EchoBuzz voice-mail
venture, has more than 80 advertisers, including Blockbuster,
Rolex, and Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Ung said he could not disclose what advertisers are part of his
free voice-mail service, but he said they include well-known
soft-drink, fast-food, music, and entertainment companies. The
advertisements offered will be tailored to gender and age group.
</P>
<P>
   Said spokeswoman Kimberly Goolsby, ``A guy won't get a feminine
hygiene ad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Potential snags with offer
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We've gotten several complaints about pantyhose promotions that
promise a free sample, but then end up billing you for extra pairs
you never wanted.
</P>
<P>
   This year we got a postcard offering us a free pair of Silkies
pantyhose in the color and size of our choice. The words ``Free
Sample'' are featured prominently on the postcard. Only on the back
does the fine print read that, after sending you a free sample, the
company will automatically send you shipments of four pairs every
month for $3.58 a pair, plus shipping and handling. They will bill
you for all of these monthly shipments, unless you write them and
tell them to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they also mention that you can return any pantyhose
you don't like, but keep in mind that you'll pay for shipping.
</P>
<P>
   When we called the Hoisery Corp. of Philadelphia asking about
their Silkies promotion, they responded by faxing us a copy of
their ``offer terms'' that say you can cancel at any time. Their
promotion is probably legal, because they do disclose in the
original postcard that you are entering into a potential long-term
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is many consumers don't realize this until they are
left with many unwanted pantyhose. This kind of ``free offer'' with
strings attached is common in the magazine and CD promotional world
as well. If you want a truly free pair of pantyhose, you should
send a ``cancel order'' postcard as soon as you get the free pair.
</P>
<P>
   In testing their no-obligation promise, we accepted a free pair
of Silkies in January. When it arrived, we instantly sent a
postcard canceling future shipments. We haven't heard from them
since.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
