<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR SAM WEISMAN PAYS ATTENTION TO DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Director Sam Weisman looks like a poker player
holding a pat hand. He's got a pair of aces _ Steve Martin and
Goldie Hawn _ with a John Cleese kicker in ``The Out-of-Towners,''
a reinterpretation of Arthur Hiller's odd 1970 movie that starred
Jack Lemmon and Sandy Dennis. Weisman, who took over the troubled
``George of the Jungle'' for Disney and transformed it into a hit,
has taken over the reins of this production. Paramount is hoping to
strike the same comedy gold as Disney. Weisman's smiling. Or is he?
</P>
<P>
   It's last April in Manhattan, and the production has
commandeered the penultimate floor in a skyscraper located in the
financial district in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Hawn portray a couple from Ohio whose son has just
left for college. On top of that, and unbeknownst to her, he has
just lost his job at a local advertising agency. In the scene
they're shooting today, Martin's arriving for a job interview.
</P>
<P>
   While Weisman hunches over a monitor, Martin, dressed in a dull
gray suit, stands off to the side, alone, with his arms folded
across his chest. He looks a bit like a monk on the verge of an
anxiety attack. Hawn is having her hair fluffed by an assistant
while another brushes makeup across her forehead. She's smiling.
Without giving too much away, the scene involves a reluctant Martin
being coaxed out of the elevator by a sympathetic Hawn.
</P>
<P>
   Cinematographer John Bailey, who started out as a cameraman on
Terrence Malick's ``Days of Heaven'' (1978) and recently was the
director of photography on the Oscar-winning ``As Good As It
Gets,'' discusses the lighting problems presented by the
floor-to-ceiling windows. Bailey wants the windows' eagle's-nest
view of lower Manhattan, but he needs to blend the light so the
background doesn't wash out the foregroud. Because, in this case
particularly, Martin and Hawn _ the foreground _ are carrying the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman, with script supervisor Joanie Blum on one side and
screenwriter Marc Lawrence on the other, observes the set through a
video monitor that feeds him the same image gathered by the 35mm
cameras. That image is all that concerns him because that's what
eventually will appear on the screen. Everything else is
irrelevant. He also knows that he's the movie's first audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's great about Sam is that he doesn't mind breaking the
cardinal rule of directing,'' says John Cleese, who plays a crucial
supporting role as a cross-dressing New York hotel proprietor. ``He
laughs in the middle of takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleese, who also played a key role in ``George of the Jungle,''
has high hopes for the film. ``I think it's a very funny movie in a
classic tradition. And Steve and Goldie are marvelous.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as electricians snake thick cables along the floor
and the overhead lights begin to raise the temperature in the
Continental Club setting, Martin lurks on the fringe.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence tells Weisman that he saw a great a cappella group
performing on the street and he's invited them to come back later
in the afternoon for an audition. Weisman, who sees the film as a
romantic valentine to New York, is looking for upbeat, authentic
music to reinforce the theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ready?'' asks Weisman of Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another minute,'' says Bailey, as he carefully measures the
light with a meter that seems glued to his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Hawn stands at attention, afraid to move for fear that she'll
disturb the work of the makeup staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right,'' says Bailey. ``Ready. Do you want to get a
run-through?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' says Weisman, as he readjusts his headset. ``Let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin gingerly walks to his position inside the elevator. The
doors close. But not all the way. That 1/2-inch slit won't do.
</P>
<P>
   It takes two technicians a few minutes to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing on the closing of the doors is important,'' says
Weisman, ``because it punctuates a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawn stands in front of the elevator. The doors open.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Martin is animated. His face grimaces in that chronic
comic way and his body comes alive. It's as if someone plugged him
in. He externalizes the inner anxiety of the job interview by
turning his legs into a rubbery mess and resists Hawn's pleas.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon, Henry, it's OK,'' says Hawn.
</P>
<P>
   Martin shrivels up.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``How was that?'' asks Weisman of Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go again,'' replies Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is repeated several more times until everyone seems
satisfied. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Editing in Massachusetts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, in an editing room located a few doors from
the Allston Car Wash in Boston, Weisman is sitting with editor Kent
Beyda, staring at the sequence on a monitor. Beyda, using Avid
Technology's film composer, on which all the takes are computerized
and editing is done digitally, is searching for one particular take
that Weisman recalls.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's Weisman doing editing one of Paramount's major
releases in a rehabbed garage?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I live here,'' he says. ``And I'm going to finish the
edit on the Cape, where I'll be with my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when his son, Daniel, 16, was admitted to Milton
Academy, the family wanted to be close so they moved from Beverly
Hills to Brookline, Mass. His daughter, Meg, 12, attends the Park
School, and his wife, actress Constance McCashin of ``Knots
Landing'' fame, is working toward her master's degree in social
work at Simmons College. They like it here.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman concentrates on the screen like a chess master planning
his next move.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one where the timing on the door is perfect,'' says
Weisman, who explains that the difference between a laugh and a dud
is sometimes just a fraction of a second. ``You have to cut at
precisely the right place or the joke is lost.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see that the shoot hasn't been easy for Weisman. He
took the troubled film over when it was still in pre-production and
the previous director left. It's similar to what occurred on
``George of the Jungle.'' And Weisman is also itching to do some
films that he generates himself _ particularly one involving the
Cape Cod Baseball League.
</P>
<P>
   Beyda finds the take. On the monitor, Martin reluctantly steps
out of the elevator and the door shuts decisively behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one,'' says Weisman. He looks pleased. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A screening in Watch City &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the evening after the Monday night premiere in
Hollywood, Weisman invited some of his friends, colleagues, and
students to a private screening of ``The Out-of-Towners'' at the
Embassy Cinema in Waltham. Later, at the nearby Watch City Brewery,
they all helped him celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just nice to see everyone here and let them know what I
do,'' says Weisman, who's teaching a class on acting this semester
at his alma mater, Brandeis University, class of 1973. He looks
happy, even though the critics' verdicts would not be known until
after the film's nationwide release three days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how it goes,'' says Weisman. ``I think Steve and
Goldie and John did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   He turns his attention to his friends and neighbors, an
out-of-towner who's found his town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
