<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN DEBORAH COX MAKES AN UNLIKELY R&AMP;B STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two pairs of Gucci shoes are on a table next to
Deborah Cox, as she sits in her Beverly Hills Hotel suite, awaiting
a dinner party. The plush suite and the expensive shoes signal that
Cox may be on her way to diva status, but that image evaporates
once this Toronto-bred singer _ the first Canadian R &AMP; B artist
ever to reach stardom _ begins to reveal her true personality.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, 25, has refined tastes _ and shares the same record label
(Arista Records) as diva queen Whitney Houston _ but please don't
use the D word around her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not,'' Cox says firmly, but not rudely, to the diva
question. ``I'm really a settled, down-to-earth person. I treat
people the way I like to be treated, and that's just with respect.
I've always been very down-to-earth and not fazed by the music
business, or by what other people do. I just walk my own path.''
</P>
<P>
   Walk her own path?
</P>
<P>
   A better word is ``running,'' for that's been the pace of Cox's
career in the last several months. She just made history with the
longest-running No. 1 R &AMP; B hit of all time _ 14 weeks at the top
with ``Nobody's Supposed to Be Here,'' an impassioned, gospel-edged
tune about a rejuvenated romance. The song also hit No. 2 on the
pop charts _ and was kept from No. 1 only by the R. Kelly/Celine
Dion duet during Christmas, ``I'm Your Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and Celine, coincidentally, have played pivotal roles in
her life. Kelly is taking her out as his opening act on a tour that
stops at the FleetCenter May 7, and Dion once gave Cox a job as her
backup singer.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, if you can't tell by now, is going places. She has a
lustrous presence _ and a talent that makes her second and current
album, ``One Wish,'' one of the most spectacular examples of pop/R
&AMP; B singing this side of Houston and Mariah Carey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deborah is a natural,'' says Arista president Clive Davis, who
has advised numerous hit singers in his tenure. ``She's got soul,
beauty, and a roaring, powerful voice. The time for her is right
now, and she is breaking as America's newest star.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has a vested commercial interest in Cox, but he's also
taking an abiding personal interest. ``He just wants me to have the
best,'' says Cox. ``It's kind of like a parent _ and Clive has
really been that for me. A lot of times I'll see myself a certain
way, but Clive, because he's been in the business for so long and
has groomed superstars, knows the right steps to take. So I take a
back seat and just sit back and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox's real parents were both Guyanese. Her mother remarried and
her stepdad was Canadian. Cox grew up in the suburban town of
Scarborough and attended the Claude Watson School for the Arts in
Toronto. But her vocal influences are mostly non-Canadian: ``Gladys
Knight, Stevie Wonder, Marvin Gaye, Bob Marley, and Aretha
Franklin,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An R &AMP; B rarity
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Cox was surrounded by many forms of music, but had
to hunt to find R &AMP; B. ``In Toronto, I didn't hear a lot of R &AMP;
B,'' she adds. ``There aren't any R &AMP; B stations in Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, she learned from her parents' records.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my first dose of black music. I heard jazz, reggae,
and R &AMP; B from my parents' records,'' she says. ``I also went to a
Catholic primary school and during those years from grade two to
grade eight, I did talent shows and joined local bands. I started
signing with bands when I was 12 and singing commercial jingles
when I was 14. That gave me a lot of experience learning about the
studio and about the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of bumps and bruises along the way,'' she
adds. ``When I was 15, I went to a performing-arts high school. It
was during that time that I met a songwriter/producer, Lascelles
Stephens, and the two of us wrote songs and put our ideas on tape
and sent them to different record companies. Then in 1993, I got
the attention of Clive Davis. . . . I moved to LA in 1994 and put
out my first album in 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   To make it from Canada, and especially as an R &AMP; B singer, Cox
has been up against steep odds, but she never doubted herself. When
she spoke recently at a Grammy in the Schools seminar before a
bunch of high school students, she had some straight-from-the-gut
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much told them that to be in this business, you've
got to have heart. You've got to love to do it because there's
going to be a lot of hard work where you're not going to get paid.
And if you're in it for the money, then get out of the business.
Don't even think about being involved. You've got to educate
yourself. And you've got to be able to be flexible if you want to
be an artist, because not every time is your vision what the record
company's vision is. So I've learned to compromise and I've learned
to work with the record company in that aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The gospel influence
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She also learned to appreciate gospel music, which has
influenced her dramatic, push-the-boundary voice. ``Like I said, in
Toronto the culture is different, so I didn't grow up singing in
Baptist churches. But I did audition for a play called `Mom, I Want
to Sing,' which was a gospel-based play. And that's where I started
to study a lot of different (gospel) singers. I studied Yolanda
Adams _ she's an incredible vocalist _ and BeBe and CeCe Winans.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox co-writes half of her material _ she and Stephens co-wrote
the optimistic ``I Won't Give Up'' and ``Love Is on the Way'' on
her recent CD _ but she also used outside contributions from
heavyweight tunesmiths such as Diane Warren and Montel Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The latter co-wrote the record-setting ``Nobody's Supposed to Be
Here.'' As Cox says, ``We did a dance remix of it, and it has spent
10 weeks at No. 2 on Hot 100 singles charts. So the song, as urban
as it originally sounded, the dance version has taken it to a whole
other level and a whole other audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences had better get used to that, because Cox plans to
stick around awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about longevity,'' Cox says. ``I want to be an artist
who, 10 years from now, won't be a has-been. And part of that
longevity is singing really great songs. That's always been our
main goal and focus. Every album we put together, it's about the
song. And that's what's going to give you the longevity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
