<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6269 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERBS-IDENTITY-BOS &LR;      04-05 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBS-IDENTITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBS UNIFY AN ETHNIC GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUCE, Yugoslavia _ The slogan painted on a boulder outside this
highland village reads ``Unity Saves Serbs,'' but Svedlana
Pavecevic, a 32-year-old lawyer, is dismayed by the bellicose
nationalism that is rallying so many Serbs in the face of Western
air attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbs have become devils to the world,'' she said. ``When this
is all over, we will have to live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavecevic, five months pregnant, fled to her sister's home here
from Belgrade last week as NATO bomb attacks intensified and she
became terrified for the life growing in her womb. ``We could feel
the blasts on our backs, and we wondered, `How could it come to
this in the Europe of 1999?' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Serbs, especially the young and educated, she despises
the regime of Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic, whom she regards
as a thug and dictator.
</P>
<P>
   She also believes that the NATO attacks are at least as morally
repugnant as any violence inflicted on Albanians in Kosovo. ``A
wrong done in Kosovo does not make right a bomb on a Yugoslav city
where also innocent people are living,'' she said. ``My baby will
be born into a war because of Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she added: ``In the depths of night, a few Serbs have
to wonder, `What is bringing the world's fury down upon us? Will
the bad name given Serbs follow us for years and years, even
centuries?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The first yellow forsythia are blooming in Kuce, and sheep
browse peacefully on the steep rock-strewn slopes. This Montenegrin
Serb enclave seems a world away from the chaos enveloping
Yugoslavia. No smart missiles are zeroing in on the sturdy stone
houses or the village's sole cafe. No long columns of desperate
refugees are arriving to prick the local conscience.
</P>
<P>
   But the world's anger at Yugoslavia is uppermost in the minds of
every one of Kuce's few hundred inhabitants. Scratch any Serb these
days, and you will find an ouraged patriot quick to denounce the
airstrikes. Beneath the bluster and defiance, however, you will
find some Serbs deeply anguished by their new status as
international pariahs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much evil blood pulses through the veins of the Balkans,''
said Radoca Milic, 64. ''Some of it is our own, although nobody
wants to admit this. We are so quick to cry out against the wrongs
done to us, and so blind to the evil we do.''
</P>
<P>
   In that, many Serbs and their Montenegrin cousins seem
frighteningly similar to the ``good Germans'' of the Hitler era,
almost willfully ignorant of the horrors being perpetuated in their
name.
</P>
<P>
   Not so many miles from here, terrorized ethnic Albanians are
hemorrhaging from Kosovo province, driven from their homes by
paramilitary goons operating under the banner of Serb nationalism,
and with the blessings of the Milosevic government in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But only a few Serbs even concede a tragedy is unfurling in
their beloved homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers are crying, any human ear can hear them,'' said Milic.
``We have to admit that we have brought the world down on us
because we have too often turned our eyes away.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's a distinctly minority view, one increasingly seen as
almost subversive in Yugoslavia as even Milosevic-hating liberals
feel a patriotic duty to close ranks against the United States and
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart, I cannot accept that Serbs are committing
atrocities in Kosovo,'' said Nenad Jegdic, an electrical engineer
who in the past has joined protests against Milosevic, but who now
feels all Yugoslavs have no choice but to support the government.
``We are mostly decent, hard-working people who wish no one any
harm. How does Mr. Clinton expect to solve a problem by blowing up
bridges and buildings in Belgrade? It is the Americans who are war
criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   During the early days of the allied air campaign, Montenegro TV
broadcast CNN images of refugees streaming from their ruined cities
in Kosovo. But the republic has since bowed to pressure from
Belgrade to censor Western news accounts. Serbs in the rest of
Yugoslavia have been exposed to nothing but Belgrade's efficent
propaganda machine for years.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most pro-Western Serbs scoff at the suggestion that
massive atrocities are occurring in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it is impossible,'' said farmer Sretan Bulatocic, 69.
``Serbs do not kill people except in self-defense. Maybe some bad
Serb has done some bad things, just like some bad Albanians have
done some bad things. But how can you label our whole society? To
call us guilty as a people is crazy and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   There are still ruins in this village of houses destroyed by
German troops in World War II in retaliation for attacks by Serb
resistance fighters, who were among the most ferocious anti-Nazis
in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was shot dead by Germans when I was 4,'' said
Rudamila Bulatovic, Sreten's wife. ``Now we wonder whether we will
be shot dead by Americans. It is the fate of Serbs to be
misunderstood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
