<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6270 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS &LR;      04-05 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING A REVEALING LOOK AT BREAST CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLAUDIA STERNBACH  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   APTOS, Calif. _ It's not that it's an unattractive photograph.
Not at all. It's actually quite beautiful. Stark. In black and
white, the image is somber, yet hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Under other circumstances I would appreciate its artistic form
and admire the talent of the photographer. I wouldn't be the least
bit uncomfortable gazing on the image of the totally naked breast.
I think the woman who posed, who stood bravely in front of the
camera, her breast lighted by the sun, should be applauded. And
envied.
</P>
<P>
   This looks like a picture at a gallery exhibit. Or one from a
book on nudes. But the first time I saw it was when I opened my
mail. A package had arrived from my publisher. This was to be my
book cover.
</P>
<P>
   I liked how my name looked on the cover. Spelled correctly. Just
above the woman's underarm. I liked how the title, ``Now Breathe,''
was laid out in two different type fonts.
</P>
<P>
   But the naked breast. The sunlit nipple. Oh my.
</P>
<P>
   Kira, my 13-year-old daughter, panicked first. ``What if people
think it's you?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't thought of that. Taking a second look at the image, I
realized that wouldn't be so bad. Whoever had posed was much better
built than I. But that didn't cut it with Kira. Kids at school
might see the book. They might think I had posed. It could ruin her
life. (At 13 it is sometimes hard to see the whole picture.
Difficult to get a glimpse of the whole world when your vision is
obstructed by the capital letters, ME, ME, ME.) When Michael came
home I showed the cover to him. ``Wow'' was his response. ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good wow, or bad wow?'' I wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just `Wow.'''
</P>
<P>
   I tried to imagine this book sitting on my parents' coffee
table, next to the candy dish full of M&AMP;M's. I couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   I pictured my father-in-law showing it off to his poker buddies.
</P>
<P>
   That was really a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Becky, when she saw it, mentioned the South. And the
Bible Belt. Perhaps this cover wasn't quite lady-like enough for
that neck of the woods.
</P>
<P>
   I phoned the publishers to express my concerns. They are lovely
people. They want the book to be successful. They love the cover.
</P>
<P>
   Love the cover. They also own the book. They were kind but firm
_ in a lovely way.
</P>
<P>
   I let a couple of days go by. I left the picture on my desk and
every now and then would take a peek. It is a book about having
breast cancer, so putting a breast on the cover made sense. But I
had pictured something different. Flowers maybe. Or Half Dome in
Yosemite. The roller coaster down at the boardwalk. (There's a good
metaphor.) I asked my well-published friend Anne how often she has
gotten to choose her cover art. Never, she told me. She offered to
coordinate a benefit for me. A ``buy-back-the-book'' benefit. She
would gather some friends and they would all do readings. They
would sell tickets. A fine plan. If I wanted to buy back the book.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day Becky said she thought it might be a good cover
design. It made a statement. And my friend Christy told me she
couldn't think of anything more appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   I passed by my desk and looked at the photo again. I was
starting to warm to it.
</P>
<P>
   A few days went by and Kira asked me what I was going to do
about the cover. I asked her how she felt about it. Did it still
bother her? Apparently, the shock had worn off. She shrugged her
shoulders. ``Whatever,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   High praise.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know who she is _ this woman in the photograph. But I
have begun to feel as though I somehow owe it to her to let her
live on the cover of this book. She was brave to pose for the
camera. She is quite a beauty and the picture of health.
</P>
<P>
   For years we kept cancer in the closet. We only whispered the
word behind closed doors. We have come a long way. So what better
image for a book about breast cancer? What could be more honest?
More truthful? And after being diagnosed with cancer, there is no
time for anything but the truth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Claudia Sternbach's book, ``Now Breathe,'' is being published
by Whitaker Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
