<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRIS-ODONNELL-IN-COOKIE'S-FORTUNE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRIS O'DONNELL ISN'T ROBIN ANY MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Chris O'Donnell in a scene from
``Cookie's Fortune.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Chris O'Donnell won't be slipping into his Robin tights again
anytime soon. And, truth to tell, that's not a bad thing.
 &HT;    ``Ever since my wife found out we were going to have a baby,
it's been `Goodbye, healthy food!' and `I want steak, I want
potatoes,''' he says, patting a stomach which does indeed display a
slight paunch. ``The other night, I said, `Shoot, I'm the one who's
getting fat here.'
 &HT;    ``I'm not sure those tights from my superhero days would fit
anymore.''
 &HT;    O'Donnell breaks into a laugh, disrupting breakfast on a cool
spring morning at Los Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel. Yes, he can joke
about ``Batman and Robin'' (1997), the much-hyped turkey that _ at
least according to rumor _ almost cost him his career.
 &HT;    ``I couldn't get a job,'' O'Donnell moans, emitting a fake sob,
and then laughs again.
 &HT;    Actually, he says, his two-year hiatus from the screen was
intentional. Largely it was to give him time to get married and
adjust to life as half of a couple, but it also involved getting
away from Hollywood for awhile and, perhaps, giving audiences a
break as well.
 &HT;    ``You also get to the point where I think people get sick of
seeing your face onscreen,'' O'Donnell says. ``I knew it was time
to disappear for a little while.''
 &HT;    Now he's back, with a full slate of projects including, most
notably, Robert Altman's ``Cookie's Fortune,'' opening April 9 in
New York and subsequently around the country, and ``The Bachelor,''
a romantic comedy that's due in September and represents his debut
as a producer.
 &HT;    It's been a while since O'Donnell was around, but he still comes
across as Hollywood's biggest boy scout. While their peers were
gilding the Tinseltown party circuit, he and his wife _ Caroline, a
kindergarten teacher _ were living the quiet life in Chicago. His
biggest extravagance was the reported purchase of a $1,000 bed from
this very hotel.
 &HT;    And, yes, teen-age girls are still flinging themselves at this
reluctant sex symbol and, yes, he still says he isn't interested.
 &HT;    ``To me, the relationship I have with my wife has so much more
value than just a fling here and there,'' he says with a shrug. ``I
guess it all comes down to what you believe in. My morals are part
religion and part the way I was brought up, which was with
values.''
 &HT;    That isn't to say that he can't turn up the heat onscreen.
``Cookie's Fortune'' casts him as Jason Brown, a dimwit Mississippi
cop in love with the town rebel (Liv Tyler). When her aunt Cookie
(Patricia Neal) is found dead, it's up to O'Donnell's character to
investigate what Cookie's nieces (Glenn Close and Julianne Moore)
insist is a murder.
 &HT;    Along the way O'Donnell has several steamy scenes with Tyler.
Steamy, at least, from an audience point of view.
 &HT;    ``It was funny,'' the actor says, ``because when we did our
first makeout scene, they said `Cut,' and I pulled back and looked
at Liv. She was just red everywhere on her face. I was like, `Good
God! What did I do to this girl?''
 &HT;    Actually, all he did was to forget to shave, not realizing that
Tyler has extremely sensitive skin.
 &HT;    O'Donnell sighs.
 &HT;    ``The crew was looking at me like, `You brute!'''
 &HT;    It was the chance to work with Altman that sold him on getting
back to work, O'Donnell adds.
 &HT;    ``It was kind of like a no-brainer,'' the actor says. ``Robert
Altman calls, and I was like, `OK, I'll do it.'
 &HT;    ``Then you say, `Oh, what's the role?'''
 &HT;    Despite box-office flops with ``In Love and War'' (1997) and
``The Chamber'' (1997), O'Donnell was still on Hollywood's hot list
when he virtually disappeared from sight.
 &HT;    Not everybody could turn down multimillion-dollar paychecks,
especially with a wife and family to think about. And indeed,
O'Donnell admits that he was tempted.
 &HT;    ``It was tough,'' he concedes. ``But you know what? I was
looking at my friends who were living a 9-to-5 life, and I envied
them. I wanted to come home in the afternoon, read the paper, eat
dinner and watch TV. I didn't want the craziness of Hollywood.''
 &HT;    It was a natural reaction from a young man who has been famous
ever since a spur-of-the-moment response to a Chicago newspaper
advertisement turned into a featured role in ``Men Don't Leave''
(1990) and made the Boston College business major a star.
 &HT;    ``Being famous so young is tough,'' the 29-year-old says. ``For
instance, I've been doing interviews since I was 18 years old. I've
been asked my life philosophy more times than I can count. I want
to scream, `I'm 18 years old, I haven't figured anything out!'
 &HT;    ``I'll read my old interviews and think, `Are you for real?'''
 &HT;    After ``Men Don't Leave'' (1990), O'Donnell found himself on a
fast train to stardom, appearing in such hits as ``Fried Green
Tomatoes'' (1991), ``School Ties'' (1992) and ``The Three
Musketeers'' (1993).
 &HT;    Along the way, however, he misplaced his privacy. A few years
ago he was in a fender-bender in Chicago, the actor recalls, and
the investigating officer wanted an autograph for his kid.
 &HT;    ``It's worse in L.A.,'' he adds. ``I got attacked at the Ivy,
coming out of lunch in the middle of the day. It was this group of
kids across the street with video cameras.
 &HT;    ``I started to think, there's videotapes all over the world of
me doing random dumb things and in bad free T-shirts,'' he says
with a rueful smile. ``Now I get up and think, `Do I want this
orange shirt preserved forever on someone's tape? What should I
wear for historical purposes?'''
 &HT;    Nowadays he's wearing two hats, as star and producer of ``The
Bachelor,'' a remake of Buster Keaton's 1925 silent-film classic
``Seven Chances'' that casts him as a man given 24 hours to get
married or lose his inheritance.
 &HT;    ``The best scene is when I'm running down the streets of San
Francisco being chased by 1,000 women in bridal gowns,'' O'Donnell
says. ``Depending on your perspective, that's either heaven or
hell. Since I'm married, I guess it's hellish.''
 &HT;    And no, if you were wondering, he wouldn't mind another chance
to play Robin, either.
 &HT;    ``I don't think they're going to do another `Batman' with me,''
he says. ``If they do another movie, they'll wait a couple of years
and then completely reinvent it with new actors.''
 &HT;    For the first time all morning, he sounds a little depressed.
 &HT;    ``I would do another Batman,'' he says. ``I enjoy doing them.
But it's not anything on a priority list.''
 &HT;    Topping that list is jetting east to start setting up a nursery
at his family's Chicago home, where he is to be found when he's not
at his new production office in Los Angeles.
 &HT;    Oh, yes, and about that bed: Actually there were two of them,
and if they're a sign of Hollywood decadence, O'Donnell can live
with it.
 &HT;    ``I did buy two beds from the Four Seasons Hotel in Los
Angeles,'' he admits. ``One for our house in Chicago and the other
for our place in L.A. I had to buy the beds, because they were the
most comfortable ones I've ever slept in.''
 &HT;    And, yes, the total cost ran to $1,000 per bed.
 &HT;    ``Hey, I think a regular, nice, king-sized bed is $800,''
O'Donnell says defensively. ``It's not like I went nuts or
anything.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
