<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-STARS-N-SYNC-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK SYNC: BEHIND THE SCENES WITH A TEEN SENSATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of the singing group 'N Sync. 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    He's a winner, but he isn't going to Disney World.
 &HT;    Justin Timberlake is actually in Orlando, Fla., for a couple of
days. But the Orlando native has better things to do than hang with
Mickey _ such as rehearsing with his band, the phenomenally popular
'N Sync.
 &HT;    ``So I'm really just in Orlando, not at home,'' says Timberlake,
who at 18 is the youngest of the five 'N Syncers.
 &HT;    The band works hard, and that work has been paying off. In
barely a year the group's two albums _ a self-titled debut album
and the ``Home For Christmas'' holiday album _ have sold more than
7 million copies, fueled by frothy hits such as ``I Want You
Back,'' ``Tearin' Up My Heart'' and ``God Must Have Spent a Little
More Time on You.''
 &HT;    That's made 'N Sync pop's hottest boy outfit of the moment,
eclipsing _ at least for now _ fellow Orlandoites the Backstreet
Boys and Hanson. Their only competition is provided by Britney
Spears, an old friend since her days co-starring with Timberlake
and 22-year-old bandmate Joshua ``J.C.'' Chasez on the Disney
Channel's ``The Mickey Mouse Club.''
 &HT;    ``It's become so flattering,'' says 27-year-old Chris
Kirkpatrick, 'N Sync's founder and oldest member _ as well as its
most recognizable, thanks to his colorful, braided hairdo.
 &HT;    ``We always have to keep each other in check,'' Kirkpatrick
says. ``We'll all go into one room or something and laugh and go
`Can you believe this is happening?' It's like a dream to us, just
to be walking in the airport or something and have someone say
`Hey! It's 'N Sync!'''
 &HT;    Not that the group's fans stop with shouts. Timberlake's
favorite fan memory is of one girl at an airport in Europe who
tried to get to the band by jumping onto a luggage-conveyor belt.
 &HT;    ``Of course she didn't make it through,'' he says with a laugh.
``Her disguise wasn't that good.''
 &HT;    But, he adds, the fans generally aren't that inventive.
 &HT;    ``They're usually grabbing at your clothes and ripping them off
and things like that,'' Timberlake says. ``I think the girls are
just _ they're real sweethearts, and it's just funny to see how
they try to get to you.''
 &HT;    Sometimes that's inopportune, however. Kirkpatrick recalls a
particular night in an Orlando bar, when he was chatting with a
young woman he had been dancing with. Six other girls spotted him
from across the club and came screaming over to where the couple
was standing.
 &HT;    ``They all started doing the `I Want You Back' dance, and then
they started going `Here's my phone number' and stuff like that,''
he says. ``And I'm going, `Oh, no ... '
 &HT;    ``That kind of blew it with that girl. She was like, `I'm going
to get a drink. I'll be right back.' And I never saw her again.''
 &HT;    Kirkpatrick isn't complaining, though. Stardom at this level was
only a dream when the Pittsburgh-area native moved to Orlando nine
years ago to live with his father and study music at a couple of
area colleges. He also worked at Universal Studios, where he met
Timberlake and future bandmate Joey Fatone, now 22.
 &HT;    While Timberlake and Fatone went the Disney route, Kirkpatrick
was forming his own bands. He even turned down an invitation to be
a Backstreet Boy after singing in a school choir with that group's
Howie Dorough.
 &HT;    ``He came in and said `We're having auditions for the Backstreet
Boys,''' Kirkpatrick recalls. ``I already had my own group, and my
heart was with them. I'm a very loyal person.''
 &HT;    That group eventually broke up, and in 1995 Kirkpatrick called
Timberlake and Fatone, who by then were free agents after the
cancellation of ``The Mickey Mouse Club,'' about his next project.
Timberlake brought Chasez with him, and 19-year-old bass singer
Lance ``Lantsen'' Bass was recommended by Timberlake's vocal coach.
 &HT;    The quintet, which takes its name from the last letter of the
first name or nickname of each band member, gradually put its sound
together, with assistance from ``Mickey Mouse Club'' music director
Robin Wiley, who arranged a version of the Beatles' ``We Can Work
it Out,'' as well as four original songs. Meanwhile Timberlake's
mom steered the fledgling group's business operations, as well as
housing Kirkpatrick and Chasez.
 &HT;    The group also benefited from the tutelage of Orlando-based
starmakers Louis J. Pearlman and Johnny Wright, although they're
currently in litigation over finances with the former.
 &HT;    In their early days, Timberlake says, the band weren't quite
sure what they were doing.
 &HT;    ``We were just really singing together,'' he says, ``anything we
could do a cappella, from Boyz II Men to old '50s groups.''
 &HT;    But early on, all five group members knew they were onto
something special.
 &HT;    ``There really is a chemistry involved,'' says Kirkpatrick, who
despite his wild image serves as 'N Sync's ``big brother.'' ``A lot
of us knew each other before the group ... and it's just amazing
that we've been together for about three years and we've never had
a fight.
 &HT;    ``We've all had music as a goal,'' he adds, ``and we're five
brothers experiencing music and life together. It's something that
you can't describe. You just have to experience it.''
 &HT;    And it's been quite an experience, including not only
chart-busting record sales but also an appearance in Macy's
Thanksgiving Day Parade _ sharing a float with a bunch of enormous,
dancing M&AMP;Ms _ and a gig opening for Janet Jackson. The group's
third album is currently in the works, with a tour headlining
stadium shows set for summer 1999.
 &HT;    The challenge, they acknowledge, will be maintaining this level
of fame in a sector of the music business known more for quick _
and temporary _ success stories than for long-term careers.
 &HT;    But Timberlake insists that 'N Sync isn't destined for the
bubble-gum-rock scrap heap.
 &HT;    ``Anybody who really groups us that way has only seen our
faces,'' Timberlake says. ``And I can see how it might throw them
off at first, just because of the way it looks. But when people see
our stage show and hear our music, they recognize the difference.
We're always thinking ahead _ we always want to move to that next
step.''
 &HT;    ``I know the five of us are going to stay true to the music,''
Kirkpatrick adds. ``We're happy with the teen idolness, getting in
the teenybopper magazines, having the girls go crazy at the shows.
But, like all good books, it must come to an end _ we understand
that. I can only say that in five years' time, I can tell you that
'N Sync will be together, whether or not we're superstars.
 &HT;    ``I would rather be a member of this group than the Beatles, the
Rolling Stones, any of those other groups, because these are my
friends,'' he says. ``'N Sync isn't even a group to us anymore _
it's a way of life. It's our being.''
 c.1999 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
