<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6260 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELISSA-JOAN-HART-IN-     04-05 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELISSA-JOAN-HART-IN-SABRINA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELISSA JOAN HART: A WIZ OF A WITCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Melissa Joan Hart with Beth Broderick,
Caroline Rhea and Jo Ann Worley in a scene from ``Sabrina, the
Teenage Witch.'' 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget about black cats, bats and bubbling cauldrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sabrina, The Teenage Witch'' is the sunniest show about the
black arts ever, thanks to Melissa Joan Hart, the high-spirited
young actress who provides a dependably upbeat tone to the show's
supernatural goings-on.
</P>
<P>
   Whether floundering with her latest boyfriend or conspiring with
the show's oddly animatronic feline, Salem _ Hart swears it's ``a
drunken rabbit with a hairpiece'' _ she serves as the popular
anchor to ABC's Friday family programming.
</P>
<P>
   Recently we sat down with Hart _ as well as Beth Broderick and
Caroline Rhea, who play her aunts Hilda and Zelda _ for some
Mexican food on the show's school-cafeteria set, along with a chat
about almost anything concerning the show, from learning lines to
facing fans and even Hart's attractive bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Hart's first starring experience was with the cable series
``Clarissa Explains It All,'' which is still airing in reruns. In
retrospect, she says, it's remarkable that she made it through
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were my high-school days,'' the actress says. ``I was
kind of young to have that much responsibility. I wouldn't
recommend it to any teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come down on people my age for playing teen-agers,''
the 22-year-old actress adds, ``but I think it's so much better to
have older people playing teen-agers than to have teen-agers
playing teen-agers and missing out on things like high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhea laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw `Clarissa' last summer,'' she says, ``I couldn't
believe what a little baby she was. My nephew, who is 4, is
obsessed and loves Melissa, whom he calls `Bobrina.' He also loves
`Larissa,' but refuses to accept that it's the same person.''
</P>
<P>
   Her eccentric role doesn't win her that kind of passionate
devotion, Rhea adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going through customs in Canada at Christmas, and I had
tons of presents,'' she recalls. ``I walked to customs, and the guy
goes, `Don't worry, I recognize you, you're that girl from TV.' And
I go, `Oh, well, thanks.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he says, ``You're on `3rd Rock from the Sun.'''
</P>
<P>
   All three women laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go, ``OK,''' Rhea concludes. ``Alien, witch _ close enough.
I'm not paying duty, that's the bottom line!''
</P>
<P>
   While Rhea has been talking, Hart has been flipping through
publicity photos for the show. She stops, her brow furrowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have my hands on my butt,'' she says, looking again
at the pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a magnet, honey,'' Broderick adds, earning another
round of laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've watched Melissa evolve from little girl to sexy mama,''
Rhea says cheerfully.
</P>
<P>
   ```Sexy mama,''' Hart grouses good-naturedly. ``Thanks.'
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want to be called, then?'' Broderick asks.
</P>
<P>
   Hart stops and thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ```Sexy mama's' fine with me,'' she says with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tortures us that she's growing up,'' Broderick says with a
smile, ``because we all want to give her advice and she doesn't
want to take it. Completely, exactly like the show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I take it a lot, though,'' Hart says defensively. ``I ask for
it a lot. These women, they know what they're doing. I'll ask
mainly about boys. Boys, career, anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know about boys,'' Rhea says, ``and Beth knows about men.''
</P>
<P>
   The two older women laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys are slightly less irritating,'' Rhea says, ``and their
skin is better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Men come in handy,'' Broderick adds. ``No. 1, they eat my
food. No. 2, they move heavy things.''
</P>
<P>
   More seriously, Rhea and Broderick are united in their praise
for Hart's professionalism and talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the most unbelievable, uncanny ability to memorize
dialogue,'' Rhea says, ``like no one I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' Hart says, clearly pleased. ``A lot of it comes from
`Clarissa,' which I did for four years. There was tons of dialogue
in that. I had monologues, two-page monologues, three times a show.
So it's easier for me to memorize scene by scene here, because I
have a few lines per scene.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Broderick's turn to discuss Hart, and she pauses
thoughtfully before speaking: ``I really, really, really think she
has ... great hair!''
</P>
<P>
   Again the three women laugh, hard enough to have trouble eating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now give us compliments,'' Rhea demands.
</P>
<P>
   Hart shrugs, perfectly willing to cooperate. It's Rhea's turn
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, she knows everything about astrology and can
tell you anything about a boy,'' the young actress says. ``She
knows all this boy information, for some reason. It's unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can't give herself advice, though.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, that was the compliment?'' Rhea snorts. ``Now to
your Auntie Beth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beth, too, is great at men,'' Hart says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   More seriously, she says, ``The two of them are like sisters to
me, and have taught me so much. Beth is very into old-school
training techniques, so she keeps me professional, she keeps me in
check.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, because they get along so well, but they're both
very opposite, kind of like yin and yang.''
</P>
<P>
   The three may play witches on television, but they don't believe
in magic themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made this tostada disappear,'' Broderick offers helpfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make career opportunities disappear with my big mouth,''
Rhea adds. ``But you know what men constantly ask me? This is the
only thing that drives me crazy: I'll be in line somewhere and
they'll say, `Why don't you make the line move faster? If you have
magic, why are you even in line?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always get, `Can you make my wife disappear?''' Hart says.
</P>
<P>
   Broderick snorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's nice,'' she says sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' Hart says. ``It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   All three get bags and bags of fan mail, they report.
Surprisingly, however _ given the show's genesis in a children's
comic book _ they rarely hear from young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine is all from adults,'' Broderick says. ``Mostly men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine is virtually 90 percent from men,'' Rhea agrees.
``Apparently, only three little girls watch this show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do get a couple of girls,'' Broderick says, ``and I try to
answer them when I get them. I get girls that say, `Aunt Zelda,
you're the only one who'll understand _ my mom works all the time
and I have this problem and I think you can understand me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get those, I do write back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhea laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get `Dear Aunt Hilda, I'm crazy, too,''' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all gotten the bikini catalogues,'' Broderick adds,
provoking laughter from all three.
</P>
<P>
   ```Pick your favorite bikini and fill in your size and I will
send it to you,''' Rhea says in a humorous voice. ```And then
please have yourself photographed in it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Fat Chance ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Of all their viewers, the three women agree that it's the
children, and especially little girls, that they're the happiest to
reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get little girls, little boys, college kids,'' Hart says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is meaningful to kids, and I think it does have a
great message,'' Broderick says. ``I mean, I wish when I was a kid
that I'd been watching a show where women were so clever and so
forthright and powerful. I love the way Sabrina deals with boys, I
love the equality in her relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have that when I was a kid,'' she says. ``We didn't
have people like that to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is the Los Angeles-based senior writer for TV
Guide Canada.) &LR; 
