<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-GOLDWYN-DIRECTS-A-WALK-ON-THE-MOON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GRANDSON ALSO RISES: TONY GOLDWYN STEPS BEHIND THE CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Tony Goldwyn with Anna Paquin on the set
of ``A Walk in the Clouds.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Tony Goldwyn knows more about Hollywood history _ which his
family has had a lot to do with _ than about Jewish-American
history.
 &HT;    But that hasn't stopped the actor, best known as Patrick
Swayze's lethally conniving friend in ``Ghost'' (1990), from
producing and directing ``A Walk on the Moon,'' a drama about the
coming of age of the very Jewish Kantrowitz family in 1969 that
will open across the country throughout April.
 &HT;    ``I'd never even heard of the Concord,'' Goldwyn says of the
fabled, now-shuttered Catskills summer getaway. ``My grandfather
was Jewish, but I grew up in Los Angeles in a completely
nonreligious household. The Jewish experience was really not a part
of my upbringing, yet I completely identified with this world when
I read the script.
 &HT;    ``I just figured that, if something moves me deeply, it will
move others, too.''
 &HT;    Goldwyn, a boyish-looking 38-year-old who's relaxed and
confident during a conversation at a Manhattan hotel, unearthed
Pamela Gray's script while seeking material to act in and produce.
 &HT;    ``I felt the need to broaden my horizons as actor,'' says
Goldwyn _ who might be a born producer, given that he's the son of
movie producer Samuel Goldwyn Jr. and grandson of the late,
legendary Hollywood impresario Sam Goldwyn. ``Developing my own
projects seemed like a smart way to go.''
 &HT;    Goldwyn worked closely with Gray to hone the script, originally
called ``The Blouse Man,'' through several drafts. The project
reached a turning point, however, when Goldwyn's director of choice
dropped out, spurring an unexpected discovery in the novice
producer.
 &HT;    ``At that point I realized I wasn't comfortable giving it to
someone else,'' he recalls. ``It became very obvious to me that the
only solution was to step up and do it myself.
 &HT;    ``I hadn't had a desire to direct, really at all, until I'd
gotten into the story development,'' he adds. ``Very shortly after
that, Dustin Hoffman dropped down from the sky as our producer, and
I found myself directing a movie.''
 &HT;    The film stars Diane Lane as Pearl Kantrowitz, a married woman
who, on summer vacation, falls into an illicit affair with a
free-spirited blouse salesman (Viggo Mortensen). The affair rocks
the worlds of her loving-but-dull husband (Liev Schreiber), their
two children (Bobby Boriello and Anna Paquin) and her knowing
mother-in-law (Tovah Feldshuh).
 &HT;    The emotional fireworks take place against a backdrop of
Woodstock and the Vietnam War, with the first moon landing looming
ominously _ and metaphorically _ in the background.
 &HT;    ``Taking the enormous risk of being true to yourself is a
courageous and dangerous thing to do,'' Goldwyn says. ``It can be
painful.
 &HT;    ``If you wake up one day and think, `How did I get here? Is my
life what I dreamt it would be when I was young?' and the answer is
`no' or `not quite,' then you have to determine if you can do
anything about it or if you are powerless,'' he adds. ``If you
determine that you're not powerless, what are the consequences of
change?
 &HT;    ``That's what the film explores,'' the novice director says.
``That's an impulse I identified with. Sometimes you need to break
all the rules, burn down the house and start over.''
 &HT;    Goldwyn grins.
 &HT;    ``Oh, I could relate,'' he says. ``Directing may seem like my
shot at breaking free, but my decision to be an actor was a very
big deal.
 &HT;    ``People not in the business may think film, as a whole, is the
family business, but that's not the case at all,'' he explains.
``Acting in a family of producers was an anarchic decision. And I
didn't even do that in the traditional way. I didn't go to L.A. and
do the inside thing _ I went to New York and into theater, because
I knew that's how I could authenticate my career for myself.''
 &HT;    Though over the last decade he's established himself as an
actor, Goldwyn freely admits to some doubts about his directorial
debut.
 &HT;    ``I figured I could fail, but that it would be worth giving
something I care about my best shot,'' he says. ``What's the worst
that could happen? I fall on my face.
 &HT;    ``As an actor I'd worked with a number of first-time
directors,'' he adds. ``From that I knew the recipe for success as
a director was surrounding yourself with people who really know
what they're doing, trusting them and not pretending to know what
you don't know.
 &HT;    ``I hired good people and leaned on them, and I also had Dustin
around as this creative eye who was watching my back.''
 &HT;    But no matter how good a support team he or she may have, it's
to the director that everyone turns for the answers to the thousand
questions that arise every day on the set.
 &HT;    ``I surprised myself,'' he says. ``I had the answers. It shocked
me, but it all felt very natural.
 &HT;    ``I think I had a whole set of skills that are suited to the job
of directing that I didn't realize I had,'' he adds. ``I had
managerial skills, and was able to make decisions fast.
 &HT;    ``Making decisions is the hardest aspect,'' Goldwyn says. ``You
have all of these choices and options that you could easily agonize
over, but you learn to trust your instincts.
 &HT;    ``And I found that process fun.''
 &HT;    If that sounds like a man who's planning to keep directing, it
should. But that doesn't mean he's giving up acting. Goldwyn will
be seen soon in the independent films ``Trouble in the Corner'' and
``The Lesser Evil,'' both completed before he became involved with
``Moon,'' and will be heard as the voice of the title character in
Disney's ``Tarzan,'' due in June.
 &HT;    Still, Goldwyn's new love is getting most of his attention.
 &HT;    ``I love acting, but directing seems to be taking a front seat
right now,'' he says. ``It's so time-consuming that I haven't had
time to act in a movie in two years. Last year I did a play (``The
Dying Gaul''), but to devote the necessary time to `Moon' I had to
drop out of three movies I really wanted to do, including one with
Oliver Stone.''
 &HT;    Goldwyn plans to spend the summer at home in New Haven, Conn.,
with his wife, production designer Jane Musky, and their two young
daughters. Even there, however, he'll be working with the writers
of two studio films, family dramas that he hopes to direct.
 &HT;    He's come quite a ways from his yuppie-scum days in ``Ghost,'' a
film which he's now more comfortable with.
 &HT;    ``Because of `Moon,' I think I've escaped `Ghost' in at least
one way,'' he says. ``I'm less concerned about perceptions of me as
an actor.
 &HT;    ``Every day when I go down the street, people say, `Hey!
Ghost!''' he explains. ``As an actor, that was getting a little
claustrophobic and limiting.
 &HT;    ``I know I'm blessed to have something like that,'' he adds.
``Every actor wants to be recognized. But I'm more comfortable with
`Ghost' now that I've diversified what I do.''
 &HT;    Goldwyn smiles.
 &HT;    ``I'm in a whole new chapter, because I feel I've reinvented
myself,'' he says. ``Directing opens up my career. It's a
tremendously gratifying job _ I feel that I'm using a much fuller
part of myself, and have a chance to achieve my potential in a way
I don't think I ever would have as an actor.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``A Walk on the Moon,'' consult
the Miramax Films Website at www.miramax.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate. &QL; 
