<HEADER>
A6272 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ROCKET-BOS &LR;      04-05 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ROCKET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ROCKET BOY, WE HAVE A PROBLEM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It started with a Pringles &UR;  &LR; potato chip can. It ended with a kid
getting slapped down for trying to reach for the stars and for his
father's approval.
</P>
<P>
   Like the current movie ``October Sky'' and the best-selling book
on which it is based, ``Rocket Boys,'' this is a story about a
young boy who became fascinated with the idea of building his own
model rockets. And like the book and movie, it is also about a boy
and his father trying to get closer.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the real-life 1950s tale of Homer Hickam, the West
Virginia kid who overcame small-town prejudices and went on to a
career as a rocket scientist with NASA, this one seems to involve a
modern-day ``zero tolerance'' school policy run amok, and a child
being punished for what was little more than an attempt at
creativity and father-son communication.
</P>
<P>
   David Silverstein is 13, and was a seventh-grader at Desert Sky
Middle School in Glendale, Ariz., where his family just moved last
fall from Chicago. Several weeks ago, his parents saw ``October
Sky'' and David's father Edward Silverstein was deeply moved by it
_ and especially its portrayal of the conflict and resolution in
the relationship between Hickam and his father. He told his son
about the movie, and kept talking about it for the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The following Monday, David Silverstein decided to act on the
message. Never having experimented with rockets, he didn't know
that working model rocket kits can be bought easily at hobby
stores, so, like Hickam, he tried to build one from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   He used a potato-chip can for the rocket's body, attached some
Band-aids to the bottom (to light it with), and stuffed it with
some newspaper, three matches, and some model airplane paint for
fuel. He planned to try to launch the rocket from a vacant lot
after school, so he left it in his locker during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently on a tip from another student, the school's assistant
principal Robert Haley opened the locker and found the crude
missile _ which, according to rocket scientists including Hickam
himself, was a guaranteed fizzle. The rocket was taken to the
principal's office and disassembled. And then the police bomb squad
was called.
</P>
<P>
   David Silverstein was apologetic, admitting he made a dumb
mistake by bringing the device to school. But the school still
suspended him for 10 days. At a later school district hearing, that
suspension was extended to the remainder of the school year.
David's father, with help from a lawyer affiliated with the ACLU,
has filed for an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The school, according to local reports, said he was lucky: The
device, considered inflammable because of the paint inside, fell
under rules governing ``destructive devices, dangerous instruments,
simulated weapons, deadly weapons.'' But if they had invoked the
district's ``zero-tolerance'' program by classifying it as a
firearm, he would have been expelled.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Sky principal Janet Altersitz said: ``I'm not at liberty
to discuss it. I have to think of the privacy of the kid.'' But,
she suggested, ``there is a whole other side'' to the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``There always is,'' agreed Hickam, in an interview. ``But I
think they're missing the other side. This is not a rocket story,
this is a father-son story, and I think they could really help out
if they would just calm down.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Silverstein said that ``there have been a lot of
conflicting comments from the school.'' But the bottom line, he
said, is that David has never been in trouble, never had detention,
and even the assistant principal told him that when he first saw
who the rocket belonged to he was surprised that it was David.
</P>
<P>
   The police officers who handled the case said David was truthful
and cooperative, Silverstein said. ``He believes he just made an
error in judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the paint could have caught fire, Hickam said,
``but then, so could his schoolbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have pointed out that, contrary to the letter of the
school rules, other students bring matches and butane lighters to
school, so they can smoke cigarettes outside. None have been
suspended for this technical infraction, though the flammability
and explosive potential of a butane lighter is far greater than
that of the paint in the Pringles rocket.
</P>
<P>
   David told his father he misses school, even though some kids
his age might welcome the semester of home-schooling he will now
receive. And he wishes the attention would just go away (all the
local television stations, and a few national programs, have asked
for interviews, though so far his parents have declined all such
requests, cooperating only with local newspapers and the Globe.
They did not consent to having his photo taken).
</P>
<P>
   But not all the attention has been bad. Hickam called the boy,
saying that ``the least I could do was talk to the young man and
encourage him and buck him up a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   And then some space enthusiasts in Washington heard his story,
and decided to do even more. An organization called Space
Adventures will be sponsoring a July Fourth weekend program on
rocketry in the Washington area, culminating in the construction of
model rockets that will be launched from the grounds of the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Goddard Space
Flight Center. The Silversteins, father and son, have been invited
to attend, all expenses paid. They have accepted, though the father
says his son was initially reluctant, fearing the public attention.
</P>
<P>
   Space Adventures spokesman Robert Pearlman said that the group
felt it was important to encourage the boy's interest and not let
the school win out in stifling his efforts. After the initial
suspension, Pearlman said, David at first had told his father ``I'm
just not going to do it anymore, I'm going to give up.'' The action
of the school, Pearlman said, ``just sends the wrong message.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is a sad case of a missed opportunity, Hickam believes.
``I know they don't want to lose face, but this would be an
opportunity for some education to take place. They could have said
`let's have a rocket science class.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A nearby school, in fact, does have an amateur rocketry group
which builds model rockets, and, according to local newspaper
reports, even launches them from school grounds. Local enthusiasts
probably would have been willing to come out, Hickam suggested, to
``show them how to do safe rocketry.''
</P>
<P>
   Hickam thinks the bottom line is simple. ``Boys will be boys,
kids will be kids, and sometimes when you have inflexible rules you
just get inflexible results.'' In his own school days, he said,
``the principal would just jerk a knot in you if you did something
wrong. And then it was over.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, he suggested, ``everybody just needs to lighten
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
