<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6274 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PILOTS-BOS &LR;      04-05 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PILOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWED FROM JET COCKPITS, BOMBING STRATEGY IS FRUSTRATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVIANO AIR BASE, Italy _ As the sun set behind the foothills of
the Italian Alps, US fighter jets thundered off the tarmac here
Sunday for the 12th night of NATO airstrikes against Serbian
forces.
</P>
<P>
   But the men who sit in the cockpits of these sleek warplanes
streaking into the gathering darkness said they understand the
limits of the massive firepower they are unleashing around the
clock inside Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots of the US Air Force's famed 31st Fighter Wing seemed
frustrated that their hammering of Yugoslav Army positions has done
little to stop President Slobodan Milosevic's expulsion of ethnic
Albanians from the Serbian province of Kosovo. The pilots, along
with the support teams that surround them, seem convinced that NATO
will inevitably need to send in ground troops to stop Milosevic and
secure peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have to execute an air campaign effectively so as to
allow ground troops to go in, in a contained way. We have to limit
their risk on the ground. But I think ultimately they will have to
go in to enforce the peace on the ground. It's the only way,'' said
a US Air Force captain who pilots an F-15E of the 494th Fighter
Squadron. He spoke outside a concrete bunker housing the fighter
jets Sunday as they taxied for takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting over the roar of the engines, the 33-year-old captain,
who comes from Brooklyn and is known by his call name ``Chili,''
said it was ``very difficult'' to watch television images of tens
of thousands of refugees streaming out of Kosovo every day after
finishing a night of heavy bombing.
</P>
<P>
   But ``I don't let it get to me,'' he said. ``I can't. We have to
keep our pace, our focus, and our patience.'' (Air base officials
allowed pilots to be interviewed only on condition that their full
names not be published.)
</P>
<P>
   The same sentiments were echoed across the base Sunday, from
outside the chapel where Easter Sunday services were held to inside
the mess tent, where a holiday meal of baked ham and sweet potatoes
was served.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need ground troops. You can't do it from the air. History
proves that,'' said Senior Airman George Tharpe, 25, of the 555th
Fighter Squadron of the 31st Fighter Wing.
</P>
<P>
   The 31st has seen its history, fighting in crucial battles in
Europe and North Africa in World War II. It also saw intense action
during the 1968 Tet Offensive in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   A US Marine major and pilot of EA-6B attack jets, known as
``Prowlers,'' brings his history of fighting in the Persian Gulf
War. He agreed that air power without the use of ground troops
would ultimately be futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``To claim control, you have to use air and ground forces in
combination,'' he said, shoveling down dinner as pilots on ``alert
status,'' like himself, braced for another evening of airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old major, who goes by the call name ``Cookie,''
described the mission of his attack aircraft as ``taking the eyes
away from the enemy,'' knocking out radar installations and jamming
air waves to prevent antiaircraft guns from locking onto other NATO
jets.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Persian Gulf War, he said, there seems to be no
overall strategy in the Yugoslav conflict. ``We'd like to see an
endgame, and right now we don't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, citing Sun Tzu's ancient Chinese military strategy work
``The Art of War,'' a book which he said he keeps with him, he
added, ``You have to know what your mission is and what you want to
accomplish. If you don't, you will never succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   The airmen said it was difficult to see a seemingly endless
stream of refugees pouring out of Kosovo despite their bombing
raids. Sometimes, they said, it seemed that Milosevic was winning
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Oliveiro, 39, a superintendent of the services unit on the
base, said, ``There's a lot of frustration because the troops feel
they can't see the impact they're having. You know, you hear the
refugees calling for help and wonder what the mission you just flew
is doing to help them. That wears on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant Matthew Borg, 26, of the 31st Fighter Wing, agreed:
``You see the planes launching with one eye, and then you see CNN
showing the refugees continuing to be pushed out with the other. I
think it serves to intensify our focus on what we're doing, but it
definitely puts a strain on a personal level.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in northern Italy's lush green-brown patchwork of fields and
freshly plowed farmland, the sprawling base tries to provide ways
to deal with that strain.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of buildings called the ``morale center'' houses a
state-of-the-art workout facility and a bank of computers for
sending e-mail to loved ones, as well as phones that allow
servicemen and women to communicate easily with families back home.
One booth provides video teleconferencing so airmen and their
families can see each other.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the base has 2,000 personnel and 150 aircraft
stationed there. It is the size of a small American town, with a
nine-hole golf course, three baseball diamonds, a television news
station, two radio stations, and a daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   A tent city has been built to house the several hundred added
personnel who have come from other European bases to assist in the
operation. There, amid the smoke of barbecues grilling hot dogs and
the blaring sound of rap music, the troops Sunday were debating
their mission.
</P>
<P>
   At a ``hooch,'' or makeshift pub set up in one of the tents, a
group of airmen were drinking Miller High Life, eating pork rinks,
and voicing their opinions on the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone agrees you need ground troops, but I say, let
Europe handle it. This is their back yard. Why should we risk
American lives?'' asked a master sergeant from Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   But a staff sergeant from Tennessee replied, ``I think they
should just let us do it. We are the policemen of the world, and
that comes with risks. But the point is to stop playing the
political games and let us get our job done. Let us just do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1351EDT &QL; 
