<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSISTENCE AND PRUDENT FORCE CAN WORK IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- A solid line connects several fresh dots on the
smoldering Balkan landscape, including:
</P>
<P>
   --The apparent ``emptying'' of Kosovo's capital of Pristina and
other population centers of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   --The massing of huge numbers of refugees on the borders of
Macedonia and Albania, without food and shelter, due to the
inability of those countries to transport them further or otherwise
care for them.
</P>
<P>
   --The periodic shelling by Serb forces of Albanian territory.
</P>
<P>
   --The rapidly increasing pressure from Belgrade on the
autonomous (and reform-minded) province of Montenegro, including
the replacement of its occupying army command with at least eight
senior officers known to be stooges of Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   That solid line goes by the name of aggression. For years, Serb
violence and atrocities in Kosovo have been assumed prospectively
to be doubly awful _ not only for the immense suffering of the
Kosovars it would produce, but also for the spread of the disease
further into the volatile region that would follow.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as NATO's air campaign steadily if belatedly escalates, it
should be apparent how proper those assumptions were and why the
military response is imperative, for both moral and regional
security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   This is a punch that was telegraphed not merely in the context
of the past year's bestiality by Milosevic, but when his criminal
behavior began in earnest years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even as the West froze in the face of the initial wave
of mass murder in Croatia and Bosnia, President Bush drew the line
at Kosovo during his final month in office. In a letter to
Belgrade, he warned that violent suppression of Kosovo would
produce US air attacks on Serb forces doing the dirty work and on
Serbia itself. That was in December of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was significant. Milosevic had just been reelected in
a largely rigged procedure, defeating American businessman Milan
Panic, who was then serving as the Yugoslav premier but was ousted
shortly thereafter. The handwriting was on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Bush acted for a reason as valid today as then, except now we
can see it with our own eyes: Kosovo is the territory through which
chaos will spread south and west with catastrophic human and
security consequences; it cannot be isolated by isolationism.
</P>
<P>
   And the following year _ even as he began a three-year tussle
with allies and public opinion over the horror in Bosnia _
President Clinton reaffirmed the Bush pledge and helped arrange
through the United Nations for trip-wire troops to be placed in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   At the time and since then, Clinton has been both supported in
his response to Milosevic's aggression and vigorously urged to do
more by several prominent Republicans, even in the face of their
party's increasing isolationism. Bob Dole is the best-known, but I
recently ran across a 6-year-old essay by Senator Orrin Hatch in
which he has urged that forces also be pre-positioned in Kosovo.
His description of the Milosevic way is as chillingly accurate now
as it was then:
</P>
<P>
   ``Fight one war at a time. Destabilize neighbors by arming
nationalists among its Serbian minority. Back those guerrillas with
supplies and the forces of the former Yugoslav army and air force.
Exploit peace talks as a cover for ethnic cleansing and to ward off
any Western military response. Consent to a peace plan in order to
consolidate gains once key Serbian objectives have been achieved.
Having done this, Serbs move to the next target.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia is not Kosovo, but the fact since then has been that
persistence and the prudent use of force have made an enormous
difference. And will in the present circumstances. The NATO
campaign against Milosevic has barely begun. It is escalating daily
and spreading throughout Kosovo. Currently, the only real limits
are weather, not politics.
</P>
<P>
   With a bit of hindsight, it's clear from military and policy
officials that there were hopes that the Serbs might take a
symbolic airstrike or two and use them as political cover to
consent to last month's Rambouillet agreement. Those hopes
influenced the initial character of the strikes. It's also clear
that Clinton had tons of advance warning that Milosevic would not
stop his murderous campaign and might accelerate its pace, and that
initially airstrikes could not stop the horror on the ground. That
did not prevent unanimity here and within NATO to begin the
military response.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's miscalculation has been much more severe, namely
that NATO's and America's will to persevere could be broken. The
reverse is occurring, and Milosevic can no longer even count on a
continued taboo against the use of ground troops in combat against
him.
</P>
<P>
   For those who were listening carefully, Clinton said last Friday
only that there is a ``good possibility'' our objective can be met
with air power alone. And he pointedly noted that the air campaign
would be necessary either on its own or as prelude to the insertion
of troops.
</P>
<P>
   As Milosevic knows by now, the scheduled rotation of one of the
First Infantry Division's brigades from Germany to Kuwait was
halted last week.
</P>
<P>
   Democracies can be maddeningly slow to act, but it should be
increasingly clear that the response to the worst aggression in
Europe since the Nazis is not going to be perfunctory _ fittingly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
