<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SERB AT HEART,' BUT US NATIVE IS TORN BY WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REZEVICI, Yugoslavia _ Caught between Serbia and the US Sixth
Fleet, Marko Taylor, a genial 38-year-old builder from Baton Rouge,
La., may bebe one of the last ordinary Americans living in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As the bombs pound Belgrade and other areas, and anonymous Serb
nationalists telephone death threats against Taylor's family, he's
wondering if it just might be time to head for surroundings that
are more congenial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd expected to live my life here,'' he said sadly, standing
atop the nearly completed three-unit apartment building into which
he has poured all of his energy and most of his savings since
moving two years ago to this scenic village perched on a bluff high
above the Adriatic Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it looks like this place is set to become America's next
Vietnam, not the kind of place I'm comfortable keeping my family,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have been told to leave Yugoslavia by the US State
Department. Aside from a dozen of so journalists covering the
crisis from within Yugoslavia, diplomats believe Taylor may be
among the last American citizens stubbornly hanging on. That's a
precarious position, given the deepening anger at the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was born in Alabama and raised in Louisiana. But his
mother is Serbian, and he inherited a love of the language, the
culture, and the Orthodox Christian faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I'm a Serb at heart,'' said Taylor, who speaks with
a soft Southern drawl. ``But I suppose I could have picked a better
time to discover my roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, Taylor married a Serb woman _ Milena, 25, a
former fashion model from Belgrade. With their infant son,
Dimitrje, they settled in Rezevici in 1997, after Milena earned her
master's degree from the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just made a decision I didn't want my boy growing up in the
States. It's a culture so totally overwhelmed by mass marketing,
drugs, sex and violence,'' he said, adding with a laugh:
``Obviously, I'm come to just the right place to escape violence.
Talk about out of the frying pan . . .''
</P>
<P>
   He and Milena acquired a 300-year-old stone house that had been
damaged by an earthquake. They toiled 105 days to rebuild it into a
breezy, spacious home, with an apartment downstairs for his
parents, who joined him after his father retired from a veterinary
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Marko Taylor also cleared several acres below the house where he
planted potatoes, cabbage, peppers, onions, and cucumbers.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be no harvest. ``We've been getting phoned death
threats, the level of anti-American hatred just about doubles with
every smart missile slamming into a bridge or a power plant. I'd
chosen to live among these people, but I'm the enemy now,'' he
said. ``There's just too much risk for my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is a builder, not a politician, and follows the war only
on CNN and other news broadcasts he receives by satellite
television. He said he feels trapped in a war between the two
countries he loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take the American out of me, but neither can you
take the Serb,'' he said. ``It's a part of who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   He describes himself as profoundly disturbed by TV images of
ethnic Albanians made homeless by Serb paramilitary thugs, backed
by the military of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shock to see this being carried out in a country that
by any other measure is civilized. These are just horrific acts,''
he said. ``But I don't think the US fully understands what it's
getting into, and I can't help but feel there still might have been
some diplomatic solution.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he believes, Yugoslav civilians will suffer most
from the NATO air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hitting power plants, we're hitting fuel depots,'' he
said. ``Come winter, there's going to be a big dying here, and this
time, it will be Serbs who will be victims.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
