<HEADER>
A6279 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-BOS &LR;      04-05 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS PONDERS ITS PLACE IN KOSOVO CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator Richard G. Lugar says the United States is
in danger of ``losing the war in Kosovo.'' Senator Robert
Torricelli says the campaign is ``never likely to succeed.''
Senator Tim Hutchinson says the ``normal rallying around the
President during a military action never really happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite a growing congressional chorus of complaints about
US military efforts in Yugoslavia, the Capitol hallways are
virtually deserted. There are no congressional hearings on NATO
airstrikes. No debates on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are there calls for Congress to return from its two-week
recess for an emergency wartime session. And as elected officials
take to the airwaves to express their various concerns, shaking
their fists on television and in newspaper op-ed columns, their
absence here seems to reflect an increasing congressional identity
crisis when it comes to waging war.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1941 has Congress declared war, and never has Congress
invoked the War Powers Resolution of 1973, instituted to limit the
authority of the president following the quagmire in Vietnam. From
Korea to the conflict in Kosovo, in fact, Congress has never set
the course for military action by challenging the president,
despite numerous interventions abroad and countless hearings and
debates back home.
</P>
<P>
   While there are plenty who say that is the way it should be _
with the president and Congress presenting a united front during
wartime _ there are some who question whether elected officials
have washed their hands too much, abdicating responsibility if
something goes wrong in a foreign conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the complexity of the Balkan campaign, both houses of
Congress debated it for a total of 13 hours. Then, once airstrikes
were nearly under way, members of Congress passed a resolution to
support the NATO campaign, a resolution to endorse peacekeeping
troops, and a resolution saying they support the military. Then
they left for Easter break.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has done ``very little, and I don't understand it,''
said Representative Bill Goodling, a senior member of the House
Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president gets us involved. Then as a Congress, you have
to say, `Well, we now have to support our troops,' '' said
Goodling, a Republican from Pennsylvania, who plans to introduce
legislation to block any funding for US ground troops in Kosovo.
``It's tough to get ahead of his moves. That's what scares me
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The inherent wartime tension between Congress and the president
is as old as the nation, purposely written into the Constitution to
keep both branches in check. Congress is supposed to declare war;
the president, as commander in chief, is supposed to send troops
marching into battle.
</P>
<P>
   But the nature of modern-day conflicts has muddied the
definition of war, and the War Powers Resolution has done little to
bolster the role of Congress in controlling when and where US
troops engage in combat, members and analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1973 resolution, the president has 48 hours to notify
Congress after dispatching soldiers into a dangerous conflict.
Congress then has 60 days _ plus a possible 30 extra days if
demanded by the president _ to specifically authorize the use of
troops. Without that authorization, or an outright declaration of
war, US troops are supposed to be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, members of Congress and analysts said, withdrawals
never occur because the War Powers Resolution is never formally
triggered by the president or Congress. Congress _ wanting neither
to embarrass the president with what is essentially a veto, nor to
increase its own liability in case of a tragic outcome _ is left to
influence the process in less formal ways, such as public criticism
or private meetings with the military and administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same old story: You have a lot of them screaming
about how stupid it is, about what bad policy it is, but how in the
end they have to support the troops,'' said Gordon Silverstein,
author of ``Imbalance of Powers,'' an analysis of foreign policy
and the Constitution. ``In the end, if this is a total disaster,
Congress can say, `I told you so.' And if it's a great success,
they can say, `of course Congress was supportive of the troops.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There have been signs that the struggle for congressional
control is growing. Before the current recess, Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott introduced legislation that would have blocked
funding for troops in Yugoslavia _ a tack Congress has not taken
since 1993, when it cut off funding for the mission in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Representative Tom Campbell, a Republican from
California, wrote a letter to House Speaker Dennis Hastert
requesting a trigger of the War Powers Resolution.
</P>
<P>
   And throughout the break, congressional leaders have been in
contact with the administration. Republican Senator John W. Warner
of Virginia, chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, has
held twice-weekly briefings on Capitol Hill with military leaders.
Democratic Senator Christopher J. Dodd of Connecticut flew to
Brussels to meet with NATO officials. And Hutchinson, a Republican
from Arkansas, was pushing Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen to
allow legislators to visit the region.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of how much muscle Congress should flex will
probably not take center stage until both houses reconvene,
particularly as the push for US ground troops grows. When that
issue comes to the fore, said Campbell aide Suhail Khan, President
Clinton would be wise to ``invest members of Congress in the
decision, so that if and when we have bodybags, they go back to
individual districts . . . to explain it to constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If members just put up their hands and say, `I don't know, the
president is doing this,' '' he said, ``that doesn't make for good
policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
