<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6290 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CLOCK-BOS &LR;      04-05 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CLOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING FORWARD, THEN FALL ASLEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're feeling extra sleepy this morning, join the club.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling should be no surprise, according to several
specialists on sleep. The whole week after the change to daylight
saving time is a period when our internal clocks are so out of
whack, everything from body temperature, coordination, sensitivity
to light, and the ability to perform mundane tasks is affected.
</P>
<P>
   Just traveling in a car will be riskier than on a typical
morning _ a frightening thought.
</P>
<P>
   Research in England, Canada, California, and elsewhere has shown
a consistent pattern. During the week after clocks spring ahead,
the rate of traffic accidents increases. A study in Canada, for
example, showed a 7 percent increase in deaths from auto accidents
during the week after the time shift.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side comes in the fall, when the clocks are set back
and everybody gets an extra hour to sleep. Then, the research
shows, accident rates go down.
</P>
<P>
   The best strategy for coping? Well, consider the obvious: Take a
nap. Says Dr. Martin Moore-Ede, president of Circadian Technologies
in Cambridge, Mass., former professor at Harvard Medical School,
and author of ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to Getting a Good
Night's Sleep'': You don't want to go into the week
sleep-deprived.'' Ideally, going to bed up to an hour earlier than
usual should help start the week off right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that Americans now are sleeping at least one to two
hours too little,'' said James Maas, professor of psychology at
Cornell University and author of ``Power Sleep.'' When that chronic
shortfall is compounded by an additional hour of deprivation
because of the annual clock change, Maas said in an interview,
``mood is affected. People are more stressed and irrational.''
</P>
<P>
   Add that to a lowering of reaction times and coordination that
also typically result from insufficient sleep, and you have a
recipe for an unpleasant and risky morning commute this week, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem people will have waking up comes from the
sudden shift in lighting. Those who have welcomed being able to
wake in daylight for the last several weeks may suddenly find
themselves getting up in the dark again, and feeling drowsier as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Light is the main synchronizer of the body clock,'' explained
Dr. David Avery, associate professor of psychiatry and behavioral
science at the University of Washington School of Medicine and a
specialist on sleep. ``In the absence of light, our body clocks
tend to drift clockwise to later times.'' In other words, you're
going to feel sleepier later, and want to sleep longer.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that can help reset the internal clock, he said, is
exposing yourself to morning daylight. ``Outdoor light, even on a
cloudy day, is 10 times brighter than most indoor lighting,'' Avery
said. ``So try to get outside as soon as possible in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Many physiological changes accompany the daily rhythm of our
internal clocks, Avery said, including a cycle in body temperature
that reaches a minimum in the early morning hours, typically
between 3 and 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid disrupting that cycle, it is important not to sleep in
a room that is too warm, several specialists emphasized. Ideally,
the bedroom temperature at night should be cooler than normal
daytime room temperatures. ``It's important for the body to cool
down before going to sleep,'' said Avery.
</P>
<P>
   But the temperature cycle can get thrown off. ``In the winter,
many of us are at our temperature minimum at 6 a.m. It feels like
the middle of the night, and physiologically it is the middle of
the night. In the spring, that minimum gets pushed
counterclockwise, and we're able to wake up more refreshed,'' Avery
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the dreaded time change. ``With the change, all of a
sudden we're waking up in the dark again, and waking up closer to
our temperature minimum. It feels more like the middle of the
night. It's like a mini-jet lag, like we're flying one time zone
eastward.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is affected in the same way, of course. Some
people's natural daily cycle tends to be shorter than 24 hours, so
they have a tendency to drift toward earlier sleeping and waking
times. For them, the time shift may actually feel beneficial, Avery
said. The difference, he said, usually corresponds to whether
people think of themselves as ``morning people'' or ``night
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the majority, the adjustment to the time shift will
bring drowsiness, and people should plan accordingly. Moore-Ede
stressed that individual differences are great, and that to some
extent plans for adjusting should be tailored to the individual.
But there are some general guidelines that apply:
</P>
<P>
   --Take naps. A nap can help to prevent you from starting off the
day with an added sleep deficit. But don't sleep too long: 20
minutes is considered ideal; any longer than that will propel you
into deep sleep and you will tend to wake up groggy, and have a
harder time getting to sleep at night. And afternoon naps during
the week, if possible, will help maintain a rested state and keep
you more productive.
</P>
<P>
   --Go to bed early. Ideally, getting to sleep an hour earlier
than usual (according to clock time) will keep your body on its
normal cycle, and help you ease into the shifted time.
</P>
<P>
   --Lay off the nightcaps. Alcohol is known to interfere with
normal sleep cycles, so especially during a period of transition,
such as the change to daylight saving time or a trip to a different
time zone, it is important to go easy on the drinking.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the most important news: All these measures will not
only help you make it through this week, they could also help you
to live longer. ``Healthy sleep is the most important determinant
of lifespan,'' said Maas. A large-scale ``meta-analysis'' that
looked at thousands of separate medical studies found that getting
enough sleep is more important than diet, exercise, or any other
factor in increasing people's longevity, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
