<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENTLY REVIEWED MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``The Matrix'' Eye-popping special effects do battle with
a dumb, dense script. The technowizardry, which owes as much to
Japanese anime and Hong Kong action ballets as to the
morphmeisters, carries the film past the kind of story that, when
you unravel it, makes you say, ``This is it?'' Keanu Reeves is OK
as humanity's unwitting savior from super-intelligent machines.
Carrie-Anne Moss adds more than her share of black-leather-clad zap
as his acrobatic guide. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``The Out-of-Towners'' Frantic yet mostly tired remake of the
1970 Neil Simon farce about a couple from Ohio chewed up by big bad
New York until they learn to behave like New Yorkers and fight
back. Steve Martin and Goldie Hawn play the couple this time
around, in a film that never quite meshes her warmth and his
technique. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !!! 1/2 ``10 Things I Hate About You'' Surprisingly witty and
refreshing transfer of Shakespeare's ``The Taming of the Shrew'' to
an American high school. It works because there's no taming and no
shrew. Julie Stiles's Kate is a smart maverick with an icepick
tongue. Heath Ledger's cool loner Petruchio never tries to muscle
her, but wins her with sensitivity and a Gene Kelly dance routine.
(PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FL) !!! ``A Walk on the Moon'' Handsomely crafted directorial
debut by actor Tony Goldwyn, who delivers a well-acted period
piece, circa 1969. It revolves around the convergence of Woodstock,
the Apollo moonwalk, and Diane Lane's Jewish housewife and mother
on vacation in the Catskills, haunted by the thought that life may
be passing her by. She's susceptible to the low-key advances of
Viggo Mortensen's traveling man. Nice work, too, from Anna Paquin
as her teenage daughter embarking on her own summer of discovery.
(R)
</P>
</TEXT>
