<HEADER>
A6318 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-PRAYER-BOS &LR;      04-05 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PRAYER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHILLING NOVEL OF DEATH AND MYSTERY IN A MIDWESTERN HAMLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
A PRAYER FOR THE DYING 
By Stewart O'Nan. Henry Holt. 
195 pp. $22. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether in spite or because of his protean talents, Stewart
O'Nan has cheekily announced from time to time that he would rather
be known as a horror writer than as a literary one. This
provocative statement offers a sly salute to the scary guys he
reveres (Edgar Allan Poe, Stephen King), but it also suggests the
central position in O'Nan's fiction of his own version of the
uncertainty principle. The things we most believe in can turn on a
dime; war may be hell, but so are cruelty and betrayal and a
blighted conscience _ the wounds visited on a soldier and his
family in its aftermath. A sunny day in an O'Nan story is not to be
trusted: It could well be masking an apocalyptic fire, or offering
one last piece of beauty before the siege.
</P>
<P>
   The sum of these qualities (suspenseful timing, spooky ambience,
revelatory metaphor) has recently resulted in a little cross-genre
I'll call highbrow terror, enjoying a crest in publishing these
days with works such as Ian McEwan's ``Enduring Love'' and William
Trevor's ``Felicia's Journey.'' In ``A Prayer for the Dying,''
which feels intentionally elliptical, O'Nan takes his already noir
sensibility and turns it up a notch. He has created a spare,
ominous portrait of a small Wisconsin town in the years after the
Civil War, and the result is as subtle and insistent as an autumnal
twilight. But it's summer in the town of Friendship when the novel
opens: full of cool ponds and sweet voices of children and the play
of light upon the fields. Sublime, in other words, which must mean
something horrid has already made it across the county line.
</P>
<P>
   O'Nan credits Michael Lesy's cult classic ``Wisconsin Death
Trip'' with inspiring this story, which also owes a nod to Albert
Camus's ``The Plague'': As the young protagonist, Jacob Hansen,
makes his way through his daily rounds in Friendship as sheriff,
undertaker, and preacher, he runs into a series of unexplained
deaths. A tramp moving through town, a former soldier still
wandering six years after the war, is found dead in the woods. A
woman is delirious in a meadow, crying out for Jesus; in two days
she'll be dead. Jacob has to go out to the elderly Sullivan
sisters' place and shoot their mare, who is wild-eyed and foaming
at the mouth with blood. Intent upon giving hope to the living even
as he buries their dead, Jacob is also half the town's public
health department _ the other half is old Doc Guterson, who quickly
realizes that what he's seeing is an epidemic of diphtheria.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Prayer for the Dying'' covers two infinite weeks in that
terrible summer, when Jacob and Doc must decide if and how to
quarantine the town, tend to the terminally ill, isolate the
still-contagious bodies. Doc has already sent his wife out of town;
Jacob has instead tried to keep his beloved Marta and their new
daughter, Amelia, at home in isolation. Every new cough is a
terror; every new terror must be swallowed, lest it cause a panic.
The morning church bells tally up the losses by ringing out the
ages of the dead, who get younger with each passing day.
</P>
<P>
   And of course the bells will eventually toll for thee, which
brings us to a tricky problem with ``A Prayer for the Dying.'' The
novel is recited, with laconic gravitas, entirely in the second
person, that second person being Jacob. ``The two of you sit there
a minute in the cool room, pondering what this means to Friendship.
Your thoughts refuse to connect, run together like the cicadas
outside, screaming in the trees.'' Leaving aside the possibility
that Jay McInerney's ``Bright Lights, Big City'' may have tainted
forever the notion of writing an entire novel with the ubiquitous
``you,'' this is a deeply disconcerting point of view, at least
initially. I assume that its use here is meant to ensure a kind of
forced intimacy in the face of horror _ Jacob as Everyman, his
failings and fears and moral choices ones that You, too, Universal
Reader, might have made when those bells tolled for thee. It's
surprising to me that this device works even some of the time,
given that it's a fairly contrived effort to merge Jacob's
consciousness with ours. But the story at the heart of the novel
still manages to be stronger than this misconceived narrative
viewpoint, and one eventually reads past it to the saga of a town
in agony.
</P>
<P>
   What O'Nan does splendidly in ``A Prayer for the Dying'' is
flesh out his story with compelling historical accuracy without
ever showing his hand. The mortician's craft, the near-futile
efforts to quarantine a town, the ways in which the medical
paradigm of the 1870s dealt with an air-borne bacteria _ these are
elements central to Friendship's tragedy and yet they appear with
seamless delicacy. Much of what Jacob knows and loves about his
life and community will be challenged or destroyed, and the ways he
chooses to meet this adversary _ his tools of faith and
pathological denial and perseverance _ will form the moral core of
this awful, elegiac story. ``Crazy Jacob the Undertaker,'' the town
boys call him, and while some of that scorn is leveled at any man
who takes care of the dead, it also speaks to Jacob's
eccentricities: his talking gently to the bodies he prepares for
burial, his praying to a God he's only half-heartedly sure of, his
own private troubles he brought home from the war. Those hardships,
while instructive, were scant protection from the enemies he fights
now: an epidemic, a wildfire to the north, a town panicking under
the threat of both.
</P>
<P>
   A minor caveat: It's best to read this brief and gripping novel
without knowing too much about it first, because much of its power
derives from the ink stain of unknown terror at its margins. O'Nan
indulges in a few moments of Revelations overkill _ a fire in the
lake, a flock of sparrows plunging from the sky _ but he largely
allows understatement to be his chilling guide. The terse,
hand-painted signs that Jacob posts outside of Friendship read,
simply, ``Town Sick.'' That's plenty frightening enough, and it
doesn't need a metaphor to drive home the message.
</P>
<P>
   After fear comes its leaden reality, of course, and if Jacob has
learned anything in his brief years upon this earth, ``it's that
hope is easier to get rid of than sorrow.'' ``A Prayer for the
Dying'' is heavy with that grim truth, even as it delivers to us a
man who, through madness and the halls of grief, tried to do the
best he could.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is the chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
