<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6323 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-HEMINGWAY-2TAK     04-05 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HEMINGWAY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT HOLLYWOOD LEARNED AT PAPA'S KNEE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You ought to go to the movies more,'' a character says in
Ernest Hemingway's short story ``The Killers.'' ``The movies are
fine for a bright boy like you.''
</P>
<P>
   In this, his centenary year, Hemingway shines as a very bright
boy, indeed. On July 21, his 100th birthday, Scribner will release
a previously unpublished novel, ``True at First Light.'' The rights
to it went for a reported $1 million. Next Saturday and Sunday, the
Kennedy Library, which is the repository of Hemingway's papers,
will observe his centennial with a two-day conference boasting a
starry array of participants that includes four Nobel laureates and
seven Pulitzer Prize winners.
</P>
<P>
   As a prelude to the conference, on Thursday, playwright and
screenwriter David Mamet will introduce a Hemingway double feature
_ ``To Have and Have Not'' and the 1946 version of ``The Killers''
_ at the Brattle Theatre in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   For Hemingway, the movies were and were not fine. He happily
accepted the large sums Hollywood offered for screen rights. Yet
beyond what the movies might do for his bankroll, he disdained
them. He never thought much of film as an art form _ or at least
not American film _ and, unlike such contemporaries as William
Faulkner and F. Scott Fitzgerald, he resisted all efforts to lure
him to write for the studios. ``No, I'm top where I am,'' he told
his friend Howard Hawks, the director of ``To Have and Have Not.''
``I don't want to go out to Hollywood. I don't like it. And I
wouldn't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Those last two statements are somewhat suspect. Hemingway liked
Hollywood well enough to befriend not just Hawks but also Gary
Cooper, Ava Gardner, Ingrid Bergman, and Marlene Dietrich. Nor, as
such associations suggest, was he averse to Hollywood's favorite
religion, the cult of celebrity. A larger-than-life image was
something he carefully cultivated and just as carefully traded on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hemingway is himself a star,'' David O. Selznick, the producer
of ``Gone With the Wind'' once remarked. ``He has box-office.''
</P>
<P>
   He belongs alongside those men (and, appropriately enough in a
place that felt so attuned to Hemingway, men they all are) whose
artistic influence continues to shape American film. D. W. Griffith
invented the grammar and syntax movies still use three-quarters of
a century later. Hawks, John Ford, and Alfred Hitchcock showed
Hollywood its true calling, the exploration of genre. Elia Kazan,
as director, and Marlon Brando, as demiurge, put in place the
template for screen acting that remains dominant today. And
Hemingway did something nearly as important: He put into literary
practice and legitimized the way American movies present the world.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Great Train Robbery'' to ``The Thin Red Line,''
American film has had a single defining principle: Action is
character. The first person to put that principle on the page, to
validate it and demonstrate the extent of its artistic
possibilities, was Hemingway. Other writers of literary merit _
Robert Louis Stevenson, Joseph Conrad, Jack London, Rudyard Kipling
_ had written stories predicated on adventure and set in exotic
locales. Not surprisingly, screen adaptations of the work of all
four have been plentiful. It was Hemingway, though, who updated
Descartes's ``I think, therefore I am'' into the far more filmable
``I do, therefore I am.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Action as character
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He made the relation between character and action axiomatic and
seamless. The author who in ``A Farewell to Arms'' assailed
abstractions (``Abstract words such as glory, honor, courage, or
hallow were obscene'') or who in ``Death in the Afternoon'' and
``Green Hills of Africa'' made action, in the form of fighting a
bull or hunting big game, seem a sacerdotal rite _ this was an
author Hollywood could, and did, thrill to. Other writers of the
time were trying to imitate the movies. The most obvious example is
John Dos Passos in his ``U.S.A.'' trilogy. Hemingway was doing
something different. He was moving in parallel to them and, in so
doing, helped enlarge them.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that his novels and stories provided Hollywood
with such good material (see accompanying story). It was, rather, a
question of attitude toward the portrayal of subject: the belief
that externalities mattered and carried meanings intrinsic as well
as extrinsic. It is a commonplace that Hemingway worshiped
technique. In his fiction, how things get done is as important as
what gets done, or why they they get done, or even who does them.
Far more than, say, gun or war or sex _ each of which Hemingway
also provides _ how is the motion picture camera's favorite
three-letter word.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Hollywood, the argument can be made that motion
pictures helped shape Hemingway, too. Even if he largely disdained
movies in later years, he hadn't always felt that way. He told The
New Yorker's Lillian Ross that as a boy he'd gone with his
grandfather to see Griffith's ``The Birth of a Nation'' no fewer
than 30 times.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that very fact indicates how limited was the movies' effect
on Hemingway. The style of silent films was so revolutionary _ with
its close-ups and fades, zooms and montages _ that one can easily
overlook how hopelessly anachronistic its substance tended to be.
Nowhere is the disparity clearer than in Griffith's work, where the
formal properties of narrative are so innovative and the narrative
content itself so reactionary.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway's art, the critic Hugh Kenner has written, ``was the
art of avoiding subtitles,'' and the arrival of sound coincided
with the arrival of his work in Hollywood (Hemingway first came to
the screen, via an adaptation of ``A Farewell to Arms,'' in 1932).
Sound toughened the movies and also particularized them. Melodrama
and slapstick, the two great modes of silent film, ``speak'' a
universal language. Talkies made the movies idiomatic. British film
became clipped, German film guttural, American film at once urgent
and laconic. In Hollywood, modern, muscular speech _ the gab and
palaver of precinct house and newsroom, of nightclub and union hall
_ replaced the mannered fustian of Victorian theater that had
provided silent film's language of feeling as well as the diction
for intertitles. Sound placed the movies firmly in the 20th
century, and few American writers of the late '20s seemed as up to
the minute as the author of ``In Our Time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
