<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6326 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-HEMINGWAY-2ND &LR;      04-05 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HEMINGWAY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... Our Time.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hawks said he learned about dialogue on the screen from reading
Hemingway. That is no small praise coming from the man who directed
such wonders of the spoken word as ``Bringing Up Baby,'' ``His Girl
Friday,'' and ``The Big Sleep.'' The lessons Hemingway had to teach
Hawks and his fellow filmmakers derived from his singular ability
to combine simplicity, indirection, and the appearance of realism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The art of indirection
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His self-proclaimed goal was le mot juste, the exact right word,
a phrase he took from Flaubert. The most obvious consequence of
such a search was that the resulting prose must needs be stripped
down and precise. This was just what movie people sought in their
own medium: the smallest number of words for the most amount of
action. More than that, though, Hemingway's own dialogue excelled
at indirection, in which a great deal might be said even as very
little is actually spoken. ``Three-cushion'' dialogue Hawks called
it: ``Because you hit over here and over here and go over here to
get the meaning. You don't state it right out.'' That very
waywardness gives dialogue an extra layer of verisimilitude.
Conversations are not equations, after all. But it must remain a
calculated waywardness if dialogue isn't to fall into mere
talkiness.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Hemingway's dialogue is all that realistic. It's
no more realistic than his famously stylized exposition. The point
is that it should seem so natural, and therein lies much of its
genius. So, too, with movie dialogue, which needs to be every bit
as artificial while never seeming at all stagy. The trick is to
keep the artifice from calling attention to itself. This Hemingway
did, and did mesmerizingly, through his offhand rhythms and simply
constructed sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The classic Hemingway hero is a man of feeling concealed within
a man of action: hard and inexpressive on the outside, sensitive or
even wounded within. He fights wars, hunts and fishes, drinks too
much, and (always) goes his own way. Yet he is also usually
introspective, cosmopolitan, worldly-wise.
</P>
<P>
   The Hemingway type provided a model for Hollywood to seize upon
in the creation of its own favorite hero: the tight-lipped
idealist, the hard-headed dreamer, the tough guy nursing a broken
heart. The highest expression of this type was Humphrey Bogart
during the '40s and '50s. Unlike that other great Hollywood type,
the John Wayne hero, who failed to express emotion for the simple
reason he didn't really feel any, the Bogart hero felt emotion, and
felt it deeply, but he held it in almost-constant check. The nature
of the Wayne figure's heroism lay in how many men he might kill in
the course of two hours. The truest measure of the Bogart figure's
heroism was his ability to function, and do so with seeming ease or
even bravado, despite the turmoil he contained within himself. His
every on-screen minute was a demonstration of the Hemingway ideal
of grace under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Could the Bogart persona have come into existence if Hemingway
hadn't been providing prototypes for it throughout the '20s and
'30s? (In a nice instance of life imitating art imitating art,
Hemingway was a great admirer of the actor.) Rick Blaine, in
``Casablanca,'' can be seen as the ultimate Hemingway hero. Like
Nick Adams, of the early short stories, he's rootless. Like Jake
Barnes, in ``The Sun Also Rises,'' he's lived in Paris and must
share the woman he loves. Like Frederic Henry, in ``A Farewell to
Arms,'' he scorns authority (and his friendship with the cynical
Major Rinaldi recalls Rick's with the cynical Captain Renault).
Like Harry Morgan, in ``To Have and Have Not,'' he's smuggled guns.
Like Robert Jordan, in ``For Whom the Bell Tolls,'' he's an
anti-Fascist who fought in Spain. Like all those characters, he's
no stranger to violence and is most comfortable, if also least
happy, in a society of men without women.
</P>
<P>
   If Kazan and Brando created the template for American movie
acting, then Bogart created the most distinctive template for
American male movie stardom, a masculine ideal that continues both
to inspire and haunt us. Think of Harrison Ford, Gene Hackman, Nick
Nolte, Mel Gibson (in his more sober roles), the Tom Hanks of
``Apollo 13'' and ``Saving Private Ryan.'' They are Rick Blaine's
grandchildren _ and the great-granchildren of Robert Jordan,
Frederic Henry, Nick Adams. All of them can, with every
justification, call Ernest Hemingway ``Papa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6328 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-GEORGES-ART-2TAKE     04-05 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GEORGES-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCALLOPERS, ENVIRONMENTALISTS AT ODDS OVER GEORGES BANK 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRHAVEN, Mass. _ It was one of the most drastic steps ever
taken to protect fish: 5,000 square miles of the open sea off New
England, including portions of legendary Georges Bank, were
declared off-limits to fishermen after they had nearly wiped out
the cod and other fish that live on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Almost five years later, the fish have started to recover, but
one species has prospered more than the others in the park-like
serenity of the closed areas. Scallops, New England's second most
valuable seafood, have grown so fat and plentiful that some
scallopers risk Coast Guard seizure of their boats to fish in the
forbidden waters.
</P>
<P>
   Now, under heavy political pressure from the scallop industry,
fishing regulators are considering letting them back in to the
closed fishing grounds, launching an intense debate about where the
term goals of conservation must yield to the needs of hard-pressed
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every judgment they make is on the side of the fish, the
scallops, which is fine, but we never get a break,'' said Herman
Bruce, owner of the scallop boat Florence, tied up at Fairhaven's
Hathaway Wharf. ``Our frustration is that these stocks are rebuilt
and we should be in there.''
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists and some fishermen fear that the hard won
gains from the 1994 crackdown could unravel if scallopers fish
heavily in closed areas. The weighted metal dredges dragged behind
scallop boats catch not only scallops, but everything in their
path.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific concern is also growing about scalloping's impact on
marine life that has no commercial value but contribute to the
ecology, such as sponges or the homely barndoor skate, which were
driven to near-extinction because it is inadvertently caught in
fishermen's nets.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, critics of the reopening plan say it would set a bad
precedent by rewarding political pressure. The frustrated
scallopers hired a prominent Washington lawyer as well as former US
Representative Gerry Studds to plead their case, and appealed
directly to US Commerce Secretary William Daley, who oversees
fishery management, to consider reopening some scallop grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington politics is a poor substitute for hands-on
science,'' warned Robert H. Russell and Jennifer Atkinson of the
Boston-based environmental group, Conservation Law Foundation, in a
recent letter to the Gloucester Daily Times. ``It seriously
undermines a regional . . . system that is addressing, albeit
slowly, the tragedy of overfishing.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the push to reopen Georges Bank also reflects the pain
of solving an overfishing crisis when fishermen are so reluctant to
leave their boats. Despite hard times, New England's scallop fleet
has held steady at around 300 boats even though federal biologists
say 100 or fewer are needed, making them increasingly desperate for
a larger catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've been in this business a while, you're locked in,''
explained James Kendall of the regulatory New England Fishery
Management Council. ``It's a way of life. It's not just a
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of Georges Bank, an underwater plateau whose
abundance had sustained fishermen for four centuries, showed what
can happen when modern fishermen, equipped with vast nets and
high-tech fish-finding equipment, aren't restrained. By 1994, the
National Marine Fisheries Service warned that cod, a staple of the
region's economy, had reached record low levels, and could only be
saved by reducing fishing to near zero.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Fishery Management Council closed three fishing
grounds, including two on Georges Bank, in one of the largest
closures for fish conservation in the world. Since then, the cod
catch on Georges Bank has dropped to levels not seen since the 19th
century, representing a loss of perhaps $90 million a year compared
to the big catches of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, sea scallops weren't part of regulators' worries on
Georges Bank, largely because they were more plentiful in other
areas. But regulators banned them from the closed areas anyway,
because the chain link sledges used in scalloping catch so many
groundfish as a byproduct, called ``bycatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the scallopers, concentrated in the New Bedford-Fairhaven
area, blame fishing restrictions for hard times that have seen the
New England catch fall from 20 million pounds or more each year in
the early 1990s, to less than nine million pounds in 1997. Scallops
in the closed areas alone could offset half the drop, according to
a National Marine Fisheries Service estimate, with scallops valued
at $21.9 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Though the waterfront looks prosperous enough _ the sky above
Hathaway Wharf bristles with masts and booms from scallop boats
tied up three and four abreast _ appearances are deceiving.
Fishermen say that lenient creditors have allowed them to stay in
business, awaiting better times ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't know the resource was there, we would have thrown
in the towel already,'' said Malvin Kvilhaug, owner of three
Fairhaven-based scallop boats.
</P>
<P>
   But the hard times are far from over for scallopers, who could
see the number of days they are allowed to fish reduced from 120
this year to just 50 days in 2000. Biologists at the National
Marine Fisheries Service believe the scallop fleet needs to reduce
fishing by more than 50 percent to prevent scallops from facing the
same fate as the cod.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been a boom and bust fishery . . . They pounce
on'' scallops before they are full grown ``and they catch very
small scallops. They really fritter away the longterm benefits of
stability,'' said Steven Murawski, a biologist at the National
Marine Fisheries Service in Woods Hole.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6331 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-GEORGES-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     04-05 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GEORGES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 FAIRHAVEN, Mass.: ... Woods Hole.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In addition to fishing limits, the Clinton administration wants
to eliminate boats, using $8 million in federal money and $32
million from industry to buy out scores of scallopers.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the tightening regulatory noose, scallopers turned
political last year, forming the Fisheries Survival Fund advocacy
group, hiring lobbyists, making their own video _ and petitioning
Commerce Secretary Daley to reopen part of the Georges Bank closed
area on an emergency basis.
</P>
<P>
   For scientific heft, they turned to Brian Rothschild, a
respected former federal fisheries biologist who now runs the
University of Massachusetts' Center for Marine Science and
Technology in New Bedford. Rothschild worked out a plan with the
National Marine Fisheries Service that would allow scallopers to
dredge closed area 2 to find out how many scallops were there.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen were astonished at what they found, taking pictures of
each other sprawled on mounds of big scallops. Though scientists
are still debating the exact amount of scallops in closed area 2,
staff at the New England Fishery Management Council estimate that
scallopers would catch scallops eight times as fast in the closed
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could sustain next year's whole (scallop) catch in area 2.
That's a big catch,'' said Rothschild.
</P>
<P>
   Although Daley declined to reopen closed areas himself, he
called on the New England Fishery Management Council to consider
reopening part of closed area 2 by June. He also called for federal
biologists to study scallop abundance in the other two closed areas
with an eye to additional openings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is welcome news for hundreds of fishing families. Their
economic survival depends on access to these closed areas,'' said
Senator Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts, who took Daley to Fall
River in February to talk to scallopers.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of Daley's intervention said it politicized the
already-difficult task of balancing conservation and the economic
needs of fishermen. At a minimum, they said, it forces the New
England Fishery Management Council to make complex decisions with
limited information under intense time pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Paul Howard, executive director of the New England
Fishery Management Council, said his staff is rushing to provide
information on five key issues before the council is scheduled to
vote on reopening closed areas to scallopers at its April 14
meeting in Providence:
</P>
<P>
   --For every pound of scallop meat harvested in the closed area 2
experiment, dredges pulled up two pounds of fish such as yellowtail
flounder, whose plight was one of the reasons the area was closed
in the first place. This bycatch can be limited by keeping
scallopers out of the richest flounder areas, but scientists are
unsure if it could slow the flounder's recovery.
</P>
<P>
   --The effect on scallops from opening area 2 is also unclear. It
could actually help scallop stocks if fishermen concentrate on the
closed areas and allow depleted scallop beds to recover. However,
dozens of inactive scallopers could be tempted by the reopening to
go fishing again, increasing overall scalloping.
</P>
<P>
   --Scientists also don't know enough about life on the seabed to
say what effect more scalloping will have. The recovery of scallops
in the closed areas shows that they can recover, but there are few
studies on the recovery of non-commercial plants and animals or the
effect of dredging on fish spawning areas.
</P>
<P>
   --Re-opening a closed area to scallopers _ but not ground
fishermen _ will be an enforcement headache in part because the
boats look somewhat alike. Howard said that already-inadequate
enforcement efforts would have to be increased.
</P>
<P>
   --Finally, scallopers will have to work around the lobster
fishermen who started placing their traps in closed areas once the
dragging equipment was gone. Otherwise, lobstermen and scallopers
could get into a heated gear conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make one decision without looking at all the other
decisions,'' said Howard. ``It's very complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the 17-member council could devise a complicated
re-opening scheme that attempts to balance these concerns, limiting
where the scallopers can go in the closed areas and reducing the
total number of days they can fish in exchange for access to the
rich closed areas.
</P>
<P>
   However, council member and former scalloper Kendall said that
limiting scallopers' fishing rights erodes the whole point of
giving them access to the closed areas: to catch more scallops.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Doug Hopkins, a council member and a lawyer
for the Environmental Defense Fund, said unrestricted access to the
closed area would be even worse, undercutting the broader agenda of
control. At the same meeting where the scallopers' appeal will be
heard, he notes, the council is considering another 22 percent cut
in Georges Bank cod fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Hopkins added, the scallopers may have undercut
their own cause by pressing for the emergency reopening. He said
the council was studying a plan to rotate scallop fishing grounds,
opening closed areas in exchange for closures of others. But the
rotation plan has been eclipsed by the pressure to open up Georges
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's heartbreaking in all this,'' Hopkins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
