<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6335 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARRAKHAN-ISLAM-BOS &LR;      04-05 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARRAKHAN-ISLAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARRAKHAN'S ILLNESS TESTS NATION OF ISLAM PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Louis Farrakhan's health again in question, the Nation of
Islam is being forced to confront the possibility of carrying on
without the charismatic leader who built the organization into a
powerful voice of black pride and alienation.
</P>
<P>
   This is an unsettling prospect, observers say, because there is
no one waiting in the wings who commands anywhere near the respect
and loyalty that Farrakhan does. Nor is there anyone with the kind
of personality to ensure the Nation of Islam retains its high
public profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minister Farrakhan is the Nation of Islam,'' said Arthur J.
Magida, author of ``Prophet of Rage: A Life of Louis Farrakhan and
His Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation relies on his charisma, which is extraordinary, his
organizational skills, and his image as perhaps the most courageous
and defiant black man in the United States,'' Magida said.
``Without him, I believe the Nation might have great problems
recruiting new members or maintaining itself as it is now
structured.''
</P>
<P>
   But some observers also said the Nation of Islam's next leader
probably would not invite controversy the same way Farrakhan does
by targeting Jews and whites. Farrakhan lost the support of many
blacks who might otherwise have found the Nation's message
attractive because of the group's anti-Semitic and racist
statements, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Press reports have presented conflicting pictures of the health
of the 65-year-old Farrakhan. Newsday reported Saturday that his
immune system has shut down in reaction to his treatment for
prostate cancer, which he has been battling for several years, and
that he was in serious condition. But his son-in-law, Leonard
Muhammad, told the Associated Press on Saturday that Farrakhan was
walking around and probably would be out of the hospital in a few
days.
</P>
<P>
   Two men who visited Farrakhan in the hospital, former Washington
mayor Marion Barry and the Rev. Jesse Jackson, also have said
Farrakhan is not gravely ill.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Nation of Islam leaders are said to be ``shaken and
concerned'' over Farrakhan's health problems, according to an
official who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, Farrakhan has dominated the Nation of Islam, using
it as a platform to promote his controversial brand of black
nationalism, discipline, and faith.
</P>
<P>
   To many of his followers, Farrakhan is the only truly authentic
African-American voice in America. Even among blacks who say some
of his statements are anti-Semitic and racist, Farrakhan is admired
for organizing the most significant event for blacks in recent
history: the Million Man March in Washington in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farrakhan has really taken the Nation to the highest levels of
attention one could possibly imagine for such an organization,''
said Sulayman S. Nyang, professor of African and Islamic Studies at
Howard University in Washington. ``No one can be sure what will
happen after him.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan has not established a clear hierarchy of succession,
some observers said, and his absence could trigger a power struggle
between moderates who want to move the organization toward
mainstream Islam and hardliners who brook no dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have emerged as potential successors are
Mustapha Farrakhan, the leader's son, who oversees the Fruit of
Islam, the Nation's security force; Dr. Abdul Alim Muhammad, one of
Farrakhan's personal physicians and a trusted adviser; and Benjamin
F. Muhammad, the former Benjamin Chavis, who was forced to resign
from the NAACP for improper use of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin F. Muhammad, who leads the Nation of Islam in New York,
is viewed with suspicion by some Farrakhan followers because they
believe he wants the organization to hew to a more orthodox brand
of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much saw the minister's decision to bring Benjamin
Chavis into the Nation as a way of making sure that if or when he
passes from the scene, there could be a group of people who are in
a position to be in leadership,'' said Ronald Walters, director of
the African-American Leadership Program at the University of
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it will be difficult for the Nation of Islam to emerge
from the shadow of the man who revived the organization after it
had been disbanded in 1975 by Imam Warith Deen Mohammad, the son of
the Elijah Muhammad, who had led the Nation since the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with 5,000 members in 1979, the Nation of Islam now
says it has as many as 200,000 members. It has mosques in most
major US cities, including Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Walters is more sanguine than others about the group's future
because he believes Farrakhan has built a strong infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's finances are healthy. Its holdings include a
restaurant in Chicago; a popular newspaper, The Final Call; and a
thriving network of local organizations across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Minister Farrakhan is not there, I don't think the Nation
is any danger of immediate collapse,'' Walters said.
</P>
<P>
   But his replacement might have a hard time matching Farrakhan's
blending of religion, politics, and culture to create a unique
world view, observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Most mainstream Muslims say the Nation of Islam bears almost no
resemblance to the orthodox Islam practiced by hundreds of millions
of adherents around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The nation believes that Allah, or God, was incarnated in 1930
in Detroit as Fard Muhammad, the founder of the organization, that
whites were created by a disloyal black scientist, and that the
biblical Adam was black.
</P>
<P>
   Observers said there are signs that Farrakhan is trying to make
the Nation of Islam more mainstream in an effort, perhaps, to
broaden its appeal and ensure a prosperous future. For the first
time, the group followed the same fasting calendar as Muslims
worldwide during the last Ramadan, the month-long Islamic holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Muslim calendar is tied to the lunar calendar,
Ramadan begins on a different day each year. But Elijah Muhammad
told his followers to fast in December because the shorter winter
days would make the dawn-to-dusk Ramadan fasts easier.
</P>
<P>
   Also, at a meeting of Nation of Islamic leaders this year,
Farrakhan, according to Magida, said the only texts now valid for
his followers were the Koran and the collected accounts of the
prophet Muhammad's words and deeds.
</P>
<P>
   It's still unclear, however, if this means Farrakhan is
supplanting or changing the beliefs he inherited from Elijah
Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nation of Islam is certainly in for some interesting and
challenging times,'' Nyang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
