<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENT-GENERATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROMISE TO THE NEXT GENERATION OF LATINOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speeding down the sidewalk, my skateboard hit a rock and I fell
down, smack in front of another child walking home from school. Her
hair in cornrows, the girl looked up at me and asked innocently,
``What are you, Spanish?''
</P>
<P>
   I stood there, a girl of 10, in my J. J. Walker ``Kid
Dy-no-mite'' T-shirt, and with shrugged shoulders said, ``I guess
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then, in between games of double-Dutch and
ring-o-livio, I wondered who I was, what I was. Growing up during
the ``Black is Beautiful'' '70s, my black girlfriends, Tina,
Valerie, Karen, could see their culture displayed _ even if often
negatively _ on movie screens, TV, and on the radio. But rarely did
I see mine.
</P>
<P>
   Though Latino _ mostly Puerto Rican _ culture percolated
throughout my Harlem neighborhood, it felt like it belonged to the
people of my mother's generation. The mothers on my block played
scratched 33 rpm vinyl recordings of merengue and salsa music.
Outside, Latina mothers would trade ``bochinche'' (gossip) in
Spanish, as their ninas and ninos spoke slang.
</P>
<P>
   At home, the tension between the culture my mom was trying to
instill, and culture I had adopted, created a perpetual tug-of-war.
Mom insisted her three children speak Spanish but we protested. Our
world rolled in English. But I admired our values: religious faith,
a strong work ethic, humility, and most of all, warmth. There is no
English equivalent for a carinoso person. You need several words _
loving, giving, nurturing _ to get at its nuances.
</P>
<P>
   Our culture evolved over thousands of years. It was shaped by
the industrious Incas, Mayans, Aztecs, Tainos, Arawaks, and Caribs;
Spanish colonizers who forced Roman Catholicism and the Spanish
language; and West African slaves whose art, music, cuisine, and
spirituality melded with ours. That mix makes us a people of many
hues, from dark-skinned Latin brothers like Sammy Sosa, to
light-skinned ``mamis'' like Cameron Diaz. Latinos, as a people,
understand diversity in a way that most ethnic groups can't.
</P>
<P>
   But as a kid, a first-generation child of a Puerto Rican mother
and Cuban father, the beauty of the culture escaped me. If it
wasn't on TV, children of my generation figured, it was irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   America's fascination with the mambo, with Desi Arnaz, Ricardo
Montalban, and Charo had long fizzled. Freddie Prinze was dead.
America just wasn't feeling us. Because I didn't see Latinos
reflected in pop culture, I subconsciously assumed we were
irrelevant. For most of America, there were only two ethnicities:
black and white. In East Coast cities with growing Latino
populations, we got branded as ``Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   As children we struggled with the label, with trying to fit with
those around us, while our mothers nagged, ``Necesita practicar el
espanol'' (You need to practice Spanish). We responded, ``All
right, moms.'' So we'd speak Spanish at home, not on the basketball
court. We blasted The Ohio Players, Stevie Wonder, and P-Funk on
our radios, not Celia Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   And when emceeing was born in the South Bronx housing projects,
Latinos rapped along. We rebelliously drowned out our parents' Tito
Puente with Grandmaster Flash, Roxanne Shante, and Doug E. Fresh.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until college, when I started taking Latin American
studies, that I began to truly understand the forces that shaped
Latino culture. From the Dominican Republic to Mexico to Colombia
and all countries in between, Latinos have lived a life of constant
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   From that struggle, incredible literature, poetry, and artwork
was born. If poverty and oppression gave us nothing else, it
fostered creativity and the innate sense to nurture what's most
important: family.
</P>
<P>
   Though we as a group remain a silent minority in America, we're
growing quickly. In a generation, we'll be the largest minority
group in a generation. And it's not because we're sneaking across
the border. Our population boom is due mostly to our love of kids.
We don't ascribe to the 2.5-children household that has become
almost a standard.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, as advertisers, casting directors, record executives,
and all the other controllers of American populart culture tap into
Latino culture with greater frequency, children from all other
ethnic groups will be eyeing our style, and will try to emulate us.
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit, I can't wait. I'll be a mom by then, and my
children won't have to think twice about who they are. By then,
Latino culture will be reflected everywhere, enriching American
culture with our voices, our spirit _ and with mucho carino.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Cindy Rodriguez is a member of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
