<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE, HORROR, AND MERCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO -- In an age when many a novel needs to be
carried by wheelbarrow, the book has a dozen chapters and 218
pages. The prose is spare, and even in translation its effect is
hypnotic. Readers follow the plot in an almost syncopated gait as
the hero wanders from Blumenstrasse to Bahnhofstrasse and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reader'' is now a publishing phenomenon in paperback,
thanks in part to Oprah Winfrey's book club, but thanks also to
Carol Brown Janeway, who translated the novel from German in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   I read the book last year, trying to escape from Bill Clinton's
troubles. But any story based on temptation and betrayal has
Clintonesque lessons. Or maybe not. ``Going there might be
dangerous. But it was obviously impossible for the danger to act
itself out,'' the narrator says. ``That is how I rationalized it
back then, making my desire an entry in a strange moral accounting
and silencing my bad conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Because ``The Reader'' begins when the narrator is an
adolescent, readers might fear garrulous anxiety. But things
happen, and the plot moves swiftly, with apt introspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does everyone feel this way?'' the narrator asks. ``When I was
young, I was perpetually overconfident or insecure. Either I felt
completely useless, unattractive, and worthless, or that I was
pretty much a success, and everything I did was bound to succeed.
When I was confident, I could overcome the hardest challenges. But
all it took was the smallest setback for me to be sure that I was
utterly worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics caught onto this book after readers did. ``The best
novel I read this year,'' Neil Ascherson wrote in the British
Independent, calling it ``an unforgettable short tale about love,
horror, and mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The opening chapters deal with a stock theme, the sentimental
education of a young man,'' Robert Taylor wrote in The Boston Globe
in 1997, but ``the novel displays both a profound moral reach and a
compelling story, and to the perennial issues of the German past it
brings a fresh, provocative approach.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holocaust is the most powerful moral story of this century,
and the book's author, Bernard Schlink, symbolizes the second
generation's guilt. Now 54, he is a professor of constitutional law
and the philosophy of law in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers write elegant, precise novels about the human
condition. Other lawyers crank out hefty bestsellers of ``courtroom
drama.'' Schlink's academic specialty is collective guilt, but he
sketches his unforgettable characters meticulously. His plot is as
geometrically detailed as an Albrecht Duerer drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Schlink has encountered criticism that because he is a
second-generation ``good German,'' he seeks ignorance as an alibi.
This philistine approach, reviewing the author and not the work, is
invalid because Schlink's scholarly work not only accepts
collective guilt, but documents it in studies like ``Questions of
Law, Guilt, and Future After the Third Reich.''
</P>
<P>
   Collective guilt exists today in Serbia as in Germany from 1933
until 1945. Adolf Hitler was democratically elected by an informed
electorate. Historical evidence suggests that ``good Germans'' were
few.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Reader'' is a story, not a tract. Moreover, a good
story is the basis for a successful movie. Will Hollywood make a
movie of ``The Reader''?
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Lee Curtis has read the book and given it to friends.
Since she made ``Halloween'' in 1978, Curtis has been an American
male adolescent fantasy. It's hard to see the daughter of the
former Bernie Schwartz of Brooklyn, aka Tony Curtis, portraying a
character in this story, but Jamie Lee is brave, even if Hollywood
and ``The Reader'' may not be a match.
</P>
<P>
   No movie can ruin a book, and ``The Reader'' will remain
powerful because, as its title suggests, it shows how reading can
conjure up characters and transform them with feelings of love,
memory, and momentous regret.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
