<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE DO `EYE CRUSTIES' COME FROM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When we wake up, why do we have crust in our eyes?
</P>
<P>
   S.S., Mattapan, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Eye crusties'' are the leftover protein and fat from tears
that have dried up. Tears have three components: Salty water, which
comes from the tear gland behind the upper outer corner of our eye;
Protein, secreted by the conjuctiva, which is the clear film that
covers the eye; And fat, which comes from ducts in the eyelids.
</P>
<P>
   Tears do lots of jobs. They clean the eye. They fill in tiny
imperfections in the surface of the cornea which needs to be
perfectly smooth for the best vision. They also deliver nutrients
to the cornea, which has to be clear to let light through to the
iris so it has no blood vessels. And of course tears flow at times
of emotion, when we produce more salt water. (It's 0.9 percent
salt) At night, with our eyes closed and protected, we don't make
tears, explains Dr. Edward Murphy of the Massachusetts Eye and Ear
Infirmary. Small amounts of the tear mixture already on the surface
of the eye seep out, and without a fresh supply of liquid from the
tear gland, the fat and protein dry up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why does your breath smell so bad when you wake up?
</P>
<P>
   SB and AB, Mattapan, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are always lots of bacteria in our mouth, feeding on
the tiny leftover bits of what we've eaten. Ever hear of plaque,
the stuff all those toothpaste ads promise to get rid of? It's
nothing more than organized colonies of bacteria chowing down on
food bits on your teeth.
</P>
<P>
   When we're awake, some plaque is removed when we chew, talk,
drink, even when we breath. But overnight, when those disturbances
cease, it's party time for the bacterial colonies on your teeth and
they multiply like crazy. Their waste products are acids, which
cause cavities, and gasses, which cause that rude blast of morning
breath.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do we snore?
</P>
<P>
   S.D. Cotuit, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. To bug the person sleeping next to us, of course. Actually,
there are several causes of snoring. All of them create some kind
of restriction in the upper airway. Kids with swollen tonsils or
adenoids snore. People sleeping on their back snore because the
tissues in the neck are pressing down on the windpipe. Overweight
people snore for pretty much the same reason, or because some of
their fat is stored in tissues in the neck. People with colds snore
because they have swollen sinus tissues in the back of their
throat. Drinking alcohol causes snoring by relaxing the muscles in
the throat, which restricts the size of the airway. We snore more
as we age because of the loss of elasticity in on neck tissues,
which sag in on the windpipe. People with misshapen jaws,
larger-than-normal tongues, or on relaxant medications, all tend to
snore.
</P>
<P>
   So if you try to sleep next to an overweight elderly drunk with
a misshapen jaw and a cold who's taking muscle relaxants, bring
industrial strength earplugs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why is yawning contagious?
</P>
<P>
   P.H., Jamaica Plain, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First, lets dispel a myth. You don't yawn to take in extra
oxygen. That's been rejected in lab tests, says yawn expert Robert
Provine, Professor of Psychology at the University of Maryland's
Baltimore County campus. He had test subjects breathe air with
extra oxygen. He induced oxygen deprivation in others giving them
air high in carbon dioxide. Neither caused more or less yawning.
</P>
<P>
   Provine says ``we yawn when we're changing states of activity.
Going from sleep to wakefulness, like yawning in the morning. Or
wakefulness to sleep.'' (He says we yawn more in the morning when
we wake up, by the way.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Concert pianists will yawn before going out to an important
performance. Olympic athletes yawn before the big event. Embryos
begin yawning eleven weeks after conception.'' He says yawning is
somehow connected to changing levels of body activity, but nobody
understands just what the connection is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably helps stir up the blood and brain chemistry to
facilitate those transitions from one level of activity to
another,'' Provine says.
</P>
<P>
   Yawning is highly contagious, he says. Provine has made test
subjects yawn by letting them read about yawning, by showing them a
yawning face, even just talking about yawning or asking the test
subjects to think about yawning.
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``Yawning is ancient and autonomic,'' Provine says. ``Maybe
it's to get everyone in the tribe to synchronize their states of
activity, to increase the success of the tribe if everyone's
working together. We really don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Every vertebrate species yawns. Fish yawn. Birds yawn.
Alligators yawn. But Provine says it's apparently only contagious
in humans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
