<HEADLINE>
FBI USES POWERFUL WEAPON, A GRAND JURY, IN MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ By taking the investigation into the killings of
a California woman and two teen-age girls before a federal grand
jury, the FBI is using one of the most powerful tools it has.
</P>
<P>
   The move extends the FBI's reach, wraps the investigation in
even deeper secrecy and is calculated to prevent the leaks,
procedural and political blunders that made a mess of the JonBenet
Ramsey slaying case in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   With the involvement of a grand jury, prosecutors will be able
to subpoena reluctant witnesses and hard-to-obtain documents to
bolster the physical evidence gathered by investigators from at
least three crime scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The woman and two children _ Carole Sund, 42, and her
15-year-old daughter, Julie, and family friend Silvina Pelosso, 16
_ vanished Feb. 15 from a lodge near the Yosemite National Park.
The incinerated bodies of Carole Sund and Pelosso were found March
19 in the trunk of their burned rental car miles from the lodge.
Julie Sund's body was found on March 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to build an airtight case,'' said FBI Special
Agent Nick Rossi.
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury can compel even the most reluctant witness to
appear before it. Failure to answer its questions brings drastic
consequences, including prison time.
</P>
<P>
   No American is beyond the reach of a federal grand jury.
President Clinton had to testify before a grand jury about his
relations with Monica Lewinsky, testimony that was later turned
over to Congress, which then made it public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grand jury's subpoena power is almost unlimited,'' said
San Francisco Public Defender Jeff Brown. ``And there's also the
fact that you're on their turf. The door closes and the prosecutor
is hitting you with questions and you may not know where he's going
... You can't outsmart them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the missing women in California, the FBI is
probably using the grand jury simply because of its power to issue
subpoenas. ``That may be all they're doing,'' said Joseph
Russoniello, a former U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Brenner, dean of the University of Dayton School of Law in
Ohio, said the referral of the Yosemite case at first seemed
unusual, given the extensive physical evidence: the three bodies, a
torched car, several rolls of film and Carole Sund's wallet, plus
other personal effects found near the car and in their motel room.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the case ``sounds like the classic thing the FBI
could handle, your typical Columbo-type investigation,'' said
Brenner, a specialist in federal grand juries.
</P>
<P>
   Federal grand juries have a big advantage over other
investigative agencies: They have the power to subpoena witnesses
from other states, Brenner said. That could be crucial, she said,
if FBI agents have a theory or tips, but cannot persuade key people
to talk to them.
</P>
<P>
   There's another practical advantage: The federal grand jury's
extra cloak of secrecy can protect witnesses who fear retribution,
a principal reason grand juries are so heavily used in cases
against organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take federal grand jury testimony, it remains secret
and never gets revealed,'' said San Francisco lawyer Jerrold Ladar,
a former chief of criminal prosecutions in the U.S. attorney's
office. In California, grand jury transcripts have to be unsealed
10 days after a suspect is arraigned.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes investigators use grand juries for political cover,
when the public is clamoring for a solution but the investigation
has been bungled or is going nowhere. That seems to be what's
happening in Boulder, Colo., where District Attorney Alex Hunter
gave the JonBenet Ramsey case to a Boulder County grand jury only
last September, nearly two years into the murder investigation of
the young girl.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike investigators in the Ramsey case, the FBI has so far
been able to prevent leaks to the media in the Sund-Pelosso
killings. Investigators have yielded facts sparingly; they have
not, for example, disclosed the cause of Julie Sund's death, or how
they learned the location of her body.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal jurisdiction applies in this case because a federal
crime _ possibly carjacking _ may have been committed on federal
property, Yosemite National Park.
</P>
<P>
   That may be another plus to the investigation, said Barry
Portman, a federal defender in San Francisco. ``The advantage of a
federal grand jury is that the feds have great experience'' in such
criminal matters, whereas county investigators often don't, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, because the killings appear to have been committed
off federal property, any prosecution will likely take place in
state courts.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the FBI could wrap up its investigation with the grand
jury and deliver a tidy case to the district attorney in Tuolumne
County on a silver platter, Russoniello said. Turning over the
results of a federal grand jury investigation to a state agency
requires a court order, but ``it's done fairly frequently,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
