   KOSOVO-PILOTS (Aviano Air Base, Italy) _ The men who pilot the
warplanes streaking into the gathering darkness say they understand
the limits of the massive firepower they are unleashing inside
Yugoslavia. By Charles M. Sennott. 1050 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VILLAGE (Kruma, Albania) _ Two hundred people lived in
this town near the border and it was among first to be cleansed.
Now that's done, what happened to 20 men seized by Serbs? By Susan
Milligan. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   SERBS-IDENTITY (Kuce, Yugolsavia) _ Ordinary Serbs now find
themselves a new pariah class. They're forced to circle the wagons,
defined by a person they hate. By Colin Nickerson. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-JOURNAL (Rezevici, Yugoslavia) _ Caught between Serbia
and the US Sixth Fleet, Marko Taylor, a genial 38-year-old builder
from Baton Rouge, La., may be one of the last ordinary Americans
living in Yugoslavia. By Colin Nickerson.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-AMERICANS (Moscow) _ It's a bad time to be an American in
many parts of the world. They are fired from Russian companies, the
ambassador is insulted in Greece, McDonald's is trashed in
Belgrade. By David Filipov. 1300 words.
