<SLUG> BC-WORKING4/2-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE APRIL 5, 1999) &HT;    
 &HT;    WORKERS DESERVE FACTS ON CASH BALANCE PLANS
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the news business, there isn't anything quite as intriguing
as something that everyone wants to keep secret _ especially when
money is involved.
</P>
<P>
   So, let me shine some light on something benefit consultants and
many companies don't want you to know.
</P>
<P>
   I recently wrote about the advent of cash benefit pension plans,
which, unlike traditional plans, spread company retirement
contributions more evenly throughout an employee's career, saving
companies millions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   But they don't want you to know that, because some workers,
especially longtime, older employees, end up on the losing end of
the deal if provisions are not made during the conversion from the
old to new plan.
</P>
<P>
   Well, now it seems Congress, too, is getting interested in them,
concerned too many workers are having a fast one pulled on them.
</P>
<P>
   Consider some excerpts of transcripts of an actuarial society
meeting recently released by the Senate Finance Committee, which is
looking into this matter:
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, one consultant from the Aon Consulting group
explained, ``The basic approach here is that we're going to change
the form of their pension plan. Yes, if I have a 1 percent final
average pay plan and I reduce that 1 percent to 0.8 percent,
everybody knows _ you don't have to be an actuary to figure out _
that you just had a benefit cutback. That's kind of obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he continued: ``If you give them something different, it
isn't as obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's hard for employees to figure out the changes. One
consultant from PricewaterhouseCoopers pointed out at the same
meeting that ``very little comparison can be done between the two
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The transcripts have the benefits community in an uproar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing makes us look kind of slimy,'' said one
benefits consultant, who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sher, a principal at PricewaterhouseCoopers in Teaneck,
N.J., said the comments were made at professional meetings and are
jocular in tone. No one realized the comments would wind up in
Congress or in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Companies, he said, don't make the switch to cash balance plans
primarily to hide benefit changes because they could be negative _
that motivation is way down on the list. Mostly they do it for
business reasons or to attract and retain employees or to appeal to
young or mobile workers.
</P>
<P>
   But others aren't buying that. ``How do they sleep at night?''
asked E. Dale Wortham, president of the AFL-CIO in Harris County,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Employees need to know if their pensions have changed so they
can alter their retirement plans, said U.S. Rep. Ken Bentsen,
D-Houston. But the laws governing pension plans allow employers to
explain the changes in broad and often deceptive ways.
</P>
<P>
   If employers phrase it the ``right way,'' the losers won't find
out until it's too late, said Bentsen, who is co-sponsoring
legislation to require employers to notify individual employees of
their pension benefits under the old and new plans.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation has a long way to go _ it has to get through
committees in both houses and then to the floors _ but it is
picking up bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good idea, said Wortham. ``Most people don't have an
actuary who lives next door,'' and they can't afford to hire one.
</P>
<P>
   The United Way of the Texas Gulf Coast, which converted its
pension plan to a cash balance plan three years ago, hasn't had a
chance to study the proposed Pension Right to Know Act of 1999. But
spokesman Mario Gomez said the agency supports any effort to
provide full disclosure to employees to help them prepare for
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Reliant Energy, which switched to cash balance last year, wants
to provide employees with accurate, useful and meaningful
retirement information, said spokeswoman Sandy Fruhman.
</P>
<P>
   But, she argued, some of the information that would have to be
disclosed isn't relevant. For example, the bill would require
Reliant to make pension projections three, five and 10 years after
the conversion, but the company has already agreed to give all
employees who leave the company in the next 10 years the higher
value of either plan.
</P>
<P>
   Reliant also is worried about making long-term projections that
the bill requires because it's hard to know an employee's future
salary or what promotions he'll receive, Fruhman said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
