<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE APRIL 5, 1999) &HT;    
 &HT;    TEXAS' POOR NEED MORE THAN WELFARE REFORM
 &HT;    
 &HT;    COMMENTARY
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's mantra of ``compassionate
conservatism'' is already trite, but it will continue to be
discussed, debated and sometimes ridiculed as the governor's
presidential race continues to heat up.
</P>
<P>
   Putting aside all the political rhetoric over what Bush's use of
the term may actually mean, most people consider ``compassionate''
a perfectly good, positive and pretty straightforward word.
</P>
<P>
   It came to mind with the release of still another report that in
these days of bustling entrepreneurship and soaring stock averages
millions of Texans are still being left behind, many through no
fault of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty is at least as old as government, and those who govern
can do only so much for those who are poor. The debate is always
over how much ``so much'' should be.
</P>
<P>
   The most fashionable political attack on poverty in recent years
_ coming from such disparate sources as President Clinton and
would-be-president Bush _ has been welfare reform. And, thanks in
no small part to a mostly healthy economy, millions of people in
Texas and other states have been moved from the welfare rolls to
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Many former welfare recipients are turning their lives around,
prodded by laws forcing them to get jobs or else. For many other
poor people, however, welfare reform alone isn't the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Most poor people in Texas work, according to a new study by the
Center for Public Policy Priorities. For various reasons, usually
an inadequate education, they just don't earn enough money to make
ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, there are people out there who are working
but are still poor,'' said Dick Lavine, a senior fiscal analyst for
the center, who helped put together the report.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Public Policy Priorities is a nonpartisan,
nonprofit group that analyzes the effects of public policy on low-
and moderate-income people. It also is an advocacy group that not
only preaches governmental compassion for those in need but also
urges changes in tax, spending and educational policies that would
help more poor people to help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Using Census Bureau data from 1995 to 1997, a period during
which welfare reforms were beginning to take effect in Texas, the
report determined that one of every six Texans lived below the
poverty line. That was 16.9 percent of Texans, compared to a
national average of 13.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty rate was even higher among Texas children. Some 24
percent of Texas youngsters _ one in every four _ were poor.
</P>
<P>
   The study determined that more than 80 percent of poor families
in Texas with children and almost 60 percent of poor families and
individuals without children had one or more adults who worked
during the year.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty-stricken parents who were employed worked an average of
more than 44 weeks, or more than 10 months, a year in the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   And, the study concluded, more than 70 percent of poor families
with children get most of their income from wages, while only 11
percent relied on welfare for most of their income.
</P>
<P>
   Lavine readily acknowledged that government alone cannot improve
these people's lives. Many are struggling because of rapid
technological changes in the workplace, and others blew their
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But there are things _ aside from welfare reform _ that the
state can do to improve the prospects of many of its disadvantaged
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   One is improved health care. People cannot work or learn very
well if they're chronically sick.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with $1.8 billion in early proceeds from the state's
settlement with tobacco companies, lawmakers will make some
improvements in this critical area, including an expansion of a
health insurance program for children of the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   Not so promising are efforts to increase the state minimum wage
from $3.35 an hour to $5.15 an hour (the federal level) and expand
unemployment insurance to cover part-time workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature won't change the regressive nature of the state
tax system, which hits poor people the hardest, proportionately.
But lawmakers are considering some minor consumer relief, endorsed
by the governor, in sales tax exemptions for diapers and
over-the-counter medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But the most critical difference legislators can make is through
further improvements to the public education system, including
incentives for young people to remain in school. The jury is still
out on that one.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Texas parents who work but are still poor are
dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doomed,'' Lavine said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
