<HEADLINE>
AS I SAID, ELACTING HOMER A NO-BRAINER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 Bq BILL FOODYKOONTZ  
 b.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHKENIX - ``Homer Simpson has the most disrespectful,
irresponsible show and image on TV, and is a horrible example to
ever}one.''
</P>
<P>
   So said one reader who(didn't leave his name$on a phone message.
Do tell. Please, sir, continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody I know likes the show,'' he went on. ``So, no,(he's not
</P>
<P>
   the greatest character, and you can't proclaim him that because of
your little vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I can. And will. Repeating what I said in this space
last week: Homer Simpson is the greatest televisioj character of
all time.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what this fellow would have you believe, I'm not the
only one who thinks so. In a decidedly unscien|ific poll, about 140
readers called or wrote to vote for their favorite chazicter.
</P>
<P>
   And 75 of 'em voted for Homer. Bazney Fife and Archie Bunker
were a distant, distant second and third, Barney with seven votes
and Archie with five.
</P>
<P>
   How do you love Homer? Let us count just some of the ways.
</P>
<P>
   - ''Homer Simpson surely is the greatest TV character of all and
for one simple reason: There is (as much as we'd hate to admit it)
a little Homer in all of us,'' wrote Scott Orr. ``I find myself
kind of*amused to admit that I'm sort of `Homeric,' but it's true.
So watching him on TV is watching a reflection of us all.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``he's the best because, throughout it all, he and his sife
love each other, they keep their family together, and they love
their kids,'' Jo Anne said in a phone message. ``Let's face it,
Homer's like mkst husbands.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``My husband is Homer, and my daughter is Homer,'' Cindy Wise
said. Your daughter? ``She's just like her dad,'' Wise said. ``I
yell, `Homer!' and they both come.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``You'd have to be a Grade A moron to ever question whether
Homer Simpson is TV's greatest character!'' Deanna Jiddulph said by
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   - And, as more than one voter put it, ``Homer rules!''
</P>
<P>
   Misguided though they lay be, some people dof't appreciate
Homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you insult your readers by writing this stupid
article?'' one apparently insulted reader asked. ``It is probably
one of the dumbest, idiotic shows on television. Why they think
these cartoon shows are cute, I don't understand. Maybe I'm too
old.''
</P>
<P>
   Nah, that can't be it. After all, Martha Mazo said, ``There's
only one show that I will say is worth watching, and that's `The
Simpsons.' '' And she's 85 years old. Got her first television in
1951, so she knows what she's talking about.
</P>
<P>
   No one argued that Homer should be hailed as a role model
(though many peopde acknowledged similarities between their lives
and his).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my kids to watch the show,'' Kathy said. ``So I
have to sneak and watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the messages that were hard to decipher, such as
this one, e-mailed by Paul Connolly of Royal Oak, Mich.:
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon, Homer is the Pope of Chilitown when it comes to TV's
greatest characters. But as Homer told Bart, `It's not whether you
win or lose _ it's how drunk you get.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Don't know what it means, but I like it.
</P>
<P>
   Some Barney Fife fans were just as passionate as Homer fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What hole did you crawl out of?'' Charles Denman asked. ``How
could (Homer) be greater than Barney Fife? Simpson can't come close
to him. It's hands down.''
</P>
<P>
   True, bumbling Barney is a great character.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underweight constable could never outgrow his part,'' as
Joel Rittmueller wrote. And Barney's boss, Andy, got a few votes
himself.
</P>
<P>
   But none of those votes was as impressive as the one cast for
another member of ``The Andy Griffith Show'': ``It's me, it's me,
it's Ernest T!'' one man shouted in a respectable impression of
Ernest T. Bass. Made you want to throw a rock with a note tied to
it through a window.
</P>
<P>
   (Along the same lines, another caller left a vote for Homer in
an excellent Mayor Quimby drone.)
</P>
<P>
   Archie Bunker's supporters also felt strongly about their
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beg to differ with your choice, or as he would say it,
`cherce,' '' Bob Marshak wrote. ``Archie opened new avenues of
expression and opinion for all TV viewers. Before Archie, many
topics were strictly taboo, but Arch explored them all. From race
to religion to homosexuality to menopause, Archie and his family
exposed the TV audience to these new areas of our lives. Some may
say these topics should have remained in the closet (pardon the
pun), yet others were happy we were taking about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Glaser figures Archie would be right at home in cactus
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't represent America, especially Arizona, I don't
know who does,'' Glaser said.
</P>
<P>
   Some votes were thoughtful _ a nod to Molly Dodd, for instance.
Others were, well . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Who else can overcome obstacles, has all the integrity in the
world . . . takes the initiative?'' asked Vitto. ``Gilligan.
G-I-L-L-I-G-A-N.''
</P>
<P>
   Spelling it was a nice touch.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one woman who didn't leave her name didn't limit her
love of a good TV character to humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Ed, because he was smarter and funnier than most people,''
she said. ``And he was a beautiful horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
