<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6429 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IQ-BONDS-COX     04-05 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-BONDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bonds' big capital appreciation looks like it's history
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't worry about interest rates. So says Bill Gross, the
nation's most successful bond fund manager, who oversees $155
billion in fixed-income investments at Pimco Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: He doesn't think interest rates will move much.
</P>
<P>
   Gross has an uncanny knack for sifting through economic data and
betting the right way. He's beaten the benchmark Lehman Brothers
aggregate bond index for eight of the past 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   That success hasn't gone unnoticed. One of the funds he manages,
Pimco Total Return, now is the nation's largest bond fund, with
assets of more than $25 billion. Since July, investors in Japan
also have been allowed to invest in the fund. So far, they've
plunked down $675 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest rates may go down a bit over the next few months if
the economy slows,'' Gross says. ``But don't expect fireworks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross explains that the bull market in bonds, which began in
1981, is probably over.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would mean that the bottom (of the bond market) we saw in
October 1998 during the global contagion probably marked the ebb of
interest rates and the peak of bond prices going forward,'' Gross
says.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices and bond yields move in opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   How confident is he of his forecast?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say 80 percent,'' Gross says. He puts the chance of
inflation reigniting at 10 percent; and global recession at 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a steady, low-inflation environment, Gross says bond
investors should expect that most, if not all, of their return will
likely come from the coupon _ or yield _ on their investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would caution investors to simply think of bonds as income
and yield generators, as opposed to capital gains providers,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Current yields remain attractive, relative to inflation, which
is running about 1.5 percent, Gross says.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some fixed-income investments are better buys than
others, he says.
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorites: Mortgage-backed securities, which now
account for half of the $155 billion in fixed-income investments he
oversees. They currently yield about 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One way to invest in mortgage-backed securities is to buy shares
in a Ginnie Mae fund, Gross suggests.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes tax-free municipal bonds. Insured 10-year munis
now yield 4.45 percent. That translates into a 7.37 percent yield
for those in the 39.6 percent tax bracket, and 6.18 percent for
those in the 28 percent bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Gross recommends Treasury securities that mature in five to 10
years. They now yield 5.14 percent and 5.28 percent, respectively.
That's on average about a half percentage point less than the yield
of 30-year Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get almost as much yield, and a lot less risk,'' he
observes.
</P>
<P>
   Gross is lukewarm to high-yield, or junk, bonds, even though
their yields are attractive. The bonds could be hurt if the economy
tanks, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't load up the boat,'' he says. He suggests a mix of junk
bonds and municipals to mitigate that risk.
</P>
<P>
   Gross would avoid foreign bonds. High-quality ones have low
yields, while those of developing countries are ``dicey,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
