<HEADER>
A6430 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IQ-INVEST-ONLINE-COX     04-05 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-INVEST-ONLINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online investing has its perils and requires research
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet cuts out the middleman. For the most part, that's
good: less-expensive books and plane tickets and, in some cases,
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   If you're buying a book or a ticket, squeezing out the middleman
doesn't cost you much _ maybe some small talk at the register. But
cutting out the middleman in a stock investment can mean missing
out on information.
</P>
<P>
   This time last year, Jayme Colasanti heard about a company
announcing a 3-for-1 stock split. He'd read about it on America
Online, on a page that lists stocks with pending splits. Instead of
going to a stockbroker for advice and information, Colasanti, who
invests as a hobby, called up Yahoo!'s finance site to do his
homework. Satisfied with the company's press releases available
online, the 35-year-old Syracuse, N.Y., resident then went to a
discount broker and put in an order for 333 shares at a total cost
of $4,300.
</P>
<P>
   When the split became effective, the shares dropped much more
than the split would account for, reducing the value of his total
investment to about $500.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for an explanation, Colasanti called the only number
listed on the press releases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy came to the phone and was all accusatory, asking me
who I was. I asked about the split and what happened, and he didn't
have an answer. But he kept asking who I was and where I was from.
Keep in mind this is a public company, and I'm one of its
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I'd made a mistake right then.''
</P>
<P>
   Colasanti is one of a growing number of investors taking
advantage of technological improvements that let people juggle
investments from the den. More investors are bypassing traditional
investment routes and buying stock from Web sites of online
brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The advantages of online investing or online research are cost
savings and convenience. Just as it is true when you buy from a
store where you bag your own groceries, helping yourself can be
cheaper than paying for help.
</P>
<P>
   But in the process, some investors are throwing themselves into
the jungle of do-it-yourself investing, where the dominant law is
Darwin's: the survival of the fittest.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the interest in the stock market, and Internet stocks in
particular, is created and sustained by the Web. Investor sites
such as Silicon Investor (www.techstocks.com), Raging Bull
(www.ragingbull.com) and Yahoo! Finance (quote
</P>
<P>
   .yahoo.com) offer solid information, such as historical data
about the performance of public companies and links to Securities
and Exchange Commission filings.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the sites offer message boards, which can be sources of
reliable information, but can also be filled with rumor and hype.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has guidelines to help investors filter the information
available and possibly avoid Internet stock fraud. The main advice
is do your homework, which means more than reading press releases.
The SEC advises against investing based solely on what you read in
an online newsletter or bulletin board posting, especially when the
company is small and obscure.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC also says not to invest in small companies that don't
file regular reports with the agency, unless you are willing to
analyze the financial reports yourself, verify claims about new
products or contracts, call suppliers and customers, and check out
the backgrounds of the people running the company.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the 6,500 stocks whose prices are quoted on
the over-the-counter bulletin board do not file financial documents
with the SEC, which means investors are on their own. They would
have to contact each company and request such information.
</P>
<P>
   Regulatory agencies are trying to make sure financial
information is more readily available to investors. The National
Association of Securities Dealers recently passed a rule that will
make companies traded on the OTC bulletin board file with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Companies traded over the counter have not had to file quarterly
and annual financial reports. The new rule, adopted by the SEC in
January, requires the filings to begin by June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
