<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-INVEST-OVERSEAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Overseas investments can bolster a portfolio
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While many investors continue to pour money into U.S. stocks _
dazzled by spectacular returns over the past nine years _ others
are hedging their bets by putting some money to work overseas.
</P>
<P>
   They are attracted not only by the relative bargains, but also
by the fact the addition of foreign stocks to a U.S. stock
portfolio will _ over time _ reduce risk and enhance returns.
</P>
<P>
   Studies support that.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 16 out of the 20 rolling 10-year periods between
1979 and 1998, a portfolio that included 20 percent international
stocks and 80 percent U.S. stocks matched, or outperformed, a
portfolio invested exclusively in U.S. stocks, according to T. Rowe
Price Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptions were the last four years, when U.S. stocks, as
measured by the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, enjoyed outsized
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Investors can put their money overseas in several ways.
</P>
<P>
   One is to buy shares of international mutual funds, which invest
everywhere but in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Some funds invest only in a particular region, such as Latin
America, or in a single country.
</P>
<P>
   Many regional and single-country funds are traded on the New
York Stock Exchange, often at a discount to their net asset values.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also can buy shares of foreign companies in the form
of American depositary receipts, or ADRs, which trade like U.S.
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ADRs possess all of the other problems associated with
buying a foreign stock, including exposure to currency risk and
country risk. Returns on an ADR are determined in large part by the
sum of the return of the stock on the local exchange, plus the
return of the currency.
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign markets, such as Argentina and Hong Kong, are
closely correlated to ours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Argentina and Hong Kong both have currencies fixed to U.S.
dollars,'' explains Vivian Lewis, editor of Global Investing
newsletter. So the stocks of companies based in those countries are
likely to be negatively affected by a tumble on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock markets of other countries, such as Chile and
Israel, aren't much correlated to ours, says Lewis. She
particularly likes Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of concern about the political risks, Israel is a very
cheap market,'' according to Lewis. ``It has a lot of high-tech
companies, and we constantly find new ones that are terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   One is BVR Systems (ticker symbol BVRS), a maker of
advanced-training and computer-based simulation systems for
military use.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Magal Security Systems (MAGSF), which makes
computerized systems that automatically detect, locate and identify
intruders, or explosive devices in luggage and packages.
</P>
<P>
   In Chile, Lewis likes Provida (PVD), which administers pensions
in a growing number of countries in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   She also recommends investors consider:
</P>
<P>
   AXA (AXA), a French insurance group expanding its global reach.
In the United States, the company's insurance activities are
conducted through Equitable. AXA also controls the Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette securities firm.
</P>
<P>
   Aracruz Celulose (ARA), a Brazilian producer of bleached
eucalyptus pulp that is sold for dollars to high-grade paper makers
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Among closed-end funds, Lewis suggests Austria Fund (OST),
European Warrant Fund (EWF), First Australia Prime Income Fund
(FAX), India Growth Fund (IGF), Korea Fund (KF) and Templeton
Emerging Markets (EMF).
</P>
<P>
   ``Buy funds that enable you to do certain kinds of investing
that you otherwise would not be able to do as a retail investor,''
Lewis says. She notes, for example, that markets in some countries,
such as India, aren't readily accessible to individual American
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
