<HEADER>
A6433 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IQ-INVEST-POSITIVE-CO     04-05 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-INVEST-POSITIVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Long-term winner ever the optimist
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to investing, it pays to think positive.
</P>
<P>
   So says L. Roy Papp, who's managed money on Wall Street for more
than four decades, frequently beating the performance of the
benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way: My professor at Wharton (School of the
University of Pennsylvania) once said to me, `You can be
pessimistic whenever you feel like being pessimistic, just don't
stay there very long, because long term you can't win as a
pessimist,''' says Papp, who turned 72 last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, our country has been growing ever since it was
started,'' says Papp, who believes that although stocks have gone
up a lot, they still remain attractive.
</P>
<P>
   One reason: The U.S. economy keeps growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three months ago, economists were talking about 2 percent
growth,'' says Papp, whose collection of Chinese paintings recently
was exhibited at the Georgia Museum of Art at the University of
Georgia. ``Now, they're talking about 3 percent. The amazing thing
is this is all happening in spite of economic problems in Asia and
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The economy remains strong because consumers still are willing,
and able, to spend, Papp says. And our economy, which is less
reliant on manufacturing, is more resistant to recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recessions don't occur with regularity as they once did,''
Papp says. They used to occur every 51 months and last nine months.
</P>
<P>
   But the computer has helped change all that, Papp says. It has
boosted productivity and helped companies manage inventories
better.
</P>
<P>
   If recessions don't occur as often, ``that makes stocks worth a
lot more than they used to be worth,'' according to Papp, whose
firm manages five no-load funds, including the L. Roy Papp Stock
Fund and the Papp America-Abroad Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Papp avoids buying shares of cyclical companies, whose prospects
are closely linked to economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   He prefers to buy stocks of companies with above-average
profitability, evidenced in part by at least 10 years of consistent
earnings and dividend increases. And he likes to buy them at prices
that do not reflect their superior long-term earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   The shares are kept so long as Papp believes the prospects for
appreciation remain favorable, and the stocks are not greatly
overvalued in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   One stock Papp jettisoned was Coca-Cola (ticker symbol KO).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our largest holding in 1993 in the Papp America-Abroad
Fund,'' he says. ``We started selling Coca-Cola in 1994 because it
was very high priced. We kept some of it until last year, when we
sold the remaining stock at between $85 and $66.''
</P>
<P>
   He compares Coca-Cola to State Street Corp. (STT), which serves
as custodian and manager of almost $5 trillion in assets. Its
shares have performed just as well as Coca-Cola's, both
appreciating at an annual rate of 27.1 percent from 1988 through
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts generally believe both companies will achieve earnings
growth of about 14 percent over the next five years. Yet Coca-Cola
currently trades at more than 42 times this year's estimated
earnings of $1.44 a share; and State Street, which Papp recommends,
trades at 28 times estimated 1999 earnings of $3.03 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Papp also likes stocks in two industries that are likely to
continue to enjoy robust growth: pharmaceuticals and technology.
</P>
<P>
   In the former, he likes Merck (MRK). Papp says it has one of the
lowest valuations in the drug group, but has one of the best
new-product pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   In technology, he likes American Power Conversion (APCC), which
makes power packs and surge protectors for computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the third best average annual return for shareholders
for the last 10 years,'' according to Papp.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes chip maker Intel (INTC) and BMC Software (BMCS), a
provider of application management software that helps companies,
including those related to the Internet, to improve their
competitiveness and lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   Other stocks he recommends include insurer American
International Group (AIG); money manager T. Rowe Price Associates
(TROW); advertising giant Interpublic Group (IPG); retailer Office
Depot (ODP); and Steiner Leisure (STNRF), a debt-free company that
provides beauty parlor and spa services on 80 percent of the cruise
ships that ply the North Atlantic and Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
