<HEADER>
A6435 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IQ-SMALL-CAPS-COX     04-05 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-SMALL-CAPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small-caps' champion banking on a rebound
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eric T. McKissack invests where many fear to tread. The manager
of the Ariel Appreciation Fund, which has $335 million in assets,
invests mostly in small- to mid-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   It's an asset class that has lagged behind large-company stocks,
epitomized by the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, for five years
in a row.
</P>
<P>
   That's prompted many investors to abandon small-company stocks
and the mutual funds that invest in them.
</P>
<P>
   But McKissack believes that small- to mid-cap stocks are due for
a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   History is on his side. After all, over the past 72 years,
small-cap stocks have provided a compounded annual return of 12.4
percent, outpacing the S&AMP;P 500, with 11.2 percent, according to
Chicago-based Ibbotson Associates.
</P>
<P>
   McKissack says there are good reasons why large-cap stocks have
outperformed their smaller brethren in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The globalization of business has been to the greater
advantage of large-cap companies,'' he says. ``The huge asset
inflows into mutual funds has emphasized the larger-cap issues,
where there is more liquidity and greater ability to put dollars to
work quickly for the fund manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors also prefer investing in the shares of big
U.S. companies they are familiar with, McKissack adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigger companies also can take advantage of cost cutting and
business efficiencies to a greater degree, which has led to higher
earnings growth,'' McKissack says. ``They have also benefited from
interest rate trends. They have been able to leverage the business
and marketing environment to impact their growth rates to a greater
degree.''
</P>
<P>
   And some technology stocks _ particularly those related to the
Internet _ have rocketed in value, quickly transforming them into
large-cap stocks and attracting investors in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's drawn a lot of attention away from the smaller names,''
McKissack says.
</P>
<P>
   And prices are cheaper as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price-to-earnings ratio of the Russell 2000 is about a 20
percent discount to the S&AMP;P 500,'' McKissack observes. ``The
price-to-book value is about a 40 percent discount to the S&AMP;P 500.
So those relative valuations are historically low.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet McKissack acknowledges that history also shows that
investing in small-cap stock is riskier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our value orientation helps mitigate that risk,'' says
McKissack, who is co-chief investment officer at Chicago-based
Ariel Capital Management, which manages assets of more than $2.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   He likes to buy out-of-favor stocks _ including those that have
been misunderstood or ignored _ whose prices already are depressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they're not as volatile when the market goes into the
tank,'' says McKissack. He likes companies that have distinct
market niches, solid finances, strong managements and established
records of success.
</P>
<P>
   Among his favorites:
</P>
<P>
   Specialty Equipment (ticker symbol SEC), which makes service
equipment for restaurants, including McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still not widely known on Wall Street,'' McKissack says.
``They went through a reorganization a few years ago, so their
balance sheet isn't pristine. That has probably deterred some
investors. But the cash flow and business characteristics are very
good. The stock has done well over the past year, moving from the
mid-teens to $26. We still see upside from here.''
</P>
<P>
   McKissack also likes Equifax (EFX), which isn't a small-cap
stock. But the stock has lagged. It tumbled 22 percent Dec. 23
after the company, which provides credit and other information to
businesses, warned that earnings would fall short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, McKissack notes the company has a ``good record of
consistent earnings'' and the stock will remain under pressure
until profits get back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock's attractive for someone looking beyond the one- to
two-year horizon,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Another stock McKissack likes is Interface (IFSIA), a maker of
carpet tiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed that management was slow to recognize the
slowdown in their industry,'' McKissack says. ``But we have done a
lot of homework in terms of talking to their customers and people
in the industry and have found they remain highly regarded for
their products and service. We're fairly confident the selling is
overdone. It's selling at a fraction of sales and book value.''
</P>
<P>
   McKissack also recommends Galileo International (GLC), a
provider of computerized reservation services to the travel
industry. It has fat profit margins and low debt, but some
investors fear it may lose market share as more travelers use the
Internet to buy airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, many of the Internet-based travel providers use
Galileo and other computer reservations systems to do their
comparative travel bookings,'' McKissack says.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the money manager recommends two media companies. He
says Central Newspapers (ECP), which owns newspapers in
Indianapolis and Phoenix, is selling at a ``substantial'' discount
to its peers. Lee Enterprises (LEE, LEENB) owns newspapers and
television stations. The performance of the company's TV business
has lagged that of its newspapers, McKissack observes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity for management to improve the returns on
the TV side, or sell the stations off,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
