A6437 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IQ-TECH-STOCKS-COX     04-05 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-TECH-STOCKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech watcher: Choppy '99, then upturn
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors have been flocking to high-tech stocks, lured by their
spectacular returns.
</P>
<P>
   But it's been nerve-wracking.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks tumbled in February, only to roar back in early
March.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the volatility to continue, says Charles A. Morris,
manager of the T. Rowe Price Science &AMP; Technology Fund, which has
assets of nearly $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   One reason: The industry is working through some fundamental
issues, such as excess capacity in semiconductors, a hiatus in the
introduction of new products and the economic meltdown in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Many customers also have deferred spending on hardware and
software, as they strive to resolve the millennium bug. In some
cases, customers also have been distracted by mergers and
acquisitions, particularly in the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``1999 is essentially a workout period for many of these
issues,'' says Morris, who has managed the fund since 1991. ``But
many of those issues will be neutralized _ or begin to get better _
as we move through the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Morris isn't making any big bets.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's assets are about evenly divided in four industry
groups: Software, hardware, communications and data services.
</P>
<P>
   Within those groups, he's investing in stocks whose prospects
remain bright.
</P>
<P>
   ``Company-specific fundamentals will drive performance,'' Morris
says.
</P>
<P>
   One stock he likes is Parametric Technology (ticker symbol
PMTC), the No. 1 maker of computer programs that help engineers
design cars, planes and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Morris thinks the shares could rebound to $25 to $40 over the
next 12 to 18 months. After trading as high as $36.31 1/4 in June,
they tumbled to as low as $8.50 in October, after the company
warned of weak demand in Asia and a shift to a new product.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for his optimism: He thinks earnings will be back on
track, estimating Parametric Technology will earn 80 cents a share
this fiscal year and $1.15 to $1.40 a share next year. It earned 40
cents a share last year.
</P>
<P>
   Morris also likes Atlanta-based First Data (FDC), the largest
processor of credit card transactions. Earnings have been under
pressure, as the company restructured to close unprofitable
businesses and cut expenses. The stock traded as low as $19.68 3/4
in October, but has since rebounded to around $43, as its earnings
prospects have brightened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock has legs to go in the $50 to $60 range,'' Morris
says.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes Atlanta-based National Data (NDC), which processes
bank card transactions. It also provides claims processing and
other services to the health care industry.
</P>
<P>
   Morris thinks the stock could rise to $60 from around $42
currently, particularly if the company recasts itself. ``I would
strongly encourage the company to split into two before somebody
does it for them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Morris has avoided buying the pure-play Internet stocks,
such as Yahoo! (YHOO) and eBay (EBAY). ``They'll need to pull back
at least 50 percent for us to be interested,'' Morris says.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he suggests that investors buy the shares of four
established companies that aren't totally dependent on the Internet
for future growth, yet are benefiting from it: Cisco Systems
(CSCO), EMC (EMC), Oracle (ORCL) and Sun Microsystems (SUNW).
</P>
<P>
   The spectacular performance of one Internet-related issue, that
of Norcross-based CheckFree Holdings (CKFR), which provides
electronic commerce software and services, prompted him to lock in
profits. It jumped from a low of $5.75 in October to around $44
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold in the past month,'' Morris said. The fund had owned a
million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
