<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, April
6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WRITING-ORIGINS (Undated) _ When it comes to explaining the
origins of writing, scientists are largely at a loss. But many at a
recent symposium favored a broad explanation of writing's origins
in the visual arts, pictograms of things being transformed into
increasingly abstract symbols for things, names and eventually
words in speech. Their views clashed with a widely held theory that
writing grew out of the pieces of clay that Sumerian accountants
had used to keep track of livestock and stores of grain. Scholars
assembled also conceded that they had no definitive answer to the
question of whether writing was invented only once and spread
elsewhere or arose independently several times in several places,
like Egypt, the Indus valley, China and among the Olmecs and Maya
of Mexico and Central America. By John Noble Wilford. (2200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RESEARCH-SECRECY (Undated) _ The strings that often come
with private research money _ the publication delays while patents
and profits are pursued, the proprietary findings _ hold the
pernicious potential to impede the free exchange of information
that speeds scientific progress, experts warned during a conference
on ``Secrecy in Science'' held by the American Association for the
Advancement of Science and the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. By Carey Goldberg. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASPERGERS-SYNDROME (Undated) _ Asperger's syndrome, a
condition that is generally considered a less severe form of
autism, remains little known, but the number of diagnoses has
soared since psychiatric authorities formally defined it five years
ago. Recent survey data suggest that under some definitions as many
as 1 in 500 people have the condition, higher than the estimate for
classic autism. By John O'Neil. (1925 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-MEMORY (Undated) _ Heralding an era that will blend
the speed of the microelectronic world of silicon with the
permanence of the magnetic world of computer disks, a group of
I.B.M. researchers said last week that they had successfully
designed the building blocks of a new kind of computer memory that
could fundamentally alter computer design early in the next
century. Chips based on this new technology, known as tunneling
magnetic junction random access memory, or tmj-ram for short, would
be ultrafast, consume very little power and retain stored data when
a computer was shut down. By John Markoff. (1050 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RNA (Undated) _ New theories on how life might have
originated on earth involve RNA, not DNA. By Nicholas Wade. (800
words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BALICK-ETHNOBOTANY (Undated) _ Conversation With Dr. Michael
J. Balick, an ``ethnobotanist'' who is director of the New York
Botanical Garden's Institute of Economic Botany. He has traveled
the world exploring relationship between plants and people: the
foods that people eat, the spices in their foods, the medicines
they use, and how people manage their resources, forests, farm
lands. By Claudia Dreifus. (1625 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BALLOONISTS (Undated) _ Successful balloon that went around
the world will be donated to the Smithsonian. By Malcolm W. Browne.
(500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Shorts on science: Items on Uranus's
seasons, red glows known as sprites in electrical storms and using
electricity in the ground to reduce contamination. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LAUNDRY (Undated) _ Laboratory scientists are tackling the
rigors of the domestic battlefield known as the washing machine.
The goal is to eliminate a common laundry-day disaster, when a
washerful of white clothes is forever tinted by one colored item
that, like a rogue agent, has infiltrated the load. By Henry
Foruntain. (740 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: At
least a third of high school seniors have been drunk and heavy
drinking even occurs in junior highs and middle schools. Binge
drinking remains a serious problem on college campuses. But surveys
indicate that parents can play the biggest role in shaping the
children's drinking habits. By Jane E. Brody. (1150 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIVER-TRANSPLANTS (Undated) _ In some cases, people are
dying because HMO's are basing medical decisions on the science of
the '70s, not what's known today. Specifically, HMO's and state
governing agencies have neglected to update guidelines on liver
transplants for people with hepatitis, because in the early phases
of liver transplants, recipients with the disease could not
survive. But that changed years ago, while guidelines did not. By
Holcolm B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INTERNET-PRESCRIPTIONS (Undated) _ Prescribing drugs, like
Viagra and Propecia, on the Internet is creating a whole set of
problems and regulatory agencies are unsure what to do. By Lisa
Napoli. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TELEMEDICINE (Undated) _ The practice of telemedicine, in
which patients sit at home in front of computerized machines that
monitor their body functions, is increasing around the country and
proponents say it may actually cut costs and increase the medical
attention a patient receives. By Eric Nagourey. (970 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FIBROID-TUMORS (Undated) _ A new, minimally invasive
operation for shrinking fibroid tumors by blocking their blood
supply is becoming an increasingly popular alternative to surgery,
even though it is not yet an established treatment. By Susan
Gilbert. (1175 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Four minutes of exercise four times a week for fitness is the
claim of a company selling a new device. Two studies give
conflicting results of its effectiveness, but most major exercise
experts dismiss the device. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ The American Academy of Pediatrics has begun recommending that
all infants be checked at birth for hearing loss. In a statement
issued in February, the academy said that prompt diagnosis of
hearing problems can help offset lapses in language development.
(350 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ For people wanting the have the millennium's first baby, April
9 is the day, say experts say. But others acknowledge it's simply a
crap shoot. (275 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ New research confirms that boys overestimate their academic
ability, while girls underestimate it. It also shows that the gap
widens and suggests that depression may be the root of the girls'
lack of esteem. (350 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: Why is your
blood type _ A, B, AB or O _ so important? The most basic
classification of the hundreds of ways to type human blood, the ABO
system, is important because incompatible types of blood react with
each other to form sticky globs of red blood cells that can cause
serious and sometimes fatal circulation blockage. (300 words)
</P>
