<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JOURNAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    LETTER FROM PODGORICA: A SMALL COUNTRY STEWS AS IT WAITS FOR A
COUP
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Montenegro, Yugoslavia By almost any definition this
tiny Balkan republic should be a trivia question, meaningless to
much of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you are a buff of alpine mountains, rugged Adriatic
coastline or Slavic history, you should never have heard of
Montenegro. It is sparsely populated, has a meager economy, no
major industries and a small army.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro is a vague spot on the map, but a potentially
dangerous one.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of place that now has combat-ready troops
standing watch in front of the president's office and frequent
police roadblocks throughout the capital to inspect who is coming
and going.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing belief in Podgorica, and among Western
intelligence agencies, is that a coup or civil war could be the
by-product of the NATO-Serb conflict next door. ``If we start to
kill each other here, it will make Bosnia look like a playground,''
a senior government official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The tension is palpable. After a unpleasant brush Sunday night
with some pro-Serb men in the street, I and another American
reporter had reason to believe we were in danger. An unreassuring
Yugoslav soldier told our translator: ``No one will kill them in
Montenegro _ not for now at least.''
</P>
<P>
   First, a bit of background, and more about that incident later.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro is a multi-ethnic nation that sits next to Serbia and
serves as its junior partner in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
It has 680,000 people, not enough to classify it as a major city in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Self-governing Montenegro has been a troublesome little brother
to Serbia and the regime of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
It has become cozier with the United States and Western Europe and
aspired to make itself more democratic and less a part of
post-Communist Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Serb troops rampaging throughout Kosovo and NATO
warplanes hitting Yugoslavia, the overwhelming concern among
Montenegrans is that Milosevic will work his destructive talents on
them.
</P>
<P>
   The concern centers on federal troops ostensibly loyal to
Milosevic and stationed in Montenegro. They number between 12,000
and 30,000, depending on whose estimate you believe, and last week
they got a new commanding general handpicked by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that Milosevic wanted to dispatch more troops prompted
U.S. peacekeeping forces in Bosnia on Saturday to blow up the
railroad tracks that run between Podgorica and Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The federal troops in Podgorica have become increasingly
prevalent and provocative in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials privately report that there have been
almost daily instances of gun-pointing and hard words between the
army troops and police forces loyal to Milo Djukanovic, the
reform-minded president of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   At the information ministry here, there exists a sheet listing
the names of various news organizations. It is not a sign-up sheet
for interviews. It is a tally of correspondents looking to retrieve
cars and equipment that have been confiscated by Milosevic's
federal troops.
</P>
<P>
   On the street, anti-American sentiment is soaring. The first few
nights of the NATO bombing, military targets within Montenegro were
hit, including the airport near the capital. It has agitated
pro-Serb sentiment here, making it all the more difficult for the
Western-leaning government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is Hitler,'' a sales clerk hissed at me in a store
last week. I offered a handshake to a man in a cafe on Sunday
morning; he refused and threatened to hit me.
</P>
<P>
   A Washington Post correspondent with whom I'm traveling could
not make a international call from the apartment we have rented
here. As on previous nights, he took his portable satellite
telephone to the parking lot to get a clear signal.
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers in the neighborhood have been fascinated by the
technology and eager to practice their rough English on us between
the calls we make on the small, battery-powered telephone.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday night, two angry men joined the crowd. They were
convinced we were spies with sophisticated targeting equipment to
help NATO jets hit their targets. They spoke fiercely, motioning
their index fingers across their necks. One of the men took the
cord of the telephone and began making a noose to place around my
colleague's neck.
</P>
<P>
   We retreated to the apartment, only to be informed by one of the
teenagers whispering through a window that the men were back with
20 army troops outside our building.
</P>
<P>
   The incident underscores the problem here amid NATO's airwar and
Milosevic's ``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo: Montenegro does not
know who to trust. People here seem angry at everyone, but most of
all at their own inability to manage their fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montenegro above all needs peace and time,'' said Srdan
Darmanovic, head of Montenegro's Center for Democracy and Human
Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro: the little country that just wants to be left alone.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
