<HEADER>
A6535 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRYNICHOLS-2NDTAKE-     04-05 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRYNICHOLS-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 (PICK UP AFTER: other state agencies, Macy said.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kight said she doesn't believe a jury in Oklahoma could judge
Nichols or McVeigh fairly. Macy says he is convinced otherwise,
though he will not fight a motion to move the trial out of Oklahoma
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been four years. And you take the city of Tulsa, for
instance,'' Macy said. ``I don't think there's anyone from Tulsa
killed in the bombing. Right now, if you were to interview people
from nearly anywhere else in the state as to what they know about
Terry Nichols, their knowledge of the case is very limited. They
don't know what evidence was presented against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Macy agrees the case will be stressful and difficult to
prosecute. Nichols was not in Oklahoma the day of the bombing, but
federal prosecutors said he was clearly responsible _ plotting the
attack, stealing and buying items to build the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   One of the strongest pieces of evidence against Nichols was a
receipt for a ton of ammonium nitrate fertilizer (an ingredient in
the killer bomb), which was found in his kitchen drawer with
McVeigh's fingerprint on it.
</P>
<P>
   But jurors in the federal trial said that their first vote had
been 10-2 for acquittal, fueling 41 hours of argument before they
agreed on a verdict. And when they could not agree on punishment,
that handed the decision to the judge who was barred by law from
assessing the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm doing the right thing,'' Macy said. ``That's
the main thing I'm concerned with.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Heath, a psychologist and bombing survivor, said he's
already counseling survivors and family members to get them over
the emotional hump of the upcoming state trial. The support group
that he leads is planning a meeting next week to talk about the
trial process, as well as guilt, forgiveness and punishment _
including capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial process is a worry because you've invested so much
of your life working for the federal government, then so much of
your life since reconfirming that you'd made the right decision to
work for them,'' Heath said. ``You take a deep breath and say, `I
will not be defeated by this next trial.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I don't think I want to go through that again,''
Williams said. The assistant building supervisor at the time of the
bombing, he testified at both federal trials that anyone surveying
the outside of the building would have been aware of the
second-floor day-care facility because the children's artwork was
pasted to the glass and the children, themselves, were frequently
visible.
</P>
<P>
   He fears he would be subpoenaed again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know those were important but difficult times,''
Williams said. ``I was a basket case _ this big old tough guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh, we've come so far,'' he added. ``We've done so many
things. I've seen improvement in family members and survivors since
the last trial. I've seen them turn loose of that and do what they
needed for their loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the trial is a year from now, how rough is it going to be
as the anticipation builds during that time, he wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know those emotions are still out there.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
