A6534 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NICHOLS-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      04-05 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICHOLS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(EDITORS: MARSHA KIGHT CQ) &HT;    
 &HT;    HIGH COST: MANY FEAR ANOTHER TRIAL FOR NICHOLS WILL ONLY REOPEN
EMOTIONAL WOUNDS
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By KIM COBB 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Richard Williams stood a few yards away from the
blasted footprint of the old Murrah Building, watching bulldozers
shape the scorched earth into a memorial to the people who died
here.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   But when the first stage of the memorial opens next spring, the
state of Oklahoma will likely be taking bombing conspirator Terry
Nichols to court again. Oklahoma County District Attorney Bob Macy
last week filed 160 first-degree murder charges and three other
related charges against Nichols, who is already serving a federal
life sentence after his conviction in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In this city, where nearly everyone has some sort of connection
to a victim or survivor of the April 19, 1995, bombing, people are
divided over the wisdom of retrying Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a General Services Administration supervisor who
narrowly survived the blast and testified against Nichols and
bomber Timothy McVeigh, thinks another trial is just going to tear
open emotional wounds that were finally beginning to heal for some
people.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Kight, who lost her 23-year-old daughter in the blast, is
thinking about moving away from Oklahoma City to escape the pain
that one more trial will only make more sharp for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only speak for myself,'' Kight said. ``I've been through
enough mental anguish. Life in prison (for Nichols) is enough. The
toll it will take on people ... My question is, will it really be
worth the cost?''
</P>
<P>
   Patty Hall, a Murrah Building credit union worker who spent
weeks in a coma after the blast, said she felt that way, too, at
first. But she visited the graves of nine co-workers last Memorial
Day, and it changed her perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a peaceful thing we did, but it was more disturbing to
me later on,'' Hall said. She began to agree with people who felt
cheated that the federal charges against Nichols and McVeigh had
named only the eight federal law enforcement officers killed in the
blast _ not the other 160 people who died in and around the
building that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``So for me, let's just go ahead and have the trial,'' Hall
said. ``This will be for all the survivors and family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then that door is closed. It doesn't mean closure, because you
don't get over this. But you've got to get on with your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Macy has been roundly criticized for the cost and the redundancy
of retrial. But he said he did not foresee the emotional toll that
retrial would take on his community, because he made the decision
to prosecute those responsible for the crime when the bomb went off
April 19, 1995. His resolve was strengthened when the federal jury
convicted Nichols only of conspiracy and involuntary manslaughter
and did not assess the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   An Oklahoma City newspaper conducted an informal poll of its
readers shortly after the Denver jury handed down its verdict. Even
though he had not been formally sentenced, it was clear Nichols
would not be executed _ and only 20 percent of those who
participated in the poll favored bringing either Nichols or McVeigh
back to their home state for retrial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I don't have any choice,'' Macy said. ``It's my
duty to do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has not decided whether he will pursue state charges
against McVeigh if he has not been executed by the time Nichols'
trial is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Macy said Oklahoma County has already filed the paperwork to
transfer Nichols back to Oklahoma City to await trial, and expects
the transfer will be made within a couple of months. The state
Legislature has earmarked $800,000 for the trial, and the cost of
additional security for Nichols will be shouldered by other state
agencies, Macy said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
