<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAPPY-PILL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPLEMENT OFFERS A HEALTHY BOOST LIKE NOTHING ELSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHIL DAVIS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Joints a little achy these days? Feeling
depressed? Maybe your liver could use a little extra help defending
itself against a daily onslaught of toxins?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy'' may be your new best friend.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy is the nickname of SAM-e _ short for S-adenosylmethionine,
a compound produced by all plants and animals that is crucial to
dozens of metabolic processes, including joint tissue repair, liver
protection and the brain functions that control mood.
</P>
<P>
   SAM-e supplements have been popular in Europe for two decades,
but the compound just last month found its way onto the shelves of
American supermarkets and drugstores. Chemical giant BASF Corp.
released it on the growing U.S. dietary supplement market earlier
this month, the first so-called ``nutraceutical'' from the company
best-known for producing magnetic tapes. It will be marketed under
individual labels such as GNC and Nature Made.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say SAM-e is no snake oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of doctors come up to me and say no one thing can do so
much, but it can, and it's very well documented,'' said Dr. Richard
Brown, associate professor of clinical psychiatry at Columbia
University in New York City. ``The nicest thing about SAM-e is it
works as well as standard prescription medications, but it has less
side effects and it works faster, so people feel better sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Animals produce SAM-e from the essential amino acid methionine
energy-yielding compound adenosine triphosphate. As it breaks down,
the compound is involved in the synthesis, activation and
metabolism of biological compounds such as neurotransmitters,
proteins, cell membranes, detoxification, and even nucleic acids in
DNA. SAM-e is required in more than 35 biochemical reactions in the
body, and researchers continue to find new interactions.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, SAM-e helps a variety of cells work better.
</P>
<P>
   But as we age, researchers found, SAM-e levels in our blood
decrease, which can lead to depression, joint aches and a decline
in the liver's ability to defend itself against toxins such as
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Since its discovery in 1952, European doctors have studied SAM-e
and found it can improve the mood of depressed patients by
improving brain cell function and boosting production of mood
enhancers seratonin and dopamine. SAM-e also gives the liver a
boost in its defenses because it is the main source of glutathione,
the liver's cleaning agent. Other studies found that SAM-e helps
preserve and repair cartilage, shock absorbers in joints that keep
bones from grinding against each other and causing pain.
</P>
<P>
   Because SAM-e is natural, there are few side effects. Some users
complained of nausea or mild gastrointestinal disturbances, but
Brown said people taking placebos in studies often complained more
than those who took SAM-e.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact it has very few, if any, side effects makes it
attractive to many people because there is really no harm in taking
it,'' said Dr. Teodoro Bottiglieri, director of neuropharmacology
at Baylor University Medical Center in Dallas. ``It can be taken as
a general enchancer of health.''
</P>
<P>
   The body gets its supply of SAM-e from methionine, which is
found mostly in protein-rich foods. A deficiency of methionine,
vitamin B12 and folacin can affect the body's ability to produce
SAM-e.
</P>
<P>
   But, Bottiglieri said, ``You can't get SAM-e just by eating
certain foods.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also one big catch: the price. A 10-day supply of 20
pills will cost about $25. And although SAM-e works within a couple
ofweeks, Brown said that when it is used to treat depression, it's
best to take it for six to nine months or risk a relapse.
</P>
<P>
   SAM-e isn't for everyone. People suffering from bipolar disorder
_ also known as manic depression _ should consult their doctor
before taking SAM-e because it may push them toward the dangerous
manic side of the illness, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   He advised taking SAM-e supplements only for specific problems,
such as mild depression or joint pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can take a gazillion supplements a day if they want to,
but it really works best if you take something targeted to a
problem you have,'' he said. ``People should not take supplements
without a clear reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Another risk: Consumers will see SAM-e as some kind of magic
bullet that can reverse the biological clock or protect the liver
from abuse. Doctors stress that a balanced diet and regular
exercise are still the ultimate key to peak physical and mental
health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is not to do anything in excess,'' said Jay Rho, an
associate professor of clinical pharmacology at the University of
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   And that includes overdosing on SAM-e.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything in moderation is probably OK. When you get into large
dosages, that's where you get into trouble,'' Rho said. ``Sometimes
people think if a little bit helps, a lot helps faster, and that's
just not true. Even with prescription anti-depressants, the cure
takes quite a bit of time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
