<HEADLINE>
SEE WHAT DISNEY ONLINE HAS ACHIEVED 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Note use of italics throughout; ``last week'' is CQ)  
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ken Goldstein spent 10 years helping first
Broderbund, then its spinoff Red Orb create award-winning games
such as the Carmen San Diego series and Riven.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when Broderbund was bought up last summer, Goldstein got a
call from Jake Winebaum, the head honcho of Walt Disney's Internet
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   When Goldstein, who lived outside San Francisco, said he might
consider a new job, Winebaum invited him to dinner in Los Angeles.
That night.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein hurriedly caught a plane and has been busily
transforming Disney Online as its general manager and senior vice
president virtually ever since.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see what Goldstein's been up to the past six
months _ and if you're a parent, gamer or animation buff, you
definitely should _ mosey over to Disney Online at
www.disney.go.com, where they unveiled a major site overhaul last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest and most overdue change is a merger of Disney.com
with the separate subscription-based Disney Blast premium site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot more frequency (of use) because, by taking two
worlds and merging them into one world, we've given them a lot
more,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   You can find areas devoted to the Disney Channel and its heavily
trafficked Zoog Disney area, Radio Disney, movies, cartoons,
trivia, archival animation and much more.
</P>
<P>
   To keep customers coming back, Disney Online has added or
expanded wrinkles such as instant messaging, Disney-themed e-mail,
animation archives, online-store discounts, parental controls,
multiplayer games and access to the company's myriad
entertainment-related ventures, such as travel booking.
</P>
<P>
   Though many areas will be accessible to any visitor, the
subscription-based Club Blast will provide access to the
instant-messaging, store discounts and some other premium services
at $5.95 a month or $39.95 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll start everything in the club, then roll it out to the
rest of the areaafter 60 to 90 days,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said a new emphasis will be put on community, just as
is happening with other major sites on the Internet (memo to
Internet buzzword watchers: portal is passe; community is in).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about community, friendship and family play,'' Goldstein
said. ``It's now about how you, your family and friends can
share.''
</P>
<P>
   That means, for instance, that games such as Mickey's Bingo will
not only allow you to play bingo but chat with up to 23 other
players at the same time. The game areas will even include canned
taunts to hurl at other players.
</P>
<P>
   Just as with the larger Go Network's emphasis on parental
controls, the site will allow parents to decide who their children
will be able to communicate with while on the site, whether it's in
game/chat areas, the instant-messaging service or e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   But the whole idea is to let children and adults play with
others, safely.
</P>
<P>
   The networked universe ``is forcing us to rethink the experience
of playing computer games,'' Goldstein said. ``This whole notion of
playing games against computers is really artificial. It's like the
difference between going to Disneyland alone and going to
Disneyland with your friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Magazine for WebTV types
</P>
<P>
   When new Internet users hop online, they're much more likely to
look for an entertainment site or e-mail a pal than are the Net
vets who preceded them, according to a recent study.
</P>
<P>
   Also, more than 1 million people already own some sort of
interactive television box, be it WebTV types or any of several
miscellaneous providers who have married a TV with Internet access
and are much more likely to use it to access TV-related Web sites
while watching their shows.
</P>
<P>
   And when AT&AMP;T and America Online put their marketing muscle
behind their respective versions of interactive TV later this year,
the number of people with those merged TV/Internet boxes will
likely skyrocket.
</P>
<P>
   And that, Phillip Swann contends, is why it's the perfect time
to come out with a magazine devoted to this particular
technological union. The magazine is TV Online, based in Santa
Monica, and Swann is its editor, publisher and vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our vision is that this is going to be in every home within
five to 10 years,'' Swann said. ``Where this thing will really
start to take off is when cable providers bring it into the home.''
</P>
<P>
   The 64-page glossy magazine aims to be a cross between
Entertainment Weekly and Wired. It debuted modestly in January and
still is available only by subscription through its small Web site
at www.tvonlinemag.com.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to a trial-subscription deal given to all buyers of
Sony's WebTV box, the newborn monthly can already claim a hefty
300,000 subscribers, good design and relatively punchy articles
with a bit (though more would be better) of critical edge.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine includes the Web sites and links for the month's
notable TV programs, movies, home videos, DVDs, pay per view, CDs,
sporting events, even books. There are relatively penetrable
technical articles, lots of short reviews of general entertainment
sites and a page of all the links used in the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   For the terminally twitchy, major stories come complete with an
estimated reading time and one-line description of the story's
content (so much for old media tricks like headlines and lots of
graphics).
</P>
<P>
   But there's plenty there for the entertainment obsessed.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the piece (by former Daily News TV critic Ray
Richmond, a contributing editor to the magazine) on ABC News'
history series ``The Century'' includes a terrific collection of
history Web sites beyond ABC's rich online home for the show, along
with four short reviews of other (BEGIN ITALICS)fin de siecle(END
ITALICS) sites.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the talk of convergence, don't count on finding much
at the magazine's own Web site, at least not soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically a billboard,'' Swann said. ``With many people,
the Internet is a whole new thing. They're looking for something
more traditional to help them get online. For us, we think
(focusing on the magazine) works really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Pray for NYC
</P>
<P>
   Those peripatetic publishers, the Mad Monks James Crotty and
Michael Lane, are back at it, with a new, offbeat guide to New York
City that is equal parts travelogue and social commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Crotty and Lane have traveled the country in a pink motor home,
publishing Monk magazine from it for most of the decade now, using
a solar-powered Macintosh computer to compose stories about the odd
and offbeat things they've seen on their jaunts.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, they started a Web site at www.monk.com, and even
cut an unlikely deal last year with Playboy.com as an associated
site. And then there are the books, with the latest a delight for
those who prefer to look at Gotham's unvarnished underside.
</P>
<P>
   What's most interesting about ``The Mad Monks Guide to New York
City'' (published by Macmillan Travel), however, is how positively
ambivalent our favorite friars sound about the city. Oh, they still
find plenty to rhapsodize about in the city's quirks and
characters, sites and scenes.
</P>
<P>
   But the relentless efforts of Mayor Rudy Giuliani, the NYPD and
the Walt Disney Co. to make New York safe for even the gape-jawed
rubes amongst us seems also to have dulled the city's edge a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have the Big Mouse and the Grimacing Hunchback taken a
bite out of the Big Apple's Times Square porn parlors and
street-corner con men, their attitude also seems to have gone and
cleaned up much else in the city, even stuff that was better when
it was dark and grimy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to hear the Monks tell it, Hell's Kitchen is at best
Purgatory's Patio, SoHo is so-so, and the Lower East Side has been
``thoroughly tamed and claimed,'' then festooned with concept bars
designed to ``woo twenty-somethings eager for that antiseptic
downtown thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Monksters welcome the Giuliani-related drop in crime and
give him and the boys in blue their proper due.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anarchy had its day,'' they write. ``The city is becoming
something different. Safer, cleaner, more hospitable.''
</P>
<P>
   But there may be a cost, they also moan, that won't be fully
known for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``... After years of knocking on the door, mainstream America
has finally broken into the city,'' they write. ``Here comes
everybody _ and with their arrival, there goes a lot of what made
New York (BEGIN BOLD OR ITALIC)New York(END BOLD OR ITALIC). Call
us nostalgic, anti-growth or simply out of touch, but we think what
is currently happening to the city is tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   Dismayed by the chain megastores, the Monks went looking for
``the funky, frumpy, eccentric New York of old. Our prognosis, at
the end of our search, is a qualified mix of doom and delight.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for people who think New York is at least fun to visit,
they've detailed all here. Check it out next time you point that
jet plane East.
</P>
<P>
   (To reach David Bloom with stories, tips and other information
on the intersection of art, entertainment and technology, e-mail
him at davidbloomearthlink.net, or call (818) 713-3678).
</P>
</TEXT>
