<SLUG> BC-MISSING-PHYSICIAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ALL MISSING PERSONS CASES GET EQUAL TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Three days after the disappearance of three
women visiting the Yosemite National Park, a Santa Clara doctor
vanished in California's ski country.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Carole Sund, 42, her daughter Julie Sund, 15, and
family friend Silvina Pelosso, 16 has generated international
attention.
</P>
<P>
   But few people have heard about Dr. Katherine Wong, who
disappeared while skiing Feb. 19 about 167 miles north of where the
three sightseers were last seen. After a three-day sweep through
Bear Valley, the Alpine County sheriff's office called off its
search-and-rescue effort for Wong on Feb. 21. Her case is open, but
unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   There is no multistate hunt. No hot line. No Web site. No
brochures. No national television coverage. No big headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities insist they are giving her case appropriate
attention. ``We're waiting for the snow to melt,'' said Bob Tucker
of the Alpine County Sheriff's Department. ``We have no idea where
she is. We've checked the area in the ski resort where she was in
very thoroughly.''
</P>
<P>
   Wong's case is similar to many missing persons cases. In
California along, more than 150,000 people are reported missing
each year. More than 95 percent of those reports are runaways,
children taken by noncustodial parents or adults fleeing personal
or financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   But of the cases suspected to be abductions by strangers, very
few generate enough attention to make the victim a household name.
</P>
<P>
   These little-known cases contain the pain and heartbreak of
loved ones, but the tragedies are not played out in the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends what catches the imagination and interest of the
news media and then the community,'' said Deborah Brady, a case
manager with the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children
in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all hear about cases like Polly Klaas that are picked up by
the media. But there are similar cases that don't get so much
attention. And the parental abduction cases and the runaways who
are at risk for exploitation are very, very hard to get any media
exposure at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady also notes that if a loved one disappears, you can't count
on news coverage or public support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen cases where 15-year-old girls with no history of
running away, no known problems, who disappeared without taking any
belongings, even her contact lens case, and the local newspapers
told parents to take out an ad,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators who specialize in missing persons cases note that
many times children or married adults want to be lost. For better
or worse, they are fleeing unhappy circumstances. And the custodial
parent doesn't always want the child back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are parents who have said, `If you find him, I don't
want him,''' said Officer Patrick Mahanay of the police missing
persons unit in Oakland, Calif. ``Sometimes these kids are such a
handful for the parents that if the kid runs away it's not that big
a deal for the parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually the message is expressed more subtly, but to
investigators it's clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people fill out a report, but you can tell they don't
really want to find the person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sund/Pelosso case, Francis and Carole Carrington, Carole
Sund's parents, have spared no effort _ and no expense _ to resolve
the case. They set up a command post in Modesto and have been
joined by hundreds of volunteers who are willing to help them find
their loved ones or cope with their grief.
</P>
<P>
   The Carringtons have shown steadfast willingness to keep the
story in the news.
</P>
<P>
   It's not completely clear if developing a network of supporters
and aggressively courting the news media help to solve a crime or
return a loved one safely. In October 1993, Polly Klaas was killed
several hours after she was kidnapped from her Petaluma home by
Richard Allen Davis. The cases of the Sund family and Christina
Williams, who was abducted last year while walking her dog near her
family's Monterey-area home, much of the public effort came after
the victims were likely dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately in these cases they are almost never found
alive, they are murdered like Polly or Christina,'' said Ann Deasy
Collins, the mother of a missing child. ``I can't think of many
times where an abducted child has come home safely in these
cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins knows firsthand that the giant team effort associated
with the search for a missing loved one comes with its own rewards.
Her son Kevin Collins, 10, disappeared while waiting at a bus stop
in San Francisco on Feb. 10, 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Kevin remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't find Kevin but the support of the community is a
blessing in disguise,'' Collins said. ``It really helps you get
through this. It takes pressure off the police department.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are now many groups that help parents when their children
are abducted or loved ones disappear mysteriously. There are
toll-free numbers, Web sites and training manuals for volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   But back in 1984, that infrastructure wasn't available for the
Collins family. They built it themselves. It started with fellow
parishioners at St. Agnes Roman Catholic Church using maps that Ann
Collins' brother obtained from his job at the California Department
of Transportation. Once the story was featured in the news, the
effort grew exponentially. For the next couple of years, brochures
with Kevin's face were on the windows of businesses throughout the
San Francisco area.
</P>
<P>
   Even people with little knowledge of the case saw Kevin's
familiar image on milk cartons. His parents formed the Kevin
Collins Foundation, which helped to channel the energy and efforts
of volunteers in a series of high-profile child abductions in the
late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts of parents like those of Kevin Collins also have
changed the way law enforcement looks at these cases. By law, the
police are required to investigate all cases of missing persons.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, authorities will say that all cases are investigated
the same. Privately, many veteran officers concede that in certain
cases authorities do little more than write a report, search a few
databases and send a bulletin as a reference for other police
departments in case a body turns up elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a horde of volunteers comes to us and says, `What can we do
to find this kid?' you can bet our chief is going to see that and
put more resources on the case,'' said a veteran missing persons
investigator who asked not to be identified by name or law
enforcement agency. ``The flip side is that if the family or
community doesn't do that much, then maybe there are other cases we
should be spending our energy on, more promising cases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
