<HEADER>
A6570 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHATTUCK-HNS &LR;      04-05 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHATTUCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE APRIL 5, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (EDITORS: NO www CQ IN WEB ADDRESS) 
 
MAKE TRAVEL PLANS NOW, AND YOU'LL SAVE CASH LATER 
 
 &HT;    By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Just as it signals a need for spring cleaning, April's arrival
serves as a reminder to get our travel agendas in order.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wait until the last minute to assess priorities,
formulate budgets and plan and schedule vacations too often find no
cheap seats aboard an airplane, no affordable rooms at a hotel and
an expired passport buried in a dresser drawer.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few tips that could help avert disappointment:
</P>
<P>
   Can't decide whether to visit Hollywood, Dollywood, the Big Bend
or Big Apple? Schedule a family get-together to discuss potential
destinations. Make an honest assessment of each traveler's
objectives. Don't be shy about expressing candid opinions, and
listen to those of others. Carefully evaluate the pros and cons,
and you may avoid friction later.
</P>
<P>
   Establish a budget. A vacation should be one of the year's most
satisfying experiences; you work hard and deserve a good time away
from home or the office, and it's also an excellent occasion for
family bonding. But your enjoyment will be marred if you spend
every minute fretting about how each expenditure will affect the
bank account once you return.
</P>
<P>
   Make a practical assessment of your finances. If you can afford
to follow your dreams to Paris or Rome or take that
long-anticipated cruise in Alaska, go for it. But if circumstances
dictate that those adventures wait another year, schedule the car
for a tuneup and get ready to explore nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Still on the budgetary fence? Consider ways to make your
vacation money go further.
</P>
<P>
   Order free brochures from tourism bureaus. The literature you
receive just by making a few calls (often toll-free) can help in
finding affordable lodging, dining and attractions. Many brochures
describe hotel packages and multiple-attraction passes, and some
include coupons.
</P>
<P>
   Now is a good time, too, to check any frequent-flier accounts
you may have. Unused mileage in some airline programs expires after
a stipulated period; you may want to redeem mileage for your next
vacation rather than risk losing it. Or if you are 10,000 miles shy
of earning a free trip in Continental's OnePass program but have
earned 11,000 miles in the American Express Membership Miles
program, study the transfer rules and consider taking action. Seek
out other ways _ grocery shopping, telephone services, flowers for
a loved one _ to pad those mileage totals. And remember:
Frequent-traveler award seats are limited and fill up fast,
especially during the summer. Don't tarry before making a
redemption request.
</P>
<P>
   Those who don't rely on frequent-flier miles should evaluate air
fare trends to preferred destinations. We've already witnessed two
fare hikes on standard domestic tickets this year. And we had the
usual short-term winter sales. Some analysts believe we'll witness
one more sale before the peak travel season. But if you wait until
June to buy a ticket for air travel in July, chances are good
you'll pay a premium. Booking in advance is usually wise, too, for
hotels, rental cars and cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Don't rule out travel by train or bus. Amtrak and Rail Europe
offer cost-saving passes. So do bus lines.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers who remain open-minded about destinations normally
reap the best bargains. An exchange rate of $1 U.S. to $1.50
Canadian makes travel north of the border a good bargain. Because
of the financial crisis in Asia, packages to many parts of that
continent also cost much less than in recent years. Likewise, since
Asian tourism is down in Hawaii, a concerted effort is under way to
attract more visitors from the U.S. mainland, resulting in
discounts. Continued introduction of mammoth new cruise ships is
keeping prices down for seagoers, especially in the Caribbean. A
travel agent can provide details and recommend other bargain
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   International travelers should make sure passports remain valid
and necessary visas are secured. If you need to renew a passport,
act soon; the heaviest processing period is almost upon us.
Applications can be downloaded via the Internet by accessing
travel.state.gov. Call 900-225-5674 for passport information; a
per-minute charge is assessed.
</P>
<P>
   One final thought: Any discussion of vacation plans likely will
include at least some consideration of millennium-related events.
Do we cut back on summer travels so we can usher in 2000 with a
binge? Obviously, this is an individual or family choice. Just be
aware that most travel in late December will come with an inflated
price tag. And since the real turn of the century doesn't occur
until 2000 gives way to 2001, it's a safe wager that another round
of millennium bashes will tempt us a year later.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
