<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6576 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-GARDENS-ART-2T     04-05 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-GARDENS-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAGRANT BLOSSOMS DRAW TRAVELERS TO FORMAL GARDENS AROUND THE
WORLD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: TRAVEL-TEXAS) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
and SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever the destination, our spring travels are frequently
brightened by colorful floral displays.
</P>
<P>
   Even on short drives to visit family or friends, we cherish the
annual outpouring of flowers beside U.S. highways. The annual
outpouring of bluebonnets, Indian paintbrush and yellow coreopsis
dot Texas roadsides.
</P>
<P>
   For some travelers, more formal gardens represent a major focus
of vacationing from Alabama to British Columbia, California to the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   These are among gardens we've enjoyed during recent travels.
Most are year-round attractions, but spring is an especially good
time to visit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BELLINGRATH GARDENS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Located a short drive east of Mobile in Theodore, Ala., the
Bellingrath Gardens and Home encompass 65 landscaped acres in a
semitropical setting.
</P>
<P>
   The gardens were created in 1917 on the private residence of
Walter Bellingrath. During the Depression in 1932, Bellingrath
opened the gardens to the public, and they remain one of the
nation's premier floral attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Azaleas, which began blooming in March, are complemented this
month by lilies, pansies, tulips, snapdragons, impatiens,
geraniums, dogwood and fuchsia baskets. The season's first roses
also appear in April; 130 varieties are showcased by June. A
late-autumn highlight is the world's largest outdoor chrysanthemum
display.
</P>
<P>
   Walkways shaded by centuries-old trees encourage leisurely
exploration. Benches are strategically placed for respite and views
of lovely lakes, pools and brooks. Don't miss Rustic Bridge,
bedecked with flowers. The entire area is wheelchair-accessible.
</P>
<P>
   The Bellingrath home, situated on the banks of the Fowl River
and dating to 1935, is notable for its antique furniture and
European porcelain. Another enticement is a 45-minute river cruise
on the 150-passenger Southern Belle.
</P>
<P>
   The gardens are open daily from 8 a.m. until one hour before
dark. Home tours begin at 9 a.m. River cruises operate hourly from
10 a.m. to 4 p.m. in April and May, then at 11 a.m., 1 p.m. and 3
p.m. from June through November.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $13.95 for adults and $9.95 for children ages 5-11;
this includes entrance to the gardens and a guided home tour or
river cruise. Several driving routes lead from Mobile to
Bellingrath Gardens; from Interstate 10, take Exit 15A and follow
the signs.
</P>
<P>
   Call 334-973-2217 for more information. Access
www.bellingrath.org on the Internet. For information about other
Alabama attractions, call 800-252-2262 or access
www.touralabama.org
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Flower Fields &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each spring, hundreds of families, many dressed in their Sunday
best, make a pilgrimage to the Flower Fields in Carlsbad, Calif.,
for the ultimate photo opportunity. Picture-perfect poses put
family members waist-high in spectacularly colored blooms.
</P>
<P>
   The most predominant blooms at the Flower Fields are giant
ranunculus in a rainbow of colors, including golden yellow, vivid
orange and a creamy white.
</P>
<P>
   Also grown here are the spiky blazing star (``Tritonia
crocata''), the ruffley gladiolus, the star-shaped harlequin
(``sparaxis''), watsonia (``Watsonia pyamidata''), the purple
baboon flower (``Babiana stricta''), the towering Adam's rib
(``Chasmanthe floribunda'') and the lovely blooming shamrock
(``oxalis'').
</P>
<P>
   The commercial flower ranch owes its beginnings to the Frazee
family, which has been cultivating ranunculus in California since
the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   When the family moved its operations to Carlsbad in northern San
Diego County in 1958, the 50 acres of brilliant spring color
grabbed the attention of motorists traveling between San Diego and
Los Angeles on Route 101. Drivers often would stop for a closer
look, and a tradition was born.
</P>
<P>
   The Flower Fields, now owned by the Paul Eckes family, are in
full bloom for about six weeks each year beginning in early March.
By the time the season ends in early May, the fields will have
received about 200,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The fields are open 10 a.m.-dusk daily. Admission is $4.
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent to the Flower Fields is Carlsbad Company Stores, an
outlet shopping center with galleries and restaurants. Carlsbad
also is the site of Legoland, the spanking-new theme park that pays
tribute to the tiny plastic bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Call the Flower Fields at 760-431-0352 or access
www.theflowerfields.com. For general tourism information about
California, call 800-862-2543 or access www.gocalif.ca.gov.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Biltmore Gardens &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to upstage a Victorian mansion with 101 bedrooms and
65 fireplaces, but the Biltmore Gardens in Asheville, N.C., does
just that.
</P>
<P>
   The gardens were designed for George Washington Vanderbilt's
country home in 1890 by Frederick Law Olmsted, the landscaper
behind New York's Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   When Vanderbilt purchased the 125,000 acres that made up the
original Biltmore Estate, the land had been deforested and
overfarmed. Olmstead met the challenge with planned woodlands,
fields and gardens. A highlight of a garden tour is the four-acre
English walled garden with its formal touches and 236-foot-long
grape arbor. In the spring, this garden is ablaze with daffodils,
hyacinths and tulips. Classic statuary, manicured lawns and three
symmetrical pools are the focal points of another visitor favorite,
the Italian Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Olmstead's naturalistic landscaping also includes an azalea
trail, pools and a lagoon. Birders and other nature lovers find
spring an ideal time to explore Biltmore's meadow and woodland
trails.
</P>
<P>
   The Biltmore recently kicked off its Festival of Flowers with
the reopening of the steel-and-glass Conservatory, which underwent
a two-year, $2 million renovation. The Conservatory is home to many
exotics including ferns, cycads and orchids. The Festival of
Flowers, which runs through May 2, celebrates the return of spring
blooms such as daffodils, snowdrops and azaleas. Each day, the
festival presents special events such as barbershop quartet
performances and fashion shows.
</P>
<P>
   The Biltmore Estate is open 8:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. seven days a
week, except for Thanksgiving and Christmas days. Admission is
$29.95 ($22.50 for children) and includes a self-guided tour of the
first four floors of the Biltmore House and a self-guided tour of
the grounds and gardens. The Biltmore Estate also includes a
winery, three restaurants and several retail shops.
</P>
<P>
   Call 800-624-1575 or access www.biltmore.com. For general
tourism information about North Carolina, call 800-847-4862 or
access www.visitnc.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BUTCHART GARDENS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These spectacular 50-acre gardens, situated just outside
Victoria on British Columbia's Vancouver Island, originated in 1904
through an effort to beautify a worked-out quarry site on the
estate of cement manufacturers Robert and Jennie Butchart.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a century later, 1 million visitors annually enjoy the
floral beauty, entertainment programs and an excellent restaurant
near the gardens' entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Tulips of every imaginable color dominate in spring. Japanese
flowering cherry, dogwood, magnolia and crabapple trees are at
their prettiest. By next month, lilacs, azaleas and rhododendron
will begin peaking. The Rose Garden, which includes 2,500 plants of
250 varieties, is especially bountiful from July through September.
</P>
<P>
   Paved walkways connect all areas; elevations vary, so some
gradual ascents (and descents) are required, but paths without
stairs are available for visitors in wheelchairs. Allow time to
admire ever-changing ``dancing fountains'' amid the flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Summer evenings are especially festive. June 15-Sept. 5, the
gardens remain open until 10:30 p.m. and are illuminated by
thousands of lights in dozens of hues. Beginning June 29, musical
revues are scheduled Mondays-Fridays just prior to dusk. Fireworks
displays occur Saturday nights July 3-Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission charges vary depending on the season and number of
blooms. Current adult admission is only $8 Canadian, or about $5.35
U.S. Peak-season admission (June 15-Sept. 15) is about $10.35 U.S.
for adults, $5.20 U.S. for ages 13-17 and $1.35 U.S. for children
5-12.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria is accessed by ferry from near Vancouver on the British
Columbia mainland or from Seattle. Butchart Gardens is located 13
miles (about a 20-minute drive) north of downtown Victoria. Bus
transportation is available and advised in peak season. The gardens
open at 9 a.m. every day including holidays. Closing hours vary.
</P>
<P>
   Call 250-652-4422 for more information. Access
www.butchartgardens.bc.ca/butchart on the Internet. Call
250-953-2033or access www.tourismvictoria.com for information about
Victoria. Call 800-663-6000 or access www.travel.bc.ca for
information about other British Columbia attractions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
KEUKENHOF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For two months each spring, this 80-acre floral paradise in the
Netherlands becomes the unofficial tulip capital of the world. And
celebrating its 50th birthday this year, Keukenhof, which opened
March 25, expects to welcome almost 1 million visitors before
closing May 19.
</P>
<P>
   Situated in Lisse, about an hour's drive from Amsterdam (and
also accessed by public rail and bus or on a group tour),
Keukenhof's fields are covered with 6 million tulips, narcissus,
hyacinths and other flowering bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 1,000 varieties of tulips comprise one-half of the total
plantings, and the color combinations are so astonishing that
Keukenhof ranks among the most photographed places in the world.
New bulbs are used every year so that designs and color
combinations can be changed; some gardens are themed according to
color, fragrance and style.
</P>
<P>
   It's wise to allow most of a day here to wander about on wide,
paved walkways (all wheelchair-accessible). Signposts identify each
variety of tulip. Rest stops include numerous benches and open-air
(and indoor) dining facilities placed throughout gardens that are
accented by ponds, statues and fountains.
</P>
<P>
   On rare rainy spring days Keukenhof features 10 changing indoor
expositions and flower-arranging demonstrations in three indoor
pavilions. Periodic indoor shows focus on orchids, roses,
daffodils, lilies and other flowers.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the birthday celebration, the park also will host
Zomerhof, a first-ever summer flower show Aug. 19-Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Keukenhof by car from Amsterdam, take the A4 motorway
toward The Hague and exit on N207 toward Lisse. Train information
is available at all rail stations.
</P>
<P>
   Keukenhof is open daily from 8 a.m. until 7:30 p.m. through May
19. Admission is about $9 U.S. for adults, with 50 percent
discounts for children under age 12. Call the Netherlands Board of
Tourism at 212-370-7360 for more information. Access
www.keukenhof.nl or www.goholland.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CYPRESS GARDENS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Long before Walt Disney World and Universal Studios were even
imagined, this tropical paradise in Winter Haven, Fla., was billed
as Florida's first theme park. Created by Richard Pope 63 years
ago, Cypress Gardens continues to appeal to a wide range of
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Its botanical collection includes more than 8,000 varieties of
plants and flowers from 90 countries. Each plant is labeled by name
and nation, and paved walkways make observation enjoyable and easy.
</P>
<P>
   Another popular feature is a series of miniature theme gardens
whose emphasis is education. Learn about various floral scents,
cultivating roses, natural Florida designs, and fruits and
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Within a large butterfly conservatory, visitors walk among more
than 1,000 butterflies in free flight representing more than 50
species from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Seasonal floral festivals are a highlight: The current spring
extravaganza, which continues through May 15, is the world's
largest topiary show of its kind. Each topiary is decorated with
begonias and other flowers to create more than two dozen animal
formations. Adjacent floral beds feature 35,000 impatiens, salvia,
dusty miller, marigolds, celosia and begonias in varying colors.
</P>
<P>
   Cypress Gardens' famed water-ski shows remain a tradition. Also
offered are paddlewheel boat rides, weekend concerts, educational
programs and children's rides and games.
</P>
<P>
   Cypress Gardens is located off U.S. 27, about 22 miles south of
Interstate 4 between Orlando and Tampa. Hours are 9:30 a.m.-5 p.m.
(later on some holidays and special occasions). Regular admission
is $33.87. Seniors 55 and older pay $28.78; ages 6-17 pay $15.85.
The grounds are wheelchair-accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Call 941-324-2111. Access www.cypressgardens.com (and check this
Web site for ticket discounts available only online). For
information about other Florida attractions, call 888-735-2872 or
access www.flausa.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CALLAWAY GARDENS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 4,000 hybrid and native azaleas are just coming into
their peak at Callaway Gardens in Pine Mountain, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway Gardens is a 14,000-acre horticulture resort where the
focus is on beauty, relaxation and inspiration. In addition to
greenhouses, gardens and miles of showcase trails and roadways, the
resort also offers a man-made white-sand beach, a tennis center and
four golf courses, seven restaurants and lodging ranging from hotel
rooms to four-bedroom villas.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of a visit include the Cecil B. Day Butterfly Center,
the largest glass-enclosed butterfly conservatory in North America,
and Mr. Cason's Vegetable Garden, which produces more than 400
varieties of vegetables, fruits and herbs. The latter often is
showcased on PBS television's ``The Victory Garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Opened to the public in 1952, Callaway Gardens continues to
grow. New this year is the Callaway Brothers Azalea Bowl, a 40-acre
azalea garden that also spotlights Japanese iris, hemlock, holly,
witch hazel, maple, dogwood, camellia and grancy greybeard.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway Gardens is located about 60 minutes southwest of
Atlanta and is open daily. Admission to the gardens is $10 ($5 for
children). Call 800-225-5292 or access www.callawaygardens.com. For
general tourism information about Georgia, call 800-847-4842 or
access www.gomm.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HODGES GARDENS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Touted as the largest privately owned botanical garden in the
United States, Hodges Gardens occupies 70 acres amid a forest along
U.S. 171 about 15 miles south of Many, La., between Lake Charles
and Shreveport and not far from the Texas border.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 years ago, conservationists A.J. and Nona Trigg Hodges
spearheaded efforts to transform an abandoned stone quarry into
formal gardens while taking advantage of the area's unusual rock
formations.
</P>
<P>
   The gardens, situated on three levels, now feature year-round
blooms, with the spring focus including tulips, roses, pansies and
flowering magnolia and dogwood trees. Exotic tropical plants are
maintained in greenhouses and a conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding the gardens are a wildlife refuge, 10 miles of
hiking trails, a 225-acre trophy bass fishing lake and picnic
grounds. Tent camping and full-service RV parking are available.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges Gardens is open from dawn until dusk except on Christmas
and New Year's days. Admission is $6.50 for adults, with discounts
for seniors 55 and older and children. Most of the garden area is
wheelchair-accessible. Call 318-586-3523. For general tourism
information about Louisiana, including hundreds of festivals
scheduled this year, call 800-633-6970 or access
www.louisianatravel.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ An excellent resource to learn about 300 of the best gardens
in North America _ as diverse as the National Arboretum in
Washington, D.C.; the Betty Ford Alpine Gardens in Vail, Colo; the
International Rose Test Garden in Portland, Ore.; and the Maui
Tropical Plantation in Hawaii _ is the ``National Geographic Guide
to America's Public Gardens'' (National Geographic Society, $25).
Area bookstores stock or can order the 384-page publication.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
