<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fitness: 4 Minutes And $600 Later
</P>
<P>
   Promoters of a hot new exercise machine make a profound claim: a
four-minute workout that really works.
</P>
<P>
   The assertion comes in an infomercial from Time Works for a $600
device that works the upper and lower body with twisting and
stepping motions. Though such a less-is-more approach _ four
minutes, four times a week _ seems hard to fathom, the Time Works
infomercial and Web site prominently feature an as yet unpublished
study conducted at Adelphi University in Garden City, N.Y.
Researchers compared increases in fitness levels of two sedentary
groups of subjects who worked out four times a week. One group
exercised for 4 minutes per session on the Time Works machine and
another group exercised for 20 minutes per session on a treadmill
with an upper body component.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of six weeks, the researchers said, the four-minute
Time Works exercisers increased their aerobic fitness levels by an
average of 12.5 percent compared with the 20-minute treadmill
group's 9.7 percent improvement. Researchers also reported
decreases in waist circumference measurements in the Time Works
group but not in the treadmill group.
</P>
<P>
   Unbelievable? Many prominent exercise researchers are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``However appealing in concept,'' said Dr. David Neiman,
professor of health and exercise science and director of the human
performance lab at Appalachian State University, ``you cannot
improve cardiovascular function, gain significant health benefits,
or lose a meaningful amount of weight by doing four minutes of
exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own study published in the American Council on Exercise's
magazine Fitness Matters, Neiman found that a four-minute Time
Works session did not provide sufficient exercise to help build
heart and lung fitness or positively affect general health over the
long term.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Robert Otto, Adelphi's lead researcher, defends his
study, which he plans to present at an American College of Sports
Medicine conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' he said, ``quite a few studies have shown that
short duration activity can have a positive impact on fitness,
especially in deconditioned individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers have bitten. Since being released in 1998, Time Works,
produced by Quantum Fitness Corp. in Stafford, Texas., and
distributed by E4L, has racked up more than $60 million in sales.
Most experts stand by the college of sports medicine's
recommendation of 20 to 60 minutes of moderate intensity aerobic
activity four to six times a week for improved health, weight loss,
increased stamina and protection from disease.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Glenn Gaesser, associate professor of exercise physiology at
the University of Virginia, helped formulate the sports medicine
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now,'' Gaesser said, ``I don't think we have enough
evidence to tell people they can get by with four minutes of
exercise a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Pediatricians Urge Hearing Tests at Birth
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics has begun recommending that
all infants be checked at birth for hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued in February, the academy said that prompt
diagnosis of hearing problems could help offset lapses in language
development.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing impairment in infants can cause delays in speech,
language and cognitive development, said Dr. Philip Ziring, the
chairman of the academy's Committee on Children With Disabilities.
Often, hearing loss is not diagnosed in children until they are 2
to 3 years old and are not speaking properly, Ziring said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if hearing loss is detected early enough, babies can be
fitted with hearing aids or watch others use sign language, said
Dr. Barbara Herrmann, an audiologist at the Massachusetts Eye and
Ear Infirmary and an assistant professor of otology and laryngology
at Harvard Medical School. ``Children learn language by exposure to
language. And without some kind of exposure, it's hard to catch
up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing loss is more frequent than other disorders now tested at
birth, Dr. Herrmann said. Hearing impairment occurs in 4 of 1,000
births, yet screening is required in only 10 states. Meanwhile,
babies are routinely checked for the metabolic disorder
phenylketonuria, or PKU, which occurs in one 1 of 16,000 births.
</P>
<P>
   Screening for hearing is non-invasive and painless. One test
evaluates hearing by measuring the vibration of the small hair
cells in the cochlea when exposed to sound, and the other uses ear
cuplets over the baby's ears and sensors on her head to measure
brain response to sound. Ideally, infants are tested while they
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real challenge to pediatricians is insuring follow-up
testing and making sure these kids end up in early treatment
programs,'' Ziring said. ``You have about three to six months to
get it right. These tests can help prevent a lot of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   1/1/00 Baby Race: Push for 12:01 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   It is a date that has already crept into millennium folklore:
Friday, April 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big date,'' is what Dr. Amos Grunebaum, director of
maternal-fetal medicine at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital in
Manhattan, calls it: the theoretically ideal date for an egg to be
fertilized to produce a baby born at 12:01 a.m. on 1/1/00.
</P>
<P>
   Motels have offered special rates for that night, television
stations have sought to recruit couples for millennium baby
contests and a Web site, is offering a Millennium Baby package,
which for $49.95 offers a book of advice, a pregnancy test, candles
and massage oil. The Web site is www.babycenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   There are only two problems with the April 9 countdown, said
Grunebaum, whose own pregnancy information Web site,
www.babydata.com, offers a Conception Calculator complete with tips
on what sexual positions to try for a boy or girl. (``50 percent
serious and 50 percent fun,'' he allowed.) The first is that the
date is based on a theory that almost never works in practice. By
obstetrical convention, due dates are calculated by counting 266
days from the date of ovulation. In practice, ``only 5 percent of
women who have a due date will deliver on that specific day,'' he
said. ``It's a crapshoot.''
</P>
<P>
   The second obstacle is a misconception of where the window of
opportunity lies.
</P>
<P>
   If a woman ovulates on April 9, then her chances of becoming
pregnant are the highest between April 5 and April 9; the odds that
sex on April 10 or 11 will produce a baby ``are nearly zero,''
Grunebaum said.
</P>
<P>
   He Thinks He Can, He Thinks He Can
</P>
<P>
   Studies in recent years have shown that boys tend to
overestimate their academic abilities, while girls tend to
underestimate them. Now, researchers from the University of Notre
Dame have tracked the growth of that gap and suggested a cause.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published in March in the journal Child Development,
psychologists tracked 807 students, half starting in third grade
and half starting in sixth, for three years. They were periodically
asked to assess their own academic abilities and express their
anxiety or depression. Their teachers' assessments were collected
for comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Self-confidence, even when misplaced, the researchers wrote, can
be a powerful force for success: ``Believing that one is competent
or capable of handling a particular task can be highly motivating,
even when it is not true.'' In first and second grades, earlier
researchers found, most students give themselves high marks. At the
start of the third grade, Notre Dame researchers found only a small
gap between boys and girls in the accuracy of their ratings.
</P>
<P>
   But from then on, an increasing number of boys thought better of
their skills than their teachers did; the number of girls who were
overly harsh on themselves increased at roughly the same rate.
Emotional measures were similar: depression grew among girls and
fell among boys. Anxiety levels for girls remained almost constant,
but fell among boys after third grade.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the researchers focused on anxious and depressed students
and found that boys and girls in this group were equally likely to
underrate their skills. This led them to conclude that the gap in
self-esteem was largely explained by the higher prevalence of
emotional troubles among girls.
</P>
<P>
   They also concluded that the girls' depression was the likely
cause of their low self-esteem, and not vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the researchers said, it may be important to try to
determine why so many girls are unhappy.
</P>
</TEXT>
