<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIAN SKI TOWN STRUGGLES TO RECOVER FROM AVALANCHE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Udiaeresis symbols, or two dots, are needed over u in Galtur
and u in Kitzbuhel.) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALTUR, Austria _ It's a brilliant afternoon. The thermostat
reads 30 degrees, but the temperature feels more like 50 as the sun
transforms the Alps into one enormous mirror ball. At an outdoor
cafe, skiers have peeled away layers of clothing and now strike
poses like turtles on a pond, necks outstretched and noses pointed
toward the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Having arrived too late to ski and too early to begin the apres
ski rituals, I settle on a walk around the village.
</P>
<P>
   So this is Galtur. The only images I know of this village are
the graphic newspaper and television accounts I saw a few weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 23, a devastating avalanche pushed Galtur into the world
spotlight. It was one of more than a dozen slides in the European
Alps that have left 80 people dead since January. Galtur's
avalanche killed 31, including six of this village's 701 residents.
</P>
<P>
   This visit in mid-March is coincidental, just one of four stops
long planned on a whirlwind Austrian tour. Galtur was to be a
small-town contrast to metropolitan Innsbrook, glitzy St. Anton and
romantic Kitzbuhel.
</P>
<P>
   After watching on television the rescue efforts _ both
successful and not _ I had given much thought to re-routing this
trip, a research project for future travel stores. The
recommendations coming from my Austrian-specialist travel agency
were to go to Galtur. The agents compared the slides to a Caribbean
island that is visited by a tropical storm. Within days, they
assured, all the tourist facilities would be up and running.
</P>
<P>
   I had my doubts. Would I get a true impression of this town as a
tourist destination?
</P>
<P>
   I hop aboard one of the free buses that stops right outside
Galtur's visitors center. The buses connect a series of communities
spread along stunning Paznaun Valley, which is located so high that
it can hardly be called a valley. In the winter, it is more like a
fold in the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   My destination is Wirl, an assortment of hotels, guest houses,
cafes and some of the area's 10 ski lifts.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few minutes' drive from Galtur, Wirl is a flurry of
activity. Ski school is in session, and the bunny slopes are
hopping. Across the street, the more skilled skiers and
snowboarders are laughing and loading onto a lift called the
Birkhahnbahn.
</P>
<P>
   At the far end of the ski area's parking lot, I find some of the
most dramatic reminders of the past weeks' events: a dozen gnarled
cars, their bent interiors still packed with snow.
</P>
<P>
   I decide to walk back into town on a snow route that parallels a
cross-country ski trail. Galtur boasts nearly 28 miles of tracks
for skiing and winter walking. What should be a 20-minute walk
becomes an hourlong adventure as I make frequent stops to study the
surrounding peaks.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to deduce the path of the killer avalanche and the
smaller slides that shook this community. In places, the mountains
have completely sloughed their snow. The 8,202-foot Adamsberg
Mountain, which spawned the killer slide, seems pure in afternoon
sun.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not alone in my gawking. Carload after carload of sightseers
eases past spots of ruin. Some cars are equipped with ski racks as
if this Saturday-afternoon rubbernecking is just part of a spring
holiday. Others clearly have made the drive from the big cities for
a look at the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   While the lifts here are running again, most of the dozens of
hotels and guest houses advertise rooms to let. Little signs with
beds posted outside each establishment describe the units
available, while an electronic board outside the tourist office is
ablaze in green lights. A red light would signal a full house, but
there are no red lights this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   These signs of the time are not good, says Gerhard Walter.
</P>
<P>
   Chatting over a cup of coffee in a cozy, sun-splashed corner of
the Post Hotel's lobby, Galtur's director of tourism is concerned
for his home town. March traditionally is the village's busiest
month, but bookings, not surprisingly, are down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, we are 95 to 100 percent full,'' Walter says of
March, ``but only about 5 percent of the lodging is booked now.''
</P>
<P>
   Galtur, along with the other valley communities such as Wirl and
Mathon, count about 3,800 beds spread among its hotels, guest
houses and rental apartments. Last year, the city welcomed about
300,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a miracle, that number is out of reach this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a pity for us because in the last four or five years,
we've been able to build up tourism even when other places had bad
seasons,'' Walter says. ``Tourism was growing here by 5 to 10
percent each year. Our opinion is that that kind of steady growth
(because of the avalanches and the media coverage) is finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter's pain of the past few weeks is still palpable as he
tells of the relief help supplied by Austrian military personnel.
The military had completed its clean-up efforts and left town just
the day before my arrival, Walter says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tourism is not the major industry in Galtur,'' Walter says,
``It is the only industry.''
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of the village's visitors come in the winter, a
season that spans five months (December through April). Summer
tourism is only about three months, Walter explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to finish this season in a serious way. And then we
have to think over everything,'' Walter says. ``Now everything is
too fresh. We need to get a distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Distance always has been a theme for Galtur. The hamlet is both
plagued and blessed by its remoteness.
</P>
<P>
   It is a three-hour drive from Munich, Germany, or Zurich,
Switzerland, the closest major airports. And despite the village's
steady growth in tourism, U.S. travel agents have yet to embrace
Galtur.
</P>
<P>
   Walter admits that Americans account for less than 1 percent of
its tourist numbers. In the long run that also may be the key to
Galtur's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   This valley is the least Americanized. No fast food and no
phoniness, Galtur offers a Tyrolean experience that is genuine and
welcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Walter describes it as both family oriented and familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've been here once, you feel familiar,'' he says. ``It
is good to go to a place where you feel at home. You know the
innkeeper, you know the cafe owner. A ski village should have a
relaxing atmosphere. It should be a relaxing holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   During a TV report on Galtur's tragedy, an Austrian expert
concluded that avalanches are just a way of life for those who
choose to live so far up the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a way of life also can be a way of death.
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of the slides this year, thousands of tourists and
residents in western Austria had been essentially cut off from the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   My last afternoon in Galtur, I feel cut off from the world. No
English-language papers are to be found. My guest-house room is
without a TV, and even my watch has stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The waning hours are measured by the ring of the church bell,
which sounds every half-hour. In tiny Galtur, you're never out of
the range of the church's bells.
</P>
<P>
   Walking past the church, I admire the bell tower, a dainty spire
rising above wooden chalets. I am taken by the soothing afternoon
light that soaked the building until my eyes fall upon six wooden
crosses protruding from the church courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   Slipping and sliding on an icy walk, I carefully climb the hill
to the courtyard entrance as the bells begin to chime again. This
time, it is not the hours being announced, but a twilight song for
the faithful. The song is long; and now standing directly under the
source, my heart clangs with each note.
</P>
<P>
   I trudge through slushy snow, straddling patches of ice, to
reach the back of the small courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   The six graves are fresh and piled with flowers and greenery
just past their prime. The dates on the crosses are all the same:
Feb. 23, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about Galtur or any other destination in
Austria, access www.anto.com or
www.austria-tourism.at/index.html.en or call 212-944-6880.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
