<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT TEXAS GARDENS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: TRAVEL-GARDENS) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are some pleasing Texas gardens:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lady Bird Johnson Wildflower Center in Austin. Ecological
concepts and the beauty and value of native flora are celebrated at
the Lady Bird Johnson Wildflower Center, founded by the former
first lady in 1983. One of the center's most interesting components
is its Home Comparison Garden, which features two landscaped
gardens. One showcases common non-native grass, trees, shrubs and
flowers; the other is designed with native grasses and plants. Both
plots are carefully monitored for their ecological soundness,
maintenance costs and appeal.
</P>
<P>
   With the blooming of colorful wildflowers such as bluebonnets
and Indian paintbrush, spring is a busy time for the center.
Special events include a photo festival April 24, Earth Day and
Arbor Day celebrations April 25 and an arts festival May 22 and 23.
Located at 4801 La Crosse Ave., the wildflower center is open 9
a.m.-5:30 p.m. daily, except Mondays. Admission is $4 ($2.50 for
children).
</P>
<P>
   _ Dallas Arboretum and Botanical Gardens. The 66-acre botanical
collection boasts 33 acres of formal gardens, including one of the
largest azalea collections in the country. Also of interest is the
intimate Woman's Garden. The Dallas Arboretum, located at 8525
Garland Road, is open 10 a.m.- 6 p.m. daily. Admission is $6 ($3
for children). Call 214-327-8263.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moody Gardens in Galveston. Tropical and subtropical plants
such as hibiscus and crotons are the focus of the 242-acre Moody
Gardens, which includes restaurants, a hotel, a rain forest with
tropical birds and butterflies, and a white-sand beach. Fees and
hours vary. Call 800-582-4673 or access www.moodygardens.com on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ San Antonio Botanical Gardens. Just a short drive from the
bustling River Walk, these gardens are one of the Alamo City's
unsung delights. A favorite is the fragrant and texture-rich Garden
for the Blind. But a word of warning: The striking glass-domed
conservatory is miserably hot in the summer. The botanical gardens,
located at 555 Funston Place, are open 8 a.m.-5 p.m. Admission is
$4 ($1 for children). Call 210-207-3250 or access www.sabot.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tyler Municipal Rose Garden. Discover the meaning of petal
power at the Tyler Municipal Rose Garden, which features more than
400 rose varieties spread across its 14 acres. While most Texas
gardens peak in the spring, the Tyler garden hits its prime in
October when the city hosts its popular Rose Festival. This year's
festival is Oct. 14-17. But you don't have to wait until fall to
enjoy this garden: Roses bloom throughout the summer, and the
garden, located in Rose Park, also features camellia and daylily
displays. It's open daily; admission is free. Call 903-531-1212.
</P>
<P>
   _ Zilker Botanical Garden in Austin. Popular Zilker Park's
60-acre botanical garden includes a terrific collection of cactus,
rose and herb gardens. But the highlight is the serene Taniguchi
Oriental Garden, named for the Japanese-American who at age 77
spent 18 months creating a living gift to the city of Austin.
Located at 2200 Barton Springs Road, the gardens are open 9 a.m. to
dusk daily. Admission is free. Call 512-477-8672.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
