<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERNOBYL-`GRAVE'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST ALARMED BY PLANS TO BURY CHERNOBYL REACTOR  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This intriguing 475-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By STEVE CONNOR  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An ambitious plan to bury the crippled Chernobyl nuclear reactor
in a giant hole more than half a mile deep has been proposed by a
group of Ukrainian research centers.
</P>
<P>
   They have suggested digging a one kilometer-deep hole next to
the nuclear power plant and letting it ``fall in'' in a controlled
manner before covering it up and sealing it with layers of rubble
and concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Western experts have reacted with alarm to the idea, which is
being put forward by four respected research institutes in the
Ukraine with the support of leading figures within the Ukrainian
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Since the accident in April 1986, which sent plumes of
radioactive material across Europe, Chernobyl's stricken reactor
Number 4 has been encased in a concrete ``sarcophagus,'' which has
since showed signs of becoming unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Western nuclear engineers brought in to advise the Ukrainian
government have suggested that the sarcophagus _ which was built in
a hurry just six months after the accident _ should be replaced or
strengthened so it would last another 100 years, by which time much
of the radioactivity inside would have decayed.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian plan put forward two years ago to create a giant
monolith by filling the entire sarcophagus with concrete was
abandoned after safety assessments showed there was a hidden risk
from missing nuclear fuel believed to be still inside the building.
</P>
<P>
   Now some Ukrainian scientists have openly criticized the Western
plan, believing that the foreign grant of $758 million will end up
being spent on Western firms and consultants rather than Ukrainian
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they want Ukrainians to dig a giant grave for the
sarcophagus which would be big enough to bury the 50-story tower
block at Canary Wharf, the biggest building in Europe, and still
have room to spare.
</P>
<P>
   The Kryvbasproekt Institute in the Ukraine is leading the idea,
which also has the support of the Ukrainian Scientific Center for
Environmental Radiochemistry, the Mining Construction Institute and
the Institute of Construction Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Dmytro Hrodzynskyy, a member of the Ukrainian Academy of
Sciences, says in the magazine ``Nuclear Engineering
International'' that geological research in the region will assess
the risk of ground water contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Academy of Sciences will be performing some drilling next
year to study the issue. We should not forget earthquakes
either...But we have to support this idea in general, it is very
promising,'' Hrodzynskyy said.
</P>
<P>
   Emlen Sobotovych, another academician who backs the proposal,
said the Western plan of strengthening the sarcophagus envisages
removing the radioactive contents gradually.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four reactors at Chernobyl, only one is still working and
that is due to be shut down next year when the power plant is
scheduled to stop producing electricity for the Ukrainian national
grid. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 475-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
