<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6602 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ASPERGERS-SYNDROM     04-05 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASPERGERS-SYNDROME-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: services offered. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, many doctors give a diagnosis of nonverbal
learning disorder because it qualifies a student for more help,
said Ms. Fling, who lives in Hamilton Township, N.J. In Texas,
children with Asperger's are often labeled high-functioning
autistic for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment is usually a mix of speech and occupational therapy
combined with behavioral training focused on social skills, Dr.
Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Volkmar called the overall goal using childrens' strengths _
intelligence and verbal ability _ to overcome their deficits.
Judith Rivkin, the mother of a Manhattan 9-year-old with
Asperger's, Sam D., described the process as breaking down behavior
that most people master without thinking into discrete fragments
that can be learned by rote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of practicing what you could say,
practicing taking the other person's point of view,'' Ms. Rivkin
said. ``Things like, `Do I have to look him in the eye?' `Yes, but
just a little bit to let him know you're listening.'''
</P>
<P>
   Many parents have found music and pets helpful. Ms. Willey
called music a ``salvation'' in her own childhood. ``When you're
really obsessing on something, it's as if music makes something
click, and gives your brain permission to say, `Ah! I can float
away on this!'''
</P>
<P>
   Adolescence is particularly hard for children with Asperger's.
Many teachers find it hard to believe that a bright student who is
disrupting class is not doing it on purpose, Volkmar said. Until
recently, that often meant that students with Asperger's were
lumped in with aggressive students in special classes for
troublemakers, a practice that he said amounted ``to putting the
perfect victims in with the perfect victimizers.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam S.' mother, Lori, has dealt with the trauma of teasing both
with her son and as president of Aspen Inc., a New Jersey group
that offers support to parents in the New York region. ``Because
our kids are so bright, they have a lot of self-awareness. They're
aware that the thing is to blend in, and that they don't _ and that
can lead to depression.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Adam's district has assigned him a ``shadow'' aide,
who helps guide him away from inappropriate behavior as well as
keep him working smoothly in his mainstream classes. And his recent
victory in his school's geography bee is the kind of positive side
to his intense focus that his family and teachers can use to help
bolster his self-esteem. ``I was very worried about his starting
middle school,'' his mother said. ``But it's turning out to be his
best year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Adam sometimes comes home crying, frustrated by his
inability to connect. Volkmar recalled one teen-ager with the
syndrome who tried to translate emotions into equations and offered
to give up a watch that was his prize possession if he could get a
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   But children can be helped to connect. Ms. Rivkin said her son
has ``learned to have friends and to care about his friends.'' He
recently gave a rundown on his classmates ``all about how he likes
her, but she doesn't like him, and how this one likes me,'' and
wrapped it up by declaring ``and that's the Love Report!''
</P>
<P>
   Even adults who have overcome the most isolating elements of
Asperger's say they still struggle with the consequences of things
like having a poor grasp of what to say _ or not to say _ when.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people tell me I'm just a little weird,'' said Ms.
Willey, who has published a memoir, ``Pretending To Be Normal.''
``Other people think we're quirky and cute. Well, our quirkiness
keeps us from getting jobs, from making friends, keeps us on
antidepressants. We're screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Kirby, the creator of an Internet resource site for
Asperger's called the Oasis, said she gets messages regularly from
adults who hear a description of the syndrome and think it matches
them. Dr. Bristol-Power said many people receive diagnoses as
adults, but cautioned that the label could easily be overapplied.
``Where do you draw the line between a syndrome and diversity of
personality types, which you want?''
</P>
<P>
   The active role on the issue being taken by some adults with
Asperger's has made a push for greater acceptance for
``non-neurotypicals'' a central goal. David Spicer, a North
Carolina computer programmer who received an Asperger's diagnosis
at the age of 46 in 1994, says he is often asked if he wishes he
could be cured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if there's my autism, and then there's me,'' he
said. ``I don't exist separate from my autism.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Willey's daughter with Asperger's, Meredith, 8, is well
aware of the difficulties Asperger's imposes, from recognizing word
sounds to being easily overwhelmed by the bustle of a mall. But she
sees another side as well. ``When I find something I like, like
horses and Shakespeare and Winnie the Pooh,'' she said, ``I like
them a whole lot more than other people like their things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
