<SLUG> BC-SCI-RESEARCH-SECRECY-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN PRIVATE MONEY MEANS SECRET RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ In the old, Cold War days, when gathered
university scientists would turn to complaining about how secrecy
strictures sometimes kept them from sharing their work, they
usually meant pesky national security restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   These days, they tend to mention non-disclosure agreements,
worldwide patent rights, royalty streams, intellectual property
fights _ in a word, money. And all the commercial hindrances to
open science carried by the powerful wave of private capital that
has been washing into the country's research universities in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   The strings that often come with private research money _ the
publication delays while patents and profits are pursued, the
proprietary findings _ hold the pernicious potential to impede the
free exchange of information that speeds scientific progress,
speaker after speaker warned last week at a conference on ``Secrecy
in Science'' held by the American Association for the Advancement
of Science and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, private research financing is also undeniably good
for scientific progress, many noted, from the biotechnology
companies' bankrolling academic gene research to the start-ups
owned by professors who work that much harder in the hope of
getting rich.
</P>
<P>
   At MIT, one official said, private capital has gone from paying
for about 5 percent of research 15 years ago to nearly 25 percent
today. But, conference organizers worried aloud, at what price?
They called for a national dialogue to explore just how much the
secrecy requirements imposed by private finance cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commercialization of science,'' said Irving A. Lerch,
chairman of the science association's Committee on Scientific
Freedom and Responsibility, ``has resulted in a new regime of
secrecy which is very concerning to the scientific community,
something which we have to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the scientific enterprise _ which depends
greatly on its own control, on its openness and exchange _ and the
need of our commercial patrons to recover their investment, those
create tensions that are tremendously important.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern over the commercial influence on science is not new, but
the advent of the biotechnology era seems to be bringing it to a
head. Compared with other industries, biotechnology companies rely
very heavily on academic work for the scientific underpinnings of
their products.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, said Robert Cook-Deegan, director of the
National Cancer Policy Board, private investment in health-related
research surpassed the public money put into it, and biotechnology
companies report that about a quarter of them are heavily dependent
on academic research, and another quarter are somewhat dependent.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, said Nelson Y.S. Kiang, a professor emeritus at MIT, the
committee ``has come across a number of cases that all had the same
characteristics: someone had a scientific result that he or she was
enjoined from making public because it went against the interests
of a third party, either government or a commercial business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These were not aberrations,'' Kiang continued. ``It looks like
this is a pattern which is built into our social institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Among cases brought up at the conference was that of Dr. David
Kern, a Brown University occupational health specialist who
described the pressure he encountered not to publish his findings
of a new, potentially fatal occupational lung disease he had
identified among workers at a local textile company that had hired
him as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Kern had signed no scientific non-disclosure agreement, he said,
but the company insisted that he had and pressured his employers,
Memorial Hospital in Pawtucket, R.I., and Brown University, to
silence him. After Kern published anyway, his employers dissolved
his program, Rhode Island's only occupational health center, he
said, and barred him from treating the company's employees. They
also eliminated his tenurelike position. His contract with Memorial
was not renewed, and will run out in three months.
</P>
<P>
   Also attending the conference and put forth as a cautionary
example was Dr. Nancy Olivieri, a researcher at the University of
Toronto and the Hospital for Sick Children in Toronto. She recently
received a settlement and was reinstated by her employers after a
three-way dispute between her university and a Canadian drug
company, Apotex, Inc., over the publication of her studies of a new
drug for thalassemia, a genetic blood disorder.
</P>
<P>
   A third case was that of Dr. Betty Dong, a pharmacy professor at
the University of California at San Francisco whose research showed
that generic thyroid drugs worked as well as their brand-name
equivalents.
</P>
<P>
   Because she had signed a confidentiality contract with the drug
company that financed her work, Boots Pharmaceuticals, it took
almost seven years for Dr. Dong's results to be published in a top
medical journal. In that time, the paper's authors estimated,
Americans could have saved about $365 million a year by using the
cheaper generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The behavior of universities and scientists is sad, shocking
and frightening,'' said Dr. Drummond Rennie, another committee
member, who described Dr. Dong's case and the University of
California's failure to defend her. ``They are seduced by industry
funding and frightened that if they don't go along with these gag
orders, the money will go to less ethical institutions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists pointed to other, subtler dangers. What, for
example, of the incentive for professors who need research money to
gear their work toward areas with the greatest potential commercial
applications, rather than the greatest inherent scientific worth,
in hopes of attracting corporate sponsors? And what of the
temptation to sign contracts with sponsors all but giving away the
shop, by, say, long delaying publication?
</P>
<P>
   A study by Massachusetts General Hospital policy analysts of
more than 2,000 life-sciences researchers published in 1997 found
that about 20 percent reported having delayed publication of their
results for more than six months, or not publishing at all, mainly
because of their relationships with private sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Although the study in the Journal of the American Medical
Association said the withholding of data was less than widespread,
it said it had affected a significant number of faculty,
particularly the most productive and entrepreneurial.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with money, Alan Hartford, a
Massachusetts General Hospital research fellow, told the
conference, but ``what we must guard against is the loss of
professional values.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another, strong side to the issue that emphasizes the
good that is done by private money: studies have found that
professors with private financing publish more, teach a bit more,
and serve more as department chairs and journal editors. Indeed,
when this topic has come up in science publications, there has been
a solid chorus of voices from professors who say they see private
money as an overwhelming good, and feel unconstrained by the
agreements they negotiate with companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the Massachusetts General report also found that privately
financed researchers kept more secrets, and were three times as
likely as non-commercial professors to delay publication and to
deny colleagues access to their data.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, said Martin Michaelson, a lawyer specializing in
representing universities, the academic world seems to be divided
into two types of professors, one doing largely unappreciated
research without much funding, the other a kind of academic
rainmaker who brings in industry money and becomes ``a reigning
prince.'' And the problem, Michaelson said, is that ``they are
often not talking to each other.'' And frequently when such
entrepreneurial professors do talk about their work, they want to
reveal only enough to titillate potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, too, said Charles M. Vest, MIT's president,
is that the boundary between science and technology is increasingly
blurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``And because technology frequently is tied directly to
commercial interests,'' he said, ``it presents an even fuzzier
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what to do? Proposals varied, from calls for faculties and
administrations to defend information flow more vigorously, to more
concrete suggestions that universities refrain from taking equity
positions in companies or rein in professors tempted to sign what
they should not.
</P>
<P>
   Lita L. Nelsen, director of MIT's Technology Licensing Office
described one kind of clampdown. Sometimes, she said, ``faculty who
need money to do research to get tenure have to be told, `You
cannot sign that agreement; we will not honor it.'''
</P>
<P>
   She said she had the general impression that there was a
``drifting tide,'' at work, the attractive force of money, and not
enough of a counter-force. Maybe, she said, the conference would
get that countervailing force going.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wonderful,'' said Howard K. Schachman, a
biochemist at the University of California at Berkeley, ``to return
to the era when collegiality and sharing took precedence over
commercial interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
