<HEADER>
A6621 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASSENGERS-2TAKES-HNS     04-05 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSENGERS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(WITH PASSENGER-BILLS SIDEBAR) &HT;    
 &HT;    CONGRESS IS RESPONDING TO COMPLAINTS ABOUT AIRLINES, BUT IS
THERE A REAL NEED?
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By LAURA GOLDBERG 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trapped on a Northwest Airlines plane grounded for eight hours
in Detroit during a January snowstorm, passengers were without
food, water or usable bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, a Trans World Airlines plane sat for two hours in
December and passengers aboard had no food or water. One testified
at a congressional hearing that there were no obvious mechanical
problems and the weather was fine. Two days later, word came of an
employee sickout.
</P>
<P>
   Incidents like these, closer scrutiny by lawmakers and perhaps a
little political grandstanding are spurring a ``passenger rights''
movement in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   At least four congressional plans aimed at forcing airlines to
shape up are pending, and Vice President Al Gore has rolled out an
administration proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment portrayed by the proposals is that at airports
across America, traveler anger has intensified as services provided
by the airlines have deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much more wide dissatisfaction with airline service
than I had anticipated,'' said Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of
the House Transportation Committee and author of a passenger rights
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Whether passengers are more angry and airline service has become
worse is not clear. Even if both allegations are true, some doubt
whether the legislation is justified and whether good customer
service can be mandated.
</P>
<P>
   The various plans feature many requirements for the airlines,
which would have to tell passengers why flights are delayed and
provide refunds within 48 hours of a ticket purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The plans also call for airlines to disclose more information
about overbooked flights and frequent flier plans, and compensate
passengers for runway waits of more than two hours. They also would
increase carriers' liability for losing bags and bumping
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Though the airlines can be blamed for some passenger anger, some
of it has been triggered by circumstances beyond their control.
Delays caused by the nation's aging traffic control system,
increased security or traffic jams in driving to the airport are
just a few.
</P>
<P>
   The middle-seat factor also is making some passengers grumpy. As
more people fly, travelers can't take for granted that the seat
next to them will be empty or that they won't get middle seats
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The airline industry filled an average of 70.1 percent of its
domestic seats last year, up from 65.2 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   To make their case, lawmakers and other supporters of passenger
rights plans point to an increase in the number of complaints
against airlines that customers have made to the U.S. Department of
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   But, though the percentage increases are impressive, the
complaints are statistically small compared with the actual number
of people flying, Transportation Department statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   For the top 10 airlines:
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, there were 5,808 complaints made to federal officials.
That year, people boarded 537.9 million times. That's 1.08
complaints per 100,000 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, there were 0.66 complaints per 100,000, or 3,212
complaints for 485.7 million passengers.
</P>
<P>
   For all U.S. carriers:
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 7,994 complaints were made, while 643.3 million
passengers boarded. That's up from 4,635 complaints in 1995 with
579.7 million people boarding.
</P>
<P>
   The key indicators of service that airlines must report to the
government also don't show much change over recent years.
</P>
<P>
   For the top 10 airlines:
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of domestic flights arriving on time was 78.6
percent in 1995 and 77.2 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines got 5.18 reports of mishandled bags on domestic flights
per 1,000 passengers in 1995. Last year, it was 5.16 per 1,000
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The rate at which passengers were involuntarily denied boarding
on domestic and outbound international flights because of
overbooking was 1.06 out of 10,000 in 1995. Last year, it was 0.87
per 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   A recent morning at Bush Intercontinental Airport in Houston
also didn't reveal a sense of outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Among 15 travelers interviewed, most had little negative to say
about airline service. Several had some gripes, and just a couple
were strongly critical.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Vargus, a Tampa, Fla., retiree who travels frequently, said
he doesn't believe service has become worse. He's never had a bag
lost and said he's surprised that with all the people flying these
days, the airlines do as well as they do.
</P>
<P>
   Vargus originally had a ticket on an America West Airlines
flight from Las Vegas to Tampa. It was overbooked and he
volunteered to give up his seat.
</P>
<P>
   Substitute arrangements put him on America West from Las Vegas
to Houston and Continental Airlines from Houston to Tampa. In
exchange, he got a travel voucher for a round-trip America West
ticket. The deal suited him fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very happy with my flying life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Karen Runge and her husband were connecting through Houston to
return to Toronto on Continental from a vacation in Ecuador. She
travels often for business and pleasure, including flights to the
United States. Among U.S. carriers, she has flown mostly American
Airlines and US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Runge said she is reasonably satisfied with the airlines'
performance. Passengers and bags are moved fine. Her flights arrive
without many delays. Onboard service continues to be good, although
she said the food has declined.
</P>
<P>
   While Runge believes the service is as efficient as in the past,
she said employees are not as pleasant. That, though, is partly
because so much is expected of them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rich Laucks, a Green Bay, Wis., resident who flies once and
sometimes twice a week for his job, didn't have much positive to
say. He most often flies Northwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Airline service has become worse, he said, as carriers have cut
back to boost profits. Lines are longer because there are not
enough ticket agents, he said. Bags get lost and planes aren't kept
up as well, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Full planes mean increased employee workloads, he said. ``It
affects the morale of the people that work for the airlines, so
they're crabbier than they used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Laucks recently was on a Northwest flight and had a 30-minute
wait onboard after landing because no one was available to operate
the jet bridge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The only carrier he enjoys flying is Midwest Express, where he
said he is treated like he matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, it's all the same at all the other major
carriers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
