<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6625 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASSENGERS-2NDTAKE-HN     04-05 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSENGERS-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(UNDATED)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   (major carriers,'' he said.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of people across America have had bad experiences with
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Some have told their horror stories to lawmakers during
well-publicized hearings in Washington, while others have
complained to the Transportation Department. But such complaints
represent a fraction of what's out there.
</P>
<P>
   A senior transportation official said the department estimates
that for every complaint filed with it, hundreds are made to the
airlines. Many encountering problems don't report them to the
government or the airlines. Instead, they tell friends or
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential source for gauging complaints, the Air
Transport Association, the lobbying group of the major carriers,
said it doesn't collect statistics on complaints made to airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But there is at least one indicator that passengers are
increasingly less happy with airline service.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's rating in the American Customer Satisfaction
Index has declined. The rating, put out since 1994, is produced by
the University of Michigan, the American Society for Quality and
Arthur Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   The airline industry's index score, which was 72 out of 100 in
1994, had dropped to 67 by 1997. That mark was one of the lowest
satisfaction ratings among private-sector industries.
</P>
<P>
   The airline industry's performance comes as customer
satisfaction overall has fallen from 74.5 to 71.1.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Boyd, a Colorado aviation consultant, said airlines
generally have poor attitudes toward their customers.
</P>
<P>
   He cited Delta Air Lines, which instituted, and later rescinded,
a surcharge on all tickets not bought at its own Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that show you someone who really cares about the
consumer?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Complicated ticketing rules that even airline employees don't
understand also frustrate passengers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Parsons, editor of Bestfares.com, an online travel service,
also faulted the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers need ``truth in advertising'' for policies, including
frequent flier rules, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines raised fares twice this year as activity heated up in
Washington, Parsons said, leaving passengers feeling, ``You're
going to raise the fares one way or the other, and we're going to
get the shaft.''
</P>
<P>
   As lawmakers consider passing legislation, they point to some
legitimate anger and criticism from some industry experts. Adding
to the momentum in Washington are a few high-profile incidents at
several airlines and the technology-driven ease with which people
can express their views through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Shuster said his passenger rights proposal has struck a raw
nerve. He said he can't go anywhere, be it the floor or the House
gym, without members sharing their own or their constituents' bad
airline experiences.
</P>
<P>
   He put the bill together after the Northwest incident in
Detroit. Its provisions include payments to passengers for certain
waits on runways. For delays of two to three hours, passengers
would get 200 percent of their ticket prices. The amount goes up
after three hours. Delays caused by last-minute air traffic control
directives are exempted.
</P>
<P>
   Also, airlines must tell passengers why flights are being
delayed, diverted or canceled. They would be unable to stop
customers from using portions of their tickets. And, if asked,
airline representatives would have to tell how many seats on a
given date and route are available for frequent flier awards.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., and Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala.,
each have their own plans. Sen. John McCain, an Arizona Republican
who may run for president, and Sen. Ron Wyden, an Oregon Democrat,
co-sponsored another.
</P>
<P>
   These plans and Shuster's have some similar features. Provisions
include requiring airlines to provide information on all available
fares, give refunds for tickets within 48 hours of purchase and
return lost bags within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The airline industry is lobbying against the bills, saying that
they could mean increased costs that would be passed on to
passengers, and that they are not necessary. Industry observers say
it's too early to tell what, if any, legislation will be passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an airline doesn't do a good job in a snowstorm, should we
re-regulate the whole industry? That's foolish,'' said Gordon
Bethune, Continental's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Some, including Shuster, say more competition in the airline
industry is the real answer. The Transportation Department has
prepared new competition guidelines that are expected to go to
Congress soon.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster also has sponsored legislation to fund more
infrastructure such as gates and runways, which he said is needed
to bring in additional airlines. And Dingell's bill also calls for
increased penalties for airlines that use unfair competition
methods.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Trippler, a former travel agent who tracks airline issues
as a consumer advocate for 1travel.com, an online travel service,
said Congress should say to airlines, ``Clean it up now or we're
going to act.''
</P>
<P>
   He favors some legislative remedies, including allowing
passengers to use tickets as they want because consumers should
have the right to use as much or as little of a product as they see
fit.
</P>
<P>
   But he also believes passengers could help themselves. He
provided a hypothetical example: AirTran comes into a
Continental-dominated market with cheap fares to several cities.
Continental matches the fares. Continental frequent fliers stay
with Continental to get mileage points. Eventually, AirTran pulls
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer has made the choice,'' he said. ``We can't
protect the customers from themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he said, legislation can't fix it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definite service problems. Can we legislate customer
service? No, we cannot,'' he said. ``We can't pass a law and say,
`You've got to smile.'''
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
