<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RELATIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVERYTHING'S RELATIVE' HAS TONS OF POTENTIAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
EVERYTHING'S RELATIVE 
Starring: Jeffrey Tambor, Eric Schaeffer, Jill Clayburgh, Kevin
Rahm 
On: NBC, Tuesday night at 9:30 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On most sitcoms born A.S. ``After Seinfeld'' premiered _
everything is not relative. On series from ``Friends'' and ``Sports
Night'' to ``Spin City'' and ``The Drew Carey Show, the humor is
rooted in the single life, in the rigors of flirting, dating, and
getting dumped. But with ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' ``Everybody Loves
Raymond,'' and, now, the promising ``Everything's Relative,'' the
family sitcom is coming into some new energy, with an unblinking
focus on the comic perversities of adult children and their
not-so-adult parents. Next to the raging eccentricities of these
1990s relatives, Gomez and Morticia Addams look a bit like Ward and
June Cleaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's Relative'' takes its cue from ``Everybody Loves
Raymond,'' but its characters are more educated, more therapized,
and whacked out in more psychologically distorted ways. There are
two sons in their 20s, Leo and Marty, and a pair of needy parents
who are divorced, but still tangled up in each others' daily lives.
Jeffrey Tambor, so perfectly clueless on HBO's late, great ``Larry
Sanders Show,'' plays the father, a big kid who thinks every pretty
woman has a thing for him and feels hurt when he realizes Marty
never buys him gifts. He's a lumbering, grinning adolescent. Jill
Clayburgh plays his ex-wife, a clinical therapist who wrote a book
about obsession. Naturally, she is quite obsessed with her family,
threatening to buy a new home first in her son's neighborhood, and
then across the street from her former spouse, whom she divorced
decades ago. In a funny recurring bit, she literally never can say
goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   These two nuts orbit around Kevin Rahm's Leo. He's a comedy
writer who isn't especially funny, and he frets about his parents
like a nervous parent. He recently broke up with a girlfriend,
which his mother and father see as an opportunity to invade his
life, and he now fears that he will have to be ``breaking up with
the family.'' Rahm, who looks like James Spader, has some
wonderfully crazed moments after he watches the movie ``Shine,''
and fears his overbearing father might turn him into a broken man
like David Helfgott. He even begins to stutter. The show's only
poorly conceived character is Eric Schaeffer's Marty, a high-strung
dolt who is about to get married. While the three other characters
are riddled with amusing ironies, Marty is just an idiotic cipher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's Relative'' has lots of potential. The writing is
less abrasive and one-liner-oriented than most sitcoms, and the
situation offers some room for comic exploration. Tambor and
Clayburgh, who appear to be happily liberated from the failed drama
``Trinity,'' have the potential to make a garish odd couple (though
neither looks to be as show-stopping as Doris Roberts, the invading
mother on ``Raymond''). And Rahm is a good foil, compelled against
his better judgment to throw himself in the middle of his family's
insane activities. It's the kind of show that will need to prove
itself, to push its characters beyond their conceptual
underpinnings (the obsessed obsession therapist, the unfunny comedy
writer) and into living, breathing people we might want to laugh at
every week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
