<HEADLINE>
(WITH PASSENGERS STORY) &HT;    
 &HT;    HOW THE BILLS LINE UP
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By LAURA GOLDBERG 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore.:
</P>
<P>
   Airlines must give refunds within 48 hours of the ticket
purchase if requested.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines must be willing to disclose if a flight is oversold,
and the number of frequent flier awards that can be redeemed on
each flight.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers can't be stopped from using just portions of tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Fliers should be able to find out all fares available,
regardless of the method used to access them.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers must receive checked bags within 24 hours of a
flight's arrival unless an additional delay is reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa.:
</P>
<P>
   Airlines must explain delays, cancellations and diversions.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers on planes kept on the ground more than two hours must
be compensated. For waits of two to three hours, passengers would
get 200 percent of the ticket price. Compensation would increase
for longer waits. Delays caused by last-minute air traffic control
directives are not included.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines cannot stop travelers from using only a portion of a
ticket, or charge additional fees for it.
</P>
<P>
   A good-faith effort must be made to return property labeled with
a passenger's name.
</P>
<P>
   If asked, airlines must reveal seats on specific dates and
routes to be made available for frequent flier awards.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.:
</P>
<P>
   Airlines must file plans with the Transportation Department to
provide onboard passengers with food, water, emergency medical
services and restrooms in an emergency. Plans must outline
evacuation procedures.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Passengers on planes kept on the ground more than two hours
must receive compensation. For two- to three-hour waits, passengers
would get 200 percent of the ticket price. There would be increased
compensation for longer waits. Delays caused by last-minute air
traffic control directives are not included, and there are
exemptions for safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Liability for mishandled bags cannot be limited to less than
$2,500 per passenger, up from $1,250.
</P>
<P>
   If a passenger is bumped and an alternative flight doesn't
arrive within two hours of the original flight, the passenger would
get a voucher or refund equal to the original price of the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties for engaging in unfair competition methods would
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala.:
</P>
<P>
   Airlines must provide information about delays, cancellations or
diversions.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers can't hold passengers onboard for more than two hours
without full refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers can't be stopped or penalized for using only a
portion of tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Prices or frequent flier awards must be honored for 24 hours
after the initial offering.
</P>
<P>
   All fare information must be available through all sales
channels.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration plan released by Vice President Al Gore:
</P>
<P>
   Airlines must file policies with Transportation Department on
telling passengers about delays, cancellations and diversions; on
providing food, water and restrooms during ground delays; and
evacuations during extended ground delays.
</P>
<P>
   Liability for lost bags and bumping would increase.
</P>
<P>
   Quoted fares must remain in effect for 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines must give a written response to complaints within 60
days and file monthly reports on complaints received with the
Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines must provide more information about the availability of
low-priced fares.
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
