<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MANY DOLES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tell me again. Which Dole is running for the 2000
Republican presidential nomination?
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole is visible far up in the political stratosphere these
days, exhorting President Clinton to hang tough in Kosovo even if
it means sending in U.S. ground troops. In op-ed opinion pieces and
interviews, he has been brazenly stealing his wife's political
thunder since the NATO bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole echoes her mate's hawkish attitude toward the
Serbian tyrant Slobodan Milosevic and the refugee crisis he has
created. But her brief statement while campaigning in Arizona last
week got little national attention and added nothing fresh to the
public debate over the military and humanitarian issues involved.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the former senator's aggressive support of
NATO's interventionist role in Kosovo and his wife's limited,
cautious response does not help her presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Her biggest political problem has always been the difficulty of
convincing voters that this very feminine, perfectly coiffed
southern lady would make a tough commander-in-chief, capable of
protecting national security and American credibility abroad by
leading our troops into harm's way if need be.
</P>
<P>
   If the major issues in the coming presidential campaign are
domestic, Elizabeth Dole, a former Cabinet officer and head of the
American Red Cross, is in good shape. But if Kosovo and the guns of
war are still our central preoccupation next year, the female half
of the Dole partnership will be forced to raise her soft, honeyed
voice to new, stern decibel levels. It is doubtful she can do this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should expand the targets to the Serbian
government's infrastructure,'' she said Friday at about the time
bombing raids on Belgrade and other new strategic targets were
ordered. ``What we're doing is the right course,'' she added, ``...
and no options should be taken off the table.'' The implication
that she would back ground troops hangs in the air, but
presidential candidates do not win elections in crowded primary
fields by being coy about where they stand.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, the 1996 GOP presidential nominee, has the serious
credentials that she lacks in foreign policy. An honored World War
II veteran, he was President Clinton's choice to try to broker
peace in Yugoslavia before it became appallingly clear that
Milosevic was not interested in peace at all.
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, in an ABC-TV interview, Bob Dole endorsed ground
troops in Kosovo as ``an option'' that ``if necessary, should be
exercised.'' Is it coincidence that Elizabeth Dole, known for
relying on carefully scripted comments, a few days later used the
same word, ``option,'' as her husband?
</P>
<P>
   It's a common word, but there are lots of appropriate
alternatives to it that other public figures have used. Does the
candidate think and speak for herself in foreign policy or not?
</P>
<P>
   When she speaks, why should anyone listen?
</P>
<P>
   Her presidential candidacy has the elements of ``buy one, get
two,'' which candidate Bill Clinton promised in 1992 while rashly
advertising Hillary Clinton's political skills. But he was mocked
for giving his wife a co-equal status that conservatives felt she
did not deserve since her name was not on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   And if memory serves, voters were asked in 1996 to buy Bob Dole
directly and rejected that opportunity. A recycled role for him as
a White House auxiliary does not seem to be the stuff of great
popular appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bob Dole's endorsement of Clinton's slowly building
determination to take down Milosevic, return the suffering Kosovar
Albanians to their homes and bring peace to Yugoslavia is
important, politically and historically. He is not the only
Republican bringing bipartisan support to this risky venture. But
he has the gravitas to make it easier for less courageous
politicians to reject isolationism and agree with the correctness
of a military policy being carried out by a president they
distrust.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole is unequivocal about the folly of giving up and
abandoning the hundreds of thousands of refugees huddled by
Milosevic's brutality without water, food, sanitation, identity or
hope. He insists we must win the war and achieve all our political
and military objectives. Period.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary, he says, ``we must introduce NATO ground forces
and arm Kosovar Albanian authorities. ... it is time to increase
the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole is right. But where is Elizabeth?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
