</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-COMPUTERS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FAA READIES COMPUTER TEST FOR Y2K BUG
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ High above Colorado this weekend, a government jet
will test whether the nation's air traffic control system has been
immunized against the computer ``millennium bug.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been saying for a year that we'll be ready,'' Ray Long,
who directs the Year 2000 program office for the Federal Aviation
Administration, said Monday. ``This is our chance to prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof will be sought Saturday afternoon when an FAA Lear
jet, with its onboard systems set to Dec. 31, 1999, will take off
from Grand Junction, Colo., fly on to Colorado Springs, and land at
Denver International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   All aviation systems are set to run on Greenwich Mean Time, the
time zone that includes London. So the simulated millennium will
arrive aboard the test plane at 5 p.m. Mountain Standard Time,
seven hours behind Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   Ground-based tracking systems will monitor the government plane,
as well as all other commercial and military craft that will be
flying through the region at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the test is designed to see whether all
parts of the complex air traffic control system will monitor
aircraft transponders correctly when the new millennium begins.
Those devices feed the plane's location, speed, altitude and other
data into the FAA's computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, we'll be acquiring two sets of data,'' Long said.
``We'll then read the (real-time and simulated) results. They
should lie seamlessly on top of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer readouts will be compared at the FAA's technical
center in Atlantic City, N.J., with the results to be announced
April 13.
</P>
<P>
   Long said the Denver area was chosen for the test ``because it
includes every type of monitoring system in the FAA's arsenal,
which means these results could be replicated anywhere else in the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the agency was stung by criticism from the
General Accounting Office, which told Congress that as many as a
third of the nation's airports would fail to meet the FAA's
self-imposed June 30 deadline for completing tests and computer bug
fixes.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO noted at the time that prior safety concerns appeared to
have been resolved. But it warned that computer failures in baggage
handling and other areas could trigger flight delays that could
ripple through the entire air travel system.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``Y2K'' problem has arisen because some computers
are unable recognize the year 2000, leaving them prone to crash or
to spew out bad data.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has adopted a five-stage process for solving its own Y2K
problems: awareness, assessment, renovation, validation and,
finally, implementation, which is scheduled to be completed on June
30.
</P>
<P>
   Long said 370 of the FAA's 423 mission-critical computers were
already certified as fully Y2K-compliant. ``We have met or exceeded
every goal,'' he claimed.
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph Morgan Jr., who coordinates the FAA's Y2K work at
foreign airports, gave a more problematic report. ``It's too early
to know whether other countries will deal with the problem, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Morgan noted that 60 percent of all international
flights to and from the United States involve only six nations, all
of which have active Y2K remedy programs. Those nations are Canada,
Mexico, Japan, the Dominican Republic, Britain and the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Long plans to accompany FAA Administrator Jane Garvey on an FAA
plane across the United States as 2000 dawns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to board a plane shortly after midnight and fly
west through all four continental time zones to demonstrate our
confidence that the nation's airspace system is perfectly safe,''
Garvey said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
