<SLUG> BC-SEC-WALKER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC BATTLES 'BULL MARKET IN INTERNET SECURITIES FRAUD'
 &HT;    By DAVID McNAUGHTON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Securities and Exchange Commission is
``stretched pretty thin now,'' but is bent on leaving Internet
fraud artists ``naked, homeless, and without modem,'' (CQ) the
agency's chief enforcement officer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Walker compared the SEC's effort to police the Internet
with its campaign against insider trading in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes this challenge even tougher for us is that we do
not have available to us new or additional resources to do the job,
although some members of Congress have expressed interest in making
additional resources available,'' said Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hopeful we will get more staff,'' he added in an address
at the National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has about 2,800 employees, including 850 in the
enforcement division run by Walker. The agency's annual budget is
about $300 million, equal to about a fifth (CQ) of the revenue it
produces from filing fees, fines and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Walker listed enforcement actions the SEC has taken against what
he called ``a bull market in Internet securities fraud,'' and
promised more.
</P>
<P>
   One area is the offering of free stock on the Internet, in
return , say, for clicking on a specific Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``These giveaways are illegal more often than not,'' said
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The issue for the SEC is the question of whether the offering is
in effect a sale. The sale to the public of securities that have
not been registered with the SEC is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can expect to hear more on this topic from us very soon,''
he promised.
</P>
<P>
   Walker also said the SEC's crackdown on Internet securities
fraud will expand in the months ahead through unspecified efforts.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Sen. Susan M. Collins, R-Maine, plans to offer
legislation to help the SEC fight Internet fraud. One proposal
would let the SEC bar brokers and dealers who have been banned from
the business from moving on to stock promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, ``this creates a path for corrupt brokers to continue
to deceive investors,'' said Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Another Collins proposal would allow the SEC to apply _
nationwide _ enforcement actions by state regulators. That's aimed
at securities law violators who simply move their operations after
a run-in with state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
