<HEADER>
A6667 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-ENGLANDER-SFCHR     04-05 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ENGLANDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH WRY: A POWERFUL NEW VOICE WITH AN INDELIBLE SENSE
OF  TRAGEDY AND HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By DAVID WIEGAND  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nathan Englander is not the next Isaac Bashevis Singer, although
you'll probably hear that he is in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that this young and talented New York-born resident of
Jerusalem revisits territory made familiar by Singer's work
(including Chelm, the legendary village of benign fools), but his
debut collection of nine unforgettable short stories, ``For the
Relief of Unbearable Urges,'' establishes Englander's voice as
unique.
</P>
<P>
   Who is Nathan Englander, and why is he making such a big splash
in the publishing world? Knopf has ordered a first printing of
30,000 copies of ``Unbearable Urges'' _ a very big debut for
someone who published only three stories in Story magazine before
his book was sold (a fourth, ``The Last One Way,'' appeared in the
New Yorker earlier this year).
</P>
<P>
   Englander grew up in New York an Orthodox Jew and is a graduate
of the Iowa Writers Workshop. Each of the stories in his first book
is rooted in Orthodox Judaism, but what gives them all an
irresistible universality is their celebration of individuality. In
different ways, the stories speak to the need to break with
traditions when those traditions stifle the essence of life. Even
when Englander pokes fun at the tenets of Orthodoxy, he does so
with a wise understanding that even the most restrictive traditions
are born of the eternal human need to reconcile the joys and
tragedies of life.
</P>
<P>
   Humor and anger are the most common responses to life's
frustrations in Englander's world, and at times, the responses of
his characters are funny and angry at the same time. In
``Reunion,'' for example, Marty has been tossed into a mental ward
after he staged a knock-down, drag-out fight in a synagogue in
which the Torah was knocked to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   For his sin, the entire congregation shares 40 days of fasting.
His gripe with the congregation is that he is consistently passed
over to give the blessing during services. His wife, Robin, is so
furious at his behavior, she hurls dishes at him: Englander alludes
to Kristallnacht by calling their final tiff ``the night of the
broken dishes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marty's real sin is that he embarrasses everyone by his
outsized life and sense of himself: That's why he's been
consistently overlooked for saying the blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Reb Yitzhak's angry outburst gets him fired as a
department-store Santa Claus in ``Reb Kringle.'' He feels guilty
about his annual job, a case of ironic typecasting, thanks to his
girth and his snowy beard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sin, this job,'' he tells his wife. ``Not since the
time of Noah has the world seen such boundless greed.'' Still, he
suffers the indignities of playing Santa, including wet pant legs
and sciatica like ``broken glass running up and down the nerve in
the back of his thigh.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he's pushed over the edge when a boy asks for a menorah
because his new father insists on celebrating Christmas instead of
Hanukkah. Yitzhak goes ballistic. He knows that his tirade will get
him fired, but there are principles at stake. ``He grabbed the
pompom hanging down from his head and yanked off his hat, revealing
a large black yarmulke. `This ... is not a fit job for a Jew.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even the saddest tale in Englander's collection, ``The
Twenty-Seventh Man,'' is laced with bleak humor. The story takes
place during the darkest hours of Stalin's reign, when the dictator
orders that 26 Jewish writers be rounded up, taken to a prison and
executed.
</P>
<P>
   Their ``crime'' was that, as Jews, they could never be entirely
loyal to the Soviet state. By a bureaucratic error, however, a 27th
man is added to the list, a man who is both completely anonymous
and the most prolific writer of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Pinchas Pelovits, through his unpublished writing, ``had
constructed his own world with a compassionate God and a diverse
group of worshipers. In it, he tested these people with moral
dilemmas and tragedies _ testing them sometimes more with joy and
good fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   The other writers _ variously drunk, wasteful of their talent,
sucking up to the state with terrible poetry or hiding their Jewish
heritage behind false names _ are nothing compared to this foolish
boy.
</P>
<P>
   The writers are tossed into a cell and tortured. Fretting over
their fate and puffed up with self-importance, the other writers
squabble, while Pinchas alone keeps writing his fable:
</P>
<P>
   ``The morning that Mendel Muskatev awoke to find his desk was
gone, his room was gone, and the sun was gone, he assumed he had
died. This worried him, so he said a prayer for the dead, keeping
himself in mind. Then he wondered if one was allowed to do such a
thing, and worried instead that the first thing he had done upon
being dead was sin.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the writers will die, but only one will die a great man,
the one among them who will be instantly and forever forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   The title story in the collection pits most directly the ancient
Jewish traditions and laws against modern life. Dov Binyamin is a
Hasidic Jew in Israel married to a woman who will not sleep with
him, reputedly because of the longest menstrual period known to any
woman on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The more he begs for her attention, the more she ignores him. He
goes to a rabbi, who gives him a dispensation to visit a prostitute
``for the relief of unbearable urges.'' ``I suffer greatly under
the urges with which I have been blessed,'' he tells the rabbi. Dov
Binyamin goes to Tel Aviv, ``the city of sin,'' and meets Devorah,
who is so filled with life that it frightens him.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining that it is a sin to spill seed in vain, he doesn't
use a condom. Back home, his newfound indifference to his wife
makes her want to sleep with him again. Happy ending in store? Not
quite: Careless about what he's been wishing for, Dov Binyamin now
has a venereal disease to boot, thanks to his adherence to Jewish
law. ``This couldn't possibly be the solution the Rebbe intended,''
Dov Binyamin thinks, as a different kind of fire burns in his
loins.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of Jewish humor are planted deep in an enduring sense
of tragedy. Great Jewish comics as well as great Jewish writers
have understood the fundamental irony of life, that its gift comes
with strings, not the least of which is that eventually everything
we care about, including our own lives, will be taken away from us.
</P>
<P>
   Writers like Singer, Malamud and others have shared a common
theme: For all of its pain, life is pretty absurd when you think
about it. But a sense of the ridiculousness of life's fundamental
tragedy is not the sole purview of Jewish writers, which is why the
greatest of them have been able to tap into universal recognition
among readers of every description.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Englander evokes Singer, but he also calls to mind the
tragicomedies of absurdist dramatists Samuel Beckett and Eugene
Ionesco _ whose plays, not coincidentally, were brought famously to
life by two of America's greatest Jewish comic actors, Bert Lahr
(``Waiting for Godot'') and Zero Mostel (``Rhinoceros''). To
paraphrase that old Levy's Jewish Rye ad campaign, you don't have
to be Jewish to enjoy, laugh at and weep over Nathan Englander's
stories. You just have to appreciate extraordinary, insightful
writing. Englander's is a fresh, awe-inspiring voice that speaks
with a timeless understanding that life's tragic joke is on all of
us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL; 
 &QL; 
FOR THE RELIEF OF UNBEARABLE URGES &QL; 
By Nathan Englander &QL; 
Alfred A. Knopf; 205 pages; $22 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
