<HEADER>
A6672 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      04-05 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10-CENT GAS HIKE_WE'VE LIVED TO SEE THE DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today would've been my father's 89th birthday, and he probably
would have felt that he lived too long if he'd gone down to the
corner gas station and watched them jack the price up 10 cents a
gallon in a matter of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Dad said that gas cost not much more than 20 cents a gallon when
he first started driving.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was an old Ford with the doors ripped off to
make it look sporty, and some kitchen chairs nailed down for a back
seat. That used Ford cost him about a month's pay, he used to say.
</P>
<P>
   No way could he afford a new car then, much less today, when a
new vehicle averages more than $20,000, or about six months salary
for the average American. And while we struggle to make car
payments and get to the gas station before the price bumps another
10 cents, BP Amoco Plc cuts a deal to buy Atlantic Richfield Co.
for more than $31 billion.
</P>
<P>
   When my twin sister and I were born just before World War II,
Dad had to sell the family car. And we couldn't afford another
until Dad bought a used 1951 Plymouth Cranbrook sedan in 1956. I
was allowed to drive it into the driveway for washing and waxing
... something I've not exactly overdone anytime since.
</P>
<P>
   Animals and people don't much like change, especially the
overnight kind. It comes so fast these days that we simply try to
swim out from under the avalanche. And if we think we've seen
change, those of my father's generation must be excused for
occasionally retreating to the so-called good ol' days.
</P>
<P>
   When my father was born _ at home, of course _ Japan had just
annexed Korea; Montenegro had declared independence from the
Ottoman Empire; Ty Cobb, Honus Wagner and Cy Young were national
heroes, and more than 70 percent of our bread was homemade.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Dad was 16, he was encouraged to leave high school
and join the peace-time Navy. In 1926, change was beginning to
accelerate: that year saw the introduction of everything from
Scotch tape to Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph Valentino and Harold Houdini died; Joe Stalin ousted
Leon Trotsky; Gene Tunney beat Jack Dempsey, and Babe Ruth hit
three World Series home runs. A Michigan company advertised all the
materials needed to build a five-room house for $487. And Al
Capone's guys were selling bootleg beer for $30 a case.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure whether Dad ever felt he had been able to swim out
of the avalanche of change. As a high school drop-out, he worked at
everything from commercial photography to bar-tending. He drove a
tanker truck and operated a punch press. He was a traveling
salesman, tavern owner and sheet metal mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on his lifetime is like doing an environmental impact
statement to scatter his ashes on Lake Michigan. He didn't impact
his environment much more than the mass of working men who lead
lives of quiet desperation. But if he knew many moments of
desperation, Dad certainly didn't go quietly into that good night.
</P>
<P>
   My father knew thousands of song lyrics _ even if he couldn't
sing well _ and lots of jokes. ``I gotta million of 'em!'' was his
borrowed Jimmy Durante line. This made him a helluva bartender. He
might have lived and died as a tavern keeper, but something called
the Outfit bought out his round-the-clock tavern in Cicero, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Dad knew the importance of tipping in the service industry and
almost always left a hefty gratuity. But he taught me that it
worked both ways, and a penny tip said more than words about bad
service. Dad also would get up from a table or counter and leave a
restaurant if it was apparent that his order was languishing under
a heat lamp.
</P>
<P>
   He could barely tip-toe to 6 feet, but Dad was built like a
barrel and no one, of any size, got in his face without getting
into trouble. Except a woman, of course, because Dad was Old School
polite to the point of charming. Open the door for 'em; give 'em
your seat on the streetcar; take off your hat in the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Dad also came with the kind of built-in prejudices you'd expect
in a lower middle-class, blue-collar culture. When my older sister
announced that she was having a party, and told Dad that ``there
will be some black people,'' he didn't say a word. But on the night
of the party in our cleaned-up basement, Dad left and didn't return
until long after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Dad's street language was as rough as you could hear in any bar
or back street, but God help the child who might repeat any of it
within earshot of either parent. We learned early the taste of
Fels-Naptha brown laundry soap.
</P>
<P>
   Dad was the reasonably quiet father who came home, ate supper
and seemed to pay only cursory attention to family talk of school,
church or whatever. He worked weekends in good weather to earn that
little bit of extra money for luxuries ... like a television set.
</P>
<P>
   He drank heavily, until he got adult-onset diabetes, but I never
saw him drunk. Dad also smoked heavily, and that eventually killed
him.
</P>
<P>
   And that's too bad, of course. But if he'd lived to see gas go
up 10 cents in one pop, that might've made him feel he'd already
lived too long.
</P>
</TEXT>
