<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6671 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PTECH-CENTERPIECE-CHA     04-05 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PTECH-CENTERPIECE-CHATTERBOTS0 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just the FAQs, ma'am
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new twist on an old technology is being used to
create human-like guides to Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Neuromedia in San Francisco, and, to a lesser
degree, Big Science in Roswell, are developing chatterbots. These
are programs fueled by artificial intelligence software, which has
been around since the 1970s but never found a practical use. It
might have one now.
</P>
<P>
   Big Science's Tom Rearick and Neuromedia's Walter Tackett are
trying to sell the chatterbots as customer service representatives
for Web sites, answering FAQs, or frequently asked questions. But
these representatives aren't flesh and blood, they're extra-smart
computer programs.
</P>
<P>
   Neuromedia is one of the few companies that have a ``virtual
representative'' in commercial use. Tackett, chief executive
officer and chairman, said Oracle, Charles Schwab and
DaimlerChrysler have Neuromedia chatterbots in use or in
development.
</P>
<P>
   Rearick believes conversational software robots, or bots, will
be increasingly used on sales Web sites to greet customers and
answer questions. Bots can have a human face and serve to
personalize the impersonal _ a blend of the Wal-Mart greeter,
customer service desk and search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Rearick is not convinced the delivery of text, sound and video
will be the Internet's forte. Right now, the Internet is an
``awkward telephone,'' a ``flickering, postage-stamp-sized
television,'' a ``scratchy radio,'' and a ``50-pound, tethered
newspaper,'' he said. Rearick thinks the Internet's true edge will
be its ability to connect _ and the bots are a tool to make that
connection easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``If new technology is supposed to be orders of magnitude better
than the technology it replaces, then what is the Internet good
at?'' he said. ``It's not a good substitute for any of the things I
mentioned. But it is incredible at making a connection between one
individual and a remote computer. But computers are hard to
understand. So why not teach computers humanese instead of teaching
humans computerese?''
</P>
<P>
   The word ``bot'' is short for robot. A bot is a software program
designed to sift data. An easy way to understand Rearick's use of a
bot is to think of it as a really specific search engine. Say
you're shopping at a bookseller's Web site, have managed to find
your book and want to buy it. As a first-time customer, you more
than likely will be asked to fill out a page or two of forms and
enter a major credit card number, all of which must happen before
you find out what it will cost to ship your book to you. As Rearick
sees it, the bot would be an icon on the screen that a customer
could activate and type in a question asking how much shipping
would cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of all stores are less than three clicks away,
but the Web sites have tens of thousands of pages that raise lots
of questions to a novice user,'' Rearick said. ``And portals are
adding features. There is no way to add links and not increase the
complexity without having a detrimental effect. There is no way to
organize it all. But what if you had your own personal guide? It
would provide answers that otherwise could be an obstacle to a
sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Rearick also sees the bots being used as errand runners. Someone
going on a vacation could ask their bot to search the Web for the
right clothes, a map, plane tickets and a place to stay.
</P>
<P>
   The technology behind bots is not there yet. For now, the bots
respond to questions on specific topics. Computer experts call that
limited domain, and it means the bots are programmed to be
conversant on one topic, such as a company's inventory, but shaky
on most everything else.
</P>
<P>
   But if bots fulfill the promise Rearick thinks they hold, it
will be, in part, because of the work of people like Robby Garner.
</P>
<P>
   Garner develops artificial intelligence software as a hobby.
From his basement office on a residential street in Cedartown, a
small town in northwest Georgia, Garner has won an international
artificial intelligence award for two straight years.
</P>
<P>
   The Loebner Prize is based on the premise that one day software
will simulate human thought. The concept of artificial intelligence
was first theorized by Alan Turing. In 1950, Turing published a
paper titled, ``Can Machines Think?'' The Loebner contest was
started in 1991 to answer the question. Garner's software has come
the closest the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea of chatterbots is maybe in its infancy,''
Garner said. ``I just don't feel like the technology is really
there to be especially useful. The conversations they're capable of
are more geared toward information, virtual sales reps that can
talk about a product. We still don't have a computer you can just
tell things to. That's really the ultimate goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it's easier to just click on a FAQ selection
and see your answer. The advantage, if the system really worked, it
would be sort of like a search engine: Pose a question and get a
response. But the technology isn't quite there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
