<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6679 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CINDERELLA-BALLET-LAD     04-05 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINDERELLA-BALLET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADS IN `CINDERELLA' FELL INTO EACH OTHER'S ARMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Love at first sight? Well, not exactly. Call it
love at first sweaty embrace.
</P>
<P>
   It happened six or seven years ago, when Adam Cooper and his
equally well-buffed colleague, Sarah Wildor, were rehearsing a duet
for London's Royal Ballet Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite passionate, erotic dancing,'' says Cooper, mentally
restaging the encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we sort of knew something was happening,'' Wildor
chimes in, ``because (that dance) is very _ what's the word?''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper considers for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No holds barred,'' he says finally. ``Well, not quite! But,
yeah, it was obvious to us there was chemistry there. And then
about a year or so after that we got together.''
</P>
<P>
   And they both lived happily ever after ... Isn't that how fairy
tales are supposed to finish?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this one is still being written, six or seven nights a
week, in theaters stretching from London to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest chapter, we find the happily smitten couple
co-starring in the North American premiere of Matthew Bourne's
``Cinderella,'' the newest piece of cheeky revisionism by the
mild-mannered enfant terrible of British ballet. The production,
which opens Wednesday at the Ahmanson Theatre, is the highly
anticipated follow-up to Bourne's much-admired, gender-scuttling
``Swan Lake,'' produced by his dance company, Adventures in Motion
Pictures, at the Ahmanson two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cinderella'' is set in London during the Nazis' aerial blitz
of England _ the so-called Battle of Britain of 1940-41 _ when the
Royal Air Force fought Hitler's Luftwaffe for mastery of the skies.
Bourne's reimagining of the Cinderella story contrasts the drab
grimness of wartime with the escapist glitter of London's legendary
ballrooms, where couples danced defiantly to big-band music while
bombs blew England's capital into rubble.
</P>
<P>
   In Bourne's retelling, the glass-slippered heroine (Wildor)
becomes a mousy homebody who takes refuge from the war and her
dysfunctional family in the illusory glamour of London's night
life. Her Prince Charming (Cooper) has been re-envisioned as a
wounded Royal Air Force pilot with a touch of what might be called
delusional paranoia. Their ballroom scenes become a kind of
self-scripted Hollywood movie into which the two characters project
idealized versions of each other.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the time period, Bourne is using Prokofiev's
Stalinist-era ``Romeo and Juliet'' score, which is darker and not
so lusciously romantic as Tchaikovsky's better-known one. The cast
features veteran British ballerina Lynn Seymour, who also appeared
in ``Swan Lake,'' as Cinderella's alcohol-addled stepmother.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a shellshocked soldier is a far cry from Cooper's
previous incarnation as a bare-chested, sexually voracious bird of
prey in ``Swan Lake.'' In Los Angeles, Cooper's magnetically macho
performance caused female and some male viewers alike to melt in
their seats, and prompted a debate whether Bourne's ``Swan Lake''
was or wasn't intended as a homoerotic allegory.
</P>
<P>
   So which is the real Cooper _ the lean, dryly understated,
rather average-looking chap seated next to Wildor in an Ahmanson
interview room, or the predatory sexual animal of ``Swan Lake''?
</P>
<P>
   Only his fiancee seems to know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's all a bit silly, really,'' Cooper says modestly,
``because the character they see on stage is not me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, rubbish!'' Wildor breaks in. ``There's a big side of you
...''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, of course there is,'' Cooper backpedals, ``but that's not
what I'm really like. I never see myself as that sort of thing
anyway. So when people were saying all this, yeah, it's nice to
hear it, but if I start believing it ...''
</P>
<P>
   The truth, Wildor insists, is that Cooper is ``the nicest person
you could possibly meet,'' whereas she's the one with ``a filthy,
filthy mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still shocking you, aren't I?'' she teases Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still shocking,'' he says, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, neither of these pleasant, approachable
27-year-olds, who share a house outside London, strikes the
attitude of a sex-symbol wanna-be. Cooper, stylishly unshaven and
easily given to laughter, is the chattier of the two. Wildor, a bit
more reserved, has a tough-minded, let's-cut-to-the-chase style
that belies her soft blond looks.
</P>
<P>
   Identically dressed in black jeans and pullovers, they seem like
ambitious, dedicated team players, graceful personifications of the
new Cool Britannia. And although they can get pretty gaga around
each other, they're hardly joined at the hip, as their overlapping
but somewhat divergent careers attest.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper left the Royal Ballet, where he and Wildor met, about two
years ago. Since then he's been broadening his range as a dancer
and actor outside the Royal Ballet's institutional confines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard (leaving the Royal Ballet) in a way because that's
all I'd known for the last eight years,'' he says. ``I was 16 when
I joined the school and 18 when I joined the company. And also
knowing that you've got a paycheck every week, that's hard coming
away from that, kind of coming out into the wide world.
</P>
<P>
   ``But perhaps in a way it was easy, because I knew I wasn't
progressing there like I wanted to. It's just (that) it's a big
place with a lot of dancers to please, (and) you can't please
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper says he was inspired to take up dance by old Gene Kelly
and Fred Astaire movie musicals. Wildor also began her career very
young and quickly turned into a dance addict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Literally, I think it was my parents saying, `We've got to
find something for Sarah to get her out of the house!''' she says.
``And that was it, and I was 3. And I was just hooked, just loved
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The best part, she adds, was that her parents, though always
supportive, ``really didn't have a clue'' about dance. She was thus
spared the travails of having vicariously involved adults
constantly looking over her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Wildor says that being separated from Cooper professionally was
hard at first. It was as though he was ``leaving me behind in a
way, because we used to go to work together, we used to go home and
talk together, and touring was much easier because we were always
together.''
</P>
<P>
   While she still ``quite likes'' being at the Royal Ballet, she
believes that working on ``Cinderella'' has allowed her to stretch
her acting technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any sort of dancer or principal in the Royal company doesn't
tend to get that many shows of one particular role,'' she explains,
``so for me having this amount of shows is fantastic. You can
really get stuck in it and bring out different things (on)
different nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourne says that in ``Cinderella'' he cast both Cooper and
Wildor ``against type, slightly, because I thought it would be
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, he (the pilot) ends up as being quite an ordinary
guy,'' Bourne says. ``He's not the kind of hero she (Cinderella)
thinks he might be. And everyone expects (Cooper) to be this sort
of sex bomb, so that was quite interesting, to play with that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And Sarah is kind of not your average ballerina type, I would
say. She has great sort of acting skills, she moves in a very
individual way. And she brings a quality to it which is quite
unexpected in a way, because she really enjoyed going for sort of
the frumpy side of Cinderella, not just in looks but in her sort of
body language. She hunches over a bit. She's not a pretty kind of
waiflike thing, as most Cinderellas are. She's a little bit more of
an odd character.''
</P>
<P>
   While a Broadway run of ``Cinderella'' seems likely to follow
its L.A. engagement, as it did with ``Swan Lake,'' Bourne is glad
to be opening his new work here ahead of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we're sort of among friends here, which is a nice
feeling,'' he says. ``And so I think that our relationship with
this theater and Los Angeles will be one that we'll sort of
continue and hopefully develop _ maybe even premiere a piece here,
do a world premiere at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   At present, Bourne is working on a version of ``Carmen'' that he
describes as ``loosely based'' on Bizet's opera, along with a
revival of AMP's production of ``The Nutcracker.'' He's also
considering putting some of his existing work on film.
</P>
<P>
   All that activity should give Cooper and Wildor time to fly back
to Britain next summer and tie the knot, as Cooper puts it, with
``all the millions of people who want to get married in the year
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   A fairy-tale ending, you might say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
