<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refugees, hostages the face of war in the Balkans
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All three newsweeklies are filled with the images of war, but
none is more unsettling than the Time ($3.50) cover of an ethnic
Albanian woman breast-feeding her baby as she walks into Macedonia.
``The editor was concerned about the tastefulness of the picture,''
says Time's director of photography Michele Stephenson, ``but there
was no real dissension. The young mothers on the staff were all
moved by it and were able to identify with it. We felt it was the
most telling single image we had seen of the refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek ($3.50) uses its share of poign-
</P>
<P>
   ant photographs of fleeing refugees, but the magazine devotes
its cover to a grainy picture of the three battered American
soldiers who were taken hostage. Accompanying the Kosovo coverage
is an interview with U.S. Sen. John McCain (R.-Ariz.), a former
prisoner of war in Vietnam, who insists that defeat is not an
option. ``(Slobodan) Milosevic needs to understand that even if
every Kosovar is moved out, and every village is burned to the
ground,'' McCain says, ``we can get them back in and we will
rebuild their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   In U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($2.95), Michael Satchell describes
the methodical blueprint for terror that Milosevic's forces are
using against ethnic Albanians. Shortly after the NATO bombings
began, Satchell writes, ``death squads apparently working from hit
lists hunted down intellectuals, journalists, doctors, human-rights
activists and community leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   MIRACLE MAN: Long before Jimmy Swaggart and Jim Bakker hit the
airways, charismatic Pentecostal faith healer and radio preacher J.
Charles Jessup delivered his message to millions. The flamboyant
Jessup was married three times by the age of 24, raised roosters
for cockfighting and went fishing in the Gulf of Mexico in his own
seaplane. In a fascinating article in The New Yorker ($3), Peter J.
Boyer describes the rise and fall of the evangelist that Robert
Duvall used as his model in ``The Apostle.'' He also was a role
model for Elvis Presley, Boyer writes. During one of Jessup's tent
revival tours out of Tupelo, Miss., Presley asked to join the
preacher's gospel and country music band. Jessup's brother Darrel
``told him that the Jessups didn't need another guitar.''
</P>
<P>
   WASTING AWAY: Students used to gain weight when they went to
college and were fed with extra helpings of high-carbohydrate
dining hall meals and late-night pizzas. Now, People ($2.99)
reports, an increasing number of women students _ and some men _
are battling anorexia. Most are perfectionist, type-A
personalities, but part of the problem is the idolization of
reed-thin models and actresses, says sociologist Traci Mann.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY KUBRICK: In the dozen years before his death last month,
director Stanley Kubrick had become an elusive figure, shunning
interviews and publicity while finishing his last film, ``Eyes Wide
Shut.'' That didn't stop Entertainment Weekly ($2.99) from running
an interview with him. The fact that it was conducted 40 years ago
when Kubrick had just finished ``Spartacus'' is a minor point; it's
still an insightful interview.
</P>
<P>
   BRINGING ON THE NOISE: J.C. Penney plans to publish Noise, a new
magazine for teenagers and distribute it for free in its stores.
The first issue, due in July, will be 84 pages and include ads from
the retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this magazine as a vehicle to create a strong, personal
relationship with a very important customer _ teenagers,'' said
Gale Duff-Bloom, president of J.C. Penney Marketing and
Communications. The full-color magazine will focus on the latest
teen beauty and fashion styles and trends as well as sports and
music.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
