<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN MAN LINKED TO MISSING ATHEIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ An ex-convict being held in connection with the
1995 disappearance of Madalyn Murray O'Hair has admitted
involvement in four Texas homicides, at least one of which involved
the decapitation and mutilation of a victim, according to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Gary P. Karr, 50, also admitted an extensive role in what
authorities believe was the month-long kidnapping, and subsequent
killing of O'Hair and her two adult children, for $500,000 in gold
coins, according to testimony given in federal court in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Karr's involvement extended to ``concealing property (taken)
from the victims after their death ... acquiring equipment to help
the victims be moved,'' and concealing their bodies, according to
the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to FBI agent William O'Leary, who testified March
26 in the Detroit courtroom, Karr told the FBI where the victims'
bodies were buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``(He) told me the city,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, the FBI has not found the remains of America's
most famous atheist and her two adult children, Jon Garth Murray
and Robin Murray O'Hair, all of whom disappeared in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The three abruptly left Austin, Texas, in late August of that
year and spent a month in San Antonio, before vanishing on Sept.
29.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth slaying involves Danny Fry, a Florida man who went to
Texas in mid-1995 on a mysterious mission.
</P>
<P>
   His nude, mutilated body was dumped by a river east of Dallas on
Oct. 2, 1995. Fry's head and hands had been severed and were
missing, and until this spring, the identity of the body was a
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of O'Hair and her two children have not been found.
</P>
<P>
   Karr's lawyer said the case pertains to the disappearance of the
O'Hair family and Fry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given they are talking about a triple homicide and this other
body that was decapitated, I think it's obvious they are talking
about O'Hair and Fry. How many cases fit that description?'' said
Richard Helfrick, a public defender representing Karr.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a federal search warrant, more than three dozen
agents from the FBI and Internal Revenue Service spent most of last
weekend combing a 5,000-acre ranch outside of Camp Wood, a small
town some 120 miles west of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But the investigators apparently came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   Karr was one of two men charged with weapons violations after
federal authorities simultaneously questioned people in Austin,
Detroit, Chicago and Fort Worth, Texas, on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   According to the transcript of the March 26 court hearing, Karr
spoke freely to investigators who went to his apartment inquiring
about the Texas cases.
</P>
<P>
   After more than 13 hours of questioning, he was charged with
offenses related to two loaded pistols that were found in his
apartment in the Detroit suburb of Novi.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law makes it a crime for felons to possess ammunition or
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   David R. Waters, 52, was charged with the same offense after
agents found 119 rounds of ammunition during a March 24 search of
his apartment in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Both Karr and Waters have extensive criminal pasts, including
violent crimes, and both are being held without bond. They spent
eight months in the same prison in Vienna, Ill., in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Waters was serving time for battery and Karr was serving time
for aggravated kidnapping and armed robbery. Waters was released in
1987, Karr in May 1995. Karr apparently then went to Texas before
moving to Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he (Karr) got out of prison, I think he was trying to put
his past behind him, and go forward, and that if anything, Waters
interjected himself into Karr's life,'' Helfrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Waters was O'Hair's office manager several years ago in Austin.
He also was an old friend of Danny Fry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
