<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOSPEL-FRANKLIN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gospel rapper takes the heat
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kirk Franklin won't go so far as to thank the Rev.
Henry Lyons, but he has reason to.
</P>
<P>
   Since Lyons' wife set fire to one of his houses, sparking a
yearlong inquiry into the activities of the former president of the
National Baptist Convention USA, Franklin hasn't been the most
controversial figure in the black church. Charges of Lyons'
racketeering and theft have weighed a little more heavily on
congregations' minds than Franklin's infusing rap music into his
gospel message.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for that, all I can say is `Amen,' '' chuckles Franklin,
29, from his home in Dallas. ``Thank you, Father!''
</P>
<P>
   That sigh of relief comes after years of attacks from
traditional gospel circles.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's 1993 breakthrough single, ``The Reason Why I Sing,''
merely raised eyebrows in the music industry because it propelled
his first gospel album (``Kirk Franklin &AMP; the Family'') past the 1
million mark in sales. The song itself, a simple, stirring
call-and-response centered on a piano, was clear in its praise of
Jesus and posed no problem with the more upright in the pews.
</P>
<P>
   Then Franklin, a kind of choral director and crowd-rouser,
started borrowing from rapper Busta Rhymes in his improvisations.
He incorporated the bass line from Parliament-Funkadelic's ``One
Nation Under a Groove'' into his own ``Stomp'' and got all
buddy-buddy with R. Kelly, the R&AMP;B singer known as ``the
bump-and-grind guy.'' Franklin had USA Today lauding this ``new day
in gospel,'' People magazine calling him the ``apostle of gospel''
and both urban contemporary and gospel radio stations playing his
Grammy Award-winning music.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it also had some of the church folk upset,'' says CeCe
Winans, also a frequent target of opponents of contemporary gospel.
``People were saying, `Why do they have to dance so much? Why do
they dress that way?' I say, `Kirk is singing His praises and the
young people are hearing him. What's the problem?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people say they want everyone to be a part of the
church, that they want to embrace everyone, but they're
hypocrites,'' declares Kelly, who performed on Franklin's recent
single, ``Lean on Me.'' ``They just want everyone to worship God
exactly the way they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin himself won't weigh in on the subject. ``I'm trying to
please Him and only Him. If Jesus can go through all He endured,
surely little ole me can take it.''
</P>
<P>
   So when the major TV networks passed up the first gospel
pay-per-view concert, headlined by Franklin on Easter, ``I praised
Him on BET!'' Franklin says triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   And, of the time a man turned away from Franklin in first class
on an airplane because Franklin said he is in gospel music,
Franklin says, ``OK, he may think I'm a weirdo, but what matters
most is what God thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I just keep on praising Him! How I praise him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nu Nation Tour
</P>
<P>
   Gospel music with Kirk Franklin, CeCe Winans and
</P>
<P>
   Trin-i-tee 5:7.
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight-Wednesday. $39.50.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Theatre, 660 Peachtree St. N.E. 404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
