<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6730 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-LIVER-TRANSPLANTS     04-05 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LIVER-TRANSPLANTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF LIFE, DEATH AND THE RULES OF LIVER TRANSPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ralph Benedetto is dying in his mobile home in Clearwater, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Swirling around him is a debate over whether he and patients
like him should be denied liver transplants that might save their
lives _ specifically, whether the nation's health care system
denies transplants out of failure to keep abreast of medical and
technical advances or out of eagerness to save money.
</P>
<P>
   Benedetto, 44, a disabled Medicaid patient, contracted hepatitis
B 10 years ago from a blood transfusion he received after he was
struck by a drunken driver. Two years ago, his doctors said his
disease had progressed to the point where he could die at any
moment without a liver transplant. But his health maintenance
organization refused to pay for the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The HMO, Staywell Health Care in Tampa, Fla., cited guidelines
issued by the state of Florida recommending against liver
transplants to hepatitis B patients on the ground that the virus
would destroy a replacement liver just as it did the original,
leaving the patient just as sick and wasting a scarce organ in a
transplant doomed to fail. The federal guidelines that apply to 39
million Medicare recipients say the same.
</P>
<P>
   But medical researchers and liver transplant surgeons said
advances in the treatment of hepatitis B had left the guidelines
outdated. Since the early 1990s, drugs started to become available
to better treat the disease and now, the researchers say, the drugs
appear to have blocked liver damage in more than 80 percent of the
thousands of hepatitis B patients who have received transplants in
states that allow them.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say there is now wide agreement that hepatitis B, in and
of itself, is no longer a valid reason to deny someone a liver
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman at the Florida Agency for Health-Care
Administration said it was the agency's policy not to discuss
guidelines in detail. Benedetto's condition changes from day to
day, making it difficult for him to be interviewed. But his former
wife, who is caring for him, said she was furious when the
transplant doctors had recommended was denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not believe Ralph would simply be allowed to die when
everybody knew successful treatments were available,'' Theresa
Benedetto said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Dr. David R. Nelson, a professor of medicine and an expert
in hepatology at the Shands Hospital of the University of Florida
in Gainesville, and Dr. Scott E. Hallgren of the Florida Center for
Gastroenterology at Pinellas Park, had determined in June 1998 that
Benedetto was in danger of dying at any moment, but that he had an
excellent chance of regaining his health with a transplant.
</P>
<P>
   The HMO insisted that the sole reason for its denial was that
hepatitis B patients did not meet the state criteria for
transplants. Costs for the procedure are high, the company
acknowledged, with the average hospital bill for the operation in
Florida at $117,000, plus the costs of finding a suitable organ and
the subsequent costs of preventing rejection of the organ or
recurrence of viral infection, said Nancy Gareau, Staywell's vice
president for operations.
</P>
<P>
   The company, under contract with Florida to manage Medicaid
patient care, covers five or six transplants a month, Ms. Gareau
said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the HMO refused to authorize a transplant, Mrs. Benedetto
said, Benedetto was turned away by three hospitals. Jackson
Memorial Medical Center, affiliated with University of Miami School
of Medicine, said it would not do the transplant unless Benedetto
produced a $150,000 down payment, Mrs. Benedetto said. Shands
Hospital required $136,000 down.
</P>
<P>
   Both hospitals confirmed Mrs. Benedetto's account and said the
total bills could run much higher. Benedetto, unemployed because of
his disability, could not begin to pay that cost. Tampa General
Hospital also turned him away, because it said its doctors were not
convinced that Benedetto would survive a transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at several American medical centers, health care
experts and doctors do not fault hospitals that seek assurance they
will be reimbursed for transplants, whose high cost, if
uncompensated, would quickly drive them out of business. ``And if
it did one transplant free, wouldn't it be unjust to deny one to
someone else who also needed one,'' said Dr. John M. Vierling,
chairman of the American Liver Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   And while some doctors characterized Benedetto's experience as
yet another example of how tight-fisted HMOs harm patients, others
said that in their experience most HMOs were fully cooperative in
covering transplants where they were warranted.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Vierling said, the original decision in the 1980s
to exclude patients with hepatitis B from transplant rosters was
legitimate. The problem now, he said, is adapting the rules to
changing medical conditions. Once a procedure is excluded, he said,
it is often a long and tortuous process to get the rule changed.
That is true in the case of hepatitis B, he said, even though new
treatments have produced long-term success rates equal to overall
rates for liver transplants.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Donald A. Young, a senior vice president for policy and
clinical services of the American Association of Health Plans, the
nation's largest trade and lobbying association for private managed
care companies, said health care providers had an obligation to
treat their patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first rule _ the principle of beneficence _ says you have
the responsibility to provide the care needed to the individual
without regard to your own interest,'' including financial
interests, he said. But, he added, ``Second, the principle of
stewardship provides that justice must be done for all where you
have to allocate resources.'' He said it would be unethical to
spend so much time and money or resources in saving one patient
that it became impossible to save a group of others. Although the
two principles may be contradictory, Young said, the goal is to try
not to violate either.
</P>
<P>
   What does this mean for Ralph Benedetto? In the past, it might
have meant that it would not be right to give him a liver in a
transplant doomed to fail, if the organ might save someone else's
life. But today, Young said, ``It seems to me the doctors and
hospitals and the state of Florida and the HMOs should all get
together and find a way to work something out.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day on which the American Association of Health
Plans discussed the ethical considerations in the Benedetto case,
March 4, its spokesman said it had pondered the question further.
``We found the question highly disturbing,'' the spokesman said.
``We will do something.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, on March 5, after probing questions had been raised
about Benedetto's case, Kate C. Morgan, chief of the Florida Agency
for Health-Care Administration's Bureau of Managed Health Care,
said the case had prompted senior agency officials to make an
immediate change in the agency's rule on hepatitis B. ``We have
relayed that information to the HMOs, and Staywell is going to move
forward with the transplant'' as long as Benedetto is still a
candidate, Ms. Morgan said. Staywell confirmed that this was the
case, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But now Benedetto may no longer be viable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   When he was tested in June in an effort to appeal Staywell's
denial, he was found to have responded well to various medications.
But now, Dr. Enrique J. Martinez, his hepatologist, said, the virus
is renewing its attack.
</P>
<P>
   If events had been conspiring against Ralph Benedetto, now they
seemed to be mobilized on his behalf. On the afternoon of March 5,
Martinez's transplant center, Lifelink, a nonprofit institute
affiliated with Tampa General, was notified that it had just
received approval to use an experimental drug, adefovir, that was
not yet approved for general use but could be prescribed by
selected research centers on a compassionate-use basis. Preliminary
trials have found it to be 90 percent successful in controlling the
recurrence of hepatitis B viral attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he believed the chances were excellent now that
the adefovir would enable Benedetto to be put on the list to await
a transplant within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Several health care professionals said it was heartening to see
senior state health officials act so quickly in this case, but also
expressed concern. Vierling of the American Liver Foundation, said:
``Those recent developments are, of course, good news for the
Benedettos. But it is still disturbing that it took the fight and
persistence of a person like Theresa Benedetto and the action of a
few key people in the system before it could be spurred into
action. And it disturbs me that many dying patients with hepatitis
B still cannot get transplants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
