<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u x &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUKAS-PRIZE-NYT &LR;      04-05 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUKAS-PRIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE NEW NONFICTION WRITERS WIN HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The newly created J. Anthony Lukas Prize Project honored three
nonfiction authors Monday, with the largest award being a $45,000
grant to a freelance writer who has been struggling financially to
finish a book about six World War II veterans from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine the difference it will make in my life,''
said Kevin Coyne, 39, a former newspaper reporter who received the
$45,000 prize for his work in progress, ``The Best Years of Their
Lives.'' ``I had this naive faith that I could scratch out a living
from this, and it just hadn't been happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Also honored were Henry Mayer, with a $10,000 award for his book
``All on Fire: William Lloyd Garrison and the Abolition of
Slavery'' (St. Martin's Press), and Adam Hochschild, with a $10,000
prize for his account of the plundering of Congo, ``King Leopold's
Ghost: A Story of Greed, Terror and Heroism in Colonial Africa''
(Houghton Mifflin).
</P>
<P>
   Coyne said his $45,000 award would allow him to concentrate
exclusively on finishing his book, which essentially traces the
lives of World War II veterans who return home to Freehold, N.J.,
to face the shattered promises of small-town America, where the
main factory closes and race riots erupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great financial struggle these last couple years
because this book has taken a lot longer than expected,'' said
Coyne, who noted that ``without this grant it would just take
longer.'' The book is to be published by Viking Penguin.
</P>
<P>
   The series of awards was established in memory of J. Anthony
Lukas, a Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist and the author of
``Common Ground,'' who died in 1997 shortly before his last book.
about an assassination in turn-of-the-century Idaho, ``Big
Trouble,'' was published by Simon &AMP; Schuster. The awards recognize
nonfiction writing that demonstrates literary grace, serious
research and concern for an important aspect of American social or
political life.
</P>
<P>
   The awards were conceived by Linda Healey, his widow, and Arthur
Gelb, one of his former editors at The New York Times and now
president of The New York Times Co. Foundation. The project is
administered by the Columbia University Graduate School of
Journalism and the Nieman Foundation of Harvard University and is
financed by the family of Mark Lynton, who died in 1997. He was a
senior executive at Hunter Douglas manufacturers in the
Netherlands, and the father of Michael Lynton, the chief executive
of the Penguin Putnam Group.
</P>
<P>
   Finalists were Patricia Cline Cohen for ``The Murder of Helen
Jewett'' (Alfred A. Knopf); Jill Lepore for ``The Name of War''
(Knopf); William Adler for the unpublished ``Universal
Manufacturing,'' and Anne Matthews for the unpublished ``Wild
Nights: Nature Returns to New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
