</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CLAYBURGH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JILL CLAYBURGH ENTHUSED ABOUT HER LATEST SITCOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jill Clayburgh has made some odd career choices. She admits it.
</P>
<P>
   After wowing movie audiences in the '70s and early '80s,
Clayburgh almost disappeared. Flying low enough to avoid detection,
she has focused on TV movies and other small-budget projects in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always picked very far-out, edgy things,'' said
Clayburgh, who received Oscar nominations for her performances in
``An Unmarried Woman'' (1976) and ``Starting Over'' (1979). Talking
by phone from a production studio in L.A. last week, she added:
``It probably was a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   She was speaking in terms of career advancement as opposed to
artistic satisfaction _ one unreleased effort was a pro-Palestinian
film project titled ``Hanna K.'' She didn't sound the least bit
regretful.
</P>
<P>
   That may help explain her enthusiasm for another odd choice, the
new NBC series ``Everything's Relative,'' premiering Tuesday night.
NBC has ordered only four episodes of the half-hour comedy, meaning
``Everything's Relative'' may have a shorter shelf life than most
things in my refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it can't be renewed for next season. Anything's
possible. There once was a show called ``Seinfeld,'' whose pilot
aired in July 1989. Nearly a year later, four more episodes showed
up. (NBC evidently has a thing for the number 4.) But it wasn't
until January of '91 that it became a regular series.
</P>
<P>
   Though it strives mightily for the ``Seinfeld'' vibe,
``Everything's Relative'' isn't ``Seinfeld.'' But then,
everything's relative. NBC is falling off its perch as the
most-watched network. Meanwhile, ABC has a well-regarded
``Seinfeld'' clone in ``It's like, you know ...'' So why not make a
late-season play for the yada-yada-yada crowd?
</P>
<P>
   The New York-born Clayburgh, whose voice conveys a sort of artsy
detachment, doesn't pretend to be interested in the wherefore of
network programming practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with the script,'' she said. ``I thought the
humor was genuinely original and brilliant. It just made me
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   She even showed it to her husband, the noted playwright David
Rabe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved it,'' Clayburgh reported.
</P>
<P>
   Clayburgh, who will be 55 on April 30, plays a quintessentially
obsessive, overbearing mother of about the same age. It's a TV role
that has been an industry ideograph for decades, an over-the-top
alternative to the wacky neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Everything's Relative,'' though, Clayburgh keeps the
character, Mickey Gorelick, pleasantly under the top, making the
mother's obsessiveness and guilt-mongering eminently believable.
Indeed, it's the other three characters _ her ex-husband (played by
Jeffrey Tambor) and their two adult sons (Kevin Rahm, Eric
Schaeffer) _ who are a little out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's Relative'' is the second network series for
Clayburgh this season. She played the Irish-American matriarch of
the McCallister clan on NBC's short-lived drama ``Trinity,'' which
had good genes (created by John Wells of ``ER'') but poor health
(nobody watched).
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, Clayburgh said she wouldn't have considered
doing a series. But now that her two children are teenagers (13 and
16), she said she's less worried about spending time away from them
and the family home in the hills of northwestern Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trinity'' was perfect for her because it was filmed in New
York. Her contract on ``Everything's Relative,'' should it go back
into production this summer, allows her to stop work at 2 p.m.
Friday so she can be back in New England by Friday night. And
working the standard three-weeks-on, one-week-off sitcom schedule
will make the absences even more bearable, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``shocked'' and ``disappointed'' by the cancellation of
``Trinity,'' Clayburgh seems quite unconcerned about whether
``Everything's Relative'' will have a life beyond four episodes.
NBC won't announce its fall plans until next month and its
executives are mum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all get hysterical about what's going to happen in three
years,'' she said calmly. ``It's not very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a pro. Obviously, Clayburgh hasn't forgotten an
earlier experience in TV. Thirty years ago, before her film career
started, she appeared in the soap opera ``Search for Tomorrow.''
Though the series ran 35 years, Clayburgh's character, Grace
Bolton, died of a brain tumor after one season.
</P>
<P>
   If the Gorelick family survives past its brief tryout,
Clayburgh's intelligent approach will deserve some of the credit.
But don't ask her to explain her motivation or her method.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't describe myself as an actress,'' she said. ``I let
other people do that. I just try to act.''
</P>
</TEXT>
