   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ WASHINGTON _ Military and political developments
in the ongoing Balkans crisis. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POWS _ WASHINGTON _ The three American soldiers held
captive by Yugoslav military leaders have been trained to resist
their captors by strictly adhering to a rigid code of conduct
summarized in 10 sentences on a wallet card every soldier carries.
While pilots and others who operate behind enemy lines get
extensive survival training for life as a POW, those less likely to
be captured rely almost exclusively on their conviction to follow
the code of conduct and ``return with honor.'' (Montgomery, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POWS-EXCERPTS.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ TIRANA, Albania _ Developments here and in
Western capitals as the refugee crisis along Kosovo's borders
continues to worsen. (Roughton and Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JOURNAL _ MONTENEGRO, Yugoslavia _ It was a typical day
in Montenegro. We were suspected of being spies. Then armed
soldiers showed up at the apartment building where we are staying.
When we explained to them that we were journalists, not spies, one
of them assured our translator: ``No one will kill them in
Montenegro . . . not for now, at least.'' Tensions remain high _
especially for Western journalists _ in this province of
Yugoslavia. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-GOVERNOR _ MEXICO-CITY _ Rumor has it he may have fled
the country in a speedboat he received from a drug trafficker. Or
he may be hiding in some corner of Mexico. Or he might even be dead
because of the secrets he possesses. Mario Villanueva, ex-governor
of Quintana Roo state, is not expected to show up at the
inauguration of his successor Monday evening _ fueling speculation
he has fled justice before Mexico's Attorney General even filed
drug-trafficking charges against him. Villanueva _ an embarrasment
to the ruling PRI party _ is the highest-ranking Mexican politician
to be investigated so vigorously while still in office. He's now
missing along with a police commander from his state, and an
investigation into Swiss bank accounts and other dubious
acquisitions continues. Villanueva's indictment could be a coup for
Mexican justice, which is struggling for credibility. But if the
government presents a persuasive case that he's guilty _ but has
fled _ it could be viewed as another failure. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   FED-FINANCIAL _ WASHINGTON _ Suppose a major corporation sent
out an annual report confessing to problems with fundamental
record-keeping that kept the company from accurately reporting a
significant portion of its assets, liabilities, and costs. Suppose
that same company admitted that last year, it wrote checks for
billions of dollars in improper payments, had only a rough estimate
of its loans, and lacked adequate records for a majority of its
buildings, facilities and equipment. That is the financial
condition of the U.S. government and its 24 major separtments and
agencies, according to the 1998 financial audit released quietly
last week. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   FAA-COMPUTERS _ WASHINGTON _ The Federal Aviation Administration
on Saturday will test the air traffic system's ability to keep
working when the year 2000 begins. Using a Lear jet flown from
Grand Junction, Colo., the FAA will run a simulation of air traffic
as if the date were Dec. 31. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HUD-EMPOWER _ WASHINGTON _ The inspector general of the U.S.
Department of Housing and Urban Development has suggested ways to
improve HUD's oft-criticized empowerment zone program, but
officials rejected the suggestions as ``invalid.'' (Malone, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SEC-WALKER _ WASHINGTON _ The Securities and Exchange Commission
is ``stretched pretty thin now,'' but is bent on leaving Internet
fraud artists ``naked, homeless, and without modem,'' the agency's
chief enforcement officer said Monday. (McNaughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
