<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LECARRE-NOVEL-ART-2TA     04-05 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LECARRE-NOVEL-ART-2TAKES(960)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SPIES, NEW FOES: CAPITALISTS GONE AMOK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of le Carre is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It is that twilight hour when the table lamps are
lighted before the draperies are drawn closed, the time before
cocktails, when a late winter's afternoon surrenders meekly to
nightfall. At his secluded, almost secret home in a private corner
of Hampstead, John le Carre is talking about his best-selling new
novel, and the hour seems to suit this discussion of treachery and
transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Single &AMP; Single'' is le Carre's 17th novel, and his latest to
break with the sorcery of the Cold War that once conjured the
titanic contests of George Smiley and Karla, his archetypes for the
battle of duplicitous Western virtue against the Soviet foe.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when the Cold War ended, fiction's old spies were
supposed to just go home and tend their wounds and memoirs. Not so
their creators.
</P>
<P>
   To them fell the task of finding new adversaries, new crusades
to supplant the decades of tilting at Moscow. The spymasters they
created, after all, built legends for their ``joes,'' the scripts
by which agents lived their double lives. Now they must find new
legends for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   John le Carre _ the name is the pseudonym of David Cornwell _
has found one, paradoxically enough, in the very system that
triumphed over Communism, turning the battle on its head. In
``Single &AMP; Single'' (Scribner), the West itself nourishes both
antagonist and protagonist: for Western values, read unbridled
capitalism; for the KGB and its hoods, read upper-crust Western
financiers run amok in harness with Caucasian thuggery and the
Russian mob.
</P>
<P>
   As one would expect, heroism by any conventional standard is
elusive: even the dominant, central character _ Oliver Single,
errant son of archcapitalist Tiger Single _ is a traitor to his
father, a mole burrowing under the foundations of the pin-striped
class that nurtured him. And in an upending of the class system
that pervaded many of le Carre's earlier novels, the erudite Smiley
has been replaced by Nat Brock, a customs and excise man with a
Merseyside twang to his voice and a rarely visited wife in the
suburbs: ``a man of layers, not all of them savory,'' as the novel
puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Le Carre is a silver-haired 67 now. In his muted checked jacket
(with four buttons on the cuff, as is de rigueur among certain
Englishmen), his olive shirt and dark green tie, he could be a
retired civil service mandarin, a college professor, a ruminative
ex-spy gone comfortably to ground in a discreet corner of
Hampstead. He could have been any one of those if he had not become
Britain's paramount exponent of a kind of novel that is not easy to
classify.
</P>
<P>
   By his own frequent admission, he is a former member of what he
terms ``the secret world'' of British espionage, thus an initiate
in the corridors of British Establishment power, a learned man who
once taught at Eton after studies in Bern, Switzerland, and Oxford.
In his large home the easy comfort of the furnishings offset by
understated antiques is just as quintessentially English as the
four buttons on his jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   But what seems to come across in conversation is an inordinate
restlessness to define and catalog the new confusion that has come
in place of a new world order and to search for what he calls
``some kind of ethical standard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a grand theme, I think, which is very much in my mind,
which is a political one,'' he said. ``As long as we had our Great
Satan, we could see ourselves in some kind of moral light. But when
that was removed, we were left with our own excesses. We have to
create some kind of ethical standard for ourselves _ I don't
believe that has happened at all _ some kind of self-restraint,
some acceptance that the global village is not capable of infinite
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't just be carpetbaggers, exploiters,'' he added. That
theme, he said self-deprecatingly, ``was some kind of grand
pretentious vision'' underlying ``Single &AMP; Single.'' And this
period, the bull run of short-term investment capital to Russia
between glasnost and last year's debt crisis, ``was the little wave
of history I wanted to catch.''
</P>
<P>
   For le Carre aficionados the book is far more than that. It is,
the author said, a kind of companion volume to his work of almost
13 years ago, ``A Perfect Spy,'' in which he came closest to
allowing the pseudonym's mask to slip to reveal David Cornwell's
anguished relationship with his father, a matter that preoccupies
him still, for all his 67 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Cornwell, the real father, ``had a criminal record, was a
confidence trickster by profession,'' le Carre said, and the
peripatetic life of restless movings-on and deceit has stamped him
indelibly. The matter is unavoidable in le Carre's work, even
though Tiger Single is not as recognizably Ronnie Cornwell as the
father depicted in ``A Perfect Spy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a theme that runs through many of them,'' he said of his
books. ``Why did I, as a chap of 29 years old, invent a hero of
Smiley's age, and somebody of such flawed perfection as Smiley?
Perhaps he was the dad I wished I had had.'' His childhood plays
out in other ways. Ask him why so many of his fictional women are
fleeting players _ like the wife of the customs agent, Brock,
forever offstage in ``Single &AMP; Single'' _ and he will tell you that
he has ``got better at women'' after a difficult start.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my childhood there were no girls, no sisters, no mother.
Such a nomadic life: all-male schools until I ran away from
Sherborne. Then the army. Then when I went into the secret world,
in those days it was very much a man's world.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States is another tricky theme: ``I'm not very good
at America. I think I would have had to live there much longer.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He defines his secret world by negatives rather than by any
clear exposition of what kind of spying he did. ``I was never an
East-West spy runner, but it's a piece of my image I can't
escape,'' he said, suggesting that his role was more modest than
his legend suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with Yevgeny Primakov, a former KGB warhorse and now
Russia's prime minister, at a Russian Embassy dinner long after the
Cold War, le Carre said, ``I felt I should have been more of a spy
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   But his secret years did provide the mother lode of his public
life as a writer. ``I just knew that in writing terms I had found
my material, my microcosm,'' he said, ``and all I had to do was to
move it into a literary context.''
</P>
<P>
   Le Carre strongly resents any comparison with former adversaries
in espionage, like Markus Wolf, the onetime East German spymaster
who has escaped every post-Cold War attempt to prosecute him. And
if people like Wolf linger as the enemy, there are other hostile
forces caught in le Carre's sights.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly surprisingly for an author of such established stature
and such readership, there is an all too easily evoked, prickly
sense that British letters do not accord the kind of recognition
due someone of his achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my country, there seems to be a literary academy somewhere,
and a readership somewhere else,'' he said, harking back to the
mass audiences of 19th-century English novelists that were no
stigma. ``It's fairly recently that the literary bureaucracy is at
one end of the spectrum and the popular readership is at the other
end of the spectrum.''
</P>
<P>
   He is fretful, too, about the power of the news media, of the
demonizing sound bite and the spin-doctoring of information in an
age of new adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think unbridled capitalism is an enemy, and I think the
greatest single enemy is the misuse of information, the perversion
of truth in the hands of terribly skillful people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The manufacture and distribution of the sophisticated lie must
be one of the worst legacies of the Cold War,'' he said, bemoaning
the mental tyranny ``where there is only one respectable opinion
about anything.'' He added: ``If you don't have it, you are on the
wrong side of the fence. But I don't know what fence.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There have been skirmishes, too, within the literary
establishment from which le Carre seems to feel apart. In November
1997, for instance, he was caught up in a bruising exchange of
letters in The Guardian with Salman Rushdie. Last year he ditched
his American publisher of long standing, Alfred A. Knopf, and
switched agents.
</P>
<P>
   The spats and irritations, though, are not what draw the
faithful to le Carre. Rather it is the distinctive voice that runs
through most of his books, a control of tone and shading that is,
to borrow from the books, his tradecraft. ``With this palette,
everything is possible, whatever you call it: a spy story, a story
of political suspense,'' he said. ``The form is limitless. I don't
feel I have got to go and find something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the actual writing, though, it is not too fanciful to
imagine the public author and his covert characters fusing in the
writer's quest for a spy's cover. He mentions eavesdropping on
British business types in an ``all-day, all-night bar'' in Moscow
and how, on one of three trips to Georgia for ``Single &AMP; Single,''
he recounts, the gunfire from an attempt to assassinate Eduard A.
Shevardnadze roused him from his bed in a boardinghouse, leading
him to grab his passport and think, ``Here's trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is le Carre, incognito, spying out the landscape of
his new novel from the ``eyeline'' of his characters. Heading off
from Tbilisi into the hills of Mingrelia ``wearing a woolly cap and
taking a bodyguard _ I mean taking two blokes with you _ you are
not going to be recognized by anyone,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6750 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CAPTIVES-HNS &LR;      04-05 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CAPTIVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TALKS TO FAMILIES OF SOLDIERS HELD IN YUGOSLAVIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
and ALLAN TURNER 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) President Clinton has telephoned families of the three
U.S. servicemen being held in Yugoslavia and told them the
administration believes the soldiers will not face trial by
President Slobodan Milosevic's government, White House officials
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokeswoman Julia Payne said that Clinton, in the
calls, was conveying ``the sense out of Belgrade,'' the Yugoslav
capital, and had ``no independent confirmation'' from the Milosevic
government about the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The family of Texas native Spc. Steven Gonzales, at least, may
have taken the president's comments more literally.
</P>
<P>
   Texas prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald, who has been a media
representative for Gonzales's family in Huntsville, described the
call Sunday afternoon from Clinton to the soldiers' parents,
Gilbert and Rosie Gonzales.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reassured them that the government was doing everything it
possibly could,'' Fitzgerald said. ``He informed them Steven had
been classified as a POW and that he wouldn't have to stand
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said in his daily briefing
only that Clinton ``made some phone calls to some military
families'' while at the Camp David presidential retreat over the
Easter weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart subsequently identified the families as those of the
three captives but refused to discuss the substance of the calls.
</P>
<P>
   After being told of the Gonzales' apparent interpretation of the
conversation with the president, Payne said Clinton was referring
to ``the indications out of Belgrade,'' including comments from an
official of the Milosevic regime on a U.S. television interview
program Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said the Milosevic government had refused to deal with
Swedish representatives in Belgrade, whom Washington appointed as
its contact in the Yugoslav capital when diplomatic relations were
broken as a result of the U.S.-led NATO aerial bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Payne also said the Milosevic government had refused to allow
independent access to the soldiers, including visits by the
International Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   In his calls, Clinton was apparently referring to Milan Bozic,
deputy mayor of Belgrade and a minister without portfolio in the
Milosevic government. On ABC's This Week, Bozic said the captives
will be treated well and not face trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they will not be tried, and they will be back in
their homes as soon as this stupidity stops,'' Bozic said,
referring to the airstrike in reprisal for Milosevic's campaign
against ethnic Albanians in the southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav media outlets had predicted legal action against the
soldiers could come as soon as last Friday, but there has been no
subsequent authoritative update.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official said that while Bozic's comments
were heartening, it was uncertain how authoritative they were. He
also said the Milosevic government could change its mind quickly on
how to deal with the captive soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers were picked up Wednesday along the
Yugoslavia-Macedonia border during what NATO described as a routine
reconnaissance mission. Officials of the Belgrade regime have said
that the soldiers were in Yugoslavia. A NATO official has said the
three men were in Macedonia, a position the Pentagon first adopted.
Subsequently, the Department of Defense has said the location of
the men was under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Gonzales, the captive soldiers are Staff Sgt.
Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles and Staff Sgt. Christopher J.
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
