<HEADLINE>
IN A PEASANT MOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Designers from Valentino to Marc Jacobs went romantic
for spring, with pretty notions like the peasant blouse, the
ultra-feminine alternative to the ubiquitous T-shirt. Bergdorf
Goodman has two sheer cotton peasant blouses by Jacobs: a
cap-sleeved dot print ($365) and a three-quarter-sleeved solid in
pale blue, lilac or white ($400). A cap-sleeved cotton blouse in
pink or white by Theory is $135.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus has several styles by Anna Sui, including a glazed
cotton print ($175), a silk print ($205), a pale blue denim ($135)
and a pinstripe cotton ($170). There are also two cotton blouses by
Les Prairies ($130 and $165), and a dotted swiss by Rebecca Taylor
($150). An embroidered white cotton nightshirt by Katherine
Harestad is $185.
</P>
<P>
   In the peasant mood at Henri Bendel: a checked shantung dress by
Stephen DiGeronimo ($178) and a Liberty print bustier by Shoshanna
($178).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
