<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6765 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      04-05 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE OPENS DOOR TO ALLIED GROUND TROOPS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, moving to deflect an anticipated
plea for a cease-fire from Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
vowed on Monday an ``undiminished, unceasing and unrelenting''
allied air campaign against Yugoslav armed forces until Milosovic
meets tough conditions for ending the 14-day offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is to persist until we prevail,'' Clinton declared as
he launched a stepped-up refugee relief effort dubbed ``Operation
Sustain Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``We are prepared to sustain this effort for the
long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said allied bombing would continue until Milosevic
withdraws Yugoslav forces from Kosovo, ceases attacks on ethnic
Albanian Muslims in Kosovo, agrees to autonomy for the province,
permits an international security force and clears the way for
immediate repatriation of 505,000 refugees who have fled to
Montenegro, Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Milosevic does not do what is necessary, NATO will
continue an air campaign. It will be undiminished, unceasing and
unrelenting,'' the president declared.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke as senior administration officials cracked the
door for the first time to the possible movement of allied ground
troops into Kosovo to protect stranded refugees there.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said troops could enter
Kosovo if Yugoslav forces posed no ``risk'' or as the result of
``some sort of deal'' with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have previously ruled out the
use of allied ground forces inside Kosovo without a signed
agreement with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon laid the groundwork for possible creation of an
allied-protected refugee sanctuary in southern Kosovo with
preparations to send 24 Apache anti-tank attack helicopters and 18
long-range rocket launchers to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Both the helicopters and a long-range version of the rockets
launched by the Multiple Launch Rocket System have the range to
cover the entire territory of Kosovo to protect any allied troops
dispatched into the mountainous terrain to help refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spokesman said Clinton anticipates a move for a
cease fire from Milosevic in coming days because Yugoslav forces
have made great progress toward achieving the Serbian leader's goal
of eliminating ethnic Albanian Muslims from the Yugoslav-run
province.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be a surprise to see in the coming days attempts
at half measures, hollow cease-fires,'' Lockhart said, adding:
``They will not be acceptable to stop the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon declared: ``Milosevic may think
he's finished. We will not be finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended administration preparations to deal with the
flood of refugees unleashed in the wake of the allied bombing
campaign that began 13 days ago. Clinton said that it had been
``impossible to prepare fully for the chaos'' that stemmed from
Milosevic's campaign of ``ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States was shipping 500,000 individual
daily rations to the estimated 244,000 refugees crowded into
Albania and would begin shipping 600,000 rations requested by
Macedonia to feed an estimated 136,000 Kosovar refugees there.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said another 65,000 Kosovars continue languishing
without adequate food or shelter in no-man's land between Kosovo
and Macedonia _ the site of some of the most heart-rending news
photographs in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do all we can to aid the victims of Mr.
Milosevic's expulsion policy,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration agreed on Sunday to provide temporary
refuge for 20,000 refugees as part of a NATO-wide effort to absorb
100,000 Kosovar refugees in Albania and Macedonia to free space for
additional Kosovar refugees still trying to get out.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon spokesman said that the United States would
probably provide temporary housing to up to 20,000 Kosovar refugees
at the U.S. Navy base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, where some 45,000
Haitian refugees were housed during an earlier U.S. refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged concerned Americans to telephone their donations
to a newly established governor-sponsored toll free number _
1-800-US-AID-RELIEF.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6767 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0406-     04-05 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0406-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO BEGINS FLYING REFUGEES TO 'TEMPORARY' HAVENS
 &HT;    With COX-KOSOVO-MAIN, COX-KOSOVO-POWS
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. and SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ NATO forces waging an air war against
Yugoslavia also acted as a ``good Samaritan'' on Monday, beginning
an airlift of some of the 230,000 ethnic Albanians who have fled
their homes in Kosovo in the past 13 days to escape death at the
hands of Serbian soldiers and police.
</P>
<P>
   But even as a plane carrying the first 150 refugees landed in
western Turkey, President Clinton and his NATO allies emphasized
that moving the refugees to safe havens in allied countries is only
a temporary response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ethnic cleansing of Kosovo cannot stand as a permanent
event,'' Clinton said during a brief appearance in the Roosevelt
Room of the White House to announce ``Operation Sustain Hope,'' a
stepped-up effort to help the Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refugees belong in their own homes on their own land,'' he
said. ``Our immediate goal is to provide relief. Our long-term goal
is to give them their right to return.''
</P>
<P>
   To better coordinate the humanitarian assistance, Clinton
established a panel headed by Brian Atwood, the administrator of
the U.S. Agency for International Development (AID). In addition,
he ordered a toll-free telephone number for private citizens who
want to help: 1-800-USAID RELIEF (cq.).
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO wants to be a good Samaritan,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea
said in Brussels, ``but we are not a refugee organization.''
Consequently, NATO has turned to the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to coordinate assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am encouraged that western governments appreciate the
enormity of the refugee drama, which can no longer be handled by
Kosovo's immediate neighbors alone,'' High Commissioner Sadako
Ogata said in a statement from Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   In the first wave of humanitarian assistance by NATO, allied
aircraft delivered nearly 200 tons of food and emergency supplies
to refugees in Albania and Macedonia. NATO called the relief
flights a ``humanitarian air bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the continuing flow of refugees out of Kosovo is
threatening to overwhelm Albania and Macedonia, where most of these
fleeing have gathered.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that can be said is that the situation is critical,''
Albanian President Rexhep Meidana said in an interview Monday.
``I'm quite sure this flow will continue and in the next days there
will be many, many more refugees in Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Meidana said he does not support plans by NATO to
temporarily place more than 100,000 refugees in other countries.
There is a fear here that the refugees may never come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must remain near their land and their houses,'' Meidana
said. ``They must return to Kosovo as soon as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the refugees will never return to their homes in Kosovo
unless there are NATO troops in the province to maintain their
security. He also said he supports the use of ground troops to
drive the Serb forces out of the province _ a contingency opposed
by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   On the humanitarian side, a small contingent of U.S. troops
began to set up a camp near the Tirana airport handle relief
operations. The United States plans to send at least 6,000 troops
to distribute food and supplies to refugees in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the NATO airlift of refugees, the United States has
agreed to accept up to 20,000 people. ``Our goal is to take some of
the burden off the struggling front line nations,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen at the State Department and the Pentagon acknowledged
that the 20,000 refugees the United States has agreed to host may
be housed at the U.S. military base at Guantanamo, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers London-based European correspondent Bert
Roughton reported from Albania. Cox Newspapers correspondent Scott
Shepard reported from Washington).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
