<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK AMONG INSURERS GIVEN OK TO SELL IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. of Boston
joined three Western insurers Monday in winning approval from
Beijing to sell life insurance in China.
</P>
<P>
   The move gives Hancock, one of three US insurers now approved,
and other competitors an early toehold in a market that could prove
vast and profitable once fully opened up. The approvals bring to 13
the number of foreign insurers licensed to operate in the Asian
country, where markets for financial services, especially
insurance, are still tightly regulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted by this news,'' Hancock chief executive
Stephen L. Brown said in a statement. ``China is the major emerging
market for US financial institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   With an aging population and creaky pension system, the Chinese
market is seen as a new insurance frontier as US and European
markets mature. China, with a population of 1.3 billion, has more
than 130 million people aged 60 or over.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's working investment in the world's most populous
country will be small _ around $12.5 million and one office in one
city. The company, which already has four representative offices in
four major Chinese cities, must now wait for the government to name
its Chinese joint venture partner and designate the city in which
it will sell its products.
</P>
<P>
   China, which insists outside insurers form joint ventures so
that domestic players will not be crowded out of the market, has so
far restricted foreign insurers to Shanghai and the southern city
of Guangzhou. Foreign insurers must open representative offices
before seeking formal sales licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock _ the nation's 13th-largest life insurer and the biggest
in Massachusetts _ plans to focus on life insurance, with a view to
branching out into other investment products, including mutual and
pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The markets in China are undeveloped but growing rapidly,''
said Derek Chilvers, who heads Hancock's international operations.
``There's a general expectation that the government will accelerate
their opening.'' He gave no forecasts of sales revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock and the others _ Chubb Corp. of the United States, Sun
Life Insurance Co. of Canada, and Britain's Prudential Corp. _
received their license approvals on the eve of Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji's planned visit to Canada and the United States. The nods
also came as China seeks support for its application to enter the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, with $120 billion in assets under management, is the
third US insurer, after American International Group (AIG) and
Aetna Group, to work in China. Some 20 US insurance companies have
opened representative offices in China and are lobbying for
licenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
