<P>
   REFUGEES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When their refugee resettlement agency
folded, the Bosnian mother and her four children were virtually
stranded in their Fort Worth apartment, left with just a few pieces
of furniture and no community support. It was in their plight that
Pat Friar and scores of fellow members at St. Paul's Lutheran
Church in Fort Worth discovered a thriving ministry. Three years
later, Friar, a volunteer, coordinates a thriving refugee ministry
at St. Paul's. Last week, Friar and other church members drove to
Dallas//Fort Worth Airport to greet their 18th refugee family, this
one from Bosnia. Thus began the now-familiar process of guiding the
newcomers through the difficult adjustment to Texas and America. By
TIM MADIGAN. Story will move in ``a'' national category.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARAY-MEMORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ A new memoir immortalizes the late, beloved Harry
Caray. He spent a near half-century as baseball's best-known,
though, in his later years, not always the best, TV and radio
broadcaster, ending his career with a national audience for his
Chicago Cubs games. By JEFF GUINN. Story will move in ``a''
national category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
