   &QL; 
 &UR; MONEY BUDGET &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; NASDAQ100 - &LR;  How would you like to be able to invest $100,000 in a
single stock, ignore it for 10 years, and wind up with more than
$1.1 million? That's exactly what would have happened if you had
been able to buy a stock representing the red-hot Nasdaq 100 index
at the end of 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, back then there was no single stock representing
the Nasdaq 100, which is made up of the 100 largest nonfinancial
companies traded on the Nasdaq market and is heavily weighted with
high-technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But now you can buy shares in a new entity called the Nasdaq-100
Shares Trust, which began trading on the American Stock Exchange
four weeks ago. By Arthur M. Louis
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEYBAG - &LR;  (column) Question: Is there any place on the Web
where I can find out which credit cards offer the lowest interest
rates? By Arthur M. Louis
</P>
</TEXT>
