A6782 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELDERLY-DRINKING-BOS &LR;      04-05 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-DRINKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY POINTS TO BINGE DRINKING AMONG ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   College students aren't the only ones with drinking problems.
</P>
<P>
   More than 7 percent of elderly Americans are heavy drinkers and
about 4 percent are regular binge drinkers, according to a national
survey released Monday. Half of those binge drinkers say they
consume that much _ five or more alcoholic beverages _ every time
they drink.
</P>
<P>
   While those rates are lower than ones in recent surveys of
college students, they may be even more dangerous. That's because
the elderly are more vulnerable to alcohol-induced conditions
ranging from delerium to low blood pressure, and they are more
likely to be taking drugs that can be harmful when mixed with
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``More older people than you ever could conceive of are drinking
at levels that may be hazardous to their health,'' says Dr. Alison
A. Moore, assistant professor of medicine at UCLA and lead author
of the report in this month's Journal of the American Geriatrics
Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should realize that drinking gets more problematic when
you're older, particularly when you're taking medications for
things like high blood pressure and arthritis.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Delbanco, chief of general medicine at Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center in Boston and former director of the
Commonwealth/Harvard Alcohol Education and Research Program, says
the new study should set off alarms: ``Doctors are very poor at
eliciting honest reports from their patients about their drinking,
and they also often forget that it takes much less alcohol to get
an older patient into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person who drank three to four drinks a day and never
showed anything can break his hip after a glass of wine when he is
old and infirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA report, the most comprehensive ever on alcohol use
among the elderly, was based on a national survey of 3,448 people
65 and older who participated in the first phase of the National
Health and Nutrition Examination Survey. While those figures date
back to 1982, this is the first time results on elderly drinking
have been published and smaller surveys since then suggest habits
have remained consistent in the intervening years.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one percent of those questioned said they had consumed 12
or more drinks during at least one year of their lives, and 79
percent of those said that over the last year they'd had at least
one 12-ounce beer, 5-ounce glass of wine or a drink with 1.5 ounces
of spirits. Among current drinkers, 77 percent drank at least once
a month and 25 percent reported drinking every day.
</P>
<P>
   Nine percent of elderly drinkers said they had consumed five
drinks at a sitting _ the definition of binge drinking _ at least
12 times over the last year. And more than 4 percent of elderly
drinkers said they had five or more drinks every time they consumed
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   That is considerably less than the 43 percent of college
students who said they were binge drinkers in a 1997 survey by the
Harvard School of Public Health. But the prevalence among the
elderly ``still is large, I'm surprised,'' said Dr. Henry Wechsler,
who headed the Harvard study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to take a look at heavy drinking across all age
groups, including those 65 and older,'' added Wechsler. ``Such
drinking presents problems for the drinkers and for those in their
neighborhood and their family.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the problems Wechsler, Moore and others worry about are
the way alcohol can impair acuity while driving, which already
oftentimes is diminished among the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   It typically takes less alcohol to raise the blood alcohol level
in older people than in younger ones, because the elderly have less
lean body mass and less water content in their bodies with which to
dilute the alcohol. That means that binge drinking in the elderly
probably should be defined as having three to four drinks at once,
Moore said, compared to the five-drink standard used in her survey
and the one for college students. Using the lower standards, binge
drinking among the elderly is twice as prevalent as it is with five
drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Moore and her colleagues used a level of more than one drink a
day to define heavy drinking for elderly women, whereas it was more
than two a day for men, because women tend to have lower body
weight and face a greater risk of ailments like cirrhosis at low
levels of alcohol consumption.
</P>
<P>
   So what is a level of alcohol consumption that is okay and can
produce such benefits as lowering the risk of heart disease?
</P>
<P>
   ``One drink a day,'' Moore says, ``generally is a safe range for
all old people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
