<HEADER>
A6783 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-RBACKS-COX     04-05 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-RBACKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williams running backs story
 &HT;    (EDS: Info box at end of story.)
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Great running backs don't necessarily arrive in the NFL with a
flourish, Heisman trophy winner Ricky Williams acknowledged last
week, . As evidence, the former Texas star noted the two dominant
rushers of the 1998 season, Terrell Davis from Denver and Atlanta's
Jamal Anderson, who were sixth- and seventh-round draft choices,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, the nine NFL drafts have produced 29 first-round
backs, but only three of them have played in Super Bowls, and
Emmitt Smith is the only one to win a rushing title.
</P>
<P>
   The decade included more than its share of busts. Former
first-rounders Blair Thomas, Vaughn Dunbar, Tyrone Wheatley,
Rashaan Salaam, Ki-Jana Carter, Lawrence Phillips, Tony Smith,
Tshimanga Biakabutuka, Darrell Thompson and Dexter Carter have
rushed for a combined 12,141 yards and 79 touchdowns. By
comparison, Smith will enter 1999 with 12,566 yards and 125 scores.
</P>
<P>
   Despite knowing that history, Williams acknowledged that he is
more apt to be a guy like Smith than like another first-round
also-ran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams seem to feel they can find the diamond in the rough
somewhere after the first round,'' said Williams, the all-time
Division I-A rushing leader who also scored more points and
touchdowns than anyone in college history. ``But if they want a
diamond who's already rough and ready _ then I'm their man.''
</P>
<P>
   As with Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch, an ever-confident
Williams has been studied to excess by league scouts seeking flaws
in his game _ a penchant for fumbling, a postseason weight gain and
even the size of his hands. Williams fumbled 26 times in four years
at Texas, but he never lost one in the final 10 minutes of a game.
And while he had the smallest hands at the combine _ size 7 3/4 _
he still managed to catch 85 passes in his Longhorns career.
</P>
<P>
   Those questions about Williams, compounded by a record run on
quarterbacks at the beginning of the first round _ passers could be
the top three players selected _ has created a perception that his
draft stock has dropped.
</P>
<P>
   On some teams, cooler heads have prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only weakness I've seen is an inability to hit the
curveball,'' said Terry Bradway, the Kansas City personnel man,
referring to Williams' failed flirtation with baseball.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, coach Mike Ditka is prepared to offer all six of
his choices in this year's draft, along with first- and
third-rounders in 2000, for a shot at Williams. ``He's like (Earl)
Campbell and Walter Payton,'' Ditka said. ``He doesn't have
anything to prove to me. I've seen more than enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining skeptics should get an eyeful today, when Williams
works out in San Diego for league scouts.
</P>
<P>
   His weight is down to 225 pounds, said Tom Shaw, a New
Orleans-based ``performance enchancement specialist'' who trained
Williams. That's 19 pounds less than he weighed at the combine,
when his puffiness alarmed scouts, and 12 pounds under his
bowl-game weight. Shaw has predicted that Williams will run under
4.5 seconds for the 40 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Previewing the running backs
</P>
<P>
   1. Ricky Williams (RB)
</P>
<P>
   Texas 5-10-3/4, 227
</P>
<P>
   Despite naysayers, Heisman winner still is safest pick in entire
draft. Superproductive
</P>
<P>
   workhorse who will carry 25 times a game, should make immediate
impact. More fluid than he looks, decent change of direction,
finishes every run. Only negative is fumbling.
</P>
<P>
   2. Edgerrin James (RB)
</P>
<P>
   Miami (Fla.) 6-0, 216
</P>
<P>
   Smooth runner with deceptive speed for back with so much power.
Patient back, reads blocks well, runs with his pads low and can
make defenders miss. Has quick feet and will cut back in close
quarters. Very young, won't turn 21 until August, still maturing.
</P>
<P>
   3. Rob Konrad (FB)
</P>
<P>
   SYRACUSE 6-3, 251
</P>
<P>
   Often compared to Mike Alstott of Tampa Bay, but isn't as good a
lead-blocker, actually needs to improve in lead-block role. Might
be better in one-back set than as fullback. Is a straight-up runner
who needs to reduce fumbles. Good receiver, adjusts well to ball.
</P>
<P>
   4. Cecil Collins (RB)
</P>
<P>
   McNeese State 5-8-5/8, 209
</P>
<P>
   Injuries and spate of legal problems limited him to six games in
college, so he hasn't played much football over last two seasons.
Instinctive runner with powerful but squat build, strong legs.
Deceptive quickness and long speed. Beware his various court dates.
</P>
<P>
   5. James ``J.J.'' Johnson (RB)
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State 6-1-3/8, 227
</P>
<P>
   Superior physical specimen whose stock is rising. Aggressive
between the tackles and bleeds inside yardage. A little too upright
at times, gears down to make cuts and isn't very elusive. A little
older than you'd like, but willing worker who wants to get better.
</P>
<P>
   6. Kevin Faulk (RB)
</P>
<P>
   LSU 5-7-5/8, 205
</P>
<P>
   Height belies muscular upper body, strong legs and improved
toughness. Loose in hips, will change directions quickly and run
away from defenders. If he gets to the corner, it's trouble. Can do
a lot of things, returns punts and kickoffs and dangerous receiver.
</P>
<P>
   7. Amos Zeroue (RB)
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia 5-7-3/8, 203
</P>
<P>
   Built low to ground but very strong, can bench-press 500 pounds.
Remarkable balance and likes to use spin move to get out of
traffic. Big-play mentality and will take some losses looking for
long run. Some return skills but only average receiver and blocker.
</P>
<P>
   8. Sedrick Irvin (RB)
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State 5-10-3/4, 223
</P>
<P>
   Powerful lower body, but too often tries to dance past defenders
instead of blasting through them. Durable and competitive, with
naturally wide base. Might have softest hands of any back in draft.
Doesn't trust his own speed enough, gets caught from behind.
</P>
<P>
   9. Shawn Bryson (RB/FB)
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee 6-0-1/2, 235
</P>
<P>
   In-between player, not nifty enough for tailback or solid enough
blocker for full-time fullback duty. Still, it's hard to ignore his
productivity and ability to do a lot of things well. Makes
something happen when he gets ball, more athletic than initially
appears.
</P>
<P>
   Others
</P>
<P>
   RB Michael Basnight (North Carolina A&AMP;T), RB Autry Denson (Notre
Dame), RB De'Mond Parker (Oklahoma), FB Terry Jackson (Florida), RB
Joe Montgomery (Ohio State), FB Cecil Martin (Wisconsin), RB Stacey
Mack (Temple), FB Jeff Paulk (Arizona State).
</P>
<P>
   _ On the rise Mike Cloud of Boston College and Missouri's Devin
West won't run away from defenders, but they are explosive to the
hole and love to compete. Limited athletes who made themselves
players.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the decline The all-time NCAA rushing leader, Brian Shay of
Emporia State, is the kind of underdog everyone roots for.
Unfortunately, his story would have a better ending if he had
better quickness.
</P>
<P>
   _ Intriguing Arkansas tailback Madre Hill rushed for 1,387 yards
in 1995, then missed two seasons with reconstructive surgery on
both knees. His medical history is a red flag, but he ran 4.49 at
the combine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sleeper New Hampshire tailback Jerry Azumah was productive at
I-AA level and scouts like his quickness and versatility. He
doesn't have ideal size (5-10, 195) but runs sub-4.5 times and is a
tough competitor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Falcons view Coach Dan Reeves preaches that you never can have
enough good backs, and a knee injury to Byron Hanspard proved that
in '98. Atlanta could use another solid-blocking fullback behind
Bob Christian.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teams in need Cleveland, St. Louis, New Orleans, Kansas City,
New York Giants, New England, Miami, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
