A6784 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-DUVAL-COX     04-05 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-DUVAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peer reviews: Duval `amazing'
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Asked about the $190 million Big Game lottery
drawing tonight, Fred Funk quickly snapped, ``David Duval will win
that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Funk's comment captures the aura that golf's most prodigious
winner has created among his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really amazed,'' Steve Stricker said after a practice
round Monday for the Masters at Augusta National. ``Who would have
thought David would have four wins before the Masters? Or that he'd
set an earnings mark already? It looks easy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Stricker, Duval had the look of a consistent winner
before he actually won. ``I played with him about three or four
years ago,'' Stricker recalled. ``He hadn't won. I can't remember
where, but my wife was caddying for me. I told her then: `He might
be the best player in the world.' I could see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's obvious everything's clicking at the same time.
Sooner or later, you think he'll come down off this cloud he's on,
but he's still playing great.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory in this week's Masters would be Duval's first major
and, undoubtedly, would elevate him into the stratosphere
professionally and publicly. His national fame probably still
trails Tiger Woods'.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that ``he hasn't won a major,'' John Huston said.
``And that's just a matter of time. Once he does that, everything
will fall into place.
</P>
<P>
   He has struck the ball flush off the tee, his touch around the
greens has been velvety soft and his putting has been dead-on, but
a measure of good fortune has played a part in a run as successful
as Duval's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of luck,'' Huston said. ``I saw some of his
shots (in the BellSouth Classic) and he got some really nice
breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaks that come with being in an outrageous zone. And yet, many
players hardly seemed surprised at Duval's run of 11 victories in
34 outings. Rather, they were more accepting of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's ridiculous at all; it's impressive,'' Brad
Faxon said. ``It's amazing. Three years ago, people were writing
that he can't close and he can't win. Now, everybody's saying
nobody can beat him.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, a rivalry is warming up between Duval and Woods,
two of golf's biggest names and top players. ``I played with Tiger
a few years after playing with David,'' Faxon said, ``and I said
Tiger was the best, too. They're very similar. They're both very
long off the tee. I don't see a lot of differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval might not show emotion, but he's shown lots of game. ``I
wouldn't say I'm stunned,'' Justin Leonard said. ``I'm thoroughly
impressed. Incredible. If there was somebody's respect he didn't
have, he has it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
