<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NORMAN-CO     04-05 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NORMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Norman: The champ the Masters forgot
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It used to be automatic. A Masters began and Greg
Norman was installed as a co-favorite. It was a pairing as natural
as azaleas and dogwoods.
</P>
<P>
   Then it happened. It wasn't just age _ don't forget, this is a
44-year-old Great White Shark we're talking about. It was The
Collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Here in 1999, there is little difference of opinion about Greg
Norman and the Masters. Most observers think that Norman, a rebuilt
shoulder notwithstanding, is toast at Augusta National since the
6-shot, 54-hole lead vanished in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was no occasion to judge Norman; his shoulder throbbed
so much he sometimes had no idea where the ball was going. However,
he also missed the cut in 1997 in his first appearance since The
Green Jacket That Got Away.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, Norman seems to have made more
disappearances than appearances. Before the surgery, he also missed
the cut at the U.S. Open, then tied for 36th at the British Open
and tied for 13th at the PGA. This from the same player who won two
British Opens, 1986 and 1993, and on eight occasions was a major
championship runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a virus kept Norman from playing in the BellSouth
Classic at the TPC of Sugarloaf he designed in Duluth, Ga. He came
to Augusta on Monday, still trying to regather his strength from
the illness, but no one had a chance to ask what travels through
his mind this week, after he became at least physically prepared to
handle the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Norman, ranked 28th, would not have made this
week's Masters field without the new eligibility requirements that
include the top 50 of the world rankings, but he could have
received an international invitation. However, he does not talk
like a player who will be accepting, for example, USGA exemptions
to the U.S. Open, as Jack Nicklaus has done in his late 50s. ``I
don't want to be out here,'' Norman said. ``I don't want to take up
space when somebody else who is 21, 20, could be out here playing.
It's like John Elway. He's the only one who knows if he's going to
play or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in here,'' he said, pointing to his heart. ``I don't want
to sit around and just come out here and walk on the green grass
just to take up space and breathe up oxygen.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Norman still have the hunger to win? Or is it merely to
play well enough, contending every once in a while somewhere on the
globe to keep his business interests sufficiently prominent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never been driven to being No. 1,'' Norman said this
spring. ``I have been very honest about that for many, many years.
I am driven to be a competitor, and if you're a competitor on the
golf course, and your performance on the golf course is good
enough, everything else takes care of itself. I'm the same in
business. You come down to the final day, if you've got a chance to
win the golf tournament, you go, you do it. If you have a chance on
a business deal, you go, you do it. It's very much the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman seldom speaks about the mental residue from Augusta '96,
nor do people often ask. Immediately after the 78 from hell that
Sunday in April, he bared his every private thought. Nothing was
left to say. Later, Norman would marvel at the outpouring from fans
he never imagined were on his side.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, Norman was at the Masters, but just
barely. His shoulder hurting, he shot 76-78 and headed home,
embarrassed and ready for the knife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so happy I missed the cut,'' Norman told Jeff Babineau
of Golfweek. ``I remember sitting at my locker, and I was glad to
be getting out of there. I didn't want to play. We're talking about
Augusta National _ can you imagine that? . . . It was just
embarrassing. You should never be out there hitting shots like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes you wonder if the shoulder might have given out under
the pressure of the 1996 Masters Sunday. In its deteriorated,
damaged state, it was common for the shoulder to pop out of joint
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Norman's return at the end of last year showed early results _ a
Shark Shootout win with Steve Elkington and then a jubiliant part
in the Internationals' Presidents Cup win in Australia. But he has
not found similar reinforcement on the PGA Tour this year. Although
able to finish well in the Australian Masters, Norman tied for 19th
at Doral, where he's a three-time winner, and then missed the cut
at The Players Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Norman's swing, which has been slightly flattened by instructor
David Leadbetter, appears solid, but his drives seem to be lacking
some distance. Buddy Nick Price, on the other hand, contends, ``He
looks like the old Greg Norman to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to say because I never played with him
before,'' Atlanta's Stewart Cink said, ``but I don't think he's as
long. He was hitting about even with me and he's usually been
longer. I know he's been working out a lot and lost a lot of
weight. He might have a little difficult time adjusting to that
different kind of frame he's got now.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the adjustment, things can't approach the uneasiness of
last year's Masters for Norman. On what would be his last hole of
the tournament, his shoulder locked up during his tee shot at the
18th. He heeled a driver over the fans' heads along the ropes and
was stunned to see the ball hit a tree and roll back, stopping 30
yards from the teebox.
</P>
<P>
   Norman apparently finds his greatest enjoyment these days from
golf-course design, which draws him a fee of about $1.25 million
per course. His TPC at Sugarloaf in Duluth, which drew national
exposure last week at the BellSouth Classic, was the catalyst for
17 current projects.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of his day, Norman spends several hours rehabilitating
the shoulder and requires a trainer to stretch it for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I had the surgery, I had no desire to go out and hit
golf balls, because I was in so much pain. For the first 20 or 30
swings, I would just have shooting pains down my arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman's surgeon took care of them. It's those Masters' mental
twinges that could be the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
