<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTERNATIONALSOC-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNATIONAL SOCCER NOTES: Manchester United on verge of
another title
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After ending a 42-year drought against Italian teams in European
competition, Manchester United gets another dose of Italy in the
Champions' League semifinals, as the English powerhouse takes aim
this week on a rare triple crown.
</P>
<P>
   United, which ousted Inter Milan in the quarterfinals, hosts
Juventus at Old Trafford in the first semifinal leg Wednesday (2:30
p.m., live ESPN2). The goal is to go far beyond being the first
English team in 31 years to win the European Cup. The current
Premier League leaders are trying to grab their sixth league title
of the '90s and also capture the F.A. Cup. Even normally low-key
manager Alex Ferguson is talking confidently about the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think we can win all three,'' Ferguson said. ``I've
always been a bit cautious about whether we have a big enough squad
to go for all the prizes, but not now. The treble is definitely on,
and the players are up for it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, United meets Arsenal in an F.A. Cup semifinal
showdown. United holds a four-point lead over the defending
champions after both were held to draws Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Juventus can reach the Champions' League finals for a
fourth year in a row might depend on whether French World Cup hero
Zinedine Zidane is recovered from injury. The defending Italian
champions are out of the hunt for a Serie A title but have played
better since manager Carlo Ancelotti came on board in February.
</P>
<P>
   England: Fowler flap grows
</P>
<P>
   For Liverpool's Robbie Fowler, what goes around has come around.
After gesturing like a cocaine addict to celebrate scoring a goal
Saturday in a 3-2 win over Everton, Fowler faces disciplinary
action from the Football Association. Fowler said he pretended to
snort the goal line to respond to taunts of ``smackhead'' from
Everton fans, who have long accused him of using drugs. The
24-year-old also faces an F.A. hearing Friday for his ongoing row
with Chelsea's Graeme Le Saux. In a February match, Fowler made
vulgar gestures and remarks about homosexuality to Le Saux, who
promptly dropped him to the ground. The Liverpool win, by the way,
was the first over its Merseyside rival since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland: Rangers upset
</P>
<P>
   Glasgow Rangers, which signed American midfielder Claudio Reyna
last week and seemingly had a chokehold on its ninth title in the
last 10 years, was upset 3-1 by St. Johnstone on Sunday and now
leads Celtic by only six points in the Premier League. Reyna, who
had been playing sparingly at Wolfsburg in Germany, was transferred
for an estimated $3.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Goal drought ends
</P>
<P>
   Bayern Munich goalkeeper Oliver Kahn gave up his first goal in
736 minutes Saturday in a 2-2 draw with Borussia Dortmund, but his
team still leads the Bundesliga by a healthy 15 points. ...
However, Bayern will be missing some key players Wednesday in its
Champions' League semifinal with Dynamo Kyiv (4:45 p.m., ESPN2).
Leading scorer Giovanne Elber and defender Bixente Lizarazu are out
for the season with knee injuries.
</P>
<P>
   France: Leaders play leapfrog
</P>
<P>
   Olympique Marseille vaulted into the lead in the Le Championnat
(first division) race Friday with a 2-1 win over Monaco but lost it
Saturday as Bordeaux beat Toulouse 3-1 to grab the advantage by a
point. Marseille, with 62 points, plays Bologna today in the UEFA
Cup semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Lazio streak continues
</P>
<P>
   Although held to a 0-0 draw with AC Milan on Saturday, Lazio
maintained a six-point Serie A lead and extended its unbeaten
streak to 17 matches. The Rome club plays Lokomotiv Moscow on
Thursday in the first leg of the semifinals of the Cup Winners'
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Rivaldo hat trick
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian Rivaldo scored all three goals, two of them coming on
penalty kicks, as Barcelona stayed on top of the Primera Division
with a 3-1 win over Oviedo. Rivaldo has 18 goals for the season. .
. . Two Primera Clubs are still alive in European competition.
Atletico Madrid plays Parma today in the semifinals of the UEFA
Cup, while Mallorca meets Chelsea Thursday in the Cup Winners' Cup.
. . Real Madrird's Predraj Mijatovic has been fined more than
$32,000 by the club for refusing to play in Saturday's 3-2 win over
Alaves in protest of NATO bombing of his native Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil: Fan shot dead
</P>
<P>
   A 20-year-old man was shot in the head and killed Sunday during
skirmishes at Rio's Maracana Stadium before a match between city
rivals Fluminese and Flamengo. . . Former national team coach Mario
Zagallo isn't faring well in his return to domestic coaching. His
Portugesa team lost 5-1 to Barbarense Saturday and currently is
near the bottom of its group in the Sao Paulo league.
</P>
<P>
   MLS: Razov on Fire
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Ante Razov scored two goals and Peter Nowak added two
more as MLS champion Chicago Fire routed the Miami Fusion 4-1
Saturday. Razov, who has six goals in the Fire's three games, was
named MLS player of the month for March. . . . Raul Diaz Arce ended
a salary holdout and scored a goal as the San Jose Clash stunned
Los Angeles 2-1 in a shootout. . . . Roy Lassiter's second-half
goal for D.C. United beat the MetroStars 1-0. . . . Kansas City's
Wizards extended their MLS scoreless record to 550 minutes in a 1-0
loss to the New England Revolution. . . . Brian McBride knocked
home a late header as the Columbus Crew beat the Tampa Bay Mutiny
3-2. . . . Former Heritage High star Clint Mathis, playing a
leading role with the L.A. Galaxy, is profiled in the current issue
of Soccer America magazine.
</P>
<P>
   FROM THE GRAPEVINE
</P>
<P>
   Mallorca goalkeeper Carlos Roa said he might have to retire
because of his religious beliefs. Roa, the 29-year-old Argentine
who came up big in a penalty-kick win over England in the World Cup
last summer, is an Adventist rarely able to take part in worship
activities because of playing commitments on Saturdays. Earlier
this year, Roa expressed an interest in playing for Manchester
United, which will lose the retiring Peter Schmeichel after the
season.
</P>
<P>
   TOP PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   In his first match as a team captain, Ronaldo scored twice, both
goals on penalty kicks, as Inter Milan dealt a major blow to
Fiorentina's Italian scudetto hopes Saturday in a 2-0 win at San
Siro. Ronaldo, battling season-long knee injuries, helped Inter to
its first Serie A win since Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
