<HEADER>
A6798 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RELATIVE-SPI &LR;      04-05 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RELATIVE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC'S `EVERYTHING'S' RELATIVELY UNSOPHISTICATED SITCOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Described as a ``sophisticated'' comedy by the NBC publicity
mill, ``Everything's Relative'' is as sophisticated as just about
every other comedy on television. Which is to say, not very.
</P>
<P>
   For example, here's the putative central character, Leo Gorelick
(Kevin Rahm), having a talk with his mom, Mickey (Jill Clayburgh),
about her desire to meddle in the life of her ex-husband, Jake
(Jeffrey Tambor), even though they've been divorced 20 years:
``Mom, I just want you to be happy, OK? And I don't think that you
can be happy living your life purely in a reaction to his.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickey's reply: ``You're the one who always said living well is
the best revenge. Well, that's all I'm doing. I'm going to live
well and I'm going to shove it up your father's ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahhh, the sweet, sweet smell of sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just me. But Jill Clayburgh looks as likely to utter
those words as my own mom. Which is to say, fat chance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clayburgh's sly portrayal of Mickey is the best thing
about ``Everything's Relative,'' a series about two obsessive
parents who can't let go of their adult sons. Imagine what might
happen with an even more ``sophisticated'' script. Jake might be
less of a cheesy vulgarian, Leo might be a better defined central
character, and Leo's brother, Marty (Eric Schaeffer), might be more
than a one-note whiner. But with only three more chances to make an
impression _ only four episodes were made _ it's likely that
``Everything's Relative,'' despite some clever moments, is going to
be relatively disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Everything's Relative. Half-hour comedy series about a young
comedy writer and his close-knit but overbearing family. Starring
Kevin Rahm, Jeffrey Tambor, Jill Clayburgh and Eric Schaeffer.
Premieres Tuesday night on NBC. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6803 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLAINE-HNS &LR;      04-05 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLAINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID BLAINE BAFFLES AND AMAZES WITH MIND-BLOWING UP-CLOSE MAGIC 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) David Blaine, on foot, stops a car and asks its
driver, a middle-aged man with a heavy accent, permission to look
at his wristwatch.
</P>
<P>
   The man removes the watch, and Blaine shows it to a cameraman,
who's documenting the encounter for an ABC special to air April 14.
The watch reads 5 o'clock, almost straight up.
</P>
<P>
   He returns the watch to the man and, while the man clenches it
in his right fist, Blaine asks him to name a number between 10 and
30.
</P>
<P>
   ``25,'' the man says.
</P>
<P>
   Blaine cups the man's hand, then announces, ``We're going to
make the clock go to 25.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you feel it moving?'' Blaine asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah-yeah-yeah,'' says the man, excitedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Done,'' says Blaine, with a clap of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The man opens his fist. The watch reads 5:25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look-look-look,'' says the man, showing the watch to his
female passenger. ``Oh, mama mia, I can't believe that. That's
incredible!''
</P>
<P>
   No, that's David Blaine, a 25-year-old magician who not only
wants to test your mind, he wants to blow it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to mystify,'' says Blaine recently, speaking in a deep
monotone from New York, where Monday he was buried alive (more on
that in a moment).
</P>
<P>
   ``Mystery is the most important emotion that humans are
lacking,'' he says. ``As they get older and more logical, they
really leave big voids in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little babies see faces on the doors and in the dark and on
the walls. It's amazing. But as (you) get older, (your parents)
tell you, `Oh, it's not real,' and you start to pretend you don't
see them, and the mystery disappears.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who saw Blaine's first TV special are familiar with his
unusual style. He is a street magician who specializes in up-close
tricks. In the first special, 18 months ago, he freaked people out
by, among other stunts, levitating himself a few inches off a city
sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   For next week's show, ``David Blaine: Magic Man,'' he performs
feats so intense and personal that they leave some of his subjects
speechless and in tears. He resurrects what appears to be a dead
fly. He looks at a person's palm and tells him what card he's
thinking of. He gets a police officer to pick a card, then drops
the deck on the sidewalk; he tells him to check his shoe _ and the
officer's card is inside.
</P>
<P>
   He makes a chicken's head disappear and reappear, he
``projects'' the image of a card so that it appears as a tattoo on
a man's chest, and he swallows a long piece of thread, lifts his
shirt and pulls it out of his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Most spectacularly, he can walk up to a stranger, ask her to
write down the name of someone special to her, then reveal that
name in unusual ways. Once he appears to burn his arm, and the
smoke-black residue reveals the name. Another time the name appears
on a passing taxi.
</P>
<P>
   You have to see it to understand it and believe it _ and then,
in disbelief, you still won't understand.
</P>
<P>
   Blaine's subjects are unsuspecting strangers on the street, and
their reactions are as priceless as the tricks themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not magic, that's some crazy stuff,'' says one
confounded subject. ``How did you do that?''
</P>
<P>
   That's one question Blaine's not likely to answer. In fact,
Blaine isn't a person to reveal much of anything _ about his
tricks, his personal life, his past or his motives. That fits into
his image as true mystery man.
</P>
<P>
   What little we do know is that Blaine was born in Brooklyn and
raised in New Jersey, and decided, at age 16, to move back to New
York, alone. His parents were raised as Gypsies, and he knew at age
4 that magic was for him.
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't perfecting his craft on city streets, he hung out
with ``beautiful people'' _ Leonardo DiCaprio, Robert De Niro _ and
did tricks for their friends. DiCaprio hosted Blaine's first TV
special, in which Blaine visited several cities across the nation,
plus the Dallas Cowboys' locker room (Deion Sanders and Emmitt
Smith are Blaine fans).
</P>
<P>
   For this second special, he hits the streets of New York,
Memphis, Nashville and New Orleans, then journeys to remote areas
of Haiti and South America to impress the often-superstitious
people there.
</P>
<P>
   His entourage can include up to a dozen people, from a
photographer and a sound guy to someone who gets releases so faces
and IDs can be used on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cameraperson is not in on the trick,'' Blaine assures. ``I
just say, `Try to shoot everything, action, then reaction.'''
</P>
<P>
   He is not shy about walking up to strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty great thing,'' he said, speaking of the
reactions he gets. ``I like it better when there's no camera. In
fact, next show we're going to use hidden cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The question is whether there will be a next show. Monday he
was buried alive in a Plexiglas coffin in front of Trump Place in
New York. The coffin was lowered 6 feet into the ground. It will
remain visible from above, so people can watch him suffer.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is a tribute to Harry Houdini, a favorite of Blaine's.
Houdini wanted to do the stunt but died before he could attempt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to blur the line between tricks and reality,'' Blaine
says. ``I just do what I feel. Some are tricks. Some are real. It's
just whatever works for that moment.''
</P>
<P>
   He will go without food and ``only 3 to 4 tablespoons of water''
a day _ only enough to keep him alive, says promoter (and theater
producer) James Nederlander.
</P>
<P>
   The stunt, Blaine admits, intimidates him ``a little bit.'' It's
hard to practice these kinds of things, he explains. ``I guess it's
the same as preparing for death,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Should he make it _ he's scheduled to emerge Monday (April 12) _
he'll start work on a third TV special and more mind-blowing feats.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
