</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANDED FAMILY LEADS TO REFUGEE CENTER AT TEXAS CHURCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When their refugee resettlement agency
folded, the Bosnian mother and her four children were virtually
stranded in their Fort Worth apartment, left with just a few pieces
of furniture and no community support.
</P>
<P>
   It was in their plight that Pat Friar and scores of fellow
members at St. Paul's Lutheran Church discovered a thriving
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, `Here is a place where we can really help
someone,' '' says Friar, a retired office manager who met the
family when her church was asked to step in. ``They had nothing. It
was something I think we were looking for without realizing we were
looking for it. It was just like coming home to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Friar, a volunteer, coordinates a thriving
refugee ministry at St. Paul's. Last week, Friar and other church
members drove to Dallas/Fort Worth Airport to greet their 18th
refugee family, this one from Bosnia. Thus began the now-familiar
process of guiding the newcomers through the difficult adjustment
to Texas and America.
</P>
<P>
   Like the latest arrivals, most of the families have come from
the troubled Balkans. St. Paul's has also assisted families from
Sudan, Burma and Vietnam. Most of them come with only a suitcase of
belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all get more out of it than we put in,'' Friar says.
``We're looking at people who have had really bad breaks, and we're
sitting fat, dumb and happy in America. All of them have horror
stories. They've lost everything, been on the run for years. In
some cases there's physical abuse. It's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Friar's church is a key cog in a resettlement network that has
made North Texas a common destination for people driven from their
homelands. Last year, Refugee Services of North Texas, a nonprofit
organization, resettled 244 people from 67 families, often with the
assistance of area churches.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees have a well-founded fear of persecution in their
native countries based on religious, political or social beliefs.
Resettlement workers expect that many of the thousands of ethnic
Albanians currently fleeing Kosovo will ultimately end up in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Refugee Services attempts to find church sponsors for each
incoming family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important part, besides their donations, is the time
they're able to spend with the families,'' Emily Russ, a caseworker
with Refugee Services, says of the church assistance. ``With the
size of our staff, we can't sit down and have coffee every day, or
go over there. A church's involvement allows more of that.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day in a Fort Worth apartment, Friar seemed like kin
to Ivan Kis and his family of four, who fled Bosnia after Bosnian
soldiers ransacked the family's house and attacked Kis' wife in
1992. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But though her week is consumed with refugee work, Friar
deflects credit to the 80 or so people from St. Paul's who also
contribute. One man repairs appliances that the refugees may use; a
group of church men move furniture that another person has stored.
Other St. Paul members gather refugees from the airport, drive them
to an apartment they have readied, take the family for medical
exams and inoculations, drive them for groceries, help get the
children enrolled in school and get the adults jobs, and counsel
the refugees during a confusing and often frightening time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we stay in touch with them,'' Friar says. ``We want to be
friends with them after their needs have been taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Friar says, the refugees often seem confused by the
generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're surprised that people are helping them with no gain in
mind,'' Friar says. ``But God is the one who's doing it. There is
no way we could have put together what we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
