<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6805 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARAY-MEMORY-TEX     04-05 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARAY-MEMORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOT, ROOT, ROOT FOR HARRY CARAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though the official first pitch of the 1999 major league
season has already been thrown out, no baseball season ever really
begins until a really good book about the sport hits the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Well, batter up, then, because Steve Stone's ``Where's Harry?''
captures the fun, nostalgia and occasional plain silliness that
baseball is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Caray was truly a living contradiction,'' Stone says.
``Most of us don't have the nerve to live the way Harry did. He was
absolutely unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone spent 15 years playing understudy to Caray on the WGN-TV
superstation in Chicago. Caray spent a near half-century as
baseball's best-known, though, in his later years, not always the
best TV and radio broadcaster. First with the St. Louis Cardinals,
then with the Oakland Athletics, the Chicago White Sox and,
finally, the Chicago Cubs, Caray called 'em like he saw 'em, but
how he saw 'em was sometimes influenced by how much he was still
feeling the effects of the night before, or whether he was upset
with his producer for not providing more shots of buxom fans in the
bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   And yet 90 percent of his viewers and listeners loved him,
probably because, Stone postulates, Caray acted the way blue-collar
baseball fans thought they would if somehow they could switch
places with ol' Harry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always said he worked for the fans,'' Stone said. ``If they
liked what he had to say, that was what was most important to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The title of ``Where's Harry?'' reflects the question Stone says
he was repeatedly asked during his stint with Caray in the WGN
booth, and what they still want to know two years after Caray's
death at age 83.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's Harry?'' works wonderfully well, and the reason is
Stone's determination to show Caray in all his warty glory. We read
about generous Harry, who never met a good cause he wouldn't try to
help or a stranger he wouldn't try to turn into a Cubs fan. We wipe
away a few tears learning about Harry the orphan boy and Grandpa
Harry who missed quality time with his children but harvested a lot
of love with a late-life third marriage and extended family.
</P>
<P>
   But we also meet Harry the Paranoid, who was always convinced
somebody was trying to steal his job; Harry the Jerk, who
mistreated Stone on the air when a business partnership didn't work
out as planned; Harry the Dirty Old Man, who never met a pretty
young woman he didn't like; and Harry the shameless self-promoter.
</P>
<P>
   Stone is also honest about his tumultuous relationship with
Caray. There were times, he admits, when Caray's spotlight-hogging
grew tedious. He enjoys his professional role a lot more now that
Caray's laid-back grandson, Chip, shares the WGN booth at Wrigley
Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Harry and me, it was like a marriage with all the ups and
downs,'' Stone said. ``I always realized I owed Harry a great debt.
He had the power at any given time to say to the bosses he wanted
me out of there, but he never did.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Steve Stone, like baseball fans all over, misses Harry
Caray. The gregarious old-timer's good points far outweighed the
bad, Stone concludes, and baseball will never see his like again.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is an underlying theme in ``Where's Harry?,'' one
certainly not intended by the author, it is that Harry Caray was
almost as lucky to spend 15 years working with Steve Stone. Great
performers need great support; and, happily enough, ``Where's
Harry?'' qualifies as a great baseball book. If you loved Harry, or
if you love baseball, read it.
___
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1997, (basketball star) Michael Jordan visited Wrigley
Field, and Cubs officials went to his skybox to ask him if he
wanted to come up to the (WGN) booth and spend a few minutes with
Harry, who absolutely adored Michael.
</P>
<P>
   ```No way,' Michael said. `I can't do it.'
</P>
<P>
   ```Why not?' '' asked a befuddled Cubs official.
</P>
<P>
   ```I love Harry,' Michael said, `but I don't want to go on the
air and have him introduce me as Michael Jackson.' ''
_ from Where's Harry,? by Steve Stone with Barry Rozner.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
