<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ARMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SOLDIERS BUILD CAMP IN ALBANIA FOR REFUGEE RELIEF EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-BASES,
KOSOVO-ECON) 
(nk) 
 By STEVE LEVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Working under blazing runway lights, an
advance crew of American soldiers worked late Monday preparing a
camp from which about 6,000 U.S. troops will coordinate an airlift
of supplies for the ethnic Albanian refugees who have flooded this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five soldiers arriving in two large military transports
began building the camp next to Rinas Airport, on the edge of
Tirana, the capital. It will serve as a distribution point for aid
to the more than 200,000 refugees who have entered Albania so far.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have described the effort as a humanitarian
mission, and have repeatedly denied that any ground offensive is
planned.
</P>
<P>
   But local radio stations Monday buzzed with the news of the
American arrival, which many people here took as a signal that NATO
ground operations would soon begin in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much criticism among foreign officials here of
the many days it has taken relief organizations, including those of
the United Nations, to get large-scale assistance to the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But the American relief missions Monday, in addition to others
from Italy and Turkey, turned Tirana's tiny airport into a bustling
center from which cargo trucks laden with supplies filed out onto
the main highway late into the night. American officials said that
up to 500 men would be required to build the base camp before the
thousands of U.S. soldiers arrive to handle the airbridge.
</P>
<P>
   Six more American C-130 cargo planes were to arrive in Albania
on Tuesday, and the pace was to accelerate to 10 supply flights a
day by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials said that, in addition to the trucks, six
helicopters were already ferrying supplies between the airport and
the northern Albanian city of Kukes, near the Kosovo border, where
many of the refugees are living on the street and in open fields.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
