r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RELATIVE-SFCHRON &LR;      04-05 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RELATIVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAST IS THE BEST THING ABOUT NBC'S `RELATIVE' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Everything's Relative'' has a fine cast, a relatively modest
laugh track and flying broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the laugh track has good reason for its modesty.
</P>
<P>
   The NBC midseason sitcom, which premieres Tuesday, is bright,
perky and lily white, just the way NBC likes its comedies.
</P>
<P>
   It's about a young comedy writer, Leo Gorelick (Kevin Rahm) _
it's so nice to see TV writers broaden their horizons _ and his
wacky family.
</P>
<P>
   Wacky family member No. 1 is Leo's father, Jake (Jeffrey
Tambor), who is an L.A. kind of dad.
</P>
<P>
   He's a long-divorced attorney, he's self-absorbed, he wants to
be buddies with his sons and he thinks all women are in love with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Wacky family member No. 2 is Leo's mother, Mickey (Jill
Clayburgh), a clinical psychologist and expert on obsession who is,
naturally, raucously obsessive about her family.
</P>
<P>
   Wacky family member No. 3 is Leo's older brother, Marty (Eric
Schaeffer), a twice-married doctor who's homing in on his third
bride.
</P>
<P>
   The problems here seem to be about on the level of ``The
Adventures of Ozzie and Harriet.'' They just seem more worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   The gist of Tuesday night's pilot, for example, is Leo's concern
that his mother may move into his neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Rahm was somewhere in the film ``Clay Pigeons'' and has appeared
in such high-visibility TV shows as ``Pacific Blue'' and ``Rescue
77'' _ which are, I believe, publicly subsidized work projects for
young actors. Keeps 'em off the streets.
</P>
<P>
   But he's agreeable as the obligatory oasis of sanity in the eye
of the comedy storm. Rahm reminds me a little of David Spade, but
more palatable.
</P>
<P>
   The casting coups are Tambor and Clayburgh. Tambor is fresh from
six years as the pathetic Hank Kingsley on HBO's ``The Larry
Sanders Show.'' Clayburgh might not have been burning up theater
marquees in recent years, but she was, by golly, an Oscar nominee
for ``An Unmarried Woman'' and ``Starting Over.''
</P>
<P>
   Tambor is a seasoned comedy actor who can do annoying in several
variations. He's not another Hank Kingsley here. No, Jake is a (set
ital)confidently(end ital) annoying individual. But the producers
better be careful. A little can be a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The refreshing thing about Clayburgh is that she acts her
comedy. Despite being wacky family member No. 2, Mickey is the most
authentic character in the show.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose you've been wondering about the flying broccoli. It
floats through the air in a kind of fantasy sequence _ Leo feeling
oppressed by his family.  &QL; 
There's also a wacky vegetable No. 2, played by cauliflower.
</P>
<P>
   The writing isn't up to the level of acting talent. And the four
most frequently occurring words in the script seem to be ``the,''
``a,'' ``ass'' and ``hump.'' Not necessarily in that order.
</P>
<P>
   The show begins with Jake and Leo in a men's clothing store.
They go to a counter to ask about a particular label of shirts.
Something is wrong with the clerk.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' says the clerk. ``Uh, how do I explain this? OK, my name
is Tim Inman, right? That's my name. OK. So, uh, OK, you know my
name's Tim Inman.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes on for a while. The laugh track is amused but has the
good grace not to howl. You, however, may feel free to groan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
