<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 4 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton said today that
the United States was committed to a relentless bombing campaign in
Serbia for ``the long haul'' if the Yugoslav President, Slobodan
Milosevic, did not withdraw his police units from Kosovo and work
toward a political settlement that would allow the refugees to
return home. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO today gave its military commander
the authority he wanted to send 24 U.S. Apache helicopter gunships
to Albania, with surface-to-surface missiles and about 2,000
American soldiers who will use them to attack Serbian forces across
the border in Kosovo. Other developments. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   With a graphic and a map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Senior officials of the Clinton
administration have refrained from using the words ``genocide'' or
``war criminal'' in describing Slobodan Milosevic and his actions
in Kosovo. This is in part, according to one of the officials
involved in the policy, because the administration is likely to end
up having to negotiate with Milosevic. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ Refugees pouring into Albania
from Kosovo have been bringing with them detailed firsthand
accounts of mass killings and burned corpses. The reports have been
so frequent and so repetitive in their detail that officials have
brought in 60 specially trained investigators to interview refugees
and keep records for possible war-crimes indictments. By John
Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INTEL (Washington) _ A surveillance photo made public
today does show armored vehicles and civilians being routed, but
intelligence officials say that so far they have seen no evidence
of mass graves. By Steven Lee Myers. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Blace, Macedonia) _ With tens of thousands of
fleeing Albanians backed up in dismal conditions at the Macedonian
border, international relief officials today accused Macedonia of
endangering lives by processing the refugees too slowly. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ As Serbia tried to
clean up today after NATO's most intensive bombing raids so far,
Serbian television once again gave prominence to a moderate ethnic
Albanian leader, Ibrahim Rugova, and his separate meetings today
with a senior Yugoslav official and the Russian ambassador. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (London) _ The extensive news reporting of the
plight of the Kosovo refugees is having a powerful effect on public
opinion across Europe, turning pacifists and anti-NATO activists of
decades ago and anti-NATO critics of just a week ago into
supporters of sustained bombing. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ARMY (Tirana) _ Working under blazing runway lights, an
advance crew of American soldiers worked late into the night
preparing a camp from which some 6,000 U.S. troops ultimately will
man a humanitarian airlift to Kosovar Albanian refugees who have
flooded this country. By Stephen Levine.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FAMILIES (New York) _ Some ethnic-Albanians still inside
Kosovo have been able to contact their families here by phone. By
David W. Chen.
</P>
