<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALOMARS-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROTHERS TOGETHER IN CLEVELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: BBO-FAMOUS-BROTHERS) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By DICK SCANLON   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTER HAVEN, Fla. _ Many sets of brothers have played in the
major leagues. Some never got to play together.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre never played with Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Three DiMaggios played simultaneously, but never on the same
team.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Aaron and Cal Ripken Jr. didn't have much more than a ``cup
of coffee'' with their younger brothers.
</P>
<P>
   So, Sandy Alomar Jr. and his brother, Robbie _ reunited with the
Cleveland Indians _ aren't taking it for granted. But it wouldn't
have been easy picking out the brothers after spending a few
minutes in the Indians' clubhouse in Winter Haven this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Your first guess might have been Robbie and Wil Cordero, a
fellow Puerto Rican whose locker stall was right next to Robbie's,
across the large room from Sandy's locker.
</P>
<P>
   Both new to the Indians, Robbie Alomar and Cordero talked a lot
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy, who as a catcher and an Indian veteran had a different
set of responsibilities, stood apart and aloof.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably gonna hit us on opening day,'' Sandy said. ``In
spring training we're not really focusing on playing together.
We're concentrating on fundamentals and getting ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when everything is ready and you go out there to play
ball, I think that's when you'll say: `Wow, I'm playing with my
brother!'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when it'll be a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it won't be the first time. They played one game
together in 1988 and seven games in 1989 for the San Diego Padres
before Sandy was traded to the Indians. Since then, each have
played in the World Series twice. They have combined for 15
All-Star appearances, each winning an All-Star MVP award, and eight
Gold Gloves.
</P>
<P>
   But they rarely saw each other during the season.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of Robbie joining the Indians has been a Hot
Stove League topic for several years. He signed a four-year, $32
million contract on Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought it was gonna happen,'' Robbie said. ``They
were trying to make some trades, but it wasn't the right time. Now
is the right time, and looking at this club made my decision
easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother was here, I knew that. Sandy was part of the
decision. But I play this game to win, and we've got a chance to
win. And Cleveland was the most interested in my services.''
</P>
<P>
   Second base has been the Indians' weakest position since the
trade of Carlos Baerga in 1996. Now it is a strength. Robbie Alomar
will bat second or third and provide power and speed. Defensively,
he may be the best second baseman in the game.
</P>
<P>
   His older brother says it goes beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things in baseball that fans don't
understand, things you can't see from the stands,'' Sandy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans only see what happens on the action, but there's a lot of
stuff that happens in the dugout that nobody sees, but it helps
players perform better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie's a student of the game. He knows everything the
pitcher's doing. He figures things out very quickly, and that helps
out other players.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways they are very different.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy, who will be 33 in June, is married and has two children.
His career is identified with one team. He bats right-handed and
runs slowly. He's a catcher. He has become something of a
weightlifting fanatic and has built up his 6-foot-5 frame to more
than 220 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Robbie, who just turned 31, is single and engaged to tennis star
Mary Pierce. The Indians are his fourth major-league team. He is
listed at 6-foot, 185 pounds. He is a switch-hitter. Quickness is a
a big part of his game. He has stolen 340 bases.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from being the sons of Sandy Alomar, who played 15
major-league seasons with five different baseball teams and is now
a roving instructor in the Chicago Cubs' organization, they also
have much in common.
</P>
<P>
   Both Alomars are coming off disappointing seasons. Both feel an
urgency to win this season. And neither has given much thought to
the brothers who played before them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't lie to you ... when the Alous played together, I was
probably 6 or 7 years old,'' Sandy said. ``I can't remember any
other brother combination other than George Brett and Ken Bett or
some of the guys when my dad was playing. I didn't really pay
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Robbie: ``They played with my dad. When you're a kid,
you're just playing baseball. You're not thinking about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe now you think about the other brothers who have played,
the DiMaggios, the Alous, the Ripkens and those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   But it beats playing against each other, as they have twice in
the playoffs. The Orioles eliminated the Indians in 1996, and the
Indians prevailed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Robbie recalls some childhood spats with Sandy, but says they
have always been close.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest thing,'' Robbie said, ``is to play against your
brother because he doesn't want you to go 0-for-4, or you don't
want him to come up with a man on third and two out and the game on
the line. Who are you gonna pull for?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm glad that's not gonna happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dick Scanlon writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.)
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
