<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO BEGINS FLYING REFUGEES TO 'TEMPORARY' HAVENS
 &HT;    1STLEDE WRITETHRU TO NOTE NUMBER OF REFUGEES REFLECTS THOSE IN
ALBANIA
 &HT;    With COX-KOSOVO-MAIN, COX-KOSOVO-POWS
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. and SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ NATO forces waging an air war against
Yugoslavia also acted as a ``good Samaritan'' on Monday, beginning
an airlift of some of the 230,000 ethnic Albanians who have fled
Kosovo for Albania in the past 13 days.
</P>
<P>
   But even as a plane carrying the first 150 refugees landed in
western Turkey, President Clinton and his NATO allies emphasized
that moving the refugees to safe havens in allied countries is only
a temporary response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ethnic cleansing of Kosovo cannot stand as a permanent
event,'' Clinton said during a brief appearance in the Roosevelt
Room of the White House to announce ``Operation Sustain Hope,'' a
stepped-up effort to help the Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refugees belong in their own homes on their own land,'' he
said. ``Our immediate goal is to provide relief. Our long-term goal
is to give them their right to return.''
</P>
<P>
   To better coordinate the humanitarian assistance, Clinton
established a panel headed by Brian Atwood, the administrator of
the U.S. Agency for International Development (AID). In addition,
he ordered a toll-free telephone number for private citizens who
want to help: 1-800-USAID RELIEF (cq.).
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO wants to be a good Samaritan,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea
said in Brussels, ``but we are not a refugee organization.''
Consequently, NATO has turned to the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to coordinate assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am encouraged that western governments appreciate the
enormity of the refugee drama, which can no longer be handled by
Kosovo's immediate neighbors alone,'' High Commissioner Sadako
Ogata said in a statement from Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   In the first wave of humanitarian assistance by NATO, allied
aircraft delivered nearly 200 tons of food and emergency supplies
to refugees in Albania and Macedonia. NATO called the relief
flights a ``humanitarian air bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the continuing flow of refugees out of Kosovo is
threatening to overwhelm Albania and Macedonia, where most of these
fleeing have gathered.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that can be said is that the situation is critical,''
Albanian President Rexhep Meidana said in an interview Monday.
``I'm quite sure this flow will continue and in the next days there
will be many, many more refugees in Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Meidana said he does not support plans by NATO to
temporarily place more than 100,000 refugees in other countries.
There is a fear here that the refugees may never come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must remain near their land and their houses,'' Meidana
said. ``They must return to Kosovo as soon as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the refugees will never return to their homes in Kosovo
unless there are NATO troops in the province to maintain their
