<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6826 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-HEALTH-BOS &LR;      04-05 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-HEALTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS FEAR MASS DEATHS IN REFUGEE CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ More than 50,000 refugees stranded in an open
field on the Kosovo border will begin to die in large numbers if
they are not moved out of what one doctor called a ``human
cesspit'' within a couple of days, medical authorities said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   There was little prospect of meeting that timetable, however,
because the Macedonian government is refusing to cede to the United
Nations the responsibility for processing the refugees, which has
been a painfully show process. The result is a human logjam in an
open field, where a lack of clean water and sanitary facilities
threatens to cause an epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has built a huge refugee handling center just a few miles
from the open field at Blace. The United Nations said it was
capable of moving up to 20,000 people a day to the center and to
other inland camps. By Monday night, however, only a few thousand
had been moved.
</P>
<P>
   At least 120,000 refugees have entered Macedonia in the last
week, 65,000 streaming into the open field at Blace just last
Thursday and Friday, when Serb troops began packing them on trains
and forcefully expelling them from Pristina, the Kosovo capital.
The Macedonian government says it cannot afford to allow more than
20,000 refugees to stay here, insisting that the others be moved on
to other countries immediately.
</P>
<P>
   But while Western countries, including the United States,
scramble to arrange flights to take the refugees to temporary
shelters abroad, the Macedonians insist on handling the processing
of the ethnic Albanians in the open field. The Macedonians,
however, have deputized only a handful of officials to handle the
registration, creating what medical authorities say is a disastrous
backlog.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a keg of dynamite, waiting to explode,'' said Dr. Tom
Durant, a Boston physician with the American Refugee Committee,
after surveying the field Monday. ``If we don't get them out of
there, we're going to have major problems with all the communicable
diseases. A lot of people will die.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Corbaz, deputy head of the International Red Cross, said
that between 20 and 30 people have already died in the field, most
of them newborns and elderly people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weakest, the smallest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and other medical personnel working with refugees said
the outbreak of dysentery and other diseases is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lex Winkler, director of the humanitarian medical group
Medecins Sans Frontieres, shook his head as he surveyed the huddled
masses. Hundreds collapsed Monday under a hot afternoon sun as Red
Cross volunteers brought them from the field on filthy stretchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ad hoc. We're moving very slowly,'' said Winkler, who
like other physicians here is frustrated that the Macedonian
authorities are not allowing humanitarian agencies to move larger
numbers of refugees out of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees have been using an adjacent river as an open toilet,
and aid workers have been desperately trying to provide bottled
water to prevent an outbreak of dysentery.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are appalling conditions,'' said Winkler. ``The river is
one huge toilet. We're asking for trouble. At most, we have a
couple of days left. If we have dysentery, we'll have a disaster.
It will spread rapidly through the camp. We need clean water and
latrines.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few miles to the south, that clean water and those
latrines are waiting to be used.
</P>
<P>
   The UN and NATO are both trying to maintain good relations with
the Macedonian government, but the situation has grown increasingly
strained as both groups claim the Macedonians are ignoring their
pleas to speed up the process.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the UN High Commissioner for
Refugees, said that her organization has offered to take over the
registration process, but that the Macedonian government rebuffed
the offer. She said the camp would have been more than half empty
already had the Macedonians allowed the UN group to process and
register refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, the stench at the field becomes more overpowering.
Monday, the Macedonian police and soldiers keeping the refugees
inside the field, along with aid workers ferrying food and water
and diapers to them on five tractors, began wearing masks to ward
off the smell and guard against infection.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees themselves are becoming increasingly desperate.
Monday, Turkane Berisha cried as she tried to find out what became
of her father, Suleiman, who had collapsed with an apparent heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she tried to comfort her sister, Shukrane, who
also collapsed. Medical volunteers were too busy with more
desperate cases, leaving Shukrane to writhe and moan on a muddy
stretcher. Moments later, a woman came over and said she needed the
stretcher. Shukrane was moved to the bare ground, and her cries
became more hysterical.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I find out if my father is alive or dead?'' Berisha
asked. Medical staff dashed around, too busy to help her. There was
no one keeping track of who had come in for treatment, who had been
shipped off to a hospital, or who had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better for me to hear that he is dead, so I won't worry
like this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Berisha said she and her family had left Pristina last week and
had spent four days in the muddy, wretched field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I never left Kosovo,'' she said. ``We've come here to
die. The Macedonian police are like the Serbs. They are killing us,
but they are killing us more slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   At another of the medical tents, Halil Avdiu looked on
helplessly as his unconscious wife was brought in. His five
children, ranging in age from 4 to 11, wept uncontrollably, sitting
on a small duffle bag that held all their belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even animals could not live in these conditions,'' Avdiu said.
``If this goes on another week, half the people will die.''
</P>
<P>
   If Blace is a vision of hell, the NATO camp waiting for more
refugees is a little bit of heaven, at least comparatively.
Hundreds of British, French, and Italian soldiers handed out food
and blankets and showed kindness to the refugees. The refugees,
nearly all of whom are Muslim, had their shoes neatly stored
outside the flaps to their tents, which were erected by soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Aran Shala, 20, who had spent seven days in the field at Blace,
waited with Ilir Berisha and his family for British soldiers to put
up a tent for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so much better,'' Shala said. ``I thank NATO for
helping Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Winkler said the tens of thousands of refugees still waiting in
Kosovo to cross the border have no food, water, or medical help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only imagine how bad it is back there,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
