<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-TREASURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY WOES `SYSTEMATIC,' PROBERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A task force assembled after nearly $9 million was
allegedly stolen from the state treasury's Unpaid Check Fund has
found ``serious and systemic problems'' in the department.
</P>
<P>
   One example: Record-keeping was so poor under former treasurer
Joseph D. Malone that 4,000 state checks already cashed and
totaling $8 million were recorded by the treasury as outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad information coming into the system,'' Malone's
successor, Shannon P. O'Brien, said Monday in announcing findings
of the task force.
</P>
<P>
   The task force also found:
</P>
<P>
   --That one staff person was responsible for reconciling dozens
of state accounts worth millions of dollars. The employee, who left
the treasury in October _ and has not been implicated in the thefts
_ was unable to balance the books, making it easier for the
suspects to steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, the checking accounts weren't reconciled monthly
and the potential for fraud increased dramatically,'' O'Brien said,
adding: ``We probably will never be able to fully reconcile those
accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   --That former deputy treasurer Robert E. Foley, one of four men
charged with embezzling the money, was the treasury manager in
charge of implementing internal cash management controls, of which
there were few.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this isn't the classic case of the fox guarding the
henhouse, I don't know what is,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   --Guidelines for writing checks were so lax, a $100 million
check the state issued to a hospital was signed by a single
treasury employee, the task force found.
</P>
<P>
   So far, four men have been charged in connection with the
alleged theft of $8.9 million from the Unpaid Check Fund, where
uncashed state payments are held for a year. The investigation
continues.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the fund, John F. Trischitta, was arrested in
February for conspiring with an outside ``heir finder,'' Martin
Robbins, to siphon $6.5 million into an escrow account at
BankBoston. A bank employee notified the attorney general when
Robbins later tried to withdraw those funds, an act that launched
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   While that $6.5 million has since been returned to the state,
another $2.4 million remains missing.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, who was Trischitta's boss, and another heir finder,
Thomas Ciliberto, were arrested shortly after, charged with bilking
the $2.4 million from the same account.
</P>
<P>
   Heir finders try to match money or abandoned property held in
state accounts to their rightful owners, who may be dead, have a
new name or address, or otherwise have been difficult to locate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have said that the rip-off of the Unpaid Check Fund can
be attributed to two bad apples,'' O'Brien said. ``But it's more
than that. It's about two bad apples who were able to take
advantage of a faulty system without adequate internal controls.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force, which included O'Brien, state Comptroller Martin
Benison, and state Auditor Joseph DeNucci, did not focus on the
Abandoned Property Division, O'Brien said. That account is filled
with money and other property the state declares abandoned. Checks
that sit in the Unpaid Check Fund for one year are then transferred
to Abandoned Property.
</P>
<P>
   DeNucci has said recordkeeping was also poor in Abandoned
Property, which Foley oversaw in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien is seeking an additional $1.1 million in funding from
the Legislature for next year to increase what she feels is a
depleted staff, to upgrade computer systems that crash frequently,
and to hire an outside auditor to carefully monitor the treasury
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Of that money, about $580,000 would be a permanent increase for
the department to fund the new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Although DeNucci regularly investigates state departments, he
does not check each office every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the level of (auditing) detail does not exist,''
said Beth Pearce, the new deputy treasurer for cash management who
replaced Foley.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other changes the task force recommended:
</P>
<P>
   --Procedures for check cashing should be tightened. All check
signatures must be original and any payment of more than $100,000
will need more than one person to sign off on it.
</P>
<P>
   --All accounts under cash management should be reconciled
monthly.
</P>
<P>
   --O'Brien should consider increasing the insurance covering a
theft by a treasury worker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
