<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDUS-TRADE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sehgal to oversee state trade initiatives
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier and Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes named R.K. Sehgal chairman of
the Industry, Trade &AMP; Tourism board, bringing a strong
international emphasis to the department charged with bolstering
the state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said Monday he wants Sehgal, who previously boosted the
international presence of three Atlanta companies, to increase
Georgia's trade abroad. In a lunchtime speech to the Atlanta Rotary
Club, Barnes said he wants Georgia to be more aggressive about
seeking international trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes apparently intends to rely heavily on Sehgal to
accomplish this mission. Sehgal said he will recommend candidates
to Barnes for the 20 spots on the Industry, Trade &AMP; Tourism board,
which oversees the work of the state's Department of Industry,
Trade &AMP; Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Thomas, president and CEO of the 3,100-member Georgia
Chamber of Commerce, said he liked Sehgal's international
experience. Thomas said he hopes the new chairman will also step up
economic development in the state's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Sehgal, 57, replaces A. Ray Weeks, an Atlanta developer.
</P>
<P>
   A suburban Atlanta resident, Sehgal said he has known Barnes for
20 years. Sehgal gave at least $3,000 to Barnes' campaign,
according to public records.
</P>
<P>
   Raghbir Kumar ``R.K.'' Sehgal is a well-connected Atlanta
businessman credited with making Law Companies Group an
internationally known engineering company. Sehgal, 57, spent 32
years at Law, and during his decade as chief executive officer the
company grew from a respected regional company with $50 million in
revenue into an international firm with revenue of $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   At Law, Sehgal attracted well-known names to the company's
board, including former Atlanta Mayor and United Nations Ambassador
Andrew Young; former Gov. Joe Frank Harris; and the late John
Ehrlichman, Richard Nixon's former domestic policy adviser who
resigned during the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Sehgal resigned from Law in 1994. In February 1995, he was hired
as CEO of Williams Group International. Sehgal left the engineering
services company in late 1996, becoming vice chairman and CEO of
H.J. Russell, one of the nation's largest black-owned construction
companies. Sehgal said he stepped down as CEO in December 1998, but
still works as vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier and Matt Kempner write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
