<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY HATE THE CAMPAIGN FINANCE SYSTEM (BUT MAKE CHECKS PAYABLE TO
...)
</HEADLINE>
  (ac) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey
devoted years to scorning the campaign finance system as riddled
with loopholes and ruled by wealthy interests. But that has not
deterred him from partaking in it himself.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent reception at the elegant Four Seasons Hotel, Bradley
snagged moneyed Democrats between their bites of beef Wellington
and seafood parfait and tried to persuade them to contribute to his
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona is also known for championing
campaign reform. But there he was the other day at a fund-raising
brunch at the classy Sequoia restaurant on the Potomac River in
Washington. For $250, donors were treated to a buffet, topped off
with a speech by McCain, who is seeking the Republican nomination.
For $1,000, donors also got their photographs taken with the
senator and hobnobbed with him at a reception beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and McCain argue that the existing laws leave them no
choice but to devote much time to traveling the country hunting for
millions of dollars or hitting up prospects during interminable
telephone calls. Neither is willing to follow the lead of Sen.
Russell Feingold, the Wisconsin Democrat who co-sponsored a
campaign finance bill with McCain. Feingold almost lost his
re-election last year because of several restrictions he imposed on
his own fund-raising, like limiting overall spending to $1 for each
registered voter and refusing to accept unregulated donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play by whatever the rules are,'' Bradley said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the paradox is striking: Never before in American politics
have two contenders (or even one) so identified with campaign
reform taken to the presidential fund-raising circuit. Ross Perot
made his disdain for the system one of his signature issues in the
1992 campaign. But because he dipped into his own fortune to
finance his race, Perot could spurn the system that he had vowed to
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore their seriousness about reform _ and to counter
criticism that they are hypocrites _ both Bradley and McCain have
taken some steps to restrict the ways in which they collect money.
Unlike many of their opponents, they did not establish shadow
organizations in states with lax regulations like Virginia. Doing
so would have enabled them to raise huge sums of unregulated money.
Bradley has also refused money from political action committees, a
concession that McCain has not made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley and McCain are walking the tightest tightrope of any
candidates,'' said Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center
for Responsive Politics, a campaign reform advocacy group in
Washington. ``They've got to raise the money. But they've got to do
it cleaner than any one else.''
</P>
<P>
   Their reputations as reformers have posed opportunities and
obstacles for Bradley and McCain. Rather than shy away from the
issue, both candidates are highlighting it _ even at their own
fund- raising events _ to try to bestow populist, outsider tilts
upon their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley avoids the subject, but his supporters do not shrink
from drawing a contrast with Vice President Al Gore, who was
accused of bending campaign finance laws in the 1996 campaign.
McCain eagerly pounces on the vice president's practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would never, ever happen with Bill Bradley,'' said Jay
Jordan, who runs a diversified holding company in Chicago and is a
member of Bradley's national finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, McCain and Bradley are soliciting from the
very interests they have assailed. McCain, in particular, is a
magnet for contributors because he is chairman of the influential
Senate Commerce Committee; whether he is White House bound or not,
many lobbyists see it as in their interest to donate to him.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns have lined up big corporate names to help raise
money. McCain's roster includes Maurice Greenberg, chairman of the
American International Group; Richard Notebaert, chairman of the
Ameritech Corp.; Henry M. Paulson Jr., chief executive of Goldman,
Sachs; and Jerry Reinsdorf, chairman of the Chicago Bulls and White
Sox. Bradley's fund-raisers include Leonard Riggio, chief executive
of Barnes &AMP; Noble; Thomas Labrecque, president of the Chase
Manhattan Corp.; Howard Schultz, chief executive of Starbucks; and
John Bryan, chief executive of Sara Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The two campaigns performed respectably in the first quarter of
this year, each taking in more than $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Though their cries for change may catch on with voters _ and
even contributors _ others are offended that McCain and Bradley
have been so outspoken. Pat Robertson, the founder of the Christian
Coalition, has pointedly discouraged Republicans from backing
McCain. He said the senator's campaign finance proposal threatened
the ability of his organization to promote candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John McCain has done a great deal of harm to
grass-roots movements like the Christian Coalition through that
McCain-Feingold bill,'' Robertson said in a recent interview with
CNN. ``It's going to be very hard to mobilize people to support
him. I don't see him really going too far.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6839 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-2TAK     04-05 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PALM BEACH: too far.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And backers of Gore have privately warned labor leaders that
Bradley's stand on campaign finance stands would undermine unions'
influence in campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wertheimer, chairman of Democracy 21, a policy group based
in Washington, said Bradley and McCain had been singled out because
they were genuine reformers. ``I have spent 30 years working on the
campaign finance issue,'' he said. ``These two guys are for real in
their commitment to changing the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Because political action committees usually contribute only a
tiny fraction of donations to Presidential campaigns, even Bradley
acknowledged that his rejection of PAC money was essentially
symbolic. (Gore also refuses PAC donations.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't give much _ what, $4 million?'' Bradley said.
``First of all, it's what I do because of what I believe about
campaign finance reform. That's where it starts. And the second
level is that you're making a judgment that by eschewing the most
visible examples of the way campaigns are now financed, you will
draw people to your cause who recognize that there's something
different about it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also expressed confidence that his stand on campaign
finance would ultimately help, not hinder, his quest. ``The people
who disagree with me on campaign finance reform, I believe, are
obviously misinformed because they believe that this is going to
inhibit their ability to carry out their political agenda,'' he
said in an interview. ``And obviously, that's the last thing I
want. Do I want the Democrats to win elections? No. So the majority
of Republicans that I talk to believe that the system is broken,
that it's corrupt and needs to be fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley seems a bit sheepish in his appeals to donors. At the
event here at the Four Seasons _ in the same ballroom where
Republicans held their own big money event several weeks ago _ the
former senator's pitch was about his cautiousness in seeking
donations, not about his need for money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to raise money in a little different way,''
Bradley said. ``Because I believe strongly in campaign finance
reform, I think I have to set a standard that is higher than the
existing law. And so I don't take any PAC contributions, and I
don't set up sham state PACs in states like Virginia that are
totally unregulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley left it to one of the organizers of the reception, John
H. Kessler, for the hard sell. ``We have to put fuel in the fire,''
implored Kessler, chairman of an investment company in Parsippany,
N.J. ``The fuel is the money.'' The take was roughly $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   At McCain's reception in Washington, attended by friends from
the Naval Academy, the senator collected about $85,000. He did not
mention reform but vowed to spend his contributions wisely. ``There
are two aspects to money in a campaign,'' he said. ``Not just how
you raise it, but how you spend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both McCain and Bradley said it was not easy to solicit more
than $20 million, mostly in increments of $1,000, the most any
individual can give. With a smile, McCain said he had been tempted
by offers of unregulated money that he cannot accept. ``We got a
check from one guy for $10,000,'' he recalled. ``I had to say, `I'm
sorry pal, but if you've got some close family members who are over
18 ... .'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
