<SLUG> BC-LIBEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT WON'T HEAR REPORTER'S LIBEL CLAIM IN BRANCH DAVIDIAN
CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court refused Monday to hear a Waco
journalist's claim that he was libeled by a Dallas-Fort Worth
television news report that he had warned the Branch Davidian cult
of an impending federal raid in February 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents raided the compound of cult leader David Koresh
outside Waco on Feb. 28, 1993. Four U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms agents and five cult members died in the ensuing gun
battle. A 51-day standoff ended when the compound was consumed by
fire during a subsequent federal raid on April 19, 1993, that
killed Koresh and more than 80 followers.
</P>
<P>
   John McLemore sued WFAA-TV for libel. But the Texas Supreme
Court threw out the lawsuit, saying the station did not commit
libel because it did not knowingly lie or show reckless disregard
for the truth in airing its report.
</P>
<P>
   A Treasury Department investigation of the raid and its
aftermath cleared McLemore, then a reporter for KWTX-TV who was on
the scene when federal agents stormed the compound. The department
said a postal driver, acting on a tip from a Waco TV cameraman, had
warned the Branch Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   In ruling against McLemore last year, the Texas Supreme Court
deemed him a ``public figure'' because of his renown in the
community as a television reporter covering the standoff between
the Branch Davidians and federal agents. To prove libel, public
figures must show that untruths about them were reported knowingly
or with reckless disregard for the truth.
</P>
<P>
   In his U.S. Supreme Court appeal, McLemore argued that he should
be regarded as a private citizen. Private citizens need only show
that a news organization acted negligently in reporting false
information about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A public figure must not only act voluntarily when he enters
into a public controversy, he must intend to influence its
outcome,'' McLemore's lawyers argued in a brief to the high court.
``McLemore may have entered into the Branch Davidian raid
voluntarily, but nothing he said and nothing he did had anything to
do with the public issues surrounding the raid.''
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
