A6842 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTES-COX     04-05 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Win the Par-3 tournament? Not a chance
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Hey, David Duval's PGA Tour colleagues might be
in awe of 11 wins in 34 events, but they haven't gone brain-dead.
Of course they're going to sign him up for Wednesday's Par-3
Tournament and then root for him big-time. Everybody knows of the
Par-3 Jinx. Nobody ever has won the Par-3 on Wednesday and then
prevailed Sunday in the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freddie (Couples) signed me up, I guess,'' Duval said Monday
on the Augusta National grounds.
</P>
<P>
   So what is Duval pondering? Also revising that bit of history?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'll probably dump one (in the water) if I have to,''
Duval said, grinning. ``Not that I'm superstitious or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue-collar man
</P>
<P>
   First, there was Tiger Woods' Sunday Red. Now, there is David's
Sunday Blue.
</P>
<P>
   Two tournament victories in a row with Navy from cap to socks,
and you can safely presume the same outfit might come out again
Sunday at Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worn blue before when I haven't won, but I do like
blue,'' Duval said. ``I think it's kind of a nice mix. Kind of
workmanlike. You might see it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval registered at Augusta National on Monday but did not play.
Maybe it was a good idea. Ordering lunch became his first no-win
deal of the past couple of weeks. When his clam chowder arrived,
there was a fly in it.
</P>
<P>
   Don't go changin'
</P>
<P>
   Is there an advantage to having 1 3/8-inch rough at Augusta
National, as opposed to a second cut of 5/8-inch in other years
that barely was noticed? Around the greens, the new stuff can make
it easier for the players. There are some pitching areas, such as
to the right of No. 6 and No. 8, where sloped areas previously cut
extremely tight have now been rid of the chunk factor. ``If you get
around the greens with this rough, it's easier to get (the club)
underneath it,'' Brad Faxon said.
</P>
<P>
   The changes at four holes, with rough all around, ``really
aren't enough to make you intimidated or have to change a club into
the greens,'' Faxon said. ``It's just not going to hold a whole
lot.'' While it will take some spin off the ball, he said, it also
will help keep some drives from running into the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Janzen, the two-time U.S. Open champion, thinks the rough
was installed chiefly to discourage players from driving wildly,
scooting by the trouble and into the clear. ``Like at 11, you used
to be about to take it right as far as you want,'' he said. ``Now,
you can't do it. You have to play the hole straightaway.'' Beyond
that, Janzen said, the mowers also are combing the rough toward the
tees, ``so the ball rolls even less.''
</P>
<P>
   Short shots
</P>
<P>
   Because the field of actual participants is 96 players this year
_ the most since 103 in 1966 _ threesomes, as opposed to the
customary twosomes, might be used for Thursday and Friday rounds. .
. . Hotel price increases have reached a new level. The Holiday Inn
is charging $299 per night. . . . The Byron Nelson statue will be
unveiled at 11 a.m. today in downtown Augusta by the Georgia Golf
Hall of Fame. . . . Six-time Masters winner Jack Nicklaus,
attending tonight's Champions Dinner, still is recovering from his
January hip replacement and is not in competitive condition.
However, Nicklaus already is playing and is almost a sure bet to
compete in the Memorial and the U.S. Open. Nicklaus played twice
last week in Florida. . . . Augusta National seems to bring out the
best in Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar even when he's not playing well
in college tournaments. In February, he shot a 69 during a practice
round at Augusta with a double-bogey on No. 2. . . . Hank Kuehne,
the U.S. Amateur champion, will play a practice round today,
partnering with British Amateur champion Sergio Garcia, in a
friendly match with the past two Masters champions, Mark O'Meara
and Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
