<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ATROCITIES (Washington) _ Pentagon says the military has
its first clear satellite images of atrocities against ethnic
Albanians, leaving President Clinton to defend a seemingly futile
bombing campaign against Yugoslavia. By Anne E. Kornblut. 1350
words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton, vowing that
ethnic Albanians will return to Kosovo, says the ethnic cleansing
by Serb forces ``cannot stand.'' By Ann Scales. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES-HEALTH (Blace, Macedonia) -- More than 50,000 refugees
stranded in an open field on the Kosovo border will begin to die in
large numbers if they are not moved in the next few days, medical
authorities say. By Kevin Cullen. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RELOCATE (Washington) _ Relocating Kosovar Albanians to
Guam and Guantanamo would be no small cultural and climactic shock.
Immigration laws, and US facilities that are on US possessions but
not in the United States proper, are the controlling factors. By
Mary Leonard. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LIBYA-PANAM (New York) _ Clearing the way for justice after more
than a decade of defiance, Libya hands over two suspects in the
1988 Pan Am jet bombing. UN promptly suspends sanctions against
Libya. By Colum Lynch. 900 words.
