<HEADER>
A6849 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     04-05 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO SELL THE TABLOIDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; David Pecker &LR; , who is about to become chairman of the board of
the company that owns both the National Enquirer and the Star, says
he'd be willing to spend $50 million  &LR; on  &LR; ``repositioning'' those
tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   What would be an appropriate campaign? Ad Age asked a bunch of
pros how that could be done; their answers describe the process of
advertising in America:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``There's always room for trash, and that's their legacy,''
said New York's  &UR; Jerry Della Femina &LR; . ``They can't get away from
that. But they can position it as a better grade of trash, a more
exclusive brand of trash.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The first thing to do is consider semantics, said  &UR; Al Ries &LR; .
Get rid of the word ``tabloids,'' he said, and find a new label.
``You need to upgrade along the same lines as, `I don't make
movies, I make films.' `I'm not a garbageman, I'm a sanitation
engineer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ted Leonhardt &LR;  said the papers should position themselves as
``a vanguard of social change, and they are recording that in a
populist sense. It's all about getting in touch with what's real
now. ... Maybe in the end that's very healthy for all of us. All my
Episcopal roots are screaming as a result of that sort of thing,
but that's what they've got working for them.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Max Carey  &LR; of Atlanta suggested that the Enquirer come up
``with a credible spokesperson who would say the new owners are
taking it back to its core and making it a better product. ... The
mea culpa approach. ... It may be a complete lie. But it buys you
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Billy Joel &LR;  got into the act at San Francisco's Redwood Room
on Friday night, joining bassist  &UR; Pat Klobas  &LR; and pianist
 &UR; Michael Udelson &LR;  on ``Ain't Misbehavin'.'' It wasn't completely
unrehearsed; Joel huddled with Udelson for a few minutes to work
out switching sides on the piano bench several times during the
song. And  &UR; Dario Oakley  &LR; and his twins,  &UR; Seth &LR;  and &UR; Cody &LR; , ran into
 &UR; Jerry Rice  &LR; and his three kids playing video games at Q-Zar in
Redwood City on Saturday morning. Furthermore, the New York Post
reports, with some sniffiness, that  &UR; Phil Bronstein  &LR; was seen
necking with  &UR; Sharon Stone  &LR; in a New York restaurant on the first
night of Passover.
</P>
<P>
   _ April 6 is the 61st anniversary of the discovery of Teflon,
which according to Saveur magazine has ``a thousand uses, from pump
coating to protecting the Statue of Liberty from wear and tear to
making pancake-flipping a one-handed task.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In a report in the Sunday Times of London about spending a
weekend chez, the  &UR; Prince of Wales  &LR; notes that ``the Royal Family
prefers not to eat cheese in the evening; they find it gives them
unpredictable dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Anita Brandenburg  &LR; got all choked up watching ``Leeza'' on
Thursday, when actor &UR; Corey Feldman &LR;  revealed he had felt suicidal
at one poverty-stricken point because his house was a mess and he
couldn't afford a maid.
</P>
<P>
   _ The State Department has banned sales of Girl Scout cookies at
U.S. embassies, reports U.S. News &AMP; World Report, ruling that they
violate regulations about fund raising on government property.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JOURNALISTIC CLASSIC GETS UPDATED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six years ago, before she became a renowned feminist,
 &UR; Gloria Steinem &LR; 's first-person account of a stint as a Playboy
bunny made her a famous writer.
</P>
<P>
   In homage to that achievement,  &UR; Sue Carpenter  &LR; writes in the
latest issue of Jane about a stint as a Hooters waitress, where she
``pranced around in hot pants and served buffalo wings to groups of
leering men who seized every opportunity to stare down her
extra-small shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter breaks in at a Hooters in Green Bay, Wis., with 60
recruits. Two quit after trying on their uniforms, routinely issued
in small sizes. By Day 2, every one of the remaining candidates
admits to having bought a new bra to show herself off to best
advantage in the tank top. One candidate ``bought two push-up bras,
using the pads from both'' at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hooters is, in effect,'' she writes, ``the Playboy Club
updated for the '90s. It's just dressed in athletic gear instead of
stilettos. ... You must wonder whether there has indeed been a
conservative backlash to the advancements Gloria (Steinem) helped
bring about.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Studies done at the University of Michigan and Princeton,
reported in Self magazine, found that girls of 18 are more likely
to be depressed than boys of the same age. What's on the girls'
minds: their looks, friends, family, self-worth and safety. What
the boys are worried about: doing well in sports.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even get near them. They're so overexposed.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Floral arranger Avi Adler telling New York magazine that now
that orchids are available to everyone _ at the Home Depot, for
goodness' sake _ they're passe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
