NYT-04-05-99 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGAPPLY-COX     04-05 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGAPPLY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Growing selectivity has UGA sending more rejection letters
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Statistically, the profile of those accepted for
the incoming freshmen class at the University of Georgia has
changed very little _ the SAT scores and grade point averages are
both high _ but the number of those applying for admission just
keeps growing and growing, topping out this year at 13,500.
</P>
<P>
   Also growing is the number of high school seniors receiving a
letter from the admissions department informing them that they've
been rejected. Last week, almost 5,000 of those ``no'' letters went
out, compared to 3,500 in 1998 and 2,500 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the people we don't admit have good academic
records,'' said John Albright, associate director of undergraduate
admissions. ``We hold on to their folders for two years. A lot of
them come to us as transfers as juniors or seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, UGA has room for a fall freshman class of about 4,200
and for about 2,000 transfer students. More high school seniors are
admitted than there is room for _ about twice as many _ because
many of those admitted don't enroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are starting to come to campus to see if they like
it,'' Albright said. ``It's a lot like buying shoes _ some people
do all right buying them out of a catalog, others have to try them
on. You've got to have the right fit in both cases.''
</P>
<P>
   The phone calls from concerned parents to the admissions
officials had tapered off by Monday, but Albright and his
colleagues were fielding 200 or more calls a day last week. The
admissions department sends out advance information detailing UGA's
growing selectivity in the face of its increased popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're known by the company you don't keep,'' Albright said.
``The more people we turn down, the better the school we're
perceived to be. We're a real solid school, but a lot of the
increase in people trying to get in is the momentum in the growth
of our reputation. And a lot of it is word-of-mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   The 13,500 applications UGA received for fall admission
represents a 6 percent increase over the 12,700 applications turned
in last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though the final numbers aren't in, I'm sure this class will
be more academically accomplished than earlier classes,'' Albright
said, adding that the average SAT score for those accepted was
1220, while the GPA was 3.7.
</P>
<P>
   Albright noted that this year's applicant pool showed an
increase in the number of minorities. He said he isn't sure why
that number increased, but said that his office is working ``real
hard on recruiting minorities'' with top-flight credentials and in
convincing those accepted to enroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is to create a climate of acceptance
and openness to diversity,'' he said. ``We're trying to be good
stewards of the state of Georgia. We'd like to be open to a good
mix of students on our campus who are all able academically.''
</P>
<P>
   UGA Admissions: What it takes to get accepted:
http://www.admissions.uga.edu/99fqa.htmlG
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca McCarthy writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
