<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6854 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-TESTIFY-HNS &LR;      04-05 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TESTIFY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE A GUILTY PLEA, A DEFENDANT CAN ASSERT FIFTH-AMENDMENT
RIGHTS DURING SENTENCING &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By STEVE LASH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sharply divided Supreme Court ruled on Monday
that defendants who plead guilty cannot be penalized during
sentencing for refusing to detail their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In their decision, the justices unanimously held that
defendants' guilty pleas do not prevent them from later asserting
their Fifth Amendment privilege against self-incrimination during
the sentencing phase. The high court split 5-4, along ideological
lines, in ruling that a judge cannot hold the defendants' silence
against them when handing down a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision will require a federal judge in
Pennsylvania to reconsider his decision to sentence Amanda Mitchell
to 10 years in prison followed by six years of probation and a $200
fine for conspiring to distribute at least 5 kilograms of cocaine.
Mitchell had pleaded guilty to conspiracy but never testified
regarding the amount of cocaine involved.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Edward Cahn of Eastern Pennsylvania
interpreted her silence as an admission that at least 5 kilograms
were involved, elevating the mandatory minimum sentence from one
year to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the sentence,
ruling that Mitchell already had incriminated herself when she
pleaded guilty. Cahn was then free to interpret Mitchell's
subsequent refusal to testify as an admission that more than 5
kilograms were involved, the 3rd Circuit said.
</P>
<P>
   But the divided Supreme Court reversed, holding that Mitchell
retained her constitutional right even after her guilty plea.
Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, writing for the majority, said the
government could turn guilty pleas into ``a prosecutorial sword''
if defendants forfeited their right not to incriminate themselves
simply by admitting to a crime.
</P>
<P>
   In dissent, Justice Antonin Scalia, joined by three colleagues,
only grudgingly accepted the Supreme Court's line of decisions that
prohibit courts from interpreting as evidence of guilt a
defendant's refusal to testify at trial. The dissenters then
assailed the court for extending this prohibition to the sentencing
phase.
</P>
<P>
   While Mitchell had the constitutional right not to testify
before Cahn handed down his sentence, the judge was well within his
authority to make the ``common-sensical inference`` from Mitchell's
silence that at least 5 kilograms of cocaine were involved, Scalia
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though the Fifth Amendment protects Mitchell from being
compelled to take the stand, and also protects her, as we have
held, from adverse inferences drawn from her silence at trial,
there is no reason why it must also shield her from the natural and
appropriate consequences of her uncooperativeness at the sentencing
stage,'' Scalia said. Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and Clarence Thomas joined Scalia's
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, in a separate dissent, said he would be ``willing to
reconsider'' the court's holdings and allow courts to interpret a
defendant's refusal to testify at trial as an indication of guilt.
But Thomas noted that the case before the justices concerned only a
defendant's privilege against self-incrimination at sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
