<SLUG> BC-GA-TRANSPORTATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes names new budget officer
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes continued to shape his administration
Monday, tapping Bill Tomlinson as the state's new chief budget
officer in charge of Georgia's annual budget of more than $13
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson, now deputy director of the Legislative Budget Office,
will succeed Tim Burgess, the current director of the Governor's
Office of Planning and Budget. Burgess is leaving in mid-April to
join the administration at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-year budget office veteran, Burgess, 43, had served as
director for the past four years under the administration of former
Gov. Zell Miller. He now will become associate vice president for
finance and administration at UGA.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement also is a veteran of state government.
Tomlinson, 57, spent 13 years in the governor's budget office
interrupted by time heading the Education Review commission for
former Gov. Joe Frank Harris. That commission produced the plan
that led to the Quality Basic Education Act, which determines the
funding allocation for Georgia's schools.
</P>
<P>
   The quick appointment Monday _ the same day as Burgess'
departure was announced _ is but one that Barnes must make. Also on
Monday, Barnes appointed R.K. Sehgal, the founder and president of
Law International, as the chairman of the Georgia Board of
Industry, Trade and Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Another 43 appointments for vacancies on 11 state boards and
agencies _ from education to natural resources and the prestigious
Board of Regents _ still await decisions from Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also has to name his 15-member Georgia Regional
Transportation Authority and the nine-member board of his new
Georgia Department of Community Health, a superagency that pulls
all state insurance-buying functions into a single division. Those
appointments, and the naming of department heads to oversee state
agencies, are expected within the next 45 days, governor's
spokesmen have indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Kathey Pruitt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
