<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSENGER'S POSSESSIONS CAN BE SEARCHED IF DRIVER SUSPECTED OF
CRIME &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By STEVE LASH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled Monday that the
Constitution does not protect automobile passengers from having
their belongings searched by police who suspect the driver has
committed a crime.
</P>
<P>
   In its 6-3 decision, the justices extended to passengers its
long-held view that police officers, without a warrant but with
probable cause, can search all containers in a car that belong to
the driver suspected of criminality. The justices, however, said
their decision does not allow police to frisk passengers, unless
the officers have probable cause to suspect the passengers of
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Police groups hailed the court's decision as a victory in the
fight against crime. But criminal defense lawyers assailed the
ruling as a defeat for the civil rights of passengers.
</P>
<P>
   With its decision, the high court reinstated the drug-possession
conviction of Sandra Houghton, a passenger in a car David Young was
driving July 23, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After pulling Young over for speeding and driving with a faulty
brake light, a Wyoming Highway Patrol officer saw a hypodermic
syringe in the driver's shirt pocket and ordered him out of the
car. Asked why he had the syringe, Young told the officer that he
used it to take drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Backup officers then told Houghton and another passenger to get
out of the car. A search of Houghton's purse, left on the seat,
uncovered two hypodermic syringes containing methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   She was convicted of felony possession of the drug. But the
Wyoming Supreme Court reversed the conviction, holding that the
officer's probable cause to suspect the driver of criminality did
not give him constitutional permission to search the personal
belongings of a passenger.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court overturned that ruling, saying the police
have broad authority to search automobiles once they have probable
cause to suspect the driver is committing a crime. In such cases,
passengers, like Houghton, lack the Fourth Amendment's protection
against unreasonable searches, the court held.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is probable cause to search for contraband in a
car, it is reasonable for police officers to examine packages and
containers without a showing of individualized probable cause for
each one,'' Justice Scalia wrote in the court's majority opinion.
``A passenger's personal belongings, just like the driver's
belongings or containers attached to the car like a glove
compartment, are `in' the car, and the officer has probable cause
to search for contraband in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the court said drivers and passengers have ``a
reduced expectation of privacy'' when in cars, traveling on public
streets and subject to police stops. As a result, drivers and
passengers have less Fourth Amendment protection from the prying
eyes and hands of police officers conducting a search.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer agreed with the majority but wrote
separately in an effort to make clear that the court's decision
applies only to searches of automobiles and of containers belonging
to passengers. Police are prohibited from searching the passengers
themselves, unless the officers have probable cause, Breyer said.
</P>
<P>
   In a vehement dissent, Justice John Paul Stevens, joined by
Justices David H. Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg, said the
Constitution bars police from conducting warrantless searches of
car passengers when the officers only have probable cause to
suspect the driver.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
