<HEADER>
A6865 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOTTI-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      04-05 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOTTI-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DUMBFELLA' GOES ON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not ``The Godfather.'' It's not even ``The
Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   John Gotti Jr., the alleged boss of the Gambino crime syndicate,
goes on trial in Long Island Tuesday. Once, such an event would
have caused a sensation. Now, it will supply just another dribble
of proof that the Mafia has seen grander days.
</P>
<P>
   The charges tell the tale.
</P>
<P>
   When Gotti's father, John Gotti Sr. _ the fierce, elusive, and
elegant boss, known as ``Dapper Don'' and ``Teflon Don'' _ was sent
up the river in 1992, it was for a whole raft of high crimes,
including the murder of his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti's son _ known to law-enforcement agents as ``Junior'' and
in the New York tabloids as ``Dumbfella'' _ faces up to 18 years in
jail for shaking down an upscale strip joint, running a gambling
ring, robbing a drug dealer, and fibbing on a home-mortgage
refinancing application.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Mob does today is kids' stuff, it's like a street
gang,'' James Kallstrom, former director of the Federal Bureau of
Investigation's New York office, said in a phone interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still has a lot of bad characters,'' Kallstrom added, ``but
these are different people, different times.''
</P>
<P>
   The infamous ``five families'' that ran organized crime in New
York once truly had enormous power. They controlled a handful of
major unions, were major players in the concrete and construction
industries, in commercial-garbage pick-up service, and in the fish
and produce markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You paid a certain percentage of your money to the Mob, no
matter who you were,'' Kallstrom said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Schiliro, the FBI's current New York director, said Monday
that, as recently as 1988, John Gotti, Sr., was raking in $100,000
a month from construction-industry shakedowns _ personally.
</P>
<P>
   Then the FBI became adept at using the anti-racketeering RICO
statutes, passed by Congress a decade earlier _ which allowed
agents not only to arrest individuals but to confiscate their
assets and bust up the whole hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the heads of all the organized-crime
families in New York were indicted, convicted, and locked up.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the Giuliani administration stepped in and
imposed licensing requirements on certain industries _ especially
the Fulton Fish Market and the garbage pick-up business _ that the
Mafia once monopolized.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Gotti allegedly passed the titular leadership of the
Gambino family on to his son, there wasn't much left to control.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Mafia's activities today, Kallstrom said, involve
bits and pieces of the economy's dark underside: gambling,
prostitution, and narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   Schiliro noted that the syndicates still have a hand in
construction, cement, and the garment trade, though much less than
in the past. Some crime families, he said, are expanding into
``non-traditional activities,'' such as penny-stock fraud,
health-care fraud, and telephone-card scams.
</P>
<P>
   While none of this is trivial, it in no way remotely resembles
the vast, pervasive empire that the Mob bosses once oversaw.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the crime families has shrunk as well, to ``maybe
one-fifth'' their size a quarter-century ago, Kallstrom estimated.
``Even in the '80s,'' the former agent said, ``some families had
300 to 400 members and another 1,000 or so associates that did
their bidding. You just don't find anything like that today.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, it is only natural that, at the end of the century, one
of the top Mafia gangs is run _ allegedly _ by the likes of John
Gotti, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents, the past several months, have painted a pathetic
picture of the 34-year-old ``Junior.''
</P>
<P>
   When he visits his father at the maximum-security prison in
Marion, Ill. _ or so the videotapes reportedly show _ he spends
practically the whole time sulking in his chair while John Sr.
yells at him.
</P>
<P>
   The legitimate business ventures he has started have all
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The other crime-family bosses are said to dislike him.
</P>
<P>
   He had to call on his sister, Victoria, the author of
best-selling romance novels, to bail him out of jail last
September.
</P>
<P>
   The bail terms were so stiff _ including house arrest and
$24,000 a month to pay for private security guards to watch over
him _ that, last week, he asked the judge to put him back in
prison, on the grounds that he couldn't make the payments. (Monday,
he changed his mind, telling the judge he would somehow manage,
after all.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in stylistic terms, he appears the polar opposite of
his father _ overweight, poorly dressed, and driving a minivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the mobsters today,'' Kallstrom sneered. ``They're not
Carlo Gambino. They don't have the discipline, the organization,
the code of silence. I'm not saying we respected the old dons _ we
despised them. But they were different from these young guys
today.''
</P>
<P>
   When his case first came up, Gotti Jr. was going to be one of 22
defendants _ but, in the months since, the number has dwindled to
two. The others have pled guilty, chosen to cooperate with the
prosecutors, or had charges dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Gotti was about to cop a plea, in exchange for a
reduced sentence, as well _ until his sister, mother, and father
all talked him out of it, telling him the federal prosecutors had a
weak case against him.
</P>
<P>
   He is pleading innocent to all charges and denies accusations
that he has any involvement with organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will feature at least one vestige of the old-style
Mafia _ a cast of ex-Mobsters with colorful names, testifying
against the defendant, among them, John ``Jackie Nose'' D'Amico,
Dominic ``Fat Dom'' Borghese, and Willie Marshall, who once
referred to himself as a ``two-bit leg-breaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Also scheduled to appear is Frank Gioia Jr., a 250-pound star
witness who, in recent years, has helped the feds convict more than
60 mobsters, including Anthony ``Bowat'' Baretta, George ``Georgie
Neck'' Zappola, and Frank ``Frankie Bones'' Papagni.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
