<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CINCINNATI-PARKING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parking lot owners the big winners in Cincinnati as spaces at
premium
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar and Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI, Ohio _ Between mouthfuls of a bratwurst smothered in
ketchup, Chris Ciganik of Mason shared his Opening Day parking
strategy: leave early and be ready to walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were leaving a half hour before the game you might want
to leave some time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ciganik, 28, was one of 54,000-plus fans who turned out Monday
for the sold-out Cincinnati Reds' 1999 season opener against the
San Francisco Giants. Like thousands attending Opening Day, Ciganik
spent more time than usual finding a parking before he could join
an annual tailgate party held by his former University of Dayton
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati officials say the Paul Brown Stadium and the Fort
Washington Way construction projects eliminated 1,200 parking
spaces from the area around Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   For Ciganik, this meant parking in Newport, Ky., and walking 10
minutes across the Ohio River to the Third Street parking lot where
his friend and fellow UD alum Tom Thiel held a tailgate party for
60 people. Ciganik, who traveled easily from Warren County to
Cincinnati on Interstate 71, said he spent half an hour looking for
a spot before he opted to park across the river.
</P>
<P>
   Thiel, who parked his van at the Third Street lot near the
stadium at 6 a.m., said friends from both Dayton and Cincinnati
called him from their cars with cellular phones to complain they
couldn't parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   `` 'Where do we park?' That's what everyone's saying,'' Thiel
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati parking Supt. Chuck Cullen said parking problems
around Cinergy Field should be short lived. During most weekend and
night games, fans will find plenty of spots; spaces may be more
scarce during weekday afternoon games because fans will compete
with shoppers and other daytime downtown visitors, he said. But no
weekday game brings more fans downtown than the season opener, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening Day is always difficult,'' he said. ``As you get to
the playoffs and the World Series, you might have a problem. We'll
worry about those when we get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Completion of Paul Brown Stadium will mean up to an additional
7,000 parking spaces for the downtown, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, parking lot owners cashed in.
</P>
<P>
   At the CitiCentre parking lot on Third Street, for example, the
owners raised the baseball game rate to $15 from $10 in 1998.
CitiCentre typically charges customers $40 per month to park at the
lot, which sits nearly one mile from Cinergy Field. Mary Knock, who
works for the parking lot, said she doesn't look for the price to
fall again.
</P>
<P>
   Parking shortages slowed the fans down but didn't keep them from
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in team shirts, jackets and ball caps, fans filed past
peanut vendors and ticket scalpers as they crossed walkways from
Third Street to the stadium. On the walkway, a saxophonist belted
out The Addam's Family theme, while outside the stadium a rock
group ground its way through grunge rock hits. Stragglers clutching
tickets wound their way through orange barrels along the Fort
Washington Way construction zone as Reds officials released a
barrage of red balloons in the stadium signaling the start of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said morning traffic into downtown Cincinnati remained
light because baseball fans filtered in at different times. In the
afternoon, however, motorists experienced 25-minute delays on the
10-mile stretch of Interstate 75 north between the downtown and
Paddock Road, said Linda Roll of Advanced Regional Traffic
Interactive Management and Information Systems, an independent
agency that which monitors Cincinnati-area traffic.
</P>
<P>
   She attributed the I-75 slowdowns to fan traffic mixing with
daily commuter traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really crawling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
