<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-MIAMISCHOOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami Valley schools need improvement, report says
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ More than two-thirds of the Miami Valley's school
districts met or exceeded most of the standards set by state
officials to assess districts' performance.
</P>
<P>
   That simply means the schools have room to improve.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Department of Education released the state report cards
Monday, ranking 18 categories and placing heavy emphasis on
proficiency scores. The report cards were the last ``trial run''
before the standards take effect next year.
</P>
<P>
   Of 60 school districts across the Miami Valley:
</P>
<P>
   _ 42 would need ``continuous improvement'' because they met
between 10 and 16 of the performance standards.
</P>
<P>
   _ 15 districts would have met six to nine standards and would be
on ``academic watch.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Three area districts _ Dayton, West Carrollton and
Trotwood-Madison _ met five or fewer standards and would be
designated ``academic emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   When the standards take effect, any school under academic
emergency must develop a three-year ``continuous improvement plan''
and could ultimately face the possibility of state intervention.
</P>
<P>
   No Miami Valley school district would have been designated
``effective,'' though four districts _ Centerville, Oakwood,
Franklin-Monroe and Fort Loramie _ came close, meeting 16 of 18
performance standards. Springboro and Tipp City followed that group
meeting 15 performance standards.
</P>
<P>
   The ``effective'' or best designation applies to schools that
meet 17 or 18 of the criteria.
</P>
<P>
   The education department included in each district's report
cards comparisons to other districts in Ohio with similar
demographic characteristics, such as family income and racial
makeup The report cards also include data for individual school
buildings. That data allows parents to compare test scores and
attendance rates at their children's schools with other schools.
</P>
<P>
   Most local school districts mailed out their report cards to
parents Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The reading and math portions of the Fourth Grade Proficiency
Test proved the biggest stmubling block for school districts in the
Miami Valley and across the state.
</P>
<P>
   The report cards rate area districts using standards that take
effect in 2000 and adjust actual proficiency test scores to reflect
how students would have done under more stringent testing criteria
slated for the same year. Many educators complained this would
lower their fourth-grade results and hurt their ratings overall.
</P>
<P>
   They were right. Not a single school district in the Miami
Valley met the state standard of having at least 75 percent of
their 4th graders pass the reading test. Statewide, only 19 school
districts _ about 3 percent _ met the fourth-grade reading test
standard.
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the 60 area districts _ Fort Loramie and
Hardin-Houston, both in Shelby County _ met the state standard set
for the fourth-grade math test. Statewide, only 14 of 606 districts
had at least three out of four fourth-graders pass the math test.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-grade reading test will loom larger beginning July 1,
2001, when the ``Fourth-Grade Guarantee'' begins. The guarantee
prohibits school districts from promoting to the fifth grade
students who have not passed the reading portion of the proficiency
test, unless the students' principal and reading teacher agree the
student is academically prepared for fifth grade. Students who have
a disability that excuses them from taking the proficiency test
also would be allowed to be promoted.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Durfee-Hidalgo, who oversees the report-card program for
the state, said the low fourth-grade scores will likely galvanize
parents, teachers and school officials to focus attention and
resources on reading in the early grade levels. Low scores on the
math portion of the ninth-grade proficiency test had a similar
effect a few years ago, and student performance on the test has
improved, Durfee-Hidalgo said.
</P>
<P>
   A school district's performance rating on the state report cards
will depend heavily on its students' proficiency test scores.
Sixteen of the 18 performance standards consist of proficiency test
scores in various subject areas in grades 4, 9, 10 and 12. Student
attendance rates and graduation rates make up the remaining two
criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Some educators argue that relying almost solely upon test scores
to determine a school district's effectiveness can be misleading,
because the scores may not accurately reflect the quality of
teachers and instruction occurring in a school district. But it's
the law: Ohio legislators passed the report-card proposal to ensure
greater accountability among school districts and to force schools
with low-scoring students to improve. Local superintendents say
they are searching for ways to do just that, but some aren't happy
with the data.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the state wanted to design a report card to make school
districts look bad, it couldn't have done a better job,'' said
Charles Williams, superintendent of Wayne Local Schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were discouraged and disappointed last year when the report
cards were issued. We've been working all year to improve our test
scores, but won't see results until this year's test scores are
released,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   West Carrollton Superintendent Douglas Roby, whose district met
three of the 18 state standards, said he was surprised and
disappointed at the results, though district officials are
challenging the accuracy of some of the data on which its rating
was based.
</P>
<P>
   Roby said he and other school officials will work closely with
staff and teachers to place even greater emphasis on the importance
of the proficiency tests. School officials plan to produce a video
for the families of fourth-grade students that will include sample
test questions and suggestions on how parents can help.
Staff-development initiatives that will give teachers the
opportunity to learn new instructional skills are also planned, the
superintendent said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton City Schools passed one of the 18 performance
standards: the writing portion of the 12th grade proficiency test.
Only five other school districts in the state met just one
standard: Springfield, Youngstown, Warren, Dayton and Akron. Only
one district ranked lower: Cleveland, which failed to meet any of
the 18 criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Superintendent James Williams said the state's actions of
raising the score needed to pass some proficiency tests and
counting as failures those students who did not take the
proficiency test or a retest contributed to the district's low
ranking. But Williams said he will not offer excuses and accepts
the responsibility for the district to show growth and improvement
in proficiency test scores and other criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton school district will focus efforts on K-4 reading
instruction and attendance to boost future report-card performance,
Williams said. This year, about 90 percent of the district's
kindergarten students are in all-day kindergarten classes, which
should pay academic dividends as those students move through upper
grade levels, the superintendent said. And he said the district has
put programs into place that will help deal with the social and
emotional needs some Dayton students and other urban school
children bring to school with them _ needs that can have a higher
priority than learning in some students' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In the adjoining Trotwood-Madison school district,
superintendent Samuel Brewer said district officials hoped they'd
climb out of the ``academic emergency'' category, but having met
five of the state's performance standards, fell one short.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said Trotwood-Madison officials are planning a town
meeting to discuss the district report card and discuss strategies
for improvement. The district has changed curriculum and provided
additional training to teachers and has launched a computer-based
instructional program geared toward students who have failed
portions of the proficiency tests.
</P>
<P>
   Oakwood Superintendent Judy Hennessey said Oakwood school
officials will use its district report card as a diagnostic tool to
help improve instruction, but will stop short of tailoring its
curriculum to the proficiency test alone. The district exceeded 16
of the 18 standards, falling short in fourth-grade reading and
math.
</P>
<P>
   But Oakwood's superintendent noted that the school district
sponsors enrichment activities for students in areas such as
literature, art and music that may not show up on state-mandated
exams, Hennessey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goals go far beyond the proficiency tests,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
