<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DANGEROUS SCHEME IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are high costs and nasty risks associated with each of the
possible responses to Slobodan Milosevic's expulsion of a million
Albanian Kosovars from their homes. Nonetheless, one proposal being
bandied about by a cluster of senators, including John Kerry of
Massachusetts, &UR;  &LR; is too foolish to be considered seriously: a scheme
to avoid American casualties by arming the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Mitch McConnell, Republican of Kentucky, and Senator
Joseph Leiberman, Democrat of Connecticut, have proposed spending
$25 million to arm the guerrilla bands that call themselves the
Kosovo Liberation Army. In a letter to Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, McConnell described the KLA as ``a credible, capable, and
willing alternative to the deployment of Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The KLA fighters are certainly willing to fight and to receive
US weapons. But until now they have been neither credible nor
capable.
</P>
<P>
   Their lack of credibility stems not only from the political
extremism of their Marxist and Islamic fundamentalist factions and
their connection to the heroin and cocaine trafficking centered in
Albania; it also derives from their willingness to sacrifice
Kosovo's civilian population to their delusional belief in the
talisman of armed struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic bears the guilt for the crimes against humanity being
committed in Kosovo. But if the impulsive young commanders of the
KLA had not brushed aside the realistic leadership of Ibrahim
Rugova, the pacifist who had been elected president of Kosovo's
shadow government, those refugee families sleeping in the rain
might still be in their homes, and their menfolk might still be
alive.
</P>
<P>
   If an American-armed KLA were able to seize power in Kosovo, it
could be counted on to expel Serb civilians and declare
independence, creating conditions for an expanded conflagration in
the Balkan tinderbox.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the KLA lacks the ability to defeat Serb military and
paramilitary forces without the overwhelming intervention of NATO
forces. If Milosevic is to be curbed militarily, NATO must do it,
and without carrying the KLA hotheads to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
