<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-PANAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBYA TURNS OVER TWO BOMB SUSPECTS; SANCTIONS QUICKLY EASED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Libya Monday surrendered two suspects to the
United Nations to stand trial for their alleged role in the 1988
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103, ending more than a decade of US and
British efforts to bring the Libyans to justice for the murder of
270 people.
</P>
<P>
   The UN Security Council rewarded Tripoli by quickly suspending
an air embargo and economic sanctions imposed on the government
between 1992 and 1993 for its alleged role in harboring the two
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the end of a 10-year diplomatic stalemate,'' Britain's
foreign minister Robin Cook said Monday, characterizing the arrest
as an ``historic'' event. ``There will now be a criminal trial for
that act of mass murder.''
</P>
<P>
   It also set the stage for an unprecedented court case in which a
team of Scottish Judges, acting in Dutch territory, will decide the
fate of the two Libyans.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement drew mixed reactions from the relatives of the
victims of Flight 103, which exploded over Lockerbie, Scotland on
Dec. 21, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While some praised the hand-over as an overdue opportunity to
obtain justice, others said they feared that some compromise had
been struck that would shield senior Libyan authorities, including
leader Moammar Khadafy, responsible for ordering the terrorist
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hopeful that these men will be made to take
responsibility for what they have done,'' said Eleanor Bright, a
Boston-area woman whose husband, Nicholas, died in the bombing.
``But I'm concerned that at the end of the day we won't know any
more than we know today about what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects, Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-Amin Khalifa
Fahima, were handed over to the UN's top legal adviser, Hans
Corell, in Tripoli Monday, at a ceremony attended by diplomats from
throughout the African and Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   They were flown in an Italian plane bearing UN markings to the
Netherlands. Through a highly unusual legal arrangement, Britain
will now request the formal extradition of the suspects from the
Dutch government to stand trial at an abandoned American airfield
to be placed temporarily under the control of a Scottish jurists.
</P>
<P>
   It could be several months before a trial begins.
</P>
<P>
   The capture of the Libyans brought an end to a complex and often
frustrating diplomatic high-wire act by Secretary General Kofi
Annan, South Africa's President Nelson Mandela, and Saudi Arabia's
Crown Prince Abdullah. And it provided a rare example of a UN
economic embargo achieving its political objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``No country likes to be treated as an outcast,'' Annan said
Monday in explaining why Libya surrendered the two men. ``I think
Libya wanted to be able to deal freely with its neighbors and with
the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say that the deal could not have been closed without
the involvement of President Mandela. The South African leader has
maintained strong personal ties with Khadafy, a vocal critic of the
apartheid regime, since his days in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confident right from the beginning that President
Khadafy would keep his words. I will not abandon a man who helped
when we were all alone,'' Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin, said that the
Libyan's arrest represented a triumph for US and British diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   He said that a combination of tough economic sanctions and a
willingness to entertain Libya's demand to try the case in a
neutral country, the Netherlands, led to the turnover. But he said
that a separate series of US sanctions designed to thwart Tripoli's
ability to finance international terrorism will remain in force.
</P>
<P>
   The two Libyan suspects were indicted in 1991 by US and Scottish
courts and later placed on the FBI's ``Ten Most Wanted Refugees''
list.
</P>
<P>
   According to the US indictment, the suspects, both reputed
Libyan intelligence agents, placed a Semtex explosive into a
radio-cassette player and stashed it into a Samsonite suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   The suitcase, carrying a New York destination tag, was allegedly
placed by one of the suspects on an Air Malta flight to Frankfurt,
Germany, where it picked up a connecting flight to London before
being placed on Pan AM 103. The explosive blew up over Lockerbie
after take off, killing all 259 people on board and 11 on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said Monday that he would deliver a report to the council
within 90 days assessing whether Libya has met a series of
obligations _ renouncing terrorism, cooperating with the court
throughout the trial and compensating families of the victims of
the Pan AM flight and of a French airliner allegedly bombed by
Libyan terrorists _ before sanctions can be formally lifted.
</P>
<P>
   For all practical purposes, UN and US officials privately
acknowledge that UN sanctions have already been lifted for good
since it would require a vote of the Security Council to re-impose
them, an unlikely prospect given the growing unpopularity of
economic sanctions.
</P>
</TEXT>
