<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTIN GIVES RED SOX MOMENTUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ His soul brother was on the left coast,
wearing Angelic colors and warming up for Tuesday's
Anaheim-Cleveland opener in the shadow of Space Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   And so John Valentin Monday stepped into the third spot in the
Boston batting order _ the slot where Mo Vaughn flexed his muscles
last year _ and delivered the key blows in the Red Sox' 5-3 Opening
Day victory over the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin's Vaughnesque, 430-foot two-run shot onto the grassy
knoll in dead center field at Kauffman Stadium pulled the Red Sox
back from a 2-0 deficit in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo can't hit it that far,'' Valentin said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, he crashed an RBI double to left to provide an
insurance run for Tom Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   This was a hard-fought win, one made more difficult by
Valentin's seventh-inning error that allowed the Royals to score
their third run. But after Day One of the 1999 season, Pedro
Martinez (nine strikeouts) is 1-0, Jose Offerman (4 for 5) is
hitting .800, Valentin has 3 RBIs, Flash Gordon is 1 for 1 in save
opportunities, and Dan Duquette has stopped the laughter.
</P>
<P>
   What else is there to say, Sox fans? (itals)Looks like the
pennant.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be like this,'' said Valentin, traditionally a
slow starter. ``It's a pitching-and-defense type thing. Obviously,
we notice that Mo's not here. He's a guy that's going to knock in
100 runs and you can't replace what he does. We just have to have
consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin is the senior member of the Sox in terms of continuous
service. He is one of the few who can remember spring training in
Winter Haven. He is one of only three remaining players (Trot Nixon
and Scott Hatteberg are the others) who was brought to Boston by
Lou Gorman rather than Duquette. He is a Sox player who actually
can remember Daddy Butch Hobson, and Roger Clemens getting mad at
Wade Boggs. And Jose Canseco's fashionably late appearances at
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin knows Mo like no other player knows Mo. Valentin played
with Vaughn at Seton Hall, then again at Pawtucket, and finally at
Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin hit only .247 with 23 homers and 73 RBIs last year, his
first season after signing a four-year, $25 million contract. He
pledged to get out of the gate more quickly this season and Monday
was a good start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know wy I'm so slow,'' he said. ``Maybe I just like
the hot weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather was a factor Monday. Early in the day, there was doubt
that this game would be played. There was a local tornado watch and
it was pouring until a pregame ceremony in which his Royal
highness, George Brett, emerged from the right-field bullpen,
riding in an old-timey convertible. After the emergence of George
(a first-ball tosser), the tarp came off, and the game started a
half-hour late.
</P>
<P>
   The immortal Joe Randa (nine homers last year with Detroit, 23
for his career) cranked a 3-and-2 Pedro pitch over the fence in
right with one out in the bottom of the first. KC cobbled together
another run in the first before Martinez settled down.
</P>
<P>
   It was still 2-0 when Valentin came up with Offerman on second
and one out in the third. Valentin connected with a 1-and-1 Kevin
Appier fastball and drove it high and far over the wall in center.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, the memorable homers are the ones that go into
the waterfall, and the ones that stick into the side of the grassy
hills. This was one of the latter variety _ a Rawlings meteor crash
landing on the Missouri turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty windy, and that helped,'' said Valentin. ``I
think I've only hit one home run here. But I knew that one had a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Valentin booted a routine grounder (``I took my
eye off the ball'') by Rey Sanchez. The error helped KC close the
gap to 4-3. But in the ninth, after an Offerman triple, Valentin
cracked a double to the deepest part of left field, narrowly
missing another homer. Gordon had no trouble protecting the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Taken separately, the Red Sox and Royals are examples of
baseball's largest problem: the two-tier system. The Red Sox are
flush with money and have a $61 million payroll. The Royals feature
a $24 million payroll, which in part explains last year's 72-89
record.
</P>
<P>
   One of the myths of Opening Day is that every team has a chance
to win the World Series. In truth, half of the 30 major league
teams start this season with no chance to make it to postseason
play. Kansas City is one of those teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals went 22-9 and had the best winning percentage (.710)
in baseball this spring. There has been all kinds of enthusiasm
about the plucky, fundamentally sound, upstart Royals. But they
have no stars. And no chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox? We're still not sure. But a day like Monday makes Red
Sox Nation dream of another playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a good day,'' said Valentin. ``It wasn't
perfect. I gave one back, but Derek Lowe held them down. All in all
a good day. Maybe it's going to be a good year.''
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't that be a surprise?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
