<SLUG> BC-DAYTONA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daytona cops to get tough during black college spring break
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ After failing to clean up Black College
Reunion last year, city officials say they will use firm police
tactics if necessary to control crowds that are expected to top
100,000 this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Like Atlanta's Freaknik, scheduled for next weekend, the annual
gathering of African-American youth at Daytona Beach has been a
lightning rod for controversy. Revelers complain they aren't
welcome, while residents say the youths trash their town with
unruly behavior and mammoth traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   If traffic gets too bad this year, police will limit access to
the beach party zone to people with passes_ residents, workers and
visitors with hotel reservations. Everybody else will be diverted
to parking areas where they can catch free buses to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it took up to six hours to drive from one end of the
beach to the other and back,'' said Daytona Beach Police
spokeswoman Sherri Davis. ``The plan is for public safety, to allow
ambulances and fire trucks to have access in the event of an
emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the tactics are heavy-handed at best, racist at
worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just fearful of seeing a large number of blacks,''
said Daytona Beach City Commissioner Charles Cherry, who also heads
the local NAACP. ``There's a large number of whites over there
(during Spring Break) and nobody's paying attention to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Freaknik and Black Bike Week at Atlantic Beach, S.C., Black
College Reunion has been a long-running but unofficial April event
with a troubled history. In recent years, it has drawn crowds of
more than 100,000, spawning heavy criticism from residents fed up
with the gridlock, noise and behavior that has included public
drunkenness, littering and lewd acts.
</P>
<P>
   Students in the Atlanta University Center are predicting smaller
crowds this year for Freaknik. ``I don't think anyone is going to
come, because nothing has been planned,'' said Jackie Gayle, a
senior at Clark Atlanta University. ``No one is talking about it on
campus. I'm not going anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   A few Freaknik-related Web sites list activities, but the city,
which in past years had a committee to help organize the event, has
yet to reveal how it will mobilize police officers and handle
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, city officials in Daytona Beach hoped to tame that
event by embracing it, sanctioning a promoter who scheduled
concerts and other events around town to try to break up the
traffic gridlock that seemed to generate the most criticism.
</P>
<P>
   But that effort failed as the concerts and other events drew
almost no crowds, while the revelers once again turned Atlantic
Avenue, the main beach drag, into a virtual parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
