<HEADER>
A6884 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIAFARROW-AZR &LR;      04-05 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIA FARROW FILLS BIG ROLE OFFSTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
 FARROW-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KYLE LAWSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For most of her life, Mia Farrow has been content to
reveal herself through the camera's lens, or in fleeting public
appearances. Not her fault if the view is deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   On the screen, she seems such a waif. A tiny, fragile thing with
bones that threaten to poke through the transparent skin that was a
gift from her Irish mother, and a wispy voice that thins out under
stress.
</P>
<P>
   On those rare occasions when she ventures onto a theater stage,
she doesn't seem much larger than her screen persona. At 54, she
still looks like an adolescent in need of a good hug.
</P>
<P>
   The image has served her in good stead in films like ``Death on
the Nile,'' in which she played a deceitful murderess, and in
``Rosemary's Baby,'' where she took on Old Nick himself in defense
of her child. Moviegoers were caught off guard by her strength and
determination.
</P>
<P>
   Looks aren't everything; in Farrow's case, they are almost
nothing. She always has known her mind, and usually followed it. At
19, against the advice of nearly everyone, she fell in love with
the much-older Frank Sinatra and married him, only to file for
divorce a few months later. After the failure of a second marriage
(to musician Andre Previn), she began a common-law relationship
with Woody Allen that dismayed many of her friends.
</P>
<P>
   How could this work, they asked? The neurotic Jewish guy with
the most famous ``me'' complex in world cinema and the fey Catholic
girl whose real career seemed to be taking in stray children?
</P>
<P>
   It did work; for 13 years, although in hindsight, it was largely
because Farrow made it happen. The couple still might be together
if Allen hadn't begun an affair with Soon-Yi Previn, one of
Farrow's adopted daughters. By the time Farrow finished with him in
court and in the pages of her autobiography, ``What Falls Away,''
Allen probably thought Old Nick had gotten off easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't raise 14 children without learning to hold your
own,'' she says obliquely, and that's as close as she will come to
commenting on her problems with Allen. She would rather spend the
interview talking about those kids, four of which are her
biological offspring and 10 of which she adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 10 have special needs; two, for instance, are blind;
another is a paraplegic; two more were born to crack-addicted
mothers. She will give a lecture Monday, part of the Unique Lives &AMP;
Experiences lecture series at Arizona State University, that will
focus on the joy she has found in loving and nurturing such
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to the notion of adoption through the larger idea of
our common need to lead a meaningful life,'' she says. ``Not just
to survive, but to survive meaningfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``My way certainly wouldn't be everyone's way. Adopting children
with special needs is a calling; it consumes my entire day, my
entire life. It is very, very demanding, and at the same time it is
very, very rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   A devout Catholic, she has no doubts as to where her calling
originated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that anyone who does this will tell you that God
gives them a very special gift and grace to do it. I think that is
true of all parenting, but this is beyond that. What I try to
convey to people is how doable and how much fun it is, and how much
the parent receives from the child. My children have given me far
more than I have ever given them. There is no way I can repay my
debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrow's brood has made her a grandmother three times over, and
part of the interview is devoted to the obligatory bragging. One of
her sons is a lawyer, another a computer expert. A couple of the
kids are in college, but seven remain at home. The youngest is 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Andre and I adopted our first child, Lark, it was during
the Vietnam War and we wanted to do something to help the many,
many orphans that came out of that carnage,'' she says. ``It never
crossed my mind that we would be adopting more.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as Lark grew, she brought us such joy. She had been ill,
and to see her grow and be well was . . . I don't think the world
`fulfillment' is too strong. I felt fulfilled in a way that I never
had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Every adoption came as a result of family discussion, especially
as the younger children grew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each new child would find his or her place in the family and
then an adoption agency would call and say, `Here is another one.'
We would discuss it among ourselves and, if all the children were
happy and it seemed possible, I would say yes. I didn't say yes to
every child, and with others I might say no for a year or two and
then the time would be right.''
</P>
<P>
   She ponders that word for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time it happened, it just seemed right. It was never `No,
that's too many,' because it only happened when the family felt it
could give the new child the kind of love and nurturing that was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People laugh when I tell them that it's much easier now. There
are only seven at home. That doesn't seem like a lot to me. I am
one of seven children myself and I don't have trouble handling that
many. But this is it for me. By the time I get the last one raised,
I will be ready to take on being a full-time grandmother. There are
always extra kids, anyway, with sleep-overs and everything. The
house is full.''
</P>
<P>
   By involving the children in the process, Farrow believes she
has created a strong family bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older ones come home every chance they get. They want to
be here for each milestone; this one lost a tooth, that one maybe
didn't get such a good grade. My oldest son, who is a lawyer in
Washington, is the closest thing my children have to a father. If
anything happens to me, I know he would take over the family. For
something that wasn't planned, it has all turned out remarkably
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrow's father was Australian film director John Farrow, whose
credits include ``Wake Island,'' ``The Big Clock,'' '`Hondo'' and
his masterpiece, the dark political allegory ``Alias Nick Beal.''
Her mother was the ravishingly beautiful Maureen O'Sullivan, an
Irish actress who came to Hollywood when she was 19 and later
worked with Garbo, Laurence Olivier, the Marx Brothers and, most
famously, as the scantily-clad Jane opposite Johnny Weissmuller's
Tarzan.
</P>
<P>
   John Farrow died in 1963, but O'Sullivan lived until 1998,
plenty of time to be astonished at the number of her grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect she thought I was a bit daft,'' Farrow says,
chuckling, ``but she was always supportive. She was my bulwark
against everything. She had a sense of humor and wisdom and all the
survival skills. She was just a hilarious and wise friend that I
had in my corner all my life. I miss her terribly.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before her mother died, Farrow lost another touchstone
in her life. She was starring in ``Peyton Place,'' one of
television's biggest hits in the '60s, when she met Frank Sinatra
on the 20th Century Fox back lot. She was so nervous she dropped
her purse. He bent to pick it up and when he straightened, she
found herself staring directly into those legendary baby blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was at that moment that I started to fall in love with
him,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship was tabloid fodder from the first, but the
gossips overlooked one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that I divorced him doesn't mean I didn't love him,''
she says. ``I never stopped loving him, and to this day, I don't
believe he is gone. He's just somewhere else, not too far away. I
talk to him and my mom a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra's widow, Barbara, and his children welcomed Farrow at
the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I stayed at Nancy's house. It was extraordinary to
be there at that time. It was a house so full of love, so much
grief for him, so much trading of wonderful stories. Barbara and
the family allowed me to say goodbye. I will be forever grateful to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of her romance with Sinatra, Farrow seemed poised on
the verge of one of the great film careers. She's had a good run,
but not a great one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I have compromised my career radically. It's a
miracle that I even have one,'' she says. ``But God has been good
to me. The phone still rings. And I must work because I'm also the
breadwinner. I just finished a film called ``Serving in Silence.''
It reminded me of how much I enjoy acting, but there always comes a
point in any shoot when I say, `Enough. Time to go home.' We all
have our fantasies, right? Mine is that someone will come along and
drop a bag of money on my head so that I will never have to leave
the children.''
</P>
<P>
   She may have no regrets about those kids, but the rest of her
life? Well, if she has any, she's come to terms with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one makes it through life without some bad things happening
to them,'' she says. ``I've had my share, I guess, but I don't feel
bitter. That's too big. I give that to God. All that anger would
weight you down and make you a prisoner, and I want to be free.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why having children is so important. Children force you
to turn your life to something good. You want to find God? Look at
a child. Children (begin ital) are (end ital) God. I am blessed by
my children and I thank Him every day.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kyle Lawson can be reached at Kyle.Lawson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
