<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-WEATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER WEATHER ENCOURAGES NATO BOMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Balkan skies clearing, NATO is hoping to
turn up the heat on Belgrade and turn around its flagging air
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by the most powerful military in the world, with the most
technologically sophisticated armor and firepower at its disposal,
NATO forces have so far been powerless to overcome a simple fact of
nature: the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds, rain, and fog repeatedly have prevented the allied
forces from fully flexing their military muscle, grounding some of
their most effective planes and making it impossible to pierce
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's military structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather is improving,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H.
Bacon announced Monday. ``As a result, (Monday night) we were able
to hit a substantially larger number of targets than the day
before, and that in turn larger than the day before that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, however, noted that clear weather had also given NATO
sharpening images of military attacks on Kosovar villages.
</P>
<P>
   With scattered clouds and sunshine during the day, and mostly
clear skies during the night predicted by weather forecasters until
at least until Wednesday afternoon, NATO forces are likely to
increase their strikes by a ``quantum leap,'' said Chris Hellman, a
senior analyst at the Center for Defense Information, a
Washington-based military policy research group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strikes so far have been a pin-prick compared to what is
coming with better weather,'' agreed Bill Taylor, director of
political-military studies at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the allies had
been able ``to make full use of all our assets,'' and sucessfully
blast oil refineries and storage areas, air defenses, ammunition
depots and bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, planes such as the A-10 and the Warthog, a slow,
low-flying attacker that hits tanks, armored personnel carriers and
infantry with deadly accuracy, have not been used as bombers
because of inclement weather, say military analysts and Pentagon
officials.
</P>
<P>
   These planes _ plus those that fly high and rely on satellite
and other tracking systems to guide their bombs _ are likely to be
out in force this week, making it easier to strike the troops and
tank columns that reportedly are responsible for wreaking
devastation on Kosovar Albanian villages and their inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said NATO would ``focus attention on fielded forces in
Kosovo,'' which many analysts have heralded as a welcome move,
albeit one that comes too late to halt ethnic cleansing operations
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts, such as Lawrence Korb, director of studies at
the Council on Foreign Relations, warn NATO forces may be more
effective, but they will also be more vulnerable to attack from
Serbian surface-to-air missiles. ``Your risks are increasing, and
that means some casualties,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
