<HEADER>
A6902 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-     04-05 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEF GROUPS ACCUSE MACEDONIA OF PROCESSING REFUGEES TOO SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-BASES, KOSOVO-ECON) 
(nk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ With tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians
fleeing Kosovo backed up in dismal conditions at the Macedonian
border, international relief officials accused Macedonia on Monday
of endangering lives by processing the refugees too slowly.
</P>
<P>
   One official said that Macedonians were deliberately delaying
the processing out of fear that a massive influx of Kosovo
Albanians would upset the country's ethnic balance. Albanians
account for about 20 percent of this country's population, while
Macedonians, who generally sympathize with Serbia in the current
conflict, make up about 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Ghedini, press officer for the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees, told a news conference in the Macedonian capital of
Skopje that Macedonian authorities were only clearing 5,000
refugees, while 65,000 were stuck on a muddy hillside at the
border, blocked by Macedonian police and army troops from entering
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not enough,'' Ms. Ghedini said. People were now dying
at a rate of 10 a day, she said, and ``this will increase if we do
not get people out from the open.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get them out of the mud,'' she said. ``It is
extremely cold, it has been raining quite a lot, people are
weakened, fatigued and in a state of shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia has been flooded with 136,000 refugees, most of them
arriving in the last few days. In addition to the 65,000 believed
to be stranded at Blace, the main border crossing, another 30,000
people are thought to be on the other side of the border, in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A long trail of cars stretched back miles along the road, where
people have been queuing for nearly a week to cross the border. At
least one more train arrived Monday morning from Pristina, part of
the 5,000 people who had arrived over the last 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The latest arrivals came on foot from the towns of Urosevac and
even Vucitrn in northern Kosovo, fleeing Serbian forces and police
who have forced a mass exodus of ethnic Albanians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   One official with the U.N. refugee agency, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, said that Macedonian officials were barely
cooperating with the relief operation, and charged that the
Macedonians were intentionally putting brakes on the influx.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the foreign aid organizations that are providing
the food and supplies and those with NATO and the U.N. refugee
agency, which are jointly setting up camps to take the refugees
elsewhere in Macedonia, were clearly losing patience Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not want to move people into Macedonia, that is
incredibly clear,'' the U.N. refugee agency official said. ``They
do not like Albanians at all, and that feeling is incredibly
widespread among the population in Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia has declined to give the U.N. agency a full mandate to
process, register and care for refugees, though the agency has
offered to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the experience and ability to process 20,000 refugees
in one day. But they do not want us do it,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have said the influx of refugees threatens
its economic and political stability. They have also expressed
anxiety about the immediate security of the border region, and have
brought in extra troops and police to secure the area and guard the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The policy appeared to have widespread support among ordinary
Macedonians, who did not conceal their antipathy for the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't your countries take them?'' asked one young
policeman, cradling an automatic weapon as he guarded the road at
the camp. ``We don't want them.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Skopje were even more outspoken against the ethnic
Albanian refugees. ``The government should not let them in,'' said
Niko, a 24-year-old dealer of spare car parts and an ethnic
Macedonian. ``As you see we have enough problems ourselves. They
are closing the factories because there is no money and if the
Albanians come in, things will be even worse. We will become a
minority here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Macedonian government's actions on the border also seem
aimed at forcing foreign countries to take a large part of the
refugees. U.N. officials agreed that other countries should help
share the burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are one hour's flight from any European capital, and they
could offer safe havens to people,'' Ms. Ghedini said. ``They
should let them in on a temporary basis because most of these
people will want to go back to Kosovo when they can.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several busloads of refugees were taken straight to the airport
Monday evening in an apparently uncoordinated move by the local
authorities, and five planes reportedly flew about 750 Kosovars to
Turkey. The U.N. refugee commissioner had expected only 90 people
to be flown out to Norway on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   European countries have pledged to take in some 36,000 refugees,
Ms. Ghedini said. But in the meantime, the refugees should be given
immediate help inside Macedonia, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Only one foreign aid agency, Doctors of the World, has been
allowed by Macedonian authorities to set up a medical tent inside
the sprawling camp at Blace. Only local aid workers are allowed
into the camp, to distribute food and gather up the sick. The
official reason given for preventing foreigners from working in the
camp is that it is a restricted border zone.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ghedini said she worked all day and night at a transit camp
put up by NATO for the refugees. ``We were ready at 2 p.m.
yesterday. But there were no registration officials, no buses to
take the refugees,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities only began transferring the refugees in the
middle of the night. By 3 a.m., some 5,000 refugees had been moved
to the transit camp. ``But there was no official at the camp, and
we have no information as to whether they will be processed. This
is quite frustrating,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
