<HEADER>
A6904 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      04-05 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIANS IDOLIZE CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Some want to build a statue of him and put it
in the center of the capital. Others wish he could be their
president, or at least a kind of honorary president. His troubles
at home aside, Bill Clinton is very, very popular in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians have long been friendly toward the United States, a
country that many looked up to as a democratic model during
Albania's four decades of totalitarian rule by communist Enver
Hoxha, who died in 1985. Many Albanians have a family member who is
working in the United States and sending money home to their
relatives in one of Europe's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   But since the NATO bombing of Serbia, the popularity of the
United States _ and of Clinton in particular _ has skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   Next door in Serbia, people are burning American flags and
refusing entry to those with US passports. In Albania, US flags
appear to fly as commonly as Albanian ones _ on the backs of cars,
or the sides of city buses. Tirana and many small northern Albanian
towns have hotels and bars called ``Amerika.''
</P>
<P>
   At a pro-NATO rally a few days after the bombing of Yugoslavia
started, demonstrators carried signs painted with the US flag, and
saying, ``Clinton _ Protector or Freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Albanian men at the rally argued about it. One middle-aged
man said Albania should construct a statue of Clinton shaking hands
with British Prime Minister Tony Blair; the other man, in his 60s,
vehemently disagreed. Clinton should have his own statue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A US passport has become the best calling card for a visitor to
Albania. If you're an American, you might get a hug, or the last
room in a booked hotel, or the best table in a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without you, we would all be dying,'' said a travel agent,
arranging a trip for an American journalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``America _ mire,'' said a taxi driver using the Albanian word
for ``good.'' ``Clinton? super mire!'' he said, gesturing
enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's popularity here has even surpased that of Bob Dole, a
longtime follower of Balkans politics and friend to the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sympathetic to Bob Dole,'' said a high-ranking member
of the Kosovo Liberation Army. ``But Clinton _ he is number one!''
</P>
<P>
   Could Clinton win a presidential campaign in Albania?
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't even have to run,'' said a KLA member.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0443 </DOCNO>
