<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISE-KENNEDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WEEKEND AT THE KENNEDY COMPOUND: $100,000 TO THE DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just as memories began to fade of overnight stays
in the Lincoln bedroom and free rides on Air Force One, an alluring
new perk has emerged for the most generous Democratic campaign
contributors: a weekend getaway to the historic Kennedy compound in
Hyannis Port.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new leadership of Representative Patrick J. Kennedy of
Rhode Island, the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee is
poised to invite $100,000 donors to a premier retreat in September
at his family's treasured vacation spot.
</P>
<P>
   The offer is part of Kennedy's quest to raise $50 million to
help Democrats take back the House in 2000, after six years of
Republican control. Although no details were released of the
weekend activities, contributors presumably will have access to the
full range of Kennedy lore, from the home where President John F.
Kennedy monitored the results of the 1960 election, to the lawn
where Robert F. Kennedy played touch football, to the boat that
Senator Edward M. Kennedy continues to sail.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal to $100,000 donors, which also features retreats in
Newport, R.I., Pebble Beach, Calif., and a ``spring training
weekend'' in West Palm Beach, Fla., marks the DCCC's first special
incentive program aimed at major contributors. The program, dubbed
``Team 2000,'' is modeled after fund-raising initiatives by
political groups aligned with both major parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Team 2000 campaign is ``specifically designed to work with
the leading Democratic supporters nationwide and strategically plan
how we, as a party, achieve our goals,'' Kennedy wrote in a
brochure that was co-signed by the House Democratic leader, Richard
A. Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   For $100,000, donors receive ``annual benefits'' that include
two dinners in Washington with Gephardt, Kennedy and other House
Democratic leaders. The list of retreats with Gephardt and Kennedy
also features a November getaway to Puerto Rico and a January ski
trip to Telluride, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Smith, a spokesman for Kennedy and the DCCC, said the
Kennedy family has held previous fund-raising events at the family
compound on Cape Cod. But there appeared to be little precedent, if
any, for using the location for such a major, national donor drive.
The program's emergence was first reported in Monday's edition of
Roll Call, a newspaper that covers Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said it was too early to determine what kind of activities
will be offered at the Kennedy compound for the contributors. But
chances are slim they will spend the night in the homes where four
generations of Kennedys have dwelled. ``People typically stay at
hotels in Hyannis,'' Smith said of contributors who have previously
visited the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for overhauling the campaign finance system seized on
the promotion as evidence of the need for change, particularly for
abolishing soft money, the kind of large, unregulated donations
that the DCCC and other political groups are seeking with such
incentive programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a perfect illustration of the evils of the soft money
system,'' said Don Simon, executive director of Common Cause.
``What you have here is a blatant sale of access in exchange for
huge soft money contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties have defended the practice by citing the major
disadvantage they would face if they stopped pursuing soft money
dollars while their opponents continued to rake it in by the
millions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the everybody-does-it defense, which is a pretty weak
justification,'' Simon said. ``It shows the pervasiveness of this
kind of corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Republican Congressional Committee predictably
criticized their Democratic counterpart for thinking that ``selling
the Kennedy compound can fill the vacuum of ideas that currently
bankrupts their party.''
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats countered that Republicans have consisently
blocked efforts to overhaul the campaign finance system, while the
House Republican reelection committee has massively outspent the
Democratic team in the last two elections, by a total of $190
million to $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick's goal is to narrow that margin as much as possible,''
Smith said. He described the Hyannis Port retreat and other Team
2000 incentives as ``one element of how we can get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 2010EDT &QL; 
