<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-OFFERMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFERMAN DEBUT RATES AN .800 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Anybody laughing at the Sox for signing Jose
Offerman now?
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette was universally mocked for
giving Offerman a four-year, $26 million contract last winter. Even
Samuel L. Jackson took a shot on the ESPY Awards telecast.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, playing against his former team, Offerman had four hits
in five trips _ a triple, a double, and two singles. He also stole
a base and scored two runs from the leadoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost enough to make you say, ``Mo Who?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty good, wasn't it,'' said Duquette, eschewing an
opportunity to be an I-Told-You-So. ``Jose's made himself a good
hitter. He's become much more patient. A couple of times ... he
fell behind, 0-and-2, but he was patient and came back and got
hits.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first four-hit Opening Day by a Red Sox player since
Mike Greenwell in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman was booed loudly by the KC crowd. Apparently some felt
he didn't hustle here. Others may resent seeing him leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans was booing me, I really don't know why,'' said
Offerman. ``I played here three years and I always played hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette has been ridiculed for saying that Offerman could
replace Mo Vaughn's ``on-base capability.'' Now, Offerman's batting
average is .800. So is his on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited today,'' he said. ``For us to win and for me to
get four hits, that is good.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring Offerman hit .257 with four homers, 16 RBIs, and no
stolen bases in three attempts. He played second base and first
base and appeared shaky at both positions. So the Sox have made him
a leadoff DH.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman christened the Red Sox season just after 3 p.m. (EST).
He came to the plate and was roundly booed by the polite
Midwesterners.
</P>
<P>
   He shut up the locals when he cracked a 2-and-2 pitch into
left-center for a leadoff double. Somewhere in Kauffman Stadium,
Duquette (who lasted the whole nine innings this year) had to be
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman was stranded as Kevin Appier retired Darren Lewis, John
Valentin, and Nomar Garciaparra on two easy flies and a ground out.
</P>
<P>
   There were still boos when Offerman came to the plate with one
out in the third, and he hit the first pitch on a line to right for
a single. Then he stole second base (Offerman had 45 thefts last
year; the Sox leader was Lewis with 29, and Mo had zero). Offerman
rode home on Valentin's 430-foot homer to straightaway center.
</P>
<P>
   When he came to the plate against Appier in the fifth, Offerman
ran the count to 3-and-2, then flied to right.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Offerman led with a single to left off Don
Wengert. In the ninth, he tripled to left-center. Offerman led the
majors with 13 triples last year; no Sox player hit more than
eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans had a nice little preview of what he's gonna do,''
said Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman made no promises. But he knows this will help get the
Boston fans off his back about Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are two different players,'' he said, again. ``It's hard to
replace Mo. It's hard for me to do what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   No problem, Jose. Boston fans will settle for an .800 batting
average any day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
