<HEADER>
A6933 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RELOCATE-BOS &LR;      04-05 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RELOCATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SEEKS SHELTER FOR 20,000 REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department scrambled Monday to give as
many as 20,000 Kosovar refugees emergency shelter on American
military bases from Guam to Guantanamo Bay, a humanitarian triage
that aid experts said was unprecedented in both its size and
mission.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and other administration officials stressed
that the relocation of ethnic Albanians, who have fled in terror in
recent days from their homes, was a temporary relief measure and
would cease as soon as it was safe for the refugees to return to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refugees belong in their own homes on their own land,''
the president said Monday as he described the broad outlines of
``Operation Sustain Hope.'' ``Our immediate goal is to provide
relief. Our long-term goal is to give them their right to return.''
</P>
<P>
   But aside from pledging to do their share to ease the refugee
flood inundating Kosovo's neighbors, US officials offered few
details on how they intended to carry out the huge airlift
operation. The only thing that seemed clear was that no Kosovar
refugees were headed immediately to the American mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said the most likely destination was the US
naval base at Guantanamo Bay in Cuba, where some 7,000 Haitians and
Cubans were encamped at the height of boatlift activities in the
early 1990s. Andersen Air Force Base on Guam, a US island territory
3,800 miles west of Hawaii, is a second possibility. In 1996 and
1997 some 7,000 Kurdish refugees from Iraq were temporarily housed
there before being resettled in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Military spokesmen at Guam and Guantanamo said neither base was
large enough to accommodate 20,000 refugees, and it could take many
days to get the personnel and provisions, including tents, food,
and medical supplies, for even a fraction of the Kosovars. The base
at Guantanamo Bay has only 1,000 sailors and Marines now on active
duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a situation like the Haitians and Cubans,'' said a
spokesman for the Navy at Guantanamo, noting that population was
largely young men seeking political asylum in the United States.
``This is a whole new show _ women, children, and old men forced at
gunpoint from their homes. They are hurt, sick, displaced, and
emotionally distraught people. ''
</P>
<P>
   Experts in refugee relocation expressed surprise that US
officials would consider airlifting broken families from the
Balkans to tropical islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unprecedented movement of people to, what is to
them, the other side of the planet,'' said Dan Detzner, former
director of the Refugee Studies Center at the University of
Minnesota. ``It is very unusual and very distressing that if the
United States expects these refugees to go home, it wouldn't try to
resettle them closer to the home.''
</P>
<P>
   Detzner said he suspects the Clinton administration is trying to
minimize the political fallout and avoid bringing the war in Kosovo
too close to home. ``This war becomes a lot less antiseptic to the
American people if suddenly 5,000 ethnic Albanian refugees try to
resettle in Boston or the Twin Cities,'' Detzner said.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the legal question: Refugees brought to Guam, a US
territory, would have the right to seek asylum and resettlement in
the United States. The situation is not the same at Guantanamo, a
base leased by the US government from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Rizza, national refugee coordinator for Amnesty
International, said he expects the US government to restrict the
Kosovar refugees to military-run camps and stress their stay would
be short, even though the refugees appear to meet international
standards for gaining political asylum and permament resettlement
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   US officials Monday said they were not prepared to describe the
logistics of the operation _ which refugees would be chosen, how
they would be relocated, or what it will cost _ nor would they hint
at whether the refugees would be eligible for asylum in the United
States if the confinement turned out to be something other than
temporary.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said the US effort, which
could eventually involve more than 20,000 refugees, was aimed less
at resettlement than at galvanizing an international humanitarian
relief operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it makes much difference if you are going to fly
to a West European country or you're going to fly to some location
(like Guantanamo or Guam),'' Rubin said. ``You're going to be flown
out on a temporary basis and returned.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federation for American Immigration Reform, a private group
that opposes more open immigration to the United States, Monday
urged the president to reconsider relocating the refugees, arguing
that it would only encourage dictators like Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to oppress and dislocate ethnic groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
