<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6943 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      04-05 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO WILL `PERSIST UNTIL WE PREVAIL,' CLINTON PLEDGES &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By GREG McDONALD 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton vowed Monday ``to persist until
we prevail'' as the NATO air campaign against Yugoslav leader
Slobodan Milosevic's forces entered its 13th day and the refugee
disaster from the Kosovo conflict worsened.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, reaffirming the United States commitment to providing
humanitarian assistance for ethnic Albanians driven from their
homes, made it clear that Milosevic would be held accountable for
their plight and for killings in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `ethnic cleansing' of Kosovo cannot stand as a permanent
event,'' Clinton said at a White House appearance. He all but
declared that NATO's firepower would be used to force Milosevic
into accepting the resettlement of the refugees under
self-government in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Milosevic does not do what is necessary, NATO will
continue an air campaign. It will be undiminished, unceasing and
unrelenting . It will inflict such damage that either he will
change his calculations or we will seriously diminish his capacity
to maintain his grip and impose his control on Kosovo,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to sustain this effort for the long haul. Our
plan is to persist until we prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments marked a significant change in the allied
approach to dealing with Milosevic. Up until this week, NATO
leaders had held out hope of a negotiated settlement. But now,
given Milosevic's sustained effort to depopulate Kosovo of its
predominantly ethnic Albanian population, Clinton and other allied
leaders now seem intent on wiping out his military and then
treating him as war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments were reinforced by State Department spokesman
James Rubin, who told reporters that the international war crimes
tribunal at The Hague would be given ``all the help they need'' by
NATO in making a case against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a State Department report based on interviews with
refugees, Rubin said ``there is evidence'' that Serb forces under
Milosevic's direction are committing genocide and other war crimes
against Kosovo Albanians. He said the time for negotiations with
Milosevic has passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he thinks that in the coming days he can stand up and
declare this thing over through some action short of the objectives
that we have set forth, he's sadly mistaken,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO allies called on Milosevic again Monday to immediately
withdraw his army troops and security police from Kosovo, allow the
refugees to return to their homes under self-government, and to
accept a NATO peacekeeping force to guarantee their safety.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal was made as the United States prepared to intensify
its military commitment to the NATO campaign by dispatching 24
Apache attack helicopters to Albania along with 2,600 Army support
personnel and equipment. Defense Secretary William Cohen said the
Apaches will be used to attack Serb ground forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going after his tanks, his armored units, his artillery,
those forces on the ground that are carrying out this horrific
`ethnic cleansing,' '' Cohen said. ``They are going to be targeted
now and taken out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian government officially agreed Monday to serve as the
base for the Apaches and an additional contingent of 10,000 NATO
troops being sent in to help with the refugee relief effort. But
the Pentagon said that it could take a week or more to have the
Apaches in place and ready. NATO officials worry that by that time
Milosevic may be close to completing his goal of depopulating
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said even if
Milosevic ``think's he's finished'' and can simply declare for
peace at that point, ``We will not be finished.''
</P>
<P>
   That message was delivered in forceful attacks Monday by NATO
warplanes, as they continued to strike at Serb military positions
throughout Kosovo and Yugoslavia, including the capital of
Belgrade. Improving weather allowed NATO to conduct missions that
Monday focused on oil refineries and other industrial sites
critical to supplying the Serb military.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will capitalize on the clear weather to attack strategic
and operational targets throughout the operational area. But in
particular we will focus our attention on fielded forces in
Kosovo,'' said NATO Air Commodore David Wilby of the Royal Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged, however, that taking out military targets in
Kosovo is ``no easy task'' because the Serbs have become fairly
expert at playing ``cat-and-mouse'' with NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are taking every advantage of deserted buildings and
terrain to camouflage their positions,'' Wilby said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Apaches, which fly fast and low, will provide a
level of close-in combat that NATO has not yet been able to engage
in because of Serb air defenses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Apaches, the United States has sent in the
USS Theodore Roosevelt aircraft carrier battle group. The
nuclear-powered Roosevelt entered the Adriatic Sea Monday, along
with three other surface ships and a submarine armed with Tomahawk
cruise missiles. Pentagon officials said the Roosevelt's F/A-18
Hornets and other aircraft would likely start flying missions
today.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO was intensifying its attacks on Serb military
positions, it also began airlifting thousands of Kosovar refugees
out of Albania and Macedonia to countries that have agreed to
provide temporary sanctuary. The United States has agreed to take
up to 20,000 of nearly 400,000 displaced Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said that the refugees taken in by the United States
likely would be airlifted to the U.S. naval base at Guantanamo,
Cuba, which has been used before as a refugee holding point.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the same point in his comments at the White House,
where he called on Americans to make financial contributions to
help in the relief effort. He said people interested in donating
should call 1-800-USAID-RELIEF.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
