<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: PUBLIC SUPPORT IN CONFLICT CAN TURN ON MILITARY LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 Carl Hulse is in the Washington Bureau of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dazed and battered American soldiers stare into a
camera, captives of an enemy power. Courageous rescue efforts are
mounted to retrieve missing pilots. The body of a lone soldier is
paraded down a Somali street.
</P>
<P>
   In post-Vietnam America, these vivid images personalize war for
a casualty-conscious public, one that has come to know conflict on
a first-name basis.
</P>
<P>
   Americans watched in anger as bruised Jeffrey Zaun, the downed
Navy flier, was exhibited on Iraqi television during the Persian
Gulf War. They cheered in relief at the rescue of Scott O'Grady
after he was shot down in the Balkans. They cringed in anguish as
pictures out of Mogadishu showed an American corpse dragged though
the streets as well as the bloody face of Warrant Officer Michael
Durant, a captured helicopter pilot.
</P>
<P>
   A string of U.S. military operations since the mid-1960s has
resulted in relatively low casualties when compared with the
carnage of Southeast Asia, allowing residents of the electronic
village to focus intently on the losses that have occurred. This
phenomena is visible once again as the fighting in and around
Kosovo continues.
</P>
<P>
   Americans were riveted to their televisions, following accounts
of the downing of the Stealth fighter and the return of the
still-unidentified pilot. They are absorbed in developments in the
capture of the three soldiers whose names are already familiar _
Steven Gonzales, Andrew Ramirez, Christopher Stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casualties bring the war down to the personal level,'' said
Rep. Steve Buyer, the Indiana Republican who heads the House
Military Personnel Subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   This single-minded attention to potential casualties is a major
factor for the Clinton administration as it considers adding
helicopter gunships to its arsenal. Strategists are aware that
support of the deployment can turn on public response to American
losses.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters is a sharp division of opinion over whether
a nation where many still shudder at the memory of body counts from
Vietnam is willing to accept any casualties at all or will
countenance conflict only if no American blood is spilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans don't have a stomach for casualties in a world in
which there is no clear vital threat to our security interests,''
said Larry Berman, a senior fellow at the Woodrow Wilson Institute
and an expert on Vietnam-era politics. ``There is a very low
tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the mentality, the feeling is as a long as it is
bombing, the American public will accept it,'' Berman said. ``But
once those body bags start coming home, support ... is going to
disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who have studied the issue say American resistance to
battle casualties is exaggerated and can be overcome by strong
leaders able to lay out a persuasive case for American involvement
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The public is ``neither trigger-happy nor gun-shy,'' said Bruce
Jentleson, a senior fellow at the U.S. Institute of Peace who has
written extensively on public attitudes toward casualties.
</P>
<P>
   He said that U.S. acceptance of casualty risks typically hinges
on two chief perceptions _ that the main goal of an operation is to
thwart aggression and that those commanding it have a workable
strategy. If the two tests are met, he said, the public will not
balk at losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may not know where these places are on the map or have
lots of information about them, but there is a common-sense quality
to the judgment that they make,'' Jentleson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jentleson and others point to the Persian Gulf War as a case
where President Bush and military leaders were able to convince the
public of the necessity of the mission. Polls at the time indicated
public backing would remain strong even if casualties ran into the
thousands, though the final toll of less than 150 killed in action
was a welcome relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the stakes are perceived to be high, when the prospects
for success are perceived to be good and when the costs are viewed
as being commensurate with the stakes, there can be robust support
in the face of casualties,'' said Eric Larson, an analyst at the
RAND think tank in California.
</P>
<P>
   Larson believes a key element of public support for a conflict
that brings casualties is consensus among political leaders;
division between the president and Congress, for instance, can lead
to cracks in public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also say the appearance of uncertainty among the
political and military elite can cause support to rapidly crumble,
pointing to the push for withdrawal from Somalia after the military
suffered casualties and the Clinton administration struggled to
define the U.S. role there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are hesitating, doubtful, if the notion persists that
we're on the path that can't succeed, then the public mood could
swing more strongly,'' said Brent Scowcroft, national security
adviser in the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   Scowcroft laid part of the blame for the emergence of a
``zero-casualty'' mentality in the media and the immediacy with
which modern warfare is covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as there is a casualty, you people go to the parents,
wives, relatives and shove a microphone in their faces,'' he told a
group of reporters. ``And the wife or mother says, `I don't know
why my boy is over there getting killed because people can't manage
their own affairs.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there is some sentiment that President Clinton has
thus far failed to adequately prepare the public for the
possibility of losses in Kosovo or made his best case for
involvement, putting his public support at risk should casualties
occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are very patriotic and most of them would
easily understand the stakes over there, our interests, if the
president would explain his objective with clarity,'' said Sen.
Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby said that the president could well be helped in building
U.S. backing for the operation by the dramatic footage of the three
captive servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that will stiffen the resolve of the majority of the
people,'' Shelby said. ``I know that it did to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-POWS06-COX     04-05 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POWS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'CODE OF CONDUCT' GUIDES BEHAVIOR OF POW'S
 &HT;    610&AMP;add. With KOSOVO-MAIN.
 &HT;    Eds: Optional add is suitable for use as a separate box.
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the three American soldiers held captive in
Yugoslavia, the complicated world of multinational military
objectives has been reduced to a mission so simple the Army
summarizes it on wallet cards.
</P>
<P>
   The mission is to keep fighting, and the weapon is the Code of
Conduct for the United States Military.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Pentagon confirmed that authorities in Belgrade
have said they will not follow through on threats to hold criminal
trials of Spec. Steven Gonzales and Staff Sgts. Christopher Stone
and Andrew Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``The encouraging thing is that after a couple of days, the
Yugoslav government has announced that they will be treated as
POWs,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
   But becoming a prisoner of war doesn't end a service member's
obligation to fight, and the trio's status as captives to be held
until the end of hostilities highlights one of the most intangible
_ but significant _ aspects of America's military training program.
</P>
<P>
   While bombs and bullets are used by the rest of NATO forces,
America's three captured soldiers must fight Yugoslav authority by
refusing to participate in propaganda, by answering no questions
beyond name, rank and Social Security number, and by accepting no
special favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a physical task, it's a mind-set,'' said Maj. Shelly
Stellwagen (cq) of the Army's Office of Public Affairs. Fighting
the enemy through mental resistance ``becomes a part of you when
you're a soldier,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The resistance is based on a code of conduct adopted after the
Korean War that lays out a straightforward obligation of military
personnel:
</P>
<P>
   ``The duty of a (soldier) to continue resistance to enemy
exploitation by all means available is not lessened by the
misfortune of capture. Enemies whom U.S. forces have engaged since
1949 have regarded the POW compound as an extension of the
battlefield. The POW must be prepared for this fact.''
</P>
<P>
   But the intensity of that preparation varies from job to job
within the military. While pilots and others who operate deep
behind enemy lines get extensive survival training for life as a
POW, those less likely to be captured rely almost exclusively on
their conviction to follow the Code of Conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, Stone and Ramirez belong to the latter group. They
haven't attended one of the four Survival Escape Resistance Evasion
(SERE) schools run by the military branches at the direction of the
secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they've been trained repeatedly in the importance of
living by the Code of Conduct no matter what the circumstances. And
they, like all Army personnel, were given wallet cards with the
essence of the code summarized in 10 sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it enough? Good question,'' Stellwagen said. ``Based on the
experience of POWs in the past, it appears to be.''
</P>
<P>
   For retired Navy Capt. Mike McGrath, living by the Code of
Conduct was enough to keep him alive during six years as a POW in
North Vietnam. But he got his training on the code through the SERE
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' said McGrath, 59, now an airline pilot. ``I
give it great credit for saving my skin.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath was shot down June 30, 1967, and although badly injured
in the crash, he immediately was subjected to physical torture that
coerced him into signing a ``confession'' of war crimes. But in a
last act in defiance of his captors, and in the spirit of the Code,
McGrath misspelled his own name in the signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got mad,'' McGrath said, ``but they didn't make me go
back and change it, either.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   American military personnel must strive to live by the Code of
Conduct while held captive by enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Among the main points of the Code:
</P>
<P>
   _ A POW must ``think escape,'' must try to escape if able to do
so,
</P>
<P>
   and must assist others to escape.
</P>
<P>
   _ The United States does not authorize any military service
member to sign or enter into any such parole agreement.
</P>
<P>
   _ Experience has shown that, although enemy interrogation
sessions may be harsh and cruel, it is usually possible to resist,
if there is a will to resist.
</P>
<P>
   _ The POW may never willingly give the captor additional
information, but must resist doing so even if it involves
withstanding mental and physical duress.
</P>
<P>
   _ However, understand that if taken past the point of maximum
endurance by the captor, the POW must recover as quickly as
possible and resist each successive captor exploitation effort to
the utmost.
</P>
<P>
   _ Regardless of the type of detention or captivity, or harshness
of treatment, (soldiers) will maintain their military bearing. They
should make every effort to remain calm, courteous, and to project
personal dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
