<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOODWATERS STRAND 700 IN EAST TEXAS &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CINDY HORSWELL 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RYE, Texas _ More than 700 people, some without water or
electricity, remained marooned Monday after heavy rains washed out
a dam that also provided the only access to their homes in a
subdivision northeast of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For the eighth time in five years, the dam across Mill Creek in
Big Thicket Lake Estates, a subdivision that straddles the
Liberty/Polk County line, was breached about 1 a.m. Sunday after 10
inches of rain fell in about three hours, said Dianne Walton,
president of the property owners' association.
</P>
<P>
   The dam was topped by a road that provided the only access for
about half of the residents of the subdivision off Texas 146.
</P>
<P>
   One street in the marooned area remained without electrical
power Monday and, because a pump broke down on a well, more than
100 homes also were without water.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happened on Easter weekend when a lot of residents had
visitors, some from out of state. All are left stranded now,''
Walton said. ``County officials did help us move some people out by
airboat until dark on Sunday, but it was a one-way trip, and those
people aren't allowed to return until we get our road back.''
</P>
<P>
   More residents were leaving with their own boats Monday, but
Walton said authorities were advising against it because of
fast-moving water. A boat was available for medical emergencies,
however, to ferry people to an ambulance if necessary, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the dam was destroyed, one woman was evacuated Sunday by
Life Flight helicopter after suffering what was described as a
life-threatening allergic reaction to a wasp sting, Walton said.
Another woman was taken by boat to an ambulance after a serious dog
bite, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us feel very frustrated,'' said stranded resident Kay
McCoy, 53, a homemaker. ``I got enough supplies to keep me and my
3-year-old grandson for a week, but this gets tiring. County
officials have had a grant to build us a new exit for three years
but nothing seems to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Polk County received a $350,000 grant to build an all-weather
bridge and access road in the subdivision in May 1997, officials
said. It is to be built farther upstream and at a higher elevation
so that it won't wash out again, they said.
</P>
<P>
   County officials have decided not to pour any more money into
repairs for the access road that washed out Sunday. Instead, Cook
said, a temporary access road will be built where the new bridge is
to be located.
</P>
<P>
   Residents have been plagued by flood troubles since the original
dam was built decades ago. In 1994, after numerous washouts,
residents raised funds to build a new dam and access road that they
thought would withstand floods.
</P>
<P>
   That dam, however, was damaged repeatedly by floods, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
