<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-650&AMP;A     04-05 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB TV AGAIN SHOWS ALBANIAN LEADER CALLING FOR PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-BASES, KOSOVO-ECON) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ As Serbia tried to clean up Monday after
NATO's heaviest bombing raids so far, Serbian television once again
gave prominence to images of a moderate ethnic Albanian leader,
Ibrahim Rugova, showing him in meetings with a senior Yugoslav
official and the Russian ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   State television said Rugova, who is living under Serbian police
protection in Pristina, the Kosovo capital, met there Monday with
Yugoslav Deputy Prime Minister Nikola Sainovic and the Russian
ambassador to Belgrade, Yuri Kotov. The men were shown in a living
room with unidentified journalists and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova and Sainovic, the announcer said, called for an end to
the bombing in Kosovo and agreed to work for a peaceful negotiated
solution, with the safe return of all refugees. Rugova, who has
always favored a non-violent path to Kosovo's self-rule and
ultimate independence, was quoted as saying that he ``is prepared
to continue work here so everyone can see I'm still in Kosovo and
trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Rugova was said to have confirmed that he met Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic, and Belgrade television said Rugova's statement
Monday ``has caught NATO in a lie and revealed the propaganda war
waged against our country.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an intriguing follow-up, the television quoted Rugova as
saying he would like to go abroad. ``I am interested in going to
Skopje and other countries, because I am here without my
associates, and in Pristina I cannot contribute to the solution of
the problem,'' the announcer quoted him as saying. Skopje is the
capital of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, there was no audio accompanying the video footage, and
no way to verify that Rugova had said any of the words ascribed to
him. NATO has said that Rugova is under house arrest and has no
freedom of movement, that he has not called for an end to the
bombing but for an end to violence in general and that footage of
the meeting with Milosevic, which Serb TV said occurred last
Thursday, was actually two years old.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav and Russian officials have said that the
Milosevic-Rugova meeting did occur, and the official news agency
Tanjug said Monday: ``Rugova himself used the occasion to reject
Sunday's statement of NATO spokesman Jamie Shea that he had not met
President Slobodan Milosevic, and that the pictures taken on April
1 could be two years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Kotov, Tanjug continued, confirmed that Rugova ``is safe and
alive, that he is free to move and that his house is not damaged,
thus rejecting the speculations of certain foreign media and NATO
officials that Rugova has been arrested and his house burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts Monday evening to reach the Russian Embassy for comment
were unsuccessful. Shea, for his part, said in Brussels: ``We are
going to have to wait until the end of this conflict in Kosovo to
learn all of the facts about Rugova and therefore I probably should
reserve judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Western officials are concerned that Milosevic will suddenly
announce a political deal with Rugova for substantial political
autonomy for Kosovo, much along the lines of a Western-drafted
solution that Rugova signed in France, but without a role for the
Kosovo Liberation Army or NATO peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova has lost popularity and credibility to the fighters of
the Kosovo Liberation Army, but he has retained significant support
among civilian ethnic Albanians. If he is a willing participant in
a deal with Milosevic, many Albanians will regard him as a traitor
but others may welcome a chance to return home in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Yugoslav officials have said privately that Milosevic
still believes an internal political solution is possible in
Kosovo, while other officials who have his ear are pressing for a
form of partition that keeps the northern half of the province for
Serbia and effectively cedes the rest.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO is unlikely to accept either option.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In widespread bombing early Monday morning, NATO struck at
military targets and civilian infrastructure that the military
might conceivably use for resupply. NATO destroyed the empty
Yugoslav air force headquarters in Zemun, a municipality of
Belgrade, and damaged surrounding buildings; in Nis, 125 miles
south, the headquarters of the 3rd Army was demolished, along with
an army barracks.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, about 9:30 local time, Nis was hit again by ``six
or seven cruise missiles,'' television reported, but did not
specify the targets. The nearby town of Aleksinac was also struck,
as was Novi Sad, the largest city in northern Serbia, which has
been the target of earlier strikes.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, no figures for military casualties were released.
</P>
<P>
   But many government and military buildings are empty, and even
state television, expecting to be bombed, is said to have moved to
hardened bunkers and alternate transmitters.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also hit Belgrade's Surcin airport and Pristina's Slatina
airport, both of which have extensive radar facilities, and the
southern Belgrade suburb of Rakovica, which also has radar. NATO
also set a fuel depot on fire near Kragujevac, 40 miles south of
Belgrade, and damaged a bridge on the Ibar River.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was shown on television meeting aides and businessmen
and urging reconstruction of facilities damaged or destroyed by
NATO. He also awarded medals to several Yugoslav army officers.
</P>
<P>
   NATO dropped propaganda leaflets over the town of Subotica that
explained its bombing campaign and provided the frequencies of some
foreign radio stations, the Beta news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subotica people, being wise and sound, will judge for
themselves how these NATO messages sound after all it has done to
our country,'' the local authorities told the agency.
</P>
<P>
   A Serb in Belgrade said the leaflets ``will only remind everyone
of the Nazis dropping propaganda leaflets during World War II.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
