<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PHILLIPS-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGE DEPARTURE IN SAN JOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A player who is the seventh defenseman on the San
Jose Sharks would seem an unlikely candidate to be a participant in
one of the more bizarre episodes in the National Hockey League in
recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent decision by Andrei Zyuzin, a 21-year-old Russian,
to abandon the Sharks a month before the start of the playoffs has
cast an unsettling shadow over his team's impressive and somewhat
surprising drive to the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuzin, the second player chosen in the 1996 draft, insists he
left the Sharks because he felt mistreated by Coach Darryl Sutter
and because the team's management had been unresponsive to his
complaints. If this were the entire story - disgruntled player
going AWOL and demanding a trade - there would be little unique
about it.
</P>
<P>
   But Zyuzin's abrupt action was accompanied by the decision to
fire his agent, Jay Grossman, and replace him with a Ukrainian
named Vitaly Shevchenko, who is not certified as an NHL agent and
reportedly is under FBI investigation. Shevchenko, whose previous
clients include former King Dimitri Khristich, lost his
certification a few years ago when he didn't pay his dues to the
NHL Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuzin has not been seen publicly since his departure, though he
did speak with reporters by telephone from Vancouver last week. His
current whereabouts are uncertain. There is concern in the Sharks'
organization that Zyuzin's decision was made under duress from
Shevchenko.
</P>
<P>
   There have been news reports in recent years about extortion
attempts by the Russian Mafia against players from the former
Soviet Union. The Zyuzin situation may have brought this problem to
a disturbing new level.
</P>
<P>
   GROUNDED ROCKET (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Panthers have a $58-million investment in
high-scoring right wing Pavel Bure, but the Russian Rocket
underwent reconstructive surgery on his right knee for the second
time in his career last week and is gone for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Panthers officials say the 28-year-old Bure will be back in six
months, in time for the start of training camp. The Panthers had
better hope so, considering what they are paying him.
</P>
<P>
   Bure played in 11 games this season and made $3 million. If he
had been paid at that rate for an entire 82-game season, he'd have
been paid in excess of $22 million for the year. As it is, his
per-game salary this season was more than $272,000.
</P>
<P>
   SCARY SITUATION (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   As frightening as the collapsed right lung of Eric Lindros was,
the outcome could have been much worse for the Philadelphia Flyers
star, who will miss the rest of the regular season and also may sit
out the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros remains in a Nashville hospital and has been receiving a
morphine drip to quell the pain of an injury, the origin of which
remains uncertain. Half of the blood in Lindros' body bled into his
damaged lung.
</P>
<P>
   According to one report, Lindros' injury was of a severity
commonly found in the victim of ``a car wreck.'' And reportedly,
had Lindros chosen to return to Philadelphia before seeking
treatment rather than going to the hospital in Nashville, he might
have died on the flight.
</P>
<P>
   MILE HIGH FLEURY (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Theo Fleury is enjoying life with the Colorado Avalanche, who
played host to the Kings on Monday night. Entering that game, the
prospective free agent had eight goals and 19 points in nine games
with the Avalanche, and he said he might like to sign with Colorado
after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll wait to see what happens,'' Fleury said. ``The more days
that go by and the more the sun shines, I'm really enjoying it (in
Denver). It would definitely be a possibility at the end of the
year that I'd like to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   BAD INVESTMENT (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   How's this for an ominous statement on the financial state of
the NHL? Missouri billionaire Bill Laurie wants to buy Denver's new
arena, the Pepsi Center, from Ascent Entertainment Group. And he
wants to buy the NBA Denver Nuggets from Ascent.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal reportedly is contingent on Ascent finding a
separate buyer for its other sports property, the Avalanche,
because Laurie is concerned about the NHL's lethal combination of
escalating salaries and low broadcast revenues.
</P>
<P>
   LOOSE PUCKS (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Sun reported that Edmonton general manager Glen
Sather, whose contract expires after the season, will displace Dean
Lombardi in San Jose. The Sharks issued the anticipated denial. The
Sun also reported that Larry Robinson has been telling friends he
plans to take a year off and spend it on his farm in Florida,
assuming he isn't back as the Kings' coach. Robinson has declined
comment until after this season on his plans for next year. ...
When he was traded to New Jersey last week, Sergei Nemchinov became
the second player to play for the Devils, New York Rangers and New
York Islanders. The first was Pat Conacher, also a former King. ...
Phoenix reportedly would have fired Coach Jim Schoenfeld had the
Coyotes lost a pivotal game to the Mighty Ducks a few weeks ago.
The Coyotes, who began the season 17-2-2 but have been mediocre
ever since, beat the Ducks, apparently saving the coach's job. ``If
the coach is good, you don't say, `Oh, boy, if you lose this one,
you're toast,'' Schoenfeld said. ``If a coach is bad and wins three
in a row, you should still replace him. To me, the whole thing is
moronic, really. If I'm wrong for the job and the team has won five
in a row, get the guy who's right. Have the guts to make a
decision. Change the coach or change the tune, because I'm tired of
hearing the same old song.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
