<HEADER>
A6961 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES-COX     04-05 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves notebook: Jones picks up where he left off
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers and Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The start to the 1999 season looks a lot like the
start to his 1998 for Andruw Jones, who went 0 for 4 on Monday
against the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   That tacked on to his 0 for 19 streak to end spring training
spell out another spring slump for the young center fielder. Jones
finished the spring with a .169 batting average, which was actually
worse than last year's .200 spring average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not frustrated,'' Jones said after the game. ``Those
things are going to happen. You start the season 0 for 4 it doesn't
matter. You've got 161 more games to go. You just have to stay
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   One difference this year is Jones has hitting coach Don Baylor
to help get him going. After going 0 for 4 in the final exhibition
game against the Indians on Saturday, Jones went to batting cage
for some extra work with Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done his work all spring,'' Baylor said. ``He really has.
He's been a lot more dedicated, out early in the morning.``
</P>
<P>
   Baylor was looking for the positives to encourage Jones and
found one on Friday in the walk Jones took against the Orioles in
his 0 for 3 outing after Scott Erickson threw him a pair of sliders
out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Jones problems stem from swinging at breaking balls out
of the zone, but Baylor said he's also missing the pitches he likes
up in the strike zone. But Baylor said Jones had been moving his
head in those situations, something they've addressed in their
hitting sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga's pitch
</P>
<P>
   As planned Andres Galarraga made an appearance at Turner Field
Monday via video monitor, as he ``threw out'' the cermonial first
pitch via the matrix board in center field. He was being filmed at
his home in West Palm Beach, Fla. as he continues chemotherapy
treatments for non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   Standing with his two daughters Katherine (13) and Andria (7),
Galarraga said: ``I am so excited and so sorry I cannot be there
today. Anyway, I wish for the best good luck for all the players,
the Atlanta Braves and thank all the fans for all the support you
gave to me. I thank you for the Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he tossed a ball toward the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Several Braves wore Galarraga's No. 14 in permanent white ink on
their caps as Tom Glavine did Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   El Presidente visit
</P>
<P>
   It would hardly have been opening day in major league baseball
without Dennis Martinez. And it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The retired elder statesman on the Braves pitching staff made an
appearance at Turner Field on Monday on his way to Birmingham, Ala.
to watch his son Gilbert play in a high school baseball tournament
for Westminster (Fla.) High.
</P>
<P>
   After 23 seasons in the major leagues, the 44-year-old Martinez
is now doing a little coaching with his son's team and may
eventually do that on the professional level, although he turned
down a coaching offer from the Braves this offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do it, I'll do it at the big league level,'' Martinez
said. ``I don't have to go to the minor leagues to prove anything.
I'm enjoying my family right now. Next year, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he wasn't ready to quit playing after last year -
when he became the all-time winningest Latin American pitcher in
major league history with No. 244 last August 9. But eventually he
announced his retirement when nobody called. Martinez said he spoke
with Braves general manager John Schuerholz in January and
Schuerholz told him he'd heard Martinez was retired, even though he
hadn't made a formal announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I still had a chance to hook up with somebody,''
said Martinez, who only would have considered the Braves, the
Indians or the Marlins because he makes his home in Miami. ``That's
why I didn't make an announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he could still pitch, Martinez looked back at the
other end of the clubhouse where most of the players' lockers are,
smiled and nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role I did last year, I think I can do it again,'' said
Martinez, who was used primarily in relief. ``But I didn't like it
very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez work
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of the Braves were off on Sunday, rookie
left-hander Odalis Perez pitched six innings against Braves Class
AA and AAA hitters at the Disney spring training complex in
Florida. He allowed three hits, no runs, struck out 10.
</P>
<P>
   Perez will get his first major league start as the Braves fifth
starter on Friday against the Arizona Diamondbacks. While he said
his arm is in great shape, Perez said he'd like to build up his
strength. Perez, who is 6-0, 194, would like to get up to 200 for
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to work a little bit more now,'' Perez said. ``The
season is so long and you have to be ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrible two's
</P>
<P>
   Phillies pitcher Curt Schilling led the National League in
strikeouts each of the last two seasons, but his inability to get a
third strike cost him dearly in the first inning. After going 0-2
on Chipper Jones with two outs and the bases empty, Schilling
walked the Braves third baseman. Brian Jordan singled to shortstop
on an 0-2 pitch. Schilling got ahead of Javy Lopez 0-2, then the
catcher fouled off three of the next four pitches before doubling
down the rightfield line to score Jones and Jordan. ``It's a
frustrating situation when you can't close the deal,'' Schilling
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fair warning
</P>
<P>
   During the fourth inning, the scoreboard issued a cautionary
note to fans which read: ``Stay alert! Bats and balls may enter the
stands rapidly.'' The addition of ``bats'' to the warning may have
been in response to a lawsuit filed by Sterling Lapinski against
the New York Mets. Lapinski sustained head injuries during a July
11, 1997 game at Turner Field when struck by the bat of Mets
catcher Todd Pratt. . . . Phillies backup outfielder Rob Ducey
nearly cold-cocked first baseman Rico Brogna during warmups in the
eighth inning. Ducey was warming up Yorkis Perez when his throw
back to the pitcher sailed wide. The ball missed Brogna, who was
jogging out to first base, by only two feet.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing upfront
</P>
<P>
   The top of the Atlanta lineup had a tough afternoon, with Otis
Nixon, Bret Boone and Chipper Jones going a collective one-for-11
and reaching base just twice in a dozen plate appearances. Nixon
was one-for-four, with a single to rightfield in the seventh
inning. Boone was hitless in four at-bats and Jones in three.
Jones, who struck out twice, drew a walk in the first inning. Boone
did hit the ball well in all four trips. He lined out to right
field in the first inning, grounded hard to shortstop in the third,
then flew out to right and center in the fifth and seventh,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers and Len Pasquarelli write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
