<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS FACE OUTFIELD QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- When the Angels open the 1999 season tonight against
the Cleveland Indians at Edison Field, Jim Edmonds will once again
be wearing periwinkle blue.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds is on the disabled list until April 15 with a groin pull
and sore shoulder, but it could've been a lot of worse. He could've
been wearing another team's colors.
</P>
<P>
   That would've eliminated the team's surplus of outfielders, but
at what price? We're talking about one of the top outfielders in
the league here.
</P>
<P>
   Thus as another season begins, the Angels remain faced with a
similar problem. Once Edmonds returns, how do they play four
outfielders in three spots?
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, there were rumors the Angels would trade
Edmonds for a pitcher. But it's safe to say nobody offered the
Angels two 20-game winners for Edmonds, or for Garret Anderson, the
other player named in the trade rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad and Tim Salmon were said to be untouchable, leaving
the Angels with four quality outfielders, one destined to serve as
designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   How do you keep them all happy?
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins says he has a plan, but he won't say what
it is. If spring training is any indication, Anderson will be the
wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad had 18 starts in left field and one at DH this spring.
Edmonds had 14 starts in center and two at DH. Salmon had 20 starts
in right and one at DH. Anderson had four starts in left, 11 in
center, three in right and three at DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's what they want to do, I'll do it,'' Anderson said.
``They pay me to play baseball. I'm not one to rock the boat. I'm
most comfortable in left because I've been doing it for 10 years,
but I can play any of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people wish they could do what I do (for a living). I
can't complain about where I'm playing. That's the least of my
worries.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds expressed his displeasure in the trade rumors last
winter. General manager Bill Bavasi, the one who could have helped
ease Edmonds' concerns, chose not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is, we've got four excellent athletes,'' Bavasi
said. ``None of them wants to DH, and that is understandable. I'm
not saying anybody's going to blame me for having too much talent,
but I'm not going to cut back on talent to make people happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys will find out over the course of the season,
whether it's aches and pains, an injury, a lack of performance, any
number of reasons, they're all going to play the outfield a lot. To
make a trade to improve our ballclub is always a priority. To make
a trade to improve players' happiness is never a consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the four wants to sit the bench or DH. Salmon did it for
all but two weeks of last season because of a foot injury and he
hated it. Each knows he is good enough to play in the field every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Collins says he's not concerned about hurting anybody's
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the last thing we need to talk about,'' Collins
said. ``Each one will do whatever it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins won't deny that the outfield defense is best with
Edmonds in center and Salmon in right. So they'll be there most of
the time. Salmon says he expects to start 155 games in right field.
Edmonds, a two-time Gold Glove winner, can't make his
highlight-reel catches as a DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already served my time as a DH,'' Salmon said, referring
to last year. ``I want to be out there every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how it's going to work out,'' Edmonds said.
``We'll find out soon enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
