<HEADER>
A6965 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTGOMERY-SFCHRON &LR;      04-05 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTGOMERY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Montgomery Chief Is Banking on New Tactics
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Talk about headaches. Consider what's happened to Lew Coleman since
he became chief executive of NationsBanc Montgomery Securities six
months ago:
</P>
<P>
   _Thomas Weisel, his former boss, started a rival investment bank
weeks after quitting Montgomery in a huff, taking with him all the
staff and clients he could spirit away.
</P>
<P>
   _More than 20 percent of Coleman's top managers jumped ship,
many of them joining Weisel.
</P>
<P>
   _The brokerage industry and trade press gossiped about a
meltdown at San Francisco's Montgomery, fueling the view that the
firm's investment banking business had all but collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after months of silence, Coleman has come out swinging. He
vows nothing less than to catapult what was a second-tier, regional
brokerage to the top of the investment banking world.
</P>
<P>
   He has already promoted several promising younger executives,
forced out a handful of old-timers and raided the nation's top
investment banks to fill high-level vacancies. And he boosted the
value of a partnership by taking the coveted status away from about
20 junior partners.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; While commercial banks lend money, investment banks are the
clubby Wall Street firms that sell securities, organize mergers and
give strategic advice to corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   Boosted by money and clients provided by BankAmerica, the North
Carolina bank that bought Montgomery 18 months ago, Coleman says
his firm will elbow its way within three years into the ``bulge
bracket,'' becoming one of the top five U.S. investment banks
alongside such firms as Goldman Sachs and Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   It plans to get there by doing business not just with &LR;   &LR; its
traditional client list of small- and midsize companies, but with
customers of BankAmerica, including most of the largest, best-known
corporations in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business is growing away from the pure, little
boutiques,'' Coleman said in a recent interview. ``We're a company
with 2,000 people. It's a big food chain. We need to do business
with the companies institutional investors want to own,'' the
biggest corporations with the largest market value.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the odds are against Coleman. Companies tend to
stick with their traditional investment banks and don't readily
switch loyalties, they point out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montgomery's prospects of crashing the bulge-bracket in the
near term are remote,'' said independent brokerage analyst Michael
Flanagan.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also wonder whether Coleman can re-energize a firm that
got its spark from Weisel's driving personality.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rivals claim the defection of top talent has taken
away Montgomery's competitive edge in such key industries as
technology and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Several traditional Montgomery clients that have sold stock
recently, including computer component-maker Hutchinson Technology
and hardware superstore Lowe's, have turned to other investment
banks. Montgomery said it declined to co-manage Hutchinson's recent
stock offering when the lead assignment went to another firm.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery has fallen from ninth place two years ago to 24th
place today in the value of stock offerings it led, said Securities
Data Corp. Montgomery said its calculations put it in 14th place.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said Montgomery's most important business, trading
securities for mutual funds, pension funds and other institutional
investors, is thriving. Thanks to its booming brokerage business,
the firm's revenue surged 80 percent in January from the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, BankAmerica's $45 billion in equity capital gives
Montgomery the financial backing to do far larger deals than it
ever could before.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery has recruited new managers to replace those that
left. ``While we certainly did not like to lose senior people, we
have replaced them with people just as good,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Coleman argued, Montgomery ''is changing, but it's not
apparent that there is any loss of value and there has been no loss
of market share.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, a shaggy-haired, fleshy-faced 57-year-old, is
relatively new to investment banking. Five years ago, he was the
No.2 executive at San Francisco's old BankAmerica, regarded as the
top contender for the bank's top job.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, David Coulter, not Coleman, got the nod as BofA's CEO.
Coleman soon jumped to Montgomery where he played a key role in
negotiating the firm's 1997 sale to North Carolina's NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, Weisel quit Montgomery after losing fights with
NationsBank for control of key business lines. Coleman was named to
replace him. Compounding the irony for Coleman, NationsBank also
bought BofA and took its name.
</P>
<P>
   To help rebuild Montgomery, Coleman relies on Carter McClelland,
his New York-based investment banking chief.
</P>
<P>
   McClelland, a longtime Wall Street power broker and the former
head of the U.S. investment banking operations for Germany's
Deutsche Bank, has been on a hiring tear.
</P>
<P>
   He's recently hired new section chiefs in health care and
technology, handing out huge paychecks and signing bonuses to lure
top talent, according to industry gossip. McClelland said he's
merely paying the going rate.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery's investment banking chief is concentrating on wooing
BankAmerica clients while holding on to the firm's traditional
customers. Montgomery and the bank are testing joint sales teams to
call on certain customers.
</P>
<P>
   Don Putnam, managing director of San Francisco brokerage Putnam,
Lovell, de Guardiola &AMP; Thornton, said Montgomery can make headway
if BankAmerica continues to bankroll its expansion. But he thinks
Montgomery's goals of serving big corporations while keeping
traditional clients happy can't be harmonized.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm skeptical,'' Putnam said. ``A few years from now, I think
they will have the same market share and won't be as profitable as
they are today.''  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
