<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARDINAL-COX     04-05 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDINAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nigerian Cardinal, possible Papal candidate, visits Atlanta
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some came to the Cathedral of Christ the King to see
Cardinal Francis Arinze because he represents an important tie to
their native Nigeria. Some came because he provides a role model of
a powerful black leader in the international church. Others came
because they thought they might be seeing the next pope.
</P>
<P>
   Arinze, 66, presided over an evening prayer and benediction, a
brief service adoring the Eucharist, with about 200 worshippers at
the cathedral Monday night. African immigrants in native garb _
bright, long skirts and large colorful headdresses _ blended their
voices with people in business dress as they sang African hymns,
accompanied only by their clapping hands.
</P>
<P>
   After the service, he greeted a long line of well-wishers in the
church's fellowship hall.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal continues his visit to Atlanta with a Mass at 3
p.m. today at St. Catherine of Siena Church in Kennesaw, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Archbishop John F. Donoghue said the cardinal's visit
signifies the growth of Atlanta's Nigerian Catholic community.
Officials estimate there are about 2,000 Nigerian Catholics in the
archdiocese, which covers most of North Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main purpose is for him to come and see the Nigerians,''
said Joseph Ofili, a Nigeria native who has lived in Atlanta for
about eight years. ``We don't want any politics brought into his
visit''
</P>
<P>
   But other Atlantans were willing to address speculation that
Arinze could succeed Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard he's maybe the next pope,'' volunteer Mary Ann
Vorce, 34, a member of the Cathedral parish who was baptized and
confirmed into the Catholic church just Saturday night. ``I think
it's quite possible,'' said the archbishop. ``He's talked about all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Baptized into the Roman Catholic Church at age 9 from a family
that practiced traditional African religions, Arinze was archbishop
of Onitsha, Nigeria, before being called to serve at the Vatican by
John Paul II in 1984. He is one of five people charged by the pope
with pulling together the massive year-long celebration of 2000,
declared a Holy Year by the pope.
</P>
<P>
   And, as long-time president of the Pontifical Council for
Interreligious Dialogue in Rome, he represents the pope and the
Roman Catholic Church in reaching out to other faiths. As an
African, Arinze is reputed to be especially interested in the
church's relationship with Muslims, since Islam runs neck-in-neck
with Christianity as the majority religion in Africa. In his book
``Inside the Vatican,'' Jesuit scholar and Vatican-watcher the Rev.
Thomas J. Reese included Arinze on a list of possible papal
candidates. The growth of Catholicism in Africa and the increasing
influence of Third World men in the College of Cardinals increase
the chance that the next leader of the Catholic church could be
non-European.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
