<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Web Site Lists Low-Rate Cards
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Is there any place on the Web where I can find out which
credit cards offer the lowest interest rates?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Try  &LR; www.bankrate.com &LR; , a comprehensive service
sponsored by Intelligent Life Inc. in cooperation with Bank Rate
Monitor. It won't cost you anything, but prepare to be deluged with
annoying advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   You can search for the best credit card deals by state, or scan
all offerings. There is a section showing the lowest introductory
interest rates and another with the best rates after the
introductory period expires. You can find out which credit card
issuers offer rebates, which offer the best platinum-card deals,
which offer the best gold-card deals and which provide the most
generous frequent-flier bonuses. There also is data comparing
annual fees.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, you can use this site to search for low-rate auto
loans, mortgage and home equity loans and more.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great source of information for people with a pressing
need to spend money they don't have.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, you can find some of the same information every
Monday in the Chronicle's Business section, on the Data Bank page.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Lickin'
</P>
<P>
   Q: I own 40,000 shares of Boston Chicken Inc. I thought this
franchised restaurant chain was a promising speculation, but I have
lost the bulk of what I put into it. At one point, the stock sold
for more than $40 per share, but last year, the company filed a
Chapter 11 bankruptcy notice, and the stock now sells for less than
a dollar. I plan to hold it until I regain a profit on my shares or
until I die, whichever comes first. My question is: Why haven't I
continued to get quarterly reports from the company? I want to
monitor its progress, if any.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Your doleful experience is a useful reminder that hot
stocks don't necessarily rise forever. A lot of latter-day
investors seem to have forgotten that _ if they ever knew it.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Chicken, which despite its name is based in Colorado,
filed for Chapter 11 protection last October and was delisted by
Nasdaq in December but continues to trade on the Over-the-Counter
Bulletin Board. It still files reports with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, but they haven't been useful lately because
the company's finances are in chaos. For copies, try calling the
company's investor relations department at (303) 216-5356.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston Chicken's latest report, filed last month, management
indicated that the company's independent auditor,
PricewaterhouseCoopers, asked it to review and restate possibly
erroneous financial results it previously reported for 1997 and the
first three quarters of 1998. No report was ever issued for the
fourth quarter of 1998. Until the numbers are rejiggered _ which
could be quite a while _ it will be impossible for you to analyze
the company adequately.
</P>
<P>
   Management also said it has asked its investment banker to find
a buyer for the company. However, there is no guarantee that any
such savior will materialize.
</P>
<P>
   You say that you will hold your shares until they are profitable
again. That kind of die-hard attitude has been the ruin of many
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Are you certain this is the most promising place for the $30,000
or so your investment is still worth? Perhaps Boston Chicken _ like
its cousin the Phoenix _ can rise from the ashes. But there doesn't
appear to be a rational way to appraise the company just now.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes on IRA Withdrawals
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have turned 70 and soon will be required to make my first
withdrawal from my Individual Retirement Account _ which means I
will have to pay taxes on the money. Some of my holdings are in
stock, which has appreciated considerably during the past few
years. Am I permitted to pay taxes on my long-term stock gains at
the capital-gains rate? That would save me a lot of money. Someone
told me that I can do this if I take possession of the stock rather
than selling it and removing cash from the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Your informant got it wrong, unfortunately. When you use
your IRA to buy stock, any gain in the value, no matter how long
you held the stock, is taxed at your regular income-tax rate.
Someone in the 28 percent bracket, for example, would not be able
to take advantage of the 20 percent maximum rate on long-term
capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   That may seem unfair but remember: For as long as you maintained
your IRA, you were able to defer taxes on the assets in your
account. You were allowed to reinvest your dividends and any
capital gains from stock sales without forking over a chunk of the
proceeds to Uncle Sam each year. As a result, your assets grew
faster than they would have done if they had been kept in a taxable
brokerage account. Now it's time to pay the piper.
</P>
<P>
   If it's any consolation, Internal Revenue Service spokesman
Jesse Weller points out that if you withdraw stock from your IRA
rather than liquidating it, any future increase in the stock's
value will be taxable as capital gains. Only the gains you
accumulated before withdrawing the stock will be taxed as ordinary
income.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
