<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Yahoo Trying To Move Itself Beyond PCs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Yahoo isn't just for personal computers anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara Internet company yesterday said it will extend
the reach of its top-rated Web ``portal'' site beyond personal
computers and to millions of handheld computing devices and
television-based Internet appliances like WebTV.
</P>
<P>
   Palo Alto startup Online Anywhere will provide the technology to
make the connections possible under a technology-sharing agreement.
The financial terms weren't disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The move is part of a scramble by commercial Web sites to reach
a growing number of consumers who are expected to snap up non-PC
devices over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Market researcher International Data Corp. estimates the number
of handheld devices will soar to as many as 55 million in the
United States in 2002, rivaling the installed base of home personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our `Yahoo Everywhere' strategy. We are not bound to any
one computing device,'' said Ellen Siminoff, Yahoo vice president
of business development.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's popular portal site _ a one-stop destination where
consumers can converse, shop, get up-to-the-minute news and search
the Web _ is currently viewed by 50 million to 60 million people
monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo intends to reach even more of the computing masses by
employing technology from Online Anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-person company makes software that enables Internet
providers like Yahoo to quickly reformat and deliver their content
to TV set-top boxes, pagers, personal digital assistants, palm-top
computers and wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   Online Anywhere, founded in June 1997, is funded by Motorola
Ventures and venture-capital firm Draper Richards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help Yahoo users access their personalized content
and services everywhere _ PC or no PC,'' Online Anywhere chief
executive Mohan Vishwanath said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Yahoo is not exclusive, however. Online Anywhere
is discussing similar deals with other commercial Web sites,
including several Yahoo rivals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Nearly every major player in the Internet market, in fact, is
scrambling to make content available to anyone who owns a computing
device.
</P>
<P>
   America Online is already busy building its own ``AOL Anywhere''
service to link the Net to non-PC appliances. AOL eventually
intends to make its service available through high-speed cable
television, telephone and wireless connections.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Microsoft, which acquired WebTV in spring 1997, has also made
clear its plans to saturate non-PC devices with its Internet
content.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Yesterday, Yahoo shares surged $39.38, to $219.13, on news
that its first-quarter profits will surpass expectations and that
its purchase last week of Broadcast.com Inc. will ramp up
viewership and, consequently, sales. Yahoo is scheduled to announce
its results tomorrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
