A6973 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASDAQ-SFCHRON &LR;      04-05 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 New Nasdaq Trust Off to a Fast Start
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
How would you like to be able to invest $100,000 in a single stock,
ignore it for 10 years, and wind up with more than $1.1 million?
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what would have happened if you had been able to
buy a stock representing the red-hot Nasdaq-100 index at the end of
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, back then there was no single stock representing
the Nasdaq 100, which is made up of the 100 largest nonfinancial
companies traded on the Nasdaq market and is heavily weighted with
high-technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But now you can buy shares in a new entity called the Nasdaq-100
Shares Trust, which began trading on the American Stock Exchange
four weeks ago with the ticker symbol QQQ. Sponsored by the
recently merged Nasdaq and Amex, and administered by the Bank of
New York, it mirrors precisely the performance of the Nasdaq-100
index.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is priced at 1/20th the value of the index. The
index itself stands above 2,000, and most shareholders steer clear
of stocks priced that high. So Nasdaq and the Amex gave the trust a
per-share value that wouldn't frighten off most investors.
</P>
<P>
   The trust closed yesterday at $111, up $3.78.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq 100 has swung high and low over the years, but on
balance it has been a tremendous overachiever. Since the end of
1988 it has risen more than 1,000 percent, including an 85 percent
gain last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   That was far ahead of the 363 percent gain achieved during the
decade by the S&AMP;P 500 index _ the principal benchmark for money
managers. Another leading index, the Dow Jones industrials, has
gained 351 percent since the end of 1988.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a diversified portfolio consisting primarily of
fast-moving tech stocks such as Microsoft, Intel, Cisco Systems and
MCI /Worldcom, you can amass one simply by purchasing one or more
shares of the trust through your broker.
</P>
<P>
   There are other ways to invest in the Nasdaq 100 _ through a
number of mutual funds that also track it.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nasdaq trust offers investors two important advantages
over the funds.
</P>
<P>
   First is flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   You can trade them in and out in a single day, and you can sell
them short.
</P>
<P>
   With mutual funds, you can't sell short or day-trade. You must
enter a straightforward buy or sell order, then wait to learn your
price at the end of the day, when the fund manager calculates the
closing net asset value of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Kinnel, an equity fund analyst with Morningstar Inc. in
Chicago, says the Nasdaq trust should appeal to active traders who
want to take advantage of the Nasdaq 100's high volatility.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the volume so far, active traders certainly seem to
have discovered the trust.
</P>
<P>
   The trust's turnover has averaged 3.4 million shares per day,
even though there are fewer than 5 million shares outstanding. Its
opening-day volume of 2.6 million shares on March 10 was the
biggest debut in the history of the Amex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleasantly surprised by the trading activity so far,''
says Amex spokesman Dan Noonan. ``We expected this kind of volume,
but not so early on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq trust also offers an advantage for long-term,
buy-and-hold investors.
</P>
<P>
   The trust administrators charge a low management fee _ just 0.18
percent of assets per year. By contrast, mutual funds that track
the Nasdaq 100 charge more than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That can make a big difference in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   If the Nasdaq 100 were to match its 10-year growth record during
the next decade, someone who invests $100,000 now would pay a
10-year total of about $14,000 in management fees at the 0.18
percent annual rate charged by the trust.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to pay 1 percent per year to a mutual fund under the
same scenario, your fees would amount to a hefty $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq-100 Shares Trust is modeled after a dozen or so other
index-based trusts that cropped up on the Amex starting in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Most prominent among these are the S&AMP;P 500 Depositary Receipt
Trust, which tracks the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, and the
Diamonds Trust, which emulates the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq-100 trust already is producing greater daily trading
volume than any other index trust except the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   It invests in each of the 100 companies in the Nasdaq-100 index,
which are weighted in the index according to their total market
value (price per share times number of shares outstanding).
</P>
<P>
   Because high-technology stocks dominate the index, the trust is
more than 70 percent invested in tech. The 10 largest stocks in the
index account for more than half its value, and the largest of all,
Microsoft, accounts for 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco money manager Stu Pillette says the Nasdaq trust
could be a good choice for investors who want to bet on the future
of high tech but can't decide which stocks to pick.
</P>
<P>
   The diversification offered by the index ``ensures that people
aren't taking the ultimate risk of losing all their money,''
Pillette observes.
</P>
<P>
   But he warns that because tech stocks are so volatile, investors
in the trust could occasionally find themselves on a scary
roller-coaster ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stocks represent cyclical growth, and they have taken
their lumps from time to time.''
</P>
<P>
   But financial planner Richard DelMonte, with the DelMonte Group
in Danville, says: ``You have to have the conviction that the
Nasdaq 100 is a good place to be _ and I happen to be someone who
does. Many of those firms in there are going to be the blue chips
of the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
