<HEADER>
A6974 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-COX-0406     04-05 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-COX-0406 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    AIR STRIKES CONTINUE AS MORE U.S. FORCES HEAD TOWARD BALKANS
 &HT;    EDS: OPTIONAL TRIMS THROUGHOUT; STORY MAY BE TOPPED WITH LATE
BOMBING INFORMATION
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON With bridges, refineries, tanks and troops in their
crosshairs, U.S. and allied pilots used a second night of clear
Balkan weather to press a 13th day of air strikes against Serb
forces in Kosovo and their support systems across Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO stepped up its attacks on Serb forces in the field, the
USS Roosevelt aircraft carrier arrived in the Mediterranean Sea,
and its 50 strike jets were scheduled to join the attacks on Serb
positions Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Those aircraft, and another 25 electronic jamming jets and other
support aircraft from the Roosevelt, will join the growing NATO
force. In addition, four warships and one attack submarine
traveling with the Roosevelt can fire long-range Tomahawk cruise
missiles, effectively doubling NATO's sea-launched missile
capability.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, NATO air forces included more than 400 warplanes
and support craft, roughly half of which are American, including
the supersonic B-1 heavy bomber, the B-2 long-range Stealth bomber,
the F-117 Stealth bomber and F-15 and F-16 fighter/bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will capitalize on the clear weather to attack strategic
and operational targets throughout the operational area. But in
particular, we will focus our attention on fielded forces in
Kosovo,'' NATO air commodore David Wilby told reporters at alliance
headquarters in Brussels. ``We are just starting to him them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton vowed to sustain
``undiminished, unceasing and unrelenting'' raids on Serb forces
and supply lines as the White House opened the door to the
possibility of sending ground troops to Kosovo without a peace
agreement with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials insisted that there were no plans for
NATO ground troops to fight their way into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   They stressed further that the administration's goal is to
coerce Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia,
into signing a peace accord that calls for sending 28,000 NATO
troops into the Serb province of Kosovo to oversee the
implementation of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, however, there was open talk about the
possibility of sending in ground troops without the consent of
Milosevic, if the NATO bombing campaign brings about the collapse
of Serb forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be one of two things that will happen,'' White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said. ``He will agree, because of the
punishment that he is currently taking, and will continue to take,
from the air, or his military ability to impose his will on Kosovo
will be so degraded, and in some cases destroyed, that he will no
longer be able to impose his will.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lockhart, ``We will continue this effort, if he doesn't
agree, until his forces are no longer a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart and other officials insisted that the proposed NATO
peacekeeping force which would include 4,000 U.S. troops would only
enter Kosovo in a ``permissive environment.'' In other words, the
administration does not intend to launch a ground war pitting NATO
against Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally and officially, a permissive environment implies a
political agreement with Milosevic under which he consents, as he
did in Bosnia, to allow NATO peacekeepers into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly a permissive environment that we envision is one
where there is a political settlement,'' Lockhart told reporters at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether a permissive environment could exist without such
a settlement, Lockhart hinted that it could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there's an environment
</P>
<P>
   where the Serbs and Milosevic don't have the ability to impose
their will,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That comports with a statement made Sunday by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, who told the NBC television network that there
are ``other ways to create a permissive environment,'' besides
striking a diplomatic deal with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has said that he has no intention or plan of
sending in ground forces in anything but a permissive
environment,'' Albright said. ``There are other ways, however, to
create a permissive environment...What we are doing is
systematically diminished or degrading his ability to have that
kind of control over the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Against that background, Clinton's own statements Monday, while
a bit oblique, made clear that the United States is determined to
ensure NATO control over Kosovo, with or without agreement from
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either he will change his calculation, or we will seriously
diminish his capacity to maintain his grip and impose his control
on Kosovo,'' said Clinton. ``Our plan is to persist until we
prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL ADD
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With or without cooperation from Milosevic, NATO intends to
create the conditions necessary for the safe return of the more
than 800,000 ethnic Albanians who have been forced from their homes
by Serb terror roughly half of whom have fled Kosovo for the refuge
of neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic may think he's finished. We will not be finished,''
said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon. ``I think it is clear that
cleaning out Kosovo is not the end of what's going on now it's the
return of refugees to their homes in Kosovo and the rebuilding of
Kosovo and the attainment of a safe, secure, self-governing
environment that is the end state
</P>
<P>
   we're working towards now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NATO air campaign is designed to force the eventual collapse
of Serb military operations in Kosovo. In nearly two weeks of
bombing, the campaign has yet to halt Serb aggression in Kosovo,
but it has destroyed a long list of facilities essential to
maintaining that offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a dozen key bridges had been destroyed by late Monday, as
well as more than a dozen fuel depots and refineries and more than
a dozen ammunition dumps.
</P>
<P>
   Key nerve centers the central headquarters for Serb army, air
force and special police forces have been destroyed, as have
extensive portions of the communications network these forces
depend on to coordinate their activities and order changes in
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The cumulative effects of such losses, NATO has said, will
eventually choke the Serb offensive and force a chronic collapse of
the military units conducting it.
</P>
<P>
   Should NATO be required to launch a ground operation in the face
of a Serb retreat, preparations underway to expand NATO forces in
the region would serve the alliance well.
</P>
<P>
   There are 11,000 NATO troops in Macedonia. That force has long
been intended as the vanguard of a NATO peacekeeping operation in
neighboring Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Another 8,000 NATO troops are en route to Albania, ostensibly to
assist with humanitarian efforts there.
</P>
<P>
   And the Pentagon is sending 24 Apache combat helicopters, along
with 18 battlefield rocket launchers, 2,000 troops and some Bradley
tanks all to Albania to add to NATO's combat capability in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The reason given for the Apaches is to be able to knock out Serb
tanks and troops in support of the NATO air campaign. The Apaches
would be critical, however, to the support of ground operations,
should they be ordered. They were particularly effective in mop up
operations targeting tanks and troops that survived the massive air
campaign in the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches aren't expected to become operable in Albania for
another week, possibly another ten days, said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon stressed that deploying the Apaches does not signal the
introduction of ground forces to the NATO mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting troops into Kosovo right now would lead to vicious
assaults against the
</P>
<P>
   troops that would without doubt end up killing many of the
refugees trying to get out,'' said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
