<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Braves drop season opener to Phillies 7-4
</P>
<P>
   By Carroll Rogers
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves opening day game came complete with
82-degree sunshine, the sentiment of seeing Andres Galarraga
throwing out the first pitch via video, and early optimism.
</P>
<P>
   But what started with a two-run leg up on Curt Schilling and the
Phillies in the first inning came crashing down in the ninth. With
two runs, four Mark Wohlers walks, and a Ryan Klesko error, a tight
game unraveled into a 7-4 Phillies win.
</P>
<P>
   What had been billed as a pitching showdown between Schilling
and Tom Glavine played out like an offensive tug-of-war.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves scored twice as many runs off Schilling in the first
inning (two) as they did in two games against him last April (one).
Glavine gave up more runs in this start (five in 6 2/3 innings)
than he did all last April (four in 34 innings). After Scott
Rolen's two-run home run in the third inning to put the Phillies up
3-2, no lead was safe until Wohlers' struggles in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Anderson and Brave newcomer Brian Jordan had been dueling
all game for center stage before the Phillies rookie second baseman
eventually won out.
</P>
<P>
   He drove in the trying and go-ahead runs with a two-run
broken-bat bloop single off Glavine with the bases loaded in the
seventh inning and added insurance two innings later with a
run-scoring double off the center field wall. He was 3 for 4 with a
double, a run scored, and three RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``The broken bat broke our backs,'' manager Bobby Cox said.
``Period.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan also went 3 for 4, hit his first home run as an Atlanta
Brave, scored two runs and doubled up Doug Glanville after he
caught a Rolen line drive in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   But the tough outs didn't come for the Braves on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Glavine) pitched pretty darn good after the third inning,''
Cox said. ``Up until that point, his ball wasn't moving much. After
that, his ball was sinking like crazy. The old Glavine was out
there. He ran into some real bad luck in the seventh.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Bobby Abreu stirring up trouble with an infield hit,
followed by Mike Lieberthal's second hit of the game. Glavine then
settled in and recorded outs on a Desi Relaford bunt and a pop up
by pinch hitter Kevin Sefcik, bringing Cox to the mound for a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine stayed in and intentionally walked Glanville to load the
bases and bring up the left-handed Anderson. Anderson made him pay
with a flare into left center field to score two runs and put the
Phillies up 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always feel better about my chances than anybody else's so
unless I'm absolutely out of gas and I wasn't,'' Glavine said. ``It
was just a matter of `Do you want to face Glanville?' or `Do you
play the odds and face the left-hander?' We did the smart thing
probably and I made a good pitch and he just blooped one in that
beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
