<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS PLAN BOND SALE TO HELP COVER DEFICIT
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority hopes to cover part of a $150 million
budget deficit this year by selling the first Palestinian bonds,
the authority's financial affairs chief said.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the so-called sovereign debt markets would represent a
breakthrough for the Palestinian Authority, which has been unable
to raise money in the markets with its ambiguous status as a
semiautonomous territory controlled militarily by Israel. The
finance official said the authority expected to pay most of its
bills with tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Auditors Call Off MergerThe two accounting giants, KPMG
and Arthur Andersen, called off their proposed Canadian merger, in
the face of disagreement about it among partners of KPMG Canada.
</P>
<P>
   LIBERTY LIFTS STAKE IN SET-TOP BOXES
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Media Group, the cable television programming
distributor run by John Malone, became the largest shareholder in
General Instrument, the leading maker of television set-top boxes.
Malone needs to insure that set-top boxes, which provide e-mail,
telephone service and high-speed Internet access through television
sets, gain in popularity if Liberty is to increase sales of its
interactive programming.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED RENTALS BIDS FOR RIVAL
</P>
<P>
   United Rentals, the nation's largest equipment-rental company,
offered to buy a rival, Rental Service, for $553 million in an
effort to block Rental Service from buying another rival,
Nationsrent. United Rentals also offered to assume $810 million in
debt.
</P>
<P>
   OIL INVESTMENT BOOM SEEN IN LIBYA
</P>
<P>
   European oil companies are preparing for an investment boom in
Libya after the nation turned over two suspects in the 1988 bombing
of a Pan Am airliner, clearing the way for the United Nations to
lift sanctions. Libya has lost $24 billion in potential revenue
since the sanctions were imposed in 1992 and is desperate for
investment.
</P>
<P>
   COSTS OF EXXON-MOBIL MERGER
</P>
<P>
   The planned $80 billion merger between Exxon and Mobil will cost
$2 billion to complete with an additional $90 million going to
bankers and others who put the deal together, the companies said in
SEC documents.
</P>
<P>
   WAL-MART AND AMAZON SETTLE SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores agreed to settle a lawsuit accusing Amazon.com,
the Internet bookseller, of having raided Wal-Mart's workers to
learn about its computer system, the companies said. No money is
being paid, but Amazon.com and Drugstore.com, in which Amazon owns
a 46 percent stake, agreed to reassign former Wal-Mart computer
staff members to other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   DIVX DAMPENING CIRCUIT CITY RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   With consumers spending freely, Circuit City Stores looks poised
to cash in on a rebound in sales of televisions, cordless
telephones and other electronics, not to mention the growing
interest in all things digital. But there is a chink in Circuit
City's armor: its gamble on Divx, a technology that allows
consumers to pay a small fee for videos that do not have to be
returned. The product line has been a big drag on earnings so far.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL MORE RESILIENT THAN EXPECTED
</P>
<P>
   Even as Brazil struggles with its deepest recession since the
early 1990's, the country has had far fewer bankruptcies and
business closings than analysts expected. In fact, the picture of
the Brazilian economy is a lot less bleak than it was a month ago.
Now,instead of cautioning investors of the possibility of a
domestic debt default, economists are working to convince people
that a recovery could be swifter and stronger than initially
thought.
</P>
</TEXT>
