<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NOTEBOOK-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVS DISPLAY THEIR ANIMOSITY TOWARD U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-BASES,
KOSOVO-ECON) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Anti-NATO and especially anti-American
feeling has grown steadily among ordinary Yugoslavs with the
bombing of largely civilian infrastructure targets like bridges,
fuel dumps and office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than turning the people against their leader, President
Slobodan Milosevic, the attacks seem to have solidified support
behind him, as the commander-in-chief of a Yugoslav nation at war
with the world's most powerful country. While the NATO alliance is
the formal enemy, Yugoslavs seem to be reserving most of their
animosity for the self-styled leader of the alliance, the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   An American photographer visiting Novi Sad was nearly taken
captive by infuriated citizens, who threatened to tie him to a
bridge there. Extra care must be taken in conducting random
interviews. One journalist was lightly beaten by some young men
because of his nationality, and another was slapped by an older
woman.
</P>
<P>
   Vicious posters have begun to appear, mocking both Clinton's
goals of a new world order and his purported sexual habits. A huge,
painted message on a billboard overlooking the Brankova Bridge over
the Sava River bears an obscene epithet toward NATO.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, university students and faculty members went
to the trashed premises of the American and French cultural
centers, the British Council and the Goethe Institute to salvage
the libraries there, so they can be returned once the war, and some
of the passion, has finally passed.
</P>
<P>
   As Bombs Fall, Who's Next?
</P>
<P>
   Now that NATO has extended its bombings to government and
military buildings downtown, there is a lot of speculation and fear
about what new targets will be hit.
</P>
<P>
   Misko, a denizen of the Ipanema cafe, says he lives near the
Defense Ministry and can barely keep down his food. ``We should all
go to Bermuda and wait for the year 2000,'' he said, noting in the
next moment that the government has banned all men ages 18 to 60
from leaving the country during this state of war.
</P>
<P>
   His small cosmetics factory has shut down, he said, mostly
because his employees are frightened to go to work during the 12 to
15 hours of daily air-raid alerts here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love going to Italy,'' said another patron, 37-year-old
Aleksandar, sipping an espresso. ``I went first when I was 15. I
love the light, the food, everything. In a way, it's our culture,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   But the war is isolating Belgrade and the Yugoslavs. Independent
radio and television stations are being shut down, all flights into
and out of the country have halted, most Western embassies are
closed, and most foreigners have fled. ``All of us will end up in
Jagodina,'' Aleksandar said, referring to a town in rural central
Serbia that is synonymous with provincial tedium.
</P>
<P>
   Dragana says she always imagined a life abroad. But now, she
says, she feels ``more and more Serb,'' held to the land here. ``I
can't leave my parents now or our people,'' she said. ``I feel like
a hostage. But in a way, I don't mind. I have no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   When another customer ordered a Coca-Cola, Aleksandar reacted
with mock horror: ``That foreign drink!''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting Words
</P>
<P>
   While the Yugoslav government is rationing gasoline, oil and
diesel fuel, state television is having no difficulty finding ample
supplies of incendiary language.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO alliance and its members, by order of the Yugoslav
Information Ministry, are regularly called ``NATO aggressors,''
``beasts,'' ``criminals,'' ``villains,'' ``thugs,'' ``fascist
legions'' and ``hordes of murderers.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's pilots are called ``pilot assassins'' and
described as ``ruthlessly cruel,'' or ``heartless and
unscrupulous,'' while they are said to carry out ``genocidal acts
and crimes against humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav citizens and officials widely complain of being
demonized by the Western media.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Yugoslav television has hardly sanctified
Clinton, who is variously called ``Bill Hitler'' or ``Adolf
Clinton'' _ or sometimes, for simplicity's sake, simply
``Fuehrer.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also been given choicer epithets, like ``the
American pimp,'' ``war criminal,'' ``scoundrel'' and, most
elaborately, ``saxophone player, criminal and murderer.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Choose Your Dictator
</P>
<P>
   It was not especially surprising that Yugoslav state television
would show the movie ``Wag the Dog'' _ or even ``Apocalypse Now'' _
in an effort to compare NATO's intervention in Kosovo to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   But it did come as something of a shock, in a city where
Milosevic's widespread powers are undisputed, to see state
television broadcasting parts of the Charlie Chaplin film ``The
Great Dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns were soon allayed, however, when the newscast that
followed the film compared Clinton to Hitler and NATO to the Nazis,
who bombed Belgrade in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   One Silver Lining
</P>
<P>
   Milan Bozic, the deputy mayor of Belgrade, says the crime rate
here is dropping. The city had an enormous problem with criminal
gangs breaking into apartments, and there was concern that
robberies would increase because of the air-raid warnings, which
cause many people to spend entire days in the shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, felonies like robbery and murder have dropped about
60 percent,'' Bozic said. ``I suppose it's always like this in a
war. There's a sense of shared danger.'' But he also conceded that
another deterrent may be the harsh justice of military courts in
wartime.
</P>
<P>
   The Invisible American
</P>
<P>
   Serbs are a mordant race, and the war has produced both symbols
and posters. Graffiti on a wall says: ``Columbus _ damn your
curiosity!'' In a reference to the downed American F-117A stealth
fighter, one placard at a music rally read, ``The only good
American is an invisible American.''
</P>
<P>
   A postcard shows the plane and says: ``Greetings from Serbia,''
with an earlier bit of poster wit: ``Sorry, we didn't know it was
invisible.'' On the back, there is this injunction: ``If
undeliverable, please return to White House, USA.''
</P>
<P>
   Her First Words
</P>
<P>
   Milan called to say hello and describe his life in the shelters,
and he was soon in tears. His 16-month old daughter, Dushanka, has
just begun to talk. ``Some of the first words she's said have been
`siren' and `bomb,''' he said, his voice cracking. ``What kind of
madness is this?''
</P>
<P>
   He knows that the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo are going through
worse trials. ``I can see them,'' he said. ``But when you're under
attack, when you're at war, your world gets very small. There's not
always room for everyone else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
