<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN'S SAFETY NET ON THE MEND IN TEXAS &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ By some accounts, there was only one true crisis facing
lawmakers when they convened in January _ mending the tattered
safety net for abused and neglected children known as Child
Protective Services.
</P>
<P>
   An emergency appropriation of $8.9 million was signed by Gov.
George W. Bush last week, enabling the embattled agency to
immediately hire 220 new caseworkers and upgrade its lagging
technology. And now lawmakers are writing a state budget for
2000-01 that infuses the agency with millions more.
</P>
<P>
   But questions persist about the adequacy of the lifesaver being
tossed to the ``forsaken children of Texas,'' as one judge called
them in a 1998 plea to Bush and the 76th Legislature. Some
children's advocates say lawmakers, while belatedly applying money
to staffing and logistical support problems, are ignoring their
call for fundamental changes in the system.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, District Judge Scott McCown of Austin said he's encouraged
that ``extremely significant'' sums of money are given to CPS in
both House and Senate budget proposals. The House plan would
authorize the 220 new caseworkers through 2001, but McCown is
rooting for the Bush-backed Senate version that assures an extra
$117 million for 380 caseworkers and an overdue computer upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The House is devoting most of its discretionary surplus money to
education. But if more-than-expected revenues materialize by May,
key House members said they would fund the 380 caseworkers,
computer upgrades, cellular phone acquisition and increased
compensation for foster care providers.
</P>
<P>
   In late April or early May, a House-Senate negotiating committee
will begin resolving differences in the two chambers' budgets. Key
lawmakers say there is a bipartisan resolve to address the CPS woes
that some blame for poor service to the public and even preventable
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Lending urgency to the situation was the recent disclosure that
in Texas last year, 176 children died as a result of abuse and
neglect, a 71 percent increase over the previous year, according to
the Texas Department of Protective and Regulatory Services that
includes CPS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked in concert with CPS and Judge McCown in addressing
the issues they raised,'' House Appropriations Committee Chairman
Rob Junell, D-San Angelo, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   His committee approved a budget that includes $1.1 billion for
child and adult protective services. The sum is based on
predictions the agency will investigate 135,218 reports of abuse or
neglect in 2000, and 143,655 incidents in 2001. The full House will
vote on the committee's recommendations on April 13.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest problems facing the agency, as verified by a
just-completed $100,000 consultant's report, is its high employee
turnover rate that workers blame on heavy caseloads and inadequate
logistical support, officials said. The agency has about 2,700
caseworkers statewide, including about 380 in Harris County.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have vacancies. Their issue isn't needing more
caseworkers as much as it is keeping the ones they've got,'' Junell
said, adding that caseworker compensation also is an unresolved
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to single out a single agency and say we're going to
raise these folks' pay,'' Junell said. Caseworkers often make less
than $30,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   James R. Hine, the agency's executive director, agreed that the
Legislature is responding adequately to the crisis alarm sounded by
McCown and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They recognize not only the need but the urgency of it,'' Hine
said.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial objective of the budget is improving quality control
over casework by placing more experienced CPS workers in
supervisory roles to monitor the decisions of rank-and-file
caseworkers, Hine said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is hoping to reduce the 7-1 ratio between
caseworkers, who usually handle dozens of cases simultaneously, and
supervisors, he said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The agency is also doing more law enforcement-related training
for caseworkers to help police develop prosecutable cases when
necessary. And in a Tarrant County pilot project, CPS is trying to
increase involvement of treatment providers _ including counselors
and therapists _ in key decisions affecting children.
</P>
<P>
   Hine said the emergency appropriation act provides the agency an
immediate ``jump-start,'' even while final budget figures are being
negotiated for the fiscal year beginning Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, some children advocates, including Houston-based Justice
for Children, maintain the efforts are ineffective patchwork and
that for at least a decade, the agency and Legislature have failed
to address lethal flaws in the CPS safety net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, Texas led the nation again with the record-highest
number of child fatalities due to abuse and neglect. Roughly 45
percent of them involved cases where CPS had a current or prior
case of abuse or neglect on that family. Every one of those
children should have been saved had they taken reasonable efforts
to protect the children,'' said founder Randy Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice for Children supports putting more people on the front
lines,'' he said, but ``far too many of their personnel resources
are being devoted to things that don't directly help to better
protect children. We're very concerned that they're throwing more
money at the problem without addressing these deeper issues. It's
going to be a waste.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL ADD END)
</P>
<P>
   Among the fundamental issues, he said, is that ``it's still a
central tenet at CPS that they place the preservation of the family
over the protection of the child.'' A former prosecutor, Burton
contends that approach _ and a reluctance of police to take a
stronger lead in investigations _ continually endangers children.
</P>
<P>
   While this may not be the year for any radical changes in CPS
functions, no overnight cures are in sight anyway, officials said.
The agency ``has been deteriorating over 15 years,'' McCown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one biennium ... nobody should think that what we're doing
is going to create an ideal world for children,'' the judge said.
``But what is being proposed is extremely significant. It's not a
matter of the glass being half full or half empty. They're putting
some real water in the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
