</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER CLEAR SKIES, NATO SHARPLY INCREASES BOMBING MISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: 2nd take expected to move within 30 minutes.) 
 (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-BASES, KOSOVO-ECON) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO directed its most ferocious air strikes yet on
Yugoslav armored forces operating in Kosovo, and struck Belgrade
and the country's two other largest cities Monday night in an
intensified attack made possible by two consecutive nights of clear
weather, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On the 13th day of the assault, American and NATO warplanes took
full advantage of the second night without the rain and clouds that
had inhibited NATO's earlier strikes, the officials said. The
allies sharply increased the number of bombing missions over
Yugoslavia because of the break. By mid-afternoon in Brussels
Monday, NATO officials said their warplanes had attacked 27 targets
just overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Pentagon and NATO refused to specify their targets,
explosions rocked Nis and Novi Sad, the two largest cities after
the capital, Belgrade. Yugoslavia's official television broadcast
scenes of a huge fireball in Novi Sad. The city's mayor said a
power station at an oil refinery had been struck. And officials
said another bridge over the Danube River had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   With pressure building on the allies to take action that might
stem the Serb offensive against ethnic Albanians, the allies also
described what would be the first known allied raid against Serb
forces engaged in a specific drive to expel the Albanians from a
village in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at the White House Monday with Defense Secretary
William Cohen, President Clinton promised a relentless bombing
campaign Monday and said the United States was committed ``for the
long haul'' to stopping what he said was Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's purge of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be clear,'' Clinton said in brief comments to a handful
of reporters at the White House. ``The ethnic cleansing of Kosovo
cannot stand as a permanent event.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Our plan is to persist until we prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of refugees continued to stream out of Kosovo
into Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro, creating a humanitarian
crisis not matched in Europe for half a century. NATO spokesman
Jamie Shea said that since February 1998, Milosevic had displaced
at least 831,000 of the 2 million people who lived in the Serbian
province.
</P>
<P>
   Even as it conducted its military operation, NATO began an
almost equally difficult humanitarian operation to feed and give
temporary shelter for many of the thousands of refugees. The first
five plane loads left Macedonia for Turkey Monday morning, carrying
800 refugees. Several NATO nations, including the United States,
have agreed to take in about 110,000 refugees, providing them homes
until they can return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But officials in Albania, where 240,000 refugees have fled, said
that despite that nation's extreme poverty, they did not want other
countries to take in the refugees because sending them away would
only further Milosevic's goal of ridding the region of them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides said that his remarks Monday _ some of his
sharpest words yet _ were meant to warn Milosevic that a return of
the refugees was now a precondition of any end to NATO's assault on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``More empty promises and token half-measures won't do the
job,'' Clinton said, appearing at the White House with his national
security advisers. ``If Mr. Milosevic does not do what is
necessary, NATO will continue an air campaign. It will be
undiminished, unceasing and unrelenting. It will inflict such
damage that either he will change his calculation or we will
seriously diminish his capacity to maintain his grip and impose his
control on Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence assessments compiled here in Washington indicate
that Milosevic's forces might well be nearing the end of their
campaign to expel ethnic Albanians from their homes. Some officials
have speculated that Milosevic, armed with that advantage on the
ground, might then offer to end the fighting and return to the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that Clinton's comments Monday
were intended in part to pre-empt any gestures that Milosevic might
make that would not meet the conditions of the failed peace talks
in France, except for the return of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be a surprise to see in the coming days attempts
at half measures, hollow cease-fires,'' Joe Lockhart, the
president's spokesman, said. ``They will not be acceptable to stop
the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks Monday, Clinton restated the goals of the
mission, saying that for the bombing to stop, Milosevic would have
to withdraw his police units from Kosovo, agree to an autonomous,
multi-ethnic Kosovo, accept the deployment of an international
security force and take steps toward a political settlement to help
the refugees return home.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair echoed that resolve Monday.
``We will drive them back to Kosovo,'' he said of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The administration says that the refugee crisis was precipitated
by Milosevic, who has stepped up his repression of ethnic Albanians
in response to NATO's attack, which began on the night of March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's strikes destroyed the fourth bridge of the Danube, this
one near Sombar. The bridge is near Yugoslavia's northern border
with Hungary and far from the fighting in Kosovo. However,
officials have justified destroying bridges, saying they help
resupply Yugoslavia's military and police forces.
</P>
<P>
   In raids overnight on Sunday, NATO and American warplanes
destroyed four separate bridges near Kosovo, including one over the
Ibar River at Raska, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also targeted a fuel depot near Sombar and sites at a coal
mining center in Aleksinca, southeast of Belgrade, according to
Yugoslavia's official television. Kursumlija, an industrial town
near Kosovo, was struck Monday night, as was the military
headquarters at Nis, the television reported.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the targets reported by the Yugoslavs were
industrial sites in major cities, NATO officials said they were now
turning their attention to destroying the ground forces waging war
in Kosovo. In the first days of the campaign, some strikes had
destroyed staging areas, barracks and fuel and ammunition depots
directly supporting the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just starting to hit them,'' NATO's military spokesman,
Air Commander David Wilby of Britain, said Monday, before the
latest strikes began. ``The weather as you know, has only just
cleared, to give us a little more chance of hitting them hard.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
