<HEADER>
A6987 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-GOVERNOR-COX     04-05 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GOVERNOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN GOVERNOR IMPLICATED IN DRUG TRAFFICKING OUT OF OFFICE
AND SIGHT
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY Rumor has it he may have roared off into the
Caribbean in a speedboat _ or may even be dead.
</P>
<P>
   The only sure thing is that Mario Villanueva, ex-governor of
Mexico's Quintana Roo state, failed to show up Monday evening at
the inauguration of his successor in the state capital Chetumal.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva's conspicuous absence at the inauguration fueled
speculation that the tough-talking politician had outwitted Mexican
justice and fled the country before he could be indicted on drug
trafficking charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he did leave the country, he did so because he thought his
defense would be easier to conduct in a foreign country than here
in Mexico,'' Raul Cardenas, Villanueva's lawyer, told a radio
station Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas claims not to know his client's whereabouts either.
</P>
<P>
   The new governor of Quintana Roo, Joaquin Hendricks Diaz, gave a
speech at his swearing-in, pledging that organized crime and drug
traffickers would be ``frustrated'' by his state's efforts to foil
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva, who, like Hendricks, belongs to Mexico's ruling
Revolutionary Institutional Party (PRI), is not wanted on
trafficking charges _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   He has not been indicted, but until Monday he was the
highest-ranking Mexican politician to be investigated so closely on
corruption allegations while still in office.
</P>
<P>
   While he was governor, Villanueva enjoyed a measure of
constitutional protection against being arrested. Now he has none.
</P>
<P>
   A defiant Villanueva, who says he's innocent, was interrogated
once by authorities but vanished last week after failing to show up
for questioning three more times.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva could face charges he laundered drug money and aided
some of Mexico's biggest cocaine traffickers _ allegations that
have embarrassed the PRI, which is struggling to overcome a
reputation as corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   United States law enforcement authorities say that Quintana Roo,
home of Mexico's famed Cancun resort city, became a ``narco-state''
rife with corruption during Villanueva's six-year term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican and U.S. authorities reportedly are investigating bank
accounts belonging to Villanueva in Switzerland, the United States
and the Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mexico's La Jornada newspaper, protected witnesses
told investigators that Villanueva co-owns an agricultural business
in Panama with the vice-president of Panama and co-owns a ranch in
Belize with a politician in that country.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is rampant that Villanueva may have fled to Panama,
perhaps with a judicial police commander from Quintana Roo.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican newspaper cartoonists are having a field day with
Villanueva's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   A cartoon in La Jornada has Villanueva whispering into a
telephone from a palm-studded beach: ``Quick, I need something to
help me escape . . .,''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many grams?'' someone on the other end of the line asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I mean something to escape justice,'' Villanueva responds.
</P>
<P>
   If Villanueva is indicted, his arrest could be a coup for
Mexican justice and could please U.S. authorities who are critical
of Mexico's record in the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But if Mexico's attorney general presents a persuasive case that
Villanueva is guilty _ but has fled _ the case will be chalked up
as another failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible they do know where he is and can't arrest him
yet because they don't have a warrant,'' said Jorge Chabat, an
analyst with Mexico's Center for Investigation and Economic
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think he's in another country now, and I think it will
take one, maybe two years to extradite him and get him back,''
Chabat told Cox Newspapers. ``That's my bet.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
