<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-PRIVACY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT JOINS CONSUMER GROUP IN EFFORT TO ADVANCE ON-LINE
PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a step that could advance the cause of on-line
privacy, Microsoft and an influential consumer advocacy group
Tuesday plan to propose a universal standard for Web site operators
to disclose how they use personal information gathered about
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also plans to launch a free product that companies can
use to easily post privacy policies on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Some web sites already post privacy policies, but the policies
envisioned by Microsoft and the Electronic Freedom Foundation would
be readable by computers, allowing consumers to automatically avoid
sites whose owners plan to sell their names or addresses, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   The company and consumer advocates envision that in the
not-too-distant future consumers will be able to use Internet
browsers and search engines to avoid those Web sites that do not
meet the consumer's own standards for privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a privacy solution that is good for e-commerce,
because it builds trust and confidence, and it is good for civil
liberties, because it gives individuals control,'' said Tara
Lemmey, president of the Electronic Frontier Foundation, an
organization advocating for on-line privacy. The group has in the
past been critical of Microsoft but is supporting the current
effort. ``This is a first step that has to be taken, but it is a
big one.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation and Microsoft plan to ask the body that oversees
Internet standards, the World Wide Web Consortium, to approve new
guidelines that simplify a mechanism for Web sites to post privacy
policies. The privacy policies would not only be readable by
consumers, but would contain coding so that browsers and search
engines could easily analyze a company's plans for the use of
personal information, such as a consumer's buying habits or credit
card number.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's ``Privacy Wizard,'' developed with the non-profit
privacy group TRUSTe, is supposed to help small businesses with few
resources comply with the new privacy standards. The product leads
business owners through a short questionnaire and then turns the
answers into a privacy policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to create an easy and simple way for the average
web site owner to create a privacy policy, by asking, `What kind of
information do you collect?' and `What kind of uses do you put it
to?''' said Saul Klein, group program manager of Web Platform
Services at Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being very cautious to talk about this as something that
lays a foundation. It's not going to change the nature of privacy
on the Internet overnight, but it is an important catalyst.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein warned that if the software industry can not come up with
ways to improve privacy, there will be increasing pressure for
government regulation. He pointed to Europe, where the European
Union already is taking a tougher line on privacy than the U.S.
government, which has favored industry self-regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said Microsoft's own web pages already have privacy
policies, but they will have to be upgraded if the new standard is
approved, and Microsoft will also eventually have to make a browser
that recognizes the privacy policies.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts briefed by Microsoft said the step is significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of steps that have to happen for the Web to
really succeed, and one is that the privacy issue has to be
addressed,'' said Kate Delhagen, director of the on-line retail
research group at Forrester Research Inc. ``As consumers realize
how much information is being passed back and forth, they will want
to regain control of that information.''
</P>
<P>
   Delhagen said Tuesday's proposal will make it easier for
companies to post privacy policies, but that companies will then
face the challenge of honoring their own policies.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Lavin, research director at International Venture
Associates, also praised Tuesday's step. He said the privacy
movement got a jumpstart last week when IBM announced that it will
only advertise on Web sites that post a clear privacy policy
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this stuff is accepted, it could rush forward pretty fast,
so that you can eventually pop into Yahoo and say, `Find me the
sites that won't sell my name','' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin said the development is also a wise public relations move
for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives Microsoft the imprimatur of the Electronic Frontier
Foundation, which is important because they have a lot of
credibility and they've never exactly been in the Microsoft camp,''
Lavin said. ``And it certainly doesn't hurt Microsoft to have tight
privacy controls, because selling names is something they've never
done and they don't particularly need to buy any.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
