<SLUG> BC-BOEING-DELIVERIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING ON TRACK FOR RECORD AIRPLANE DELIVERIES BY END OF YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. delivered 148 commercial airplanes
during the first three months of 1999, which industry analysts said
Monday represented a good start toward the company's goal of a
record 620 deliveries by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see nothing in those numbers to suggest Boeing can't do 620
for the year,'' said Peter Jacobs of Seattle's Ragen MacKenzie.
``This was in the ballpark of what I had expected them to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another analyst, Paul Nisbet of JSA Research, said he was
expecting Boeing to deliver only 139 commercial jets in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured Boeing would get of to a slow start since they
pretty much delivered everything on the tarmac at the end of last
year,'' said Nisbet, who raised his first-quarter earnings forecast
for Boeing from 40 cents a share to 47 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing delivered a record 559 commercial planes in 1998, but in
doing so had to push 191 planes out its factory doors in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jacobs, Nisbet thinks Boeing is well on its way to meeting
its 1999 delivery goal of 620 jets.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Boeing's stock was up .375, a share yesterday,
closing at 34 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   The real measure of whether Boeing has turned things around in
its troubled Commercial Airplanes business will come at the end of
the month when the company posts first-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Boeing made zero profit on the 559 planes it
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the smallest profit on these planes (delivered in the
first quarter of 1999) will be better than last year,'' Jacobs
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether they delivered 140, 150, or 160 planes, it all comes
back to how they are doing on profit margins.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Boeing's highest priorities is reducing the costs of
building airplanes and restoring commercial profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives have acknowledged that for too long the
company went after market share at the expense of profits in the
heated battle with European airplane maker Airbus Industrie.
Executives have vowed that will change and they will make a
reasonable return on the planes Boeing sells.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing factories have not been very efficient. And becoming
more efficient will take time.
</P>
<P>
   The company has already warned analysts that commercial margins
will only slightly improve this year, to between 2 and 3 percent.
While that's better than 1998, it is well below the profits the
world's biggest airplane maker once enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts will be looking closely at how well Boeing's commercial
margins for the first quarter compare with the 1.9 percent
commercial margins the company posted for the fourth quarter of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   That will indicate whether Boeing's performance is continuing to
improve, Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is below 1.9 percent, then I would start to ask
questions. Are they really fixing anything? But if the margins are
better, that would bode well for the continuation of improvements
in the commercial group that started in 1998,'' Jacobs said
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's commercial production is expected to peak during the
first half of 1999 and will begin to fall off. The company has said
it expects to deliver only 490 planes in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter deliveries this year included 14 classic 737s; 61
next generation 737s; 14 747s; 17 757s; 11 767s; 23 777s, two
MD-80s, five MD-90s and one MD-11.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it delivered 24 military aircraft the
first three months of 1999, including two C-17s Air Force
transports, nine F-15 fighters, six F-18 Hornets; two F-18 Super
Hornets; two 767 AWACS surveillance planes and two T-45TS jet
trainers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
