u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DEPLOY-NYT &LR;      04-05 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DEPLOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SEEKS TO JUGGLE MILITARY RESOURCES ON SEVERAL FRONTS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-BASES,
KOSOVO-ECON) 
(sw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just a few weeks ago, senior American officials
described U.S. fighter jet patrols over northern Iraq as critically
important. But when the air war over Kosovo began, those flights
were suspended in order to send combat and support planes to
southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has reassigned the Kitty Hawk, the only aircraft
carrier stationed in northern Asia, to the Persian Gulf to replace
the Theodore Roosevelt, now headed to the Adriatic Sea to help the
Kosovo operation. As a result, the Air Force is putting its combat
jets on alert in the Korean theater, where tensions have been high
since North Korea launched a missile over Japan last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Supplies of cruise missiles are dwindling, and the Air Force is
scrambling to send enough fuel tankers to support both the Iraq and
Kosovo campaigns, according to Air Force officials.
</P>
<P>
   These are among the more striking examples of how the U.S.
military has had to juggle resources as it manages missions on two
fronts: the increasingly complicated military and humanitarian
operations in the Balkans and the low-level air war over Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   And they are just two smaller ``contingency'' missions which,
under current Pentagon policy, the armed forces should be capable
of handling while still remaining fully prepared to conduct two
major wars. In a four-year defense review completed in 1997, the
United States affirmed that it was ready to fight on two major
fronts, most likely in the Middle East and north Asia, as well as
to carry out ``multiple concurrent'' contingency missions on a
smaller scale _ like those now under way in Kosovo and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But as the air war over Yugoslavia continues with no end in
sight, military analysts are questioning whether this two-war
strategy is realistic. Some argue that the Defense Department has
put too great an emphasis on buying billion-dollar weapon systems
for major wars while failing to prepare sufficiently for the
dangerous missions that the military is actually conducting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does suggest there isn't enough money for these kind of
missions,'' said Michael O'Hanlon of the Brookings Institution.
``Airplanes are being used so much, but we haven't been buying
enough spare parts, for example. As a result, the tactical fighter
fleet is at its lowest readiness level in this decade.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department is feeling the strain of the Kosovo
mission, which has already cost hundreds of millions of dollars,
according to outside experts.
</P>
<P>
   The pinch is likely to be felt first in northern Asia, where the
departure of the Kitty Hawk, with all of the Navy's combat fighters
in that theater, has compelled the Air Force to put its combat
fighters on alert, meaning longer hours for the pilots and their
crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working 12 hours on and 12 hours off 7 days a week
here,'' said Cmdr. Tom Van Leunen, at U.S. European Command
headquarters in Stuttgart, Germany. ``We've asked for extra people
to work with us, because if we don't, we'll get ourselves in the
position where people are too tired to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the Kosovo campaign, Rudy DeLeon, undersecretary
of defense for personnel and readiness, said the U.S. military was
more than ready to fight the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guidance is to deal with a number of contingency
missions,'' DeLeon said then in an interview. ``This kind of
operation is what the military have trained for _ they're using
their professional skills. One of the big challenges is to force
them to take some down time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the war heated up in Kosovo, the United States had to
scale back its mission in Iraq, which the national security
adviser, Sandy Berger, had said was critical to keep Iraq's leader,
Saddam Hussein, in check and prevent him from waging an offensive
war.
</P>
<P>
   The European Command moved 10 F-15 jets and 3 EA-6B prowler
electronic warfare aircraft from Incirlik Air Base in Turkey to
bases in Italy and immediately suspended the air patrols over
northern Iraq, according to a military official who spoke on
condition of anonymity. The United States and its allies have
continued patrols over southern Iraq, but at a slower pace, using
aircraft based in Saudi Arabia and aboard an American aircraft
carrier in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to juggling the northern Iraq mission, the Bosnia
peacekeeping mission and now the Kosovo air campaign, the European
Command will also be in charge of the military support for the
humanitarian mission under way to help refugees fleeing Kosovo into
Albania and Macedonia. More than 380,000 refugees have been
registered in those countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard enough with two contingency missions at the same
time out of European Command,'' said Van Leunen. ``Now we have the
humanitarian mission, and these operations are very
humanpower-intensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Airplanes are being flown at least two or three times more often
than in peacetime, according to Pentagon and Defense analyst
estimates, and that places greater stress on the equipment, leads
to more breakdowns, and requires more spare parts and more fuel.
The Defense Department has already had to acquire extra jet fuel to
replenish supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Mobility Command at Scott Air Force Base, Ill. which
supplies all the air tankers for U.S. missions around the world,
has sent 53 tankers to Kosovo while keeping the Iraqi mission
supplied. The pace has been nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a busy, hectic time,'' said Lt. Col. Chuck Wynne at
Scott. ``There's more strain because of Kosovo _ on the crews that
fly this aircraft and on their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Some military analysts argue that American pilots are getting
good training, rather than being overworked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have lost a pilot by now if they all hadn't had
experience in the real world,'' said William Arkin, author of ``The
U.S. Military On Line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they are overstretched, but it's a prudent use of
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   The most serious shortage is in supplies of air-based cruise
missiles after the first week of the war. U.S. B-52 bombers have
dropped roughly 50 such missiles, reducing the Air Force stock by
one-third, and it is unlikely that they can be replaced before the
war is over, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
