<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISM OVER THE INTERNET'S GROWTH LEADS SHARES HIGHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market's torrid affair with technology and
Internet companies continued Monday, lifting the three main gauges
of stock market performance to records.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rallied in their first day of trading since the release
on Friday of mixed employment data for March. The news touched off
a strong rally in the bond market on Friday in an abbreviated
session. Stock exchanges were closed in observance of Good Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The employment report makes it increasingly unlikely that the
Federal Reserve will feel the need to raise short-term interest
rates in the near future, which is a positive for stocks. Still,
traders said that they were not expecting Monday's surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were kind of quiet at the end of last week, and the
positive tone during the morning was quite surprising,'' said
Andrew M. Brooks, a vice president at T. Rowe Price Associates.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, the biggest gains were concentrated
among the largest and best-known leaders of a select group of
industries, from IBM and Microsoft to Intel, Lucent and America
Online. Several financial-services stocks also soared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strong are getting stronger, and cash is going in to those
stocks that have done well recently,'' Brooks said. ``At some
point, the music is going to stop, but no one knows when that is
going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index and the Nasdaq composite index had all set
records. Trading volume on the New York Stock Exchange was light,
with just fewer than 700 million shares changing hands. On the
Nasdaq, 977.8 million shares were traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are good, but there is no volume,'' said one stock
trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``What trading there
is is all in technology, Internet issues and some financial
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which closed above 10,000 for the first time last week,
did so again Monday. The gauge rose 174.82 points, or 1.8 percent,
to 10,007.33. The S&AMP;P 500 gained 27.40, or 2.1 percent, to
1,321.12. The S&AMP;P 500 gained 27.40, or 2.1 percent, to 1,321.12.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose to a record for the first time
in two months. Bolstered by gains in stocks like Microsoft, 2\.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose to a record for the first time
in two months. Bolstered by gains in stocks like Microsoft, 2\, to
94 15/16; Intel, 6|, to 127{; Yahoo, 39], to 94 15/16; Intel, 6|,
to 127{; Yahoo, 39], to 219[, and Amazon.com, 15{, to 186{, the
index soared 66.69, to 219[, and Amazon.com, 15{, to 186{, the
index soared 66.69, or 2.7 percent, to 2,560.06.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, developments in the war in Yugoslavia were
seen as inconsequential for stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, people think the economy will continue to expand at
a 4 percent rate and that inflation is dead,'' said Byron R. Wien,
U.S. equity strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``The market
is resistant to bad news, and Kosovo is a good example of that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Dow was led higher by IBM and American Express, which
together accounted for nearly 40 percent of the rise in the gauge.
</P>
<P>
   IBM climbed 6 15/16, to 183 15/16. And American Express rose 4
7/16, to 125 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Other Dow components did nearly as well.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric gained 3, to 114|. And Hewlett-Packard, the
other computer company in the Dow, rose 3 9/16, to 71 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   America Online led the S&AMP;P 500 higher and was again the most
actively traded stock on the Big Board. It jumped 16 15/16, to 166
15/16. The gain propelled the company to ninth in terms of its
weighting in the S&AMP;P 500, ahead of companies like AT&AMP;T and Lucent
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, whose previously announced 2-for-1 stock split became
effective Monday, had a big day. It rose 3 1/16, to 58 15/16.
Meanwhile, AT&AMP;T's stock fell 1 1/16, to 77 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Online brokerage stocks soared after an analyst at Credit Suisse
First Boston said online trading rose 30 to 35 percent in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab, the biggest online broker, gained 9[, to 103].
Ameritrade Holding, the sixth-biggest online broker, soared 29
1/16, to 91|. And Equitable's Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, which
owns a widely used Internet brokerage service, gained 4 5/16, to
71}.
</P>
<P>
   But the session also had some big losers.
</P>
<P>
   Aspen Technology saw its stock fall 3 5/16, to 9 15/16, after
the software manufacturer said it expected to report a significant
operating loss for the quarter ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   And shares of Aspect Development fell nearly two-thirds, losing
14 15/32, to 7 15/16, after the software maker said it expected
first-quarter revenue and earnings to be well below analysts'
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The breadth of the market's advance improved a bit Monday, a
development some analysts said was encouraging. On the New York
Stock Exchange, 1,695 stocks rose, while 1,318 fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last week, breadth has improved a bit, but this is a
very selective market, and it has been for over a year,'' said Al
Goldman, chief market strategist at A.G. Edwards Inc. in St. Louis.
``The bears just can't adjust to the kind of market we have right
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
