<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIVX-MARKETPLACE-ART-     04-05 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVX-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: HIGH PRICE OF NEW VIDEO TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With consumers spending freely, Circuit City Stores Inc. looks
poised to cash in on a rebound in sales of televisions, cordless
telephones and other electronics, not to mention the growing
interest in all things digital.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a chink in Circuit City's armor: its gamble on
Divx, a technology that allows consumers to pay a small fee for
video movies that do not have to be returned. Each disk costs about
$4.50 and can be viewed for two days _ or longer with additional
payments. Circuit City is selling both the disks and Divx disk
players, which cost about $350.
</P>
<P>
   Though the company does not yet break out its Divx sales, the
product line has been a big drag on earnings so far. For the
quarter ended in February, Circuit City, which is based in
Richmond, Va., is expected to report Tuesday that it earned 85
cents a share, reduced a third by losses of about 31 cents from its
Divx unit, Digital Video Express, and about 9 cents from Carmax, a
subsidiary that resells used cars.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts and shareholders clearly wish the company would
just throw in the towel on Divx. Its stock would probably rise,
said David Strasser, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, and
investors would say ``good riddance.''
</P>
<P>
   Digital video disks provide better picture and sound than
conventional videocassettes, but consumers have not yet moved in
mass to the digital products. Even if they embrace the new
technology, they must choose between two competing formats: plain
DVDs that can simply be bought or rented and watched repeatedly,
and the Divx format that requires them to register their players
and hook up to a telephone line. Furthermore, many movie studios,
video-rental stores and electronics manufacturers have been
unwilling to move to Divx.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit City is actively seeking another investor in Digital
Video Express and better distribution for the products. Speculation
that it will soon line up a big video rental company to distribute
the disks has driven Circuit City's stock price up recently. The
stock has gained more than 50 percent this year, on the heels of a
40 percent rise in 1998. It now looks expensive, trading at more
than 50 times estimated earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit City initially invested $30 million in the Divx
technology after a presentation in 1995 by a Los Angeles
entertainment law firm, Ziffren, Brittenham, Branca &AMP; Fischer,
which still owns a third of Digital Video Express. Since then,
Circuit City's total investment has risen to about $200 million,
more than half of which is in the form of incentives promised to
studios that offer movies in the format.
</P>
<P>
   By most standards, the Divx investment is a small one for
Circuit City, which is the nation's second-largest
consumer-electronics retailer, with $8 billion in sales in the year
ended February 1998, trailing only Best Buy Co. Even if Circuit
City wrote off its entire Divx stake, it would amount to no more
than $100 million, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Divx gambles makes it harder for investors to place a
value on the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Divx just adds confusion to the Circuit City story,'' said
Brian Berghuis, manager of the $3.5 billion T. Rowe Price Mid-Cap
Growth Fund, a longtime shareholder who says he has recently been
adding to his stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Divx has been growing, but the losses are fairly
substantial,'' he said. ``If people could focus on the core
business, Circuit City could get a much higher multiple.''
</P>
<P>
   At its closing price of $75.25 Monday, Circuit City trades at 20
to 21 times its earnings in its core consumer-electronics business,
but at 50 times its total expected earnings for 1999. Best Buy,
meanwhile, trades at about 39 times 1999 earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Circuit's share price could climb to 30 times earnings,
Berghuis said, or $90 to $93.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury is out on Divx's prospects. It is competing with
other formats, including basic digital video-disk players,
pay-per-view cable TV and the roughly 91 million videocassette
recorders already in homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Divx technology, which was introduced nationally in
September, is sold in about 720 stores, including chains like Good
Guys and Ultimate Electronics as well as Circuit City, and disks
are also sold over the Internet. In February, Circuit City said 1
million Divx disks had been sold. But some analysts estimate that
as many as half of those were given as bonuses to buyers of Divx
machines.
</P>
<P>
   So far about 800,000 digital video-disk players, including Divx
machines, have been shipped to retailers, according to the Consumer
Electronics Manufacturers Association. Circuit City says it has
sold about 90,000 Divx players, which will play regular disks as
well as those with the Divx technology.
</P>
<P>
   Several big electronics manufacturers, Sony, Royal Philips
Electronics and Toshiba, make DVD players without the Divx
technology. In addition, Sony's film studio and Time Warner Inc.'s
Warner Brothers have said they will not release videos in the Divx
format. And while more than 400 Divx titles are available, there is
a lack of animated movies for children, typically a top
video-rental segment.
</P>
<P>
   A commitment from retailers would help. Viacom Inc.'s
Blockbuster unit, with more than 4,000 stores, and Tandy Corp.,
which has 7,000 Radio Shack stores, have been cited as possible
partners that could provide cash to the Divx subsidiary and that
could begin to carry Divx titles. All three companies declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster, while an early detractor of Divx, might go along to
beat Tandy to the punch, some analysts speculate. But Circuit City
probably has some persuading to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many retailers do not want to line the coffers of their
archrival,'' Marjorie Costello, editor and publisher of Consumer
Electronics Online News, an industry newsletter. With Divx,
consumers would no longer have to worry about video-rental late
fees _ a key source of revenue for rental stores. ``Dealers view it
as a threat to their business.''
</P>
<P>
   And for most consumers, Divx remains a mystery. ``I don't think
most consumers have a desire to have Divx,'' Ms. Costello said.
``It has to be sold to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers balk, she said, at having a telephone line hooked
up to their Divx player and at supplying a credit-card number,
which is used to bill customers who view a Divx disk again after
the initial two-day period.
</P>
<P>
   Berghuis of T. Rowe Price expects Circuit City to cut Divx loose
if things don't shape up soon. ``Either it will be making good
profits by sometime in 2000, or they'll sell it or joint-venture it
to get it off the income statement,'' he said. ``It's clearly a
wild card. I'm not betting on it at all, but it could surprise
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
