<HEADLINE>
BEIJING PROMPTS AIRLINE TO DIVERT DISSIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A prominent exiled dissident who tried to return to
China was diverted Monday by the airline he was traveling on after
it received a warning from the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   The plan by the dissident, Wang Xizhe, to test the Chinese
government was thwarted when Beijing warned the South Korean
airline he took from New York, Asiana Airlines, that it would be
held responsible for Wang.
</P>
<P>
   At a scheduled stopover in Seoul en route to Beijing the airline
put Wang, over his protest, on a flight to Bangkok, according to a
human rights group in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   After writing an anti-government petition in 1974, Wang spent 14
years in prison. Then in 1996, fearing arrest again, he went to the
United States. He remains a Chinese citizen, but has no passport,
only a refugee travel document issued by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Wang was a close ally of two democracy advocates who remain
inside China, Xu Wenli and Qin Yongming. Last fall, these two
received prison sentences of 13 and 12 years for their part in
organizing an illegal political party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
