<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES ARE LITTLE CHANGED AS ECONOMY SHOWS STRENGTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities were little changed to slightly
lower Monday, as a rise in stocks removed some demand from the debt
market. Trading was light.
</P>
<P>
   There was minimal reaction to a report by the National
Association of Purchasing Management that its index of
nonmanufacturing business rose to 62.5 in March _ the highest since
May _ from a reading of 57.0 in February.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Ablin, president of Colonial Asset Management Inc. in
Jacksonville, Fla., said, ``Last week's NAPM report on
manufacturing activity was so strong that it overshadowed today's
report.''
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year bond slipped to 5.58 percent, from 5.59
percent on Friday, while its price, which moves in the opposite
direction, increased 4/32 to 95 5/32.
</P>
<P>
   Ablin said he thought the Fed policy makers were not likely to
be swayed by Monday's report, ``especially if they have yet to be
prompted into action by the 30 percent rise in oil seen over the
last few weeks.'' Monday, crude oil futures marched higher after
the United Nations said that one of Iraq's main pipelines, which
carries oil south to the Persian Gulf port of Mina al-Bakr, had
slowed to about 45 percent of its normal rate after weekend bomb
damage. Iraq blamed Britain and the United States, but the United
States denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   As the American economy continued to show signs of strength and
little deceleration, bond yields have climbed more than a half
percentage point in the first quarter of this year, as investors,
fearing inflation lies ahead, have demanded a greater discount in
price.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Englund, chief economist for Standard &AMP; Poor's MMS, a
market research and analysis firm in San Francisco, said the market
got the employment report it was looking for last week, although
there was limited room on Friday for Treasuries to rally because of
the holiday-shortened session. This week he expects a bullish bias
to trading, based on the employment data, a flight to Treasury
securities because of the events in Kosovo, the unwinding of
Japanese fiscal year-end effects and the attractive level of yields
available.
</P>
<P>
   But corporate debt sales in the coming weeks could limit gains
in Treasury securities, since corporation give investors a higher
yielding alternative to government securities, and firms arranging
these debt sales often sell Treasuries first as hedges against
losses in case rates rise before the sales are completed. Some of
well known corporate names include Conoco Inc.; Korea Development
Bank; Delphi Automotive Systems Corp., which is a General Motors
spinoff, and Union Pacific Resources Group.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the regular weekly Treasury bill auction was somewhat
mediocre. The three-month bills were awarded with a rate of 4.265
percent, a little better than expected, and the six-month maturity
came in at 4.345 percent. The number of bids for the six-month
issue was considered weak, with a ratio of 4.03 to 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
