<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-TRADING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-QUARTER ONLINE TRADING SOARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors executed more stock trades on-line than ever in the
first three months of the year, as the volume of trading via
personal computers rocketed 30 to 35 percent, according to an
influential analyst's report issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a study that surprised industry observers and confirmed the
worst fears of traditional brokerages, Bill Burnham of CS First
Boston said on-line brokers processed a record 440,000 to 460,000
transactions daily in the quarter, up from 340,000 in the fourth
quarter of 1998, and double the June 1998 figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big, big number,'' said Bill Lauderback, a spokesman
for the Houston-based Electronic Traders Association. ``It's so
big, it's almost scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The increase was even higher than Burnham's earlier prediction
of 25 percent growth for the first quarter. And it was ``all the
more remarkable'' because it came while growth in all stock market
trades, including those made through traditional brokers, rose just
4.9 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The new figures for on-line trading vividly illustrate the
sudden popularity of Internet investing, the report said, and
``indicate that the on-line trading industry continues to take
market share'' from traditional brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is booming, the market is booming and the Internet
is booming,'' said Lauderback. ``While that lasts, the trend is
going to last.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 7.5 million Americans now use discount brokerages on
line to buy and sell stock, according to industry estimates. About
one in every seven trades, or nearly 14 percent, is executed
on-line rather than through traditional brokers. Drawn by low
commissions, free stock quotes and a wealth of research available
over the Internet, on-line investors have swarmed into the market
since 1997, when just in 14 trades, or 7 percent, were performed on
line.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the recent growth, however, may be related to the manic
rise in Internet stocks themselves, some analysts say. A CS First
Boston report issued earlier in the year concluded that the
``on-line trading industry is a case of Internet users (often
working at Internet firms) using Internet brokerages to trade
Internet stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The on-line brokerages themselves have been among the main
beneficiaries of the surge in computer trading. Indeed, shares in
the most popular on-line brokerages, like ETrade, Ameritrade and
Charles Schwab Corp., have risen at fantastic rates.
</P>
<P>
   Even the smallest on-line discount brokers are thriving. Earlier
this year, shares of New York-based Siebert Financial tripled in
four days, turning founder Muriel Siebert into a paper billionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, shares of on-line brokerage firms soared to record
levels after Burham's report was released. Ameritrade Holding Corp.
rose 29 1/16, or 47 percent, to 91 5/8. ETrade Group Inc. gained 11
3/4, or 19 percent, to 72 5/8. Charles Schwab Corp., the biggest
on-line broker, rose 9 1/8, or 10 percent, to 103 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   The spectre of a vast and growing army of individual investors
hustling into the market with little more than a click of the mouse
has alarmed securities regulators and lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying stock over the Internet is not like buying a can of
peas,'' said William F. Galvin, Massachusetts Secretary of the
State, whose office regulates securities trading in the state. ``If
you don't know what you're doing, you're not going to get your
money back. Not everybody is suited for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Galvin's office has received an increasing number of complaints
from investors who say they lost money trading on-line. ``For
experienced investors, it's probably a good thing. But it isn't for
the first-timne investor,'' Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that novice investors will strike out on their own _
without the advice of brokers bound by industry regulations to
limit investors to appropriate levels of risk _ four members of
Congress have asked the US Securities and Exchange Commission to do
more to protect the rights of on-line investors.
</P>
<P>
   In response to ``a recent surge of customer complaints,'' the
New York Attorney General's office said in February it planned to
launch an inquiry into on-line brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, traditional brokerage houses like Merrill Lynch and
Goldman Sachs said they will launch on-line services to compete
with the upstart on-line brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the wave of the future,'' said the Electronic tradig
Association's Lauderback. ``We're headed toward the day when
there's going to be trading 24 hours a day world wide. And a lot of
it's going to be done over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he warned, the current trend won't last forever. ``As soon
as the economy turns, and it eventually will, you'll see a mass
exodus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
