<HEADER>
A7002 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-GERALD-LADN     04-05 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GERALD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN MAKES IMPRESSION WITH SUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM INGHRAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Take a look around the Phoenix Suns' locker room
before a game or the autograph line after one and it's easy to spot
the big names, the superstars.
</P>
<P>
   Few can pick out Gerald Brown, the former Pepperdine standout.
He prepares for games quietly and alone, while reporters hover
around Jason Kidd and Tom Gugliotta. Afterward, it's the same
routine.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, Brown doesn't mind. That's his nature. Quiet,
unassuming. He speaks in a near whisper, almost embarrassed to be
receiving attention for playing basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Gerald,'' said his mother Wendelene. ``He doesn't
bother anybody and he goes with the flow.''
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of five brothers, Brown has never been the outspoken
type. He was a team leader for the Waves as their shooting guard
from 1993-98, but even then he preferred letting his play do the
talking _ not his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any problems with Gerald,'' Wendelene said,
``except chores. He hated doing the dishes. I had to keep him home
from a game once (during the Arizona state basketball playoffs with
Carl Hayden High in 1993), because he didn't get his stuff done.
The coach understood, but other than that Gerald was a perfect
gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown made sure he finished business at home after that. He also
led the Falcons to a state title in the 5A division, the state's
largest, in 1993. He was the Arizona Republic's 5A Player of the
Year in 1993, earning him a full scholarship to Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   He averaged 17.1 points and shot 80 percent from the free-throw
line in his final three years in Malibu. He was an All-West Coast
Conference selection in each of those seasons. Impressive enough,
but it didn't earn him one of the NBA's coveted 58 draft selections
last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt if Gerald got an opportunity, someone would be glad
they gave him a chance,'' said Lorenzo Romar, Brown's coach at
Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   Brown himself didn't expect a chance. So, instead of giving up
on his dream of playing pro basketball, he went to work. Brown
played in the L.A. Summer Pro League and the NIKE Desert Classic in
Arizona. He averaged 19.7 points, seven assists and five rebounds
in the Summer Pro League and eight points and more than four
rebounds at the Desert Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling that I would at least get invited to a camp,''
Brown said. ``And if I did, I would show them how serious I was
about making myself better. All I really wanted was just a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's lockout postponed any moves teams could make. The wait
for a phone call was agonizing. Finally, in late January, Brown
received a call from the Suns _ his hometown team. He went to the
team's abbreviated training camp and signed a contract on Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exciting,'' Brown said, ``having the opportunity to
play in front of my parents, family and friends for a team I grew
up watching.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brown knew the real work was just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a rookie and trying to fit in,'' he said. ``Just
being on an NBA roster isn't enough for me. I want to be here for
more than a year.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be enough for almost anyone else, playing with and
guarding some of the world's elite athletes, but Brown constantly
works on his game. An hour before tipoff, when most players are
relaxing, one can find Brown sweating with some of the reserves and
coaches: setting picks, playing defense, taking jump shot after
jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be satisfied with where you are,'' Brown said. ``The
guys in the NBA are the best players in the world and you always
have to be prepared. When you're a rookie, you have to do even
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Romar: ``Gerald is the type of player you have to really
watch to appreciate how good he is. He's not going to be doing all
those high-flying dunks, but he is mentally tough. You can't rattle
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers tried in a recent game. Brown stole a rebound from
Dennis Rodman and was heading for an easy layup before being fouled
hard by Rick Fox. It knocked Brown to the court, and Rodman met him
as he rose. The two exchanged words and a push. Rodman received a
technical. Brown went to the free-throw line and coolly sank both
his free throws. It pulled the Suns within five points and changed
the complexion of a game Phoenix eventually won.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big play,'' Suns coach Danny Ainge said afterward.
``Gerald showed great poise.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, typical of his style, was just happy his team earned a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that big a deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It did, however, make an impression on his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gerald showed he won't be pushed around,'' said Kidd. ``He
hung in there.'' &QL; 
Never nervous
</P>
<P>
   The first time Gerald Brown ran onto the court at America West
Arena he admitted to some major-league jitters, which calmed once
the game started.
</P>
<P>
   They resurfaced, though, when Ainge pointed and told him to
check in.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted to do was make sure I didn't make a fool of
myself,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Said fellow rookie Toby Bailey: ``It was probably the same for
him as it was for me in L.A. He didn't look nervous, but Gerald
never does.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, born in Los Angeles, lived in the Jordan Downs apartments
in Watts until 1985, when the family decided to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area was getting worse and worse,'' Wendelene said. ``It
wasn't very safe, and when they are shooting people near your
doorstep, it's time to get out. Even with all that, Gerald never
got in trouble. He didn't get in fights and he watched out for his
younger brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown took to his new hometown, even switching his allegiance
from the Lakers to the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what is so weird,'' Brown said. ``Playing for a team I
used to always watch. . . . I feel fortunate to be playing for the
Suns.'' &QL; 
Getting more time
</P>
<P>
   Brown saw limited action at first and missed about two weeks in
late February with chondromalacia (a roughening of the cartilage
under the kneecap) in his left knee. He's seen more significant
action recently. He averages 8.1 minutes and 2.8 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   He scored a career-high 10 points in Portland on Friday in 11
minutes. At 6-foot-4 and a sturdy 210 pounds, he can match up with
big guards. With his deft ballhandling and superb decision-making,
he can also fill in at the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try and improve myself every game,'' Brown said. ``You have
to be willing to do whatever it takes. Those few minutes you go in,
you have to play well and not hurt the team. I'm feeling a little
more comfortable, but I have a lot to learn and I hope that if I
keep working hard, I'll get to be around to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
