<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0504 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7007 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWENGL-POLLUTE-BOS &LR;      04-05 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWENGL-POLLUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER PLANT POLLUTION ON RISE IN NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- After years of progress in the war on smog and acid
rain, air pollution from New England power plants has jumped
significantly since 1996, as the region's electricity generators
increasingly burned cheap oil instead of the natural gas that is
gentler on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new report, the sharp increase in power plant
releases of three major pollutants _ including a 41 percent rise in
emissions of a key ingredient in acid rain _ dims hopes that a new
generation of plants that burn natural gas would quickly clear the
region's air by forcing old plants to close.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, oil-burning power plants with an average age of 25
years have been the big winners in the electricity industry, fueled
by oil prices that reached a 12-year low in late 1998. Many of
these plants, derided as ``old dirties'' by environmentalists, are
exempt from federal pollution standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any plant that has a choice of whether they burn oil or
natural gas will burn oil,'' said Cindy Lupi of Clean Water Action
in Boston, part of the environmental coalition that released the
federal pollution figures. ``The only surprise is that (the
emissions increase) is this dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Power plants and motor vehicles are the leading sources of
nitrogen oxides and sulfur dioxide, air pollutants that cause
summertime smog, which makes breathing difficult, as well as acid
rain, which can kill aquatic life.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, New England power plants made general progress
against air pollution, adding pollution controls, closing older
facilities, and burning more natural gas instead of coal and oil.
Sulfur dioxide releases from Massachusetts plants alone dropped by
60 percent from 1989 to 1995, according to the US Energy
Information Administration.
</P>
<P>
   But the results released by the Massachusetts Campaign to Clean
Up Polluting Power Plants show that sulfur dioxide releases in New
England rose 41 percent from 1996 to 1998, and nitrogen oxides
increased by 23.9 percent. Releases of carbon dioxide, believed to
cause global warming, rose by 37.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Setbacks at nuclear power plants, which release no conventional
pollutants, partly explain the increase. Long-term closures or
shutdowns of five reactors plagued the region in 1996 and 1997,
though one reactor in Connecticut reopened in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the pollution jump also reflects the slow pace with which
developers have built the many natural gas plants proposed for the
region. Despite years of talk about natural gas emerging as New
England's leading fuel, relatively few new plants are complete, and
a major new gas pipeline from Nova Scotia is still under
construction.
</P>
<P>
   With few gas plants to turn to, a handful of older oil-burning
power plants _ in Sandwich, Everett, and Salem, Mass.; Newington,
N.H.; and Freeport, Maine _ shouldered more of the energy demand,
increasing the region's air pollution in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The Canal plant in Sandwich, visible from the Bourne Bridge to
Cape Cod, illustrated the way cheap oil has blunted the rush to
natural gas even at existing plants. Former owner ComElectric shut
down one of Canal's turbines in 1996 to make it able to burn
natural gas, but since the turbine reopened it has burned oil
almost exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   ComElectric spokesman Michael Durand said that the company ``had
an obligation to the customers who bought electricity from that
plant that we produce it and sell it at the least possible price.''
He stressed that the Canal plant never exceeded state emissions
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the region's energy picture could change drastically as
increased competition comes to the power industry. Under
Massachusetts' industry-restructuring law that took effect last
year, regulators no longer guarantee a profit for power plants,
meaning a plant might close if it loses money.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups, such as the Conservation Law Foundation of
Boston, backed the law in the belief that new gas plants would
provide cheaper electricity than the ``old dirties,'' eventually
forcing many of them to close.
</P>
<P>
   So far, almost all the state's major power plants have changed
hands, but the new owners are not closing them down. Southern
Company of Atlanta, which now owns the Canal plant, wants to build
a gas plants at the site, too, but they plan to run their existing
facilities as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we believe that gas is the future,'' said Southern
spokesman Chuck Griffin, predicting that their proposed gas plant,
which could go into operation as early as 2001, would help clean up
the air by replacing power from dirtier plants.
</P>
<P>
   But Rob Sargent of the Massachusetts Public Interest Research
Group, part of the coalition that released the federal pollution
results, said the increase in pollution ``should send up some red
flags'' for anyone who is counting on deregulation of the power
industry by itself to clean up the air.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he said, deregulation has been ``an ally to cheap and
dirty power.'' In 1998, he said, older plants exempted from the
1977 Clean Air Act rules increased their output by 11 percent in
1998, the first year of deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent called on Governor Paul Cellucci to stick with a plan he
announced last fall to impose new limits on older plants, saying,
``These emission increases reinforce the need to have tight
emissions caps for the state's oldest and dirtiest plants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
