<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7008 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ATROCITIES-BOS     04-05 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ATROCITIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPY PHOTOS SHOW ETHNIC CLEANSING, US SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ US military officials said Monday they have
gathered the first clear photo images of ethnic roundups, including
pictures of Kosovar Albanians being herded onto Yugoslav roads and
marched out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the first wave of refugees was being airlifted to Turkey
and Norway, President Clinton deflected questions about the NATO
strategy, saying he did not ignore warnings that air strikes might
speed the ethnic cleansing in Kosovo. Clinton said he preferred a
critique of his military tactics over ``having you ask me why we
are permitting wholesale slaughter . . . and not lifting a
finger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible to prepare fully for the chaos that this kind
of cruelty creates,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the 13th day of NATO airstrikes, the sounds of
explosions rocked Novi Sad, the second-largest city in Serbia, and
the mayor said the power station at the oil refinery had been hit,
according to a report from the private news agency Beta. A bridge
between Kosovo and the western Yugoslav republic of Montenegro was
demolished, the Serb news agency Tanjug also reported. And five
explosions were heard in the southern Serbian town of Nis.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the bombing campaign enjoyed greater success
Monday thanks to a break in foul weather conditions, with officials
reporting successful hits on army barracks, bridges and fuel
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Increased tensions over the bombings, coupled with growing
pressure on the adminstration to detail how it ultimately hopes to
resolve the crisis in Kosovo, were felt as NATO quickened the pace
of airstrikes and fresh US military forces drew closer to the
region, defense officials said. Clinton had approved dispatching 24
Apache helicopters armed with laser-guided antitank missiles, but
it could take as long as two weeks for them to arrive in Kosovo,
and their use in battle still requires another round of approvals
from Clinton and NATO, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   With the helicopters, officials expect to be better equipped to
combat a political maneuver from Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, who is expected to propose a peace deal after having
driven out the entire ethnic Albanian population. Milosevic could
``think he's finished,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said.
``We will not be finished,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic had hinted during conversations with Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov last week that he might try such a
strategy, an administration official said. But the Yugoslav
president has not made any formal offers of peace since Primakov's
visit to Belgrade, in which Milosevic offered to withdraw Serbian
troops from Kosovo only if NATO bombing stopped at once.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic stood defiant in the face of the latest round of
bombings, repeating his accusation that NATO officials are
``aggressors'' and ``criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continued to warn the Yugoslav leader: ``A Kosovo denied
its freedom and devoid of its people is not acceptable. Our plan is
to persist until we prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   The warning came as the Pentagon announced it had obtained its
first set of clear images of ethnic Albanians under siege from Serb
troops on the ground. The images _ which appear to have been taken
by satellite, outside military analysts said _ showed Kosovars
being herded into groups and being marched in procession along
Yugoslav roads.
</P>
<P>
   The aerial shots are not detailed enough to show any atrocities
themselves, Bacon said. But coming on the heels of a report by US
war crimes ambassador David Scheffer, the photographs seem to
confirm the most gruesome of tales relayed by refugees as they left
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In his report to Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright,
Scheffer said that after numerous interviews with ethnic Albanians
who had crossed the border, he noticed a ``remarkable consistency
in the refugees' accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said, ``The large and
growing number of consistent reports by the refugees is too
significant to either ignore or understate. Kosovars are shaken
down for their cash, money and their jewelry. Those Kosovars who
resist expulsion from their homes are killed. The basic message is:
`You leave or you die.' Killings and beatings are common.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Scheffer's report, people who had been executed
were left in the streets of Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, ``with
no apparent effort to remove them.'' Refugees told tales of
paralyzed Kosovars being shot or pushed out of town in
wheelbarrows. Thousands were reportedly marched from the town of
Podujevo to the train station in Pristina, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe these reports, coupled with what we are learning
from other sources of information, clearly demonstrate that ethnic
cleansing, war crimes, crimes against humanity are occurring in
Kosovo,'' Rubin said. ``The widespread and systematic character of
the criminal conduct of Serb military, paramilitary and police
units in Kosovo points to many of the indicators of genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   The reported atrocities, combined with increased confidence
among military officials that the infrastructure of the Serb
military was in shambles, buffeted NATO's decision to turn to
high-risk helicopter missions. NATO Air Commodore David Wilby said
his pilots ``will focus our attention on fielded forces in
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will disrupt Serbian military operations on the ground,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William S. Cohen said, ``They are now open and
vulnerable to this kind of an attack. The Apaches are a very
capable aircraft that will go in low and start to target them
individually. It has a good deal of firepower and is going to
represent an enormous challenge to the forces in opposition. He's
going to be paying a high penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO estimates that some 831,000 Kosovars _ out of an original
population of 1.9 million _ are believed to have been displaced
from their homes since February 1998, when the conflict with Serbia
began. Some 400,000 of those are believed to have fled the province
after NATO airstrikes began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
said the numbers of ethnic Albanians fleeing to neighboring regions
was as follows: 35,000 to Montenegro; 120,000 to Macedonia; and
239,000 to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Another 1,000 refugees made their way Monday night to Turkey,
where officials have promisd to allow in some 20,000 in total. The
United States has pledged to take another 20,000 refugees, to be
housed in Guam or the Guantanamo Bay Naval Base in Cuba until it is
possible for them to return, Albright said earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton encouraged Americans wanting to assist in the relief
efforts to call the unwieldy 15-digit toll-free number, 1-800-USAID
RELIEF.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
