<HEADER>
A7010 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-COLLINS-LA     04-05 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-COLLINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' COLLINS GOES ALL OUT TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -- Terry Collins' managerial style isn't meant to
win friends.
</P>
<P>
   Not unless one considers an intense, aggressive, in-your-face
approach friendly.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only Collins' managerial style, it's who he is.
Collins, about to begin his third season as the Angels' skipper,
was taught at at early age that playing hard was the only way to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just my style,'' he said. ``My mother told me a story
about how when I was growing up as a little boy, one of the
neighborhood mothers called and said she didn't want me playing
with her son because I played too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins smiles when he relays that story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all I ever did. My dad taught me, if you're going to
play, play all out.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins has made that style work as a manager. In five major
league seasons (three with Houston, two in Anaheim), Collins' teams
have had a winning record every season. However, those teams have
never won a division -- he's finished in second place each time.
</P>
<P>
   But don't fault Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the years we've finished second here, we've definitely
overachieved, especially with the injuries we've had,'' Angels
right fielder Tim Salmon said. ``In Houston, every year he was
behind the Atlanta Braves. You can't blame him for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins' approach can rub players the wrong way. He wore out his
welcome in Houston, and not all the players in Anaheim like him
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough job,'' Salmon said. ``You have to manage 25 guys,
25 egos. You're not going to have 25 guys like you.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Terry is he's aggressive and intense and he
wants to get down and dirty. Play hard. If it rubs you the wrong
way, what does it matter? Just do your job. ... Does he always say
the right things? Probably not. But it's easy to throw darts at the
guy in front.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins was hired prior to the 1997 season after the Angels
conducted an exhaustive search for a new manager. It came down to
two finalists -- Sparky Anderson and Collins. The Angels liked
both, but because Collins is younger and the Angels were looking to
the future, he was the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has operated exactly as I had expected,'' Angels general
manager Bill Bavasi said. ``We interviewed a lot of managers, we
did a lot of work. Terry was no exception. We thought we had a good
handle on what we were getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``His intensity has been channeled well. He runs a game great.
He's very organized and thinks ahead. He understands and works with
the media well. He understands and works well with the front
office. He understands and appreciates not only his situation, but
other people's. And he attracts good coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organization got the right guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Collins became a coach, he was quite an athlete. At
Midland (Mich.) High School, he lettered in football, basketball
and baseball. He had various scholarship offers, but figured -- at
5-foot-8, 160 pounds -- his best bet was to play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He chose Eastern Michigan University, where he played shortstop.
He led the team in hitting in his freshman and senior seasons and
led the team in steals all four. He was inducted into EMU's Hall of
Fame in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Drafted by the Pirates in 1971, he was traded to the Dodgers in
1975, which put him on a course to the big leagues. But not as a
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to coach,'' said Collins, who has a degree in
Education. ``If there was no chance in professional baseball, I
would have coached some place. I love sports and enjoy teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins reached the triple-A level with the Dodgers, but never
got out of Albuquerque as a player. He noticed a trend in the late
1970s of triple-A player-managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `I'd like to try this,' '' Collins said.
``(Coaching) would be another way to get to the big leagues. In
triple-A in those days, they only had 21 players on a team, so they
needed somebody who could play a lot of spots, and it was me.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I started playing attention to other positions. I listened
to Wes Parker talk about playing first base. I listened to Del
Crandall, I listened to Johnny Roseboro talk about catching. Dixie
Walker was the hitting coach. I wanted to listen to not only what
they taught me, but what they taught other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins began managing in 1981 at Lodi, went to Vero Beach in
'82, San Antonio and then Albuquerque in '83. He was a
player-manager for Albuquerque in '84 and stayed as manager in
Albuquerque through the 1988 season.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' career with the Dodgers hit a road block, however. It
became apparent to Collins that then-Dodgers manager Tommy Lasorda
had no plans to bring Collins in as a major league coach, so
Collins approached Dodgers general manager Fred Claire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred and I talked about it,'' Collins said. ``I was the
triple-A manager for the Dodgers. ... Do I really want to leave the
best triple-A job in baseball? But I decided it was time to make a
change and it was the best move I ever made. Not leaving the
Dodgers so much, but because I started to meet other people. Until
then, I was always known as a `Dodger guy.' Nobody else knew
anything about me, my skills or my knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins took the job as the Pirates' triple-A coach in Buffalo,
where he stayed for three seasons before Jim Leyland made Collins a
coach with the Pirates in 1992. He got the manager job with Houston
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Collins is with a team that has the talent to win. But if
he doesn't win, don't expect Collins to run and hide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember as a kid I lost a game. I was devastated,
crushed,'' he recalled. ``I went down to my room and hid. My dad
came down and asked, `Did you try?' Yeah. `Did you try as hard as
you could?' Yeah. `Then get your (rear) upstairs. There's nothing
to cry about.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
