<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7012 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCCOY-COLUMN-COX     04-05 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCCOY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young and no love
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ And now it is as clear as an empty peroxide bottle
why Dmitri Young bleached his hair and his pointy goatee a golden
hue . . . gold hair, Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed me no love,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   The `they' in Young's sentence referred to the San Francisco
Giants, who took liberties on the basepaths against the Cincinnati
Reds new right fielder on Opening Day Monday and discovered it
isn't wise to fool with The Golden Boy.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mammoth miscalculation on the part of the Giants,
because they twice tried to take extra bases on Young and twice
looked up to see an umpire throwing up the out sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they thought I was just an infielder (former first
baseman) moved to the outfield and I couldn't throw,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Giants showed him no love, but the 55,112 in Cinergy
Field showed him adulation and adoration after his second assist of
the day. First, he threw out Rich Aurillia at home when he tried to
score from second on a shallow single. Then, Jeff Kent tried to go
from first to third on J.T. Snow's single and Young wiped him out,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd exploded and thunderous applause turned into a
standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made my day and the only thing better would have been if
we won the game,'' Young said of the standing `O' and his team's
11-8 defeat. In response, Young flung his hands into the air to
acknowledge the accolades. ``After the first assist, I felt great.
After the second one, I even said, `Whoa, now.' On the second one,
I was just going to throw the ball to second baseman Pokey Reese,
but out of my peripheral I saw (Kent) heading for third and told
myself, `No way, Love . . . and I threw it . . . pfffuuummm.'''
</P>
<P>
   And that isn't the entire story. Even though he dropped 15
pounds in the offseason, Young still isn't a commercial for
Metabolife 356. Yet, he beat out three infield hits Monday . . .
one that glanced off the pitcher's leg and two slow rollers to
third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just call me the Golden Flash,'' Young said with a broad-beam
smile. ``What makes people .300 hitters is beating out infield
hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would have thought if somebody told him before
Opening Day that he would have three infield hits and two outfield
assists, Young said, ``You're crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   What Young is doing in the outfield is the residual of hard,
hard work every day with coach Dave Collins _ hours of it every day
during spring training. And it didn't stop when spring training
ended. Young was out with Collins early Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he wants to get to the point where he can play nine
innings,'' Collins said. ``He doesn't want taken out in the seventh
for defense. What makes me so proud of him is that he works so
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   People questioned manager Jack McKeon's sanity when he decided
to switch Young from left field, where he played most of the time
last season, to right field because newly acquired Greg Vaughn is a
left fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody remembers Young's comical excursions in right field
the few times McKeon played him there last season. More than once,
Young slipped on the wet turf as the baseball skidded to the wall
and McKeon asked him if he needed a skateboard out there, or maybe
a pair of roller skates.
</P>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The credit is all Dmitri's,'' McKeon said. ``He has worked his
tail off . . . hours and hours out there. He reminds me of Tony
Gwynn and how hard he worked to make himself a Gold Glove
outfielder. And he certainly put on a display today.''
</P>
<P>
   Young isn't afraid to tell people that not only did he spend
hours making himself a better fielder, they were hard, hard hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every morning, it was work, work work . . . and I let it all
hang out, as hard as I could go,'' Young said. ``Some of my
teammates kept telling me, `Slow it down, slow down.' But I'm a man
on a mission. What you saw today is only the beginning. Get used to
it. You're gonna see a lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
