<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKERBIE-FAMILIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXTRADITION DEAL DRAWS MIXED REACTION FROM VICTIMS' FAMILIES
</HEADLINE>
   (With LOCKERBIE-LIBYA) 
(sw) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the relatives of those killed in the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103, the extradition of two Libyans suspects brought a
heated mix of reactions on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Aphrodite Tsairis of Franklin Lakes, N.J., saw the
extradition as a positive step in their crusade for justice. But
others, like Stephanie Bernstein from Bethesda, Md., considered the
extradition an insult. She worried that the deal made by the United
Nations to win the extradition would strengthen the Libyan
government and its leader, Col. Moammar Gadhafi. Many relatives
hold Gadhafi responsible for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, U.N. sanctions against Libya were
immediately suspended. And after a 90-day review by the
secretary-general, the sanctions could be removed permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Libya is victorious,'' said Ms. Bernstein, who lost her
husband in the bombing. ``This is a terrible precedent for how to
handle state-sponsored terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   The extraditions marked a turning point in the relatives'
efforts. Through quarterly meetings, monthly conference calls,
newsletters and trips around the world, the relatives have fought
tirelessly to see those responsible brought to trial. They have
also lobbied to make skies and airports safer for travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing occurred on Dec. 21, 1988, as Pan Am Flight 103 flew
over Lockerbie, Scotland. All 259 people on board the plane were
killed _ including 189 Americans _ and 11 people on the ground died
from falling wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   So much time has passed, said some relatives, that they had
begun to lose hope of ever seeing the leading suspects in court.
For them, the extraditions brought relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had come to really believe that Gadhafi was never going to
turn them over,'' said Peter Lowenstein of Morristown, N.J., who
lost a son in the bombing. ``I would have bet money on it. I think
what happened today was an important step.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Lowenstein, others who expressed support on Monday said
their reactions were more practical than heartfelt. Support in the
United Nations for maintaining the sanctions against Libya seemed
to be fading, they said, and Washington was under increasing
pressure to accept the deal or lose any chance of getting Gadhafi
to turn the suspects over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether he is put on trial is secondary to me,'' Lowenstein
said of Gadhafi. ``I think if there is evidence during the trial
that he is responsible for this bombing, then it would be his
downfall.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tsairis, whose 20-year-old daughter was killed in the
bombing, said the extraditions brought her closer to ``intellectual
closure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never have emotional closure,'' she said. ``But once
you find out the who, what, why and how of things, it helps give
some intellectual closure _ something you can put away and never
have to worry about again.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who criticized the extraditions said they were
concerned that the United Nations would lift the sanctions without
conducting a full investigation into the Libyan government's
alleged associations with terrorists. And they were concerned that
the two men charged would be given special treatment in jail and by
the court.
</P>
<P>
   They expressed these concerns to Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright in a conference call on Monday. In criticizing the
extradition agreement, the relatives called the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103 ``an act of war'' and ``the worst act of terrorism
against the United States in history.'' And they said they were
disappointed that the American government had given up on pursuing
those who ordered the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a very high price was paid for this trial because the
person who is behind it, Moammar Gadhafi, has negotiated a deal so
that he is protected no matter what happens in the trial,'' said
Susan Cohen of Cape May Court House, N.J. ``He's about to become
richer. He's about to have more weapons. And his image has been
rehabilitated by the Clinton administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cohen, whose 20-year-old daughter died in the bombing, said,
``I am going to be in pain and suffering all my life over the loss
of my daughter. And now I have to watch this. Where is the justice
for us?''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives who participated in the conference call on Monday said
Albright told them the United States could veto the U.N. resolution
to lift the sanctions against Libya, if Washington determined that
Gadhafi's government had not complied with U.N. conditions to
renounce terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   And, the relatives said, Albright assured them that if evidence
in the trial against the two suspects in custody implicated
Gadhafi, the United States would be able to pursue charges against
him under international law.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bernstein, however, said she had expected much more. The
U.S. government settled for an expedient end to the investigation,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to think that if something happens to you as you
travel in the world that your government would stick up for you,''
she said. ``Justice is not always swift. There are some principles
worth standing up for. This was one, and our government did not do
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
