<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-PITCHING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds pitching gives way to Giants bats
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ It was a day when anybody who lists their
occupation as Major League Pitcher would have been better off
spending the day on the Ohio River in a canoe, especially those
wearing the new black-trimmed Cincinnati Reds uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   For them, black was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot for which to cheer for among the 55,112 in
Cinergy Field who were Reds fans on Opening Day, but pitching
wasn't one of them during an 11-8 loss to the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Tomko, John Hudek and Gabe White were not on their best
behavior and on this day the rest of the Reds couldn't overcome the
slipshod pitching work.
</P>
<P>
   Tomko, standing in on Opening Day for Pete Harnisch, gave up
three runs in the first, then when the Reds came back to within 3-2
in the second, Tomko gave up three more in the fourth to put them
behind, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   More than three hours later, Tomko sat at his locker with his
head buried in his hands, distraught and embarrassed over the six
runs, eight hits, three walks and a hit batsman he surrendered in 3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous about Opening Day, but that wasn't it,'' Tomko
said. ``I was off. Something is not clicking right. My pitches are
not going where I want. Something is wrong and I have to iron it
out. It isn't physical. The ball is not doing what I want it to do.
I'm missing by a foot. It's embarrassing to go out and do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Dennys Reyes checked the Giants on no runs over 2
innings and the Reds scored six times in the sixth to bolt in
front, 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Hudek on this day was Hudek The Horrible. He gave up a
two-run game-tying home run to Ellis Burks in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating to let the guys down when they come back
the way they did and we have an opportunity to win,'' Hudek said.
``Burks is strong and today wasn't my day. Every pitch I made was
up in the zone. You can't throw bullpen fastballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudek started the eighth, too, but walked Rich Aurillia. White
replaced Hudek and walked pinch-hitter F.P. Santangelo. The game
went bye-bye for the Reds when Charlie Hayes crushed a home run,
turning an 8-8 tie into an 11-8 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get the ball down and pitched up,'' White said.
``Every ball was over the middle of the plate and you can't pitch
that way up here. It hurt more because of the way the club battled
and came back. I let 'em down and I'm not happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one Hayes hit a strong wind blowing in wouldn't have kept
it in the park,'' White added. ``When you make pitches over the
middle of the plate and up, you're going to get hit . . . bad
things are going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The good things were on the offensive side.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Mike Cameron carries no stigma over his defensive
abilities, but there are questions about his offense. So he hit a
two-run home run in the second, showing power.
</P>
<P>
   Then he showed flying feet during the six-run sixth. He was hit
by a pitch, stole second, took third on a wild pitch and scored the
run that tied the game, 6-6, on a grounder to third when he knocked
the ball out of catcher Brent Mayne's grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be labeled as just a defensive player,''
Cameron said. ``I want to be known for offense, too. I can hit
.280, .290, .300 and hit 20 to 30 home runs if given a chance to
play and be myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, general manager Jim Bowden leaned on the
batting cage watching Sean Casey. When somebody said they thought
Casey would win a batting championship in the next three years,
Bowden said, ``I believe that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey got a good start Monday with three hits _ a double, a
single and a two-run home run in the sixth that snapped a 6-6 tie
and gave the Reds their only lead, 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter Mark Sweeney's first appearance in a Cincinnati
uniform resulted in a three-run home run during the six-run sixth.
The Reds had only two pinch-hit home runs last year _ both late in
the season (Willie Greene on Aug. 5, Tony Tarasco on Sept. 21).
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to do my part to get us back in the game and
things almost worked out,'' Sweeney said of the inning that brought
the Reds from 6-2 behind to 8-6 in front. ``In a sense, it didn't
mean anything because we didn't get the `W.' When you get a two-run
lead like that, you gotta shut 'em down. Maybe next time I can hit
one that will end the game with a `W.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As manager Jack McKeon said, ``We saw some positives, that's for
sure. We're going to be all right scoring runs . . . we will score.
If we don't get behind 3-0 in the first, we probably win the game.
Our pitching will be better than what the fans saw. It better be.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
