<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7023 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-POWS-COX     04-05 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POW code of conduct 'a mind set' for soldiers
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the three American soldiers held captive in
Yugoslavia, the complicated world of multinational military
objectives has been reduced to a mission so simple the Army
summarizes it on wallet cards.
</P>
<P>
   The mission is to keep fighting, and the weapon is the Code of
Conduct for the United States Military.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Pentagon confirmed that authorities in Belgrade
have said they will not follow through on previous threats to hold
criminal trials against Spec. Steven Gonzales and Staff Sgts.
Christopher Stone and Andrew Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``The encouraging thing is that after a couple of days, the
Yugoslav government has announced that they will be treated as
POWs,'' said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   But becoming a prisoner of war doesn't end the obligation to
fight, and their status as captives highlights one of the most
intangible but significant aspects of America's military training
program.
</P>
<P>
   America's three captured soldiers must fight Yugoslav authority
by refusing to participate in propaganda, by answering no questions
beyond name, rank and Social Security number, and by accepting no
special favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a physical task, it's a mind set,'' said Maj. Shelly
Stellwagen in the Army's Office of Public Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting the enemy through mental resistance ``becomes a part of
you when you're a soldier,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And it's based on a code of conduct adopted after the Korean War
that lays out a straightforward obligation of military personnel:
</P>
<P>
   ``The duty of a (soldier) to continue resistance to enemy
exploitation by all means available is not lessened by the
misfortune of capture. Enemies whom U.S. forces have engaged since
1949 have regarded the POW compound as an extension of the
battlefield. The POW must be prepared for this fact.''
</P>
<P>
   The intensity of that preparation, however, varies from job to
job within the military. Pilots and others who operate deep behind
enemy lines get extensive survival training for life as a POW, but
those less likely to be captured rely almost exclusively on their
conviction to follow the Code of Conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, Stone and Ramirez fall into the latter group. They
haven't attended one of the four Survival Escape Resistance Evasion
schools run by the military branches.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they would have been instructed repeatedly in the
importance of living by the Code of Conduct no matter the
circumstances. And they, like all Army personnel, were given wallet
cards with the essence of the code summarized in 10 sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it enough? Good question,'' Stellwagen said. ``Based on the
experience of POWs in the past, it appears to be.''
</P>
<P>
   For retired Navy Capt. Mike McGrath, living by the Code of
Conduct was enough to keep him alive during six years as a POW in
North Vietnam. But he got his training through the SERE school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' said McGrath, 59, now an airline pilot. ``I
give it great credit for saving my skin.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath was shot down June 30, 1967 and although badly injured
in the crash he immediately was subjected to physical torture that
coerced him into signing a ``confession'' of war crimes. But in a
last act in defiance, and in the spirit of the Code, McGrath
misspellel iis own name in the signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got mad,'' McGrath said, ``but they didn't make me go
back and change it either.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the Code of Conduct American military personnel must
strive to live by while held captive by enemies:
</P>
<P>
   A POW must ``think escape,'' must try to escape if able to do
so, and must assist others to escape.
</P>
<P>
   The United States does not authorize any military service member
to sign or enter into any parole agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Experience has shown that, although enemy interrogation sessions
may be harsh and cruel, it is usually possible to resist, if there
is a will to resist.
</P>
<P>
   The POW may never willingly give the captor additional
information, but must resist doing so even if it involves
withstanding mental and physical duress.
</P>
<P>
   However, understand that if taken past the point of maximum
endurance by the captor, the POW must recover as quickly as
possible and resist each successive captor exploitation effort to
the utmost.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the type of detention or captivity, or harshness
of treatment, (soldiers) will maintain their military bearing. They
should make every effort to remain calm, courteous, and to project
personal dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
