<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7024 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOTTI-PLEADS-BOS &LR;      04-05 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOTTI-PLEADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DUMBFELLA' WISES UP, PLEADS GUILTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for Gotti-Trial, which is KILLED)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not ``The Godfather.'' It's not even ``The
Sopranos.'' And, Monday night, it looked like ``The Gang That
Couldn't Shoot Straight.''
</P>
<P>
   John A. ``Junior'' Gotti, alleged boss of the Gambino crime
syndicate, pleaded guilty to racketeering and other charges Monday
night _ on the eve of his trial, which was to start this morning,
and just hours after his lawyers insisted, once again, that he was
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old son of John J. Gotti, the most flamboyant Mafia
don of recent times, made the plea in exchange for a prison
sentence of six to seven years _ even after turning down a similar
deal last December. Had a jury found him guilty, he would have
faced 18 years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers said Gotti changed his pleas after learning federal
prosecutors in Brooklyn were about to indict him for tax evasion
and loan sharking, meaning he would have faced two separate trials.
The deal he struck applied to both cases.
</P>
<P>
   For those who enjoy crackling good stories about the giants of
organized crime, this surprise twist might be just as well. For the
trial of ``Junior'' Gotti would have provided yet another dribble
of proof that the Mafia has seen grander days.
</P>
<P>
   The charges told much of the tale.
</P>
<P>
   When Gotti's father _ the fierce, elusive, and elegant crime
boss, known as ``Dapper Don'' and ``Teflon Don'' _ was sent up the
river in 1992, it was for a raft of felonies, including the murder
of his predecessor, Paul Castellano.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti's son _ known to law enforcement agents as ``Junior'' and
in the New York tabloids as ``Dumbfella'' _ was charged with
shaking down an upscale strip joint, running a gambling ring,
robbing a drug dealer, and fibbing on a home-mortgage refinancing
application.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Mob does today is kids' stuff, it's like a street
gang,'' James Kallstrom, former director of the Federal Bureau of
Investigation's New York office, said in a phone interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still has a lot of bad characters,'' Kallstrom added, ``but
these are different people, different times.''
</P>
<P>
   The infamous ``five families'' that ran organized crime in New
York once had enormous power. They controlled major unions, were
major players in the concrete and construction industries, the
commercial-garbage hauling service, and the fish and produce
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You paid a certain percentage of your money to the Mob, no
matter who you were,'' Kallstrom said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Schiliro, the FBI's current New York director, said Monday
that, as recently as 1988, the elder Gotti was raking in $100,000 a
month from construction-industry shakedowns _ personally.
</P>
<P>
   Then the FBI became adept at using the anti-racketeering RICO
statutes, passed by Congress a decade earlier, which allowed agents
not only to arrest individuals but to confiscate their assets and
bust up the whole hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the heads of all the organized crime
families in New York were indicted, convicted, and locked up.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the Giuliani administration stepped in and
imposed licensing requirements on certain industries _ especially
the Fulton Fish Market and the garbage pickup business _ that the
Mafia once monopolized.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Gotti passed the titular leadership of the Gambino
family on to his son, there wasn't much left to control.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Mafia's activities today, Kallstrom said, involve
bits and pieces of the economy's dark underside: gambling,
prostitution, and narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   Schiliro said that the syndicates still have a hand in
construction, cement, and the garment trade, though much less than
in the past. Some crime families, he said, are expanding into
``nontraditional activities,'' such as penny-stock fraud,
health-care fraud, and telephone-card scams.
</P>
<P>
   While none of this is trivial, it in no way resembles the vast,
pervasive empire that the Mob bosses once oversaw.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the crime families has shrunk as well, to ``maybe
one-fifth'' their size a quarter-century ago, Kallstrom said.
``Even in the '80s,'' the former agent said, ``some families had
300 to 400 members and another 1,000 or so associates that did
their bidding. You just don't find anything like that today.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, it is only natural that, at the end of the century, one
of the top Mafia gangs has been run by the likes of John A. Gotti.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents, the past several months, have painted a pathetic
picture of ``Junior.''
</P>
<P>
   When he visits his father at the maximum-security prison in
Marion, Ill. _ or so the videotapes reportedly show _ he spends
practically the whole time sulking in his chair while the former
don yells at him.
</P>
<P>
   The legitimate business ventures he has started have all
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The other crime-family bosses are said to dislike him.
</P>
<P>
   He had to call on his sister, Victoria, the author of
best-selling romance novels, to bail him out of jail last
September.
</P>
<P>
   The bail terms were so stiff _ including house arrest and
$24,000 a month to pay for private security guards to watch over
him _ that, last week, he asked the judge to put him back in
prison, on the grounds that he couldn't make the payments. (Monday,
before pleading guilty, he changed his mind, telling the judge he
would somehow manage, after all.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in stylistic terms, he appears the polar opposite of
his father _ overweight, poorly dressed, and driving a minivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the mobsters today,'' Kallstrom said. ``They're not
Carlo Gambino. They don't have the discipline, the organization,
the code of silence. I'm not saying we respected the old dons _ we
despised them _ but they were different from these young guys
today.''
</P>
<P>
   When his case first came up, ``Junior'' Gotti was going to be
one of 22 defendants _ but in the months since the number dwindled
to two. The others pleaded guilty, chose to cooperate with the
prosecutors, or had charges dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Gotti, too, was about to cop a plea, in exchange
for a reduced sentence. But his sister, mother, and father all
talked him out of it, telling him the federal prosecutors had a
weak case against him.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday night, he had pleaded innocent to all charges and
denied accusations he had any involvement with organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, however, Gotti admitted in court in White Plains
that he had ``conspired with a group of individuals forming an
association'' _ the requisite legal language of a mob confession.
</P>
<P>
   The trial would have featured at least one vestige of the
old-style Mafia _ a cast of ex-mobsters with colorful names,
testifying against the defendant, among them, John ``Jackie Nose''
D'Amico, Dominic ``Fat Dom'' Borghese, and Willie Marshall, who
once referred to himself as a ``two-bit leg-breaker.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
