<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREASTFEEDING-WALMART     04-05 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREASTFEEDING-WALMART-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Breastfeeding lawsuit takes aim at Wal-Mart
 &HT;    By Rob Modic
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dana Derungs says she wants a little ``justice''
for herself and her 2-year-old son, Devin, from the nation's
biggest retailer, Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Derungs said Monday that an apology and a company-wide
``breast-feeding, friendly policy'' are in order for the
interference, ``humiliation,'' and ``harassment'' she said she
suffered from a female Wal-Mart employee two years ago when she
tried to breast-feed her newborn at a store in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Derungs' attorneys also said the lawsuit they filed last week
could cost the company some money, if it loses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice is dispensed in terms of money and the question is,
How much is it going to cost Wal-Mart?'' attorney Susan Brasier
said. The lawsuit does not seek a specific amount of damages.
</P>
<P>
   Derungs, of Lebanon, said she was beginning to breast-feed her
young son in the store when a female employee told her to move into
the restroom. Derungs said she refused and left the store. She said
she has never been stopped at other places, including shopping
malls and retail businesses. He said she has not tried to
breast-feed her child at a Wal-Mart since the April 7, 1997,
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Derungs later picketed the store with about 80 others and she
filed a complaint with the Ohio Civil Rights Commission. Her
attorneys said a settlement was never reached.
</P>
<P>
   Derungs said she wanted a breast-feeding-friendly policy adopted
at all Wal-Mart stores.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Brown, speaking for the Bentonville, Ark., retailer,
said Monday, ``We do allow mothers to breast-feed at our stores. We
train our associates on this.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Derungs's attorneys, Brasier of Dayton and Robert Stein
of Cleveland, said they believe Wal-Mart has a policy against
breast-feeding in its stores. Besides Derungs, they represent
Jennifer Gore, of New Lebanon, who has said she received similar
treatment at a Wal-Mart store in Trotwood in November 1997. Gore,
who recently gave birth to her fourth child, a girl, did not attend
a press conference at Brasier's law office Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Brown declined comment on the incidents involving Derungs and
Gore because of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Stein said Wal-Mart stores with in-store food courts or snack
bars fall within Ohio's ban on discrimination in places of ``public
accommodation.'' The law covers discrimination against
breast-feeding mothers, Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Derungs' supporters, Linda J. Smith, a certified local
lactation consultant, noted that businesses in Montgomery County
can obtain window stickers that say: ``Breastfeeding Welcome Here''
from the WIC (Women Infants and Children) program at the Combined
Health District of Montgomery County. Georgette Hall, breast
feeding coordinator at WIC, has a list of 29 establishments that
have requested stickers.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Modic writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
