<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHIQUITA-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      04-05 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIQUITA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER REPORTER NAMES SOURCE IN ENQUIRER-CHIQUITA CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ A closely watched case involving crime and the
ethics of journalism took an unusual turn Monday when a former
investigative reporter disclosed in court the identity of one of
his confidential sources for a stinging collection of articles last
year about Chiquita Brands International Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The former reporter, Mike Gallagher, 42, testified at a pretrial
hearing that protecting a confidential source was ``one of the
highest responsibilities a journalist has.'' He then proceeded to
say that George Ventura, a former lawyer for Chiquita, had been a
crucial source for his articles about the huge banana company.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura was indicted last fall on 10 counts of helping Gallagher
obtain illegal access to the voice-mail system at Chiquita. In a
bargain with prosecutors, Gallagher pleaded guilty to two counts of
stealing voice-mail messages and, court papers show, testified
against Ventura before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's trial is to start later this month, and the hearing
Monday dealt with an effort by his lawyers to suppress tapes and
other evidence provided by Gallagher.
</P>
<P>
   Among other legal issues, defense lawyers are trying to bolster
Ventura's case by invoking Ohio's ``shield law,'' which is intended
to protect reporters from having to reveal their sources. Ventura's
lawyers maintain that the law is aimed at benefiting not just
journalists but also the public that they serve. Independent
experts, however, say they can find no court precedent in which
shield statutes have been successfully invoked to protect a source
rather than a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony provided new details and the latest twist in
developments that drew the attention of many here and in journalism
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Those events were rooted in an 18-page special section that The
Cincinnati Enquirer, the city's dominant newspaper, published on
May 3 challenging the business practices of Chiquita, one of
Cincinnati's most influential corporations. Many of the
accusations, much of them alleging unfair labor practices in the
company's Central American operations, were backed up by quotations
from internal voice-mail messages between lawyers and executives at
Chiquita.
</P>
<P>
   But less than two months later, The Enquirer, owned by Gannett
Co., published a front-page apology, agreed to pay Chiquita more
than $10 million and fired Gallagher, its star investigative
reporter. The apology said the newspaper's assertion that the
voice-mail messages had been provided by a high-ranking Chiquita
official was false and that Gallagher had misled his editors.
</P>
<P>
   A special county prosecutor was appointed to investigate, and by
September Gallagher had agreed to provide prosecutors the names of
his sources and tape recordings of conversations with them, and to
testify at any resulting trial. In exchange, he was allowed to
plead guilty to lesser charges.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, on Sept. 16, Ventura, who had worked as a Chiquita
lawyer in Ecuador and Honduras from 1991 to 1996, was indicted on
charges that he had provided Enquirer reporters the access codes to
the voice mail of two Chiquita lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher's decision to identify his sources struck a raw nerve
among some journalists. Steve Weinberg, an investigative reporter
and former executive director of Investigative Reporters and
Editors, a journalism organization, said in an affidavit filed by
Ventura's lawyers that the disclosing of sources threatened the
ability of journalists to do their job.
</P>
<P>
   ``If investigative journalists violate those contracts and word
gets around, journalists everywhere are harmed,'' Weinberg said.
``In the end, so is the larger citizenry that depends on
investigative journalists to publicize wrongdoing within the public
and private sectors of society.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tom Goldstein, dean of the Columbia University Graduate
School of Journalism, said the Enquirer situation was so unusual
that Gallagher's actions might not serve as a precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disclosing a source is certainly an extraordinary breach, but
this fact situation is so convoluted and so odd that there may be
no precedential value,'' Goldstein said in an interview.
``Gallagher had been hung out to dry by his employers and found
himself in an untenable situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning Monday by Marc Mezibov, Ventura's lead lawyer,
Gallagher said he routinely tape-recorded conversations with his
sources without their knowledge or consent. (Such taping is legal
in Ohio and some other states so long as one party to the call
consents.) He testified that he destroyed as many as 30 tapes of
conversations with confidential sources the day before the articles
were published, in order to protect the sources' identity in case
Chiquita sued the newspaper. Six to eight of those destroyed tapes,
he said, were of his conversations with Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   But court records and the testimony show that when he was fired
and faced indictment, Gallagher turned over names, notes and
remaining tapes to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Breyer, who is prosecuting the case, said outside the
courtroom Monday that Ventura had come to the attention of
investigators before Gallagher agreed to cooperate. Ventura's
lawyers are nonetheless fighting to exclude the information
provided against their client by the former reporter.
</P>
<P>
   In another detail, Gallagher testified that he informed his
editors at The Enquirer in October 1997 that he had gained access
to Chiquita's voice-mail system. Lawyers for the paper told him, he
testified, that this was a potential misdemeanor under federal law,
but he continued to invade the voice-mail system without the
knowledge of his editors.
</P>
<P>
   The other reporter on the Chiquita series, Cameron McWhirter,
testified that the newspaper's editors had been adamant that
Gallagher never again gain access to the voice-mail system and that
he not use any of the material obtained in the later articles.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently to conceal his actions from the editors, Gallagher
maintained that he had been given copies of the voice messages by a
senior Chiquita executive with authority over the voice-mail
system. Chiquita officials said no one had that authority.
</P>
<P>
   McWhirter said he had never gained access to the voice-mail
system, and he has not been charged with any wrongdoing. In the
corridor outside the courtroom during a break, he spoke angrily of
his former colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gallagher sold out everybody,'' said McWhirter, who now works
for another Gannett paper, The Detroit News. ``He sold out his
colleagues at The Enquirer. He sold out his sources. And worst of
all, he sold out the truth of those stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher, who has not spoken with McWhirter since last summer,
was sitting around the corner in the hallway. He said that he could
not discuss his motivations. ``My lawyer's calling the shots now,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He will be sentenced after Ventura's trial and faces up to two
and a half years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
