<SLUG> BC-SIXFLAGS-DETECTORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Six Flags installs metal detectors at entrances
 &HT;    By Kelly Simmons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A TLANTA _ Parents take heart: The only heat your kids should
encounter this season at Six Flags Over Georgia will be from the
summer sun.
</P>
<P>
   New this year to the south Cobb County, Ga. theme park are 18
walk-through metal detectors, similar to those at major airports.
The security devices aren't a response to any trouble at the park,
Six Flags officials say, but rather a precaution for the security
of visitors _ including the thousands who will stream through the
park gates during this week of spring break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something some of our other parks have rolled out over
the last few years,'' said Terrie Ward, public relations manager
for Six Flags Over Georgia, one of several Six Flags theme parks
nationwide. ``It will ensure that things are not coming into the
park that might cause damage to our guests.''
</P>
<P>
   Six Flags parks in Dallas and Los Angeles also have metal
detectors installed at their gates, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Guns, sharp items like knives or scissors, and chains that could
be used as weapons are confiscated at the gate and held for guests
until they're ready to leave the park, said Josh Rainwater, a Six
Flags security officer.
</P>
<P>
   Even police officers have to give up their weapons while they're
in the park. Since Six Flags opened for weekends in March, security
officers have collected knives and chains from visitors, including
a gun carried in by a Georgia Bureau of Investigation officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much for everybody,'' said Rainwater, who points
out that even park security officers don't carry guns.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials are quick to defend the safety of the
nations's top parks, like Six Flags, and credit them for taking
advantage of the heightened security measures available.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are availing themselves of the latest technology,'' said
Joel Cliff, a spokesman for the International Association of
Amusement Parks and Attractions in Alexandria, Va. ``You can never
be too sure.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Ward said no one at Six Flags has objected to the new
policy _ least of all parents bringing their children to the park
for a day of fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' said Collins resident Delores Williams,
who was visiting the park Monday with her husband Ronnie and son
Garron, ``just because of all the things you hear on the news.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Simmons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
