<HEADER>
A7034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ASSESS-606&AMP;ADD-     04-05 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ASSESS-606&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: JAPAN'S ECONOMY UNDERGOES A REVOLUTION _ BY DEGREES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Since March, a number of Japanese companies have
unveiled extensive overhauls, job cutbacks and internal
realignments previously considered taboo in corporate Japan.
</P>
<P>
   On April 1 alone, four major Japanese companies _ Marubeni,
Sogo, Taisei and Hitachi _ pledged to reform their business
practices, following similar announcements earlier this year by
Sony, NEC and Toshiba.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, investors would have regarded the string of
announcements as a bad April Fool's joke. Everyone regarded
Japanese promises to restructure balance sheets and streamline
operations as little more than lip service to gain a few more
months of goodwill until the economy picked up and sales growth
erased obvious problems.
</P>
<P>
   Restructuring implied job cuts, whether outright, through
attrition or by eliminating excess capacity, and job cuts were
socially and politically unpalatable. Therefore, Japanese companies
did not ``risutora,'' or restructure.
</P>
<P>
   Last week alone, however, more than 25,000 jobs were slated for
elimination at big corporations, and companies promised to
reconsider their investments in money-losing businesses and pare
their notoriously bloated management hierarchies.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been plenty of grumbling from analysts and
investors that many plans fall short of a revolution, they are at
least considered a step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   The government's quarterly poll of business confidence showed a
slight improvement in the first three months of this year, and the
stock market has marched ahead, largely on the enthusiasm of
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are signs of political will,'' said Scott Hartz, global
head of management consulting services at PricewaterhouseCoopers
Management Consulting Services. ``I feel more encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited the government's extensive fiscal stimulus packages and
the profitability crisis at corporations as reasons for enthusiasm.
``I think these things do sow the seeds of change,'' Hartz said.
``The big organizations we deal with are talking far more about
Western issues like return on equity that we just didn't hear much
about a number of years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true. When Mitsubishi Electric Corp., widely regarded as
one of Japan's more conservative concerns, announced plans last
week to improve its profitability by paring away jobs and
unprofitable businesses, it said the aim was to push its return on
equity above 10 percent in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Matsui, chief strategist at Goldman Sachs (Japan) Ltd.,
considers many of the new plans genuine, compared with a similar
but short-lived spate of restructuring that began in 1993. She
estimates that average return on equity could improve as much as 7
percent from the current 1.4 percent based on the reforms companies
have announced so far.
</P>
<P>
   But the benchmark Nikkei stock index has already soared past
16,000 yen, the level at which stocks would be fairly priced in
anticipation of such a return, according to Ms. Matsui's research.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is that the gap between perception and reality is
getting too wide too fast,'' said Tadashi Nakamae, a prominent
economist. ``That means another kind of mini-bubble is being
created in the stock market _ and we all know what happens to
bubbles in the Japanese stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   Nakamae and others, including some government officials, believe
that the government is getting in the way of corporate reform,
working to stimulate demand to support sales growth that will paper
over problems like excess labor and capacity rather than force
companies to address them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The government is doing everything it can to encourage its wary
citizens and businesses to spend. It has launched more large-scale
public works programs, issued shopping coupons, cut taxes and
increased its loan guarantee program.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan has lowered short-term interest rates
effectively to zero percent, which allows overextended corporate
borrowers to maintain that condition rather than take steps to
radically overhaul their balance sheets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is trying to stop these restructuring programs
from being too aggressive,'' said Craig Chudler, the equity
strategist at Nikko Salomon Smith Barney in Tokyo. ``These credit
guarantees, the bank bailout, they're all an effort to get
companies to survive rather than having them fail and making way
for new types of business.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others argue that the government is simply unprepared for
the social costs from unemployment and bankruptcies that would
accompany a major overhaul of the corporate sector.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the job cuts that have caught the eyes of investors are,
at a closer glance, often merely promises to restrict employment
and encourage early retirement. Only a handful of companies in
extreme distress have announced plans to close factories or
production lines.
</P>
<P>
   Chudler said his analysis suggested that despite all the
cost-cutting that has been announced, costs as a percent of sales
would rise again this year _ having already posted an all-time high
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are nonetheless buying into the promises.
</P>
<P>
   Take Mitsubishi Electric's pledge to eliminate 14,500 jobs in
three years, which has helped push its stock price up more than 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the cuts will be achieved by the time-honored
Japanese practice of shifting workers to the company's affiliates
and universities _ in other words, by passing the problem on.
``They're concentrating the profit in the part of the company
that's visible and shoving the problems into the part that's not,''
said Scott Foster, who follows the company for ING Barings in
Tokyo. ``There's nothing wrong with that, but it's not what they're
painting it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the company noted that it would evaluate its
consistently unprofitable businesses for the next fiscal year with
an eye toward spinning them off, closing them or otherwise getting
out of them. ``You'd think they'd already know which businesses
have problems,'' Foster said. ``This is just more playing for
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also identified several ``core'' businesses that
analysts would prefer to see it exit, like home electronics and
automotive electronics. It remains committed to cell phones, for
example, after having sold a cell phone manufacturing plant in the
United States to Selectron, from which it now buys cell phone
units. ``That suggests that Selectron is the lower cost
manufacturer,'' Foster said. ``If they've been forced out of the
cell phone business in the U.S., the business should be considered
a candidate for some kind of divestiture, but it doesn't appear
they're thinking that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Electric is only one recent example of the type of
restructuring that Chudler compares to a Noh play, a rigidly
stylized, traditional form of Japanese drama. ``In Noh,'' he said,
``it can take an actor 35 minutes just to get from one side of the
stage to the other, and that's what I think of when I hear about
many of these plans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
