u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-DRUG-NYT &LR;      04-05 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-TUMOR AGENT MAY ALSO GAIN ROLE AGAINST HEART DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Endostatin, a compound that has been in the news for its
promising ability to cut off the blood supply to tumors in animals,
has now been shown to reduce the buildup of plaque, the fatty
deposits that clog the heart's blood vessels. The finding could
open new approaches to treating coronary artery disease.
</P>
<P>
   Plaque is a layer of cells, interspersed with cholesterol
deposits, that accumulates underneath the inner lining of arteries.
When the plaque gets thick enough, a network of fine blood vessels
known as capillaries sprouts up to feed the cells oxygen and
nutrients. Large arteries have their own blood supply system, from
which the plaque-feeding capillaries arise.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Karen S. Moulton and colleagues at Children's Hospital in
Boston and other institutions have now shown that in a strain of
mice prone to develop plaque-laden arteries, the usual rate of
plaque growth is sharply reduced both by endostatin and by another
substance, TNP-470, which also inhibits the growth of capillaries.
</P>
<P>
   The finding, published in Monday's issue of the journal
Circulation, establishes that growth of plaque in mice can be
limited by restricting its blood supply, and raises interesting
possibilities for treating heart disease in people. But the
implications are far from straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   Capillary growth is only one of several factors involved in
plaque accumulation. And any treatment that made a target of the
plaque-nourishing capillaries would have to avoid inhibiting
another kind of blood vessel: the new collateral vessels that the
body tries to build in order to allow blood flow to get around
coronary blockages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hallmark of a seminal publication is that it raises more
questions than it answers,'' Dr. Jeffrey M. Isner said of Dr.
Moulton's work, writing in an editorial in Circulation. Isner, at
St. Elizabeth's Medical Center in Boston, and other researchers
have recently had promising results in treating coronary artery
disease by spurring the growth of collaterals. He introduces the
gene that makes an agent known as VEGF, for vascular endothelial
growth factor, which has the opposite effect of endostatin's.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Moulton said the two diametrically opposed treatments might
in practice prove reconcilable by being useful at different stages
of heart disease. Capillary-inhibiting substances might help retard
or prevent plaque buildup early in the course of the disease, she
said. Collaterals tend to appear at an advanced stage of heart
disease, when a coronary artery is more than 90 percent obstructed,
and that would be the time to use vessel-enhancing substances like
VEGF.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'll have to learn a lot to find out how these two
somewhat paradoxical treatments can be applied to the same
disease,'' Dr. Moulton said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Moulton works in the laboratory of Dr. Judah Folkman, who
has pioneered the exploration of capillary-inhibiting substances
like endostatin for treating tumors. Folkman said Dr. Moulton's
work provided some reassurance that if in the future endostatin or
its relatives should be approved for treating cancer, patients
could receive the drug without making worse any heart disease they
might have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
