<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GOVERNOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO HUNTS FOR GOVERNOR IN DRUG CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHETUMAL, Mexico _ Mario Villanueva Madrid, the governor of the
state of Quintana Roo who disappeared last month after authorities
announced that he was the target of a drug investigation, failed to
appear Monday at a swearing-in ceremony for his successor. It was
the final day of Villanueva's six-year term.
</P>
<P>
   His absence shattered protocol and decades of Mexican political
tradition and strengthened speculation that Villanueva may have
decided to flee underground to avoid possible arrest, since his
constitutional immunity from criminal prosecution ended Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexican authorities did not immediately issue an arrest
order, and they made no attempt to clarify the status of the
criminal investigation they have been attempting to assemble
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they dished up a series of indignities for Villanueva
on Monday, signaling that he will be treated as a pariah now that
he has left office.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, federal authorities said they intended to audit
Villanueva's books. Here in Chetumal, the new governor, Joaquin
Hendricks Diaz, who is also from President Ernesto Zedillo's
Institutional Revolutionary Party, said he intended to conduct his
own separate audits. He also criticized Villanueva obliquely in his
inaugural speech in a baseball stadium here before hundreds of top
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its important for all authorities to obey the law,'' Hendricks
said. ``And let it be clear that the efforts of the narcotics
trafficking organizations to establish themselves in Quintana Roo
will be frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the party president said the party will not defend
Villanueva if he has committed crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any case in modern Mexican history in which an
outgoing governor has failed to appear at his successor's
inauguration because he is fleeing the law,'' said Jorge Chabat, a
political scientist. ``Governors have never faced this kind of
investigative scrutiny before. Clearly some rules of the political
system are changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican and U.S. officials have repeatedly accused Villanueva of
protecting the drug traffickers who have turned Quintana Roo, the
sun-washed Caribbean state that includes Cancun, into a major
cocaine transshipment center. But he has not been charged with any
crime, and he is not a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, however, Villanueva has ignored several
citations to appear before federal anti-drug prosecutors, and his
associates have said he feared legal and political persecution
after he left office.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to pursue an investigation of Villanueva, which
would focus on accusations of common graft rather than narcotics
corruption, suggests that Jorge Madrazo Cuellar, Mexico's attorney
general, may have been unable to assemble an airtight drug case.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Andrade, Villanueva's spokesman until Monday, said in an
interview that Villanueva's wife, Isabel Tenorio, and his two
children, ``are leading a normal life here.'' But he said he has
not seen Villanueva since March 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mario is going to surprise us all,'' Andrade said. ``I know
him well. He doesn't flee from his problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
