<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DOUBLEDAY SILENT ON SALE OF METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Nelson Doubleday, the Mets' co-owner, was smiling. The
Mets had not yet fallen behind the Marlins, 3-0, in the first
inning of what would be a sad 6-2 loss in Monday's season opener,
and when he was asked to assess his team's future, he gushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the chemistry is great,'' he said. ``Lots of charisma.
Lots of power.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested that the Mets will need another dependable
starting pitcher if they are to draw the wild card in the National
League playoffs, Abner Doubleday's great nephew nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how Jason Isringhausen works out down there,'' he
said, referring to the young right-hander down on the Norfolk farm
in the International League. ``He could be that pitcher for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Doubleday was asked about what was happening in
Cablevision's reported attempt to purchase the Mets for $500
million from him and the co-owner Fred Wilpon, he silently shook
his head.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how that story had developed, Doubleday said, ``No idea.''
And when asked what would happen eventually, he said, ``I don't
negotiate in the newspapers.'' Then he walked away.
</P>
<P>
   That's Doubleday double talk. He apparently is negotiating
somewhere with someone, presumably Charles F. Dolan, the
Cablevision impresario. As the season progresses, it remains to be
seen how long the Mets, with all that ``chemistry'' and
``charisma,'' will remain the Mets as owned by Doubleday and Wilpon
for nearly two decades with only 1986 World Series rings to show
for it.
</P>
<P>
   It also remains to be seen if Doubleday and Wilpon invested $155
million in signing catcher Mike Piazza, the left-hander Al Leiter
and third baseman Robin Ventura during the off season to drive the
franchise's price tag up to $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's opener, Piazza, Leiter and Ventura weren't worth
anywhere near that $155 million against a Marlins team not much
different than that which won only 54 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   But in the right-hander Alex Fernandez, who missed the entire
1998 season following rotator-cuff surgery, the Marlins had the
better starting pitcher and in baseball, that is usually all that
counts. Leiter, considered the Mets' ace after his 17-6 record last
season, never recovered from that first inning when the Marlins put
together three runs with mostly fluky singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're down, 3-0, you scramble, you scratch,'' Leiter
said later. ``The feeling was, you can't give up any more runs. But
when the season starts, people don't want to hear about pitches.
Bottom line is, we lost and I didn't do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   During the pre-game introductions, Leiter, who started Game 7 of
the 1997 World Series that the Marlins won, and Bobby Bonilla, then
the Marlins' third baseman, were saluted with standing ovations
from the 38,983 at Pro Player Stadium who remembered the Marlins
team that was dismantled by the former owner H. Wayne Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Marlins were getting the hits, we weren't,'' said Bobby
Valentine, the Mets' manager. ``That'll turn.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets, it must turn quickly, starting tonight, if the
Mets are to take advantage of what appears to be a relatively soft
schedule in their first 13 games _ two more here, four in Montreal,
three more against the Marlins beginning with Monday's home opener
at Shea, then three more at Shea against the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the teams on the schedule,'' Valentine said. ``I
never insult the other teams, that we're supposed to beat 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   In opposing the two teams that finished last and next to last in
the NL East last season, the Mets couldn't have asked for a better
schedule at the start of the season, although last season they were
a frustrating 11-13 against the Expos and the Marlins. But for the
Mets, their start has recently been an omen.
</P>
<P>
   With an 11-6 start last season, the Mets soon settled into
second place in the NL East before finishing one game behind both
the Cubs and the Giants for the wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   But in both 1997 and 1996, the Mets staggered to a 4-10 start
before finishing third and fourth, respectively. In 1995, they had
a 6-11 start. Those numbers won't be acceptable this season,
especially against the Marlins and the Expos. And especially after
investing $155 million in Piazza, Leiter and Ventura. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
