<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0531 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7042 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      04-05 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Deal-Making in the Digital World Occurring at Lightning Speed
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Samuel Osborn is a 21-year-old college dropout.
</P>
<P>
   He's also a former stockbroker and currently is chief executive
of an Internet subsidiary owned by a publicly traded
media-distribution company, Take Two of New York. The San Francisco
native sold his fledgling electronic commerce firm, DVD Wave, to
Take Two just about a month ago. Now he and his five-person company
find themselves at the helm of Take Two's online distribution
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Is it just me or was it not that long ago when kids lumbered
through four or more years to get their degrees and then took a
year off to traipse around Europe before sullying their hands with
business cards? Not so in the Internet era.
</P>
<P>
   And apparently not so with the likes of Osborn.
</P>
<P>
   Twentysomething entrepreneurial success stories aren't new to
the Silicon Valley, but that doesn't make the achievements of Sam
and company any less impressive. The story of how quickly he
launched and sold his Internet startup may serve as a metaphor for
the frenetic pace of deal making in the digital world.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, Osborn clearly demonstrates the kind of zealous
initiative and tireless drive that is requisite for most any
successful entrepreneur, regardless of age.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1997, as a sophomore at the University of
California at Berkeley, Osborn landed an internship at the
brokerage Bear Stearns. Liking what he saw and learned, it wasn't
long before he became a fully licensed stockbroker, spending half
of his days peddling investments from 5:30 a.m to 1:30 p.m. before
commuting over the bay to campus for a full slate of classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good time to work in the stock market,'' Osborn
recalls. ``I saw the Dow (Jones industrial average) break two
milestones while I was working there.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborn also researched stocks for clients, scouring company
prospectuses for clues on how to build companies. In addition, his
equity research efforts provided him with the opportunity to visit
companies and their top brass.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, these exercises provided the dual benefit of
being the research and development for his own company. ``I was
always thinking about what I could do on the Internet,'' Osborn
says.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet definitely was on his mind. Since the early 1990s,
Osborn had been tapping into Mosaic and other early incarnations of
the Web. He even started a Web-design business in the eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, we (kids) were the only ones who could do it,'' he
notes. The question was: What would be the next big thing on the
Web?
</P>
<P>
   ``(Digital Video Disc) was something that was new, and nobody
was really selling it online,'' Osborn recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a little more than a year ago, Osborn quit both Bear
Stearns and school to start one of the early e-commerce sites
devoted to selling and renting digital video discs, or DVDs,
online. He recruited a couple of childhood friends, Jeff Tyler and
Dave Wallerich, and the longtime pals holed up in Osborn's Berkeley
condominium to plan the launch of DVD Wave.
</P>
<P>
   Using just $10,000 of the partners' own cash, Osborn set about
finding a distributor of movies that might provide his fledgling
startup with the products it hoped to sell.
</P>
<P>
   By studying the prospectus of CDNow, an online seller of music
and movies, Osborn targeted major DVD fulfillment houses _
companies that supply DVDs to traditional retailers. Some already
were aligned with CDNow and Amazon.com, which were starting to
dabble in DVD sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he focused on Baker and Taylor Entertainment, a
suburban Chicago distribution house that has direct relationships
with record companies and movie studios, which he and his cohorts
pestered endlessly until it gave them a deal to market their discs.
</P>
<P>
   With absolutely no credit history, Baker and Taylor extended a
$500 credit line. Yep, a whole five-hundred bucks. ``So they set us
up,'' Osborn remembers.
</P>
<P>
   That was June, 1998. The site ( &LR; www.dvdwave.com &LR; ) went live a
month later. The first order came in about two weeks later. Osborn
remembers it well: a three-disc order from North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   They were off to the races. Using its relationships and
knowledge of the Web, DVD Wave built myriad relationships with
other sites to spread the word. High-touch customer service was
stressed. Business soared. Baker and Tayler extended the credit
line to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then just a few months ago, he hit pay dirt. An anonymous
customer was so impressed by DVD Wave's easy-to-use site, personal
service and competent delivery, he requested a meeting with Osborn.
The customer happened to be an executive of Jack of All Games, a
computer game distributor owned by Take Two.
</P>
<P>
   In just three weeks, Take Two was hammering out a deal with
Osborn to buy his nine-month old company for 50,000 shares of Take
Two stock, which currently is trading at about $8 a share. The
principal shareholders also received cash bonuses and kept their
jobs, which by the way, now pay a salary.
</P>
<P>
   Not having enough in the budget for a corporate attorney,
Osborn's father, John, a San Francisco estate-planning lawyer and
author of ``The Paper Chase,'' was drafted to represent his son's
firm. The deal was sealed over a weekend in early March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking to get into the Internet business, and we
thought that Sam's company could get it done,'' says Nicholas
Alexander, chief executive of Jack of All Games in Cincinnati, the
nation's largest distributor of video games.
</P>
<P>
   And now that Osborn is chief executive of an online unit of a
publicly traded company, are he and his schoolyard chums in a hurry
to re-enroll in medieval-history class? ``We have no interest in
going back to school any time soon,'' Osborn says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
