<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMOCO-CANCER-ART-2TAK     04-05 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMOCO-CANCER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL COMPANY CONFRONTS CLUSTER OF BRAIN TUMORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPERVILLE, Ill. _ It was not until the summer of 1996 that
Edward Paschke, a 54-year-old chemist working at the Amoco Research
Center here, realized that his life might be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, a rare form of brain cancer had been found in two
researchers with whom he had shared lab space. Amoco investigated
and found that a third lab worker had had a similar tumor in 1986.
And then in 1996, a malignant brain tumor had been discovered in
one of Paschke's closest colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made four brain tumors within 150 feet of where I was
working,'' Paschke said recently, as he sat stiffly on a couch in
his home here, 25 miles west of Chicago. ``It was terrifying.''
</P>
<P>
   When Paschke went for a checkup in summer 1996, doctors found a
benign brain tumor. And he was not alone. Over the next three
years, say officials at the company, now known as BP Amoco, at
least 20 brain tumors were found in current and former employees of
the center.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company began the nation's most ambitious
corporate investigation into a cluster of cancer cases in an effort
to learn if they were work-related.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very unusual pattern of brain cancer here,'' said
Jim Lowry, who heads a task force on the brain tumors at BP Amoco,
the oil giant based in London that was created when British
Petroleum acquired Chicago-based Amoco last year. ``You essentially
have this puzzle, and it points to a certain space and a certain
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancer clusters are rarely found to have a common cause.
Epidemiologists say that in large populations it is statistically
inevitable that clusters of similar cases will show up in one place
or another. In addition, cancer can develop over such long periods
that much of the evidence may be buried in the deep past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track record in these cases is not very good,'' said Peter
Inskip, an epidemiologist at the National Cancer Institute in
Bethesda, Md., who studies brain tumor cases. ``More often than
not, people have not come up with a convincing answer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Amoco, after consulting with the federal Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention and other agencies, found the circumstances
at Naperville so striking that it brought in experts from Johns
Hopkins University and the University of Alabama at Birmingham to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 20 brain tumors, which have caused five deaths so far,
seven were a rare malignant cancer called glioma, which strikes
only five of every 100,000 people each year. And five of the
gliomas occurred among chemists and lab technicians who worked over
many years in the same laboratory on the same corridor handling
toxic chemicals, including some known as heavy metal catalysts.
</P>
<P>
   In that lab, the brain cancer rate was eight times higher than
in the general population, the medical experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a two-year investigation costing millions of dollars,
BP Amoco officials hope that a comprehensive report due just weeks
from now will provide some answers. If nothing else, it may sort
out the thousands of chemicals found in the labs, to identify for
further study those used in common by the cancer victims.
</P>
<P>
   If the cause is determined to be work-related, officials say,
the company will ``do the right thing'' by compensating victims.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, a number of brain tumor victims have sued BP
Amoco, arguing that the company knowingly exposed its employees at
Naperville to toxic chemicals and unsafe conditions for years by
ignoring complaints about a faulty ventilation system.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco officials dispute the accusations, and say the medical
investigators have largely ruled out the ventilation system as a
cause of the brain tumors. But the officials also say there are no
opposing ``sides'' in this case. The company says it wants nothing
more than to resolve the situation and determine the cause of the
tumors.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Kastory, a BP Amoco spokeswoman, said the company had
hired the best experts, reviewed the work histories of more than
8,000 employees, taken apart laboratories and buildings, and
counseled and aided employees and former employees in what the
company acknowledges has been a ``terrible tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Amoco has gone to unusual lengths to uncover new brain tumor
cases, despite the threat of litigation, and has voluntarily shared
much of its information with the public and even the lawyers who
have filed suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is frustrating for us,'' said Lowry, the head of the BP
Amoco task force. ``We want to get to the bottom of this. I
personally knew five of the people with gliomas. Naturally, these
people want closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Amoco closed the third-floor laboratory of Building 503, where
five of the seven glioma victims worked, in 1996, after the fourth
cancer case was found there. Investigators said the victims
sometimes worked on the same experiments, researching polymers and
heavy metal catalysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is that five of them worked in the same general
area, and all of them crossed paths in the 1970s and 1980s, and
they were all long-term employees,'' said Michael Wells, a BP Amoco
manager on the brain tumor task force. He noted that the pattern of
benign tumors was not as unusual as that of the Glioma cases.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the floor was closed, Amoco says, Building 503 and
the entire 180-acre research campus were thoroughly tested and
deemed to be safe. Researchers tested the water, the walls for
radiation, the soil, even a microwave tower outside.
</P>
<P>
   While chemicals have not been proved to cause brain cancer, and
the mechanism by which they would cause cancer is not known,
either, the investigators hired by Amoco believe that if the brain
tumors are work-related, the most likely cause was contact with
toxic chemicals in Building 503.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
