<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0534 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMOCO-CANCER-ART-2NDT     04-05 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMOCO-CANCER-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NAPERVILLE, Ill.: Building 503.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several brain tumor victims, however, say the investigators are
overlooking the old ventilation system as a contributing factor. In
pending lawsuits, the plaintiffs say that toxic chemicals were
often stored in unventilated hallways and closets and that there
were noxious fumes in the hallways and corridors soon after
Building 503 opened. Amoco, they say, ignored repeated complaints
about the odors and failed to protect employees from exposure to
toxic chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were literally splashing our hands in known carcinogens,''
said Paschke, a researcher found to have a tumor in 1996, who spent
24 years in Building 503. ``We stored many toxic chemicals. At one
point, I stored mustard gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Amoco officials say that the medical experts have ruled out most
of those scenarios. The ventilation system was upgraded in the
early 1990s. A more likely culprit than than poorly ventilated
fumes, Amoco says, is the actual lab experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the victims concede that in the 1970s and 1980s, even
they doubted that the ventilation system or the lab experiments
posed a serious health risk.
</P>
<P>
   That began to change in 1989 after two researchers who worked in
the same lab were found to have glioma within a month of one
another. Amoco commissioned a study, but a group of outside medical
experts concluded that the event was probably ``serendipitous.''
The company was advised to monitor the situation.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly seven years, Amoco did. Then in early 1996, Nicholas
Karayannis, a 64-year-old chemist, was found to have glioma,
prompting a more comprehensive investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The illness of Karayannis, who was retired, shocked many of his
co-workers. It was discovered in January 1996 after he passed out
while having breakfast with some Amoco staffers.
</P>
<P>
   After surgery for the cancer, Karayannis knew his chances of
survival were slim, but his family says he kept up his routines. He
continued to visit his colleagues during lunch hour. He would
arrive with a huge scar on his skull, and a swelling that made it
difficult for him to wear his glasses.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Marios Karayannis, said Karayannis believed the tumor
had something to do with the chemicals he worked with. As his
condition began to deteriorate, he asked his son, a lawyer, to look
into the case.
</P>
<P>
   Around that time, Karayannis spent long hours in the basement of
his home, compiling lists, which the family found only after he
died in early 1998. There were lists of operas he had seen,
restaurants he had visited, and chemicals he had worked with. His
memory began to fail within a year of his surgery, and his son
believes he was trying to challenge himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``After his surgery, he'd go down in the basement and compose
lists for hours,'' Marios Karayannis said. ``But then he must have
gotten confused. You'd read about him going to see `Aida' or
`Carmen,' and then there'd be a list of chemicals.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Karayannis filed suit against Amoco on behalf
of his father and several others with brain tumors.
</P>
<P>
   Paschke is part of that suit. Though his tumor was benign, he
said, it was growing on a bundle of nerves and when it was removed,
he lost his sense of balance and hearing in his right ear. The
right side of his face is paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Paschke continues to work as a researcher at BP Amoco, and he
says he loves the work. But he says the company is playing down the
ventilation questions because it would leave BP Amoco open to
questions of negligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now paying the price for loose safety policies at Amoco
in the 1970s,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowry, BP Amoco's task force director, says nothing is being
ruled out by investigators. The situation, he said, has left
everyone frustrated. Because BP Amoco's research has been
comprehensive, many have lost patience waiting for answers that
even he acknowledges may never come.
</P>
<P>
   There is still some chance, he says, that investigators will
conclude that the brain tumors are not work-related, or that many
of the cases simply constitute a random cluster of cancer cases.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Lowry drew a chart on the board. At one end
were the words ``work-related'' and at the other the word
``unrelated.'' That is the spectrum. The answer, he says, may lie
somewhere in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was absolutely work-related I think we'd know by now,''
he said grimly. ``I don't think there's a definitive answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
