A7051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GTE-AMERITECH-1STLD-W     04-05 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GTE-AMERITECH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIAL DIVERSITY GETS ROLE IN WIRELESS-PHONE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to correct year in graf 5 to 1997.)  (lh) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In perhaps the first major telecommunications acquisition to be
described as a ``step forward'' for racial diversity, Ameritech
Corp. on Monday announced a deal to sell roughly half of its
wireless telephone business to a venture led by GTE Corp. for about
$3.3 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   For Ameritech's pending $62 billion acquisition by SBC
Communications Inc. to win regulatory approval, one of the two
companies had to sell a big piece of its wireless operation.
Federal rules prohibit companies from owning multiple wireless
phone licenses in a single market. Because SBC and Ameritech's
wireless units overlap in the Chicago and St. Louis areas,
eliminating the conflict was a clear prerequisite to completing the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   GTE said Monday that it would join with a private investment
firm that has no telecommunications experience: Georgetown
Partners, which is run by Chester C. Davenport, a former federal
government official, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Monday's deal said that SBC wanted to bring
a company run by members of one or more minority groups into the
wireless transaction at least partly to curry favor with William
Kennard, chairman of the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming chairman in 1997, Kennard has said that one of
his main priorities is to increase racial and ethnic diversity in
the communications industry.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is deciding whether to challenge SBC's deal to
acquire Ameritech on the grounds that is does not serve the public
interest.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, SBC said: ``Creating more diversity within the
telecommunications industry is an important goal for a number of
parties, not the least of which is the FCC, which has repeatedly
urged the industry to identify these opportunities. Since we
announced the SBC-Ameritech merger last May, we recognized that the
sale of the overlapping wireless properties would create an
opportunity for us to do well by our shareowners and good by
achieving the goal of expanding diversity within the ranks of
industry ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   The FCC declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Richard C. Notebaert, Ameritech's chairman, said in a statement:
``This sale demonstrates that the SBC-Ameritech merger will bring
substantial new competition into the Midwest, broaden the ownership
of these properties to include greater diversity from the community
and provide customers the benefits of growth and robust
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Monday's deal said that Georgetown Partners
first expressed interest last year in the Ameritech properties that
were up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it became clear that Georgetown Partners could not
complete the transaction on their own, we suggested that they
consider a number of other potential partners,'' the SBC statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Davenport said SBC had no direct involvement in
his company's aligning with GTE, which itself has agreed to merge
with Bell Atlantic Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to participate in the
wireless industry before it totally takes off,'' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown Partners will put up about $60 million of the $3.3
billion purchase price. GTE executives said that represented a 7
percent equity interest in the new operation that will run the
former Ameritech operations. The new venture, the executives said,
would have a total equity value of $817.5 million, and Davenport
would be its chairman, reporting to the president of GTE's wireless
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the deal said GTE would raise at least $2.5
billion in debt to fill out the purchase price. Davenport said that
Georgetown Partners would pay market interest rates on the portion
of the debt that it was responsible for.
</P>
<P>
   A GTE statement said that in addition to capital, Georgetown
Partners ``will provide the GTE subsidiary with marketing services
designed to capture demand for wireless products and services in
high-potential but under-served ethnic markets.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Davenport, who was an assistant secretary of transportation in
the Carter administration, said he had no special marketing acumen.
Until last year he was chairman of Envirotest Systems Corp., which
tests vehicle emissions. Envirotest was acquired last year by Stone
Rivet Inc. for $266 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a financial player,'' he said. Referring to marketing, he
added: ``I don't have any expertise in doing that, and I never said
that I did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson said Monday that he had met with
Ameritech and SBC executives in recent months to help them draft a
list of minority-owned companies that could participate in the
wireless sale, which was coordinated by Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   One of the initiatives of Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH Coalition, the
Wall Street Project, is aimed at encouraging diversity in the
business world. Georgetown Partners was a sponsor of the gala at
the project's annual conference in January, an event where
Davenport said he met with executives involved in Monday's deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge,'' Jackson said of Georgetown Partners'
participation in Monday's deal. ``Since Alexander Graham Bell,
there has never been an African-American qualified to own a
telephone company, because of historical patterns of exclusion.
Never before.'' Referring to the pending Ameritech-SBC merger and
the need for the companies to divest some wireless properties, he
added, ``Given the requirements of the merger, this was a strategic
moment to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow/PUSH Coalition endorsed the Ameritech-SBC merger
last month.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, SBC said: ``The bottom line is that this is a
good business deal for the companies. We also believe the fact that
Georgetown Partners is part of this transaction is a step forward
for diversity and inclusion in the telecommunications industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
