<HEADER>
A7053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      04-05 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Understated Cerruti &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _``It's halfway between 57th Street and the Whitney Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   _``I thought people might like a friendly place on Madison where
they can just stop by _ a place where it's calm and comfortable,
and the salespeople will be nice to them, and they can just have a
seat if they want.''
</P>
<P>
   _And ``Madison Avenue has good bus service.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the letter does O'Brien say how big the store is
(4,000 square feet) or how much fabulous limestone was imported to
cover the floors. ``Nino wanted something more lighthearted,'' he
explained. As for the bus tip, O'Brien, said, ``My richest friend
loves to take the bus, and that made me realize that taking the bus
was actually a luxury, because it takes so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerruti will celebrate his new store the conventional way, with
a party, next Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Christine Ganeaux's Start &LR;
</P>
<P>
   What happens to an unknown designer who gets the full-court
press during New York fashion week? Does she wilt, or wind up
selling to Bergdorf's? Neither.
</P>
<P>
   After Harper's Bazaar gave a fete in February to introduce her
label, Ms. Ganeaux sold a lot of clothes at her boutique on Crosby
Street in SoHo, particularly sexy trousers and motocross leathers.
She also scored some big-league media coverage. ``Elle, Travel &AMP;
Leisure, Paper, the E! channel,'' Ms. Ganeaux said, pausing. ``Who
else? Oh, Elle Decoration in England. They liked the store's
interiors.'' It was designed by Randy Hoffman, Ms. Ganeaux's
husband.
</P>
<P>
   But no retailers placed orders, and in any case, Ms. Ganeaux
isn't sure she's ready to sell wholesale. ``I've had lots of
interest from small stores, but for now I want to concentrate on my
business and grow it slowly,'' said Ms. Ganeaux, who produces
clothes exclusively for her boutique.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she's begun to produce some things herself, like
sleeveless leather tops for spring, in the room behind her
boutique. Even if it means pushing her husband's projects and
motorbikes further to the back. As Ms. Ganeaux spoke on the phone
from her workroom, Hoffman could be heard piping up in a small
voice in the background, ``I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Denim With a Difference &LR;
</P>
<P>
   With fashion in a revivalist mood, it stands to reason that one
of the newest looks right now in Los Angeles is something old.
Since Christmas, Ron Herman, the Hollywood trend king, has been
selling vintage denim and corduroy pants, as well as vivid football
jerseys and zip-front vintage sweatshirts, studded with rhinestones
and metal beads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response has been amazing,'' said Alonzo Ester, a buyer
who worked on the idea with Nina Garduno, the vice president of Ron
Herman's men's division.
</P>
<P>
   Ester said the idea originated last year during buying trips to
Japan, where vintage denim and corduroy jeans, to say nothing of
American sports jerseys and '70s airbrushed T-shirts, have found a
rapacious following. New denim is everywhere for fall. Last
October, Tom Ford of Gucci brought out his feather-strewn jeans,
which Ester admitted added heat to the trend. ``It's helped,'' he
said, ``but it's not where our idea came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Studded vintage jeans and cords sell from $135 to $400, while a
zip-front sweatshirt is about $140. Ester emphasized that each item
is hand-picked for individuality. ``They all have this feeling of
something home-grown,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
