<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7058 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-1STLD-     04-05 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 BIGGEST YUGOSLAV CITIES HIT IN INTENSIFIED NATO ASSAULT
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS top 2 grafs to add `NATO and Pentagon' attribution
before officials; SUBS 3rd graf to add three other bridges over
Danube have been destroyed; SUBS 4th graf to add NATO release of
aerial photo; ADDS in 5th graf that Shelton was with Clinton;
Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``Let me ....) 
 (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-BASES, KOSOVO-ECON) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO directed its most ferocious air strikes yet on
Yugoslav armored forces operating in Kosovo, and struck Belgrade
and the country's two other largest cities Monday night in an
intensified attack made possible by two consecutive nights of clear
weather, NATO and Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On the 13th day of the assault, American and NATO warplanes took
full advantage of the second night without the rain and clouds that
had inhibited NATO's earlier strikes, the officials said. The
allies sharply increased the number of bombing missions over
Yugoslavia because of the break. By mid-afternoon in Brussels on
Monday, NATO and Pentagon officials said their warplanes had
attacked 27 targets just overnight and planned to hit at least that
many again Monday night if the weather held.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon and NATO refused to specify their targets,
including their new pursuit of ground forces. Explosions rocked Nis
and Novi Sad, the two largest cities after the capital, Belgrade.
Yugoslavia's official television broadcast scenes of a huge
fireball in Novi Sad. The city's mayor said a power station at an
oil refinery had been struck. And officials said another bridge
over the Danube River, where three other bridges had already been
knocked out, had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, NATO released a surveillance photograph
Monday that officials said showed Yugoslav forces herding residents
from a village in Kosovo, and said other photographs depicted their
homes being destroyed. While describing the surveillance as
offering concrete evidence of President Slobodan Milosevic's
campaign to drive ethnic Albanians from the province, NATO and
Pentagon officials would not release the other photographs in the
series, and would not elaborate on their reasons for withholding
them.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at the White House Monday with Defense Secretary
William Cohen, and the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen.
Henry H. Shelton, President Clinton promised a relentless bombing
campaign Monday and said the United States was committed ``for the
long haul'' to stopping what he said was Milosevic's purge of
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be clear,'' Clinton said in brief comments to a handful
of reporters at the White House. ``The ethnic cleansing of Kosovo
cannot stand as a permanent event.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Our plan is to persist until we prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of refugees continued to stream out of Kosovo
into Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro, creating a humanitarian
crisis not matched in Europe for half a century. NATO spokesman
Jamie Shea said that since February 1998, Milosevic had displaced
at least 831,000 of the 2 million people who lived in the Serbian
province.
</P>
<P>
   Even as it conducted its military operation, NATO began an
almost equally difficult humanitarian operation to feed and give
temporary shelter for many of the thousands of refugees. The first
five plane loads left Macedonia for Turkey Monday morning, carrying
800 refugees. Several NATO nations, including the United States,
have agreed to take in about 110,000 refugees, providing them homes
until they can return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But officials in Albania, where 240,000 refugees have fled, said
that despite that nation's extreme poverty, they did not want other
countries to take in the refugees because sending them away would
only further Milosevic's goal of ridding the region of them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides said that his remarks Monday _ some of his
sharpest words yet _ were meant to warn Milosevic that a return of
the refugees was now a precondition of any end to NATO's assault on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``More empty promises and token half-measures won't do the
job,'' Clinton said, appearing at the White House with his national
security advisers. ``If Mr. Milosevic does not do what is
necessary, NATO will continue an air campaign. It will be
undiminished, unceasing and unrelenting. It will inflict such
damage that either he will change his calculation or we will
seriously diminish his capacity to maintain his grip and impose his
control on Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence assessments compiled here in Washington indicate
that Milosevic's forces might well be nearing the end of their
campaign to expel ethnic Albanians from their homes. Some officials
have speculated that Milosevic, armed with that advantage on the
ground, might then offer to end the fighting and return to the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that Clinton's comments Monday
were intended in part to pre-empt any gestures that Milosevic might
make that would not meet the conditions of the failed peace talks
in France, except for the return of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be a surprise to see in the coming days attempts
at half measures, hollow cease-fires,'' Joe Lockhart, the
president's spokesman, said. ``They will not be acceptable to stop
the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks Monday, Clinton restated the goals of the
mission, saying that for the bombing to stop, Milosevic would have
to withdraw his police units from Kosovo, agree to an autonomous,
multi-ethnic Kosovo, accept the deployment of an international
security force and take steps toward a political settlement to help
the refugees return home.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair echoed that resolve Monday.
``We will drive them back to Kosovo,'' he said of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The administration says that the refugee crisis was precipitated
by Milosevic, who has stepped up his repression of ethnic Albanians
in response to NATO's attack, which began on the night of March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's strikes destroyed the fourth bridge of the Danube, this
one near Sombar. The bridge is near Yugoslavia's northern border
with Hungary and far from the fighting in Kosovo. However,
officials have justified destroying bridges, saying they help
resupply Yugoslavia's military and police forces.
</P>
<P>
   In raids overnight on Sunday, NATO and American warplanes
destroyed four separate bridges near Kosovo, including one over the
Ibar River at Raska, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also targeted a fuel depot near Sombar and sites at a coal
mining center in Aleksinca, southeast of Belgrade, according to
Yugoslavia's official television. Kursumlija, an industrial town
near Kosovo, was struck Monday night, as was the military
headquarters at Nis, the television reported.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the targets reported by the Yugoslavs were
industrial sites in major cities, NATO officials said they were now
turning their attention to destroying the ground forces waging war
in Kosovo. In the first days of the campaign, some strikes had
destroyed staging areas, barracks and fuel and ammunition depots
directly supporting the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just starting to hit them,'' NATO's military spokesman,
Air Commander David Wilby of Britain, said Monday, before the
latest strikes began. ``The weather as you know, has only just
cleared, to give us a little more chance of hitting them hard.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that the strikes directed against the ground forces
would soon ``severely disrupt'' the Yugoslav offensive. Other NATO
and Pentagon officials acknowledged that the rout of the remaining
Albanian rebels was nearly complete.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, NATO warplanes had the first clear night in a week
and struck 27 targets including gasoline production and storage
sites, airfields, air defenses, ammunition depots and bridges,
Wilby said.
</P>
<P>
   In those raids, Yugoslavia's air defenses put up a significant
fight, having held back on previous nights. Pilots encountered
ferocious anti-aircraft artillery and several SA-3 surface-to-air
missiles. However, all NATO aircraft returned safely on Sunday and
did so again by Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   NATO warplanes also stepped up the propaganda war. An Air Force
EC-130 broadcast radio and television signals into Yugoslavia,
trying to undercut Milosevic's grip on the official media by
detailing the campaign against the ethnic Albanians and saying that
NATO did not oppose the Yugoslav people, only Milosevic's
government. Other planes also dropped leaflets.
</P>
<P>
   The United States announced plans to boost its relief efforts as
it prepared for the temporary resettlement of at least 20,000
Albanian refugees onto American territory, probably at the
Guantanamo Naval Air Station in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is undertaking a vast relief effort, flying in
10 missions a day from Italy to Tirana, the Albanian capital, at a
rate of more than 65,000 meals per day, or enough to feed 500,000
people for three months. It is also sending tents, sleeping bags
and other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The scale of the relief effort was so huge that it threatened to
overwhelm the already crowded skies in the Balkans. A Pentagon
spokesman said the deployment of 24 Apache helicopters to Albania
was being complicated by the large number of relief flights already
entering Albania's capital, Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   The relief effort and the deployment of the Apaches is deepening
the American commitment on the ground in the Balkans. The first 40
of 500 Air Force personnel have arrived in Albania, while the
Apaches and a rocket system to back them up will involve nearly
2,800 soldiers, according to the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance was part of a near-daily public-relations
campaign to explain and justify NATO's bombing and the American
contributions to it. He has struggled to simplify his message over
time as he tries to prepare the American public for what looks
increasingly like a lengthy and dangerous ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's use of the phrase ``cannot stand'' implied the kind of
drawing a line in the sand that President Bush used to muster
public support against Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush said in his 1991 State of the Union address: ``The
community of nations has resolutely gathered to condemn and repel
lawless aggression. Saddam Hussein's unprovoked invasion, his
ruthless, systematic rape of a peaceful neighbor, violated
everything the community of nations holds dear. The world has said
this aggression would not stand, and it will not stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as political pressure builds in Congress over concern
that the United States is becoming more enmeshed in the Balkans
than it initially planned, Clinton has refrained from a
full-throated call to arms, and public opinion remains ambivalent
toward the mission.
</P>
<P>
   With Congress on recess and lawmakers spread around the globe,
it is impossible to gauge the prevailing view of the conflict in
Serbia, but at least some Democratic senators who voted last month
to support the NATO airstrikes seem now to be having second
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who is
chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, warned
Clinton that many senators had voted in favor of the bombing
``against their better instincts'' and that a majority would
probably oppose sending in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not get my vote,'' Torricelli said. Largely because
of strong Democratic support, the Senate endorsed the bombing by a
vote of 58-41.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli also said that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and Sandy Berger, the national security adviser, ``had best be
holding their hat in their hands'' because of their optimistic
predictions about the effectiveness of the air campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
