<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7060 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GOTTI-TRIAL-2TAKES     04-05 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOTTI-TRIAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOTTI PLEADS GUILTY TO RACKETEERING ON EVE OF TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds., this is an added starter on NYT Page 1, later editions)  
(ac) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ Less than a day before his trial was to
begin, John A. Gotti, accused of being the acting boss of the
Gambino crime family, pleaded guilty Monday to being part of
criminal racket that involved bribery, extortion and the threat of
violence. In return, he faces a maximum sentence of seven years and
three months in federal prison and a $1-million fine.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the sentence is much less than the 20 years Gotti
might have received if convicted in a trial, prosecutors contend
that the plea will further damage the power of both the Gotti
family and its interests and the larger Gambino crime family that
his father John J. Gotti led for many years until he was convicted
in 1991 and imprisoned for life.
</P>
<P>
   Although plea negotiations have been an on-again, off-again
proposition for months, Gotti's lawyer, Gerald Shargel, said his
client made a firm decision to accept a deal after learning that
federal prosecutorswere about to indict him on tax charges and
realizing that he would be the endless target of prosecution unless
he submitted to a criminal plea.
</P>
<P>
   Shargel said that Gotti, 35, wanted ``closure and finality'' so
he could eventually return to his Oyster Bay home to raise his four
children before they are grown. ``It was a no-win situation,''
Shargel said after emerging from an unusual nighttime hearing at
which Gotti made his plea. ``If he won at trial, every prosecutor
with a gun would be out looking for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gotti, wearing a dark brown suit, light brown shirt and a brown
and tan tie, took off his glasses and spoke softly and solemnly as
he recited the crimes that he had arranged to plead guilty to.
</P>
<P>
   He first admitted to conspiring with members of an association
to commit criminal offenses. That was not as much as the government
had hoped, since he did not specifically admit to being the acting
boss of the Gambino crime family, an admission that would have
violated one of the cardinal rules of the underworld.
</P>
<P>
   For a reputed mob commander, Gotti looked unusually humble as he
replied to questions put to him by the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you been inducted to plead guilty by any promise?'' Judge
Barrington D. Parker Jr. asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No your honor,'' Gotti said, his hands folded in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you been induced to plead guilty by any threat of force,
and do you plead guilty voluntarily?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do you honor,'' Gotti replied.
</P>
<P>
   In his plea, Gotti admitted to four acts of racketeering. He
said ``it was part of my pattern of racketeering'' that in 1996 he
had paid bribes to an officer of a labor organization, which the
government identified as an officer of Local 445 of the Teamsters
Union. Federal officials said later that the bribe was an attempt
to win a contract worth $5 million to $10 million for construction
at Stewart Airport in New Windsor, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti also said that in 1996 he ``conspired with others'' to
extort money through ``threatened force'' from a construction
project in Mount Vernon, N.Y., supervised by DeFoe Corp. The
government said the amount of money he extorted was $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The other two racketeering acts, he said, were running an
illegal gambling operation in Connecticut and understating his
income on an application to refinance his mortgage. Although he did
not specify the amounts of money involved, Carol L. Sipperly, the
lead prosecutor, said the operation took in $5,000 to $6,000 a week
and that the loan was was $338,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti also pleaded guilty to two additional crimes that were not
part of the original federal indictment in January 1998 but were
put into three guilty plea as a result of a new investigation by
the U.S. attorney in Brooklyn. One of these _ making loans between
January 1990 and September 1994 at usurious interest rates _ Gotti
described to the judge as ``loansharking.'' The second charge was
that he understated his income on a 1994 tax return.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the guilty pleas involved Scores, the Manhattan
topless club, that was originally the center of the case against
Gotti, who was accused of extorting money from the club's owners
and employees.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Gotti's plea deal is only the latest in what the government
contends is a series of damaging blows to the power of organized
crime in New York and other major cities. In New York, the
conviction of Gotti comes on the heels of the July 1997 conviction
of Vincent ``the Chin'' Gigante, then the head of the powerful
Genovese crime family, for conspiracy and for an unsuccessful plot
to kill the elder Gotti.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Nicholas Corozzo, the designated successor
to the elder Gotti at the top of the Gambino family, pleaded guilty
in federal district court in Brooklyn to loan sharking,
racketeering and other charges, in exchange for a 10-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the efforts of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Manhattan
District Attorney Robert Morgenthau have reduced the mob's
influence at the Fulton Fish Market, in the city's commercial
garbage hauling industry and at the Javits Convention center.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's unusual court session, which began at 6:40 p.m.,
was attended by dozens of lawyers and investigators in the office
of the U.S. attorney for the Southern District. Gotti was
accompanied only by his three lawyers and his brother, Peter Gotti.
Judge spent roughly an hour making sure that Gotti understood each
charge to which he was pleading guilty and that the plea was not
the result of force or threats of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after reciting the crimes that he committed from a sheet
of yellow legal paper, Gotti faced the clerk of the court, who
asked him how he pleaded to three different categories of crimes.
Gotti pronounced ``guilty'' three different times.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti will be sentenced on July 8, though the boundaries of his
sentence were outlined by an agreement reached by Gotti's lawyers _
Shargel, Bruce Cutler and Sarita Kedia, and the prosecutors, Ms.
Sipperly and Marjorie Miller. The agreement is not binding on the
judge, but judges typically go along with such requests.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Parker could sentence him to anywhere from
5 years, 10 months to 7 years, 3 months. He also would be forced to
forfeit the $358,000 in cash that investigators seized from his
house, an 89-acre property in Pennsylvania and one additional
property. And he will pay a $1 million fine.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection for Gotti's trial was supposed to start on
Tuesday morning, with 500 residents of Manhattan, the Bronx,
Westchester, Putnam, Rockland, Dutchess Orange and Sullivan
counties summoned for what would have been at least a two-week
screening process. Gotti's lawyers appeared in court on Monday
morning to spell out some of the procedures for that screening and
to withdraw a request that Gotti be returned to jail so he could
save on the $24,000-a-month for the private guards he was required
to pay for.
</P>
<P>
   That mini-drama was supplanted later in the day by what appeared
to be secret negotiations between prosecutors and defense lawyers.
Richard Rehbock, a lawyer who has known Gotti for more than 15
years but was not permitted to represent him, emmerged at 5:30 and
told three reporters that the negotiations concerned questions on
the questionnaire. The reporters returned to their offices. What
almost gave his ruse away was that he was smoking a cigarette for
the first time in four months, an indication that something more
ominous was being discussed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
