<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7068 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKERBIE-LIBYA-1STLD     04-05 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKERBIE-LIBYA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBYA HANDS OVER BOMBING SUSPECTS, AND U.N. LIFTS SANCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS to insert ``on paper, that is'' in 7th graf.)  (See sidebar, LOCKERBIE-FAMILIES) 
(ac) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTRECHT, Netherlands _ More than a decade after Pan Am Flight
103 exploded over Scotland, killing 270 people, the two Libyans
charged with planting the bomb arrived in The Netherlands on Monday
to face trial for the crime. As a result, the United Nations
immediately removed its severe sanctions on the Libyan government
of Moammar Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   The end of those sanctions, in place since 1992, allows
international air travel and the sale of vital industrial equipment
to resume. The step will also release Libyan assets that had been
frozen in a number of countries. But separate sanctions imposed by
the United States in 1986 _ before the deaths over Lockerbie,
Scotland, in 1988 _ will not end until other conditions are
fulfilled, American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The delivery of the suspects in a highly unusual arrangement of
trial in the Netherlands under Scottish law followed years of
international pressure and months of diplomatic negotiations with
Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   Americans relatives of the dead expressed some bitterness at the
turn of events, arguing that Libya had won more than it lost. But
others expressed the hope that the extraditions would mark an
important turn on the road to exacting punishment for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The two Libyans, Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-Amin Khalifa
Fahima, both assumed to be government agents, were brought here
under a complex arrangement that treats a former military base near
here as temporary Scottish territory, so the suspects can be tried
under Scottish law. It was this formula _ promoted by Britain _ of
holding the trial in a third country that finally broke the
deadlock and ended Libya's long refusal to cooperate with American
and British prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish judges presiding over the trial will have to weigh
the still secret evidence, provided by the United States and
Britain and decide whether the two Libyans are guilty of planting
the suitcase bomb. The judges will then face the more fundamental
questions of who gave the orders to blow up the plane and why. The
British and Americans have outlined the main conclusions of their
case, but have withheld the particulars.
</P>
<P>
   Libya handed over the two suspects this morning in Tripoli, the
Libyan capital, to Hans Corell, the U.N. undersecretary-general for
legal affairs, in the presence of envoys from half a dozen Arab and
other nations invited by Gadhafi. An Italian plane made available
to the United Nations took the two Libyans, each accompanied by a
relative and a lawyer, to the Dutch military air base, Valkenburg.
Dutch authorities at first took the two Libyans into custody after
they arrived this afternoon but an hour later formally extradited
them to Britain _ on paper, that is _ so the Scottish police could
take over.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch military helicopters then took the Libyans to Camp Zeist,
a former military base a few miles outside the city of Utrecht.
Some of the camp's buildings are being converted to include a
detention unit for the suspects and a room for the Scottish court.
More than 100 Scottish officials, including prosecutors, police and
court employees have already arrived in recent days. The camp, once
used by American military and then taken over by the Dutch, is kept
under tight guard by Scottish police.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton issued a statement Monday saying that he was
``gratified'' by the extraditions. ``Now, at last, the road to
justice has begun.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright spoke with about 20 family members of the Lockerbie
victims in a conference call Monday reassured them that the
sanctions on Libya could be reimposed if the Libyan government
backed away from any part of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who was deeply
involved in the diplomatic maneuvering leading up to the handover,
said Monday that this ended ``a 10-year diplomatic stalemate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had over a year of hard diplomatic effort and tough
negotiations to get here,'' Cook said. ``There will now be a
criminal trial for that act of mass murder and the relatives of all
those who died will have their first opportunity to hear all the
evidence that we hold in open court.''
</P>
<P>
   He said one of the most difficult aspects of the case was that
the government had not been able to tell relatives of the victims
of the explosion ``what we know and suspect happened to their loved
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of those who died were on the ground in the village of
Lockerbie, while most of the passengers who died were Americans.
</P>
<P>
   British and American investigators concluded that a bomb was put
aboard the Pan Am flight on its way from Frankfurt to New York
during its stopover at Heathrow Airport. Less than an hour after
takeoff, the Pan Am Boeing 747 exploded in flames, killing its
passengers and crew members. In 1991, Britain and the United States
indicted the two Libyan government agents in connection with the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries, which have gone to great lengths to amass the
evidence for the crash, have insisted for years that the suspects
must face trial in either Scotland or in the United States. When
Libya refused, the two countries pressed the United Nations to
impose sanctions in 1992. The sanctions were toughened in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   These sanctions have barred air travel to and from Libya as well
as the sale of arms and spare parts for aviation and for the oil
industry, which is vital to Libya. Although the sanctions were
suspended Monday, the Security Council must still vote to lift them
completely. It can do so within 90 days if the Secretary General
reports that Libya has met other conditions, such as cooperating
with France in its investigation of a UTA flight over Niger in 1989
in which 171 people died and committing itself to pay compensation
to the families of the crash victims in case its two agents are
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock was broken last year when Washington and London
took up an old Libyan offer to have the two suspects face trial in
a third country. Libya had argued the two could not get a fair
trial in Britain or the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Libya's handover of the two follows months of mediation by South
Africa and Saudi Arabia and threats by the United States and
Britain that Libya could be subjected to even tougher sanctions.
President Nelson Mandela of South Africa and U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan involved themselves personally in the negotiations with
Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the sanctions played a role in Libya's decision, Annan
said Monday, ``I prefer to think they played a role. No country
likes to be treated as an outcast.''He added, ``Libya wanted to get
on with its economic and society development.''
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for the trial at Camp Zeist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
