<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0547 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KORS-FASHION-ART-NYT &LR;      04-05 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KORS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EAR FOR WHAT WOMEN WANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Kors was at Bergdorf Goodman a couple of
weeks ago to meet customers, and was reminded of a day early in his
career when he went to a store in Minneapolis where Bill Blass _
one of his idols, then and now _ was making a personal appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the Peter Frampton look, long curly blond hair and
scruffy jeans,'' Kors said, ``and this saleswoman said to me, `If
you clean yourself up, you can be just as good as Bill Blass.'''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he hasn't yet reached the iconic stature of Blass, but
Michael Kors now has a crew cut, wears cashmere sweaters and, more
important, has been named the 1999 women's wear designer of the
year by the Council of Fashion Designers of America. Both the
signature collection he shows on Seventh Avenue and the one he
designs for Celine in Paris have been winning high praise from the
fashion press, retailers and customers. And now that LVMH Moet
Hennessy Louis Vuitton, which owns Celine, has bought one-third of
his business and infused the company with money and opportunities
for expansion, Michael Kors is poised to become a global brand
name.
</P>
<P>
   When he appears at a store these days, loyal customers flock to
see him. He enthusiastically combs the racks, pulling out pieces he
likes and showing the women how to put them together in different
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love doing trunk shows,'' he said in the midst of a recent
one at Saks Fifth Avenue. ``It shows me who the customer is and
what she wants.''
</P>
<P>
   His customers are like Sue and Sally Spiegel from Chicago, a
mother and daughter, who were at the Saks event in New York and
have both been wearing his clothes for years. ``When you find
something you like, you stick with it,'' Sally Spiegel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you really Michael Kors?'' her mother asked, as she paid
for a white pants outfit of his.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm really Michael Kors,'' he answered, ``and I was in
Chicago last week and where were you?'' She was charmed.
</P>
<P>
   There are also celebrity customers like Claire Danes, Lauren
Hutton, Barbara Walters and Bebe Neuwirth (who first met him in the
elevator of their apartment building in Greenwich Village). And
then there are the young New York social types like Aerin and Jane
Lauder, Samantha and Serena Boardman, Lulu de Kwiatkowski and
Brooke de Ocampo, many of whom have become his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Michael 8 or 10 years,'' Ms. de Ocampo said. ``A
lot of time I'll see him out and about at different parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wearing his clothes as long as I've known him. In my
age group right now, in between the stage of slouching-around
clothes and ladies-who-lunch clothes, he's perfect. It's how the
young American well-dressed woman likes to look.''
</P>
<P>
   Kors, 39, says he thinks about his customers when he designs.
``I think, `This is for so-and-so to wear to the beach.' And my
sample sales always turn into personal shopping sessions. I hate to
see things sitting on a rack. I'll say `Send this to so-and-so and
tell her she has to buy it.''' And she does, because she trusts his
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   This connection with his customers is one reason for his
longevity in the fashion business. Like the steady-Eddie supporting
actor who finally gets his chance in the spotlight, Kors is
enjoying the fruits of 18 years of toiling to build his business.
There were some shaky times: he had to close down his lower-priced
Kors line for three years (it is now licensed to Onward Kashiyama),
and some stores dropped him. But those stores and more are now
clamoring for his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nordstrom kind of dabbled with Kors over the years,'' said Sue
Patneaude, the store's vice president for designer apparel, ``but
we became vitally interested in the Michael Kors line this year and
will carry Celine this fall for the first time. He seems to have
matured and become very focused. All the talent he's been trying to
harness all these years has come together. He's all of a sudden
ended up front and center. It's cosmic.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip B. Miller, the chairman of Saks Fifth Avenue, who gave a
cocktail party in February for Kors in the store and a dinner
afterward at Chow, considers him ``one of the designers of
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He represents a big growing business for us,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Kaner, the senior vice president and fashion director of
Neiman Marcus, agrees that it's a Michael Kors moment. ``He's at
the top of his form and seems more secure than ever,'' she said.
``He's able to do two collections, each with its own identity, and
both strong.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After his recent public appearance at Bergdorf's, relaxing over
a Coke and cookies (no cigarette, he gave up smoking last
November), Kors ruminated on the reasons for his sudden success
after 18 years. ``I think I've been consistent,'' he said. ``I've
stuck to my guns. Fashion to a certain degree is a roller coaster,
and I've held a steady course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you sum up this time in fashion,'' he continued, ``it's
casual luxe. It's what we've always done, which was for a cult and
is now more mainstream, for more people. It's not just the press
and retailers, but a broader group of customers who are saying,
that's the way to dress right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been very much about the customer,'' he added.
``What never changes is that everyone wants to look tall and thin
and young. When everyone from Claire Danes to Courtney Love to
Barbara Walters all wear the same clothes, that's when I know I'm
doing my job well.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the criticism from some quarters that what he does is
just sportswear, not high fashion?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to Paris last year to do Celine,'' he said,
``people said, `You're a sportswear designer.' I said, Two of the
most legendary names in French fashion _ Chanel and Yves Saint
Laurent _ both had a sportswear attitude. And I think the two
greatest garments designed in the world are the T-shirt and jeans.
They're ageless and sexless and they came from America.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that what Kors stands for is sportswear.
There is nothing chichi about the sweaters, skirts, pants, jackets
and coats he designs, but they do carry a sense of luxury with rich
materials like cashmere, silk, leather and fur.
</P>
<P>
   His three lines _ Michael Kors, Kors by Michael Kors and Celine
_ all share a design sensibility that stamps them as his work. No
mean achievement considering the simplicity of the designs.
</P>
<P>
   But don't call him a minimalist, please.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear `minimalism,' I think `pretentious,''' he said.
``I think of a room so minimal you're afraid to sit in it.''
</P>
<P>
   He sprinkles his evening wear with glitter and isn't reluctant
to use exuberant colors like orange, red and cerulean blue, playing
them against basics like camel and black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says I use blue because my eyes are blue and I use
camel and brown because I'm blond,'' he said. ``But people expect
those colors from me. If I don't show something blue, women ask for
it.'' Indeed, a woman approached him at Bergdorf's and complained
that there was nothing blue in the spring collection.
</P>
<P>
   There are other signatures, which he refers to as Michaelisms,
that are in some form in all his collections. These are the
turtleneck (``The turtleneck thing you have to blame on my
mother,'' he said. ``She's turtleneck-obsessed, even living in Los
Angeles.''), the white shirt and the strapless black dress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
