<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACQUISITIONS-AD-COLUMN-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND THE BIG GET BIGGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Fla., Ill., N.Y., Md., Calif., Texas, Ga.)  (lh) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two big agency companies are on the acquisition trail
again in deals that underscore the urgency with which the global
giants are seeking to expand their services.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to broaden its offerings in retail marketing _ and
add more glue to a relationship with a big automotive client _
Omnicom Group, the world's No. 1 agency company, has agreed in
principle to acquire Zimmerman &AMP; Partners Advertising in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., which specializes in local auto dealer
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   And to increase its expertise in data base marketing, Young &AMP;
Rubicam Inc., the world's No. 5 agency company, is buying Knowledge
Base Marketing Inc. in Chapel Hill, N.C., which specializes in the
so-called customer relationship services that are at the heart of
electronic commerce and other targeted marketing campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Acquisitions like this, said Edward H. Vick, chief operating
officer at Y&AMP;R in New York, are meant to ``extend our capabilities
and our marketing expertise to better help our clients achieve
results in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R is acquiring Knowledge Base, a leader in data base
marketing, in a cash and stock deal valued around $175 million; it
is the largest acquisition made by Y&AMP;R since the company went
public last May. Terms of the agreement between Omnicom and
Zimmerman, which is still being completed, were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman had been a major local dealer agency for Mitsubishi
Motor Sales of America, handling dealer groups in markets like
Baltimore, Dallas and Miami, until losing those assignments in the
last year to Deutsch Inc. in Los Angeles and New York. The losses
came after the collapse of a deal calling for Zimmerman to be
acquired by Grey Advertising in New York, the world's ninth-largest
agency company, and for a team of Zimmerman and Grey to handle
those duties.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Zimmerman, which also has regional offices in cities like
Atlanta, Chicago and San Francisco, is to become the agency for
local dealers selling cars and trucks for the North American
operations of another Japanese automaker, the troubled Nissan Motor
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is the second instance in a month that Omnicom has
made significant efforts to strengthen ties with a large, important
automotive client, coming after a decision to have Merkley Newman
Harty in New York handle the Mercedes-Benz of North America account
for DaimlerChrysler AG.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan is the largest worldwide client of TBWA Worldwide, an
Omnicom agency, representing about half of the agency's $1.6
billion in global billings. Under the agreement, Zimmerman will
become an agency dedicated to the dealer account of Nissan North
America, with billings estimated at $200 million. That assignment
would be shifted from the TBWA/Chiat/Day unit of TBWA.
</P>
<P>
   TBWA/Chiat/Day will continue to handle the national brand, or
so-called factory, advertising for Nissan along with the national
brand and local dealer advertising for the sibling Infiniti
division. Those billings are estimated at $400 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   TBWA/Chiat/Day is preparing to create campaigns for several 2000
model year vehicles considered crucial for a comeback of Nissan,
which was recently given a substantial financial infusion by the
French automaker Renault SA. Those products include the Xterra
sport utility vehicle and the Maxima sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson, executive vice president at Omnicom in New York,
confirmed a report of the acquisition this week in the trade
publication Adweek. The seven regional offices of TBWA/Chiat/Day
that had handled local dealer advertising are likely to become part
of Zimmerman, he said; they are in cities like Chicago, Dallas and
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman will report to Omnicom rather than TBWA, he added, as
part of efforts to give Nissan dealers a voice deemed more
independent from the factory.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Zimmerman, chairman and president at Zimmerman, referred
telephone calls to Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R's acquisition of Knowledge Base, a privately held company
with revenue estimated at $40 million to $50 million, will bolster
the offerings of its direct-marketing arm, Wunderman Cato Johnson
in New York. Knowledge Base will operate as an autonomous unit
under current management, reporting to Jay Bingle, chief executive
at Wunderman Cato in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that this combination with Young &AMP; Rubicam enhances
our ability'' to help clients achieve ``the most effective and
efficient execution of marketing programs,'' said Tim Toben, chief
executive at Knowledge Base, who will continue in that post.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge Base develops and manages data bases for more than 200
clients in various fields, including energy, financial services,
health care, retailing and technology. Among them are CDNow, the
online music retailer; Ford Motor; Mellon Bank; Microsoft, and
United Healthcare. Knowledge Base has more than 280 employees in
offices in Chapel Hill and seven other cities, including Chicago,
Houston, Mexico City and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R will ``continue to look for acquisitions'' like the deal to
buy Knowledge Base, Vick said. Shares of Y&AMP;R fell 12.5 cents
Monday, to $40.875, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
