<SLUG> BC-BBN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: MCGWIRE LOOKS AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The cheers for him rock the stadium. It is opening
day of the baseball season here, and there is always a full house
for this event, but this one is special. Because of him, because of
what he has done. And Monday night in Mark McGwire's first time at
bat in the 1999 season, he received a standing ovation from the
50,000-plus fans, with flashbulbs sparkling in a light drizzle, and
the fans remained standing as he walked on a 3-2 pitch from the
Milwaukee left-hander Rafael Roque. Then they booed the pitcher for
his, to them, lack of fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has been in demand. He was ushered in to kiss the pope's
ring when the holy father visited here over the winter. He even got
a cameo on a television sit-com. He is rich, he is famous, he is
adored. One might imagine that he needs a psychiatrist like a hole
in the head. Not true. He sees one regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone does'' need one, he said before Monday night's
opening game at Busch Stadium. ``Just some people don't want to
admit it. Everyone has problems _ maybe not problems, but issues.''
</P>
<P>
   To the question _ the most asked question in sports at this
moment _ ``Can you top last year?'' McGwire has a reply, one that
presumably grew out of therapy. ``That's living in the past, it's
what's been done,'' he said. ``Last year means nothing. You have to
turn the page.'' It is a way of relieving whatever psychological
burdens one may place on oneself.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, 35, is huge _ 6 feet 5 inches, 250 pounds, 17{-inch
biceps. He is our Atlas, our Tarzan, our Captain Marvel, our Sultan
of Swat. He is the guy who did the unthinkable, bashing 70 home
runs for the St. Louis Cardinals last season _ breaking Roger
Maris' sanctified record by nine homers, beating Babe Ruth's by a
big, fat 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look in awe at Mac in batting practice,'' said the veteran
outfielder Darren Bragg, who joined the Cardinals as a free agent
from Boston this spring. ``We're all men, but he's five or six
levels beyond the rest of us. When we try to hit a homer, we try to
hit it over the fence. When he tries to hit a homer, he tries to
hit it out of the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   But appearances, and statistics, can be deceiving. In a society
in which some still perceive it a weakness of some kind to seek
help or support mentally, McGwire has been up-front about visiting
a psychiatrist. ``I've been seeing somebody since November of
'91,'' he said. He looks at a visitor directly, no pretense in his
blue eyes, an easy smile glimpsed within his red goatee.
</P>
<P>
   In the winter of 1991, McGwire was not on top of the world. In
fact, he felt as if he was sinking deep into it. In his fifth full
season in the big leagues, as a first baseman for Oakland, he had
batted just .201 and had fallen to 22 homers, well down from his
league-leading 49 as a rookie. His marriage was falling apart, and
he was separated from his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt I needed help then,'' he said, ``and I felt I
couldn't get out of this by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The next season McGwire improved to a .268 batting average and
42 homers. Then he suffered debilitating injuries and got down
again. ``I thought about giving up baseball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire talked with his psychiatrist and eventually decided not
to leave baseball.
</P>
<P>
   His physical health improved and so, apparently, did his mental
health. ``His concentration and intensity grew stronger,'' said
Tony La Russa, the Cardinal manager who also managed McGwire in
Oakland. ``I watch him in the dugout as he gets ready to go to the
on-deck circle. He's focusing, he's grinding. He seems oblivious to
anything else that's going on. You can actually see the power of
his mind rippling.''
</P>
<P>
   And what issues, as McGwire termed them, might be bothering him
at other times? Personal ones, he says, ``like everybody else.''
Business? Family? Pressure? ``Sure,'' he said. He has said that if
he doesn't hit 70 homers this season ``some people will say I
failed.'' He won't, he said. To hit 50 or more, that's his goal.
</P>
<P>
   He says he can handle whatever pressures might develop. ``My
mind is too strong _ nothing is going to get in my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Will he continue to see a psychiatrist? McGwire nodded. ``The
day you stop learning,'' he said, ``is the day you're 6 feet
under.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
