<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7212 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORGAN-BIOGRAPHER-500     04-05 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-BIOGRAPHER-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOLAR'S STORMY LIFE WITH MORGAN'S GHOST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are not a perfect couple: J. Pierpont Morgan,
the inarticulate, unreflective and unofficial central banker of the
United States before there was a Federal Reserve, and Jean Strouse,
a former Radcliffe English major whose analytic gifts were
previously focused on a biography of Alice James, a powerless
invalid.
</P>
<P>
   But for the last 15 years, Ms. Strouse has lived nearly
full-time, on paper and in her head, with Morgan, the titan who
gave birth to industrial America and many of New York's most
important cultural institutions. She has pored over Morgan's ledger
books, investigated his mistresses and found pressed violets in the
diary of his first wife. Even now, she has yet to move the
Morganalia out of her one-bedroom apartment on the Upper West Side.
``Morgan takes up more space than I do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In short, no one alive knows him as well. Evidence: her 796-page
``Morgan: American Financier,'' published this month by Random
House, in which Ms. Strouse is part detective, part novelist, part
psychologist. Reviewers are in awe that Ms. Strouse has found a
human being underneath the rapacious robber baron (the view of the
left) or the financial Moses (the right). For her part, Ms. Strouse
spent her first five years with Morgan eyeing him with a
prosecutor's disgust. ``It was as if I had my hands on my hips
saying, `Oh, sure,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ms. Strouse liked Morgan but didn't excuse him _ and
felt she had forged an intimate connection. ``But it took years to
feel that,'' she said in an interview at the Morgan Library, the
same place where Morgan famously locked up the nation's bankers
during the financial panic of 1907 and ordered them to sign a
bailout package. ``Because he's such an alien character to me. He
didn't want to know any of the things I wanted to know.''
</P>
<P>
   And what, if Morgan were alive and down the hall (he died in
1913), would she ask him?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Strouse hesitated. She is a journalist-turned-scholar, with
a serious reputation. ``I don't think I want to say,'' she said.
Which makes it all the more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Well, she relented, there was the matter of his first wife,
Amelia _ Memie _ his true love, who was already so sick with a
serious cough when he married her in 1861 that Morgan had to hold
her up at the altar. He then insisted on taking Memie to the
Mediterranean for a cure, only to be told in Europe that Memie had
tuberculosis. Morgan nursed her obsessively and carried her up and
down seven flights of stairs in Paris. But Memie died four months
after the wedding, when Morgan was 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether that marriage was ever consummated,'' Ms.
Strouse said, a little embarrassed by her admission. It is not, she
admitted, a historically important question, just the human
curiosity of someone who knows Morgan, and cares. ``Because he
really loved her,'' Ms. Strouse said. ``I don't know if he ever got
over her death.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These days Ms. Strouse, 53, is enjoying that moment when the
private life of a scholar becomes the public life, however
fleeting, of just-published biographer. There will be a party for
her at the Morgan Library next week, a book tour, plus her re-entry
into the 20th century. (Ms. Strouse knew it was time to move on
from Alice James, the sister of Henry and William, when she began
writing ``Dec. 12, 1878'' on her own correspondence.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I want to do this again,'' she said of big
biography. ``It was too long and hard. A friend of mine says that
biography is a little like marriage _ you only have room in your
life for one or two. Well, I've had two.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Strouse has never married, was involved with a man until
recently and travels in the gossipy intellectual world of what
people sometimes call The New York Review of Each Other's Books.
Ms. Strouse grew up in Los Angeles, where her father was an
internist, came to New York after graduating from Radcliffe in 1967
to work as an assistant to Robert B. Silvers, the co-editor of The
New York Review of Books, left in 1975 to write her 1980 Alice
James book (which won the Bancroft Prize), spent four years as a
book critic at Newsweek, then started working on Morgan in 1983.
She plays squash and dresses well, but otherwise lives a very
un-Morganesque life.
</P>
<P>
   When her 1983 advance payment from Random House ran out _ she
describes it as ``in the low six figures'' _ Ms. Strouse put
together academic grants, teaching jobs, money from her mother and
additional payments from Random House. ``I've been living like a
graduate student, and I've had it,'' she said. ``Especially writing
about somebody who lived the way Morgan did _ it was comical.''
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through, she nearly gave up when she began waking up at
4 a.m., convinced she would would never understand the 19th century
financial data. ``But I couldn't pay back the advance, and I also
couldn't admit failure,'' she said. A friend who runs a hedge fund,
Roger Alcaly, talked her through it, and today Ms. Strouse is a
trustee of some family investments. ``I've been educated,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She has no idea what she'll do next, but well remembers when she
finished the book _ Aug. 19, 1998. Two days later she took a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so light,'' she said. ``It was the first vacation I'd
taken without J.P. Morgan in 15 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
