<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A NEW DAY, BUT THE METS AGE QUICKLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The New York Mets spent the off-season spending money to
keep their top players and making trades to become potential
postseason contenders.
</P>
<P>
   But on opening day the Mets could not beat the Florida Marlins,
the worst team in the National League last season. The Mets'
revamped offense left 14 runners stranded, including the bases
loaded twice, and went 0-for-9 with runners in scoring position in
Monday's 6-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Al Leiter pitched at Pro Player Stadium was as the
Marlins' starter in Game 7 of the 1997 World Series. Leiter, who
struggled all spring, allowed three first-inning runs, five
overall, in five innings Monday. He threw 124 pitches, surrendered
nine hits and two walks and had five strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   His first-inning troubles provided a quick reminder that no
matter how improved the Mets look on paper, they are still
struggling against a team that finished last year with 54
victories, the fewest in the league. In 1998, the Mets were only
7-5 against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets hope to get off to a quick start this season, the
schedule maker did not do them any favors. The first 13 games of
the season will be against the Marlins and the Montreal Expos. The
Mets, who won 88 games last season, were 4-8 against an Expos team
that won 65.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins' starter, Alex Fernandez, recovering from rotator
cuff surgery, had not pitched since Oct. 8, 1997, but Monday he
pitched five strong innings.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura, one of the vaunted off-season acquisitions, did
not have an auspicious debut. He flied out to leave the bases
loaded in the first inning and in the bottom of the frame did not
look like a five-time Gold Glove winner. He got a late jump on Luis
Castillo's leadoff Baltimore chop that led to a single and he was
unable to glove Derrek Lee's hard smash to third with one out and
runners on first and third, turning a potential inning-ending
double play into a run-scoring single and opening the way for the
Marlins' three-run rally.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Dunwoody lined a run-scoring single to center, Mike Piazza
committed a passed ball to allow the runners to move to second and
third. Preston Wilson, who was part of the trade that brought
Piazza to New York last May, delivered a sacrifice fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, the Mets were down, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura atoned for his transgressions with a third-inning
sacrifice fly. But through their first three at-bats, the Mets had
left six runners on base, including four in scoring position,
against Fernandez, who left after 95 pitches to a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   And then Florida added two more runs in the fifth off Leiter to
make it 5-1 when Wilson singled Lee home with two out, then stole
second and scored on Kevin Orie's double off the left field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Marlins, the Mets are built to win now. Their
starting lineup averages 31 years of age, their starting rotation
34; their closer is 38. Phillips had talked before the game about
his only expectation being that his players perform to their
average capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, the general manager was asked, is this a
playoff team? ``It should be,'' Phillips said, well aware that the
Mets have not qualified for the post-season since 1988. ``It better
be.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, the Mets looked a lot more like the team that had
trouble beating the Marlins and the Expos last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
