<DOCNO> NYT19990405.0555 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-1STLD-WRI     04-05 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO APPROVES SENDING U.S. CHOPPERS, MISSILES AND SOLDIERS TO
ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 5th graf, He wants ..., to DROP number of ethnic
Albanians who have been forced out; SUBS 8th graf, Allied transport
..., to DELETE that planes have not yet begun evacuating refugees,
hundreds were airlifted to Turkey on Monday.) 
 (ART ADV: Two maps showing targets of attack in Balkans and in
Kosovo are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BASES,
KOSOVO-ECON) 
(nk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO on Monday gave its military commander
the authority he sought to send 24 U.S. Apache helicopter gunships
to Albania, with surface-to-surface missiles and about 2,000
American soldiers who will use them to attack Serbian forces across
the border in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's secretary-general, Javier Solana, also got approval for
the deployment from the Albanian authorities Monday evening,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache anti-tank helicopters and their missile systems are
expected to be in position in about a week, supplementing a bombing
campaign that the allies say has only begun to get seriously under
way now that the weather has cleared.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's top commander, Gen. Wesley Clark of the United
States, asked for the helicopters, along with the 12 additional
Stealth F-117A fighters and the scores of attack planes based on
the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   He wants the aircraft to bolster the bombing campaign that has
so far failed to stop Serbian forces in Kosovo from driving ethnic
Albanians out of the province in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just starting to hit them,'' said Air Commodore David
Wilby, a British officer who is the spokesman for the allied
military command. ``I think you will find very direct results
coming in shortly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monday more refugees kept pouring out of Kosovo, and 34,000
of them arrived in Albania and 10,000 in Macedonia on Sunday alone,
allied officials reported.
</P>
<P>
   Allied transport planes flew 31 missions on Sunday to bring in
200 tons of food and medical supplies to the refugee camps along
the Macedonian border, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Direct allied air attacks against the Serbian forces were
hampered until Sunday night by clouds and rain, military officers
here said. They said they hoped that the Apache helicopters, which
can fly at low levels at night and in any kind of weather, would
stop the attacks on civilians where higher-flying planes could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very grateful to the United States for making available
this extremely important capability,'' said the alliance's
spokesman, Jamie Shea. He said the allies would view any threat to
Albania from the Serbian forces under Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic with extreme seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   Clark asked for the Apache helicopters to improve the air
campaign's ability to attack individual Yugoslav Army units and
heavily armed paramilitary police units that have been surrounding
ethnic Albanian villages with tanks or other armored vehicles,
driving out all the inhabitants at gunpoint and then herding them
onto buses and farm vehicles for expulsion to neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches fly close to the ground at more than 150 mph and can
launch up to 16 laser-guided Hellfire missiles at targets like
tanks from more than three miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the helicopters, President Clinton decided to send 18
rocket launchers that fire ground-to-ground missiles used to attack
radar systems and anti-aircraft weapons that could pose a threat to
the anti-tank helicopters. The rockets, M-39s, have a range of 100
miles and warheads that explode and disperse 950 deadly grenades
apiece over a wide area, sending lethal metal fragments that can
kill soldiers and disable or immobilize their anti-aircraft
missiles or guns.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches use laser guidance systems and night vision devices
that let a two-member crew zero in on armored personnel carriers
and tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, the most effective anti-tank weapons the NATO
campaign has been able to use against the marauding Serb units are
the two-engined A-10 aircraft that became known as ``tank killers''
in the Gulf War of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Military officers said A-10s were in the air Monday as the
allies took advantage of improved weather over the Balkans to bomb
27 targets, including an oil refinery on the northwest outskirts of
Belgrade overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Among the targets hit overnight, Wilby said, were Serb tanks
ringing the Kosovo village of Glodane _ one village among hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   He showed photographs of the tanks, and said that later pictures
the command did not make available showed that the Serbs had set
fire to the village after forcing the inhabitants out. He said he
could not release photographs of the damage done to the Serb tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we want to stop the violence in Kosovo immediately,
as soon as we possibly can,'' Shea said Monday. ``The most
important thing is that at the end of the day we should be able to
reverse this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing in the Apache helicopters posed ticklish problems for
Washington _ where their involvement was seen as taking the United
States one step closer to sending in ground troops to help the
refugees go home to Kosovo _ and for allied countries who do not
want to widen the war by bringing on attacks against Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Italy, wary of NATO actions that could increase the
flow of refugees across the Adriatic, and in Greece, where public
opposition to the bombing runs strong, have called for an end to
the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Italy nor Greece, nor any other country, raised
objections Monday to a proposal to let Solana negotiate the Apache
deployment with the Albanian authorities, diplomats said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
