<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MAKE OPENING STATEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was New Hampshire, minus the apathy.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday at Dodger Stadium there was the red-white-and-blue
bunting, the pageantry and all the promise you'd expect from an
opening primary.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 NL West race was formally launched in front of a
sellout crowd, with the upstart Arizona Diamondbacks playing
Elizabeth Dole to the pedigreed Dodgers' George W. Bush. At the end
of the long and winding campaign, each side hopes, is a date in the
Fall Classic against the incumbent New York Yankees, the American
League's answer to Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The first of 13 regular-season meetings between the two teams
was such a slice of heaven, they played 11. In a game that saw both
teams parade pitchers to the fore like stump speakers, the Dodgers
eked out an 8-6 win that delivered a message, loud and clear, to
anyone in the crowd of 53,109 who stuck around long enough to hear
it:
</P>
<P>
   Never count these Dodgers out.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Raul Mondesi on this day could do no wrong. His
three-run blast in the bottom of the ninth sent the game into extra
innings and his two-run homer in the 11th settled it.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Mondesi found himself ahead of Mark McGwire's
single-season record pace of a year ago (McGwire hit one homer off
the Dodgers' Ramon Martinez in the 1998 season opener at St.
Louis). Three-hundred-and-twenty-four homers, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi also drove in the Dodgers' first run, in his first
at-bat. It was one heck of a declaration, coming from a player who
batted just .224 with runners in scoring position last year.
</P>
<P>
   So was the patience he showed at the plate. Notorious for
swinging at the first pitch, Mondesi passed on every initial
offering in his six at-bats. He came to the plate in the bottom of
the ninth with two men on and two outs and proceeded to lay off
reliever Gregg Olson's first three pitches, all balls.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, first-year manager Davey Johnson decided it was
time to make a statement that some surely would view as slightly
left of center. He gave Mondesi the green light to swing on the
next pitch. Olson made Johnson look like a genius by throwing a
high fastball that the high fastball-loving Mondesi crushed into
the left-center field seats.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi later would say he couldn't decode Johnson's hand
signals so he made a unilateral decision to swing away. It was that
kind of day for Mondesi and the Dodgers, who skirted certain
cataclysm twice in the early innings before staging their comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching ace Kevin Brown, making his much-anticipated Dodgers
debut, retired the Diamondbacks in order in the first, though it
would require a dozen pitches. From the first pitch (a ball) to the
111th (which Jay Bell sent into the bleachers to drive in three
runs) it was a pockmarked performance for the man who aims for
perfection every time he throws to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona loaded the bases in the second and again in the third,
which put the pressure firmly on the Dodgers' softest spot. That
would be the infield, which was a minefield last year.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Eric Young let it be known early on that we can
expect things to be different in 1999. He deftly avoided a sliding
Tony Batista and turned the double play to save Brown in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   And shortstop Mark Grudzielanek _ he of the 33 errors in 1998 _
gobbled up a grounder by Luis Gonzalez and flipped the ball to
Young for the force that defused Arizona's charge in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Young also made it clear the broken right foot he suffered in
September is sufficiently healed by stealing twice off Diamondbacks
starter Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who very nearly was traded to the Dodgers from Seattle
last June before being dealt to Houston, signed a ludicrously
lucrative deal with Arizona last fall. His four-year, $52 million
contract was part of a $119 million spending spree by Diamondbacks
owner Jerry Colangelo aimed at upgrading the team's talent. If
Arizona doesn't become the first second-year franchise to post a
winning record since the 1962 Angels, it won't be for any lack of
trying on Colangelo's part.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve days after the Diamondbacks landed Johnson, the Dodgers
signed Brown to the mother(lode) of all deals _ $105 million over
seven years, thus setting up the most compelling showdown this side
of Gore vs. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one could have have foreseen that Brown would give
up three home runs _ two to Bernard Gilkey and one to Bell. Not
after he allowed only eight in 257 innings in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could anyone have predicted a gamer like Dodgers catcher
Todd Hundley striking out four times, an enigma like Mondesi
driving in six runs and a former Diamondback, Devon White, knocking
in more runs than Arizona's resident slugger, Matt Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was just one game in 162, but for the Dodgers it was a
powerful opening statement. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
