<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOTTI-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JUNIOR' GOTTI SEEMS MORE SON THAN BOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ His father was the man who worked himself
up the company ladder and transformed himself into the Dapper Don,
the one with the expensive suits and agile criminal mind, the big
man around town who instilled fear and respect. He was, of course,
John J. Gotti, the head of the Gambino crime family.
</P>
<P>
   The son, on the other hand, was the quiet, shy neighborhood guy
with his plebian tastes, the one who was thrust into the spotlight.
He was John A. Gotti, better known, in an affectionate and
belittling way, as Junior.
</P>
<P>
   They came from wildly different backgrounds, but now, they'll
end up in the same place: behind bars in a federal penitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, John Gotti, 35, agreed to plead guilty to six charges
of federal racketeering and false information. So instead of facing
a trial that had been billed as one of the most important, and most
anticipated, mob trials of the last decade, Gotti will now face a
sentence of between five years, 10 months and seven years, 3
months.
</P>
<P>
   Had he been convicted, Gotti would have faced a possible
sentence of 20 years. So, on one level, the deal seems to make
sense, because it means he will still be a young man when he
completes his sentence and returns to his wife and four children in
Oyster Bay on Long Island _ unlike his father, who is serving a
life term.
</P>
<P>
   But on another level, the deal almost seems bitterly apropos for
a man who never seemed very comfortable, or proficient, stepping
into the very large shoes of his legendary father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to be Henry Ford; it's another to be Edsel
Ford,'' said Aaron Rosenthal, a retired New York City assistant
police chief who is now an adjunct professor at John Jay College of
Criminal Justice. ``In no way, shape or form, from the day he was
allegedly made the boss, did I expect him to have a long run. He
wasn't in the wars. He didn't come up through the ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gotti's father grew up on the tough streets of the East New York
and Brownsville sections of Brooklyn, dropping out of high school
at age 16 and logging nine arrests and several brief jail sentences
for street fighting, public intoxication, stealing cars,
burglaries, bookmaking and gun possession by the time he was 24. He
then scratched his way up, through guile and street smarts, to the
top of the Gambino crime family.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti, by contrast, grew up in the tight-knit, middle-class
neighborhood of Howard Beach, Queens, graduating from the New York
Military Academy, a private boarding school. He never went to
college, but he is an avid reader, friends have said, and he has
amassed a large collection on American Indian history, in part
because he sees parallels between Italian-Americans and American
Indians, believing that both groups have been oppressed by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   As a young businessman, his lawyers say, he organized legitimate
trucking and truck-leasing companies and a real estate firm. But
eventually, he, too, fell into the organized-crime world, law
enforcement officials have charged.
</P>
<P>
   And after his father was convicted of murder and racketeering
charges in 1992, the younger Gotti was later anointed acting don _
a role that reportedly made his mother very unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   It is a role that he lapped up, according to law enforcement
officials. But he never quite fit the bill, in appearance or in
action.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti is a stocky man, 5 feet 9 inches tall, who keeps fit by
lifting weights. And until recently, he was the sartorial opposite
of his father, preferring jogging suits or jeans, a Windbreaker and
a baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti proved to be a mediocre businessman, investigators said,
frittering away his father's legal and illegal businesses, which
included loan-sharking and gambling interests.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Gotti seemed eager to portray himself not as
the swaggering, swashbuckling celebrity that his father had
created, but rather as a suburban joe with a minivan who showed up
to parent-teacher meetings and delivered cookies and cupcakes to
school parties. He began to spend more evenings with his family in
his 14-room, $700,000 home than with the reputed mobsters that he
had previously surrounded himself with at bars and dance clubs.
</P>
<P>
   And there were questions about whether he possessed the
requisite toughness of a traditional wiseguy. After his indictment
in January 1998 on federal racketeering charges, it was widely
reported that he was tantalizingly close to several plea deals with
prosecutors, only to pull back at the last moment at the behest of
his defiant parents.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Gotti decided to cut the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you grow up in the system, and you've been brainwashed,
you become like a rock in the Ganges: You've been washed over, and
you take the shape,'' Rosenthal said. ``But when that life doesn't
seem so charming anymore, you're going to have a whole lot of
thoughts, and one of them might be, `This might not be worth it.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
