<HEADER>
A7232 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-1STLD     04-05 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MORE STICKS AND FATTER CARROTS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6, It is too early ..., to recast. ) 
 (HLW)  
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question we are wrestling with in Kosovo today is this: How
should America react when bad things happen in unimportant places?
</P>
<P>
   You need only watch the footage of refugees streaming out of
Kosovo, and believe just half of their chilling tales of Serbian
atrocities, to know that something really bad is happening there to
which America should not be turning a blind eye.
</P>
<P>
   But you need only ask your congressman to find Kosovo on a map _
and watch the blank stare that comes back at you _ to appreciate
how unimportant Kosovo is to any vital American interests.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with this dilemma, the Clinton strategy has been to use
NATO air power to try to reverse the bad things happening in
Kosovo. But the administration's unwillingness to commit ground
troops to actually expel the Serbs from Kosovo is an admission that
its liberation is not worth the loss of many, if any, U.S. lives.
To put it another way, the cruise missile is the Clinton team's
weapon of choice for combating evil in unimportant places.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to say this strategy will not achieve an
acceptable outcome in Kosovo, and that troops will have to be sent
in. What one can say now, though, is that for this strategy to work
will require much tougher sticks and much fatter carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the sticks, I wouldn't underestimate the impact on a
modern European state of sustained NATO air bombardments, which
should be intensified once the weather clears. People tend to
change their minds and adjust their goals as they see the price
they are paying mount. Twelve days of surgical bombing was never
going to turn Serbia around. Let's see what 12 weeks of less than
surgical bombing does. Give war a chance.
</P>
<P>
   As for the carrots, while NATO steps up the air war, it also
needs to step up its diplomacy. Remember, you can bomb, curse,
condemn and kill the Serbs, but there is just one thing you can't
do, and that's make peace in the Balkans without them. There are
too many of them. Let's dangle two options before the Serbs right
now _ either a modified Rambouillet deal that would give the
Kosovars internationally protected autonomy in a Kosovo still under
Serb sovereignty, or a partition of Kosovo. The Serbs would get the
northwest sliver, which contains their Orthodox monasteries and
holy sites, and the Kosovo Albanians would get the remaining 90
percent, with an international peacekeeping force separating them.
</P>
<P>
   NATO needs to combine unreasonable bombing with a reasonable
peace offer. For now, this strategy is preferable to a ground war,
for two reasons. First, once NATO invades Kosovo, it owns Kosovo.
Anyone who cares about the future of NATO does not want to see the
alliance managing the daily relations between Serbs and Albanians
in Kosovo. It would be an endless, debilitating task.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if we have to fight a ground war, let's at least fight
it in optimal political circumstances. As Michael Mandelbaum, a
foreign policy expert at Johns Hopkins, points out: ``George Bush's
great achievement in the gulf war was the broad backing he earned
from the American public and the allies, and the basic neutrality
he earned from the Russians, by making it clear that he had gone
the extra mile to get an acceptable diplomatic deal before
launching the ground war.''
</P>
<P>
   All the foreign policy experts say that now that the war in
Kosovo has started, ``We have to win.'' OK, but win what? When you
are trying to stop bad things in unimportant places your task is to
minimize the bad without making the unimportant into a sucking
chest wound that weakens NATO and diminishes America's overall
position in the world. I don't want NATO to win Kosovo or the
Kosovars. I want NATO to stop what was bad and get out. I want NATO
to win Serbian agreement either for the Kosovo Albanians to return
to their homes _ with an international observer-peacekeeping force,
including Russians, managing relations between Albanians and Serbs
_ or for a partition of Kosovo, with a peacekeeping force
separating the factions.
</P>
<P>
   We need to see if sustained, unreasonable bombing, combined with
sustained, reasonable diplomacy, can achieve such goals. Sure, it
will take time, but considering the years NATO will have to spend
in Kosovo if this strategy doesn't work, I suggest we find the
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-99 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
