<SLUG> BC-SUPERIOR-DEAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEEL MAKER EXPANDS IN EUROPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Superior Industries International Inc., a leading
American wheel maker, has made further inroads into the European
market by winning a contract from the Rover Group Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Suoftec, Superior's European joint venture company in
partnership with Otto Fuchs of Germany, will supply cast aluminum
wheels for some of Rover's sport-utility vehicles and passenger
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Terms were not disclosed, but the deal announced Monday is a
multiyear contract. It is also Los Angeles-based Superior's first
contract with Rover Group and marks the initial production run of
cast wheels from the company's manufacturing plant in Tatabanya,
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to get cast wheels for the Hungary plant for
a while, so this is a real important addition from that point of
view,'' said R. Jeffrey Ornstein, Superior's chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The factory, which opened in late 1997, employs 550 people and
also supplies about 700,000 forged wheels a year to Audi. It can
make about 2.5 million wheels annually, and the new deal with
Longbridge, England-based Rover will boost production to about 50
percent of capacity, Ornstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Cast aluminum wheels are lightweight and offer manufacturers
more design options than are available in the forging process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aluminum is the material of the future in the automotive
industry ... and Superior will continue to be a major
beneficiary,'' Ornstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Shipments to Rover are expected to begin this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Superior also makes aluminum wheels and other aluminum
components for major domestic and foreign manufacturers. It also
manufacturers accessory products for the national automotive
aftermarket.
</P>
<P>
   The company is coming off a strong fourth quarter when profits
and sales hit record levels.
</P>
<P>
   In the December fourth quarter Superior earned $19.55 million,
equal to 71 cents a share, an increase of 25 percent from the prior
year's period, on sales of $152.7 million. In the 1997 fourth
quarter, Superior earned $15.65 million, or 56 cents a share, on
sales of $150.9 million, which beat analysts' expectations by
almost 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1998, Superior earned $52.32 million, or $1.88 per
share, compared with income of $55.39 million, or $1.96, in 1997.
Sales in 1998 totaled $539.4 million vs. $549.1 million the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Superior stock closed up 6.25 cents Monday at $23.6975.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
