<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN SUBWAY KILLING RULED FIT TO STAND TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man with a history of mental illness who is accused
of pushing a woman to her death in front of a subway train was
found fit to stand trial for murder Monday by a Manhattan judge.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Carol Berkman of state Supreme Court rejected pleas from
defense lawyers that Andrew Goldstein, who has a long history of
schizophrenia, be found incompetent and confined only to a secure
mental institution. Citing reports from two psychiatrists who said
Goldstein functioned well when taking his medication, Berkman ruled
that he was fit to stand trial for second-degree murder in the
death of Kendra Webdale, 32, who was pushed in front of an N train
in the 23rd Street station in Manhattan on Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standard of fitness is not a particularly high one,''
Berkman said in her ruling. ``While Goldstein is impaired, he is
not so impaired that he cannot assist in his own defense or undergo
the stresses of a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   If Goldstein is found guilty of second-degree murder, he will
face 25 years to life in jail, but if the jury finds that he was
not responsible for his actions because of mental illness, he will
likely be confined to a mental institution.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's lawyer, Harvey Fishbein, is expected to focus his
defense on the state and the city's systems for caring for the
mentally ill. He pointed out at Monday's hearing that Goldstein was
hospitalized for schizophrenia six times last year, frequently at
his own request, and was released from a hospital just a little
over two weeks before the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Dankner, a lawyer representing Ms. Webdale's family,
announced Monday that they would file a $20 million medical
malpractice lawsuit against the city hospital system, for allowing
Goldstein's release after treatment last year. The suit will also
name the city's subway system, Dankner said. He added that
additional lawsuits will be filed against any private hospitals
that are found to have recently treated and released Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor in the criminal trial, William Greenbaum, is
expected to argue that Goldstein was not taking the medication that
suppresses his schizophrenia at the time of the attack, and was
responsible for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   On videotape and in written statements, Goldstein confessed to
pushing Ms. Webdale to her death. Goldstein told police that a
psychotic episode caused him to believe that a ``spirit or ghost''
entered his body and forced him to push Ms. Webdale, in a chilling
assault that rekindled the fears of many subway riders of random
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Webdale's sister, Kim, attended Monday's hearing and said
she was ``very pleased'' with Berkman's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should never have released this man,'' Dankner said. ``He
never should have been walking free on the streets of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Dankner said that he was still trying to determine all the
hospitals where Goldstein was treated for mental illness. Fishbein,
Goldstein's lawyer, said he would not discuss Goldstein's private
medical history.
</P>
<P>
   Dankner said that Goldstein was treated twice last year at
Bellevue Hospital in Manhattan and once at Elmhurst Hospital in
Queens _ both run by the city _ and that a private hospital, North
General in Manhattan, treated him for 22 days last winter and
released him on Dec. 15, two weeks and two days before the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Bade Goodman, a spokeswoman for the corporation counsel's
office, declined to comment Monday. Cheryl Anderson, a spokeswoman
for North General, said she had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a hint of how the trial could broaden to the larger issue of
treatment of the mentally ill, Berkman suggested Monday that she
was constricted by the current legal standards for the mentally
ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt that someday, probably after we are all gone,
people will look back at our treatment of mental illness under the
law and be shocked and appalled,'' she said. ``But that is really
not the issue I have before me today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
